<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: GOP undermining of census a shameful hustle
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The demagoguery against the census reached a new low last week
when the U.S. Senate adopted a resolution in effect telling
Americans just to skip any census questions they don't feel like
answering and assuring them they won't be prosecuted, fined or ``in
any way harassed by the federal government'' for taking a hike.
</P>
<P>
   That is, the demagoguery reached a new low so far. It is not
clear that the competition is over.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine: the nation's highest deliberative body suborning mass
law-breaking. It is an astonishing sight. The senators also urged
everyone to return the census forms as required by law, but for
covering their tails, that's the legislative equivalent of a string
bikini.
</P>
<P>
   The right-wing and, increasingly, the Republican grandstanding
against the census is one of the most shameful political hustles in
years.
</P>
<P>
   It started, as so much damn foolishness does, with radio
talk-show hysterics yelling about a government plot to pry into the
private lives of citizens. To just what nefarious end is unclear,
but surely to some evil purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Like sparks on dry grass, that set off a spreading brush fire of
outrage, and before you could say ``cheap shot,'' politicians of
the more flagrantly irresponsible sort were lining up to pose and
sputter against the Clinton census.
</P>
<P>
   No less than Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott mused that maybe
offended citizens shouldn't bother to answer any questions on the
long form -- one in six of us get those _ that didn't strike their
fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no Clinton census. This is the U.S. census,
required by the Constitution every 10 years. The long-form
questions about plumbing, income, disability and more are
traditional and are designed to provide data on which specific
federal programs, enacted by Congress, can be targeted and
budgeted. Members of Congress saw the questions two years ago;
there wasn't a peep against them.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in Washington cares a fig about individual responses, but
the better the data, the more effectively your tax dollars can be
spent. (The talk-show response to that is, ``Aha! Just more
evidence that the government has 'programs.' ``)
</P>
<P>
   The sponsor for the non-compliance resolution was Robert C.
Smith (R-N.H.), who is not exactly the brightest bulb on the
marquee. He complains that asking about race divides us. Right. We
wouldn't know we were of different races if the census didn't force
us to notice.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was non-binding and was passed by a voice vote.
It is, in short, legally meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not politically meaningless. Smith's move dovetails
with other efforts by conservative Republicans to undermine the
census, in part out ofsome odd, ideological kink that anathematizes
it but, more slyly, in hopes of confusing the head count in ways
that may make it possible to skew congressional reapportionment to
conservative advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Beware the politicians who don't want you to be counted. Some
simply don't want you to count.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He writes from
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
