<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 16)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ADULTERY: And Other Diversions  &LR; By Tim Parks. Arcade, $12.95.
The author displays both storytelling skill and acerbic
self-knowledge as he explores the relationship between moral
constructs and real life in meditations on marriage, European
politics and other topics. The result is ``an elegant demonstration
of the freedom and power of the essay form,'' Robert Grudin wrote
in The New York Times Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE STORIES OF J.F. POWERS  &LR; New York Review, $14.95. James Farl
Powers (1917-99) was a Midwesterner whose small output _ three
collections of stories and two novels _ has attracted something of
a cult following. This anthology of his short fiction is populated
by housekeepers, parishioners and, especially, Catholic priests
living out their small-scale dramas in the United States'
heartland. ``His talent was happiest in the concentration, the
focus, of the short story,'' Denis Donoghue wrote in an essay in
The New York Times Book Review last month. ``It was as if he
thought life most clearly disclosed in the telling anecdote.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued Powers' novels.  &UR; MORTE D'URBAN &LR; 
($12.95), which won the National Book Award in 1963, is about a
charismatic, go-getting Chicago priest who is banished by his
superior to the Minnesota outback. ``This is a comic novel, with
some fine slapstick touches,'' Richard Sullivan wrote in 1962. ``It
is at the same time sharply satirical.''
</P>
<P>
   The hero of  &UR; WHEAT THAT SPRINGETH GREEN &LR;  ($12.95) is another
worldly priest who struggles to maintain his dignity and resist the
tug of the secular world in his suburban parish. ``No eye has been
sharper, no ear finer than that of J.F. Powers at discerning the
nuances of service to God and mammon,'' Amy Edith Johnson wrote in
1988. ``The beauty of Powers' writing lies in its art's being
almost invisible.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BROKEN TOWER: A Life of Hart Crane  &LR; By Paul Mariani.
Norton, $15.95. The first biography of the poet in 30 years
re-examines Crane's short, sad life, which ended with his suicide
at 32. It includes frank discussions of his sexuality, his
infatuation with New York City and his difficulty maintaining
friendships. The ``aim isn't to moralize Crane's life but to retell
it as `a great Greek tragedy' in Jazz Age dress,'' Langdon Hammer
wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROBERT FROST: A Life &LR; , by Jay Parini (Owl/Holt, $16), is a
sympathetic look at the cantankerous New England poet who gave up
college (he was a better Latinist than Pound or Eliot) for
subsistence farming and part-time teaching. Last year the reviewer
Christopher Benfey called this a ``sturdy and well-informed''
portrait.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST AMERICAN SHORT STORIES OF THE CENTURY  &LR; Edited by John
Updike and Katrina Kenison.  &UR;  &LR; Houghton Mifflin, $18.95. Each tale
in this celebration of short fiction appeared in an annual series
called Best American Short Stories, which began in 1915. (A new
story from the 1999 edition has been added.) ``Finding wonderful
stories that you don't already know is one of this collection's
great pleasures,'' Michael Gorra wrote last year. There are ``some
surprising _ even striking _ selections.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAST THINGS  &LR; By Jenny Offill. Delta, $11.95. The protagonist of
this first novel is a 7-year-old girl who witnesses her mother's
downward spiral into madness, and who tries to make her way through
a claustrophobic world fraught with codes, disguises and mysterious
signs. ``Offill's fresh voice, endearing and quirky, makes you
willingly suspend disbelief,'' Nancy Willard wrote in The New York
Times Book Review in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HAUNTED WOOD: Soviet Espionage in America _ the Stalin Era
 &LR; By Allen Weinstein and Alexander Vassiliev. Modern Library,
$14.95. Drawing on thousands of secret documents from the Stalin
years, an American scholar and a Russian journalist shed light on
the ``golden age'' of Soviet espionage. ``What emerges most sharply
is proof of the guilt of certain Americans whose spying for the
Soviet Union has been the subject of debate for over half a
century,'' Joseph E. Persico wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANY THOUSANDS GONE: The First Two Centuries of Slavery in
North America  &LR; By Ira Berlin. Belknap/Harvard University, $16.95. A
historian examines the many forms and meanings of slavery between
the arrival of the first blacks in Virginia in 1619 and the rise of
King Cotton. ``This masterly work ... illuminates the first 200
years of African-American history more effectively than any
previous study,'' George M. Fredrickson wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A TUSCAN CHILDHOOD  &LR; By Kinta Beevor. Vintage Departures, $13.
An Englishwoman recounts her bohemian childhood in a 15th-century
castle in Tuscany, and tells how World War II altered the region
and its inhabitants. Last year the reviewer Philip Gambone admired
Beevor's ability to make ``the irrepressible Tuscan spirit ... come
to life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARADISO  &LR; By Jose Lezama Lima. Dalkey Archive, $14.50. This
ambitious novel by a major Cuban poet concerns a boy's coming of
age and the wisdom he gains while searching for his dead father.
``Lezama not only has the power to create absorbing and memorable
images, he has also placed these images into a vast network of
philosophical and mythical significance,'' Edmund White wrote in
1974.
</P>
</TEXT>
