<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 09:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN12-CO     04-10 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Census 2000 not that nosy, just lazy
 &HT;    For release April 12, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has become commonplace to gripe about the census. Invasion of
privacy is the most used depiction. Actually, the census doesn't
ask you much that it doesn't already know.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have been coping with one of two forms of Census 2000
response: the short form which basically asks you little else other
than your name, rank and serial number and the longer form, which
asks you a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   One of six American homes were sent the long form, mine being
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   It went on page after page, asking questions that I thought it
already had the answers to. Some friends who also got the long form
are clearly displeased by the tenor of the questions. I feel more
amused than abused.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I didn't find it that intrusive. Is there anything more
probing than your income tax form? By the end of the weekend, most
of us will have reported to Internal Revenue every dime we made
last year, how much we paid for our medical expenses, what we spent
on charity, who fed off us as dependents and everything about our
businesses as regards to expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Census 2000 form didn't ask much more. I was, however,
perturbed by one question. I didn't mind when it asked how much I
earned in salary, or how much I received in interest or dividends,
even how much I might have gotten in Social Security benefits. IRS
already has that information. In fact, I had to refer to my tax
form to get the information for my census form.
</P>
<P>
   What irked me, however, was when Census 2000 asked me to add it
all up. One would think that with all those computers and abacuses
at the disposal of the federal government, they could do their own
addition.
</P>
<P>
   My accountant had to do something similar for my tax form, but
by the time he finished inserting the deductions, applying the
doodads, separating gross from net, I never could get a clear
understanding. I just signed where he told me to sign and mailed it
off to the feds.
</P>
<P>
   Now Census 2000 wants me to do their addition for them. After
much contemplation, I did it but I wonder what would have happened
had I not. Would some government official come knocking on my door
demanding I add things up? What would have happened had I told him
to go over to the IRS office and ask them?
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, this was a minor detail and I complied.
</P>
<P>
   Another question that somewhat buffaloed me was about my
heritage. Census 2000 wants to know if we're Greek or African,
Italian or Chinese, Latin American or German. Many of us don't
know.
</P>
<P>
   I found the question difficult to answer inasmuch as my people
have been wandering for thousands of years, chased from here to
there and back again -- likely intermarried or transmutes by
conquering armies of rapists. (The latter might explain why a
doctor once informed me a condition on my hand is inherent to those
with Viking blood running through their veins.)
</P>
<P>
   Inasmuch as my discernible heritage wasn't listed, I opted for
the bottom line that was identified as ``other.'' My first thought
was to put down the Land of Canaan as the origin of my forbearers
but some dude at Census 2000 might misconstrue my family's roots to
be in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Shall I put down Russia, or shall it be Poland; perhaps Ukraine,
maybe Lithuania? It's all a hodgepodge; grandma was from there,
grandpa from somewhere else -- always moving around, at the
direction of the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   I finally settled on ``Eastern European.'' Let Census 2000
figure it out from there. After all, I did their mathematics for
them, they can do the geography.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
