<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Discrimination Is Painful. It Can Also Be Agonizing.
</P>
<P>
   A study titled ``We Don't Carry That'' suggests that people who
need medication for severe pain may have trouble getting it if they
live in neighborhoods that are mostly black, Hispanic or Asian.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 347 pharmacies in New York City, conducted by the
Mount Sinai School of Medicine, found that in nonwhite
neighborhoods only 25 percent of pharmacies carried enough morphine
or morphine-like drugs to treat severe pain; in white
neighborhoods, 72 percent did. Interviews with doctors and
pharmacists in Los Angeles and the Midwest suggested similar
problems there.
</P>
<P>
   Half the druggists blamed low demand, saying they could not
afford to stock items that customers did not buy. Some also cited
onerous narcotics laws and fear of theft in high-crime
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some pharmacies who are very anxious about armed
robberies and will have signs saying that they don't carry
narcotics,'' one pharmacist said.
</P>
<P>
   If demand is truly lower, no one knows why. Minorities are no
less likely than whites to suffer from illnesses that cause great
pain. Blacks, in fact, have higher cancer rates than whites.
</P>
<P>
   Some pharmacists suggested that demand was lower in poor
neighborhoods because they had higher proportions of uninsured
people who could not afford to fill prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors who reviewed the survey said racial bias might be at
work because the results fit into a wider pattern of inequality in
health care, revealed by recent studies showing that blacks are
less likely than whites to be referred for kidney transplants or
surgery for early-stage cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study comes on the heels of many other studies that have
documented a disparity in treatment in which racial and ethnic
factors seem to be the predominant factor,'' said Dr. Richard
Payne, chief of the pain and palliative care service at Memorial
Sloan Kettering Cancer Center. ``And that's quite disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, doctors are less likely to prescribe painkillers
for blacks and Hispanics with broken bones or postoperative pain,
perhaps because of the false perception that they are more likely
to be addicts or less likely to need treatment for pain.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DENISE GRADY
</P>
<P>
   Play Ball!
</P>
<P>
   Forget robins, equinoxes and daylight saving time: spring has
begun. On Monday, after a peculiar road trip, during which several
teams played their first league games in Japan, baseball really got
under way again.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees' pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre has seen
more than three decades of opening days, but he awoke on Monday
thinking baseball. ``I found myself craving it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre wasn't alone. As the Yankees waited to play their
West Coast opener against the Anaheim Angels, about a dozen players
gathered in the clubhouse more than three hours before their own
game, to watch televised highlights from other games that day.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' Andres Galarraga, who sat out last year with cancer,
bashed a home run in Atlanta and the Yankees cheered. Vladimir
Guerrero, of the Montreal Expos, hit two home runs, the second a
mammoth shot that awed the Yankee couch potatoes. And when Derek
Bell, the Mets' new outfielder, hit a pivotal home run in Shea
Stadium, the Yankees grunted as one, urging him on as he swung.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BUSTER OLNEY
</P>
<P>
   The Last of the Clinton Five Is Cleared of Wrongdoing
</P>
<P>
   Labor Secretary Alexis Herman, the fifth cabinet officer in the
Clinton administration to be investigated by an independent
counsel, was cleared of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   After a 23-month investigation, the prosecutor, Ralph I.
Lancaster Jr., said there was no reason to seek an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The scorecard on the Clinton five: Herman and Bruce Babbitt, the
interior secretary, were cleared by independent counsels; former
Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros pleaded guilty to one misdemeanor
count, and Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy was acquitted of all
charges at trial. An investigation of Commerce Secretary Ronald
Brown ended after he was killed in a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NEIL A. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   Follow the Money
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's leaders talk tough to the press, saying the
government's antitrust charges are wrong. But they sing a different
tune to their brokers.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson found
Microsoft in violation of the nation's antitrust laws, several of
the company's leaders, including chairman Bill Gates, exercised
options to sell company stock worth tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good bet. On the day of the ruling, Microsoft's stock
lost almost 14 percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOEL BRINKLEY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: JOEL BRINKLEY &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATO Finally Catches One
</P>
<P>
   The accused war criminal Momcilo Krajisnik was arrested at his
parents' Bosnian home by French NATO troops and flown to the
international tribunal in The Hague, where he pleaded not guilty to
war crimes for his role in Serbia's ethnic cleansing campaign in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik, a close ally of the Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic, is considered the most important war crimes suspect yet
captured by NATO, which has been criticized for not pursuing more
aggressively those responsible for the atrocities committed in the
Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Richard C. Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
said of Krajisnik's capture, ``This is possibly the most important
day since the Dayton agreement on Bosnia,'' which ended the war in
1995. Krajisnik, 55, faces a maximum sentence of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Incredible Is Testable, But in Another Dimension
</P>
<P>
   Superstring theorists have a problem: You can't test a theory
that posits that all matter consists of ``notes'' produced by tiny
strings vibrating in nine-dimensional space. We aware of only three
dimensions because the rest are curled up into extremely tiny
balls, a hundred million trillion times smaller than a proton.
</P>
<P>
   But Lisa Randall of Princeton University, Raman Sundrum of
Stanford University and Joseph Lykken of the Fermi National
Accelerator Laboratory have proposed that at least one of the extra
dimensions is actually a four-dimensional megaverse inside which
the universe floats like a bubble. They believe that energy might
occasionally leak into the fourth dimension _ and that idea might
be testable.
</P>
<P>
   When two particles are slammed together in an accelerator, the
amount of energy going into the reaction should equal the amount
coming out.
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't, energy could be leaking into the fourth
dimension. Scientists are searching records of past accelerator
experiments for signs of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe a discovery of extra dimensions is already sitting on a
tape in some data bank,'' Lykken said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By GEORGE JOHNSON
</P>
<P>
   A Friend of Ours Writes
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker magazine was renowned for attempting to verify
every fact it published. In a recent book on the magazine, however,
onetime staff writer Renata Adler announced without proof that the
late Judge John Sirica was ``corrupt,'' ``dishonest'' and had
``clear ties to organized crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Sirica, who presided over the Watergate burglary trial, which
ultimately led to the resignation of President Richard Nixon in
1974, was widely regarded as a scrupulously honest jurist.
</P>
<P>
   Adler told a New York Times reporter that she would publish
proof of her charge when she pleased. Meanwhile, John Dean, former
Nixon counsel, suggested Adler might have been misled by G. Gordon
Liddy, whom Sirica sentenced to prison for his role in Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Goods
</P>
<P>
   Border guards in the former Soviet republic of Uzbekistan seized
a radioactive cargo on an Iranian truck bound for Pakistan, said
State Department officials. The material, found in 10 lead
containers about the size of a thick briefcase, was being tested by
officials in neighboring Kazakhstan, where it originated, to see if
it could have been used to make a nuclear weapon. Pakistan has a
history of smuggling nuclear components, and is believed to have
built about a dozen warheads.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TIM WEINER
</P>
<P>
   Whose Life Is It, Anyway?
</P>
<P>
   No one should be forced to be a parent, according to a ruling by
the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court concerning the fate of
frozen embryos created by a couple with fertility problems. After
the couple divorced, the 44-year-old former wife wanted to use the
embryos for one last try at getting pregnant, but the ex-husband
objected, though he had earlier signed consent forms saying she
could have the embryos.
</P>
<P>
   In the third such dispute over embryos to reach a state supreme
court _ and likely not the last, given the estimated 150,000 frozen
embryos nationwide _ the Massachusetts court said that, despite the
contract, it would be bad public policy to coerce parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   The Coup That Fell to Earth
</P>
<P>
   Nawaz Sharif, ousted by a military coup last October from his
position as Pakistan's prime minister, was convicted of hijacking a
commercial airliner. He was sentenced to life imprisonment and
ordered to forfeit all his personal property. Six co-defendants
were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's hijacking was a peculiar one in that he didn't take
over an airplane. Rather, he ordered that a Karachi-bound plane be
refused permission to land, even though it was running low on fuel.
The plane carried 198 passengers, including Gen. Pervez Musharraf,
who would depose Sharif later in the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Red Faces in High Places
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army, already battered in recent years by sexual
misconduct scandals, was jolted again with the disclosure that a
general accused of sexual harassment by the Army's highest-ranking
woman was appointed last August to be the service's deputy
inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of the officer, Maj. Gen. Larry G. Smith,
prompted Lt. Gen. Claudia Kennedy, the Army's first woman to earn
three stars, to lodge a formal complaint against him.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said she was concerned that he would be responsible
for investigating accusations of wrongdoing, including sexual
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN LEE MYERS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 0937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
