<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REENACT-AUTHENTIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REENACTMENT PARAPHERNALIA   MORE REALISTIC THAN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY TAYLOR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Mass. -- A generation ago, reenactors of
Revolutionary War skirmishes often took liberties with dress and
gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to see people in cutoff chinos with rubber bands,
people with plastic pistols and cartridge pouches made from
handbags,'' said Henry Cooke of Randolph, a historical tailor and
authority on clothing, military uniforms, and accouterments of the
1770s and 1780s. Another example was what he called a ``Coney
Island tricorn,'' a rigid caricature of a militiaman's hat.
</P>
<P>
   That has all changed. Since the 200th anniversary of the 19th of
April of '75, a flurry of works by historians _ Robert Gross's
``Minutemen and Their World'' and David Hackett Fischer's ``Paul
Revere's Ride'' notable among them _ and a proliferation of Web
sites by living history groups have spread the word about
authenticity to every Middlesex village and farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scholarship has improved vastly in the last 25 years,'' Cooke
said. ``Most people can dial up enough sources of information to
put together a credible interpretation that looks well. We're not
just recreational reenactors but educators.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the meticulous reenactors on both sides of Battle Road
engagements next weekend will be David Workman, a Wakefield artist
whose militiaman is loosely based on Nathaniel Cowdrey, a Reading
farmer 225 years ago, and Roger Fuller of Northborough, who next
struts in public as both a grenadier and light infantryman with His
Majesty's 40th Regiment of Foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than a hobby,'' said Fuller, 43, a former German
teacher and camera shop proprietor whose grenadier uniform was
custom made by Cooke. ``It's a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Not an inexpensive one. The replica .75-caliber Brown Bess
muskets with 42-inch barrels that he and Workman carry cost about
$700 today. Fuller estimates that his entire grenadier's outfit,
including musket, sword, bayonet, canteen, cap, knapsack,
haversack, and oilskin gaiters, costs about $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   An authentic militiaman's clothing, musket, and gear would come
to $2,200, perhaps less if the reenactor made his own clothing,
according to Cooke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grenadiers were the elite, the ones who wouldn't turn and
run,'' Fuller said as he and Workman were photographed in full
regalia outside Workman's home in Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 5 feet 10, and my bearskin cap makes me 7 feet tall. I
carry a gray blanket and a goatskin-covered knapsack, good for
water-proofing. My woolen jacket, with epaulets, is madder red,
from dye of the madder plant. The leather cross belts, woolen
waistcoat, and breeches are buff. The gaiters are oilskin. The
jacket buttons are pewter, made from castings of originals found in
an 1815 excavation in New York from the Battle of Brooklyn, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuller's bearskin cap has a brass plate with the Latin motto,
``Nic Aspera Terrent.'' ``Roughly translated, `Difficulties be
damned,' '' Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   He began the hobby in November 1997, 22 years after Workman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw an ad in a local newspaper by a militia company looking
for volunteers,'' said Workman, 52.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be fun. Since becoming involved, I've
steeped myself in the history of the period. We read lots of books
and we pick up information from each other. There's a world of
difference in the information available to us. Daniel Chester
French's minuteman statue at the North Bridge is full of
19th-century mistakes, for example. The huge hammer lock on the
musket is out of proportion. And there definitely were no
shirtsleeves on the 19th of April. We know that that day was not
that warm. His farmer has his coat on a plow. They'd all have had a
coat or jacket on that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for dark gray gaiters, which stretch from his shoetops to
over his knees, Workman's militiaman outfit is a study in browns _
felt hat, capable of being cocked, kerchief around his neck, a
linen jacket and waistcoat, buttons of wood, and leather breeches.
He carries a wooden canteen. From his waist belt hang a bayonet and
hatchet. Slung over his shoulder is a knapsack containing a blanket
and such provisions as salt cod, dried corn and peas.
</P>
<P>
   Workman will join the encampment April 13-17 at Lincoln Park in
Lexington, but he said he hasn't decided whether to sleep overnight
in a tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in a few hundred reenactments over the years,'' he
said, ``but this is a big one.''
</P>
<P>
   Workman belongs to the 2d and the 10th Massachusetts regiments,
both formed later in the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller's grenadier uniform includes a perforated brass
cannister, worn on his cross belt, which would contain a ``slow
match,'' or smoldering cotton cord soaked in a phosphorus compound.
This was used to light the fuses of grenades these soldiers
carried. But the actual grenadiers on the Battle Road 225 years ago
carried no grenades, Fuller said, and neither does he.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grenades were used in storming fortifications,'' Fuller said.
``Of course, there weren't any fortifications in America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
