<SLUG> BC-REENACT-1775-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPIC PRODUCTION NOTES WORLD-CHANGING EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY DROHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Mass. _ It is an epic production befitting the birth
of a nation.
</P>
<P>
   It stars the common man, the minuteman, who inspired the world
when he began to fight for his rights on April 19, 1775.
</P>
<P>
   Battle Road 2000 comes to you live, featuring an international
cast of almost 2,000 on a stage 12 miles long. A five-day pageant
celebrating the 225th anniversary of Patriots Day, April 19, will
be the largest Revolutionary War reenactment ever held in New
England, drawing units from 26 states, Canada, and Great Britain.
Organizers expect an audience of 200,000.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the events of April 19-20, 1775, will be
reenacted in the order they occurred. Battle Road opens an
eight-year series of Revolution reenactments at their original
sites along the East Coast, destined to end in Yorktown.
</P>
<P>
   The premiere features a dozen major production numbers,
including an encampment with 400 tents that opens Thursday, a huge
fife and drum muster on Friday night, memorial tributes to the
British, Colonial craft exhibitions, parades, and severallarge
battle reenactments.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Revere will be arrested in Lincoln at the site of the
original capture, in real time, at 1 a.m. Saturday. Five hours
later, more than 500 British Regulars will march down Massachusetts
Avenue and face the 77 minutemen on Lexington Green. ``The shot
heard round the world'' will be fired. The rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excitement is building,'' said Colonel Gardner ``Skip''
Hayward, commander of Battle Road 2000 and the D.W. Griffith of the
production. ``This will be more than three times the size of the
largest Battle Road we have ever had, including a record number of
British.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayward and his staff of 30 have been planning the event for
four years. Battle Road reenactments are a traditional part of
Patriots Day, but this year the cast is surpassed only by the 1981
Yorktown event in Virginia, the largest American Revolution
reenactment ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's huge,'' said Hayward, a member of the Lexington
Minutemen, president of the Lexington Historical Society, and an
ex-Marine. ``It's also complicated. Most reenactments are held on a
single field, or in a large, open area. This one stretches through
three towns, goes in and around Minute Man National Park, and at
sites along parts of Route 2A into Lexington.''
</P>
<P>
   Battle Road commemorates the day when 700 Redcoats were sent to
seize Colonial arms and supplies in Concord. Minutemen confronted
them in Lexington and Concord. More minutemen answered the alarm
from Acton, Arlington, Bedford, Carlisle, Chelmsford, Groton,
Lincoln, and many other towns.
</P>
<P>
   Outnumbered, the Regulars retreated to Charlestown, fighting a
series of skirmishes along the way. The Colonials lost 49 dead, 40
wounded, and five missing; British losses were 73 dead, 174
wounded, and 26 missing.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers only begin to express the solemnity and importance
of Battle Road, which Brandeis history professor David Hackett
Fischer called ``a pivotal point in world history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened at Lexington and Concord symbolized, clarified,
crystallized a great transformation in the western world,'' Fischer
said. ``Henry James called it `the hinge on which the future was to
turn.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It set people thinking in a new way, about new ideas _ that
government exists not to strengthen the power of the state but to
serve the greatest good for the greatest number, that it was
possible to solve public and historic questions in terms of reason,
that free markets are the key to growth and prosperity _ all ideas
fundamental to our way of life. And none of them existed before
1775.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer's 1994 book, ``Paul Revere's Ride,'' is widely praised
by historians for clarifying some of the confused events and
popular mythology of Battle Road. The book is especially
appreciated by living-history hobbyists, to whom ``authenticity is
everything,'' Hayward said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That book is our bible,'' he said. ``It has helped us
tremendously. We have the highest standards of authenticity for
Battle Road. We have come a long way from the reenactments of the
'20s, when the British marched in red bathrobes.''
</P>
<P>
   For veteran reenactor Henry Cooke of Randolph, who among other
roles will march Saturday as a member of the 10th Massachusetts
Regiment, the impact of living history is personal and immediate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes for a few fleeting moments it seems real,'' Cooke
said. ``You get a sense of what it was like to be frightened out of
your wits when a column of Redcoats comes at you, with bayonets
fixed, looking 7 feet tall in their fur hats. You feel the fear the
common man must have felt. You realize that these were ordinary
people in extraordinary times.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer appreciates the show as well as the history lesson. He
cited ``a wonderful scene'' two years ago at Battle Road featuring
historical interpreter Myles McConnon of Bolton, who was helping
answer questions along the bike path in the national park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I observed that the Regulars and the minutemen were out in
force, and so were the cyclists, dressed as if they had descended
from another planet, with their helmets and vinyl cycling suits,''
Fischer said. ``They were coming up in family groups, and they
stopped when they saw Myles in character, dressed in his
18th-century civilian costume.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the children who noticed first. They screeched to a
halt and began to gather around Myles as he talked. And then their
parents came over, and soon after another cyclist, and then
another. Pretty soon there was a crowd, and it occurred to me that
the impact of the event was striking home.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a teacher, I think this is one of the great teaching
opportunities, to help explain a moment in world history. The
impact of that battle reverberated through the Colonies and then it
began to spread around the world, not only to Britain and Europe,
but to other places as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to think of a moment that has had such a sharp
impact on our lives,'' Fischer said. ``There's that political
slogan, `Think nationally but act locally.' Here, it was, `Act
locally and think universally.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
