<SLUG> BC-REENACT-UNIFORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE IS THERE: PASSING MUSTER AS A MINUTEMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY DROHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Mass. _ When in the course of human events it becomes
necessary to don short pants and fight the Redcoats, I am there.
</P>
<P>
   I am a member of Colonel Bailey's 2nd Massachusetts Regiment,
enlisting for three hours to experience the living history hobby on
a sunny Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It's a glorious day for time travel here on the grounds of
Buckman Tavern. You can step off Massachusetts Avenue and into
1775. Or you can drift in on the strains of ``Yankee Doodle'' on
the fife and drum and join the 300 men, women and children at the
``muster.''
</P>
<P>
   The event is a sort of dress rehearsal for Battle Road 2000, the
five-day pageant scheduled April 13-17 to celebrate the 225th
anniversary of the battle of Lexington and Concord with a cast of
2,000, the largest Revolutionary War reenactment ever held in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   I am turned out in a striking red and blue ensemble provided by
my haberdasher/historian, Henry Cooke of Randolph. This
hand-stitched, authentic garb is comfortable: red coat with
hand-embroidered buttons, matching breeches, buff stockings, blue
waistcoat, and a floppy black hat, roughly the same outfit my
brother wears golfing.
</P>
<P>
   Should I adopt a persona, as many re-enactors do, or just wing
it? Being a raw recruit, I go with Option 2. I'm a well-dressed,
generic minuteman from Reading. I carry a musket, a .69-caliber
French Charleville replica that is heavy, awkward, and (by design)
doesn't work. It's just my kind of weapon.
</P>
<P>
   I am also equipped with a wooden canteen, which I plan to fill
later at the tavern, and a leather cartridge box (only one
cartridge; don't tell the Brits). A sharp, pointy thing is attached
by a fine chain to the box. I wonder what it is, besides my most
effective armament.
</P>
<P>
   I report to the commanding officer of Bailey's, Captain Brad
Chetwynd, 58, of Dracut, a veteran of more than 500 reenactments in
25 years of ``the hobby.'' He is turned out in a snappy purple
``sleeved waistcoat'' made by his wife, Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   The captain sizes me up and steers me toward the rear rank of
the 50-member troop. On the way, he gives me the lowdown on
musters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of veterans before the Revolution, colonists
who had fought on the British side in the French and Indian War,''
Chetwynd tells me. ``They would hold periodic militia days, or
muster days, not only for military training but as a social outing
for the families. It became a major social event. Of course at some
point, the rum keg would be broken out.''
</P>
<P>
   My captain places me carefully in the last rank, alongside other
``private soldiers.'' They are a friendly lot, people who make
their own authentic outfits, sign e-mails to each other ``Yr
Obedient Servant,'' and grumble good-naturedly in 18th-century
vernacular about Army life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lads,'' says Captain Chetwynd. ``Stand by for a safety
inspection and a clothing inspection. We'll get orders soon from
the commanding officer, whom I happen to know personally.'' Eric
Chetwynd, one of Brad's two sons, is commander of the 1st Battalion
for the Battle Road event.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we drill. I am an inept soldier, but my comrades are
indulgent, having fought for the inalienable American right to fake
it. I love this hat, but the huge brim is a liability on the parade
ground. I keep knocking it off with my musket when the order is
``shoulder arms.'' It might well be ``dislodge hats.'' I keep
jabbing myself with the sharp, pointy thing.
</P>
<P>
   I try to focus on not injuring anyone with my Charleville as
shoulder-to-shoulder (and I mean exactly that) we practice
marching, pivoting, and facing about. There is a neat maneuver
where we all face about quickly, each grabbing his cartridge box so
it doesn't swing out and whack the neighbors. I have to grab my hat
instead.
</P>
<P>
   So I apologize to those I whack with my cartridge box: Kimball
Tarr of Merrimac; Troy Richards and Patrick Fennelly of Reading;
Larry Sands, Dave Pirie, and Tom Frary of Marblehead; Mike Thompson
of Haverhill; Jeff Rider of Hudson, N.H., and Cathy Sminkey of
Chelmsford, known in the troop as ``Charles.'' Also, her husband,
Scott. Also, those two 9-year-old drummers, the elderly fifer, and
the bicyclist. The British sergeant major I whacked on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``You did fine,'' says the regiment's first sergeant, Mark
Nowacki of Wilmington. He acknowledges the drill is not always
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes `dress right' looks like `sidle right' or `drift
right,' '' he says, to the amusement of the lads. ``And then
there's ``mill about, smartly.''
</P>
<P>
   To my great joy, he brings up the sharp, pointy things, even
calling them that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget, `Adjust pointy things,' '' he says, ``or the
ever-popular, `Hurl pointy things!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, ``What's that pointy thing?'' is a common question
among spectators. It's called a vent pick, Nowacki says, used for
cleaning the vent on the side of the musket.
</P>
<P>
   We ``stand down'' for a rest. I seek advice from a more
experienced soldier, Sterling T. Wall of Shirley. This 11-year-old
sixth-grader has done dozens of reenactments, including Quebec and
Mount Vernon, with his father, Sterling Wall. The youth gives me a
few pointers, along with his reason for being here: ``It's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterling the elder drills us, then demonstrates how to load a
musket, a procedure largely lost on us because I am a noncombatant,
and Sterling the younger uses an all-wood weapon.
</P>
<P>
   We fall in for the final assembly. As we hurry up and wait, a
splendidly dressed British officer watches us from a distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lads,'' says our captain, ``you might notice that British
officer over there, with his beautiful new boots. Take a good look.
I might remind you that your captain has no boots.''
</P>
<P>
   The call sounds for assembly. To drum and fife, we parade by the
townspeople. A sudden gust of wind whisks my hat 20 feet away. I
cannot break ranks and fetch it without embarrassing the unit. A
kindly camp follower rushes in to retrieve it. She catches up to
the troop, hands it to me, smiles encouragement. No one breaks
stride.
</P>
<P>
   Now I get it. With that little drama, I transcend time. Because
the action is unscripted, I am not consciously pretending. I just
need my hat. For a few brief moments, I am definitely in the 18th
century.
</P>
<P>
   At assembly, the Battle Road commander, Colonel Gardner ``Skip''
Hayward of the Lexington minutemen, offers bold words against the
crown, which the entire company punctuates with spirited shouts of
``Huzzah! Huzzah!'' in unison.
</P>
<P>
   We are dismissed. My enlistment is up. I say good day to my
captain, who invites me to reenlist anytime. As I head for the
stables, I'm thinking that the hobby offers something for everyone,
be it research into geneaology, military tactics, encampment,
cooking in the manner of the time, music, or clothing.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the intangibles are the attraction. I mean, how often do
you get a chance to be among a crowd that shouts ``Huzzah!
Huzzah!'' in unison?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
