<SLUG> BC-FLFEEING-JOURNALIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN AS EXILE, HE ARGUES FOR AID TO COLOMBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Each lives in exile in Miami, just a few miles
apart, their families left behind, their fate in Washington's
hands.
</P>
<P>
   But that's where the lives of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez of Cuba
and 38-year-old Francisco Santos of Colombia part. Americans have
been seeing pictures of Elian on his swingset every day, caught in
a media glare so bright that it has obscured a world of other
stories, particularly in Cuba's backyard _ tensions in Venezuela
and Ecuador, an assassination of a journalist in Haiti, and
questions about elections in Peru and Haiti, among them.
</P>
<P>
   It has also obscured much of what is happening in Colombia, the
country from which ``Pancho'' Santos fled last month. Several Latin
American experts say his story has far greater ramifications for US
national interests than the drama of whether a boy and his father
will be reunited.
</P>
<P>
   Santos left his homeland after he learned a guerrilla commander
in the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia _ known as the FARC _
had ordered his death. The guerrillas were angered by newspaper
columns Santos wrote that were critical of the guerrillas'
reluctance to make peace in that country's ongoing civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Although Colombians routinely flee their country's violence,
Santos's departure shocked Colombians and US policy makers alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is someone from one of the most prominent families of
Colombia, running the largest newspaper, a leader in the peace
movement, having to flee. It's like having (former Washington Post
publisher) Katharine Graham forced out of the country,'' said Adam
Isacson, senior associate at the Center for International Policy.
``It means even in Bogota, even among the elite, you're not safe
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Santos's escape adds to the mounting anecdotal evidence that
Colombia is growing ever more violent, just at the time when
Congress debates whether to send $1.7 billion to fight drugs along
the Andean ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Should that add urgency in favor of passing the funding package?
Or should it give members of Congress pause before committing to a
deteriorating situation?
</P>
<P>
   Santos, a former Nieman Foundation fellow at Harvard University,
believes Washington should approve the money; if it doesn't, he
said, it would be a ``huge blow'' to Colombia President Andres
Pastrana, who has pushed for a peace agreement. Santos quietly
delivered that message last week to several members of Congress at
a dinner arranged by US Representative William Delahunt, a
Massachusetts Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said, in an interview later, that he would prefer to
see the US anti-drug spending come in the form of, say, $150
million to use on alternative crop development, rather than 63
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives hope for the future,'' Santos said, relaxing in the
elegant sitting room at the home of his friend Luis Alberto Moreno,
Colombia's ambassador to the United States. Seven vases of cut
Colombian roses were arranged around the room, a silver bowl of
unwrapped chocolates were not far from his fingers. ``The plan is
critically important now. Otherwise, if it doesn't happen, it could
generate a lot more violence. There's still going to be violence no
matter what, but we need a symbol of hope to move forward. And the
only hope is now the States.''
</P>
<P>
   Santos could be a character out of a Gabriel Garcia Marquez
novel, his story having the feel of his country's history _ the
boyish aristocrat kidnapped by drug lords, chained to a bed for 263
days, let go and years later leading a massive peace movement
called ``No Mas,'' or No More. And now, living far from home, apart
from his wife and their four children.
</P>
<P>
   But, in Santos's case, real life made a better story than
fiction; rather than write a novel about Santos, Garcia Marquez
wrote a nonfiction account of his kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   And Santos's life has, at times, seemed stranger than fiction.
Only four days after he was released in 1990, Santos found himself
in Cambridge, Mass., accepted as a fellow in Harvard's journalism
program, getting a taste of life in the United States for a year
before returning to the struggle in his country.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's back, in exile, and will attend a Nieman reunion later
this month, as he tries to readjust to life here. He says he's
finding it extremely difficult, and he deeply misses his wife and
children, who stayed behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some days when I can barely get out of bed. I say,
`Why am I here? My life is there, my country is there.' It's a lot
harder than I thought,'' Santos said. ``I'm even getting flashbacks
from the time of my kidnapping. I'm doing math equations in my
head. It's been 10 years since I did this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he harbors no second thoughts about leaving; he had heard
for months that a FARC commander wanted him dead, and early last
month he became sure of it when a known hit squad came looking for
him in a restaurant only minutes after he had left.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling to Washington last week invigorated Santos. Robert
White, former US ambassador to El Salvador and Paraguay and now
president of the Center for International Policy in Washington,
said he was most impressed with one of Santos's suggestions for
congressmen: Go visit the guerrillas _ the people who want Santos
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands that you need to include them,'' White said.
``I think he will go back. Some of us will be working on the FARC
to try to get some guarantees for his safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Santos said he would return if the peace process advances
significantly, or if, as he put it, ``I get tired of this and go
home and risk my life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Donnelly is the Globe's diplomatic correspondent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
