<HEADLINE>
IT'S RUSSIA'S VERY LIVED-IN GHOST TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ In a dimly-lit room on the sixth floor
of a crumbling walk-up, Konstantin the Wizard faced a pale thin
young woman. He lit a candle, asked the woman to close her eyes,
and began the ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Konstantin waved the candle clockwise, forming large circles in
front of the woman. After the seventh circle, he made seven signs
of the cross. He repeated the procedure three more times _ from
behind the woman, to her left and to her right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this dirt!'' Konstantin said as he pointed to the
greenish wax that oozed from the candle. ``This was inside her. It
is the negative energy that was disturbing her.''
</P>
<P>
   Konstantin sees ghosts everywhere and he knows how to get rid of
them _ a craft he said he learned from his grandfather. For $35, he
will cleanse an apartment of evil spirits. For $20 he will wave his
magic candle and purge people of what he calls ``bad energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Konstantin won't give his last name. His advertisement in local
newspapers reads simply ``Wizard,'' and gives his telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you feel any better? Do you feel lighter?'' Konstantin
asked the woman, who had been suffering from stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I do. I feel like I could fall asleep,'' she answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good. Now I want you to imagine all the people, living or
dead, who have hurt you, and I want you to forgive them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them I can't forgive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgive them!'' he commanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgive them,'' she said softly, after a long pause.
</P>
<P>
   Most large cities have their ghost legends, and one can find
people like Konstantin anywhere in the world, but St. Petersburg
provides a particularly fertile ground for the services he offers.
</P>
<P>
   This town takes its ghosts seriously.
</P>
<P>
   People here will tell you with a straight face that spirits roam
St. Petersburg's streets, canals, alleys, and courtyards. Stay here
long enough and you begin to believe them.
</P>
<P>
   There is something about the way dilapidated buildings here cast
rippling shadows on the canals, the way the wind oozes through the
maze-like adjoining courtyards, which suggests that even when you
are alone _ you are not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Below, in unmarked graves, lie the remains of hundreds of
thousands of people who died building the city three centuries ago
_ earning St. Petersburg the ghastly moniker ``Gorod na Kostyakh,''
the ``City on the Bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Even politicians here feel the need to pay homage to the
supernatural aura. Anatoly Sobchak, the city's former mayor, had
admitted to believing in mysticism. He said he was convinced that
Russia was doomed to endless tribulations until the remains of
Soviet founder Vladimir Lenin were removed from their Red Square
mausoleum and given a proper burial.
</P>
<P>
   And the city's current leader, Vladimir Yakovlev, has invoked
other worldly explanations for tragic misfortunes.
</P>
<P>
   In June of last year, when the roof of a downtown subway station
collapsed, killing seven people, Yakovlev suggested that a vengeful
God _ as opposed to municipal negligence _ had caused the tragedy.
He noted that Communist authorities, in the 1960s, had destroyed a
church to build the subway station.
</P>
<P>
   Lev Lurie, a prominent local historian, conceded that St.
Petersburg ``is definitely a very strange city,'' but said he does
not believe in the supernatural. ``Everything here can be explained
rationally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others are not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The border between the mystical and the rational in St.
Petersburg is very thin,'' said Viktor Krivulin, a local poet.
``Looking at St. Petersburg's history without the mystical element
is like playing Chopin on the piano and only using the white
keys.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Brian Whitmore is based in Moscow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
