<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CUBA-POLICY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICY REVIEW ON CUBA LIKELY, US OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once the shouting stops in the Elian Gonzalez case,
the larger issue of US-Cuba relations is headed for a broad
reexamination in the coming months, Clinton administration
officials and members of Congress say.
</P>
<P>
   The result could soon be a number of small but portentous new
changes in the prickly relationship, from new exemptions to the US
trade embargo and making it easier for Cuban-Americans to visit the
island, to a possible weakening of the political clout of exiles in
Florida and elsewhere who are opposed to Cuban President Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic and Republican members of Congress have
predicted a backlash against the Cuban-American protesters in Miami
for their vociferous demands that the boy stay in the United
States. National polls show 60 percent of Americans favor reuniting
the boy with his father, who now waits in a Cuban diplomat's home
in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   It is also significant, said three US officials in interviews
last week, that for the first time in recent memory US and Cuban
governments were publicly and prominently working together on the
same side of an issue _ reuniting father and son.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is likely to produce a dramatic change in the near
term, the US officials said, but it is expected to create a renewed
focus on US policy toward the island and could spur incremental
changes in the longstanding American trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will continue to look at constructive ways of
moving things ahead in small ways,'' said one US official, speaking
on condition of anonymity. ``I don't expect anything dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has had a unilateral economic embargo against
Cuba for nearly four decades, sanctions that began with the premise
_ now largely discounted _ that Cuba was a threat to US security.
Four years ago, Clinton signed the Helms-Burton law, which further
tightened the terms of the embargo, giving Congress the power to
approve any major changes toward normalization with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to enact some small changes is either up for
consideration in Congress or is being prepared in congressional
offices. Among the possibilities in the next year: legislation that
would exempt food and medicine from the embargo and would allow
easier terms for exiles to visit family in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, the two governments have cooperated in
smaller endeavors. The most promising one is the sharing of
information in antidrug operations. Officials also have worked
together on environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Many more Americans have begun touring Cuba in recent years as
travel restrictions have eased. The Clinton administration has also
allowed Cuban-Americans to send larger remittances to their
families back home and has opened the embargo slightly to permit
sales of certain agricultural and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But since Elian was found floating barely conscious on an inner
tube near Fort Lauderdale more than four months ago and the custody
issue became so contentious, officials in the White House and
National Security Council have carefully skirted issues having to
do with Cuba. One White House official said there has been no
e-mail traffic on Cuban issues over the last several months. That
is highly unusual, the official said, calling it an indicator of
the political sensitivity arising from the custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the battle over Cuba policy already is bubbling up, whether
senior US officials like it or not, and Cuban-Americans are girding
to defend the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite clear that the strategy of the left and other
sundry embargo haters on this issue is to exploit some of the
dynamics of this Elian issue to demonize the Cuban-American
community and, by extension, delegitimize US policy toward Cuba,''
said Jose R. Cardenas, Washington director of the Cuban American
National Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as if a hound has picked up the scent of the
fox,'' he continued. ``I have in mind someone like (US
Representative) Maxine Waters. They smell blood and they are
proceeding apace. I think it is a great miscalculation on their
part. I see a rejuvenated Cuban-American community that is going to
be even more vigilant to anybody attempting to exploit the Elian
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters, a California Democrat, could not be reached for comment,
but her spokesman, Frank Phillips said, ``Her main focus is
reuniting the son with his father. She's never been in favor of
politicizing this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters had previously called for closer US-Cuba relations. She
is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry, the Massachusetts Democrat and member of
the Foreign Relations Committee, said in an interview that a
reevaluation of relations with Cuba was ``way overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a frozen, stalemated, counterproductive policy that is
not in humanitarian interests nor in our larger credibility
interest in the region,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   While saying that US diplomats should not unilaterally remove
the sanctions, he said, ``There is just a complete and total
contradiction between the way we deal with China, the way we dealt
with Russia, the way we have been dealing with Cuba over the last
(several) years. It speaks volumes about the problems in the
current American electoral process. . . . The only reason we don't
reevaluate the policy is the politics of Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   In Florida and New Jersey, Cuban-Americans form powerful voting
blocs, giving them key leverage in the presidential electoral
counts. Both major presidential candidates, Vice President Al Gore
and Texas Governor George W. Bush, have sided with those who want
Elian to stay in the United States, saying they want a family court
to decide the issue, not the Immigration and Naturalization
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Chuck Hagel, a Nebraska Republican, said there was ``no
question that the mishandling of this case is going to have
consequences in the future regarding Cuban-American policy. Will it
change? Of course it's going to change. We have an irrelevant
anachronistic policy toward Cuba. Everyone is trading with Castro
and Cuba except the US.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel, who cosponsored legislation to exempt food and medicine
from the embargo, said the debate over Elian has ``brought some
transparency to the political hold that the anti-Castro
Cuban-Americans have held on Florida and New Jersey politics. It
holds the same hostage factor on American politics because of the
larger electoral votes in Florida and New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, government officials are less optimistic that the Elian
drama has created openings for Havana and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true, the United States government has taken the right
position that Elian should be with his father,'' one Cuban official
said. ``But it has failed to carry out its own laws mostly because
it fears upsetting the right-wing (Cuban-American) community in
Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred L. Padula, professor emeritus of history at the
University of Southern Maine in Portland and a former State
Department Cuba analyst, said he was cautiously optimistic about
warming relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been disappointed so many times in the past, but it
seems to be kind of a real drift of a renewal of relations,''
Padula said.
</P>
<P>
   One factor, he noted, may be changing American attitudes toward
Cuba. Those perceptions, he said, may be subtly altered by the
pictures of Elian himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those saying we can't send Elian back to terrible Cuba because
life would be hell for Elian, well, take a look at Elian,'' Padula
said. ``He looks pretty healthy to me. Maybe that says Cuba isn't
so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cardenas and the anti-Castro Cuban-American foundation,
however, the perception about Cuba that must endure is this:
Elian's mother risked and lost her life trying to escape the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cuban community is like a wounded bear right now,'' he
said. ``There is a tremendous sense of frustration, and we will
very much advocate that Cuban-Americans work out their frustrations
at the ballot box.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe reporters Richard Chacon in Havana and Charles Radin in
Boston contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
