<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-AFRICA-PROGRESS-BOS &LR;      04-10 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-PROGRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAISSANCE IN TROUBLED AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda _ With the Cold War and apartheid consigned to
history, it has become fashionable among African leaders and
intellectuals to talk of an African ``renaissance,'' an era of hope
and progress flowering on the world's most troubled continent.
</P>
<P>
   That notion _ the centerpiece of a conference this weekend near
Johannesburg _ invites skepticism. Africa still appears to be a
playground of malevolent forces. Critics point no further than
Congo, where 10 sovereign states and 11 guerrilla armies wage
tangled wars and cart off natural resources. As The Economist
magazine's intelligence unit put it, ``one obvious casualty of
(Congo) is the African renaissance. . . . That vision now lies in
ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   But such conclusions dismiss the fundamental difference between
Africa's past and present conflicts: For the first time since
Portuguese trading ships anchored off the coast of Angola 500 years
ago, Africa is determining its own course. The conflict in Congo _
dubbed the continent's ``first world war'' _ marks the birth, not
the death, of a new African order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Africans should resolve their own problems as they understand
them,'' said Bizima Karaha, leader of one rebel faction fighting
against the Congolese government. ``That is the beginning of the
African renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, when Makau Mutua, a human rights lawyer from Kenya,
first presented the concept of an African renaissance,
inconceivable changes were sweeping the globe. The Soviet Union had
vanished, Germany reunified, democratic reforms galloped across
Eastern Europe, and the Balkans had not yet revealed their horrors.
</P>
<P>
   Across Africa, the end of the Cold War broke the grip of long
civil wars and brutal dictatorships. Angola and Mozambique, two
US-Soviet battlegrounds since 1974, were moving toward a negotiated
peace. Nelson Mandela was a free man and apartheid was crumbling.
Countries from Mali to Zambia were ceding to popular demands for
pluralism. ``Africans stand at the threshold of a new epoch . . .
(a) democratic renaissance,'' Mutua declared.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1990s turned out to be one of the bloodiest decades on
record in Africa. Rwanda horrified the world with an ethnic
genocidal rampage carried out with more efficiency than the Nazi
campaign against Europe's Jews: some 800,000 people slaughtered in
less than three months. Angola's peace process collapsed and the
country is now back to war. An estimated 16,000 South Africans died
in the final throes of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   Such foul play is not over. Ivory Coast rang in the new year
with a military coup d'etat. Namibian President Sam Nujoma altered
the country's constitution to extend his rule. Soldiers mutilated
civilians in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   It is conceivable, even probable, that things will worsen before
they get better. As peace efforts falter in Congo, rising ethnic
hatred threatens to transport the fighting to Rwanda and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   But the turmoil in Africa today is inevitable, as the old order
_ shaped by colonialism and the Cold War _ breaks apart. These
conflicts, while easily misread, represent a kind of progress, a
march toward a more stable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are principled wars,'' said Patrick Mazimhaka, Rwanda's
chief peace negotiator in Congo. ``They have nothing to do with
American policies in Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Positive trends course beneath the tumultuous surface.
Devastated by one of Africa's longest civil wars, Mozambique is
today a model of accommodation. Two parties that once fought each
other with unspeakable brutality contested their second peaceful,
democratic elections in December. Bush warfare has given way to
parliamentary debate.
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe, civil society is making a brave stand against an
increasingly violent and menacing autocrat. While President Robert
Mugabe manipulates racial and political tensions ahead of
parliamentary elections next month, a growing opposition movement
rallies the public to force a peaceful end to bad governance.
</P>
<P>
   Blind non-interference, the longstanding first tenet of African
diplomacy, is yielding as Africans engage in a more concerted
approach to progress. They are forging integrated regional markets
and espousing higher ideals of governance. Perhaps most important,
the gun is no longer the first tool of dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go through this period of chaos to sort out the
mess. Had the Cold War not been so hot in Africa, people might have
worried more about good governance,'' said Jan van Eck, a
specialist on Central Africa at the Center for Conflict Resolution
in Cape Town. ``Africa has a culture of violence: If you have a
problem, shoot at it. Now we need to legitimize dialogue as a means
for solving problems.''
</P>
<P>
   That's happening with greater frequency. African leaders from
Uganda to South Africa have been involved almost continuously in
seeking a solution to Congo since the war broke out 20 months ago.
Their failure so far does not subtract from the significance of
their efforts, argued Cedric de Coning, an analyst at the African
Center for the Constructive Resolution of Disputes in Durban. The
process itself is unprecedented in African diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Burundi's fractured parties last November tapped Mandela to
jump-start their stalled talks on ending the central African
state's civil war. Last week Mandela brought in Olusegun Obasanjo,
the new democratic president of Nigeria, to help push for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Both men made urgent appeals for movement toward majority rule.
But their presence alone was more significant than anything either
could have said. Never before have South Africa and Nigeria been
ruled by democratic leaders at the same time. The joint involvement
of Mandela and Obasanjo in Burundi illustrates the potential
stabilizing influence of the budding relationship between their two
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Africa is not totally unfettered by foreign influences and
global economics. France admitted to organizing the coup in Ivory
Coast. ``But foreign powers don't have the leverage they used to
have,'' Van Eck said. ``We're in a completely different era.''
</P>
<P>
   The continent today rests in the hands of a new generation of
political and business leaders. Many were schooled in the West,
most were forged by struggles not against colonialism but the
corrupt authoritarian regimes that followed. They experiment with
democratic models and design grand visions. Their policies have
sometimes drawn suspicions _ Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
allows no parties; Paul Kagame, the military wunderkind from
Rwanda, launched two wars against Congo (formerly Zaire) in pursuit
of ethnic harmony _ but they reflect African aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the new architects of an African renaissance is
Thabo Mbeki, the new president of South Africa. A formidable
intellect, Mbeki seeks a vigorous African transformation from
poverty and misrule to prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, South Africa's white rulers bombed African
capitals, sabotaged power pylons and railroad tracks, and fought
bush wars to prevent black rule at home. Today, South Africa is the
driving force of integration, security, and development on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such change, Mbeki knows that negative images carry
further. At an economic summit in Namibia nearly two years ago, he
told a fable of a fictional town in Mississippi. When Somalis
consume their country in clan rivalry and Togo's president steals
an election, he said, and then Africans speak of a renaissance, the
people of that Mississippi town laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we must stop the laughter,'' Mbeki said. ``We have to
rebel against political instability on our continent, because when
something goes wrong in Somalia, the residents of Dead Man's Creek
do not say something has gone wrong in Somalia. They say something
has gone wrong in Africa. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``To achieve an African renewal in politics, in economics, in
social life, and in culture we have to act together as Africans. If
we are not willing to do it, the citizens of Dead Man's Creek will
continue to laugh.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
