<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2143 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-UGANDA-IMAGE-REVIEW     04-10 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-UGANDA-IMAGE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UGANDA'S TRAUMA: A DEADLY CULT STIRS QUESTIONS ABOUT A NATION'S
SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The news out of Uganda has been very bad, and
that nation's two daily newspapers have spared their readers none
of it. For three days running, the state-owned paper, The New
Vision, ran front-page, full-color photos of rotting corpses _ a
sad few of the perhaps 900 victims of a deadly cult, the Movement
for the Restoration of the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures were so awful that investigators have now barred
cameras from any other grave sites they may find, a possibility
that is depressingly likely. The New Vision received many
complaints about the photos, perhaps loudest from government
officials.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone thought the decision to publish them was wrong.
For Uganda has been groping for explanations for the mass killings,
and alongside sensationalism in the daily press there has been a
remarkably frank discussion of the roots of the problem _ most
interestingly, a tracing of the current religiosity and mysticism
associated with cults to the despair left by years of dictatorship,
poverty, AIDS and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion in the press, in both its liveliness and
thoughtfulness, mirrors a larger discussion taking place in Ugandan
society about the cult and the murders, and this reveals a great
deal about Uganda itself _ how far it has come in its tortured
passage of 38 years from independence, through a brutal
dictatorship and at last toward a society where open expression is
recognized as a tool for solving the nation's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to be shocked,'' said the Rev. John Mary Waliggo, a
Catholic priest who is one of Uganda's human rights commissioners
and a professor of African history, after the photos were
published. ``From this shock, we will be able to find out what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the pictures were just part of the aggressive coverage
of the cult murders by Uganda's two papers, The New Vision and The
Monitor, and their coverage has mirrored Ugandans' general
reaction: shock, horror, a search for blame, along with an ample
measure of ``What will the world think of Uganda now?''
</P>
<P>
   That last thought is predictable. It has been only 21 years
since the dictator Idi Amin was deposed after a rule of brutality
and death that made Uganda a synonym for state-sponsored horror.
</P>
<P>
   But in the years since, Uganda has developed in a way that might
surprise most outsiders. It has become one of the brightest spots
of central Africa, with a growing economy and an intriguing leader,
a left-leaning former rebel, Yoweri Museveni, who talks loudly
about his ideas for everything from cattle-rearing to toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were aware that it was a danger to Uganda's image abroad''
when the cult story broke, said William Pike, a Briton who is the
editor of The New Vision. ``But we didn't let that get in the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. In few African countries could a story headlined, ``Are
you in a cult?'' run next to another headlined, ``Why have I lost
my sex drive?'' This happened in the March 23 edition of The New
Vision. But while some of the coverage has been sensationalistic _
headlines like ``Another Grave!'' and speculation that the victims
may have actually been Muslim fundamentalists because some men were
circumcised _ most of it has been straight and has pulled few
punches.
</P>
<P>
   Both The Monitor (independent, with a circulation of 26,000) and
The New Vision (state owned but independent in its news coverage,
with a circulation of 35,000) have seriously posed the questions:
``Why this?'' and ``Why Uganda?''
</P>
<P>
   And so they have devoted much space to Uganda's history of
combining religion and violence (three rebel groups over the last
15 years have claimed religious inspiration). Over the years, the
papers have also spent much time looking into problems of poverty
and development and the spread of AIDS, which Waliggo said in an
interview is the chief culprit behind religious sects that have
healing and miracles as their hallmarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have sought healing as a religion,'' he said. ``Western
medicine can't heal them, and many fear African traditional
medicine.'' When people have problems, he said, they will turn to
whatever looks most attractive _ and Uganda happens to have more
than its fair share of fringe religious groups, many bordering on
mystical cults.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, the difference between religion and magic is very
narrow,'' he said. ``You can pass from one to the other very
easily. It is like sanity and insanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more thoughtful newspaper coverage in this vein has
come from the editor of The Monitor, Charles Onyango-Obbo, who in
his columns has stitched together politics, poverty and the
failings of established churches in his search for answers as deep
as the problems his people face.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the shortcomings of religion, he wrote: ``There is
reason therefore to fear that what has been burnt and buried in
Kanungu are only the bodies of the members of the Movement for the
Restoration of the Ten Commandments. Its spirit remains very much
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that all the discussion here has been so somber or
speculative. Some of the newspaper coverage, in fact, has been
almost mythic, like a long piece in The New Vision about the rise
of cults of the Virgin Mary. This included a description of a
Rwandan beauty, Specioza Mukantabona, who had claimed visions of
the Virgin. She was, the article said, disgraced after skeptics
traced her ability to bleed divinely from the mouth to
blood-bloated ticks under her tongue. After that, the paper noted,
``She easily turned into one of the most expensive prostitutes of
modern times.''
</P>
<P>
   The papers have also won some small victories. They questioned
why Uganda's security departments did not realize earlier that the
cult might be a threat. The government has since officially
apologized. And they questioned why most of the exhumation of
corpses has been carried out by prisoners, with bare hands. The
government suspended digging until it could buy gloves and masks.
</P>
<P>
   But Onyango-Obbo, the Monitor editor, has included the press in
his list of those who should shoulder some blame. Because Uganda
has suffered so much abuse at the hands of its government, he said
in an interview, the press has not been well equipped to ask the
probing questions that could help Ugandans understand the
desperation of people who would join a murderous cult and believe
so blindly in its empty promises. ``In this country,'' he said,
``it was always the government committing the crimes. So we didn't
have to do any soul-searching on a personal level.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
