<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2145 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0411     04-10 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0411 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spring arrives with the pitter patter of little claws
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It's a sure sign of spring, or that I've had
enough winter, when I catch myself doing odd things like making
backyard chat with a couple of fat squirrels who just happen to be
complaining because their breakfast is late. I remind them they're
living in my trees, rent-free, so maybe they'd better show some
appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, by the time I shuffle up to the kitchen sink to
fill the kettle, Albert is doing rodent calisthenics on a limb just
outside the window. He nails me with his beady little eyes.
</P>
<P>
   When I step onto the back porch to change into my yard shoes,
Benjamin (I name them alphabetically) is plastered half-way up the
screen door, clucking and whipping his tail in annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cut me some slack, here,'' I mutter, shoving him out of the
way with the door so I can get out. ``Remember, I'm wise to you
guys. You think I don't know you're only a fuzzy tail away from a
rat?''
</P>
<P>
   Albert clicks his little claws down the side of a favored pine
and joins in the tirade. Now there are two of them protesting. I
remind them I'm bigger than they are and a whole lot smarter.
Benjamin suggests that if I were really as smart as I think I am,
he'd be the one hauling home 40-pound bags of sunflower seeds from
the feed store instead of me.
</P>
<P>
   According to the calendar, winter's gone, but around here that
doesn't mean for sure the birdbath won't freeze up one more time,
or that it's not going to snow all over Miss Maybelle's new Easter
bonnet, but today promises to be warm and sunny.
</P>
<P>
   It's still early enough in the morning for cardinals to be at
the feeders because, as my son once explained, they prefer to feed
in dusky light. Makes it tougher for the neighborhood cats to spot
their vivid red feathers. Sparrows and finches flutter back and
forth, and a nuthatch is hanging upside down from the trunk of
Albert's condo.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of bluejays raucously swap bird jokes. ``Didja hear the
one about the owl and the farmer's daughter?'' They share a shriek.
I can only guess at the punchline.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of mourning doves head-bob their way around the base of
the feeders, unwilling and ill-equipped for the gymnastics of
perching. These guys always seem to be in a bad mood, arguing over
territory and slapping their wings to intimidate, as they flutter
out of each other's way. Makes me wonder how they came to be the
symbol of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't seen the raccoon yet or any of his telltale droppings on
the porch roof, but Biddy knows he's in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Late the other night I was stretched out in the tub, idly
contemplating my big toe sticking up through the bubbles as Biddy,
my Siamese guardian and resident nag, lay on the bathmat dreaming
of catnip mice and laps that never move. A whisker shuddered, then
a paw, and then in one fluid motion she leapt up, let out a banshee
wail, and raced off.
</P>
<P>
   Bedrooms to basement and back she went, summoning guttural
growls from the very pads on her feet. Eyebrows up and tail fur
standing at attention, she was on the third circuit when she
skidded into the bathroom and, due to a slight miscalculation,
landed smack on my chest in a foot of water. She froze and stared _
like it was all my fault.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly fresh out of energy and ideas, she flopped and lay
there, paws awash, tail swishing bubbles onto the tile, and looked
embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   Later, we sat together on the bathroom floor wrapped in towels
as I attempted to restore her feline dignity. ``It's spring,'' I
explained patting her face dry. ``Even people get goofy.'' She
turned an icy blue stare on me, worked one paw out of her terry
cloth cocoon, and tentatively placed it on my mouth.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect she found the comparison odious.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail to: 320
West Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail:
eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
