<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CDNow is struggling, and I hope it survives
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first CD I ever bought over the Internet was from
CDNow, an online retailer now, sadly, on the skids.
</P>
<P>
   It was recommended to me by a co-worker who happened to know the
two brothers, Jason and Matthew Olim, who founded the company.
</P>
<P>
   CDNow was a wonderful source of online music launched by these
two music lovers who were frustrated by music store clerks and
often-dismal selections in the brick-and-mortar superstores like
Tower Records.
</P>
<P>
   CDNow was _ and still is _ a great place to find music from that
obscure Celtic rock band you've been hearing about or to track down
the latest techno, blues or other favorites average retailers don't
stock.
</P>
<P>
   The site is also a great source for all kinds of music, for all
kinds of tastes. Users can even make their own CDs from a selection
of music the company provides. Prices can run a little high
sometimes, but if you absolutely, positively must have your
favorite CD from your favorite artist, it's a Web site worth
checking out.
</P>
<P>
   But late last week, word went out that CDNow is in some serious
financial trouble. Shares took a big tumble to a record low of
$3.41, after the accounting firm of Arthur Andersen expressed
concerns. CDNow's shortage of working capital, losses from
operations and significant payments due this year for marketing
agreements raised a flag with the accounting company.
</P>
<P>
   CDNow says it has enough cash on hand to meet its obligations,
and that it has retained an investment banking firm to explore
options _ such as a possible sale or additional financing
arrangements. One potential merger with the Columbia House music
club fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   In the investor relations section of the CDNow site _
considerably off the beaten path before the financial woes became
public _ the company insists it has plenty of cash and plenty of
options.
</P>
<P>
   For people who love music and who love the myriad unique options
the Web provides, CDNow's troubles are worth noting.
</P>
<P>
   Just last January, the Olim brothers wrote a book documenting
their success called ``The CDNow Story: Rags to Riches on the
Internet'' with the subtitle ``How two kids in a basement grabbed
the online music business.''
</P>
<P>
   But what a difference a year makes. CDNow, the online music
store that could find anything for anybody, now must find its own
way. It faces stiff competition not just from online retailing
behemoth Amazon.com but from a variety of online record stores
including brick-and-mortar stalwarts Tower Records and the Virgin
Megastores. Truly savvy surfers can even navigate to sites all
around the world and come up with Brazilian, French or Israeli
music they can't find at their local store.
</P>
<P>
   CDNow has become the virtual ``shop around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   The small music store that features variety is in danger of
losing everything, at least partly because the big superstores like
Amazon and Tower, latecomers, are bigger, cheaper and armed with
slicker technology to make the shopping experience easy and
efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Things like this happen in the real world all the time. Small,
friendly neighborhood bookstores get put out of business by the
superstore that sets up shop down the street. Small, family-owned
record companies can't compete with the volume discounts and miles
of floor space in the huge record stores. Now, with digital
download technology, some music fans aren't buying music from CDNow
or anybody else. They're downloading free MP3 files from sites like
MP3.com or Napster.
</P>
<P>
   CDNow has 3.2 million customers, a great TV ad campaign and many
of Amazon's technology gizmos. Sometimes their prices are as good
as or better than Amazon's.
</P>
<P>
   However, the company has lost $174.3 million. That's nowhere
near what Amazon.com loses in just one year, but CDNow is a less
prominent company that has never been able to explain its losses
with Amazon's finesse and conviction.
</P>
<P>
   CDNow is still very much in business, and, with a little luck,
they won't be the casualty of the great Internet shakeout pundits
and analysts have been predicting. (Grocery site Peapod.com and
health site DrKoop.com face similar situations.)
</P>
<P>
   Should CDNow get the cash infusion it needs to keep going,
hopefully it will develop a business strategy to stay up and
running for the benefit of lovers of special music, like founder
Olim, who just wanted his Miles Davis CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
