<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take pick of browsers
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   If I continue to use AOL as my Internet service provider, do I
also need a browser like Netscape Navigator or Internet Explorer?
Can't AOL get me to the Web?
</P>
<P>
   _Judith Kohlberg,
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: AOL can do it all, including providing your Web browser.
On the flip side, you're not stuck with using AOL's browser either.
Download a free one off the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Once you've logged into AOL, you can launch the Web browser
of your choice, then surf to your heart's content.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   If I were to switch from my ISP, can I keep the same e-mail
address? I hesitate to switch because I could potentially lose
touch with people who have my existing address. What's the best way
to handle that?
</P>
<P>
   _Joseph Goldstein
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Sorry, Joe, no can do. Your e-mail address must change.
If you switch ISPs, the domain (name(at)domain) will be different.
Why? Well, it's like you're moving to another state and your
address changes. For instance, if your address is
jgoldstein(at)compuserv.com and you're moving to bluelight.com, the
new address could be jgoldstein(at)bluelight.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: It's important to note that more than the domain name may
change. Someone else using bluelight.com already may have glommed
onto jgoldstein. Be prepared to be creative when picking the name
part of your address. Or, a way to guarantee you'll never have to
change your e-mail address again, if you switch ISPs, is to sign up
for free e-mail with Yahoo or HotMail, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: If you're afraid of losing touch with buddies and
business contacts, run both accounts parallel for a bit. That way,
you can let people know your new address before stopping your old
service.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I want to create a family Web site where I can place
genealogical history (family tree), pictures and stories of family
members. I don't want to share this outside our family. Suggestions
for a Web site?
</P>
<P>
   _Brandt Ross
</P>
<P>
   Sue: This might fit the bill. Go to www.MyFamily.com. My Uncle
Larry and Aunt Barb, who are jazzed about genealogy, pegged this
site for our family.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: I dug the free site's features. In addition to building
an online family tree, you can post family photos, anecdotes and
recipes. A log-on process offers the security you're looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: The site is jam-packed with possibilities. Calendaring.
E-mail. Addresses. Chat. You name it, they've got it. I just came
across something cool on that site called the Family Store. Set up
your own mom-and-pop business and sell products.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Great commercial, Sue. For comparison shopping, browse
over to www.genealogy.com or www.familytree.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
