<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surprise, surprise! Framework is alive and runs on Windows
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Those FBI agents on television who are always assuring
us that ``the truth is out there'' are quite right, you know. All I
need to do is express befuddlement over some issue or get something
wrong, and the truth comes flying through the transom.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it comes in like a school of wet mackerels and other
times on the gentle wings of a dove, but believe me, somebody out
there always has the truth.
</P>
<P>
   And I appreciate knowing it. I can do without the ``you imbecile
...'' openings, but it's good to have the right info and to pass it
on to those who were searching for it in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   A very kind gentleman named Charles Fuller responded to my
nostalgic ruminations about the old DOS multifunction program
Framework and the obstinate fellow who was running it in preference
to Windows. Fuller's reply, and the URL he sent along, was for me
rather like discovering an entire tribe of living Neanderthals _
all busily conversing in HTML and keeping track of their mammoth
hides in spreadsheets.
</P>
<P>
   Framework lives.
</P>
<P>
   My original correspondent had wondered whether he could copy his
old Framework program into a newer computer and run it under DOS. I
still can't answer that definitively. However, if he will go to his
modern computer and point his Internet browser to www
.framework.com, he'll be amazed.
</P>
<P>
   This one-time Ashton-Tate, then Borland product, long believed
(at least by me) extinct, is alive and well and in its sixth
iteration under the aegis of a firm called Selections &AMP; Functions.
It is still DOS-based, but it runs with any version of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher says its ``unified outline windowing environment
includes word processing, spreadsheets, databases and HTML tables,
file and directory management, data management, codeless hypertext,
text-based interpreter and rapid development computer language.''
</P>
<P>
   It is available in a number of special-purpose versions,
including one for the visually impaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``While compatible with Windows 95, 98 and NT,'' its publishers
continue, ``Framework is a DOS application, giving it a significant
speed advantage over Windows applications as well as the ability to
run without Windows altogether. Framework graphic output allows it
to run both in a window under Windows and in full-screen-graphic
mode using its own fonts.''
</P>
<P>
   Astonishing, no? Consider the cultural and anthropological
implications. What would some modern young information technology
specialist think if he took a seat on the 9 a.m. train from the
suburbs next to an old guy running a fancy new IBM laptop, looked
over and saw Framework on the screen? He'd probably report it to
Scully and Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
