<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forget the gizmos, just give me some old-fashioned technology
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ My brother called a few moments ago. He's a small-town
physician, and I'm a blue-collar newspaperman. We love each other
but _ since we are so different _ we end up scrambling to find a
conversation sometimes. He asked me, as he usually does, ``What's
new and exciting with technology?''
</P>
<P>
   I keep up pretty well. And I know the stock answers, I know what
the buzz is, but this was my brother, not some speech I was making.
</P>
<P>
   I realized that very few of the new things that excite the real
experts do much for me. For instance, there's wireless Web use.
Gosh, I'd rather play golf than walk down the golf course,
exchanging e-mails while trying to make up an excuse for why my
drive killed a golf course goose.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's MP3, downloading music files and playing them on
one of the tiny little music machines. My CD player is easier.
Besides, the music available online is either pirated copies of
commercial songs or tunes by groups that seem to have names like
``Too Stupid to Die.'' I'd rather listen to Peggy Lee.
</P>
<P>
   New computers ... well, there are always new computers, and they
are always faster and have more nifty features. But most of them
boil down to beige-colored boxes that tend to mess up at the most
inconvenient times.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that the technology companies are almost desperate
to find some world-killer application or device these days. Instead
of worrying about what the world needs, they're more concerned with
what they can do, what they can invent, not what people need.
</P>
<P>
   I get a lot of e-mail, get a lot of calls and talking to real
people _ the consumers who are made to feel almost inadequate
because they don't have Palm Pilots, cable modems or 1-gigahertz
PCs _ helps me tune out some of the hysteria that I read and hear.
Because of the e-mail, I get to talk to the real experts, the
people who would rather pay the mortgage than own a PC powerful
enough to run an astrophysics research program, who use Walkmans
instead of MP3 players, and who are just now getting fast telephone
modems and live in places where cable modems and DSL _ the
telephone company's high-speed data service _ is either unavailable
or not worth the money for ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   But I had to tell my brother something and _ being desperate _ I
told him the truth.
</P>
<P>
   _ I'm impressed by fairly mundane gadgets that are making a real
difference in people's lives. And so are many of my readers.
Instead of raving about MP3, they tell me that WebTV _ that simple
gadget that turns your TV set into an Internet machine _ has let
them join the world of cyberspace, let them send e-mail and browse
the Web without confusing them.
</P>
<P>
   _ The regular cell phone is also becoming as much a part of life
as the regular telephone and the TV. Rates have dropped to where
ordinary people can have one, and it's become a reliable lifeline
on lonely drives, an easy way to summon help. And with today's rate
plans, which often include free long-distance service, it's become
more than an auxiliary telephone. It's become the way a lot of us
call our family and friends, using that free long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   _ E-mail, that techno-dinosaur of the Internet that dates to the
days when the name World Wide Web sounded like a comic strip title,
has reinvented the art of personal correspondence. People are
writing again. And, maybe it's just my bias, but I think that it's
bringing back the art of the conversation. Sure, we've swapped
rocking chairs on the front porch for computers in the spare
bedroom, and that's not as warm and good, but it sure beats
watching prime-time TV alone.
</P>
<P>
   So what's new and exciting in technology? It's the old stuff.
And it's the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
