r l BC-TECH-REPORT0411-COX     04-10 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT0411-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Find something or everything about nothing
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the great things about the Internet is that it
eliminates the need for know-it-alls.
</P>
<P>
   Curious about which Monkee's mother invented Liquid Paper? Don't
ask the guy three desks down, who does nothing but work and watch
cable television. Just check the Web and find out about this
not-so-famous mother.
</P>
<P>
   One site in particular, www.bigwaste.com, is a virtual Wal-Mart
of seemingly worthless information.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Waste of Space Collection of Factoids,
www.bigwaste.com/library/factoids/, should be bookmarked for anyone
seeking answers to anything about nothing in particular. ``The
factoids are tidbits of information I pick up from here or there,
which take up valuable space in my brain _ space which could be
used to substantiate my value in society or to augment the quality
of humanity itself, but instead is foolishly and continuously
consumed with inutile knowledge,'' writes Wesley Treat in the
introduction. ``I hope you enjoy them as much as I do.''
</P>
<P>
   A few of the factoids. (Accuracy is not vouched for.)
</P>
<P>
   _ The typo-correction fluid Liquid Paper was invented by the
mother of Michael Nesmith, Monkees guitarist.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the summer of 1959, the U.S. Postal Service experimented
with the delivery of letters by guided missile.
</P>
<P>
   _ The world's first land speed record was set by an electric car
at 39 mph.
</P>
<P>
   _ George Washington's dentures weren't, as legend supposes, made
of wood, but were fashioned from hippopotamus tusk.
</P>
<P>
   _ There exists a makeshift, one-hoop basketball court inside the
peak of Disneyland's Matterhorn.
</P>
<P>
   _ From 1942 to 1945, car 3544 of the Orient Express was employed
as a French brothel.
</P>
<P>
   _ The semicolon, as it appears in English today, was used by the
ancient Greeks as a question mark.
</P>
<P>
   _ Giraffes have no vocal cords.
</P>
<P>
   _ The salt contained in all of the world's oceans could cover
the United States in a layer a mile and a half thick.
</P>
<P>
   _ The perpetually popular children's clay substance Play-Doh is
the result of an attempt to create a cleaning product for
wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   _ For the entire length of the film ``Casablanca,'' no one ever
says the words ``Play it again, Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   A TRIP TO DISNEY FAN LAND
</P>
<P>
   Wonder what all those Disney fanatics do when they're away from
the place? One Web site, laughingplace.com, gives you a good idea.
Almost makes you want to take the question back.
</P>
<P>
   The site includes updated Disney news, links to other sites,
trivia questions and opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   One day last week, the site's news section included links to an
Orlando Sentinel story about some Disney employees' confusion
regarding the new mustache policy, which allows them to be worn,
just not grown, at work.
</P>
<P>
   Another link is to an interview with Alan Thompson Jr., half of
the (Rod) Miller &AMP; Thompson duo playing ragtime duets at Disneyland
on Friday and Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   For those who care, here's the origin, for posterity, of how
they met:
</P>
<P>
   ``One day when I was at Disneyland with my marching band, I came
by the piano and asked Rod to play the `Maple Leaf Rag.' He played
it for me, and I couldn't believe how fast he could play. I doubted
I would ever be able to play like that but knew right away I had to
learn how. A couple weeks later, I came back and asked him to teach
me to play ragtime. He said, `I'm not going to teach you because I
don't teach any piano.' He told me it takes a lot of commitment and
a lot of practice, four to six hours a day. I kept bugging him for
three months. Meanwhile, I worked on improving my own ragtime
music. Impressed by my progress, he finally said `yes.'''
</P>
<P>
   A Disneyland update from the previous week was still available,
complete with an overhead photograph of Disney's California
Adventure and pictures of the Golden Gate bridge replica under
construction, the new entrance and exit turnstiles, and other
construction photos.
</P>
<P>
   The site also includes discussion boards. A person with the
screen name of Tron182 was discussing the new ``Walt Disney World
Racing'' game for PlayStation last week. Tycoon11 was spending his
free time comparing Disneyland with the Magic Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll asked, ``How often do you visit a Disney theme
park?''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 163 reported respondents, 49 percent visited more than
four times a year and 45 percent came about three times but none
chose ``never.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
