<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR-OF-THE-YEAR (San Antonio) _ Editor &AMP; Publisher, the
leading journal of the newspaper industry, has named Robert Rivard
of the San Antonio Express-News editor of the year. It is the first
time in the magazine's 116-year history that it has bestowed the
honor, reserved for the editorial chiefs of the nation's 1,500
daily newspapers. By DICK J. REAVIS.
</P>
<P>
   LAREDO-BRIDGE (Laredo, Texas) _ If you've visited this border
city in the past five years, you've had to negotiate around the
miles of tractor-trailers lined up on the southernmost stretch of
Interstate 35 every afternoon, waiting to trundle over the
20-year-old Bridge No. 2 into Mexico. That will all be different
come Saturday, when Laredo opens its newest border crossing _ and
prohibits cargo trucks from using either downtown span. By BONNIE
PFISTER.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-CAMPUS (Merced, Calif.) _ Despite nearly universal
popularity in the Central Valley and the enthusiastic backing of
California Gov. Gray Davis and Vice President Al Gore, the
University of California at Merced is no slam dunk. Opposition to
situating the UC system's 10th campus in the grasslands north of
Merced is coalescing around the issue of protecting thousands of
vernal pools. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ When Buick rolls out its all-new
Rendezvous sport-utility vehicle next spring, it will be none too
soon for dealers nationwide. They have had to deal almost daily
with loyal customers who want to buy another Buick product but feel
the need for a sport-utility rather than a sedan. By G. CHAMBERS
WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   GM-PICKUPS (Undated) _ The styling of General Motors' updated
GMC Sierra and Chevrolet Silverado isn't radically different from
the previous generation. Instead, GM spent the money more wisely,
improving just about every other aspect of the vehicle as well as
tuning up the styling. The result is a pickup that not only is much
better than it was before, but which also outshines its
competitors. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-TRADER (San Francisco) _ Last week, Nasdaq plunged and I
decided to take the dive, too. I became an online stock trader. And
if I can be a little smug, I didn't do so badly for somebody who
didn't have a clue what she was doing. By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DRAFT (San Francisco) _ With next weekend's NFL draft,
you'll be hearing an awful lot about such former student-athletes
as LaVar Arrington, Courtney Brown, Peter Warrick and Chris
Samuels. In most mock NFL drafts, these will be the first four
players chosen, though not necessarily in that order. By JOHN
CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   With: FBN-DRAFT-TEAMS.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS (San Francisco) _ With Steve Young's status still
unsettled and Jeff Garcia the only other quarterback on the roster,
the San Francisco 49ers are compelled to look for a QB in next
week's draft. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Can you imagine catching two
striped bass at once _ including one that wasn't even hooked? A
miracle? Well, maybe there is still time for miracles for the
striped
</P>
<P>
   bass in the San Francisco Bay and Delta. You see, on a trip to
the Delta this past week, we really did catch a striped bass
without using even a hook (and we'll get to that). By TOM
STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The other night I watched the new
mental hospital drama ``Wonderland'' with one of the toughest of
critics _ a former mental patient. The ABC show has been praised by
TV critics for realistically portraying life in a big-city
emergency psychiatric ward. It has been panned by the National
Alliance of the Mentally Ill for portraying the mentally ill as
violent. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   BANK-OF-AMERICA (San Francisco) _ In the year and a half since
the Bank of American was taken over, the bank's stock price has
fallen, then fallen again, at times hovering under half of what it
was at the time the two companies merged. More significant for San
Franciscans, the old Bank of America _ an institution nearly a
century in the making _ has disappeared almost overnight. By GAIL
TODD.
</P>
