<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2171 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     04-10 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO SAVE FACE, KARPAN MOVED FROM MINING AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone gave Kathy Karpan, director of the U.S. Office of
Surface Mining, bad advice about accepting a job interview with a
mining industry advocacy association. As a consequence, on April
10, she became former chief of the nation's top coal-mining
regulatory agency.
</P>
<P>
   On April 7, Secretary of the Interior Bruce Babbitt announced
the management change. Karpan has been reassigned. She will be
acting deputy assistant secretary of land and minerals management,
responsible for non-mining issues involving the Bureau of Land
Management and the Minerals Management Service. It's a titular job,
one without much authority or responsibility. The position is
layers below the power to make real decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt can authorize as many acting deputy assistants as he
sees fit to effectively run his department. Acting deputy
assistants and deputy assistants do not need to be confirmed by
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   To fill in the new vacancy, Kathrine Henry, Interior's associate
solicitor for the Division of Minerals Resources, became acting
director of the Office of Surface Mining. Henry was acting director
of OSM for nearly a year before Karpan took the position in August
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, Henry will remain as chief of OSM until the end of
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Karpan interviewed for the position of president of
the National Mining Association, the very industry her agency is
charged with regulating under the federal Surface Mining Control
and Reclamation Act of 1977. In doing so, Karpan crossed the line
between what has the appearance of propriety and what does not. And
appearances are everything.
</P>
<P>
   It is extremely rare for the head of an federal agency, while
still in that position, to interview for a job in the private
sector with an industry the agency regulates. The inherent conflict
of interest is overwhelming. The appearance of a conflict of
interest is overpowering.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewing for the mining job raises too many questions about
previous mining regulatory decisions Karpan had made. Had she ruled
in favor of the mining industry to curry favor for such a job
opportunity? Would Karpan rule against the mining industry in
retaliation if she didn't get the position? She could no longer be
an effective director of OSM.
</P>
<P>
   Karpan's position there was tainted. She had to be moved.
</P>
<P>
   Back in mid-March, Karpan was contacted by a headhunter for the
National Mining Association, to see if she was interested in
interviewing for the association's top job. She was apparently told
that the decision would be made in a week. And no doubt she was
told she would be on a very short list of finalists for the
position _ which pays nearly half a million dollars a year, more
than four times what she made as head the regulatory agency.
</P>
<P>
   It's the nature of politics in the nation's capital that when a
president's term of office is nearly over, public officials begin
looking for work in the private sector. The desire to secure a job
in business before one's government job ends is understandable. The
experience federal employees have gained from working in the
government can be useful to many large corporations and
multinationals.
</P>
<P>
   Karpan sought the advice of the Department of the Interior's
Office of Ethics. Although she did not inform Babbitt's office of
the interview, Karpan did everything else according to the rules.
She submitted a written request to recuse herself from any
decisions regarding the mining industry from March 15 to March 26.
Since no decision had been made about the job with the mining
association by March 26, Karpan then took a two-week vacation. That
vacation ended April 9.
</P>
<P>
   So on April 10, she began a new job within the Department of the
Interior _ insulated from all mining issues. Essentially, Karpan
can sit in her new job until she can quietly and gracefully resign.
</P>
<P>
   The current president of the National Mining Association,
Richard Lawson, isn't slated to retire until the end of the year.
If Karpan gets the mining association job, she can continue to draw
a federal paycheck until Lawson packs up and heads out.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt's decision to move Karpan saves face for Karpan and ends
the appearance of impropriety at the Department of Interior's
Office of Surface Mining.
</P>
<P>
   In merely shifting Karpan from her former duties, Babbitt gave a
nod to how well she had run OSM. In the five years before Karpan
took over the agency, the Office of Surface Mining had gone through
five different directors. The agency's morale was low and it hadn't
been operating effectively. Karpan turned that around in less than
three years.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to get Karpan's side of the story, attempts were
made to reach her. But Karpan did not return calls to her Virginia
home on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Karpan could have saved herself and the department a great deal
of criticism had she asked to be moved out of the Office of Surface
Mining before she had interviewed with the mining association.
There was another option, of course _ she could have resigned
before interviewing. Either choice would have been preferable to
what she did.
</P>
<P>
   We expect a great deal of our public officials, perhaps too
much. We hold them to high ethical standards, pay them much less
than they would get in the private sector and demand they stay
clear of even the appearance of impropriety. It is difficult if not
impossible to strike a fair balance in these matters. Nevertheless,
Karpan came up with the short straw.
</P>
<P>
   Karpan had to make up her mind whether to be interviewed for the
mining association position when she was queried by telephone. She
had a few moments to think about it. Perhaps the lure of the money
caused a brief glitch in Karpan's thought processes. In her years
as a public servant in Wyoming, however, Karpan showed remarkable
political savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Karpan, an attorney, is the daughter of a coal miner and a
native of Rock Springs. She knows the coal industry.
</P>
<P>
   From 1984 to 1986, Karpan ran Wyoming's Department of Health and
Social Services, one of the state's largest agencies. She resigned
in 1986 to run for the second highest office in Wyoming, the
secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   She was elected and then re-elected to that office in 1990. She
was a strong secretary of state who had a firm grasp of the issues
and wasn't afraid to make tough decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Karpan ran unsuccessfully as the Democratic candidate for
governor of Wyoming in 1994. And she made an unsuccessful bid to
fill the Senate seat vacated by former Sen. Al Simpson in 1996. She
lost to Mike Enzi.
</P>
<P>
   The episode is over, but it has left a bad odor in the air. And
it will linger awhile _ despite the corrective measures taken by
Babbitt. It is likely, however, that Karpan's reputation will carry
a whiff of it for a much longer time. And that's too bad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2174 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COMPUTERS-GIRLS11-COX     04-10 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-GIRLS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDY SAYS MANY GIRLS DISDAIN COMPUTER CAREERS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Girls are avoiding high-tech careers not because
they fear failing, but because they believe computer jobs are
boring and lonely, according to a study released Tuesday(cq).
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, they use e-mail and the Internet and word
processing, but when it comes to computer fluency _ finding
innovative ways to use information technology or to adapt new
technologies as they emerge _ girls and women just aren't in the
forefront,'' said Pamela Haag, director of research for the AAUW
Educational Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're used to hearing a lot about math and science phobia''
among older girls, Haag said. But, she said, when the researchers
talked to girls in middle school and high school, ``it wasn't that
they were anxious about technology, they were estranged from it and
opting out from acquiring skills that are key to our economy and
will be key to our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Her foundation, an affiliate of the American Association of
University Women, paid for the two-year study, which was directed
by a predominantly female commission of 15 prominent researchers,
teachers, journalists and entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Only one-fifth of high tech jobs are held by women, the
commission said. Moreover, on-the-job use of technology lags among
teachers, about three-fourths of whom are women.
</P>
<P>
   The commission predicted that women will continue to trail men
in computer-related activities until there are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Changes in ``tedious and dull'' computer science courses that
weed out most students, rather than arouse interest in the field.
</P>
<P>
   _ More use of classroom technology to study non-technical
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   _ Education for today's teachers that goes beyond ``drive-by''
workshops to emphasize how teachers can design instruction that
takes advantage of new technology.
</P>
<P>
   _ Creation of new ``high skill'' computer games that appeal to
boys and girls, as an alternative to today's ``high kill'' action
games for boys and ``pink'' passive games for girls.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marketing campaigns that smash the stereotype of the high-tech
workplace as a sterile set of cubicles full of boring men who are
better at relating to machines than to people.
</P>
<P>
   ``When asked, girls and women describe a prevailing concern that
computer science will stunt their diverse range of intellectual
pursuits and interests,'' the commission said. ``Girls tend to
imagine that computer professionals live in a solitary, antisocial
and sedentary world.''
</P>
<P>
   Disputing that stereotype, the commission said, ``Tinkering with
(computer) code need not be seen as less artistic than tinkering
with color, form and shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Its recommendation: ``Educators, parents, employers and guidance
counselors need to impart a more complex, realistic view of jobs
that rely heavily or centrally on computer technology. Many of
these jobs emphasize communication, collaboration and creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.aauw.org/2000/techsavvy.html
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
