A2199 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-PAUL-NEWMAN-IN-WHERE-     04-10 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAUL-NEWMAN-IN-WHERE-THE-MONEY-IS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK SHOT: PAUL NEWMAN IS BACK `WHERE THE MONEY IS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Paul Newman dancing with Linda
Fiorentino in a scene from ``Where the Money Is.'') 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Paul Newman was born in 1925. When you do the math, it doesn't
seems possible.
 &HT;    The Hollywood icon, race-car driver and hugely successful
food-products marketer isn't just aging gracefully _ at 75, he
hardly seems to be aging at all.
 &HT;    You can see the evidence in ``Where The Money Is,'' opening
April 14 nationwide. Newman plays a convicted bank robber who scams
his way out of prison into a nursing home by faking a debilitating
stroke, only to run into a nurse (Linda Fiorentino) who has a
larcenous streak of her own.
 &HT;    And, yes, sparks fly between the pair in the kind of caper movie
that Newman hasn't tackled since ``Butch Cassidy and The Sundance
Kid'' (1969) and ``The Sting'' (1973), or at least ``The Color of
Money'' (1986).
 &HT;    ``There was a lot of larceny in it,'' Newman says with a slight
smile, ``which brought me back to Butch Cassidy, `The Color of
Money's' Fast Eddie and Henry Gondorff from `The Sting.'''
 &HT;    Newman pulls up his sleeve to reveal a sleek but inexpensive
digital runner's watch.
 &HT;    ``There's something so attractive about larceny,'' he says.
``One of the great hustles is this $49 watch I'm wearing, which is
amazingly accurate. When guys who have Rolexes come up to me, they
say, `Why are you wearing that piece of junk?'
 &HT;    ``I say, `I'll bet your fancy watch is at least 20 seconds off
and mine is on the money,''' Newman says, his eyes gleaming. ``I
get them to bet me a hundred bucks. Then they say, `But how can we
check?' And I say, `Well, you can call that time number at the
Naval Observatory.' They say, `Well, how can we get that number?'
 &HT;    ``And I say, `It's (202) 762-140l.'''
 &HT;    Newman settles back with a chuckle.
 &HT;    ``Of course they hand over the hundred bucks without even
bothering to call,'' he says. ``They know they've been hustled.''
 &HT;    Newman's cheerfully down-to-earth manner reflects his demeanour
on movie sets, where he's famous for his professionalism, his
absence of star attitude and his pleasure in the collaborative
camaraderie of movie-making.
 &HT;    ``I think of it as a community,'' he says. ``The best work
always comes out of exploring, inventing and imagining together.
Even out of terrible ideas you get some wonderful moments. My
philosophy is, if it isn't fun to get up in the morning and go to
the set, then why the hell do it?
 &HT;    ``I like to play around between scenes,'' he admits, ``but five
minutes before the cameras roll I want to make sure everything has
quieted down. You've got to exercise discipline and let everybody
know the horseplay is over and it's time to work.''
 &HT;    The focus of ``Where the Money Is'' may be his character's one
last bank job, but that didn't keep him from doing the research
necessary to fake a stroke convincingly.
 &HT;    ``I went to a rehabilitation hospital,'' he says, ``and spent
some time with stroke victims. You watch them, observe them, as you
would any other person you want to put up on the screen.''
 &HT;    He's done that dozens of times, in the process creating a
gallery of memorable characters whom the public adores, sometimes
to the point of confusing them with Newman himself.
 &HT;    ``That doesn't have anything to do with me,'' the actor says.
``The things I say are written for me, all those great one-liners.
The lady who is co-starring with you has been instructed by the
director to fall in love with you in front of the camera. The real
Paul Newman is not what you see on the screen.''
 &HT;    That distinction isn't always clear to his fans, he adds.
 &HT;    ``Right after I did Rocky Graziano in `Somebody Up There Likes
Me' (1956),'' he recalls, ``I went with a bunch of people to have a
few beers down on Second Avenue. Guys would walk up and smack me on
the shoulder and say, `You think you're so tough? You think you're
a boxer?'
 &HT;    ``Then, after `The Color of Money,' I'd be in a bar with a pool
table and somebody would say, `How about a little game? We don't
have to play for money, what would you like to play for?'
 &HT;    ``I'd say, `How about your house?''' Newman says with a laugh.
``That usually ended the conversation.''
 &HT;    More recently, he adds, he may have alienated some of his fans
without really meaning to.
 &HT;    ``I cut my finger slicing some green peppers,'' he says. ``It
was really bad, bleeding pretty profusely. So I hopped on my motor
scooter and went down to the hospital. The doctor fixed it up and
said, `I want you to keep that finger elevated. Hold it up in the
air.'
 &HT;    ``Well,'' he says with a grin, ``it happened to be my middle
finger. So as I walked out of the emergency room holding my middle
finger up, people were looking at me like, `Why is Paul Newman
doing that to us?'''
 &HT;    Newman is making fewer films nowadays, feeling that at this
stage in his career he can afford to be selective. ``Where the
Money Is'' provides his first starring role since ``Twilight''
(1998), and is his first film since a supporting turn in ``Message
in a Bottle'' (1999). Instead, he's devoting more time to Newman's
Own, the food-products line through which he raises money for
several charities.
 &HT;    ``If someone had told me 20 years ago that I'd have my face on a
bottle of salad dressing, I'd have had them committed,'' the actor
says. ``I'm glad that the money goes for good causes. I don't
exactly live low on the hog, so I can afford it.
 &HT;    ``I think it's better to give it away in your lifetime,'' he
adds, ``so you can see the benefits. I don't understand people who
hoard their fortunes and give them away after they're gone.''
 &HT;    Newman's other passion remains driving fast cars _ which in
January led to a serious accident at the practice run for the
Daytona 500.
 &HT;    ``Bad judgment,'' he says matter-of-factly. ``But I'd rather
drive at Daytona than on I-95. It's safer there than on the freeway
_ at least you're pretty sure the guy in front of you isn't going
to do something stupid. I may do something stupid, but that leaves
the guy behind me out of luck.''
 &HT;    There aren't a lot of 75-year-olds out racing cars, but Newman
says that his durability there, like his longevity as an actor, is
simply a matter of luck.
 &HT;    ``I'm just very fortunate that my body hasn't abandoned me
yet,'' he says after a moment's thought. ``That's the luck of the
draw. If you're born with the right metabolism, you're just
lucky.''
 &HT;    A lot of actors say they hope to work until their dying day, but
Newman freely admits that he expects to retire fairly soon.
 &HT;    ``I've talked about it,'' he says. ``In fact, I think I've been
retiring every year for the past 15 years. I'd like to do one more
great film that would be my swan song _ a film with my wife Joanne
or Robert Redford or Tom Cruise. I'd love to find a really
memorable film to go out on.
 &HT;    ``At some point you have to get out,'' Newman says. ``I don't
want to retire on my knees.''
 c.2000 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
