<HEADER>
A2202 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-SOPHIA-COPPOLA-DIRECT     04-10 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOPHIA-COPPOLA-DIRECTS-THE-VIRGIN-SUICIDES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORN TO DIRECT? SOPHIA COPPOLA STEERS `THE VIRGIN SUICIDES' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Sophia Coppola directing Kirsten Dunst
in a scene from ``The Virgin Suicides.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Sofia Coppola began studying filmmaking as a preschooler.
 &HT;    ``At age 4, I was in the Philippines hanging out on the set of
`Apocalypse Now' (1979),'' says the daughter of legendary director
Francis Ford Coppola. ``I remember being helicoptered into the
jungle. It was like one great big adventure.''
 &HT;    Her education continued on the set of ``The Godfather, Part
III'' (1990), which Coppola calls ``my acting debut and one of the
most uncomfortable times of my life. Let's just say the critics
were harsh.''
 &HT;    Her graduate school was watching her father deal with bankruptcy
and what seemed at the time like the end of his Hollywood career.
 &HT;    ``I learned from him that, no matter what, you never give up,''
Coppola says. ``I never remember my father losing faith in his art
_ I don't remember him ever being discouraged.''
 &HT;    And now Coppola has stepped into the arena herself, writing and
directing a big-screen adaptation of Jeffrey Eugenides' cult novel
``The Virgin Suicides,'' the story of three death-obsessed sisters
in 1970s Michigan and the neighborhood boys who are obsessed with
them.
 &HT;    To help get her first major film, which will open April 21, to
the big screen, Coppola recruited an impressive, eclectic cast that
includes Danny DeVito, Kathleen Turner, James Woods, Kirsten Dunst,
Josh Harnett and Giovanni Ribisi.
 &HT;    The only name in the credits that didn't seem to belong was her
own, she says, since previously the only thing she had directed was
a short for the Bravo cable channel.
 &HT;    ``Of course, the name Coppola gets you in the door,'' says the
novice director, who is also the cousin of Nicolas Cage and the
niece of Talia Shire. ``You can get the assignment. But from then
on you really have to prove yourself.''
 &HT;    Since first reading the book, she had sensed that ``The Virgin
Suicides'' would be that proving-ground.
 &HT;    ``It's not often that you fall in love with a piece of
literature,'' she says. ``In my own mind, I was almost picturing
the movie as I read it.''
 &HT;    But a film adaptation was already in the works at another
studio, with another director. Nonetheless, Coppola jotted down a
few ideas. A year later, she began tinkering with a script ``for
the fun of it.''
 &HT;    Suddenly, however, the other studio dropped its plans, and
Coppola was able to acquire the rights.
 &HT;    ``I almost couldn't believe it,'' she says. ``Honestly, I felt
like I was meant to do this story.''
 &HT;    Still, the decision to direct it herself was difficult.
 &HT;    ``I was so close to the material that I couldn't imagine anyone
else directing it,'' she says. ``But still, the first day we shot
in Toronto, I was very nervous. Driving to the set, my biggest fear
was that I was going to suddenly freeze up and the cast would look
at me and say, `So what should we do?'
 &HT;    ``In my nightmare scenario, I would go blank and everyone would
say, `Replace her.'''
 &HT;    Even though the film was being produced by Francis Ford
Coppola's American Zoetrope, there was one place she didn't turn
for help.
 &HT;    ``It would have been so easy to pick up a phone and say, `Dad,
what should I do?''' Coppola says.
 &HT;    ``I am guilty of trying to remember all the advice he had given
me over the years,'' she admits. ``For instance, on many sets he
told me that good directors do not stand by the video camera and
watch the takes. He told me that you sit right next to the camera,
so you are connected with the actors.
 &HT;    ``My father feels you distance yourself if you're absorbed with
a video monitor.''
 &HT;    She didn't take all his advice, though.
 &HT;    ``I remember him telling me to sit down and try to nap between
shots,'' Coppola says. ``Sorry, Dad, I just couldn't do that on my
set. We shot this movie in 29 days _ there wasn't time to sit
down.''
 &HT;    Complicating matters was that she had recently been married to
another first-time director, Spike Jonze, who was then making
``Being John Malkovich'' (1999).
 &HT;    ``We both shot our first movies at the same time,'' Coppola
recalls. ``In a way it was bad, because we were newlyweds and these
movies were taking over our lives. But we could understand what the
other person was thinking and feeling _ we would comfort each other
during the rough moments.''
 &HT;    All the more ironic, then, that as a child growing up in Napa
Valley, Calif., Coppola never planned on a career in filmmaking.
After seeing her father's struggles, she wanted to be a painter.
 &HT;    Her father thought she should try acting, however, and when
Winona Ryder dropped out of ``The Godfather, Part III,'' the
director hired his daughter to make her screen debut _ one which
became one of the most panned in Hollywood history.
 &HT;    ``I was 18, and it was one of the most uncomfortable times in my
life,'' Coppola admits. ``I didn't read every single review, but I
read a lot of them. I was aware of the criticism, and frankly I
thought it was unfair.
 &HT;    ``First of all, it was so harsh,'' she says, wincing. ``Can you
imagine being so young and having them pick on what your face looks
like in a close-up?
 &HT;    ``I wasn't totally devastated, because I wasn't preparing to
become some great actress,'' she concludes. ``I got slammed, but I
could rationalize it and think, `So what? This was an experiment.
And at least I'll never say that I didn't try it.'''
 &HT;    Afterwards, Coppola dabbled in clothing design.
 &HT;    ``I didn't know what I wanted to do,'' she says. ``I knew I was
interested in film, but it was too daunting to admit to myself that
I wanted to be a director.''
 &HT;    Nowadays, she's willing to admit it. In fact, she's already
writing her next project, which she hopes to direct next year.
 &HT;    ``It's been a crazy year,'' she says with a laugh. ``I finished
the mix on my movie the night before our wedding. Any other groom
would have been really mad that his bride was so occupied. My
future husband completely understood.
 &HT;    ``He did his mix right after our honeymoon!''
 &HT;    Jonze's new father-in-law also understood.
 &HT;    ``My father is an inspiration to both of us,'' Coppola says. ``I
just hope to have my father's enthusiasm when I'm his age. My
father will still come home from a set completely excited about
what he learned about moviemaking on that particular day. It's
still a grand adventure for him.''
 &HT;    And, yes, she's still eager to win his approval.
 &HT;    ``To tell you the truth,'' she says, ``my most nerve-wracking
moment is when I sent my father the script I wrote for `The Virgin
Suicides.'''
 &HT;    The next day the phone rang, and the novice screenwriter's heart
was in her throat.
 &HT;    ``He didn't even give me a note or a suggestion,'' Coppola says.
``My dad simply said, `You should make this film. This is the kind
of movie I want to do someday, too.'
 &HT;    ``I couldn't get a better compliment.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
