<HEADER>
A2204 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-JAMES-CAVIEZEL-IN-FRE     04-10 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMES-CAVIEZEL-IN-FREQUENCY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATTER OF TIME: JAMES CAVIEZEL STARS IN `FREQUENCY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of James Caviezel in a scene from
``Frequency.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    James Caviezel has ``The Twilight Zone'' on the brain.
 &HT;    ``I remember the one where they don't show the girl's face and
she's getting plastic surgery to look like one of the pig people,''
Caviezel says. ``I remember the one with the boy sending everyone
out to the corn, and I remember the one with this woman who would
never die, who'd stick a beetle on you and age you. That one got
me.''
 &HT;    Caviezel, the intense young actor whose credits include ``My Own
Private Idaho'' (1991), ``Wyatt Earp'' (1993), Terrence Malick's
``The Thin Red Line'' (1998) and Ang Lee's ``Ride with the Devil''
(1999), has an appetite for the weird.
 &HT;    ``I believe in a lot of that,'' he says. ``There are so many
solar systems. I wouldn't hesitate to think there are other
civilizations out there. There are a lot of apparitions that
happen, that have been happening for centuries.
 &HT;    ``I wouldn't put any limitations on God,'' he adds. ``Part of me
wants to believe. It gives me hope.''
 &HT;    Caviezel's latest film, ``Frequency,'' is all about sci-fi and
hope. It's also about father-son bonding, a serial killer and
hearing dead people.
 &HT;    Caviezel stars as John Sullivan, a somber New York cop whose
firefighter father, Frank (Dennis Quaid), died nearly 30 years ago
in a blaze. One night, however, a freak atmospheric phenomenon
allows John to communicate with Frank via ham radio, with John in
1999 and Frank in 1969, one day before his date with destiny.
 &HT;    Hoping to save his father's life, John warns him about what is
to come, and inadvertently triggers a series of unpredictable
consequences _ including murder _ which threatens to throw history
as we know it completely out of whack.
 &HT;    ``The film is a number of things, and everybody is going to see
something different,'' the soft-spoken actor says during an
interview at New York's Regency Hotel. Caviezel is sporting
dark-brown hair, a scruffy beard, black-rimmed plastic glasses and
a gray sports coat over a camelhair vest.
 &HT;    ``It was the father-son relationship that drove me to want to do
it,'' he explains, ``and that's set in the trappings of a
sci-fi/suspense thriller. What I liked, in reading it, was how the
genres switched.
 &HT;    ``The last time I saw a movie like that was `Life Is Beautiful'
(1998),'' he adds. ``Who, going into it, knew the Holocaust would
emerge from the beginnings of a love affair? That combination
weaved together very nicely, and I thought `Frequency' did the same
kind of thing.''
 &HT;    Given his affection for sci-fi and an abiding belief in God, the
31-year-old actor didn't find it hard to make his character or the
situation feel real.
 &HT;    ``Regardless of any religious affiliation, if you have some sort
of belief in the unknown, that there's something out there ... I
have that element in me,'' Caviezel says, ``and I used that. I
think films like `Frequency' or `Ghost' (1990) or `The Sixth Sense'
(1999) have an element that people want to believe. They want to
believe in the hereafter.
 &HT;    ``I just used the ham radio and the aurora borealis in
`Frequency' as a metaphor for that,'' he says. ``When you lose
somebody you love _ and my father had a near-miss with death after
open-heart surgery _ you look back and think of all the things you
wish you had done.
 &HT;    ``Here, it's great to go to a film and fantasize about that,''
he adds. ``Would you change paths? Would you do things that may
cause severe consequences?''
 &HT;    For himself, he says, he doubts that he'd change anything.
 &HT;    ``I don't think I would,'' he says thoughtfully. ``Everything
happens for a reason. I believe in the theory that life gives you a
lemon and you can turn it into lemonade. Even the bad things that
happen in our lives, good things can happen from them.
 &HT;    ``Learning can be that way at times, but there are a lot of
benefits from it,'' the actor says. ``It's kind of like working out
_ I don't particularly enjoy it, but it's great when I hit that
shower.'
 &HT;    Caviezel's take on acting is equally colorful. The two elements
that he most appreciates, he says, are those moments when he
connects with a fellow actor and the opportunity to touch
moviegoers in a darkened theater.
 &HT;    ``I know when I see movies I get something from watching an
actor on screen,'' he says. ``Even before I became an actor, I felt
that. That's pretty powerful.
 &HT;    ``So I enjoy going to theaters and seeing people react,''
Caviezel says. ``(A performance) is something I can give to
someone, and it's very fulfilling for me. I see acting as a
service.''
 &HT;    Caviezel, who grew up in the state of Washington, where he still
lives with his wife, began acting in the early 1990s, first as a
guest star on such television shows as ``The Wonder Years.'' Later
he made his movie debut with a small role in Gus Van Sant's ``My
Own Private Idaho.'' Bigger roles in bigger films followed, among
them ``Ed'' (1996) and ``G.I. Jane'' (1997).
 &HT;    Slowly but steadily, he's climbed the Hollywood ladder. But,
while proud of his accomplishments, Caviezel cringes when he sees
the ``Frequency'' publicity, which has his and Quaid's names above
the title _ tangible proof that he's finally achieved stardom.
 &HT;    ``I don't really think about it,'' he says. ``Whenever the
agents say, `We're going to get your name above the title,' I say,
`Just make the movie good.'
 &HT;    ``To me, the film business, what I do, is a service,'' he adds.
``Being where I'm at is such a miracle anyway. I was a basketball
player _ I went to movies, and I felt this real strong calling
inside that said, `You're supposed to be an actor.' I talked to my
dad, and he said, `You don't want to get into that crap.' I said,
`Yeah, yeah. You're right.'
 &HT;    ``Through a twist of fate _ what if? _ I broke my foot,'' he
recalls. ``My college coach said, `You always screw around doing
these impersonations. Why don't you go talk to the drama
teacher?'''
 &HT;    Caviezel shrugs.
 &HT;    ``It just happened that way,'' he says. ``So many times I wanted
to quit. I just can't believe I'm here sometimes.
 &HT;    ``I hope I always feel that way,'' Caviezel adds. ``It keeps me
grounded. I have great family. I have people who tell me things I
might not want to hear, but that I ought to hear. That's important.
 &HT;    ``So the simple things are the things that I don't ever want to
lose,'' he concludes. ``I saw that in Terrence Malick. He will
always be my father in film. It's good to have a mentor like him in
the film business, because he kind of holds you accountable.''
 &HT;    Caviezel will next turn up in the family boat-racing drama
``Madison'' and then the uplifting ``Pay It Forward'' with Kevin
Spacey, Helen Hunt and Haley Joel Osment.
 &HT;    But while he may be on a roll, he's clearly struggling with his
newfound stardom. Fortunately, he got some advice from another
reluctant star that still rings loud and clear.
 &HT;    ``Jimmy Stewart told me, `This is a service. If you serve people
and look at it from that point of view, you will always find it
fulfilling,''' he says. ``People ask if acting is noble. It is
noble to serve.''
 &HT;    Jimmy Stewart?
 &HT;    ``It was 1991,'' Caviezel says, smiling sheepishly. ``I was at
(producer) Jerry Weintraub's house.
 &HT;    ``I was a waiter.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Frequency,'' consult the
official Web site at www.frequencymovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
