<HEADER>
A2205 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-MATTHEW-PERRY-ON-BRUC     04-10 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTHEW-PERRY-ON-BRUCE-WILLIS-ON-FRIENDS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATTHEW PERRY BRINGS A BUDDY HOME TO `FRIENDS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Bruce Willis with David Schwimmer in a
scene from ``Friends.'') 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not for release in Canada until 23 April. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes even friends need friends.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Matthew Perry, who recently invited a pal to drop by
and guest-star on a few ``Friends'' episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Kudrow, Courteney Cox Arquette and company didn't complain
too much _ after all, Perry's friend was big-screen superstar Bruce
Willis.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing Willis, with whom he made the current box-office smash
``The Whole Nine Yards,'' has given Perry a whole new perspective
on life in the spotlight. For the first few years of ``Friends,''
the young actor found himself uncomfortable with his own
popularity. It was last year, during the making of ``The Whole Nine
Yards,'' that he found a new comfort level.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it kind of goes in waves,'' Perry says. ``When we
first started being in the public eye, I was the one who just loved
it. In that first season, I was going to malls, humming the theme
song, hoping to get recognized ... Later, the attention was too
much. Now, I'm just used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry's newfound ease is well-timed, considering his current
status as a genuine movie star. Released several weeks back, ``The
Whole Nine Yards'' came from virtually nowhere to become one of
this year's biggest feature hits, holding the No. 1 box-office spot
against all comers for three straight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He may have achieved stardom on ``Friends,'' but Perry admits he
was a little nervous about acting alongside Willis, who _ though he
also got his start on television, as co-star of ``Moonlighting''
(1985-1989) _ has been one of Hollywood's top international stars
since ``Die Hard'' (1988).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the first big star that I've worked with,'' Perry says,
``so I was kind of intimidated. I wasn't sure how the dynamic would
work, but he got a kick out of being funny again.''
</P>
<P>
   He got a taste of Willis' notoriously jocular humor even before
filming began.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me before I accepted the part and left a message on
my machine _ `Hey, Matthew. Call me back or I'll burn your house
down!,''' Perry recalls. ``It was funny. I called him back _ I was
pacing all over my house talking to him _ and, by the end, we were
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Good enough friends, in fact, that he was able to convince
Willis to pay a return visit, guest-starring in a three-week arc of
``Friends,'' starting April 27, as the stern widower father of a
20-year-old young lady who happens to be dating Ross (David
Schwimmer).
</P>
<P>
   This sort of stunt-cast ratings trick has worked well for
``Friends'' in the past _ previous guest stars have included Julia
Roberts, George Clooney, Noah Wyle and Brooke Shields _ and it
demonstrates that the show's producers still know how to keep
things interesting.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Perry says he believes that ``Friends'' is fresher than
ever in this, its seventh season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have more momentum this season than ever before,''
he says matter-of-factly, relaxing on a beat-up sofa on the
``Friends'' set. ``I think the show has always been good. There's
just been a certain dynamic in the press to build it up, then tear
it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like that with `Seinfeld,''' he adds. ``All of a
sudden, people were saying `Seinfeld' was terrible in its fifth
year. But it wasn't _ it was the same show.''
</P>
<P>
   He blames that same negativity for the way the media has
approached those ``Friends'' stars who have made feature-film
forays. Aside from Kudrow, who won critical plaudits in ``The
Opposite of Sex'' (1998) and ``Analyze This'' (1999), and Cox
Arquette's role in the ensemble ``Scream'' films, the press has
generally lacerated the movie work of the ``Friends'' cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little unfair,'' says Perry, who prior to ``The Whole
Nine Yards'' had appeared in such misfires as ``Fools Rush In''
(1996) and ``Almost Heroes'' (1998). ``I think there is a bit of,
`A David Schwimmer movie must do better, because he's on TV all the
time.' It doesn't work that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Passing by, Perry's co-star and on-camera romantic interest
Courteney Cox Arquette agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who just do movies can have failures and it's OK,'' she
says. ``But with us it's, like, `Whoa! Another Friend bites the
dust! Keep your day job!'''
</P>
<P>
   That day job has been hopping lately, with the ongoing romance
between Chandler (Perry) and longtime pal Monica (Cox Arquette)
keeping fans in a tizzy. However, Perry cautions that viewers
shouldn't necessarily expect to see the two live happily ever
after.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the secret these days to a successful TV show is
to keep people unhappy,'' Perry says with Chandler-esque
resignation. ``You don't want to see a happy couple. If you just
had Monica and Chandler in love, staring at the stars, people
aren't going to watch that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he turned 30 only a few months ago, Perry is actually
the seasoned acting veteran of the ``Friends'' cast, having been
working steadily since the 1987 Fox sitcom ``Second Chance.'' He
admits that it's tough playing the same character week in and week
out, but claims that taping in front of a live audience is what
gives ``Friends'' that extra boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps a lot,'' he says. ``I mean, we've done a silly amount
of shows, more than 130 shows or something. And we still get
nervous before the show, which is cool. The day I don't get nervous
before the show is the day I probably shouldn't be here anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get in there and you hear the laughter,'' he adds,
``your performance just comes up. It's like putting on a different
one-act play every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry isn't contenting himself with merely playing Chandler,
either. He wrote one of this season's episodes of ``Friends,'' and
is developing a pilot for ABC, called ``The Shrink.'' As if that
weren't enough, the success of ``The Whole Nine Yards'' has left
him fielding a slew of film offers for his next summer hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   If everything falls into place, who knows? He might wind up as
famous as his friend Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   If he does, though, Perry says he can handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good far outweighs the bad,'' he says with a shrug. ``Now,
if there's a guy outside my house taking pictures, I don't have to
panic about it. People aren't chasing us around anymore _ they're
chasing around the new 18-or-19-year-old stars.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor at TV Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Friends,'' consult the NBC Web
site at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York Times
Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
