<HEADER>
A2235 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-10 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LOCK UP THE CRAZY TV 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The other night I watched the new mental
hospital drama ``Wonderland'' with one of the toughest of critics _
a former mental patient.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC show has been praised by television critics for
realistically portraying life in a big-city emergency psychiatric
ward. It has been panned by the National Alliance of the Mentally
Ill for portraying the mentally ill as violent.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Billy, a veteran of six hospitalizations for
manic-depression, panned ``Wonderland'' for assaulting the senses,
not for assaulting the oversensitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is silly. It's all people flipping out,'' Billy said.
``There's too much shouting. Mental hospitals are so quiet you can
hear the Thorazine rattling in the tiny paper cups.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy admitted he may have done some shouting, but he had
another criticism: ``Real mental hospitals are more entertaining
than this. There's a reason they're called funny farms. This one
isn't funny enough.''
</P>
<P>
   I had to stop him from telling his old stories about escaping
down the laundry chute, smoking weed in the empty seclusion room
and mobilizing the manics to vote down the chronics for control of
the TV set.
</P>
<P>
   Billy also panned the show for inducing illness _ not mental
illness, but seasickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``That green lighting and jiggling camera are driving me nuts,''
he said. ``The jiggling camera is meant to make things seem
realistic, but human perception doesn't work like that. God gave us
Steadicam.''
</P>
<P>
   See what he means about crazy people, even recovered ones? They
can be very funny.
</P>
<P>
   What do we get on ``Wonderland``? In just two episodes, a
schizophrenic shot five people, a pregnant woman was stabbed in the
stomach and the killer schizophrenic committed suicide with a
fountain pen. And millions of viewers got seasick.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Thursday's show, one of the actors came on and
made a little statement about how the mentally ill are
overwhelmingly nonviolent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not on this show,'' Billy said.
</P>
<P>
   The one scene that got to Billy on Thursday's episode was when
the parents of the homicidal schizophrenic got upset at doctors
discussing their son as a ``case.'' They begged the doctors to use
their son's name.
</P>
<P>
   The show does communicate some of the torment of psychosis, and
the anguish of families seeing the madness in their loved ones'
eyes, and hearing it in their bizarre tales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' does not succumb to the romantic notion that
insanity is arbitrarily determined by society and that asylums are
filled with sane people, interrupted by mind-numbing psychiatric
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to describe, to someone who has never seen it, how
terrible and intractable madness often is,'' anthropologist T.M.
Luhrmann writes in ``Of Two Minds: The Growing Disorder in American
Psychiatry.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget ``Wonderland.'' Luhrmann's book is hardly intended as
entertainment, but she describes the insane and their doctors in
marvelous novelistic detail _ and she finds the humor Billy talked
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``When psychosis is not brutally awful, it is funny, and
sometimes looking for the humor in it makes it more possible to
handle the pain of seeing a human being lose his mind,'' she writes
sorrowfully.
</P>
<P>
   Luhrmann spent years doing field work in a variety of mental
institutions, studying psychiatry the way an anthropologist would
any culture. The culture of psychiatry is unnecessarily split
between two belief systems. One would treat mental illness by
passing out pills; the other would do talk therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd never get anywhere if we didn't do both,'' said Dr. Mark
Leary, deputy chief of the psychiatry department at San Francisco
General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Just as most work on the range would make lousy cowboy shows,
most mental illness would make lousy hospital shows.
</P>
<P>
   As Billy put it, ``The mentally ill are just working hard being
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Then ``Wonderland'' ended and gave way to the local news and the
story of the wacked-out bicyclist shooting it out with cops on the
Bay Bridge. Maybe it will be a future episode of ``Wonderland.''
</P>
<P>
   It's harder to do the stories of all the former mental patients
like Billy, who are living and working among us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-10 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUICK BANKS ON RENDEZVOUS TO MEET CUSTOMER DEMAND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ When Buick rolls out its all-new Rendezvous
sport-utility vehicle next spring, it will be none too soon for Guy
Sensiba, sales manager at Cavender Buick in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Buick dealers nationwide, Cavender Buick for several
years now has had to deal almost daily with loyal customers who
want to buy another Buick product but feel the need for a
sport-utility rather than a sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Buick is the only General Motors division that has no
sport-utility or minivan product to offer longtime customers who
want to follow the consumer trend and buy a trucklike product
instead of a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had the Rendezvous right now, but at least it is on
the way and we know when it will be here,'' Sensiba said recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have customers who have driven Buicks exclusively for 25
years trading them in for Chevrolet Tahoes, and there's not much we
can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He told of a longtime customer who came in just to apologize
because the man had decided to trade his wife's Buick for a Tahoe,
a full-size sport-utility. ``He said his wife liked her Buick, but
she was tired of sitting in traffic behind those big SUVs.''
</P>
<P>
   Buick dealers watched their business erode as first the minivan
and then the sport-utility craze swept America. Other GM dealers
have products to offer their customers other than traditional cars;
even Cadillac now sells a full-size SUV based on the Tahoe. Pontiac
dealers have the Montana, a combination minivan/SUV, and later this
spring will get the Aztek, a mini-SUV designed for a youthful
audience. Oldsmobile dealers have had a premium compact
sport-utility _ the Bravada (based on the Chevy Blazer) _ and the
Silhouette minivan for several years.
</P>
<P>
   At many Buick dealerships, it's rare to see anyone under age 60
shopping for a car, even though this GM division offers two
contemporary sedans that car experts widely agree are right on
target to appeal to baby boomers and consumers in their 30s: the
midsize Regal and full-size Lesabre (which is very similar to a
Toyota Camry).
</P>
<P>
   That should change with the introduction of the Rendezvous,
which will be an exclusive Buick product not shared with any other
GM division, Buick officials say.
</P>
<P>
   And it should be a hit with consumers, auto critics say, because
it takes the best of the styling and attributes of such popular
SUVs as the Lexus RX 300, Mercedes-Benz M-class and BMW X5 and
rolls them all into one affordable package.
</P>
<P>
   The Rendezvous is also a bit of history in the making: It's the
first Buick truck product in almost 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it's technically considered a truck, this is a
vehicle that maintains the kind of comfort and convenience that
consumers expect from a premium family sedan _ a blend of carlike
ride, handling and interior amenities with the versatility and
roominess of an SUV.
</P>
<P>
   That blend signifies the future of the sport-utility genre,
where the vehicles are getting much more refined and much less
trucklike while retaining the qualities that endear SUVs to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   To be introduced as a 2002 model, Rendezvous will go into
production in spring 2001. Buick dealers already have gotten a
close look _ it was shown to them in San Diego in February during
the Buick Invitational Golf Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the vehicle platform of the GM minivans such as the
Pontiac Montana, the Rendezvous will be offered with a variety of
seating arrangements that will accommodate up to seven passengers
(with the optional third seating row). Remove the third seat, and
the vehicle can be arranged to hold up to 108.9 cubic feet of cargo
_ about five-and-a-half times the capacity of a Buick Park Avenue
sedan's trunk.
</P>
<P>
   It will come either with two-wheel drive or the optional GM
Versatrak all-wheel-drive system that offers sure-footed traction
under almost all road conditions. It can be equipped to tow up to
3,500 pounds, which should make it an attractive vehicle for
consumers with boat, horse or recreational trailers.
</P>
<P>
   Why create a Buick truck after eight decades of cars? It's a
matter of survival for dealers and the brand itself, GM officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research shows that the boomer and Generation X groups,
who tend to buy SUVs and other trucks, acknowledge there is plenty
of quality behind the Buick marquee,'' said Buick division General
Manager Roger W. Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the opportunity is there to transfer what a lot of
customers like about a Buick to a premium vehicle built according
to a brand-new formula _ highly functional, enjoyable to drive, and
highly luxurious.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendezvous will be the first SUV to combine three-row seating, a
flat load floor, all-wheel drive and independent rear suspension.
It will have a traditional Buick oval-shaped grille that marks it
immediately as a Buick product, but unlike the more garish big
Detroit luxury cars of the past, the grille will be painted rather
than chromed.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-inch-wide rear hatch opening will be wide enough to
accommodate 4-by-8-foot sheets of plywood, one of the important
benchmark standards for any contemporary truck product.
</P>
<P>
   Power will come from a 3.4-liter V-6 engine generating 185
horsepower and 210 foot-pounds of torque. A major advantage of this
engine will be the Rendezvous' fuel economy: up to 19 miles per
gallon in the city and 24 mpg on the highway with the
front-wheel-drive model, or 17 city/22 highway with all-wheel
drive. That's a huge improvement over most of today's mid- and
full-size SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   Safety features will be built in throughout the vehicle,
including front and side air bags for the front-seat occupants,
safety-cage construction and four-wheel antilock disc brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury features will abound, including power-everything,
automatic climate control, advanced security systems and the
availability of GM's OnStar communications and guidance system that
uses Global Positioning System satellite technology.
</P>
<P>
   No prices have been announced yet, but Buick expects to position
the Rendezvous to compete directly against sport-utilities in the
low- to mid-$30,000s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
