<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2245 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-GM-PICKUPS-HNS &LR;      04-10 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-PICKUPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REVAMPED GM PICKUPS GO BEYOND LOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For almost two years after Ford introduced its redesigned F-150
pickup line in 1996, people wanted to know when General Motors was
going to roll out its long-awaited and much-anticipated next
generation of full-size pickups.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of consumers thought that GM was already way overdue with
a new pickup when the restyled F-150 appeared, because another
rival, Dodge, had debuted the newest generation of its full-size
Ram pickup in 1994, a radically redesigned vehicle that took the
market by storm.
</P>
<P>
   GM finally got around to updating its full-size pickups for
model year 1999.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that GM took its time in bringing out the updated GMC
Sierra and Chevrolet Silverado so that it could get these vehicles
just right.
</P>
<P>
   No, the styling isn't radically different from the previous
generation. GM has endured some criticism for that from people who
were awed by the dramatically different styling that Ford brought
to the new F-150 and Dodge brought to the Ram.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the fenders are a bit more round and the overall look
is considerably more modern that before, but a radical restyling of
the GM pickups really wasn't necessary. GM took the time to conduct
focus-group sessions with many of its customers before redesigning
the trucks, and found that the vast majority did not want a bold
new look for the vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, GM spent the money more wisely, improving just about
every other aspect of the vehicle as well as tuning up the styling.
The result is a pickup that not only is much better than it was
before, but which also outshines its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But as good as those first redesigned (1999) models were, the
2000 models are even better.
</P>
<P>
   First on the list of improvements for this year is the optional
fourth door for the extended-cab models. For this review, we tested
a three-door model, but I can tell you after a week of driving the
Sierra that I would prefer to have the fourth door.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with the three-door is that the door is on
the passenger side. That just doesn't make sense. Statistics show
that full-size pickups have only one occupant in them about 90
percent of the time. And if the driver wants to load or unload some
inside cargo, he or she must walk around to the other side of the
truck.
</P>
<P>
   GM put the third door on the driver's side in its compact-pickup
line (the Chevy S-10, GMC Sonoma and Isuzu Hombre), and justified
that by saying that it would be more convenient for the driver to
load and unload from the driver's side. But apparently that logic
didn't carry through to the designers of the full-size pickups.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth door costs just $728, and it's worth it. If you
choose the three-door model to save money, though, you'll have to
deal with having the third door on the passenger's side. Still,
that's better than the alternative of just a few years ago _ no
rear doors at all. And if you're using the Sierra to haul people,
they can get into and out of the back on their own.
</P>
<P>
   In that back seat, there is a lot more room for people and cargo
than you'll find in the competitors' vehicles. The door is wide
enough for easy entry and exit, too. Sierra (and Silverado) have
the largest door openings on extended-cab pickups in the full-size
pickup segment.
</P>
<P>
   GM increased power by 15 horsepower in two of the full-size
pickups' engines for 2000. The 4.8-liter Vortec V-8 is now rated at
270 horsepower, while the 5.3-liter Vortec V-8 now has 285
horsepower. Torque is up by 10 foot-pounds in each engine, too.
</P>
<P>
   Our test vehicle came with the 5.3-liter engine, which offered
plenty of smooth, responsive power for all conditions, from
around-town stop-and-go driving to high-speed cruising.
</P>
<P>
   Several safety and convenience features were added for 2000,
including programmable automatic locking and unlocking of the
doors. Drivers can customize their vehicles to lock automatically
when the truck reaches 15 mph, and to automatically unlock when
they stop and remove the keys from the ignition. These features can
be turned on or off independently, and, for security reasons, the
system can be set to lock and unlock only the driver's side door
automatically, or to lock and unlock both sides simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   We drove the two-wheel-drive 1500 model, the smallest of the
full-size GM pickups and also the one with the best ride. Still, it
does ride like a truck, no matter how carlike GM tries to make it
</P>
<P>
   The interior is the Sierra's best attribute. The extended-cab
models have a back seat that is really a seat and not some short,
ill-designed attempt at one. There is support for the thighs and
plenty of leg room. About two-thirds of pickup buyers choose
extended-cab models because they need the extra passenger space,
but only the Sierra and Silverado offer a truly practical rear
seat.
</P>
<P>
   With the changes GM made in the 1999 models, the truck's frame
is stronger than before, the V-8 engines are all new and more
powerful than ever, and even the brakes are far superior to those
of the previous GM trucks and any of the competition. Four-wheel
disc brakes are now standard across the line.
</P>
<P>
   The base engine is a 4.3-liter V-6, which is standard on two-
and four-wheel-drive 1500 models. It cranks out 200 horsepower and
260 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
