A2246 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-10 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LOCK UP THE CRAZY TV 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The other night I watched the new mental
hospital drama ``Wonderland'' with one of the toughest of critics _
a former mental patient.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC show has been praised by television critics for
realistically portraying life in a big-city emergency psychiatric
ward. It has been panned by the National Alliance of the Mentally
Ill for portraying the mentally ill as violent.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Billy, a veteran of six hospitalizations for
manic-depression, panned ``Wonderland'' for assaulting the senses,
not for assaulting the oversensitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is silly. It's all people flipping out,'' Billy said.
``There's too much shouting. Mental hospitals are so quiet you can
hear the Thorazine rattling in the tiny paper cups.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy admitted he may have done some shouting, but he had
another criticism: ``Real mental hospitals are more entertaining
than this. There's a reason they're called funny farms. This one
isn't funny enough.''
</P>
<P>
   I had to stop him from telling his old stories about escaping
down the laundry chute, smoking weed in the empty seclusion room
and mobilizing the manics to vote down the chronics for control of
the TV set.
</P>
<P>
   Billy also panned the show for inducing illness _ not mental
illness, but seasickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``That green lighting and jiggling camera are driving me nuts,''
he said. ``The jiggling camera is meant to make things seem
realistic, but human perception doesn't work like that. God gave us
Steadicam.''
</P>
<P>
   See what he means about crazy people, even recovered ones? They
can be very funny.
</P>
<P>
   What do we get on ``Wonderland``? In just two episodes, a
schizophrenic shot five people, a pregnant woman was stabbed in the
stomach and the killer schizophrenic committed suicide with a
fountain pen. And millions of viewers got seasick.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Thursday's show, one of the actors came on and
made a little statement about how the mentally ill are
overwhelmingly nonviolent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not on this show,'' Billy said.
</P>
<P>
   The one scene that got to Billy on Thursday's episode was when
the parents of the homicidal schizophrenic got upset at doctors
discussing their son as a ``case.'' They begged the doctors to use
their son's name.
</P>
<P>
   The show does communicate some of the torment of psychosis, and
the anguish of families seeing the madness in their loved ones'
eyes, and hearing it in their bizarre tales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' does not succumb to the romantic notion that
insanity is arbitrarily determined by society and that asylums are
filled with sane people, interrupted by mind-numbing psychiatric
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to describe, to someone who has never seen it, how
terrible and intractable madness often is,'' anthropologist T.M.
Luhrmann writes in ``Of Two Minds: The Growing Disorder in American
Psychiatry.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget ``Wonderland.'' Luhrmann's book is hardly intended as
entertainment, but she describes the insane and their doctors in
marvelous novelistic detail _ and she finds the humor Billy talked
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``When psychosis is not brutally awful, it is funny, and
sometimes looking for the humor in it makes it more possible to
handle the pain of seeing a human being lose his mind,'' she writes
sorrowfully.
</P>
<P>
   Luhrmann spent years doing field work in a variety of mental
institutions, studying psychiatry the way an anthropologist would
any culture. The culture of psychiatry is unnecessarily split
between two belief systems. One would treat mental illness by
passing out pills; the other would do talk therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd never get anywhere if we didn't do both,'' said Dr. Mark
Leary, deputy chief of the psychiatry department at San Francisco
General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Just as most work on the range would make lousy cowboy shows,
most mental illness would make lousy hospital shows.
</P>
<P>
   As Billy put it, ``The mentally ill are just working hard being
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Then ``Wonderland'' ended and gave way to the local news and the
story of the wacked-out bicyclist shooting it out with cops on the
Bay Bridge. Maybe it will be a future episode of ``Wonderland.''
</P>
<P>
   It's harder to do the stories of all the former mental patients
like Billy, who are living and working among us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
