<HEADER>
A2247 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-EDITOR-OF-THE-YEAR-HN     04-10 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITOR-OF-THE-YEAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     E&AMP;P NAMES RIVARD EDITOR OF YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DICK J. REAVIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Editor &AMP; Publisher, the leading journal of the
newspaper industry, has named Robert Rivard of the San Antonio
Express-News editor of the year.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time in the magazine's 116-year history that it
has bestowed the honor, reserved for the editorial chiefs of the
nation's 1,500 daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our decision was made by our top editors, and it was made by a
unanimous vote,'' E&AMP;P Executive Editor Steve Yahn said.
</P>
<P>
   In stories about the award and its first recipient, editors at
the magazine cited three factors as pivotal in honoring Rivard:
</P>
<P>
   _ His role in dealing with the December 1998 disappearance and
slaying of the newspaper's Mexico City bureau chief, Philip True,
</P>
<P>
   _ His ``unselfish commitment to the long-term future of
newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The opinion of San Antonio civic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's April 10 issue quotes Andy Sarabia of Communities
Organized for Public Service and Steve Moore, executive director of
the San Antonio Convention and Visitors Bureau, in support of its
choice of Rivard.
</P>
<P>
   Rivard, 47, a graduate of the University of Texas at San
Antonio, began his newspaper career in 1977 as a sports reporter in
Brownsville. He covered the Central American wars for the Dallas
Times-Herald and for Newsweek, later becoming that magazine's chief
of correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   Rivard returned to Texas in 1990 as deputy managing editor of
the San Antonio Light, moving to the Express-News when the city's
two dailies were consolidated three years later. He became editor
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Express-News is published in the morning and has a daily
circulation of 217,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his duties at the Express-News, Rivard is a
director of the Inter-American Press Association, and he was a
judge for the 1999 Pulitzer Prize contest, whose results will be
announced this month.
</P>
<P>
   When True was reported missing on a solo hiking trip in Mexico's
remote Sierra Madre mountains, Express-News General Manager Tom
Stephenson recalls that Rivard called him and Publisher Larry
Walker to a Sunday meeting to set a course for the newspaper's
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Larry and I thought that it was dangerous, but Bob was
adamant that he should go to Mexico,'' Stephenson said. ``He wasn't
going to be able to live with himself if he didn't do everything
that he could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivard led the expedition that, a few days later, discovered and
unearthed True's body from a shallow grave in a canyon where he had
been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have never recovered Philip's body or known what
happened had Bob not gone,'' Walker said. ``He exemplified what
newspeople from around the world would like an editor to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Two men were arrested last year in the killing, but Rivard noted
that neither has been brought to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``In May,'' he said, ``we'll be going to Mexico again, to meet
with the governor and attorney general of Jalisco state and with a
new judge in the case, and to demand some answers.''
</P>
<P>
   In E&AMP;P's edition naming Rivard as editor of the year, the
magazine publishes an article about True's disappearance and
slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am grateful that the case is being spotlighted,'' Rivard
said.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also cites Rivard for his decision in October to
decline an offer to become editor of the Miami Herald. He turned
down the job when the Hearst Corp., owner of the Express-News,
agreed to increase the newsroom budget.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial in E&AMP;P notes that Rivard ``demonstrated an
unselfish commitment to the long-term future of newspapers when he
turned a golden career opportunity _ editorship of the Miami Herald
_ into an investment in new journalists, better staff pay and a
bigger news hole.''
</P>
<P>
   As Rivard explained, ``I thought that I had taken the
Express-News as far I could take it, given the resources that were
available. We had too few people who were not paid well enough, and
there was a news space problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, he recalled, ``Hearst bought a newspaper that
didn't have computers and didn't have presses. It has been
investing millions since 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   In negotiations to keep him in San Antonio, he said Hearst
``decided to invest in its people as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Also important, Rivard said, were actions by Hearst on behalf of
True's widow and infant son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martha True is now in Brownsville, little Philip is a happy,
healthy baby and Hearst has secured the family's future,'' he said.
``The corporation's concern for Philip's family was central to my
decision to stay here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Express-News is not yet a great newspaper, but it has
great days and I think that we're on our way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
