<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2250 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-10 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE GAME STRIKING OUT OR BATTING .300?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball is dying. Nobody cares about it.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is thriving. The game has never been more exciting.
</P>
<P>
   I know what you're thinking. I'm arguing with myself. My tenuous
connection with reality has finally evaporated. Next thing you
know, I'll be insisting that Elian Gonzalez should stay in Miami
and go back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Those contradictory judgments about the condition of baseball
come from a couple of pundits who usually aim their intellectual
firepower in the direction of weightier matters _ public policy,
politics, societal trends of global significance.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Krauthammer, who writes for Time magazine, and
George Will of Newsweek decided to ponder baseball in the April 3
issues of their respective magazines. Leave it to the deep-thinkers
to examine the same crime scene and reach diametrically different
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Krauthammer says that major-league baseball has never recovered
from its ``catastrophic'' 1994 strike and that the game is in
``deep decline.''
</P>
<P>
   Will says that the impressive accomplishments of future Hall of
Famers such as Cal Ripken, Derek Jeter and Ivan Rodriguez make
baseball ``in many ways better than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Krauthammer says that America has tuned out the sport _ that
fans chatter eagerly and endlessly about basketball and football,
but where baseball is concerned, ``There is no talk. No interest.
No buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   Will says that baseball is embarking on a ``crackerjack (so to
speak) season'' and that even though the first game was played in
Japan this year, opening day remains a ``civic festival.''
</P>
<P>
   If these guys are that far apart on baseball, I can't wait to
see their competing columns on the relative qualifications of Al
Gore and George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But we're talking baseball, as well we should be at the outset
of a new season; it's the one point in time when every fan can
believe that his or her favorite team might have an autumn date
with destiny.
</P>
<P>
   As a lifelong aficionado of the game, I must confess that I hope
against hope that Will is correct. Nothing would please me more
than to see the onetime national pastime recapture its former
glory, to see the game that once caused school kids to play hooky
re-establish itself as the preeminent sport in a sport-crazed
nation.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand _ as a disillusioned baseball fan who has
spent much of the last decade boycotting the game in disgust, I
find it hard to disagree with Krauthammer's pessimistic assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the boycott. I'm forever running into someone who wants to
know if I'm still boycotting baseball _ an encouraging sign,
perhaps, in view of Krauthammer's contention that nobody even talks
about baseball these days.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is ``yes.'' And ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   There I go again.
</P>
<P>
   To the annoyance of some hard-core boycotters, I modified my
boycott two years ago to place more emphasis on keeping players and
team owners from getting their hands on my hard-earned money, and
less on the futile goal of shutting myself off from any exposure to
the game.
</P>
<P>
   I refuse to attend games in person or purchase licensed
merchandise such as T-shirts and coffee mugs. But I can watch games
on television, and I can read baseball stories in the newspaper. I
can watch baseball highlights on the TV news.
</P>
<P>
   It is undeniably a wimpy boycott. But it's my boycott, and I
figure I can go about it any way I see fit.
</P>
<P>
   Next question: Why bother?
</P>
<P>
   Did you see the item in the Sports section the other day that
said the average salary of major-league ballplayers this season is
$1,988,034? The story said that 377 of the game's 840 players _
nearly 45 percent _ make $1 million or more; 20 players will
collect $9 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Two problems: The fans are footing the bill. And most of the
ungrateful bums who haul down those preposterous paychecks aren't
worth a fraction of what they are being paid.
</P>
<P>
   So _ is baseball dying or thriving?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it depends on whether you ask the payers or the payees.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
