<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOU HAVE A CHOICE OF FUNDS, THINK DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Q. I participate in my company's profit-sharing. In addition
to the fund I am using, I have choices of four other Diversified
Investors Strategic Allocation funds: Short-Term Horizon, Short
International Horizon, Intermediate Horizon, and Long Horizon. What
do you suggest I do?
</P>
<P>
   J.G., La Mesa, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. These are what are called funds of funds _ or funds that
limit their investments to shares of other mutual funds within the
same family. The idea is to provide a diversified portfolio that is
appropriate to your situation. In the case of the Diversified
Strategic Allocation funds, the company chooses among 14 separate
funds, allocating the portfolio according to the investor's
investment timeframe.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, a long-term portfolio will be accumulating for more
than 10 years, an intermediate one for five to 10 years, and a
short-term investment for less than five years. With nine years to
go until a typical retirement date, you're in about the right
place.
</P>
<P>
   But you can also use these categories to reflect your appetite
for risk. If you consider yourself a conservative investor, you
could well decide to switch to the more cautious Diversified
Investors Intermediate Horizon Strategic Allocation fund.
</P>
<P>
   To give you an idea of the way the portfolios of these funds
change, I'll list the top five holdings of each: The
intermediate/long-term fund has 13.9 percent of its assets in
Diversified Special fund, which focuses on small-cap growth stocks;
11.4 percent in Diversified Growth fund, a large-cap growth fund;
11.1 percent in Diversified Investors Equity Income, with a
large-cap value-oriented portfolio; 10.9 percent in a core bond
fund; and 10.2 percent in an international stock fund.
</P>
<P>
   With Intermediate Horizon Strategic Allocation, you would have
23.2 percent in the bond fund, 10.1 percent in the Special fund,
9.4 percent in a high-yield bond fund, 8.9 percent in a
high-quality bond fund, and 8.5 percent in the equity-income find.
In short, by moving from a concentration of stocks to a heavier
bond portfolio, the intermediate-term fund is safer, but is also
less likely to deliver stock market gains.
</P>
<P>
   Given the state of the market, if I were you I would switch to
Diversified Investors Intermediate Horizon Strategic Allocation
fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have had Fidelity Puritan for years, but recently it has
not done well. I am elderly and hesitate to sell if this fund has a
good chance of recovering. Do you think this is a temporary slump?
</P>
<P>
   M.A., Fort Worth, Texas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Puritan certainly has been taking its lumps, but I wouldn't
lose faith. This is a well-disciplined fund, maintaining a solid
value-oriented stock portfolio, and a solid (if far from gilt-edge)
portfolio of bonds. Both sectors it favors _ bonds of all stripes
and value-oriented stocks _ have been the wrong places to be in the
last year or so, although in the near term the value stocks have
been picking up.
</P>
<P>
   I think you can blame the lion's share of the fund's 2.9 percent
loss in 1999 on the bond position. But remember 1994, the last
horrible year for bonds before 1999. That year, Puritan's total
return worked out to a scant 1.8 percent. The next year, however,
the same bond portfolio that had plagued it in 1994 propelled it to
a 21.5 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying 2000 will be anything like 1995 for Puritan. But
I do think it's a solid fund and it has been sticking to its
knitting, no matter how unpopular its chosen market segments are at
any particular time.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in the current choppy markets it should prove
relatively steady. Its stock portfolio is focused on financials,
industrials, and services, and its price-to-earnings ratio is a
comforting 24.7. It has a distinct underweighting in technology
issues _ one reason it bucked the bond market of 1999, but also the
reason it is not suffering horribly this month.
</P>
<P>
   Although Morningstar Mutual Funds had reduced its rating to
three stars, or average, that's based entirely on statistical data.
It seems as clear that its analysts want to give its shareholders
some solace: a classic conservatively managed balanced fund,
Morningstar summarizes.
</P>
<P>
   I agree, and suggest you hang on for better seasons. Despite the
poor recent performance, look to its five-year record of 14.57
percent average annual gains, or the 10-year record of 13.41
percent. In time, shareholders who stay with the fund should be
rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 90-year-old mother received some AT&AMP;T spinoff stocks as an
inheritance 13 years ago. Some have been sold since then to
supplement her $500 monthly Social Security income. She lives alone
in a senior apartment complex and is very private, so I only know
that the value of her stocks was about $100,000 in January 1999.
Her quarterly dividends and her Social Security income have not
been enough to meet her obligations. Her rent is $400 a month, plus
utilities. Though a novice, I'm of the opinion that the stocks are
too risky. In truth, she's too elderly to chance it at all. I'd
much prefer that she cash them in, set aside the capital gains tax
money in some short-term savings account, and put the balance in
some kind of government or state bond. If I'm correct, the
principal would be safe, and the yield would be more than she is
currently receiving. At the moment I've got her attention and feel
she will act on my suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   B.K., Bedford, N.H. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You're certainly right that your mother isn't getting much in
the way of yield. As this is written, the best she is getting is
2.9 percent from US West; at the other end of the spectrum, the
yield on Vodafone Airtouch is a token 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   I agree it would be better under the circumstances to sell these
securities and replace them with a fixed-income holding, but I'm
not sure I'd go for either state or government bonds. In the first
case, state bonds are attractive to most people for their
tax-exempt feature. From your description of your mother's
finances, it seems that taxes are not likely to pose a major
problem. Government bonds, or a government bond fund, would be
better, with a reasonable expectation of yields in the 6 percent
range. But just as stocks are susceptible to the markets, bond
funds can lose money. Last year, as interest rates rose steadily,
many bond funds ended up in the red.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, at this point CD rates look relatively
attractive. Last week, the nation's best rate for a five-year CD of
less than $100,000 was 7.46 percent. So why fool around with
government bonds and accept the risk when you can get a better
yield with full insurance at the bank?
</P>
<P>
   The only wrinkle is that you need to shop around fairly
aggressively. That 7.46 percent high compared to a 6 percent
national average. You can find the highest rates in newspapers and
online, such as at www.bankrate.com. It provides all the
information you need, including toll-free telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   If you take this course, calculate beforehand what your mother's
tax obligations are likely to be. My guess is you'll find that a
great percentage of the proceeds of any sale is going to be a
taxable capital gain. You might discover you would be better off
spreading the sales over two or more years.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you take the CD route, I suggest you put the bulk of
the money into a five-year CD,but leave a fairly modest amount _
perhaps a tenth _ in a six-month CD, where you can find rates of up
to 6.70 percent and retain a higher degree of liquidity. Then, if
your mother runs into unexpected expenses, she won't face an
early-withdrawal penalty as with the 5-year instrument.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
