<SLUG> BC-KOREA-TALKS-870&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS FOR A NORTH-SOUTH SUMMIT MEETING SURPRISE MANY SOUTH
KOREANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ The news that this country had sealed its
biggest diplomatic breakthrough in its half-century of conflict
with North Korea, its estranged and impoverished twin, seemed to
have reached everyone in this capital by late Monday morning and
left no one indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   From experts in their think tanks to commuters rushing to work,
South Koreans seemed stunned by the secret diplomacy whose fruit,
announced in an unprecedented simultaneous statement issued in the
capitals of both countries Monday morning, will be a June visit to
the North Korean capital, Pyongyang, by President Kim Dae-jung of
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly speaking, no one saw North Korea saying yes to a
summit meeting at this time,'' said Cho Dong-ho, the head of North
Korean economic studies at the Korea Development Institute, a
private, non-profit research group here. ``We have all been deeply
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was positive in almost every instance, but came
freighted with complex sentiments and anxieties that are the legacy
of a shared history of wartime violence, yield-no-quarter
ideological jousting and harshly contrasting economic fates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really think these countries will unify anytime soon?''
asked Han Kyoung-ok, a 51-year-old woman who was preparing to board
a train at midday. ``For people of my generation, this is good
news. But younger people have grown soft in this country, and now I
fear that the Northerners, who have lived through so much, will
out-compete us.''
</P>
<P>
   Her statement reflected in part the fact that the span of her
life, roughly the period since June 1950, when the war that divided
the countries broke out, has coincided with an extraordinary
turnabout in the fortunes of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of their separate histories, North Korea,
although more sparsely populated, was by far the more prosperous of
the two. But since the 1970s, and accelerating more each year,
South Korea has outstripped its neighbor, becoming one of the
world's most energetic and entrepreneurial societies while the
Stalinist north, though still heavily armed, has wallowed in
devastating famines and industrial collapse.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   These contrasting fortunes are advertised by billboards that by
night flash slogans like ``South Korea: the land of opportunity''
on the mountainsides just south of the heavily armed border. These
days, though, the message seems unnecessary, as North Koreans risk
their lives to flee hunger, crossing into China in hopes of
eventually making their way to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Like Han, several other South Koreans interviewed expressed
trepidation about the diplomatic opening with the North, and the
unpredictability of renewing high-level contact between countries
that share the same language, history and culture but that have
been so divided by politics and economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't support unification, because things are nice the way
they are now,'' said Hwang Ji-hwa, 21, who spoke while in downtown
Seoul. ``There are just too many differences between our countries.
If we try to unify, things might get out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While others applauded Kim's so-called Sunshine Policy, the
program of steady diplomatic and financial engagement with North
Korea that produced the breakthrough, some South Koreans warned
that what lies ahead is plenty of heavy slogging and ultimately a
high price tag for reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Many South Korean experts on North Korean diplomatic behavior
wondered aloud Monday what price had been extracted by the
Pyongyang government for the breakthrough, especially given the
announcement's timing, on the eve of critical legislative elections
here Thursday. In practical terms, the vote will determine how much
power the South Korean president, Kim, wields for his remaining
three years in office.
</P>
<P>
   And in addition to finally rewarding Kim for the steep political
risks he has taken in reaching out to the North, several analysts
here said that Pyongyang had likely calculated that the eve of the
vote was the moment to strike a diplomatic deal at the highest
price. After its dramatic news conference Monday morning, the
government released no new details about the agreement with North
Korea, leaving people to guess about its terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all waiting for the details of what we must give them
and what we can expect from North Korea,'' said Yeon Ha-cheong, the
dean of the school of marketing at Myongai University in Seoul, and
an expert in relations with Pyongyang. ``North Korea will certainly
demand lots of things.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's recent pattern of diplomatic behavior seems to
support this view. For years, following the end of the Cold War and
the loss of most of its Communist allies, the country bore the
title of the world's most isolated regime. Now North Korea has
recently emerged as one of the most diplomatically active
countries, as it has rushed to establish ties with a wide range of
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Often, though, formal ties _ or even serious diplomatic contacts
_ have come at a steep price. There have been persistent reports in
recent weeks that since agreeing to resume official talks with
Japan, Pyongyang has sought $5 billion in ``reparations'' from
Tokyo for its colonial rule in Korea.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The United States, too, has often been put in a position where
it had to commit to helping ease North Korea's economic
catastrophe, through major food or fuel deliveries, in exchange for
Pyongyang's cooperation in suspending its nuclear weapons
development or halting the testing of its long range missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, after weeks of campaigning against Kim's Sunshine Policy
as a fruitless sellout of South Korea, the president's political
rivals were threatened by the dramatic diplomatic turnabout and
clung to the line that a summit meeting with hidden, and presumably
high costs is no victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government must have paid a huge price, or agreed to some
secret conditions to reach this deal, but that side has not been
revealed,'' said Jan Kwang-keun, a spokesman for the Grand National
Party, the main opposition group. ``We want to remind people that
such compensations involve taxpayers' money.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
