<HEADLINE>
APPRAISAL DIDN'T RING TRUE, BUT THE SETTLEMENT WAS A GEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many people thought Michael and Nancy Greco were crazy, but you
have to admire their tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who don't remember, the Grecos took a cruise
last year and, at a stop in Cozumel, paid $2,400 for a tanzanite
and diamond ring that their Mexican jeweler appraised at $6,530.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great price _ one many consumers would put in the
category of too good to be true. But the Grecos had been reassured
by representatives of Celebrity Cruises, a division of Royal
Caribbean Cruises Ltd., that everything was on the up and up.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise line representatives, a company called Onboard Media,
offered a guarantee of quality and value as long as passengers
shopped at approved stores. The guarantee was contingent on an
appraisal by an independent gemologist within 30 days of a
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   As I reported in December, Michael Greco did what most consumers
never do. After returning to his home in Southeastern
Massachusetts, he tracked down an independent gemologist who
appraised the ring at $1,900. Stunned, Greco alleged fraud and
started raising a ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   The Cozumel jeweler, Rachat &AMP; Romero, insisted that its
certified appraised price was more like a suggested retail price.
The jeweler offered to refund Greco's money if he returned the ring
or pay him $500, the difference between his $1,900 appraisal and
the $2,400 he had paid for the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Onboard Media called the Rachat &AMP; Romero offer ``extremely
diplomatic'' and said it wasn't required by the guarantee. Company
officials said the guarantee meant only that participating
retailers would repair or replace any unsatisfactory item. They
also suggested a second appraisal was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Greco refused the jeweler's settlement offer. He said he had
caught Rachat &AMP; Romero engaging in fraud and that giving him his
money back wasn't enough. The $2,400 he paid for his ring was 37
percent of the jeweler's appraised price, so he said he would be
satisfied to pay only 37 percent of the $1,900 appraised value. In
other words, he would go away if he got to keep the ring and Rachat
&AMP; Romero refunded $1,697, plus the $100 cost of Greco's appraisal.
Rachat &AMP; Romero balked.
</P>
<P>
   After the column appeared, readers reacted. A few praised Greco,
but most thought he was trying to pull a fast one. In general, his
critics thought he was naive to have relied on the jeweler's
appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old saw that you get what you pay for is certainly
appropriate in the jewelry industry,'' said Marc Jasmin of Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Greco's critics thought he should take the jeweler's
offer. But Greco wasn't about to give in. In a Jan. 10 letter to
Rachat &AMP; Romero, he raised the stakes: He demanded a ring
acceptable to him with a true value of $6,500, or $4,100 in cash _
the difference between the jeweler's appraised price of $6,500 and
the $2,400 purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accept my offer or come here to sue me for what you believe is
right,'' Greco wrote. ``If you come here, be aware that
Massachusetts law allows for triple damages plus reasonable
attorneys fees if we win.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Pubols of Rachat &AMP; Romero reponded with a letter saying
the jeweler's earlier refund offer was ``more than generous. . . At
this point we will have to consider the matter closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the two sides talked again on Jan. 27, and Pubols agreed to
Greco's original demand _ that he be charged only 37 percent of the
$1,900 appraisal. But Greco now wanted more. He made a counteroffer
that he be allowed to keep the ring plus receive a refund of the
full $2,400 purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 21, Hugh Treadwell, vice president of Onboard Media,
wrote to Greco, saying that the company would honor his
counteroffer and refund the full purchase price, without any
conditions. His only caveat was that he wanted to run two
additional appraisals on the ring to see if Greco's $1,900
appraisal was accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If two or three independent appraisals confirm yours, it is in
our company's and this industry's best interest to properly verify
that fact in order to take any action,'' Treadwell wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Told of Greco's settlement, Jasmin of Waltham, Mass. said,
``There is truth to the adage that the squeaky wheel gets the
grease. . . One would only hope that Greco would be a bit smarter
next time. If he tries for another refund, he may find his next
encounter less fruitful.''
</P>
<P>
   Greco said he knows some people will think he made out like a
bandit. But he doesn't see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still didn't get what we were originally told we would
get,'' he said, noting he was promised a $6,500 ring for $2,400.
``This whole thing also took all the romance and the excitement out
of purchasing the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trailbreaker.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consumers looking for a little help in understanding online
transactions might want to check out www.trailbreaker.com. The site
offers basic information on everything from buying appliances to
movies and even has someone knowledgable in each area who offers
advice.
</P>
<P>
   The site carries no advertising. It makes money when it guides a
consumer to a merchant with whom it has a referral arrangement or
on fees that other Web sites pay to carry the information.
</P>
<P>
   Boston.com, which is affiliated with The Boston Globe, pays such
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Deb Visco of Olde Towne Mortgage Co. of North Andover, Mass. is
the site's expert for buying mortgages online. She gives useful,
basic advice on what to look out for, including the warning that
some online mortgage companies charge a higher interest rate if you
talk to an actual person.
</P>
<P>
   Trailbreaker lists E-Loan and iOwn.com as the two top mortgage
sites. But what's only implied in Visco's column is perhaps the
most interesting tidbit of all.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of her column, she says that if you're uncomfortable
with or unsure about the online process, you can always deal with a
traditional lender. In an interview, she went even further,
suggesting that regular lenders are far superior _ in part because
they will be more familiar with local customs and laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you want a mortgage lender out of California
anyway?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Odds &AMP; ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Mineral mix-up. Greg Chabot is accustomed to getting credit
card solicitations for gold and platinum cards. But recently he got
one for an Aspire Diamond Visa card. ``With a name like diamond,
you'd expect to be treated like a preferred customer with low
interest rates,'' he said. But when he looked at the fine print, he
discovered just the opposite. Diamond status qualifies you for an
interest rate of 27 percent, and 33 percent in the event of
delinquency. Ouch!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bruce Mohl is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached at
617-474-2510, by e-mail at mohl(at)globe.com, or at The Boston
Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
