<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2265 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS &LR;      04-10 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST POCKET FUZZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, you're at a party in what now seems like another life, and
this guy looks over his hors d'oeuvre cracker and says ``Akamai.''
Or maybe he says ``eBay'' or ``CMGI'' or ``Sycamore,'' and he says
it the way the businessman in ``The Graduate'' said ``plastics'' to
Dustin Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   But you're not some kid fresh out of school. You've got mutual
funds, a career, and nice suits. Mostly you've got rock-solid
common sense, which seems to justify the superior laughter in your
swift retort: ``Akamai? Never heard of it. Get real.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the stock that was selling for pocket fuzz as an
unknown doubles, triples, and heads for Pluto, you remember the
night, and the party, and the guy, and the hors d'oeuvre cracker.
You even remember the olive and the cheese on the cracker. You
close your eyes and hear the wail of a saxophone doing a mean riff
with a train whistle somewhere in the back alley of your mind, and
you're singing the blues for the one that got away.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Sarkis, president of Back Bay Restaurant Group,
remembers the night he was too busy to listen to AOL founder Steve
Case, and associates, attending an opening of a Papa Razzi
restaurant in Washington in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Yeah, yeah, yeah,' '' Sarkis recalls. ``I had 200
people to serve.'' A friend of his did listen and bought AOL at $11
a share. ``He's not working now,'' Sarkis says with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   It hurts so bad, even though times are good _ because times are
good, really. When fortunes seem as easy to grab as a cup of
coffee, any fortune not grabbed assumes the proportions of a fiscal
fish story. The loss pains even those business stars who would seem
to be beyond caring, since they run the success stories that were
once the hot tips over hors d'oeuvre crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Allen, cofounder of Microsoft and now head of Vulcan
Northwest Inc., did not want to talk about the time he sold his
stake in AOL cheap. David Wetherell, chief executive of CMGI, who
passed on eBay, sent a terse e-mail saying he was ``not interested
in revisiting it.''
</P>
<P>
   That bad, huh?
</P>
<P>
   ``The regret is more dramatic today,'' says Joe Weintraub,
management professor at Babson College and an organizational
psychologist. ``It's like looking in a window, pressing your nose
against the glass. The stress is greater because of all the
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, those missed opportunities to buy _ or to sell just before
the market tanks, as it did last week. The only way to deal with
the road not taken to the bank is philosophically. Think Robert
Frost. Think Alfred E. Newman. Think Mike Kornblum.
</P>
<P>
   Kornblum is a Boston public relations executive who got in on
the ground floor of eBay for $17 a share because his sister worked
there, allowing him to take advantage of a special offer to family
and friends. ``I was scared to death,'' says Kornblum, who invested
$3,500 and saw the stock price double by the end of the day. That's
when he bailed out, netting about a $3,000 profit, after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider the $3,000 a gift from heaven that I didn't work
for,'' Kornblum says. ``If you take any other attitude you'll go
crazy.'' He adds that his sister is headed for early retirement at
age 34 and is helping to pay for his kitchen remodeling.
</P>
<P>
   Humor helps at times like these, and a visit to the Bessemer
Venture Partners' Web site is a balm to the wounded psyche.
Bessemer is probably the only company in Massachusetts _ maybe in
the world _ laughing at the ones that got away. The Wellesley
venture capital firm features an ``Anti-portfolio,'' subtitled
``Don't Click Here,'' listing smart investments never made in
winners including eBay, Apple Computer, Intel, Intuit, Lotus, and
Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   The company notes that its ``long and storied history has
afforded our firm an unparalleled number of opportunities to
completely screw up.'' You gotta love these guys.
</P>
<P>
   Partner Chris Gabrieli says the file was inspired by the
intensity of the culture of regret out there in Boom Nation and by
the sound of so many heads banging against so many walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an unprecedented sense of scale and success today,''
he says. ``Venture guys and entrepreneurs are totally obsessed with
this. They're focused on what they've missed _ that's what's
driving the dot-com craze.''
</P>
<P>
   Woulda, shoulda, coulda. Hear that lonesome whistle blow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
