<HEADER>
A2266 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-SAVING-BOS &LR;      04-10 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-SAVING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS AREN'T BIG SAVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government just reported that America's personal savings
rate for February was the lowest it's been since the Great
Depression. Is that bad?
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad if a person is putting nothing away, running up debt,
and renting.
</P>
<P>
   But it's good if a person is saving in ways not measured by what
many economists consider to be an outmoded government yardstick.
</P>
<P>
   The personal savings rate, 0.8 for February, is figured as a
percentage of disposable income. It's what's left when consumption
is subtracted from the income generated by the nation's production
of goods and services (gross domestic product, or GDP).
</P>
<P>
   While the number includes money saved from income _ such as
savings accounts and 401(k) retirement plans _ it does not include
equity in a home, real estate investments, or capital gains in
stock portfolios. And that last one is where about half of America
is now growing its money.
</P>
<P>
   Like many statistics, the Commerce Department's personal savings
rate is a ghostly outline of society that does not always reflect
the complexities of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the longest-running economic boom in US history,
government statistics indicate Americans are saving less than ever.
While that's not quite true _ Americans are growing their assets
through the stock market and their home equity at record levels _
they are spending more. According to the Commerce Department, US
consumer spending rose 1 percent in February, more than double the
increase in personal income.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are spending more on big-ticket items, including
luxury autos, home electronics, and high-end homes, and using
easily available credit to make those purchases. But many have
learned a tough lesson from those easily obtained credit cards and
the resulting debt.
</P>
<P>
   Take Melanie and Duane Sylvia. They're in their 30s, have three
children, ages 2, 4, and 6, and have successfully climbed out of
the almost $10,000 in credit card debt they had held since the
mid-1980s. They still have nothing saved except for what Duane puts
into a 401(k) account through his job driving a food-delivery
truck. But through scrimping they were able to purchase a house.
</P>
<P>
   They are relentless savers on what might be called ``the drip
scale'' _ those small decisions that add up to a big difference in
the family budget but are never tracked by government radar. They
own one car. They don't buy brand-name clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to go out for pizza every Friday night,'' says
Melanie. ``Now it's once every couple of months. We don't need that
expense. When I go to the store, I think, `Do I really need this?'
Instead of buying the extra sweater or sweatshirt, I leave the
store and sleep on it. I don't usually go back the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sylvias got their fiscal act together through the Consumer
Credit Counseling Service of Southern New England, a nonprofit
organization that assists about 26,000 people a year. The service
analyzes expenses _ ``down to toothpaste, toilet paper, and
stamps,'' says Melanie _ and then sets up a plan to pay back
creditors on a monthly basis. The Sylvias owed nearly $10,000 on a
half-dozen credit cards but paid them off in four years. Now, they
have just one card that is used ``only in the crunch'' of holiday
shopping or emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are chronic undersavers,'' says Debbie Eaton, a vice
president at the counseling service. She says her organization sees
people primarily in the age 35 to 50 range ``who have no
contingency plan if something goes wrong,'' such as job loss or
medical emergency. The current strong economy, she says, feeds the
sense of overconfidence that savings aren't needed.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Kidd, who runs budgeting and credit workshops for Quincy
(Mass.) Community Action Programs, has seen attendance dropping
over the past year. Last week's session, in Randolph, was canceled
for a second time due to lack of interest. Kidd has seen all income
levels in her workshops, run for the past five years, and notes
that high-salaried individuals often have the toughest time saving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see people who earn $120,000 a year who don't save a dime,''
she says, ``and people making $30,000 who manage to put money
away.'' She adds that the most determined people she sees are
single mothers in the Braintree (Mass.) Self-Sufficiency Program
who are struggling to get out of government-subsidized housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so anxious to move forward,'' says Kidd. ``They want
to save, and they do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The psychology of why some people save and some don't can be as
convoluted as the human mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't oversimplify this,'' cautions Richard Wagner, past
president of the Financial Planning Association and principal of
the firm WorthLiving LLC in Denver. ``Saving is a psychologically
and spiritually complex act. It depends on your family upbringing
and maybe your dad telling you that anyone who had more than
$10,000 in the bank was a snooty jerk. A person has to get past
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He recommends that people try to save 15 percent of their gross
income, putting it wherever they're comfortable saving. He finds
that his clients are ``generally pretty good about saving,'' and he
considers the government's personal savings rate ``an elusive
number, and an almost useless number.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shapiro, under secretary for economic affairs at the US
Department of Commerce, admits the number is fuzzy, adding that the
government is going to come out with a new savings-rate formula
this year that will include capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to put the number in context,'' he says. ``The
level of personal savings matters in respect to how well people are
prepared for their own futures.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with the caveats, he says the low rate is still
troublesome, because a lot of people are living without a financial
cushion. He notes that the wealth people are accumulating in the
stock market can be misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting richer,'' he says, ``but not necessarily
because they're saving. The value of their stock is going up. So
instead of saying, `I need to save $50,000 to send a kid to
college,' they invest $25,000 and watch it grow. Pretty soon it's
$40,000 and they figure they don't have to save as much.''
</P>
<P>
   America is often compared unfavorably to Japan and European
countries, where personal saving rates are traditionally higher.
But observers point out that stock market returns are lower
overseas, and that the adage ``save till it hurts'' is not good
national policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese are saving way too much,'' says Robert Fichter,
senior vice president of the Massachusetts Bankers Association.
``It's almost a compulsion in that society. But Japan's economy
needs more spending. The country is in a very serious recession.''
</P>
<P>
   Fichter says the new economy is redefining the piggy bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not living in the Christmas Club age anymore,'' he says.
``The passbook savings account is not relevant to the world we live
in. Participation in the market may be overzealous, but investors
are sophisticated. Even if we do suffer a downturn, we're not going
back to 1950.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
