<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COLORFUL, LASTING LEGACY OF LIP SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lipstick. The word evokes images and associations. Lipstick
names and colors. Sneaking your mother's lipstick. Your first
lipstick. The lipsticks you tried and traded in high school. The
lipsticks you wore to the prom, at your best friend's wedding, when
you met the love of your life, when you finally pulled yourself
together after he dumped you.
</P>
<P>
   Even nuns wear lipstick, some nuns at least. A discreet dab of
lip color has been allowed since Vatican II, according to Jessica
Pallingston's ``Lipstick: A Celebration of the World's Favorite
Cosmetic'' (St. Martin's Press).
</P>
<P>
   ``A whole book about lipstick?'' my husband asked when he found
me reading Pallingston's book.
</P>
<P>
   I pointed out that he was reading ``The Horse's Health From A to
Z.'' Then I read him a paragraph about Elizabeth Arden, cosmetics
tycoon and Thoroughbred racing enthusiast. In 1966 her obituary in
The New York Times read, ``She treated women like horses and horses
like women.''
</P>
<P>
   That's stated a little ambiguously. I assume the Times meant she
treated both like Thoroughbreds. As far as anyone knows, she didn't
use lipstick on her horses, but she did have her grooms buff them
with other products, notably her famous Eight-Hour Cream, a kind of
glorified Vaseline which, I can attest from long personal
experience, is great over or under lipstick, or on a bare muzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lipstick'' is an entertaining blend of scholarship, pop
culture, and humor. Pallingston delves into the history of
lipstick, as far back as what she calls the First Golden Age of
Lipstick, in ancient Egypt, when blue-black was the favored shade
for women and men. She researched how modern lipsticks are made and
marketed and interviewed experts about how to choose and apply
lipstick. She offers advice on surviving the intimidation of makeup
reps. (I like her observation that walking down cosmetics aisles,
with people spraying you with scent and screaming, ``Can I give you
a makeover?,'' can make you feel ``like a leper wandering the
streets of a medieval village.'')
</P>
<P>
   Pallingston is described as ``a certifiable lipstick addict''
who owns more than 100 tubes, all listed by name, starting with
Taxi Cab, Mermaid, and Fiend, ending with Deadly Nightshade,
Poodle, Whoopee!, and Surrender Dorothy. Why would anyone name a
lipstick Deadly Nightshade? To say nothing of Dominatrix, Bloody
Maria, Roach, Bruise, Plague, or Hot Cross Buns. Pallingston writes
that in many ancient cultures, when you were named, you became your
name. So it is with lipstick. You are what you wear. (It may be
time for a change. I always feel so wimpy asking for another tube
of French Fawn.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, the firm Volupte introduced two new lipsticks, Lady and
Hussy. Pallingston quotes Kathy Peiss, author of ``Hope in a Jar,''
a history of the cosmetics industry: ``Women could choose the look
of gentlewoman or prostitute _ and apparently Hussy outsold Lady
five to one.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipstick is more than color in a tube. It's potent stuff _
sexual, totemic, magic. ``I say lipstick is a primal need,''
Pallingston writes.
</P>
<P>
   She quotes Bill Mandell of Revlon, saying, ``If women didn't
make up, they'd drink.'' It's a condescending observation, but
there may be some truth in it. Lipstick can be addictive.
Pallingston even explores a suggestion that lipstick is a drug
because many women report feeling a powerful rush when they apply
it. After reading ``Lipstick,'' I can understand why they might.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
