<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2269 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-10 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT'S CHINA CARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDOVER, Mass. _ So what's it going to be?
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that a hotbed of the new economy, with a future
intimately linked to exports, will be a symbol of ostrich
protectionism in direct contradiction of New England's economic
interests?
</P>
<P>
   Or, down the stretch toward a defining political moment, are the
region's congressional ``leaders'' going to join the rest of the
region and acknowledge the realities as well as the possibilities
of a new century?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in the auditorium of Agilent Technologies, the
second-largest employer, after Raytheon, in the district of US Rep.
Marty Meehan of Massachusetts. Meehan is the Clinton
administration's biggest gun and brightest star on the trade and
economic issues that are the essence of post-Cold War foreign
policy kicked off the campaign to win congressional approval of
normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright played the advocacy violin
like a virtuoso.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, that meant praising Meehan to the skies to several
hundred of his constituents, calling him ``one of my favorites,''
celebrating his independence, his work ethic, and his deserved
reputation for bipartisan accomplishment in an often gridlocked
Congress. The fact that he is undecided on the China issue at this
early stage of the countdown to a late May vote was given a
respectfully wide berth.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright also made a slam dunk case for making normal
relations with China permanent, no longer subject to annual fights.
In return, China has agreed to a host of concessions in conjunction
with US support for its membership in the 135-nation World Trade
Organization, all involving the opening of its potentially vast
market to US goods and services and the slashing of tariff levels
and other trade barriers. She made it clear that a no vote on trade
relations means forgoing enormous business opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Albright picked a perfect place to begin making the
administration's case. Agilent is all cutting-edge technology with
great export growth potential. Already, she noted, it is doing
significant business in China with communications-related products.
</P>
<P>
   But she was also shown some of what is going on in health care _
patient-monitoring equiment, the devices that shock stopped hearts
back into rhythm, all getting smaller and thus portable through the
miracles of electronics. And it just so happens that China agreed
in the deal negotiated last year to slash its tariffs on these
kinds of products by more than half. It is also the case that China
has agreed to open up its its society to the normal distribution
process, enabling exporters to sell, advertise, and service their
products as they do everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   What that means, Albright said, is ``no more forced technology
transfers,'' where firms have to accede to Chinese demands that
they manufacture via joint ventures inside China. Instead of what
amounts to the export of jobs, what is now in prospect is the
export of far more actual products, which is as direct a route to
job creation in this country as there is.
</P>
<P>
   Even under the current system, she noted, exports from
Massachusetts companies to China more than doubled during the
1990s. China's opponents in the United States like to point out
that for all the recent growth, the current trade is no more
important than commerce with Belgium, but this fight is not about
the present; it's about the future.
</P>
<P>
   The economic case is irrefutable. What makes Albright's advocacy
especially helpful in areas with significant numbers of House votes
up for grabs like New England is her unmatched ability to put
economics in the larger context of world affairs and the US
national interest, especially in the absence of a competing
conceptual vision from the labor, environmental, right wing, and
humans rights interests seeeking to ``contain'' or, worse, to
confront China.
</P>
<P>
   She gets attention when she notes that all of America's friends
in China's neighborhood, from Japan and South Korea to Taiwan,
ardently favor its entry into the WTO to foster both trade and
continued change in the country. She gets attention when she notes
that the human rights activists with everything on the line, from
Hong Kong to Beijing itself, feel similarly.
</P>
<P>
   But she gets special attention when she argues forcefully that
the upcoming trade relations decision in Congress offers a choice
between two futures. One offers exciting hope: an accelerated pace
of modernizing change inside China with less central control and a
more global outlook. The other is gloomy, politically and
economically: a virtual Cold War, all the more gloomy because it is
so avoidable.
</P>
<P>
   In a full day of appearances from here to Boston, Albright
underlined how hard she is willing to work to create new
mechanisms, with teeth, for restraining China's worst habits in
economic as well as human rights practices.
</P>
<P>
   But her appearances also underline what a force she is in this
fight. It is not simply because she is secretary of state but also
because she is the first woman to hold the post.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, she offers a protective embrace for those willing
to step forward on this issue. No novice at this, she made it clear
she is happy to play this role in the weeks leading to the critical
votes in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But that should not let New England's congressmen all the way
off the hook. It's time for leaders to show themselves.
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
