<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TALK' IS CHEAP: KYRA SEDGWICK LOWERS HER SIGHTS WITH NEW SITCOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kyra Sedgwick scampers through ``Talk to Me'' as though she's
been heavily coached on How To Succeed in Slapstick Sitcoms By
Really, Really Trying. The main lesson learned: Do everything very
quickly. She talks loud and fast and often, and in the spirit of
recent female sitcom leads, she's needy and clingy and unsure of
herself _ even though by episode's end, we're supposed to believe
she is actually strong and secure and independent.
</P>
<P>
   Likable and certainly believable in film roles, where she
typically stands her ground, Sedgwick has traded all that in for
Janey Munro, a radio talk-show host who is popular because she's
``funny, irreverent and sometimes controversial,'' although humor,
irreverence and controversy are nowhere to be found in the two
episodes of ``Talk to Me'' sent for review, the first of which airs
Tuesday on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   What supposedly makes Janey's show such a hot ticket is the way
she shoots from the lip about her life and loves and opinions, most
of which stand in direct contrast to her radio-booth sidekicks, all
of whom are testosterone-laced lugs.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot episode finds Janey feeling lousy about feeling lousy
over yet another breakup (the scum fell for another woman) and
vowing to ``act like a man'' _ which means to get over it by not
discussing it or thinking about it and, of course, by sleeping
around.
</P>
<P>
   And so Janey then spends the half-hour playing the gender-war
games while at the same time making the point (rather meekly) that
women hurt and can't move on after relationships because they have,
well, feelings. (Actually, I've always thought that women were
better at breakups because with them, when it's done, it's
``done,'' whereas men often wake up sometime later wondering what
the heck hit them.)
</P>
<P>
   In the second episode, when Janey flirts with a woman
(model-turned-actress Paulina Porizkova) to prove to one of her
co-workers that sex between two women is stimulating to ``all''
men, it turns out that the woman Janey is hitting on is gay, and
since she can't possibly hurt the woman's feelings by telling her
that she doesn't play in that particular league, they ``date.''
Which, after they have a great time hanging out, leads to yet
another ``Talk to Me'' revelation: If only women were equipped
with, well, you know, life would be good.
</P>
<P>
   Janey is joined in the booth by Rob (David Newsom), her co-host
and longtime friend; Marshall (Max Baker), who specializes in sound
effects and one-liners; and Cam (Michael J. Estine), the show's
producer.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Jacobson is Sandy, the often-dissed program director.
(He's saddled with a double whammy: He gets no respect because he's
the station owner's son and because he's such a dweeb.) Janey's
radio gang also dumps on self-help host Dr. Debra (Beverly
D'Angelo), yet another dig at radio host Dr. Laura Schlessinger.
Rude and rigid, Dr. Debra's favorite line before hanging up on
listeners is ``Get over your darn self.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, Janey lives with her sister, Kat (the hilarious Nicole
Sullivan from ``Mad TV''), who appears to be some kind of
professional volunteer, if that makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the supporting characters, this is definitely
Janey's show. And Sedgwick, whose recent film credits include
``Something to Talk About'' and ``Phenomenon,'' is up to the
challenge. She gives a performance that, considering the lack of
good material here, is a model of team playing. If the supporting
characters were original and the lines funnier and more
sophisticated, she'd be courting comparisons to Marlo Thomas'
``That Girl'' instead of Brooke Shields' ``Suddenly Susan.''
</P>
<P>
   But sadly, the show prefers gimmicks to quality storytelling.
Gene Simmons, for example, appears in the premiere episode as
himself, a guest-star device ``Talk to Me'' will no doubt continue
to take advantage of. Produced by Suzanne Martin, who spent nearly
three seasons on the staff of ``Frasier,'' ``Talk to Me'' _ which
takes over the ``Sports Night'' time slot for the remainder of the
season _ needs to get funny fast.
</P>
<P>
   If not, Sedgwick will find what other film stars have found when
slumming on the tube: TV can be a ruthless place.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
