<HEADLINE>
$ADV16 
 EVERYDAY ETHICS 
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16, AND THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by EVERYDAY ETHICS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By RANDY COHEN 
 c.2000 Randy Cohen 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 10% Dissolution
</P>
<P>
   Q. My agent hit on me in an aggressive, annoying way. I should
have fired him but a project was pending, and to my regret, I
decided not to. The project was awarded to me and I had only to
sign the contract when he hit on me again. This time, I fired him.
The next day I was off the project. Should I tell his wife what a
scum he is? Is revenge so bad?
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous, New York
</P>
<P>
   A. You should not call your former agent's wife. You'd be
directing your anger at an innocent person, and besides, such a
call would probably be ineffectual. If she is unaware of her
husband's character, a single phone call from a stranger is not apt
to enlighten her. In any case, you should not pursue cheap (albeit
enormously tempting) revenge of any sort; you should seek justice.
</P>
<P>
   While your ex-agent's behavior does not meet the definition of
sexual harassment for Title VII _ he was not your employer _ he may
have violated your professional relationship in ways that a lawsuit
can remedy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be worth it for a person in her situation to have a
consultation with a lawyer,'' says Anne Vladeck of Vladeck,
Waldman, Elias &AMP; Engelhard, a firm that specializes in employment
law.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he may well have violated the civil rights laws of
your city or state; contact the appropriate agencies. And you can
certainly talk to your former agent's boss, who, if he knows you
will not merely let the matter drop, may be anxious to resolve it
promptly. The one thing you should not do is passively accept this
treatment. While you may understandably want to put this
unpleasantness behind you and simply find a new agent, it would be
exemplary if you could give a thought to the next client who'll
walk through this guy's door. Take action now, and you may spare
someone else the same mistreatment you received.
</P>
<P>
   Q. While on the Long Island Railroad, I spilled a cup of coffee
on the floor and had little to mop it up with. I warned my close
neighbors to get their bags off the floor, but I could hear
passengers muttering and cursing. Should I have asked those
affected for their names and dry cleaning bills, or should I have
just skulked off the train?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.N., Wantagh, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. You are responsible for cleaning up your own mess. If you
spilled coffee on a co-worker's sweater at the office, you'd
certainly offer to get it cleaned. Your obligation doesn't change
because you've besmirched many people or because they are
strangers, even on the railroad. When you spilled your coffee, you
should have stood up and, despite the risk of embarrassment, warned
everyone to get their bags off the floor. Then you should have
found the conductor and asked for a mop. Were you too late with the
mop, you should have asked for dry cleaning bills. To avoid just
such mishaps, many transit systems, including the New York subways,
thoughtfully discourage passengers from drinking or eating on the
train _ especially elaborate dishes with rich sauces accompanied by
many bottles of wine. They stain.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The head of my academic department is stepping down and we
are all being asked to sign a card saying job well done. But I
think the job has been done very poorly. How do I choose between
the honesty in not signing and the camaraderie in participating?
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous, Arizona
</P>
<P>
   A. Dr. Johnson, that most punctilious of men, ruled on this more
than 200 years ago: ''In lapidary inscriptions a man is not upon
oath.'' So err on the side of generosity: sign the card, and
delight in the fellow's departure.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have ethical questions that you need answered? Send them
to ethicist &LR; nytimes.com, or Everyday Ethics, New York Times
Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th floor, New York, N.Y. 10168.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
