<HEADLINE>
DIVORCE TRIGGERED N.H. JUDICIAL SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ The whole thing started with a bitter
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures of alleged judicial misconduct that have rocked
New Hampshire began with the acrimonious divorce of former Supreme
Court justice Stephen Thayer and his wife, Judith Thayer.
</P>
<P>
   The divorce was a small snow-slide at the top of a mountain. But
the revelations that divorce proceedings brought to light have
turned into a roaring avalanche threatening to topple the top level
of the state's judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Albert ``Buzz'' Scherr, an associate dean and professor of law
at Franklin Pierce Law Center, likened the situation to the White
House scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about the Clinton impeachment thing,'' Scherr said.
``Nationally, that's the equivalent. It all came about because of
this stupid little Whitewater thing that turned out to be not much
of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Scherr said Stephen Thayer is ``not a bad person. He got in a
set of circumstances in a time of his life when he made some bad
decisions. And look what's resulted from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Thayer resigned from the Supreme Court March 31 rather
than face a grand jury investigation into allegations he tried to
influence cases in which he had an interest, including his own
divorce. The state Legislature will consider this week whether to
open impeachment proceedings against Chief Justice David Brock. And
some are calling for a clean sweep of the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Already, as a result of the fallout from this case, the Supreme
Court has instituted rules of recusal, and justices' outside
incomes have been capped. A proposal is at hand to investigate the
divorces of other New Hampshire judges.
</P>
<P>
   But the divorce that started the avalanche was the one that
ended the pairing of Stephen and Judith Thayer, who had seemed to
be ideological soulmates.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Thayer, who was regarded as the most conservative jurist
on the state's high court, had a relatively rapid rise to the top
of the New Hampshire legal community. After spending three years in
Vietnam and earning a Bronze Star, he got his law degree from John
Marshall in Chicago in 1974. Not long after his arrival in New
Hampshire, he became an early backer of Ronald Reagan's effort to
win the 1976 presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Reagan appointed Thayer US attorney for New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Thayer was active in the same conservative Republican
circles.
</P>
<P>
   They married two days after Christmas in 1982 and had one son,
W. Stephen Thayer IV. With Judith Thayer's two daughters from a
previous marriage, they lived in Manchester's North End, home to
many of the state's legal and political movers and shakers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the same year that Governor John H. Sununu appointed
Thayer to the state Supreme Court, he appointed Judith Thayer to
her first term on the State Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   She was appointed its chairwoman by former governor and now US
Senator Judd Gregg. Through her unpaid but highly visible post, she
championed such measures as a proposal to drop minimum state
standards for public schools and institute ``character education.''
Some recall her style in that post as abrasive and confrontational.
</P>
<P>
   Their son attended private boarding school, and Stephen Thayer
earned more than $100,000 a year as a Supreme Court justice and, in
one year, another $91,000 from teaching.
</P>
<P>
   But financial troubles began for the family in 1985, according
to their final divorce decree. By the time Judith Thayer filed for
divorce in 1998, the couple had incurred significant credit card
debt. A judge ordered their house sold. In court, Stephen Thayer
acknowledged that the pair ran some $17,000 in the red every year.
</P>
<P>
   But Judith Thayer maintained she was kept in the dark about the
family's finances.
</P>
<P>
   The court found both Thayers ``responsible for living beyond
their means.''
</P>
<P>
   A partial transcript of the divorce proceedings in Hillsborough
County Superior Court reads:
</P>
<P>
   Judith Thayer: ``I really don't understand where the money
went.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Thayer: ``She told me it's a man's job to provide. She
wanted to play tennis, and do her prayer group.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Thayer: ``I asked for 15 years why our finances are
managed this way . . . and I was told that if I didn't like it, I
could leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Thayer: ``We had difficulty talking about finances . . .
It was yelling and screaming, and nothing was resolved . . . (It)
was really a source of chaos in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   It was during divorce proceedings that Stephen Thayer's failure
to report a $50,000 loan he had received from Manchester lawyer
Emile Bussiere came to light. The state's Judicial Conduct
Committee and the FBI both investigated; Thayer was cleared by the
FBI.
</P>
<P>
   But when the divorce was appealed to the New Hampshire Supreme
Court _ the state doesn't have a separate appeals court _ the
avalanche picked up speed.
</P>
<P>
   Thayer's fellow jurists recused themselves from hearing his
divorce case. But when Thayer allegedly tried to wield influence
over which justices would hear his divorce _ and when Chief Justice
David Brock allegedly listened _ the court clerk reported the
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Philip McLaughlin launched an investigation
that led to Thayer's resignation, to Brock's possible impeachment,
and to the revelation of a long-standing practice of judges
commenting on cases from which they had been recused.
</P>
<P>
   David Nixon, who first represented Judith Thayer, said the
divorce ``was acrimonious from the start.'' He said he ``cautioned
everybody. . . from the beginning. . . everybody involved'' of the
potential implications of the divorce being played out on a public
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``As part of any lawyer's obligations, I think you try to steer
your clients in the direction that is in their best interest. . .
some of this information that we were obtaining through depositions
and discovery shed light on some of these loans that Mrs. Thayer
wasn't aware of,'' Nixon said. ``I thought that sooner or later
that would reflect badly on both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, his cautions didn't seem to have much effect.
</P>
<P>
   He said the couple attempted mediation, ``but it got nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Kamasinski, a non-lawyer currently representing Judith
Thayer, said she would have been willing to settle if a reasonable
offer had been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, (Judge) Thayer didn't do what most men in his
situation do _ offer a generous settlement and shut up,'' said
Marcus Hurn, a law professor at Franklin Pierce Law School.
</P>
<P>
   The divorce, as it would play out under a white-hot spotlight,
turned operatic.
</P>
<P>
   Under a court order, the Thayers' 17-room house was sold.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during court proceedings in October, the Thayers'
15-year-old son stood and confronted his father in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks a lot, Dad,'' the boy yelled sarcastically. ``Thanks a
lot for everything you've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Thayer refused to leave the family home, claiming the
judge had no authority to order the sale before the final divorce
hearing. She was inside with her daughters and other family members
when sheriff's deputies broke open the front door. Thayer and her
daughters were put out into the October rain.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time a high-profile divorce among the
state's legal elite has taken center stage.
</P>
<P>
   The case calls to mind an earlier acrimonious divorce involving
fomer state Supreme Court justice Charles G. ``Chuck'' Douglas III
and his fourth wife, Caroline. That case was fodder for national
magazines and inspired a TV drama loosely based on it.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mrs. Douglas and Mrs. Thayer have said they found it nearly
impossible to find representation in their divorce proceedings,
citing the state's ``old-boy'' legal network and lawyers' fear of
retaliation from the bench. Many in the state's legal community
deny those allegations; but both women have ended up being advised
and represented by Kamasinski, who describes himself as a ``legal
reformer.''
</P>
<P>
   Thayer, through Kamasinski, has asked the court to put her
divorce appeal on hold. Caroline Douglas has asked for a new trial.
On Friday, Stephen Thayer asked that his child support and alimony
payments be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, Judith Thayer's first lawyer, said he was ``saddened to
the point of being sickened by the whole thing. There's no pleasure
to me in seeing what I feared and predicted come true.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
