u a BC-ABANDONED-BABIES-BOS &LR;      04-10 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABANDONED-BABIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS PUSH FOR BABY ABANDONMENT AT `SAFE' SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jennifer Layton, a soft-spoken, stay-at-home mother, says that
politicians just don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   She looks at one of the hottest legislative trends in the United
States today _ combatting baby abandonment with the establishment
of ``safe havens'' at which distraught young women can anonymously
drop their newborns _ and her blood boils.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds absolutely wonderful,'' said Layton, who was adopted
after being left in a trash can in a Boston hotel 29 years ago when
she was a few days old. ``But it's absolutely outrageous. It
devalues life, it condemns the child to a lifetime of not knowing
about herself, and it won't work.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many infants are abandoned in this country each
year, and no professional concensus has developed on how to deal
with them. But a rapidly growing number of politicians nationwide
think they've found a solution: establishing facilities where
teenagers, who constitute the vast majority of the parents
involved, can leave their babies with no questions asked and no
risk of being prosecuted, as people usually are if they are
suspected of deserting a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these girls are given another option, I believe they won't
panic and just dump the baby,'' said Representative Ann Dandrow, a
GOP legislator who has sponsored ``safe haven'' legislation in
Connecticut. ``We'd be preventing a crime, maybe saving a baby's
life, and definitely freeing up more children for adoption.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in response to a spate of widely publicized
abandonments, Texas became the first state to legalize anonymous
baby drop-offs at specified locations such as police stations,
firehouses, and emergency rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The idea has spread like wildfire since then.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia's governor signed such a bill last month, Colorado
and Minnesota are in the final stages of enactment, and similar
measures are pending in more than 20 other states.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is the only New England state considering such a
law.
</P>
<P>
   While advocates of this approach maintain it could save some
babies' lives and help resolve a traumatic dilemma for distressed
young women, it has numerous detractors outside the political
arena. Many mental-health and child-care professionals regard it as
a reflexive response that is well-intentioned, but could cause more
problems than it solves.
</P>
<P>
   They say that nearly all the affected teenagers feel so confused
and upset, or are in such deep denial, that they're highly unlikely
to drive or seek a ride to any prescribed site, much less one
occupied by authority figures such as police. None of the nine
babies abandoned in Texas since its law went into effect was
dropped at a designated site, but six of them were left in the
hospitals at which they were delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, citing extensive research showing that adoptees
develop healthier mentally if they can learn about their personal
histories, grass-roots organizations such as the American Adoption
Congress and an adoptee-rights group called Bastard Nation are
aggressively opposing legalized baby desertion because it nearly
guarantees the children will never have access to information about
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we talk about desertion, we're not talking about girls
who are thinking rationally . . . and that's what these laws expect
them to do,'' said Susan Dark, director of the Adoption Connection
in Peabody, Mass. For 25 years, the organization has helped
thousands of adoptees, including some who had been abandoned,
search for their biological families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, we shouldn't be thinking only of the moment,'' Dark
added. ``These girls can change their minds. . . . and their babies
are living, breathing people who will grow up, and who have a right
to ask questions and get the answers, who have a right to an
identity, who have a right to a medical history.''
</P>
<P>
   The critics say that politicians, in their zeal to deal with an
emotional and high-profile issue, are emulating an approach the
United States criticizes in other countries. Government-sanctioned
abandonment occurs most frequently in China, where little girls are
dropped at orphanages because families are legally permitted to
have only one child.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest long-term risk in this country, according to
detractors, is that it will convince young mothers facing
less-than-dire circumstances that it's a socially acceptable way of
resolving a tough problem. And that, they fear, could lead to more
teen pregnancies and abandonments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not designed to be a prevention program, but to save
the life of a child who's already here,'' countered Justin Unruh,
director of the Baby Moses Project in Texas, which is developing a
program to inform teenagers about that state's new law. ``And we
would rather have a child without any background or medical history
who is safe than one who is without any background or medical
history who is found in a dumpster.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither individual states nor the federal government track how
many infants are discarded each year. The closest thing to an
official estimate is in an unpublished survey conducted by the US
Department of Health and Human Services, which based its data on
print and television news stories.
</P>
<P>
   The department counted 65 babies abandoned in public places in
1991, including eight found dead, or an average of 1.3 abandoned
per state; in 1998, the tally rose to 105, with 33 dead, or 2.1 per
state. Some analysts say that the abandonment probably hasn't
grown, but reporting has become more prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   Some professionals say they understand why the safe haven
initiative has proliferated and contend it probably is an
overreaction, one with consequences its sponsors haven't
considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``This idea may have some merit, but it does seem like a
knee-jerk reaction,'' said John Krall, chief analyst for the
National Abandoned Infants Research Center at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``It probably feels like a good idea to
people, and may even help a baby in some isolated cases, . . . but
I think it has a lot of pitfalls and certainly doesn't even try to
address the root causes of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Mental-health specialists suggest that, as long as social
stigmas relating to teenage and unwed pregnancy exist, the
strongest safeguard against baby abandonment is education. They
added that parents and teachers need to get more involved, both to
promote prenatal care and to help the mothers-to-be cope with the
emotional turmoil so they can rationally decide whether to keep
their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most promising response is public awareness, to
get more young people to know there's someone to talk to, to
counsel them, that there's someone to help them make decisions in
everyone's best interests,'' said Michael Kharfen, a spokesman for
the Health and Human Services' Administration for Children and
Family.
</P>
<P>
   Some professionals suggest that hospital- and clinic-based
programs are preferable to safe havens. The thinking is that if
young women were encouraged to enter hospitals _ perhaps with
guarantees of privacy, protection, and free care _ they and their
babies would be healthier; they would have access to their infants
if they changed their minds about parenting; and the children,
along with their adoptive parents, would later have access to
genealogical and medical information.
</P>
<P>
   The unpublished Health and Human Services study, a copy of which
was provided to the Globe, indicates the benefits of such an
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Most abandonments have historically taken place in hospitals,
which keep track of their numbers. There were 22,000 nationwide in
1991 and 31,000 in 1998, the ovewhelming majority involving mothers
with drug-dependency problems. None of the children died, and
nearly all are believed to have been returned to their mothers
after the parents were rehabilitated, to be in the custody of other
relatives, or to have been adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters of the legalized-abandonment approach said they
understood it might have some flaws, but insisted that something
had to be done, even if only as an initial response.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take things in steps, and I truly believe this is
the important first step,'' Dandrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how many babies are abandoned in Connecticut each year,
she said she didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there have been some, and if we save even one baby's
life, it's worth it,'' she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
