<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Black and White'' James Toback's film about rich white
kids trying to be black rappers and black rappers trying to become
show-biz power brokers has ambition, ideas, edge, and good
performances by two athletes: boxer Mike Tyson and basketballer
Allan Houston. But it can't finish what it starts, and veers off
into spiralingly inane melodrama. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Return to Me'' Likable fluff, marking the directing debut
of actress Bonnie Hunt. The romantic comedy is driven by warm,
engaging performances from David Duchovny as a depressed widower
and Minnie Driver as a shy artist. Neither realizes that she's the
recipient of his late wife's transplanted heart. This one wants to
be another ``Moonstruck,'' but settles for a lot of Dean Martin on
the soundtrack. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``Rules of Engagement'' This military-combat thriller and
courtroom drama has its moments, most of them involving Samuel L.
Jackson. He's the Marine colonel rescuing an endangered ambassador
and his family from a besieged US embassy in Yemen. But after his
unit returns fire, killing women and children, he's hung out to dry
in a politically motivated trial. Neither Jackson nor Tommy Lee
Jones, as the colonel's old buddy and defense lawyer, can defend
himself from their ill-defined characters in a sketchy script. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Southpaw'' Involving, home-grown documentary about scrappy
Irish welterweight boxer Francis Barrett, who was cheered by his
countrymen for representing Ireland in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics
before he was accepted as a Traveller living in a trailer outside
Galway. The hardships he faces in trying to establish himself as a
boxer make it clear that his toughest fights are outside the ring.
(Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``X'' This Japanese animation drawn by the four-woman
collective known as Clamp is perfunctory about its characters and
its good-versus-evil showdown. Making most of its points on the
illustrative rather than the human level, it's driven by dark,
grandiose, nightmare images of Tokyo reduced to rubble. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
