<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2281 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-WARGNIER-BOS &LR;      04-10 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WARGNIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGIS WARGNIER'S JOURNEY TO FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a child, film director Regis Wargnier was intrigued with
secrets _ more than anything, with the things adults tried to keep
hidden from him. Growing up in France in the 1950s and '60s,
foremost in the young boy's mind was the massive, impenetrable veil
that separated his world from mysterious millions who lived on the
other side. ``The USSR was a locked world then,'' recalls Wargnier,
``and I really thought there was this huge curtain made of iron. I
wanted to know who are these people? Why are they so dangerous? Why
do they live behind the Iron Curtain?' Somehow, I kept that with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, Wargnier has transposed his lifelong
fascination to film. ``East-West,'' starring Sandrine Bonnaire,
Oleg Menchikov, and Catherine Deneuve, was nominated for an Academy
Award for best foreign language film this year; it lost to Pedro
Almodovar's ``All About My Mother.'' The film, which opens in
Boston on Friday, tells the story of Alexei Golovine, a young
Russian doctor living in France, who returns to his mother country
with his French wife and young son at the behest of Stalin, who in
1946 launched a propaganda campaign to lure emigrants back with the
promise of amnesty, a Soviet passport, and the chance to
participate in postwar reconstruction. Upon their arrival in
Odessa, the family quickly discovers that Stalin's promises were
empty. Alexei is posted to the infirmary in a textile factory in
Kiev, and the family is allocated a single room in a communal
apartment in Kiev. So begins a long, painful quest for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   It's that journey toward freedom _ be it political, social, or
psychological _ that drives Wargnier's films. ``Yes, I think I am
freedom, or liberty, obsessed,'' says the director, chatting in a
conference room at the Lenox Hotel. Only one of his films has been
shown in the States: ``Indochine,'' which won the Oscar for best
foreign-language film. But all five resonate, Wargnier says, with
the same theme: ``You don't get caught by a story like
(``East-West'') if it doesn't mean something deep, very deep, to
you. It's independence. What is it to be free? If you want to be
free, do you have to pay for it?''
</P>
<P>
   The story began to take shape in Wargnier's mind in 1995, when
he was traveling in a former republic of the Soviet Union to
research an adventure film that was never made. While there, he was
surprised to meet some locals speaking French. ``They told me, `Oh,
we speak French because we were born in France, and lived there
until we were 9 or 10.' Their fathers were Russian and mothers were
French, and the father wanted to go back home. They were like the
little boy in the movie, plus 45 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Wargnier was intrigued, to say the least. He called a close
friend who lived for a time in the former Soviet Union many years
before. That friend relayed another story of a couple he met in the
town he lived in: a Russian man who had returned home with a French
wife. They fought for 40 years to get back to France. ``The opening
scene is, in a way, what happened to them,'' Wargnier says. ``It's
not a true story, but it's from several true stories we put
together.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The plot thickens
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wargnier co-wrote the screenplay with two Russian collaborators,
Rustam Ibragimbekov and Serguei Bodrov, and a fellow French scribe,
Louis Gardel. It was not easy, Wargnier confirms, to gather
firsthand reports from the people who lived through it. ``You know,
they keep distant. You can change lots of things, but you can't
change the mentality. You can't just take out the frame of mind. It
was like somebody said to them, `oh, we have news for you. God is
dead. We made a great mistake. This regime? The laws and rules?
Dead. Sorry. Just go on with your life.' But these people have been
taught that we are the enemy. You are, I am, we, the westerners. We
are really mistrusted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``East-West'' is not a true story, Wargnier says, but rather
several true stories blended into one. The unifying thread was a
common strength of spirit, a truly altruistic urge to survive. ``I
was sitting in a Moscow cafe with my co-writer, Serguei,'' Wargnier
recalls. ``His friend was there, who had been 10 years in a camp.
It was like the Olympic runner with the torch at the opening
ceremonies; he's content to pass the torch to someone else. He said
that almost every day they heard that somebody had escaped. Or they
knew that in the next room someone was preparing to escape. This
hope stuff, or freedom stuff, it works even if it's for someone
else. He said you didn't need to get it for yourself if you were
sure someone was getting it. Sometimes they were all trying to give
a hand to someone else, and that was keeping them alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Wargnier's first film, 1986's ``The Woman in My Life,'' was a
low-budget independent about a neurotic relationship _ the battle
for liberation waged on an internal landscape. Then came ``I Am the
King of the Castle,'' a gothic tale of two kids engaged in war with
each other. In ``Indochine,'' which also starred Catherine Deneuve,
a young Vietnamese rebels against her mother as her country rebels
against France. And in 1994's ``A French Woman,'' starring
Emmanuelle Beart, Wargnier told the story (based on his mother's
experience) of a military officer's wife trying desperately to find
her own life.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``East-West,'' Wargnier says, ``it's the most obvious.
It's about basics. In USSR, liberty number one was denied: to go
where you want to go, talk to who you want to talk, love who you
want to love.'' He hopes that US audiences will walk away from the
film with an increased awareness of just how tenuous those basic
freedoms are. ``Some people in France think `Oh, the Berlin wall
has fallen down 10 years so it belongs to the past,''' Wargnier
says. ``No. History is in the present. The more dangerous walls are
the invisible walls. Like in Austria, where the right wing is
growing. Every day, somewhere, people are being oppressed. There
won't ever be enough movies to deal with this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1402EDT &QL; 
