u e BC-TV-PRESIDENT-BOS &LR;      04-10 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PRESIDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAKING OF `THE AMERICAN PRESIDENT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The presidency is the apogee of political ambition, the symbol
of a nation, an exalted office that Al Gore and George W. Bush will
spend untold millions pursuing over the next seven months.
</P>
<P>
   It is also, to hear many of its occupants tell it, one of the
lousiest jobs on earth. Even John F. Kennedy, who usually reveled
in the role of president, got so fed up at the woes mounting around
him in the summer of 1961 that one night he growled jokingly to
reporter Hugh Sidey: ``I'm going to give this damn job to Nixon.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidey, Time magazine's longtime White House correspondent,
chuckled at the recollection, as if to say he knows exactly how
many grains of salt should be taken with such presidential laments.
``Every one of these guys, starting with Kennedy . . . they want to
be heroic presidents,'' said Sidey, who has retired from the beat.
``They all kind of want that greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two centuries, that ``damn job'' offering a chance
at greatness has been held by 41 men _ all of whom are profiled in
PBS's 10-hour series ``The American President,'' at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the first documentary series to offer a portrait of
every single president, it is narrated by Sidey and written,
produced, and directed by the father-and-sons team of Philip B.
Kunhardt Jr., Philip B. Kunhardt III, and Peter W. Kunhardt. Philip
B. Kunhardt III said the goal of the series is to show ``how much
their individual personalities have brought to bear on the
evolution of the office.''
</P>
<P>
   The series boasts interviews with all the living ex-presidents,
except for Ronald Reagan, who is afflicted with Alzheimer's
disease. The current White House occupant, Bill Clinton, discusses
his impeachment in an episode titled ``The Balance of Power,''
slated to air Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As for the presidents no longer living, the series opted not to
take the usual route of relying on actors to supply the voices.
Instead, ``The American President'' features a roster of military,
political, and media types that includes former governor William F.
Weld (in the voice of another one-time Bay State governor, Calvin
Coolidge), General Colin Powell, former senator Robert Dole, Walter
Cronkite, George Will, Tim Russert, the Rev. Billy Graham, and Don
Imus. (Imus accepted the role of Andrew Johnson, a white
supremacist and the first president to be impeached, after five
others had turned it down. Among those rejecting the role was Pat
Buchanan, who sent back a script with a note saying ``You can take
your trashy script back,'' according to Kunhardt).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A not-so-linear look
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To compress 41 presidencies into 10 hours, the Kunhardts devised
an approach that links presidents across decades and even centuries
according to themes their presidencies had in common. ``We all felt
a little bored by the idea of doing it chronologically,'' Kunhardt
explained. ``To start with Washington and walk in lock step through
history would put people to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   So, for instance, the first hour, titled ``Family Ties,'' looks
at four presidents _ Kennedy, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, John
Quincy Adams, and Benjamin Harrison _ who were the scions of
privileged families that transferred power from one generation to
the next. The second hour, ``Happenstance,'' examines vice
presidents upon whom the presidency was thrust because of
assassination or natural death: Harry Truman, Andrew Johnson,
Chester Alan Arthur, Millard Fillmore, and John Tyler. ``The Heroic
Posture,'' airing Wednesday night, looks at military heroes who
ascended to the presidency, from George Washington to Ulysses S.
Grant to Dwight D. Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to see if there were patterns, and there were,''
said Sidey. However, he added, ``It would be a serious mistake to
make too much of them.'
</P>
<P>
   The series also tries to cast an unexpected light on presidents
whose images have become calcified over time. For instance, Abraham
Lincoln is often depicted as a figure of near-saintly idealism,
driven by a zeal to stamp out slavery while preserving the union.
But the Kunhardts made the dry-eyed choice to include Lincoln in
the episode titled ``The Professional Politician,'' along with
presidents more commonly associated with backroom maneuvering, such
as Lyndon Baines Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a crafty man, a hugely ambitious man,'' Kunhardt said
of Lincoln. ``He was devoted to party politics, and he worked the
machinery all his life.''
</P>
<P>
   The segment on Kennedy does not conclude, as one might expect,
with his assassination in Dallas, but rather with his
overwhelmingly successful trip to Ireland, where he was hailed as
the first Irish-Catholic president. ``It's so well known, the story
of his shooting and death,'' said Kunhardt. Instead, the
assassination is treated in a later segment on LBJ.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hail to the chief, indeed
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat ironically, perhaps, ``The American President'' (not to
be confused with the Rob Reiner-directed, Aaron Sorkin-scripted
feature film) arrives at a moment when the presidency occupies a
smaller place in American life, at least in Sidey's view.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it is a relatively tranquil era, free of economic
catastrophe and major wars. ``Crisis tends to etch a president in
clear terms,'' said Sidey, who is president of the White House
Historical Association. Moreover, he said, ``This is a time in
which the private sector is driving not just the country, but the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another factor that has shrunken the stature of the
presidency, in Sidey's view, and that is television. He believes
that CNN and other networks have assumed outsize importance in the
conduct of foreign policy, with leaders such as Yassir Arafat and
Moammar Khadafy taking their cues from their TV sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television just overwhelmed us; the White House is just a
stage now,'' said Sidey. ``It's a power that on many days is
greater than the president's, what echoes through that world.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-year task of immersing themselves in the study of
America's presidents and trying to see them whole led Sidey and
Kunhardt to reappraise some of them. Sidey said that Grant went up
in his estimation (``As a person, anyway; his presidency was a
mess''), and so did Rutherford B. Hayes, who declined to seek an
extra term because he concluded the country didn't need him
anymore. Kunhardt said he now thinks of Jefferson's first term as
one of the greatest ever, and views James Garfield as ``one of the
greatest minds we ever elected.''
</P>
<P>
   A clear theme that emerges from the series is that while some
presidents have been happy warriors in office _ Theodore Roosevelt,
FDR, Reagan _ the presidency was to many others, in Sidey's words,
``a pain in the side.'' Jefferson, for instance, enjoyed his stint
so little that he did not include the fact that he was the nation's
third president on the list of accomplishments he wanted engraved
on his tombstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an onerous job for many of them, if not most,''
Kunhardt observed. ``Almost all of them say something about what a
miserable place (the White House) is, and how they can't wait to
get out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
