<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2283 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u a BC-NEW-AMERICA-HOTEL'S-R     04-10 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-HOTEL'S-RACIAL-DISCRIMINATION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOYCOTT BUSINESSES GUILTY OF RACIAL DISCRIMINATION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By DERRICK K. BAKER  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Denny's restaurant chain is on my list of offending
businesses found guilty of racial discrimination in 1993, followed
in 1996 by Texaco and in 1999 by the Cracker Barrel restaurant
chain that dots the sides of the nation's highways. Recently, the
Adam's Mark Hotel chain was added to the ignominious file of
companies that will never again benefit from my patronage because
of their mistreatment of people who happen to be black.
 &HT;    The hotel chain settled five lawsuits with the U.S. Department
of Justice that were filed in May 1999, after several black guests
were treated as security risks last year during the Black College
Reunion in Daytona Beach, Fla.
 &HT;    The African-Americans charged that they _ and other black people
_ were instructed to wear special orange wristbands. The white
guests were not. The black guests were charged a nightly minimum of
$250 for the hotel's least expensive rooms. White guests were not.
Black guests had to pay an additional $50 for anyone who visited
their room during the weekend. Visitors of white guests were not
charged a fee.
 &HT;    The corporate folks who run the 21-hotel chain didn't admit to
any wrongdoing, but agreed to pay $4.4 million to guests and
visitors of the resort. The five original plaintiffs will each
receive $25,000. The company also agreed to initiate
nondiscrimination policies and begin efforts to attract more
minority customers as part of the settlement.
 &HT;    Adam's Mark will implement several measures designed to validate
that it provides equal treatment for all guests. A national equal
employment opportunity organization known as Project Equality will
independently oversee the implementation of the terms of the
agreement, which will be in place for four years.
 &HT;    Under the settlement, Adam's Mark will enhance existing
corporate policies and practices to ensure that no guest will be
discriminated. The hotel will also create a diverse secret-shoppers
program to ensure equal treatment of guests.
 &HT;    Discrimination based on race happens everyday and in every way _
especially when you call yourself an African-American, or look like
one. Unlike the blatant actions taken by the Adam's Mark hotel
staff, blacks are often covertly victimized and minimized by racial
discrimination. However, it would be unfair to place every last
employee of an Adam's Mark or Denny's in an unfair light, when a
few perpetrating employees cast a bad light on the entire
corporation.
 &HT;    The elimination of racial discrimination will happen as soon as
every last person on Earth is dead. A brutally harsh analogy, but
true nonetheless. Combating racism _ a pernicious illness _ is the
bane of blacks' existence.
 &HT;    Consequently, it should be ridiculously easy to reject the idea
of patronizing a business of any size that conspicuously displays a
reckless disregard for African-Americans' financial support.
 &HT;    While a Texaco or a Cracker Barrel will never miss the few
dollars I won't spend with them as a result of my personal boycott,
the principle of the matter, and an overwhelming sense of
self-respect and racial pride, remains paramount for people with
similar views.
 &HT;    Any person of color who accepts the corporate equivalent of
having saliva spat into their face must rethink their priorities,
particularly when there are hundreds of other hotels and
restaurants to patronize.
 &HT;    Don't risk patronizing establishments that will disrespect you
to the degree that you risk incarceration because of your inability
to refrain from knocking some offending clerk back into his
mother's womb.
 &HT;    When employees at various local operations of multimillion
dollar companies mistreat customers of color, local management is
responsible for responding to the act, remedying it and
appropriately reprimanding the employee. When that sequence of
events doesn't happen, it's logical to assume that the culture of
the operation condones such behavior, which also makes local
management _ and ultimately the corporate honchos _ culpable for
the mistreatment.
 &HT;    In these lawsuit-happy times, it is logical to expect that when
tip-dependent waitresses, minimum-wage cashiers at family
restaurants, or the front desk staff at a luxury hotel overcharge
black customers and hold them to different and higher standards,
corporate management should anticipate a lawsuit, which probably
means shelling out money for its defense, and to settling a
class-action lawsuit.
 &HT;    The outcome of the Adam Mark's case once again proves that
biased actions based on racial discrimination and corporate
indifference is extremely costly, and not only for mistreated
customers who happen to have been born black.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Derrick K. Baker is a columnist for N'Digo, an African-American
weekly newspaper published in Chicago.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 N'Digo 
