<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-GENGHIS-REVISITED-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PATH OF KAHN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By ENKHSAIKHAN JARGALSAIKHANY  
 &HT;    Chinese civilization rests on the formidable shoulders of the
great Confucius. Macedonians revere Alexander the Great as a hero
and a cultural icon. For Mongolians, Genghis Khan occupies the same
rarefied stratum of history. He is seen as a leader and sage, whose
achievements revolutionized Mongolian society. Yet to most
residents of the West, the perception of Genghis Khan remains that
of a barbarian _ the quintessential cartoon savage.
 &HT;    Centuries of interaction have opened the doorway to
communication between East and West, leading to new understandings
of the cultures and histories of countries like China, Japan and
India. Unfortunately, this progress toward enlightenment is far
from universal.
 &HT;    Mongolian Americans feel it is time that misconceptions about
our culture are addressed _ and dismissed. No better time exists
than now, the cusp of the new millennium, with 2001 proclaimed by
the United Nations General Assembly as the ``Year of Dialogue Among
Civilizations.''
 &HT;    But the first step in understanding Mongolia, before even
arriving at a point where educated questions may be asked, is to
come to the realization that for Mongolians, Genghis Khan was more
than a warrior and conqueror. He was a teacher honored for his
wisdom, and the founder of the Mongolian nation.
 &HT;    Like Alexander the Great, Genghis Khan extended his empire by
conquest. Unlike Alexander's, Genghis Khan's empire did not
fragment after his death. In fact, due to the administrative skills
and judicious rule of Genghis Khan and his descendants, it became
the largest land-empire in recorded world history.
 &HT;    Still, few people in America would utter the phrase ``Genghis
the Great,'' except perhaps in jest. It's almost as if it is a
dangerous notion for Westerners to find a heroic ideal like that of
Alexander in an Asian man, Genghis Khan.
 &HT;    I'm not denying that there is a darker side to the Khan, as
there has been to world leaders from Mao to Napoleon to Roosevelt.
Without a doubt, the building of the Mongolian empire came through
bloodshed and destruction. Yet it is recognized by historians that,
at the golden peak of the empire, the Mongols reopened the Silk
Road, allowing for a flood of contact, exchange and diplomacy
between East and West.
 &HT;    The Mongol court provided special privileges for artists and
craftsmen, giving them tax exempt status. The patronage of the
Mongol courts in China, Iran and Central Asia led to an
unparalleled period of cultural synthesis and flowering of the
arts. The court also maintained strict laws of religious tolerance
for all. These and other positive aspects of Mongol rule are
inconvenient realities to those for whom a reevaluation of the
Mongols would require a reassessment of the role of Asia and nomads
in world history.
 &HT;    Genghis Khan was the founder of the Mongolian nation, and its
chief lawgiver and judge. His decrees, compiled into a system of
laws called the Yasa, became the basis for governance throughout
the Mongol empire, and extended beyond the empire to neighboring
lands, where they remained a part of common law until the 19th
century. The edicts of the Yasa promoted tolerance, group
consensus, women's rights and the safe- guarding of landscape and
wildlife _ the first codified environmental protection laws of
their kind.
 &HT;    It is often said that ``history is written by the victors'' _
not in this case. The history of Genghis Khan and the Mongols was
written by non-Mongolian chroniclers who were subjects of the
empire. It was through their subjective lens that perceptions of
the Mongols were disseminated in the Middle Ages, and their
viewpoint has persisted until today.
 &HT;    Since these historians were conquered peoples, it is not
surprising that the positive aspects of Mongolia's contributions
proved to be less prominent in their accounts than the terrible
stereotypes.
 &HT;    The tarnishing of our nation's image has experienced little
reprieve over the centuries. Genghis Khan's one big moment in the
Hollywood spotlight was an absurd and offensive portrayal by John
Wayne _ of all people. It did little to lift the great man's
memory.
 &HT;    But time heals most wounds, and a new sense of global
consciousness is emerging. Mongolians in America are hopeful that,
in the age to come, a more accurate and sensitive understanding of
our culture, our role in world history and our most prominent
historical figure, might someday be achieved.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Enkhsaikhan Jargalsaikhany is the Mongolian Ambassador to the
United Nations.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 A. Magazine 
