<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-RACISM-IN-JUDICIAL-SYSTEM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JUDICIAL SYSTEM RIFE WITH RACISM, FEDERAL JUDGE CHARGES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By VERNON JARRETT  
 &HT;    Just as racial profiling by this nation's law-enforcement
officers is finally being exposed, evidence of racial
discrimination throughout America's federal and state judicial
systems can no longer be ignored, according to a veteran New York
federal judge.
 &HT;    Federal Judge Robert L. Carter, senior judge of the Southern
District Court of New York, pulled no punches when he spoke before
the New York County Lawyers' Association at the fourth annual
Haywood Burns Memorial Lecture, which took place in May. He charged
that racial discrimination is so widespread in America's criminal
justice system that its correction is as crucial as providing equal
educational opportunity for inner-city children.
 &HT;    Carter said that throughout his career as a lawyer and judge he
had been concerned chiefly with racial inequality in education;
however, recent research has forced him to conclude that ``at every
level and in every phase of the various systems, racism is at
play.''
 &HT;    Strong language for a senior federal judge who has spent 28
years on the federal bench.
 &HT;    Carter finds it appalling that reports from the Department of
Justice show that of the 1.8 million people in local, state and
federal prisons, 900,000 _ or 50 percent _ are black. Blacks make
up between 12 percent and 13 percent of the nation's total
population.
 &HT;    He said it was sad for the whole nation when, in 1993, America
had from ``five to 10 times'' the number of people incarcerated
than other Western nations. The racial data makes the scenario
worse, he said. In 1993, America imprisoned blacks at a rate 20
times the rate that Europeans jailed their citizens. He noted that
in 1996 the Department of Justice reported that one in three black
males between the ages of 20 and 29 were involved with the justice
and prison systems.
 &HT;    If this trend continues, one in four black male babies born
today will spend at least a year in jail. Predictions for white
male babies is one in 23, he said.
 &HT;    Carter said that according to research he reviewed, the number
of black women and teen-agers who are incarcerated reflects the
judicial system's overall biased approach to criminal justice. From
1985 to 1995, the number of black women prisoners increased by 204
percent _ eight times the rate of white women, he said. Meanwhile,
black juveniles, who comprise 15 percent of the nation's youth
population, make up 32 percent of those arrested on drug charges,
and 63 percent of those cases have been moved up to adult criminal
courts.
 &HT;    Does this mean that black criminality outrageously surpasses
that of other races? No. The outrage lies in the court system's
mistreatment of blacks. According to the Department of Health and
Human Services, in 1998 blacks comprised only 15 percent of
America's drug users. However, they made up 37 percent of those
arrested and 53 percent of state court convictions.
 &HT;    If blacks made up only 15 percent of our drug users, Carter
asked, how was it that nationwide 66,000 were arrested as opposed
to 15,000 whites? And why, between 1990 and 1994, were 75 percent
of all juveniles arrested for drugs black while only 25 percent
were white?
 &HT;    Members of Congress were astounded when in 1995 the Sentencing
Commission exposed the fact that 52 percent of crack users were
white in contrast to 38 percent who were black. Yet, blacks
represented 90 percent of the total number of people convicted for
offenses involving crack.
 &HT;    Something is wrong somewhere. Carter noted that Congress itself
made it possible for a person caught carrying 5 grams of crack
cocaine to receive a mandatory minimum sentence of five years in
jail. But a person whose drug of choice is powdered cocaine must be
caught with 500 grams of the stuff to handed the same sentence.
Incidentally, powdered cocaine is presumed to be a favorite of
whites.
 &HT;    Carter then turned to Marc Mauer's study, ``Race to
Incarcerate,'' to show how in 1990 white men represented 78 percent
of the total arrests for drunk driving, which killed 22,000 each
year. He compared those 22,000 casualties with the 21,000 deaths
caused by AIDS from unclean needles, drug overdoses and slayings
associated with drug sales.
 &HT;    Carter then pointed to the drunk drivers who are given
misdemeanor sentences and are required to perform community service
or pay a fine.
 &HT;    Makes you think.
 &HT;    Carter also pointed to statistics from the NAACP-Legal Defense
Fund's 1999 report which showed that 43 percent of those on death
row are black. While only 50 percent of homicide victims are white,
84 percent of those sentenced to death are convicted of killing
whites.
 &HT;    Carter's final shocker: He fears that ``774,000 low-skilled
blacks'' will soon be leaving prison and flooding the labor market
_ unlikely candidates for either employment or absorption into
their communities. And they will be denied the right to vote
because they have become disenfranchised ex-cons.
 &HT;    Much food for thought.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Vernon Jarrett is an active member of the national advisory
board of the Rosa and Raymond Parks Pathways to Freedom Program for
Youths. In 1991 he received a Lifetime Achievement Award from the
National Association of Black Journalists.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Vernon Jarrett 
