<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-INDIANS-MAY-VOTE-GORE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INDIANS, GORE IN 2000  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By TIM GIAGO (NANWICA KCIJI)  
 &HT;    Long before the first primary election, I wrote an article about
the presidential candidates and their chances of advancing to the
November elections. My predictions came true.
 &HT;    Of course, I evaluated the candidates through my Native-American
eyes. At first I wrote that of all the candidates, Bill Bradley
would be the best president for Indians and John McCain a close
second. George W. Bush would be a tragedy.
 &HT;    As the incumbent vice president, Al Gore was a part of an
administration that made efforts to address many of the problems in
Indian country.
 &HT;    But, after taking a more pragmatic look at the candidates, I
concluded that the status quo would prevail and that George W. Bush
and Al Gore would move on to the November elections.
 &HT;    Several wealthy Indians from the Pequot Nation in Connecticut
jumped on the John McCain bandwagon a bit late. They contributed
$20,000 to his campaign a couple of days before Terrible Tuesday.
They probably wished they had put it on the roulette table at their
Foxwood Casino because McCain went down in flames on Super Tuesday.
 &HT;    Up in the state of Washington, the Indian nations are out to
nail Sen. Slade Gorton's hide to the wall. Gorton (R-Wash.) has
attempted to introduce legislation that flies in the face of Indian
law, Indian treaties and federal law. Like George W. Bush, he
believes that state governments should have total jurisdiction over
Indian tribes. Of course, Slade is very popular with the general
population (read: white) of Washington, and they do have the
numbers to keep him in office.
 &HT;    Only in recent years have Indians become interested and involved
in national politics. For too long they just assumed that they did
not have the clout to impact federal elections. But, with the
advent of casinos and bingo halls, the tribes suddenly found
themselves with a little extra cash that they could invest into
politics _ so much so that when the gaming compacts were written
for the Indian tribes of New Mexico, one stipulation was that the
tribes do not use any gaming revenues for political contributions.
 &HT;    Can you imagine any state government telling a business (and a
casino is a business) how they can or cannot spend their profits?
What unmitigated gall.
 &HT;    Why are the elected officials of New Mexico so afraid of the
Indian tribes and pueblos spending their money to influence
elections? Non-Indians have been doing it for years, and while they
forbid the Indian nations from doing it, they continue to do it
themselves. What hypocrisy!
 &HT;    The Indian vote doesn't mean much in states with small Indian
populations. For instance, the Indian vote in New York State won't
change a candidate's chances one way or the other. However, in
Arizona, New Mexico, South Dakota and other states with large
Indian populations, the Indian vote can be pivotal.
 &HT;    In the past, it was hard to convince Indian voters that the
person who is elected can greatly influence their lives. Laws are
made by Congress, and Congress can (and has) taken land, minerals
and natural resources from the Indian nations with a stroke of the
pen. Schools, hospitals and law enforcement have been helped or
hindered by acts of Congress.
 &HT;    For many years, Indians generally ignored national and state
elections and concentrated on their own tribal elections. As the
Indian media gained a voice in Indian country and more information
became available to the voters of the Indian reservations, this all
began to change.
 &HT;    I believe Gore will be the candidate of choice for 99 percent of
Indian voters. He has had the opportunity to serve in an
administration that reached out to the American Indian and created
programs that would bring jobs and better schools to the
reservations. That's a major plus.
 &HT;    Sometimes the further one is away from the Beltway the better
vision they develop. Out in Indian country, we have a pretty clear
view. Looks like Al Gore in 2000.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Tim Giago (Nanwica Kciji _ ``Stands up for Them'') is an Oglala
Lakota. He is editor and publisher of the weekly newspaper, The
Lakota Nation Journal. He can be reached at: P.O. Box 3080, Rapid
City, S.D. 57709-3080 or e-mailed at: editor at
lakotanationjournal.com
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Tim Giago 
