<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2295 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-MUSICALS-BOS &LR;      04-10 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-MUSICALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BATTLE FOR THE AMERICAN MUSICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fight for the soul of the American musical
continues unabated. At one extreme are corporate merchants, such as
Disney, with their musical cartoons, and at the other are the
artistes, with their pseudo-operatic attempts to reinvent Broadway
in the likeness of their patron saint, Stephen Sondheim. Those in
the latter camp have found a radiant spokeswoman for their cause in
singer Audra McDonald, but the list of their Broadway failures just
gets longer _ Jason Robert Brown's ``Parade,'' Michael John
LaChiusa's ``Marie Christine,'' and Andrew Lippa's ``The Wild
Party.'' Meanwhile, the awfulness of the new Elton John-Tim Rice
``Aida'' makes you want to shout, ``Come back to Broadway, Paul
Simon _ all is forgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   All is not lost, though. Musical jewels do emerge, such as
``Ragtime'' and Julie Taymor's contribution to ``The Lion King''
from a couple of years ago. There are a couple of bright,MUSICALS,
Page F6 &QL; 
shining nonrevivals on Broadway this year, too, though they aren't
traditional musicals at all _ ``Contact'' and ``James Joyce's The
Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   They are, however, traditional musicals in the sense that they
possess the same virtues that the great musicals have, from ``Show
Boat'' onward _ sharp writing; a seamless mixture of song, dance,
and story; witty lyrics; and a sense of whimsy or romance that
leads to a heightened reality. Source material really has nothing
to do with it. ``Anna and the King of Siam'' was not a literary
masterpiece, but ``The King and I'' is a great musical. Verdi's
``Aida'' is one of the world's great operas; the musical based on
it is one of Broadway's biggest duds.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what unites trivial pursuits such as ``Aida'' and
Andrew Lloyd Webber's upcoming ``Whistle Down the Wind'' on the one
hand and artistic pretensions like ``Parade'' and Simon's
``Capeman'' on the other is a lugubrious sensibility. They're
operatic in intent, but pop-eratic in delivery, peddling phony
transcendence in the case of Sirs Elton and Andrew and bleak chic
from the sons of Sondheim.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to denigrate Sondheim, who reportedly is no fan of
operatic pretensions such as recitativ narrative and who is perhaps
the last great lyricist of musical theater. But ``Sweeney Todd,''
``Company,'' ``A Little Night Music,'' and even ``Passion'' are not
operas, or evenpoperas, they are full-blooded musicals in every
sense, picking up where he left off with the lyrics to ``West Side
Story.'' He is still charting his own serious course. It's the less
talented trying to sail behind him who have landed the musical on
the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contact'' and ``The Dead'' have seemingly little in common
with Sondheim's musicals _ neither has a real score, for one thing
_ but there are some similarities worth considering. First and
foremost is their uniqueness. ``Contact'' creates a world totally
its own, somewhere in between modern dance and musical theater,
with its three tableaux of relationships, from the 18th century to
the present. ``The Dead'' takes the Joyce story from which John
Huston made his last film and follows the musical cues to create
its own rich universe, warmer than Joyce's but no less bound to
mortality, with Shaun Davey's mixture of traditional Irish songs,
operatic excerpts, and his own ballads.
</P>
<P>
   Both have recently moved from off-Broadway theaters to larger
Tony-eligible theaters because of huge demand, proving there is a
market for new musicals that have their wits and their tunes
together. ``Contact'' doesn't have any new music of its own, and
yet the spirit-soaring feeling one gets watching it is certainly
akin to that of seeing a great musical like ``Company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Contact'' is the brainchild of choreographer Susan Stroman and
Sondheim collaborator John Weidman. It follows romantic
relationships from 1767, when three characters swing their way
through a Lady Chatterley-like menage a trois, through a scene of
1950s sexism to the current times, with dancing that makes the jaw
drop and melodies that make the toes tap, with a superb combination
of prerecorded classical, jazz, and rock music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contact'' is what ``Fosse'' would have been had it not set its
sights so low. The three stories share a lush sensuality, from an
18th-century peek of thigh to the more bared and buffed sexual
dancing of today. The triptych opens with the 18th-century lovers _
a young woman on a swing being pushed by her servant while being
wooed by someone of her own class. First one and then the other
will join her on her perch and give new meaning to the term
swinging singles, all to the tunes of Stephane Grapelli.
</P>
<P>
   Part 2 continues the whimsy with shades of Richie Aprile and
Janice from ``The Sopranos'': Karen Ziemba plays a woman who is
literally taken out to eat at an Italian restaurant by her Mafioso
husband, who orders her not to move, smile, or even look at anyone
while he goes to the buffet. But whenever he leaves, her fantasies
take over and she dances up a storm (to Tchaikovsky, Bizet, and
Grieg) with the waiters and other diners. How is this different
from modern dance? It's Ziemba's acting, which recalls Giulietta
Masina's touching persona in ``La Strada,'' as much as her
crotch-in-face dancing that makes this scene and sets the
post-intermission stage for the finale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``All That Twilight Company''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's in this tableau where ``Company'' meets ``All That Jazz''
and even ``The Twilight Zone.'' Boyd Gaines, a Tony winner who
starred in ``Company'' and ``Cabaret,'' plays an alcoholic ad
executive who comes home from picking up an award to his soulless,
modern Manhattan apartment where, after numerous comically
choreographed attempts at suicide, he decides to join his
colleagues at a pool hall that becomes a swing-dance club, playing
everything from Dion to Benny Goodman at night. He keeps trying to
make it with one of the beautiful danceaholics _ a woman in yellow
_ while the audience wonders if he'll ever get past his dreary
reality and make real contact with her or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Stroman's direction and choreography are inspired throughout,
but it's in this scene where we, like the ad agency executive, can
see other possibilities in musical theater. Thomas Lynch's set
design, which turns the apartment into a dance hall and back again,
is a tour de force in and of itself, but it's Stroman _ whose
credits include the latest revivals of ``Oklahoma!'' and ``Show
Boat'' _ who shows what can happen when the imagination takes over
and fantasy creates new, glistening realities. That's what musical
theater has always been about and Stroman and friends prove it's an
ideal still worth pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   It comes along at just the right time, considering what a
depressing tourist trap Elton John and Disney have made of
``Aida.'' It obviously has some resonance with those who think the
musical world begins with John and ends with 'N Sync. This is
another attempt to get rock writers to write for Broadway in hopes
of luring younger audiences to theater, but there's no excuse for
the condescension and utter stupidity of ``Aida,'' particularly
after Taymor proved with ``The Lion King'' that you don't have to
dumb down.
</P>
<P>
   Disney got good people here as well _ Robert Falls (``Death of a
Salesman'') directed and cowrote the book with David Henry Hwang
(``M. Butterfly''), and Bob Crowley (``Carousel'') did the set and
costume design. They're not the problem. There's nothing wrong with
scrapping Verdi, but when your musical sights don't transcend
Andrew Lloyd Webber (Tim Rice wrote this book, as well as many of
ALW's) and you're not even trained in that limited genre, the
result is bound to be as insipid as ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   Can you feel the love tonight? Not if you've ever heard the real
thing _ and as Stroman shows, the real thing can be the Beach Boys
as well as Verdi. Young people will flock to ``Aida,'' but the hope
for the future is with ``Contact'' and ``The Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``Contact'' is at Lincoln Center's Vivian Beaumont Theater, ``James
Joyce's The Dead'' at the Belasco Theatre, and ``Aida'' at the
Palace Theatre in open-ended runs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
