<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2298 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COURT-MELTDOWN-BOS &LR;      04-10 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-MELTDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT DRAMA TAKES PLACE IN A CHANGING NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be you could rely on certain things in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Live Free or Die. Income tax as ultimate taboo. Conservatism
with a quirky, libertarian streak. The Union-Leader of Manchester's
staunch opposition to all things _ and persons _ Democrat and
liberal. The New Hampshire Supreme Court, a bastion of traditional
values upheld by a strong core of Republican appointees.
</P>
<P>
   But that New Hampshire is passing. And if anyone needed evidence
of that, they need look no further than the recent turmoil swirling
through the halls of the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Anywhere else, the resignation of Justice W. Stephen Thayer III,
demands that Chief Justice David A. Brock be fired, and the
attorney general's scathing report alleging that judges routinely
had inappropriate involvement in cases from which they'd recused
themselves, would be remarkable, perhaps even unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   But in New Hampshire, local observers say, the impact is
seismic. The court's current crisis exposes a state at a turning
point, caught between the traditional _ the small-town, old-boy way
of doing things _ and the new New Hampshire, a high-tech haven
where talk of an income tax is no longer political suicide.
</P>
<P>
   And presiding over it all is Governor Jeanne Shaheen, a
transitional figure if ever there was one: a Democratic woman, the
state's first female governor, who took the no-income-tax pledge,
earning the admiration of none other than the Union-Leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of fundamental institutional pieces in terms of policy
and philosophy are probably being irreparably and irretrievably
changed,'' said Tom Rath, a former state attorney general and a
Republican political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Two candidates for governor this year _ one a Democrat, one a
Republican _ have refused to take the no-income tax pledge. The
Democratic challenger boldly promises to introduce an income tax,
and manages to remain a serious contender.
</P>
<P>
   Life under Concord's golden dome is hardly what it once was. A
Democratic governor is a rare thing in the Granite State. There
have been just four since 1900, which is why so many appointments
to the bench in the past have been Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But now there are as many Democrats as Republicans in the state
Senate. And there are more Democrats in the House of
Representatives than there have been in almost 20 years. The three
senior office-holders in the state _ the governor, the speaker of
the House, and the Senate president _ are all women. Soon, the
Supreme Court might have its first woman. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlikely alliances form &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In such a shifting climate, unlikely alliances among former foes
have produced dramatic shifts on key issues. This year, the House
approved bills to abolish the death penalty and legalize hemp
farming, and last year it voted for a bill to introduce an income
tax for the first time in state history.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved bills to make gun owners responsible for
keeping weapons away from children and endorsed longer methadone
treatment programs for heroin addicts. None of those votes made it
into law, but support for them was unprecedented in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, much of the change is being driven by some of the
state's newest residents, those who fled across the border from
Massachusetts dreaming of tax-free, small-town life, but trailing
big-city notions of the way government should work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the new people keep saying, `We've come so we can go
back to the old ways,' '' said Representative Alf E. Jacobson of
New London, former president of the New Hampshire Senate.
``Avoiding taxation and avoiding the big city and all that. But
many of them bring their own philosophies with them so that changes
occur as a result of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson himself has tried to change one of the state's most
enduring traits _ its citizen government. One of the smallest
states in the union, New Hampshire has a Legislature that is one of
the biggest, providing one lawmaker for every 2,500 residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say you could cut it in half without a problem,'' he said.
His bill to do so got only 33 votes, however. ``There's a mythology
to some degree about it being a citizen legislature and, therefore,
more democratic than a professional legislature such as
Massachusetts or New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson also proposed legislation in 1998 challenging the right
of the Supreme Court to devise its own rules. Though that bill
failed, too, he thinks it could pass now.
</P>
<P>
   While economics and demographics have driven much of the change
in New Hampshire, the institution that sparked the protracted
debate over the most contentious change _ a statewide income tax _
is the hidebound Supreme Court itself.
</P>
<P>
   Its 1997 decision struck down the system of funding local
schools solely through municipal property taxes, a practice that it
said penalized students in poor communities. As a result, the state
has scrambled to come up with alternatives for sharing the wealth
of richer towns with poorer ones. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Judges face criticism &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The court ruling unleashed the controversy over taxes that has
gripped the state for the past several years, and made some
legislators and residents intensely critical of the judges who sit
in the courtroom with the roaring fire overlooking the Merrimack
River.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the (Supreme Court) judges' decision that has really
opened this whole discussion,'' Rath said. ``There's an irony to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the shadow of the Supreme Court controversy, Shaheen last
week appointed a nonpartisan, former Dartmouth president, David
McLaughlin, to the blue-ribbon commission that will study the
state's tax structure. And, in another sign of the shifting times,
her failure to appoint a strong opponent of income taxes has
elicited no outrage from a public that still takes fierce pride in
living in the last state in the union without a broad-based tax _
either sales or income.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me that was the big surprise last week,'' said Jere R.
Daniell, a Dartmouth College history professor. ``By depoliticizing
the panel, she has bought herself some time. It will certainly
allow for a thorough study, and it could open up the possibility of
a broad income tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of the school funding decision, some legislators,
and the Union-Leader, could spare no sympathy for Thayer and Brock
last week. Publisher Joseph W. McQuaid signed a front-page
editorial pillorying the justices after news broke that Thayer had
allegedly tried to influence his own divorce appeal and another
case in which he had an interest, and that Brock listened to him.
</P>
<P>
   McQuaid demanded that Shaheen remove four of the five Supreme
Court judges. True, McQuaid suggested that Shaheen's new
appointments be only temporary, but the fact that a prominent
conservative was advocating that a Democratic governor name a slate
of new judges was a sure sign that something significant was
happening in the Granite State.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Thayer, coupled with the possible ouster of
Brock and the upcoming retirement of Judge Sherman Horton, could
allow Shaheen to virtually remake the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential for change is tremendous,'' Jacobson said.
``You're going to get a whole new opportunity for a governor to
appoint members who could be there for 30 or more years, and her
influence, her ideas, could carry on for that period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The state will be watching Shaheen very closely if she replaces
Brock and other judges. For that reason, said Marcus Hurn,
professor of law at the Franklin Pierce Law School, Shaheen will be
very careful to appoint judges with unimpeachable credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``After one of these big dust-ups, everybody's watching the
governor,'' he said. ``And the governor usually has the sense to
seek out very admired, judicious people, and you wind up with a
better court than average because everybody's on their best
behavior for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the high court judges have passed firmer rules on
recusals, no longer allowing disqualified judges to participate in
decisions, even to offer suggestions on punctuation and grammar.
</P>
<P>
   A vastly reshaped court could usher in the sort of dramatic
change that has taken root in the other branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This scandal is really the result of personalities and the
ingrown, good-old-boy network of the state bar,'' said Linda
Fowler, professor of government and director of Rockefeller Center
at Dartmouth College. ``And to the extent that New Hampshire is a
small state and everybody knows each other and people kind of have
been inclined in the past to give each other the benefit of the
doubt, this scrutiny and the public outrage about it are going to
change some norms in the courthouse.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ralph Jimenez and Stephen Kurkjian of the Globe staff contributed
to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1408EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
