<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2299 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-MUSICAL-REVIVAL     04-10 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-MUSICAL-REVIVALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEANWHILE, THERE'S A RUN ON REVIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Revivals are tricky business when the play in
question has had what might be considered a definitive performance.
It can take a powerhouse interpretation to make you forget a
scintillating night of theater from the past and go with a
different flow.
</P>
<P>
   This has a particular relevance now that what could be called
the Paul Thomas Anderson Repertory Company has relocated from LA to
New York, with the stars of that director's ``Magnolia,'' ``Boogie
Nights,'' and ``Hard Eight'' surfacing on Broadway and off. Philip
Seymour Hoffman and John C. Reilly are alternating every third
performance as the bipolar brothers in Sam Shepard's ``True West,''
while William H. Macy and Philip Baker Hall hold forth in David
Mamet's ``American Buffalo.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cherry Jones, Gabriel Byrne, and Roy Dotrice are
starring in a remounting of Eugene O'Neill's ``A Moon for the
Misbegotten'' in a production free of Anderson alumni or actors
with three names. These are gutsy choices on the part of all these
actors, because others still cast a long shadow over these plays
even though a relatively small number of theatergoers saw them. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``True West'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sam Shepard's seminal play about family dysfunction pairs an
outlaw brother named Lee against Austin, a Hollywood screenwriter.
It's doubtful that the Steppenwolf production taped for PBS,
featuring then-little-known actors John Malkovich and Gary Sinise,
will ever be topped _ who could be more menacing than Malkovich?
</P>
<P>
   British director Matthew Warchus (``Art'') tries something
different by alternating Hoffman and Reilly after every three
performances. But Hoffman's performance as Lee is so buffoonish I
was ready to write Shepard off along with the actors _ Reilly
wasn't much better as Austin. A few days later, after they switched
roles, the whole operation made far more sense. Not only is Reilly
a hilarious Lee and Hoffman a wonderfully modulated Austin, but as
Hoffman gets less and less civilized his Austin turns into Lee as
he had played him a few days before. It's as if Warchus and Hoffman
are underlining a kind of randomness in Shepard's script, that a
turn here or there is enough to chart an entirely different path
for an individual.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most people can't afford to see the same play twice in a
limited run; if you're going only once, see Reilly as Lee and
Hoffman as Austin. Not only are they far better performances, but
Shepard's writing bristles with an intelligence and energy that
seems merely portentous with the roles reversed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``American Buffalo'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mamet, too, can seem an empty vessel when not done right. Al
Pacino set the standard as Teach, the small-time con man with a
rapid-fire, foul-mouthed, spittle-spraying delivery. I always
thought Pacino was a little over the top and was looking forward to
William H. Macy, who had been dismissed as not fiery enough.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately the reviews were right. Macy captures more humor
in the part, and more of Teach's loser quality in the process, but
if director Neil Pepe's idea was that underplaying Mamet would
bring out more richness in the script, it doesn't work. ``American
Buffalo'' can be played at something less than full-tilt boogie,
but Mamet becomes irrelevant at a tempo this slow. Philip Baker
Hall doesn't help matters. His Donny is so uninvolved that if you
hadn't seen him shine in Anderson's films or elsewhere you might
think he was an elder acting student. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A Moon for the Misbegotten'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two productions of Eugene O'Neill's play stand side by side in
the memory _ the classic with Jason Robards and Colleen Dewhurst
that was taped for television (and will soon be available on home
video) and the American Repertory Theatre production with Ian
Bannen and Kate Nelligan.
</P>
<P>
   I can't say that the current revival with Gabriel Byrne and
Cherry Jones makes three, but Jones is such a fine Josie Hogan she
almost carries it into the pantheon. One wonders if she saw
Nelligan at ART when Jones was here, but it hardly matters. When
the acting is of such a high caliber, comparisons are academic.
O'Neill gives his characters more room to breathe than Mamet and
Shepard _ part of which makes him a better playwright _ and Jones
finds room of her own to breathe. Some critics have found an
actress as slight and pretty as Jones to be be an unsuitable earth
mother, but that's their lack of imagination, not Jones's.
</P>
<P>
   The performance I had trouble with was Byrne's. Perhaps
understatement is a problem with all these film actors, but Byrne's
James Tyrone is such a deadened zombie of a character that he has
nowhere to fall. It's the occasional sputters of life that Robards
and Bannen flashed that made their defeats so tragic.
</P>
<P>
   To the production's credit, Roy Dotrice all but steals his
scenes as Josie's father, who tries to unite the two misbegottens,
but even with his shenanigans, Jones's transformative abilities,
and O'Neill's poetic if overly boiled dialogue, this isn't quite a
full moon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``True West'' runs through June 4 at Circle in the Square;
``American Buffalo'' through May 21 at the Atlantic Theater
Company; and ``A Moon for the Misbegotten'' through June 18 at the
Walter Kerr Theatre.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
