<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2303 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIES-TUCCI-BOS &LR;      04-10 1691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUCCI FINDS A MOVIE IN A TALE OF BLOCKED CREATIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stanley Tucci, the lead actor, writer, and director
of ``Big Night,'' ``The Impostors,'' and, opening Friday, ``Joe
Gould's Secret,'' remembers _ daily _ a lesson he learned from one
of his acting professors.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love to watch people do common, everyday activities,''
Tucci recites, while sitting over lunch in a West Village
restaurant, not far from where much of his new film was shot.
``It's fascinating to watch somebody eat. It's fascinating to watch
somebody smoke a cigarette _ nothing else, just that. People will
be fascinated by that. What is that person thinking? What's going
to happen?
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Renoir,'' he goes on, ``or Tarkovsky, at the most
extreme. Fellini _ `La Dolce Vita' is one of the most incredible
movies ever made, and there's no plot.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucci's own films reflect this lesson well. The ending of ``Big
Night'' _ a long, silent shot, in which his character, the owner of
a wonderful but failing Italian restaurant, cooks an omelet from
start to finish _ is one of the great movie endings of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Impostors'' is loaded with plot; it's a parody of plot.
But its priceless moments _ the scene where the unemployed actors,
played by Tucci and Oliver Platt, practice facial expressions, and
another where they connive to get free food from a baker _ are pure
character and situation.
</P>
<P>
   It's a perfect fit, then, for Tucci's latest film to be ``Joe
Gould's Secret,'' based on two articles that appeared in The New
Yorker, and were later combined into a book, by Joseph Mitchell. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mitchell's legacy &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who died four years ago at the age of 87, had, and
still has, a worshipful following, especially among other writers.
Calvin Trillin, the longtime New Yorker writer, once said he would
trade ``pretty much everything I've written for a paragraph of `Old
Mr. Flood' or `Joe Gould's Secret.' ''
</P>
<P>
   David Remnick, the magazine's current editor, treasures a
photograph of Mitchell and A. J. Liebling sitting together, the
pair representing a sort of yin and yang of the New Yorker style _
Liebling, as Remnick puts it, the ``Rabelaisian, Whitmanic writer
of appetite,'' Mitchell ``this completely austere, controlled,
haunted chronicler of the city and the human condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell wrote about a New York that no longer exists and that
even when he wrote about it, from the late 1930s through the
mid-1960s, was on the verge of vanishing. He wrote long, leisurely
profiles of gypsies, bartenders, oystermen, Mohawk steelworkers,
Bowery bums, and the assorted cranks, wannabes, couldabeens, and
get-alongs who give a neighborhood its character.
</P>
<P>
   A Mitchell essay typically began with a plain but evocative
description of a place _ a riverfront, a graveyard, a fish market,
a tavern, a city square. A character entered the picture, Mitchell
started up a conversation, and suddenly, seamlessly, the piece
became a meditation on life and death, or a mystery story, or a
tale of personal revelation, in an understated, time-suspending
way.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci, who is now 40, had never heard of Mitchell until seven
years ago, when his wife gave him, as a birthday present, ``Up in
the Old Hotel,'' a thick compilation of Mitchell's New Yorker
essays that had just been published.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew that I loved old New York and books about old New
York,'' Tucci remembers. ``I started reading, and quickly realized
this was the best writing I had ever read in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing that drew him was that, in a Mitchell piece, as Tucci
puts it, ``the drama is nonexistent. Or, rather, the drama is
simply existence. That is drama enough, or it is for me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A collecting connection &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was another way in which Tucci, though 51 years younger
than Mitchell, felt a connection to the writer. When Tucci had
first moved to the city from suburban Westchester County in 1982 _
as an aspiring actor, just out of college, without much work or
much else to do _ he walked the streets, jotted notes about ideas,
sat in bars, talked and listened to people, and collected old
pieces of glass and metal from junk shops and demolished-building
sites.
</P>
<P>
   As he read more of ``Up in the Old Hotel,'' he discovered that
Mitchell loved to do exactly the same things. Mitchell was an
inveterate street-walker and building-admirer, and he kept a vast
collection of old doorknobs and hinges and bottlenecks and cornice
fragments that he had found, and meticulously labeled, over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, shortly after he finished the film, Tucci's
wife gave birth to twins. One of Mitchell's daughters _ who lives
in New Jersey and still has her father's antique remnants _ gave
him, to pass along to his twins, two silver spoons out of a
collection that Mitchell had taken from New York restaurants that
no longer exist. ``Wasn't that nice of her?'' Tucci says softly,
clearly still deeply touched.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci plays Mitchell in this film, and to delve into the role,
he listened over and over to tapes of interviews Mitchell gave to
National Public Radio, getting down cold his soft North Carolina
accent and his hesitant cadences.
</P>
<P>
   Trillin, who knew Mitchell for 30 years, says of Tucci's
performance, ``He was Mitchell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Gould's Secret'' is the best known, and possibly the best,
of Mitchell's works. As Mitchell described his subject in his first
sentence, ``Joe Gould is a blithe and emaciated little man who has
been a notable in the cafeterias, diners, barrooms, and dumps of
Greenwich Village for a quarter of a century.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The man behind the story &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gould was a white-bearded chatterbox, the scion of a rich Boston
family and a Harvard graduate who descended into a jolly, and
erratically brilliant, madness. He called himself ``the last of the
bohemians,'' and claimed to be writing a book called ``An Oral
History of Our Time,'' which he said was approaching 9 million
words and which he compared to Edward Gibbon's ``The History of the
Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire.'' Short essays, supposedly
taken from his tome, were published by prestigious literary
journals of the day, and were admired by E. E. Cummings, Ezra
Pound, and William Saroyan.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell hung out for hours and months with Gould (played in the
film by Ian Holm), taking down his blatherings and his life story.
The New Yorker published the first of two pieces he would write
about Gould in 1942, under the title ``Professor Seagull'' (taken
from Gould's claim that he had figured out seagull language and had
translated ``a number of Henry Wadsworth Longfellow's poems'' into
the argot).
</P>
<P>
   Gould died in 1957 in a mental hospital. Several litterateurs
hunted for the ``Oral History'' manuscript, said to be stored at
some farmhouse in Long Island. Mitchell, when asked, often joined
the search party. Then, in 1964, he wrote a sequel, ``Joe Gould's
Secret,'' and revealed _ with no less tenderness or respect than he
had paid him in his first essay _ that the manuscript did not exist
and that he had known this, had shared and kept this secret of
Gould's, for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Gould's Secret'' was the last work to appear under
Mitchell's byline. It is the stuff of legend that, for the next 36
years, Mitchell regularly showed up at his New Yorker office, could
often be heard banging away at his typewriter, but never produced
another article.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious parallels were drawn, sometimes by Mitchell himself.
He recounted in that final essay that, for a long time, he had an
idea for a novel. He described its outline, a good many of its
details and flourishes. But, like Gould, he never sat down to write
his magnum opus. He later remarked to friends, ``Joe Gould _ that's
me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Getting Tucci's take &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All of Tucci's films are, in one way or another, about the comic
struggles of the artistic process and the various forces that try
to thwart it _ a saga perhaps inspired by his own career of, until
recently, small parts in undistinguished works (for example, the
bad guy in the ``Beethoven'' dog movie).
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Night'' is about a brilliant chef driven to cook in his
own way, without compromise, even though it means the collapse of
his restaurant _ and about the slick businessman across the street
who serves up terrible food but packs them in every night.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the film's original distributors, at MGM, wanted
Tucci to tack on an extra scene after the great omelet-cooking
shot, in which the phone rings and reservations start pouring in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really shocked,'' Tucci recalls of the meeting where the
suits proposed this new ending. ``I was thinking, `Oh yeah, that's
a sure-fire hit, they'll come in by the millions for that.'
Audiences would have hated that. I don't think audiences always
want happy endings. They're not as afraid of ambiguity as some
people think they are.'' (MGM dropped the film when Tucci refused
to change it.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Impostors,'' though more farcical, was about a fight
between a pair of hapless but dedicated actors who can't get work
and a dreadful actor who's unjustly rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   There are no villains in ``Joe Gould's Secret,'' only creators
thwarted by their own internal demons _ Gould, who was too crazy to
set anything down, and Mitchell, who may finally have been too
haunted by his own demanding standards.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci these days goes back and forth between acting in big
Hollywood movies (``to put a roof over my head'') and making the
small films he cares about, sometimes acting in other small
ventures just because he likes them. (For three days of work on
``Daytrippers,'' a delightful independent film a few years ago, he
was paid $225.)
</P>
<P>
   He says the next film he plans to direct, which takes place in
his hometown in Westchester County, ``has nothing to do with the
creative process.'' Which may be a sign that _ after creating three
movies that bear his signature, without compromise, to critical
(and even some commercial) success _ Tucci has laid his own demons
to rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2304 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-OBRIEN-BOS &LR;      04-10 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-OBRIEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE OLD SOD, WHERE MODERN MEETS RURAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
WILD DECEMBERS 
By Edna O'Brien. 
Houghton Mifflin. 259 pp. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ireland may be the only place in the world where talk is cheap
and also priceless. The island's oral sensibility is one of gossip
bumping into literature: a collision of pub fights, fence-hanging
yarns, and the poetry of the gods. Joyce understood this first and
best, of course; his exaltation of the ordinary simply and forever
changed the face of fiction. His intrepid heiress-apparent, Edna
O'Brien, has spent the last four decades celebrating a similarly
fecund narrative world of the bawdy and sublime; for her efforts,
she saw her first seven novels banned in her homeland _ the first
one toasted on the chapel grounds by her own parish priest.
</P>
<P>
   And in ``Wild Decembers,'' she has given talk itself the power
of a sweet-tongued devil. It's there in the ancient legends that
hover over rural Cloontha, ``a locality within the bending of an
arm,'' and there in the old grudges and new rumors that dictate the
order of things. It's there in Cloontha's bars and beauty salons,
in its misunderstandings and land disputes and murderous threats.
Most of all, it's there in the evolution of narrative: the way we
hear, interpret, then reweave the facts into intractably human
truths _ where fields ``mean more than fields . . . fields lost,
regained, and lost again in that fickle and fractured sequence of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this is a story about ceaseless rain and
turf-cutting and tragedy, more Thomas Hardy than Joyce in its mists
of preordained misery. The final volume of a trilogy, ``Wild
Decembers'' follows ``House of Splendid Isolation'' and ``Down by
the River''; what links the novels is not a specific story line,
but the shroud of Irish history, where passion begets violence and
where honor generally commands the price of blood. You can tell
from the first paragraph this is O'Brien country, with its sucking
calves and golden bogs and too-sweet smells of earth and death. Few
other writers take you inside a fictional realm so utterly and
swiftly by way of language _ by the sheer internal sounds and look
of words upon the page.
</P>
<P>
   The feuding sons of her classical story are Mick Bugler,
returning from a few years of self-exile on a sheep farm in
Australia, and Joseph Brennan, the elder brother of a sheltered
young woman named Breege. The two men's ancestors fought for years
over rights to their abutting lands, the history of which is
recorded in pub talk and memory, and maybe in the dusty archives of
a land office miles away. With the look and air of a dark-horse
charmer, Bugler possesses the only tractor on the mountain _ and,
within a matter of weeks, the heretofore-unclaimed attentions of
Breege. The Brennans' parents died when Breege was a young girl,
and Joseph moved in to fill the void; his subsequent protectiveness
of his sister her is only slightly mollified by his initial
affection for Bugler.
</P>
<P>
   Circumstances conspire to alter this fleeting harmony. Angry
sentiments are exchanged over the tractor, which, for all its
suggestion of modernity's forward march, winds up broken down on
Joseph's land. Word arrives of a fiance, Rosemary, soon to join
Bugler, thereby eclipsing any idea of a future for him and Breege.
These embers of discord are transformed into a brushfire by the
collective mischief of Cloontha's residents. A pair of conniving
sisters, Rita and Reena, decide to torment and even ruin Bugler
after they've failed to draw him into their web. The local misfit,
known as the Crock, is a physically deformed man who has led a life
of humiliation and rage; his bitterness has festered over the years
into malevolence, and Breege _ by the simple fact of her innocent
disregard _ becomes his target. Within a matter of months, rumor
and malice have turned into allegations and court fights, with
Joseph and Bugler each threatening the other through hired
solicitors as well as physical assault. Breege, her loyalties
divided but her heart resolute, finds herself alone in the barn
with Bugler for one splendid moment _ which is just long enough to
change everything, forever, for them both.
</P>
<P>
   This is an old, old story _ I kept thinking of Alfred Noyes's
``The Highwayman'' and Hardy's ``Tess'' _ with a darkness you can
see coming from clear across the moors. And yet O'Brien has filled
it with a resplendent ache that is hers alone. The novel breathes
with animal symbolism: a martyred greyhound, named after her
birthplace of Violet Hill; lowing calves, crying for their mothers;
a lost and exquisitely fragile butterfly, hostage to the mercy of
the man who holds it. These moments imbue the novel with a sense of
mystical doom, as unstoppable as spilled blood or a setting sun. At
such times the narration is Faulknerian in its alliterative march
toward destiny; when Breege's voice occasionally takes over, the
story feels stripped-down and piercing. This is an etching of a
tragedy, perfectly delineated, its boundaries set by land rights
and misdeeds and the very limitations of the human heart _ an inner
territory of beauty and imprisonment that is Ireland on the edge of
time, what O'Brien calls ``the confines of the place, back out to
the far reaches of the mountain, the ballerina birch, and the
fugitive amethyst river.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien has taken the title for ``Wild Decembers'' from an Emily
Bronte poem, and with it she has brought the same heather-tinged
heartache that clung to all those 19th-century heaths. It's
testament to the old-fashioned feel of the novel that you hardly
notice what decade it is until Rosemary arrives wearing thigh-high
boots; much of rural Ireland, after all, is a stubbornly sovereign
land of preindustrial passions. And when progress does arrive at
little, well-insulated Cloontha, it does so with all the power and
destructive possibility of a freight train. ``You can go years and
years of normal life,'' thinks Breege, ``all day, every day,
milking, foddering, saying the given things, and then one day
something opens in you, wild and marvellous, like the great rills
that run down the mountain in the rain, rapid, jouncing, turning
everything they touch into something living; a mossy log suddenly
having the intent and slither of a crocodile.'' It's that
crocodile, heavy-eyed and treacherous, arriving at the end of a
passage of great beauty, that sets Edna O'Brien apart. No mere lush
romantic, she knows that great change and desolation are two
different aspects of the same darkening sky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-PRESIDENT-REVIEW-B     04-10 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PRESIDENT-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 10-HOUR DRAMA WITH 41 CHARACTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE AMERICAN PRESIDENT 
Narrated by: Hugh Sidey 
Written, produced and directed by: Philip B. Kunhardt Jr., Philip
B. Kunhardt 3d, Peter W. Kunhardt 
On: PBS 
Time: 9 p.m., through Thursday 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the numerous virtues of ``The American President'' is
that it shows us what a capacious joint the White House is.
</P>
<P>
   Just consider the remarkably different figures who have called
it home. There was Franklin Delano Roosevelt (in office 1933-45), a
man whose ebullience, empathy, and self-confidence (``Above all,
try something,'' he said in the depths of the Depression) supplied
a dose of optimism to a nation desperately in need of it.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Benjamin Harrison (1889-93), who glumly
opined that a president's life is ``like that of the policeman in
the opera: not a happy one,'' then went on to prove it. Harrison's
interactions with citizens were so cold that he became known as
``the human iceberg.'' When a friend urged him to ``for God's sake,
be human,'' Harrison rejoined: ``I tried it, but I failed. I'll
never try it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison's presidency was utterly forgettable, while Roosevelt's
represents an indelible chapter in our history. The times they
lived in had a lot to do with that, of course. But the useful
lesson of ``The American President'' is that the nation's chief
executives leave their stamp on the office not just by their words
and deeds, but through the sense of self they transmit to the
country they govern; in other words, through their personality.
</P>
<P>
   To a striking degree, the series argues, a president's character
shapes the nation's destiny. George Washington, while ``easily
embarrassed by his lack of learning,'' possessed the wisdom and
strength of character to spurn an offer to become king of the newly
liberated country. (``Banish these thoughts,'' he said.) John
Tyler's forceful personality helped clarify the question of
vice-presidential succession. The Constitution was vague on that
issue, so when William Henry Harrison died, it wasn't clear whether
Tyler, his vice president, would serve as president or as a
temporary caretaker. The Cabinet believed it was the latter, but
Tyler disabused them of that notion in their first meeting, saying:
``I am the president. When you think otherwise, your resignation
will be accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   With 41 chief executives to cover, the series moves too quickly
to cover any individual presidency in detail. But what it lacks in
depth, it makes up for in sweep. The thematic links it establishes
among the presidents are generally sound; for instance, Tuesday
night's installment covers four presidents largely defined by
foreign policy (Monroe, McKinley, Wilson, Bush), and Wednesday's
looks at four generals who became president (Washington, Grant,
Eisenhower, William Henry Harrison). The series has an eye for the
telling detail, noting, for instance, that one in every seven
people on the podium during John F. Kennedy's inauguration was a
member of the Kennedy family.
</P>
<P>
   A respect for the presidency pervades the series, which is fine
except when the tone becomes overly celebratory. However majestic a
figure George Washington was, it's distracting to hear a brass
fanfare playing behind the narration. Also, no mention is made of
Washington's ownership of slaves, a rather large contradiction in a
man who symbolized this country's fight for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The handsome volume published in conjunction with the series
(and sharing its title) notes that the 41 presidents have been
``all men, all white, and all Christian.'' It adds optimistically
that the country is ``moving inexorably toward greater inclusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
