<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DREAMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTURING THE PARADOX OF FDR VEEP HENRY WALLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
AMERICAN DREAMER 
A Life of Henry A. Wallace 
By John C. Culver and John Hyde 
Norton, 608 pp., illustrated, $35 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an oral history that Henry A. Wallace recorded near the end
of his life, he concluded that it was good he had missed out on
becoming president in 1945, after the death of Franklin Delano
Roosevelt, because no one as divisive and controversial as he could
have led the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace had been Roosevelt's vice president from 1940 to 1944 _
forced on the party by FDR, who saw his rumpled, even eccentric
secretary of agriculture as a philosopher who would ``help the
people think.'' But when he ran for a fourth term, Roosevelt
allowed the party bosses to dump Wallace from the ticket and
replace him with the more comfortable and conventional Harry S
Truman.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace is remembered today mainly for his own quixotic and
red-baited 1948 campaign _ Cambridge radicals of a certain age can
wistfully sing the campaign verse (written to the tune of the old
folk song ``Passing Through'') that begins: ``Yes, I was at
Franklin Roosevelt's side, just a while before he died.''
</P>
<P>
   In this fine biography, John C. Culver, a former United States
senator from Wallace's home state of Iowa, and John Hyde, a former
reporter for The Des Moines Register, have not just revived and
rehabilitated a barely remembered political figure, they have
captured the paradox of a man who could be so widely admired and so
deeply hated.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was born on a farm, in October 1888, and the family's
major enterprise was agricultural journalism, publishing the
influential and widely read Wallace's Farmer. And had he never been
pulled into politics, he would deserve attention as an agricultural
economist and innovator _ principally for his role in developing a
hybrid corn that is now planted worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rarely has a public figure's talent so perfectly matched his
opportunity,'' write Culver and Hyde of Wallace on his taking over
the Agriculture Department in the grim Depression year of 1933.
``Born to a family whose very mission was he preservation of
agriculture, (he) had become the mobilizing general of just such an
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The party leaders who swallowed their anger when Wallace was
forced on them in 1940 got even four years later, moved mainly by
concerns that Roosevelt would not live out a fourth term and that
Wallace was too unpredictable, too undependable, to serve as
president. The account Culver and Hyde provide of the 1944 national
convention _ ``six astonishing days,'' they call it _ is a
masterpiece of political writing, from the maneuverings to win
Roosevelt's support for Truman to Wallace's own electrifying speech
nominating Roosevelt ``in the cause of liberalism,'' which
threatened to undo the plotters.
</P>
<P>
   The most contentious issue that any study of Wallace must
address is his split with Truman over foreign policy and
international control of the atomic bomb _ and, as a consequence,
the charge that Wallace was, if not a communist, certainly too
friendly toward the Soviet Union. Culver and Hyde track the
development of this issue carefully and comprehensively.
</P>
<P>
   From their account, it is clear that Wallace too often left
himself open to red-baiting and that his enemies took advantage of
every opportunity to target him. As presidential adviser Clark
Clifford put it in a strategy memo for Truman's 1948 campaign,
``every effort must be made . . . to identify and isolate him in
the public mind with the Communists.''
</P>
<P>
   And it worked. As Culver and Hyde write, ``everything had turned
on its head. The quiet son of Iowa soil had been transformed in the
public mind into a wild-eyed fanatic bent on destroying the
American way of life. . . . The deeply religious grandson of a
Presbyterian minister had become an apostle of godless
totalitarianism.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the politics and the controversy, Wallace, in the hands
of two skillful _ and admiring _ biographers, becomes an engaging
personality: an odd stick, but charmingly so. When he proposed to
his future wife, he presented her with a bag of diamonds borrowed
from a trusting local jeweler. ``Here,'' he told her, ``pick one
out.'' She slept fitfully that night with the bag under her pillow.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the Truman administration _ the last of the
Roosevelt cabinet members to do so _ Wallace was for a time editor
of The New Republic. Often he would disappear from the office in
the company of ``a mysterious man'' he called Max. His publisher
feared that ``Max'' was some kind of ``political agent.'' But no,
he was a retired East Side grocer who would take Wallace around to
neighborhood delicatessens _ from which he would return ``with his
overcoat pockets stuffed with tins of gefilte fish and bottles of
borscht.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final 17 years of his life after the 1948 campaign,
Culver and Hyde write, Wallace ``never returned to the good graces
of the broad American public.'' If for no other reason than that, a
full-scale biography of Wallace is welcome. That is it also a
masterful portrait of so fascinating a man makes it all the more
welcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
