<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2310 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STOLEN-ART-BOS &LR;      04-10 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOLEN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM DETAILS NAZI'S ROLE IN ARTWORK ON ITS WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN DEZELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On Friday, George Shackelford, chair of European
paintings at the Museum of Fine Arts, was grabbing faxes, fielding
phone calls, and retrieving e-mail about a 17th-century Italian
painting in the museum's collection once owned by a notorious
Nazi-era art dealer.
</P>
<P>
   The information reduced the possibility that Domenico Fetti's
``Parable of the Good Samaritan'' was one of tens of thousands of
art objects stolen from Jewish families and art sellers during the
Third Reich. And so an image of the painting _ and most of what
Shackelford knows about it _ was posted on the Internet
(www.mfa.org) Saturday as the MFA launches a site that illustrates
and annotates as many as nine works of art whose history of
ownership suggests they may have been plundered.
</P>
<P>
   The MFA's move is an effort to address growing concerns about
the possible presence in American museums of what are known as
spoliated works _ and criticism that institutions have not been
quick enough to reveal what they know about those pieces.
</P>
<P>
   But the MFA's response to what is surely the most volatile issue
in the art and exhibition worlds today may provoke more questions
than resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Museum of Fine Arts is absolutely in the forefront of
museums that are doing the right thing in posting suspicious art on
the Web that allows anyone who has a legitimate claim to it to come
forward,'' said Jehuda Reinharz, president of Brandeis University
and a member of the Presidential Commission on Holocaust Assets in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the information that has emerged and the burgeoning
public awareness about Nazi-era art in recent years, provenance
research at the MFA and elsewhere is a wide-ranging, painstaking,
and not always fruitful process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Provenance is different for virtually every painting,'' said
Shackelford. ``Many of our Monets have unbroken lineage. Monet's
`Haystack With Snow,' for example, went from the artist to the
dealer, Durand-Ruel, to Horatio Lamb of Boston, to Aimee and
Rosamund Lamb, who gave it to the museum in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is much more typical, particularly with older paintings,
is that you have a run of provenances, then have a big break
because transfers from hand to hand were not publicly conducted, or
records were not kept.''
</P>
<P>
   Shackelford randomly opened a recent catalog raisonne _
considered the definitive record of a work's ownership history _
and pointed to an entry for Paul Cezanne's ``La Maison Rustique''
(circa 1879), which is at the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford, Mass.
The catalog shows that the painting changed hands seven times, but
entries about three of those exchanges appear with question marks.
</P>
<P>
   The Fetti is considered suspicious because it was handled by
Gustav Rochlitz before it was acquired by the collector Frederick
Haussman, who sold it to the Hans Schaeffer Galleries, the New York
dealer from which the MFA bought it in 1946. Rochlitz, a German
dealer, was an art adviser to Nazi field marshal and avid collector
Hermann Goering, and a key figure in the Nazi plunder of Jewish art
collections and dealerships in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The MFA learned last week that Hausmann owned the painting as
early as 1941, and that he was living in New York then, ``which
takes it out of the realm of a lot of looting during the war,''
said Shackelford. ``What we don't know is where it was before
1941.'' Shackelford traced the painting to a 1927 exhibition whose
records show that Rochlitz lent it. He might have bought and sold
the Fetti legally before the Nazis came to power, ``but we don't
know,'' he said. That is why the Fetti will be on the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some works of art that you'll never be able to pin
down, because information about them was destroyed or is still
classified or was never there,'' said Constance Lowenthal, of the
Committee for Art Recovery of the World Jewish Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The hope among Jewish advocacy organizations, the Commission on
Art Recovery, and museums is that releasing information on art
works will not only lead to the recovery of stolen property _ some
of it worth millions of dollars _ but will yield more information.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that tens of thousands of paintings, sculptures, and
decorative objects owned by Jewish families and collectors were
systematically pillaged during World War II emerged at the end of
the Cold War, as long-sequestered records and objects increasingly
became available to researchers.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, interest in the Holocaust, seminal books on World
War II plunder and its aftermath, and press investigations,
including several in the Globe, widened and deepened public
awareness of the thousands of works of ``homeless'' art in museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became very clear to the museum community that this cannot
be ignored and that they have to do something proactive to
demonstrate that what they own or possess is truly the museum's
property, instead of sitting back and waiting for claims,'' said
Lowenthal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 the American Association of Museum Directors adopted
guidelines for museums to identify and deal with claims for
spoliated objects. The standards call for the organizations to
conduct comprehensive reviews of their collections to determine
whether any works were stolen during the Nazi era and to address
problematic pieces ``candidly and responsively.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the past year, heirs to an Henri Matisse painting at the
Seattle Art Museum and one by Lucas Cranach the Elder at the North
Carolina Museum of Art have resulted in the return of stolen
property. Most major museums have begun reviews of their
collections, and while some claims for restitution or compensation
from museums are mired in legal conflict, there is a sense among
institution leaders that ``the system is working,'' said James
Cuno, head of the Harvard Art Museums. ``The problem for
noncontinental museums such as ours is usually not that we hold
works of art that have a legacy of confiscation. Usually, it is the
second- or third-generation ownership of art. We're dealing with
objects purchased by people in good faith, and we have to trace it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowenthal and Reinharz credit the museums with progress in
researching and identifying problematic art. But Elan Steinberg,
executive director of the World Jewish Congress, maintains that
museums have come to this point with reluctance, and are not moving
quickly enough to determine whether ``they have clear title to
these works. It's all very good that they're beginning to fulfill
their principles of two years ago, but it wasn't until there was a
public outcry that we began to see movement here.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grossman, an MFA trustee and Jewish community leader,
downplayed the differences in approach among those concerned about
questionable art.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue in which you have scholarship, you have
politics, you have a moral imperative, and the most tragic event of
the 20th century rolled into one. Sometimes it's very hard to see
the motivations of other individuals or groups. But if you think
about it, all of them are entirely legitimate and honorable. At the
end of the day, Malcolm (Rogers, MFA director) has implemented a
bold plan that recognizes the museum's concerns, a moral
imperative, and good public policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
