<P>
   &UR; RAMPAGE KILLERS SERIES &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RAMPAGE-KILLERS-III (Salt Lake City) _ With the voices inside
her head ordering her to kill, Lisa Duy walked into Doug's Shoot'n
Sports here to buy a semiautomatic pistol. The manager, Dave
Larsen, ran a background check on her and the agency quickly
approved the sale, having found no record of felony convictions or
mental illness. The only thing unusual, Larsen thought, was that as
she left the store, Ms. Duy was wearing the shooting-range ear
protectors he had lent her. Less than two hours later, on Jan. 14,
1999, Miss Duy, ear protectors still in place, walked into the
studios of television station KSL and began firing her new weapon.
She shot more than four dozen times in all, killing a young mother
and wounding the building manager. What the background check had
been unable to detect was that Ms. Duy had a long history of
psychiatric problems. Of the 100 episodes of rampage killings
examined for this series by The New York Times, none better
illustrates than the case of Lisa Duy just how difficult it can be
to enforce a key provision of the nation's fundamental gun control
law. That provision prohibits people who have been involuntarily
committed to mental institutions from buying a handgun. But laws in
most states guard the privacy of the mentally ill, so gun
background checks typically fail to turn up mental health
histories. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   Third in a series of four.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-PLANE-CRASH (Washington) _ The Pentagon killed the V-22
Osprey 11 years ago. Too expensive, too experimental, it said. But
the plane, a hybrid helicopter/turboprop, wouldn't die. Congress
kept it alive. No one fought harder than Rep. Curt Weldon, from the
Pennsylvania district where the aircraft would be built. Now 3 of
the 15 finished craft have crashed, killing 26 soldiers. The
aircraft remains expensive, experimental _ and exemplary of the way
weapons are built for today's military. The Pentagon has now
grounded the Ospreys that haven't already crashed. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Nashville) _ Vice President Al Gore attends a ceremony
honoring his mother, plans a town meeting in the evening. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Notes from the campaign trail.
</P>
