</P>
<P>
   KOREA-TALKS (Seoul, South Korea) _ From experts in their
think-tanks to commuters rushing to work, South Koreans seemed
stunned Monday by the news of a summit meeting with North Korea in
June. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-EMBASSY-U.S. (Washington) _ Unsatisfied by the firing of a
Central Intelligence Agency employee, China on Monday rejected U.S.
explanations for last year's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-FOREIGNERS (Tokyo) _ Shintaro Ishihara, the radical
governor of Tokyo, set off a swell of criticism in diplomatic
circles and foreign communities here with his remarks that
immigrants in Japan, mainly people of Korean and Chinese descent,
were likely to stage riots following a major earthquake. He called
on Japan's self defense forces to be prepared to maintain order
during such an uprising. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ELECT (Lima) _ As the vote count in the presidential
election continues, so does the tension, as it remains unclear if
President Alberto Fujimori has a first-round victory. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-POLITICS (Essen) _ The Christian Democrats, in the wake
of the Helmut Kohl scandal, try to chart a new course on Monday as
Angela Merkel becomes first woman to the head party, elected at a
party conference where Kohl, the former chancellor, didn't even
show up. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
