   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINES-ADS (Undated) _ The magazines that are doing well have
never had it so good. Magazines like In Style, Vogue, Vanity Fair
and W are so packed with advertisements that they blowing past
their records for size, heft and length. They are part of a growing
breed: the obese magazine, publications so fat that if they were
people, they ought to be in a high school auditorium sweating to
the oldies with Richard Simmons. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Nasdaq stocks are weaker, while blue chips
are posting modest gains. At 2:10 p.m. EDT, the NASDAQ composite
index is down 175 points, led by Microsoft and Oracle. The Dow
Jones industrials were up 99 points, led by J.P. Morgan, American
Express and General Motors. The S&AMP;P 500 was down 5 points. Treasury
prices were slightly higher. Crude oil was lower, at $24.70 a
barrel. European stock markets were little changed: London was down
0.39 percent and Frankfurt was flat. In Asia, Tokyo's Nikkei closed
up 1.81 percent; the Hang Seng in Hong Kong was down 0.54 percent.
By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA-EARNINGS (Chicago) _ Motorola is to report
first-quarter earnings after the stock market closes. The forecast
is for 58 cents a share. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Moves by companies like Ito-Yokado and
Sony to offer banking services face a roadblock as an influential
politician is urging regulators to reconsider plans to issue
banking licenses to such companies. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-PRIVATIZE (Singapore) _ A bill to privatize and
reform the heavily indebted national power company in the
Philippines finally appears headed for passage after delays that
had lasted for years. Passage is viewed as a litmus test of
economic reform in the Philippines because the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund have threatened to withhold billions of
dollars in loans to the country if there are further delays. By
Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column. By Reed
Abelson.
