<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PROPERTY RIGHTS _ AND WRONGS _ IN A WIRED WORLD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO-OWNS-IDEAS?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Thomas Jefferson's inspiring vision, there are no barriers to
the acquisition of knowledge. Nobody owns it, everybody partakes of
it _ and the world becomes richer. Two centuries later, when
knowledge has taken over much of the economy, Jefferson's words
seem to take on a new power. These days, ideas are capital. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 825 words; 900 words uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BREAK IT UP, BOYS: `WINDOWS' OF OPPORTUNITY FOR MICROSOFT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIXING-MICROSOFT-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may have come as a shock to the markets, but few others can
have been surprised that Microsoft was this week found guilty. A
bolder and more imaginative Bill Gates would now consider
restructuring his company himself, as a better and more creative
alternative to the terrifying legal lottery that he appears to have
chosen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEST'S MACHIAVELLI IS NO BETTER THAN IRAQ'S HUSSEIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RETHINK-SADDAM-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If, year in, year out, the United Nations were systematically
killing Iraqi children by air strikes, western governments would
declare it intolerable, no matter how noble its intention. They
should find their existing policy toward Iraq just as unacceptable.
In democracies, the end does not justify the means. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ZIMBABWE ON A KNIFE-EDGE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ZIMBABWE-FOLLY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe is in crisis. The blame lies almost entirely with
President Robert Mugabe and his ZANU-PF, the party that has ruled
the country since it gained independence from Britain in 1980.
Mugabe has always swung between emotion and reason. Conceivably,
reason may regain the upper hand and he will allow next month's
election to be free and fair. But some nudging will almost
certainly be needed. If not, disaster will surely ensue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHINA: GOLDEN ECONOMIC PRIZE, OR RISING MENACE? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHINA-DEMYSTIFIED-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The West cannot quite make up its mind about how it wants to
deal with China. In America, big business lobbies Congress to treat
China as a normal trading nation, while Congress urges the Clinton
administration to sell more weapons to Taiwan, as defense against
Communist Chinese threats. Golden economic prize (2.6 billion
armpits to deodorize) or rising international menace (those ugly
threats)? Is China one or the other? Both or neither? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,025 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JAPAN NEEDS A NEW PRIME MINISTER WITH A MANDATE, SOON &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POST-OBUCHI-JAPAN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Keizo Obuchi's stroke last weekend, Japan has had to find
a new prime minister. No one, however, seems to be looking for any
other change; that, most Japanese seem to think, can wait until
after the general election, due sometime before autumn. Alas, Japan
cannot afford to be so relaxed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOENIX: THE NEXT SILICON VALLEY? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOT.COM-PHOENIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's arid Southwest is attracting people faster than any
other part of the country. Maintaining quality of life, while
continuing to attract the firms that will provide the jobs to
sustain population growth at almost three times the national rate,
is a balancing act. For Phoenix, the answer may be the Internet.
After all, an industry that doesn't need too much space, and brings
in a lot of money and not too many people, seems like a good
prospect for a city that wants to slow down a bit. Could Phoenix be
the next Silicon Valley? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Arizona) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (875 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JACK E., OH...: IT'S A SINNERS' RACE FOR TEDDY'S SEAT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOSTON-BADBOYS-SENATE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even in the age of negative politics, there is something a
little extraordinary, even admirable, about Jack E. Robinson III's
run for the Senate seat that comes up for election in Massachusetts
this year. In his nine-page ``Robinson's Report,'' he reveals every
skeleton in his political closet, and is now challenging his
notoriously inhibited opponent, Sen. Ted Kennedy, to do the same. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Massachusetts) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE KU KLUX KLAN: STILL RIDING, WITH A BIGGER AGENDA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KKK-ARKANSAS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Half a century or so ago, the Ku Klux Klan was remembered for
its nocturnal cross burnings, its bombing of black churches, its
occasional murders. Now, in a new century, it has picked up the
trappings of modernity. It has an Internet address for the
``Invisible Empire.'' And now Klansmen leave their rallies in
minivans and SUVs, not on horseback. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Little Rock, Ark.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIMARYCOLOR-COLUMN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This week's droll ``Primary Color'' column) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (425 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNCOMPROMISING POSITIONS OF RUDY GIULIANI &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RABID-RUDY-NY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an age when politicians seem able to ``emote'' anything, New
York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani is a gloriously feeble actor.
Assuming, that is, that Hizzoner even bothers to try _ which he
usually does not. Make a few sympathetic comments about unarmed men
killed by policemen? Not on your life, Mister. Keep financing a
museum that has annoyed you? Fugeddabahdit. A few routine
courtesies to your opponent? Whodya think you are, lady? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 225-word trim at 800; 1,125 words uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOES DOLLARIZATION MAKE CENTS FOR EL SALVADOR? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOLLARIZE-ELSALVADOR?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will El Salvador be the next Latin American country to adopt the
dollar as its currency? On paper, at least, El Salvador is a far
more promising candidate for dollarization that, say, Ecuador,
which recently adopted the greenback out of desperation with its
own, sliding, currency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; E-MAIL, SANS REGRETS: BEFORE YOU HIT THE `SEND' BUTTON... &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EMAIL-`WHOOPS!'-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who has not banged out an angry reply to an apparently brusque
e-mail message, hit the send button _ and then regretted it? Surely
no technology has led to so many rifts and fractured friendships
(not to mention subpoenas) as electronic mail. But nowhere is
e-mail more perilous than in negotiations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAKISTAN'S SOCCER-BALL INDUSTRY MENDS ITS TATTERED IMAGE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KIDS-LABOR-PAKISTAN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ending child labor in Pakistan can have unexpected consequences.
In the mid-1990s, Pakistani soccer-ball manufacturers were under
attack when the western press discovered that they were employing
children for 80-hour-a-week shifts, working for pennies in near
darkness. The industry hastily made profound changes and, three
years later, child labor in Sialkot's soccer industry is mostly
history. The effects, though, have been double-edged. Like soccer
itself, getting rid of child labor is not always a win-win game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 350; 1,375 words uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE FORBIDDEN `SECRET ROOMS' OF PORNOGRAPHIC POMPEII &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EROTIC-POMPEII-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half centuries after the excavation which brought the
ancient, destroyed cities of Pompeii and Herculaneum to light, a
collection of ``obscene objects,'' long kept behind closed doors,
is about to be opened again to the general public. A preview of the
erotic material in Naples reveals more than anything that they are
far above the standards _ as art as well as entertainment _ of what
passes for pornography today. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 200; 950 words uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
