<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Humor, Political Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 425-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; DEAD MEN WALKING: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John McCain and Bill Bradley, who have both withdrawn from the
presidential race, garnered double-digit tallies in this week's
primaries in Pennsylvania and Wisconsin. Alan Keyes, who is still
running, got 10 percent of the vote in Wisconsin. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURPRISING REGRET OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be as spontaneous any more.'' (The notoriously
preprogrammed Bush campaign complaining about the new Secret
Service detail, New York Daily News, April 2) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOUBLE-THINK OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush said that ``all of us need to encourage people to
fill out the census'' before going on to say that he could
understand why some people ``don't want to give all that
information to the government'' and that ``if I had the long form
I'm not sure I'd want to, either.'' (He got the short one.) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SLEEP-OVER OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ridge edged ahead in the Republican vice presidential
stakes. Bush slept at the Pennsylvania governor's home on a
campaign visit. He chose to stay in hotels during visits to
Wisconsin (governor: Tommy Thompson) and New Jersey (Christine Todd
Whitman). &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENDORSEMENT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a family that voted Republican. But for years
I've voted with the Democratic Party. I would probably go with
Gore.'' (Erin Brockovich, New York Times, April 5) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOK OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Earth in the Balance,'' by Al Gore. Sam Wyly, the Texas
financier who spent $2.5 million on a vicious ad campaign attacking
John McCain's environmental record, cited the tome when he
confessed his unexpected admiration for the vice president.
Meanwhile, Bush said that Gore ``is probably going to have to
explain what he meant by some of the things in his book.'' Bush for
one would be grateful for the explanation: he has not read the
soon-to-be-republished tract. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURPRISING THANKS OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush thanked Kansas for his victory in the primary on April 4.
Unfortunately, Kansas is not holding a primary. (National Journal's
Hotline, April 5) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CYNICAL ADVICE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Women consistently respond to the phrase `for the children'
regardless of the context.'' (Frank Luntz, a Republican pollster) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DONOR FATIGUE: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Governor and Mrs. Bush gave $334,000 to charity in 1998. The
Gores gave just $15,000, but that was 7 percent of their taxable
income, while the Bushes' donation was 2 percent. (Associated
Press, April 4) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
