<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANKS-560&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN RETHINKING PLANS TO OPEN BANKING INDUSTRY TO NON-BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Plans to allow non-banks to enter the banking business
here are faltering.
</P>
<P>
   Hideyuki Aizawa, an influential politician who heads the ruling
party's Financial Issues Research Committee, is urging financial
regulators to reconsider plans to issue banking licenses to
companies like Sony Corp. and the retailer Ito-Yokado, saying the
banking laws need to be redrawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that the regulators should not consider this
issue too lightly,'' Aizawa said in a telephone interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that laws in the United States prohibit non-financial
companies from operating banks. ``Usually the regulators here
always say, `It's done in the U.S., it's done in the U.S,' but in
this case, it is not done in the U.S.,'' Aizawa said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been eagerly anticipating the entrance of new
players into the banking business here in hopes that they would
shake up the staid, clubby world of Japanese banking and bring some
competitiveness to the market. Sony intends to build a bank online,
while Ito-Yokadohas been preparing to add a bank to the many other
services its 7-Eleven convenience store affiliate provides.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate is becoming increasingly politicized. Elections
are looming, and the small- and mid-sized regional banks that might
suffer the most from the competition of Internet banking and other
new entrants are among the most loyal supporters of politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Michio Ochi, the former head of the body that is overseeing the
restructuring of the banking industry here, the Financial
Reconstruction Commission, lost his job for essentially admitting
this relationship. Ochi had suggested that he would intervene on
behalf of bankers if they thought his inspectors were too harsh.
The opposition seized on Ochi's remarks as proof that the ruling
party favors bankers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The brief scandal over Ochi's slip-up has been widely cited as
contributing to the cause of the stroke that felled former Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi earlier this month. Obuchi is hospitalized
and fighting for his life.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Aizawa has worked to raise legitimate questions about allowing
corporations to run banking businesses, and some analysts agree
that the regulators may need to give the subject greater
consideration. ``The point is that the standards have to be
clear,'' said Setsuko Akiba, a banking analyst at Deutsche
Securities in Tokyo. ``Without standards, it is premature to
discuss whether the entry of new players like Sony and Ito-Yokado
is appropriate or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Aizawa and others question whether it is fair to allow other
companies to enter the banking business while circumscribing the
ability of banks to invest in other businesses. ``If we are to
approve the advance of other businesses into banking, then we have
to allow banks to advance into other businesses,'' Aizawa said.
``Unless we do so, we are not establishing equal footing for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he expressed concerns about the government's
responsibilities if a bank controlled by a corporation should
encounter financial difficulties.``The Japanese government has put
trillions of yen into Japanese banks already to shore them up, so
if similar problems occur in banks set up by businesses outside the
banking field, similar obligations could arise,'' he said. ``So our
position is to require the regulators to be very careful about this
issue.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To some extent, though, the regulators have already sanctified
non-bank ownership of banks. In February, the Financial
Reconstruction Commission gave a consortium led by Softbank Corp.
the exclusive right to negotiate to buy the failed Nippon Credit
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Although some banks are expected to participate in the
consortium, Softbank, one of the world's largest Internet
incubators, and Orix Corp., a leasing company, lead the group and
would hold the biggest stakes in Nippon Credit Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Softbank's credit is rated ``speculative'' by
Moody's Investors Service, while both Sony and Ito-Yokado enjoy
very high credit ratings. Questions have been raised about how
regulators can refuse to grant Sony and Ito-Yokado a banking
license if an existing bank is being sold to Softbank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there are a group of companies bidding for Nippon Credit
Bank, so it's a little different,'' Aizawa said, although he noted
that many people were raising that question.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians have already tried to block the Softbank bid, citing
as yet unspecified conflicts of interest relating to its adviser,
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. Goldman, Sachs advised the government on its
sale of the Long-Term Credit Bank, another failed bank, to a group
led by Ripplewood Holdings LLC, a Wall Street investment bank, and
politicians have raised questions about whether Goldman's work on
that deal gave it an unfair advantage in helping the Softbank group
prepare its bid for Nippon Credit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
