<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2403 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TALK-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      04-10 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALK-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL `TALK,' NO ACTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Tues., April 11) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Kronke &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Imagine Howard Stern and Dr. Laura Schlessinger working together _
well, maybe ``working'' and ``together'' wouldn't form the precise
term _ at the same radio station. Not a bad premise, but in ABC's
new comedy ``Talk to Me,'' it's undone by indifferent execution.
</P>
<P>
   Kyra Sedgwick stars as Janey Munro, a shock-jock (at least by
network television's standards-and-practices provisos) who, like
most sitcom characters who are career women at the beginning of a
series, is distraught over the end of a relationship. She has a
coterie of glib supporting players who work on her show, who would
be utterly interchangeable if the casting department didn't provide
helpful, simplistic cues _ cute guy (David Newsom), black guy (Mike
Estime), British guy (Max Baker).
</P>
<P>
   She, alas, also has a nebbishy boss (Peter Jacobson, in but a
very slight variation on Gordon Jump's mild-mannered mealy-mouth on
``WKRP in Cincinnati'') who is roundly held in thrall by Dr. Debra
(Beverly D'Angelo). Dr. Debra's a venomous, morality-spouting
manipulator who's the psychological equivalent of the WWF to her
callers, pile-driving their fragile psyches into the turnbuckles of
her own self-inflicted standards.
</P>
<P>
   You can see where creator-executive producer Suzanne Martin _
who previously worked on ``Frasier,'' also about radio-station egos
_ is going with this, but she's taking her sweet time doing it.
D'Angelo scarcely registers in the first two episodes, and she only
has one brief scene with Sedgwick, whose character is the dominant
one so far but is scarcely interesting enough to carry the series
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick is entertaining as the young woman struggling to
exercise control over her life _ she has a funny scene in tonight's
episode where she wavers between tearful blubbering and exuding
cool machisma during a seduction _ but she's not terribly
convincing as the ``outrageous'' on-air personality. (Her character
wouldn't hold a job long if she routinely conducted interviews as
uninteresting as the one she does tonight, with Kiss' Gene
Simmons.)
</P>
<P>
   D'Angelo doesn't seem to have gotten a peg on her character yet,
either, but then, she hasn't been given much opportunity. But
Martin has already skewed the series such that when the inevitable
clashes do occur, D'Angelo won't have much leverage with the
audience. Holland Taylor would be perfect _ and far more
sympathetic _ in the role, but she's already got a job, on a far
better series, ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week's episode virtually screams flop sweat, as Janey
considers an arbitrary, poorly motivated lesbian fling while her
ditsy sister Kat (Nicole Sullivan) is offered a temporary on-air
job. These are story lines one might expect from an old show
grasping for ideas (Kat's story might be more amusing if viewers
knew the character better), not one fresh out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   Most problematic of all, ``Talk to Me'' could use better talk:
The dialogue basically lacks wit, and when it does have a little
snap, it feels utterly synthetic. The title, ultimately, is ironic,
because no one is trying to listen or, even, be heard; performers
simply seem to be biding time until they can pop off with their
next little self-satisfied wisecrack. The truth-in-advertising _
but admittedly off-putting _ title for this sitcom would be
``Listen to Me.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QL; 
The show: ``Talk to Me.'' &QL; 
What: Sitcom about bickering radio personalities. &QL; 
The stars: Kyra Sedgwick, Beverly D'Angelo. &QL; 
Where: ABC (Channel 7). &QL; 
When: 9:30 tonight. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1521EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
