<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIL-SAFE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY MADE LIVE TV `SAFE'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a measure of what an exceptional piece of material George
Clooney and company were working with that Sunday night's live
production of ``Fail Safe'' on CBS boasted nerve-racking tension
for reasons completely different than the one that no doubt lured
many viewers _ who was going to screw up?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: no one, at least not significantly. There was some
microphone static early on and a sound effect seemed to have a
phone hanging up before the conversation concluded. Get past that,
though, and you had a taut little drama, acted extremely well (with
exceptions) and smartly directed by Stephen Frears (whose current
film ``High Fidelity'' represents the high mark of Y2K cinema), who
cogently linked the disparate stories.
</P>
<P>
   I saw the live East Coast feed and glimpsed portions of the West
Coast feed _ didn't want to miss the ``Sopranos'' finale, after all
- which was ostensibly presented as a kinescope, but except for
changes in image texture that were only perceptible in close-up
shots, the feeds seemed pretty indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer Clooney, out of nostalgia or love for
adrenaline rushes, has a real love for live TV _ he helped convince
NBC to do a live ``ER'' when he was on that series, and has long
stated Sunday night's ``Fail Safe'' as a dream project. Nowadays,
the live aspect is simply a gimmick, but this kind of ``event''
television may be one of the last ways massive audiences can be
assembled to inspire Monday-morning water-cooler quarterbacking in
TV's increasingly fractious world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fail Safe'' is based on a nail-biter of a book (at least
that's my childhood memory) by Eugene Burdick and Harvey Wheeler
that served as an early cautionary wallow in technophobia. The
story takes place during the Cold War, when computer malfunctions
inadvertently send a team of jet fighters carrying nuclear payloads
toward its Moscow target. America alerts Russia to the mistake and,
wishing to avert global nuclear disaster, must resort to
increasingly desperate measures, including sharing crucial military
information with the enemy in an effort to shoot down American
pilots who believe they're heroically serving their country.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's production boasted plenty of fire-power in the
cast, more even than Sidney Lumet's great, original 1964 film it
very closely mimicked. In addition to Clooney, who actually had a
pretty tiny role (along with Don Cheadle, he played a fighter pilot
delivering the deadly payload to Moscow), the presentation featured
Richard Dreyfuss as the president of the United States. In the
film, Henry Fonda handled the role quite memorably and with a sense
of weariness and common decency _ Dreyfuss interpreted the part
more urgently but didn't resort to histrionics, which can't always
be said of him.
</P>
<P>
   High marks also go to Brian Dennehy, a commanding presence in
the U.S. war room as Gen. Bogan, and Noah Wyle, who brought moments
of exquisite subtlety to his role as the president's translator,
Buck (played by a very young Larry Hagman in the original). Harvey
Keitel seemed kind of wooden as Blackie, the military officer
closely allied to the president but suffering from nightmares; Hank
Azaria's hawkish Professor Groteschele was written so
one-dimensionally that his scenes with Keitel were pretty much lost
causes (Walter Matthau managed the role with greater aplomb in
'64).
</P>
<P>
   With a running time a good half-hour shorter than the film
version, a lot of the texture was inevitably whittled away (which
severely truncated the tragic emotional resonance of Blackie's
character). Hence, we leaped more directly into the conflict, and
there was a fair amount of baldly expository dialogue. But this
also made for a lean, mean production that didn't have much time
for noodling around and therefore simply kept ratcheting up the
tension.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, this production didn't have a war-room colonel
flip out and attack Gen. Bogan, as happens in the film. On the
debit side, it brought in a child to make a manipulative pleading
dispatch to the fighter pilots as they approached Moscow. (On the
other hand, the character of the wife brought in for the film was
more shrill than the kid, so this difference probably registers as
neutral.) Frears, alas, wasn't able to match the devastating impact
of the original's finale, though he likely was plenty successful
for folks who haven't seen the earlier incarnation.
</P>
<P>
   One quibble: In a bid to make a political statement, the
production at evening's end listed all the countries that have
nuclear capability. Given the story's main premise, wouldn't it
have been just as relevant to list the countries with crummy
computer systems? &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Fail Safe.'' &QL; 
What: Live television adaptation of the cold-war thriller by Eugene
Burdick and Harvey Wheeler. &QL; 
The stars: Richard Dreyfuss, Noah Wyle, George Clooney, Brian
Dennehy, Don Cheadle, Sam Elliott, Harvey Keitel, Hank Azaria,
James Cromwell. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
