<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ENVIRONMENTALISTS SEEK TO STALL NEW CALIFORNIA CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERCED, Calif. _ Opposition to locating the University of
California system's 10th campus in the grasslands north of Merced
is coalescing around the issue of protecting thousands of vernal
pools.
</P>
<P>
   Vernal pools _ puddles that form and linger after rain _ are the
habitat for many rare species of flora and fauna, such as fairy
shrimp. The 10,300-acre UC-Merced campus planning area is the
largest unfragmented vernal pool site in California.
</P>
<P>
   The timetable calls for groundbreaking by the summer or early
fall of 2001 and the beginning of classes, with a first-year
student body of 1,000, in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   But before the first shovel full of dirt is turned, university
officials and Merced County will have to navigate a permitting
process daunting in scope and complexity.
</P>
<P>
   Separate environmental reviews are under way by UC-Merced
officials and Merced County, which is also revising its general
plan to factor in an entire new residential community of 30,000
people adjoining the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the works are a Clean Water Act study that will require
approval by both the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the
Environmental Protection Agency as well as a long-term regional
conservation plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long process, and we're all scrambling because the
governor wants to get it started,'' said Elizabeth Borowiec, who is
monitoring the university campus project for the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   Merced planning chief Clifford Graves is hopeful that the
permits prerequisite to groundbreaking will be in hand by next
summer. The campus has the support of Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat,
and Vice President Al Gore, who has vowed to put federal
environmental approval on a fast track.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Burke, a Modesto environmental advocate and spokesman
for a new coalition, Protect Our Water, said the timetable is too
ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of process, they're barely at square one,'' said
Burke, 50, who ran a backpacking store in Davis before taking up
full-time environmental advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   UC-Merced is Davis' pet higher education project. Nevertheless,
Burke maintains that ``there is a serious issue here that they just
can't gloss over.''
</P>
<P>
   To drill in the point, the Protect Our Water organization has
hired a law firm, which has warned the University of California and
Merced County officials that until a Clean Water Act permit is
obtained, spending money on the campus site is ``inappropriate and
should cease.'' The university system does not yet have title to
the property.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers still awaits the university
system's application for the Clean Water Act permit, said spokesman
Jason Fansellau. The Corps' analysis will ``include looking at a
completely separate location'' for the campus if the size of the
proposed campus cannot be minimized.
</P>
<P>
   The next budget proposed by Davis includes $24.3 million for the
UC-Merced campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environmental issues talked about are very well known and
documented, and we have been working diligently to address them,''
Graves said. ``We have made a commitment to treading lightly on the
land and being environmentally responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   As for potential legal problems, ``we are confident at this
point that we have an approach that will be approved'' by both the
courts and regulatory agencies, Graves said.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Samuelson, senior associate to the chancellor and director
emeritus of University of California's Natural Reserve System, said
that the comprehensive university and county planning process now
under way will maximize preservation of the site's ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   And while there are at least 7,000 vernal pools in the
10,300-acre planning area, ``only 3 to 7 percent of the pools are
on the 2,000-acre campus site,'' he said. About 3,000 of the
remaining 8,300 acres will be developed for residential and
commercial uses, with the rest left in open space.
</P>
<P>
   Samuelson acknowledged that university officials still have some
missionary work to do with environmentalists, including faculty
members, if they are to meet the governor's timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Samuelson and other UC-Merced officials toured the campus site
with eight biologists and environmental scientists from other
campuses on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Brent Mischler, director of UC-Berkeley's Jepson
Herbarium, whose field is integrated biology. ``We wanted to
volunteer our expertise to the planners . . . to help them make
decisions (with) politically neutral advice,'' Mishler said.
</P>
<P>
   Samuelson acknowledged that faculty criticism needs to be dealt
with and expressed the hopes that critics will ``come around on
some of their views'' when they're fully backgrounded on plans for
the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Although the site selection process for the system's 10th campus
began in 1988 and culminated in 1995 with the selection of the
Merced site, some critics believe that the environmental
sensitivity of the site was insufficiently publicized.
</P>
<P>
   Mischler conceded that serious criticism of the site selected
comes late in the game. ``We can't blame the administration
entirely for that,'' he said. ``When the process was going on, no
one was too concerned, probably because we were really busy. ...
But now the biology faculty of the university is concerned about
it. We want to do this right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tehipite chapter of the Sierra Club opposes the Merced site.
``It's a sprawl-inducing site,'' said Shannon Eddy, acting director
of the state office of the Sierra Club in Sacramento. ``They want
to build a six-lane parkway over land with nothing on it now except
the most pristine vernal pool site in California.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all greed development with the university as the
centerpiece, just like UC-Irvine,'' said Jeanne Larson, president
of the California Native Plant Society's Fresno chapter. ``It's one
of the most beautiful and last places where we have these vernal
pools and pristine conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Tolson, steward of five Northern California natural
reserves for the University of California system, said opponents of
the Merced campus site are battling uphill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's highly unlikely they're going to change their minds, but
it needs to be said that that's a stupid place to put it, to
destroy something pristine that's already there,'' Tolson aid.
``From a strictly ecological view, there are plenty of places where
a new university could be situated,'' such as the abandoned Castle
Air Force Base near Merced, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
