<SLUG> BC-LAREDO-BRIDGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW BRIDGE TO EASE CONGESTION IN HOT BORDER CROSSING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BONNIE PFISTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ This border city, perennially congested by
18-wheelers that are the telltale sign of the booming trade between
the United States and Mexico, is getting a break from gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, a new crossing will open and cargo trucks will be
prohibited from using either downtown span over the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to cross the river like we'd cross any street to go to
a restaurant or to visit our friends,'' said Laredo Mayor Betty
Flores, a lifelong resident. ``We used to do that all day long
every day as if it were nothing. Now it's a chore.''
</P>
<P>
   With the new $60 million World Trade Bridge, the adjacent
infrastructure and federal port facilities, city leaders hope to
relieve much of the downtown congestion.
</P>
<P>
   As of Saturday, cargo trucks will be rerouted at the Bob Bullock
Loop interchange, eight miles north of downtown, and shunted onto a
new highway to the new bridge.
</P>
<P>
   There, the trucks can snake along five miles of winding drives
well away from commuters and tourists who have borne the costs of
the North American Free Trade Agreement, which also has brought
many benefits to this city of 185,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA, which lowered tariffs on goods bought and sold among the
United States, Mexico and Canada, took effect on Jan. 1, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the city's bridges have seen the number of truck
crossings double, reaching 1.3 million last year. With booming
commercial transportation needs have come breathtaking population
growth _ the second-fastest in the nation _ and new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Laredo has been lifted out of the
double-digit unemployment doldrums that plague America's southwest
border. The jobless rate fell to 8.1 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   Trade has been so good for Laredo that the city effectively
loaned Washington the money to build the port surrounding the new
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The General Services Administration will pay the city $18
million annually for 20 years, acting City Manager Cynthia Collazo
said.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth international crossing is planned within 10 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1540EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0159 </DOCNO>
