<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN DEMOCRATS NAME NEW LEADER AS THEY BATTLE KOHL SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESSEN, Germany _ Angela Merkel, a woman raised in a communist
system, took control Monday of the Christian Democratic Union , the
conservative movement that has dominated post-war German politics
but now faces a crisis over its finances and its identity.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democratic Union is not about to implode as its
sister party did in Italy during the 1990's. Although battered by a
financial scandal over the past four months, the party has shown
itself to be too close to the conservative German soul, too
essential to block the emergence of a nationalist right and too
central to Germany's democracy itself.
</P>
<P>
   But it was quickly clear at a three-day party congress here that
began Sunday that the Christian Democrats face problems far deeper
than the slush fund scandal that has tarnished the reputation of
former Chancellor Helmut Kohl to the point that he has chosen not
to appear at this meeting. He had not missed a party congress since
1951.
</P>
<P>
   Merkel, a 45-year-old physicist who spent most of her life in
the former East Germany, is determined to craft what she has called
a ``new beginning.'' She was overwhelmingly elected leader Monday
by party delegates here, bringing a fresh face, a beguiling manner
and a steely determination to an enormous task.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Ms. Merkel is about a new style in politics, one that
is direct, honest and clear,'' said Hannelore Heuser, a party
member from southern Germany. ``That is the most drastic and
significant change after what we now perceive as the dangerous
murkiness of the Kohl system.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the honeymoon wears off, Merkel's clear-eyed gaze and
frank talk may not be enough to overcome the crisis she faces. Put
bluntly, the Christian Democratic party _ now in opposition after
16 years in power under Kohl _ no longer knows what it is, and it
is broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zur Sache'' _ ``back to business'' _ screamed the slogans
here, an attempt to signal that the fallout from the uncovering of
tens of millions of dollars in party funds in Swiss bank accounts
and illegal campaign contributions is over.
</P>
<P>
   But with communism gone and little socialism left to fight,
religion ever less significant in German society, and the governing
Social Democrats busy showing their centrist credentials by
slashing taxes and promoting the interests of large companies, the
remaining business of the Christian Democrats remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party no longer has a broad and integrating idea for our
post-socialist and increasingly post-Christian society,'' commented
Tobias Duerr in the influential weekly Die Zeit. Its support has
fallen from traditional postwar levels of over 40 percent to under
35 percent _ still the backing of a mass party but not enough to
win national elections.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The most frequent image evoked here to suggest the party's
future was that of a bridge. Delegate after delegate used it to
suggest a movement that will represent globalization and the
fatherland, modernity and community, managers and workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the party of the social-market economy and we will
remain so even in this time of globalization,'' said Juergen
Ruettgers, who is fighting an uphill battle to dislodge the Social
Democrats in an election in the state of North Rhine-Westphalia
next month. ``We are the bridge between the market and human
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Picking up a similar theme, Norbert Blum, a former labor
minister under Kohl, thundered: ``I can't drink a beer on the
Internet. We still need our social state, our good-neighborliness,
our hands outstretched to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is that Christian Democracy does not look much like
a bridge today. Germany's ponderous social-market, consensus-based,
postwar model is cracking, and the shifting, fast-moving
shareholding culture of the ``new economy'' is taking hold. The
party's response is divided, for it created the model that is now
dying.
</P>
<P>
   Some on the right of the party favor a wholehearted embrace of a
fiercely competitive model free of the heavy costs of welfare;
others, among them Merkel, say the essence of the German social
insurance system must be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Certain officials, like Ruettgers, see political capital in an
anti-immigrant message at a time of fears over global economic
pressures. Others, like Merkel, say such an approach is
counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   Friedrich Merz, the 44-year-old new leader of the party's
faction in parliament, says his generation is tired of being held
responsible for Germany's Nazi past and bitterly attacks the
government for isolating Austria because of the presence of Joerg
Haider's rightist party in the government. Others, including the
new general secretary, Ruprecht Polenz, warn that ``it is critical
that we not drift to the right.''
</P>
<P>
   In a much-applauded speech, Merkel tried hard Monday to dismiss
such divisions. ``It is precisely because we unite
Christian-Social, conservative and liberal convictions that we are
the broad people's party of the center,'' she said. Looking back at
Europe's unification and Germany's, she said the party was
``history's winner.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that many currents have always flowed through
Christian Democracy, and the party's contribution to peace and
integration in Europe has been enormous. But the world has changed,
and the Social Democrats of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder have
declared themselves the ``new middle'' and occupied the center
ground once held by Christian Democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the middle, there is now a huge overlap between the two big
parties, and that is a considerable problem for us,'' said Lothar
Hegemann, an insurance broker, Christian Democrat for three decades
and delegate from Duesseldorf. ``Germans do not like changes of
government, and I fear that unless Mr. Schroeder makes a big
mistake, he probably has the next election in 2002 sewn up.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the Christian Democrats' problems in fighting that
election was evident here at the austere opening-night dinner _
cold ham, potato salad and cabbage. The smoked fish, the roast
duck, the vast array of delicacies that marked the flush feasts
during Kohl's rule were gone, victims of financial hardship.
</P>
<P>
   Matthias Wissmann, the treasurer, said the party faces an annual
deficit of over $8 million and will have to cut personnel, rent out
part of its new Berlin headquarters and shrink its publications.
</P>
<P>
   Only with exceptional contributions from party members, he
added, will the means be found to overcome the results of lax
financial management and a $21 million fine imposed for illegal
acts by Kohl and other party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every crisis is an opportunity,'' Merkel said Monday. But the
crisis is deep, and the opportunities still unclear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1544EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
