<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2430 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-POST-IT-TRIBUTE-TEX     04-10 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POST-IT-TRIBUTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRIBUTE TO THE POST-IT NOTE ON ITS 20TH ANNIVERSARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am a Post-it Note junkie. Phone numbers, grocery lists,
messages of vital importance to the spouse (''Call travel agent re:
trip to Fiji!''). At work, I am running out of stickable spots for
these eminently addicting communication devices. There are
currently 19 Post-its applied haphazardly around my work station:
basic reminders (''Pay rent''), important phone numbers (''Computer
guy x.7658''), and cryptic minimemos to which even I can no longer
assign meaning (''13816 Star, 109 pg.''). In desperate times, I
occasionally stick Post-its to myself.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting in this electronic age that Post-it Notes,
which require setting pen to paper, continue to gain popularity.
But 20 years after they were first introduced to pushpin-weary
Americans, Post-its still cling _ lightly and conveniently _ to the
popular landscape.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1. Eureka!
</P>
<P>
   Spencer Silver calls it a ``classic case of serendipity.'' In
1968, Silver, a scientist for the research and technology company
3M, was trying to create a water-soluble adhesive. He devised an
experiment that, well, flopped, but it resulted in a new and
curious adhesive, one that stuck readily but not tightly to
surfaces. Under the microscope, the adhesive's uniform spheres
``kind of sparkled in the light,'' Silver says. He embarked on a
search with his 3M colleagues for a way to use the new invention.
(3M is the same company that gave us Scotch tape and the clothing
insulator Thinsulate.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   2. Aha!
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later, Art Fry, an employee in 3M's retail-tape
division, is a member of his church choir. But sometime between
Wednesday practice and Sunday service, the bookmark flagging that
week's hymns falls out. ``I was trying to find my place, and the
sermon was a little dull that day, so I thought, I wonder if I
could make a bookmark that would stay in place?'' Fry, who had been
a new-product developer at 3M for 20 years, remembers his colleague
Silver's earlier discovery and high-tails it back to the lab. He
applies the adhesive to the back of his bookmark. Hurray! It
sticks! It comes off! It sticks again!
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   3. The idea sticks
</P>
<P>
   Fry tries the bookmarks out on his colleagues. ``They thought it
was cool but they didn't use any,'' he says. Then, one day, Fry is
writing a report. He flags a page and jots a note on the sticky
bookmark with an arrow pointing to the text. Wait a minute, he
thinks, I can write on this sticky paper?! Within a week, Fry has a
revamped prototype, and his colleagues catch Post-it Note fever.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   4. Consumers take note
</P>
<P>
   Marketing the sticky pads takes time. 3M calls the invention a
``repositionable note'' in brochures and ads, and consumers seem
confused. So in 1978 3M inundates Boise, Idaho, with Post-its,
handing out thousands of samples (3M now refers to that event the
as the ``Boise Blitz''). Ninety percent of the people who try the
product say they will buy it themselves. In 1980, Post-its goes
national.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   5. Sticker shock
</P>
<P>
   A direct-mail campaign to Fortune 500 CEOs results in a letter
back to 3M from Lee Iacocca, who loves the sticky-notes concept.
Back then, the original Post-its are called ``Press and Peel''
notes, and the 3-inch-by-5-inch pad sells for 98 cents. By 1990,
they were called Post-it Notes.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   6. Happily ever after
</P>
<P>
   Post-it fame didn't really change the lives of Silver and Fry
(well, maybe a little: ``People started listening to me in the
lab,'' laughs Silver). Neither got rich from the invention (which
is the property of the company), but it has ``earned us a lot of
respect within 3M.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver retired in 1996 after 30 years with the company and 22
U.S. patents to his name (he worked on the technology behind
box-sealing tape for a while). Fry, semiretired, lectures around
the world was named by Esquire magazine as one of ``The 100 Best
People in the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the introduction of Post-its, numerous companies have
copied the ``repositionable note'' idea.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TRUE STORIES
</P>
<P>
   A Minnesota woman once bribed a Russian official, whose
signature she needed to approve an adoption, by furnishing the
official with Post-it pads and some pens.
</P>
<P>
   A sleepy traveler in the Atlanta airport, not wanting to doze
off and miss his flight, decorated himself with Post-it Notes
asking fellow travelers to ``Please wake me for the 8:35 a.m.
flight to Savannah. Thank you.'' It worked.
</P>
<P>
   The wife of scientist Silver applies Post-its on their home's
sliding glass doors, so guests don't walk into them.
</P>
<P>
   Fry, the 3M product developer, affixes Post-its to his tie when
he eats airplane meals: ``Voila!'' Post-it bib!
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE USES
</P>
<P>
   Decorate a newlywed's car.
</P>
<P>
   Make a cartoon flip book.
</P>
<P>
   Label leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Use for New Year's resolutions reminders and ``quit smoking''
reminders
</P>
<P>
   Keep cats busy by sticking Post-its to their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Make price tags for garage-sale items.
</P>
<P>
   Play Pin the Post-it on the Donkey.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Post''-modern
</P>
<P>
   Alaskan artist Melynda Schwier-Gierard uses up to 60,000 Post-it
Notes in each of her wall-sized panels, folding and applying the
Post-its in intricate designs.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide
</P>
<P>
   Post-it Notes come in 27 sizes, 56 shapes and 50 colors, and are
sold in 100 countries. In Japan and China, consumers prefer their
Post-its as small narrow strips instead of larger horizontal pads.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Wide world
</P>
<P>
   It would take approximately 506.9 million Post-it Notes (the
27/8-inch square ones) to circle the globe.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
