<HEADLINE>
THE WORD THAT HAS BEEN BANISHED AT THE WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 16)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Certain words and phrases become taboo in the White House.  &UR; Out
of the loop &LR; ,  &UR; amiable dunce &LR; ,  &UR; malaise &LR;  and  &UR; crook &LR;  come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton White House, we are told by Glenn Burkins of The
Wall Street Journal, is eager to make clear that it is ``not being
driven by a quest to establish'' Clinton's  &UR; legacy &LR; . The
interviewer reports that John Podesta, the chief of staff, ``has
banned the use of that word in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the word, in its political sense, is most often
being used in derision. ``The Clintons'  &UR; legacy &LR; ,'' wrote The St.
Petersburg Times as far back as 1996, ``will be the attack and
invasion of our justice system by social entrepreneurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the columnist Stephen Chapman pronounced,
``Clinton's  &UR; legacy &LR;  is likely to be the enduring diminution of the
office he holds.'' In that year, the New York Times columnist
Maureen Dowd suggested that ``Bill Clinton's biggest  &UR; legacy &LR;  may
not be in politics, but in letters .... He has inspired one
entirely new and remarkable genre: feminist erotic journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   More charitably, Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida recently said that
free trade ``is a place where Clinton can legitimately say that he
has a  &UR; legacy &LR; .'' And when asked by a reporter, ``How much of the
president's  &UR; legacy &LR;  is dependent on peace in Ireland and in the
Middle East?'' the White House spokesman Joe Lockhart replied,
``His  &UR; legacy &LR;  will be decided, thankfully, not by us and not by
any of the people who are scribbling in notebooks.''
</P>
<P>
   That official rejection of  &UR; legacy &LR; -itis may have led to the
banning of the word itself in White House usage. Podesta probably
winced when President Clinton, at a recent fund-raising gathering
of American Indians, deplored U.S. negligence of their rights,
adding, ``This is the part of the historical  &UR; legacy &LR;  we want to be
proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it was not in the context of Clinton's own historical
bequest to the American people and could thus not be construed as a
violation of the ban.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin  &UR; legare &LR;  means ``to dispute'' and ``to bequeath,''
which is fitting when you consider how many bequests are disputed.
Not in dispute, however, is the 1460 coinage by Robert Henryson,
who writes of a widow's `` &UR; legacy &LR;  and lamentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its ban, watch for what is sure to be the most overused
word of the coming interregnum. An unwanted gift from a
predecessor, parent or older sibling is derogated as a
 &UR; hand-me-down &LR; ; a happier, lasting bequest is called  &UR; a legacy with
legs &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   BOLD INITIATIVE
</P>
<P>
   Readers who enjoyed the exhaustive exegesis in this space of Al
Gore's use of  &UR; risky tax scheme &LR;  were promised a similar study of
favored words of his opponent, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   We have an entry culled from a column by Gail Collins in The New
York Times, wherein my colleague wondered ``whether Gore is right
in charging that the Bush tax plan is `risky,' or Bush is more
correct in dubbing it `bold.'''
</P>
<P>
   As far back as 1997, the governor described his tax plan to the
Texas Legislature as ``this complex,  &UR; bold &LR; , aggressive plan.'' The
Dallas Morning News promptly hailed his `` &UR; bold &LR;  tax plan.'' In a
presidential primary debate in New Hampshire late last year, Bush
described his tax proposal as ``a good,  &UR; bold &LR; , practical plan.''
One of his early competitors, Sen. Orrin Hatch, later saluted the
Bush proposal to reduce taxes by $483 billion over five years as
`` &UR; bold &LR;  but responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's qualifier _ ``but responsible'' _ was intended to strip
any possible riskiness out of the Bush plan (or, as Gore keeps
deriding it, ``scheme''). It indicates the senator's subtle
awareness of the adjective's ability to trouble the easily daunted.
</P>
<P>
   The word, of Teutonic origin and first spelled  &UR; bealde &LR; ,
appeared in Old English about the end of the first millennium.
Shakespeare, in 1593, felt it necessary to place it near a synonym:
``when their brave hope,  &UR; bold &LR;  Hector, marched to field.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as the meaning of ``brave'' took firm hold, Shakespeare
recognized that the word had acquired a different sense, of
``overly audacious, too forward'': In his 1605 ``King Lear,'' he
wrote of ``men so disordered, so deboshed and  &UR; bold &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bold &LR; , applied to a person, today connotes ``pushy,'' sometimes
``fearless,'' but on the edge of ``reckless''; applied to an idea,
however, the connotation is slightly stronger than  &UR; audacious &LR;  and
just short of  &UR; courageous &LR; . It's better to have  &UR; bold &LR;  ideas than
timid ones.
</P>
<P>
   But watch out for cliche fusion: The Dow Jones database spits
out 1,802 hits in the past decade on  &UR; bold initiative &LR; . William
Godwin coined  &UR; initiative &LR;  in 1793 to mean ``the first step in some
enterprise'' and (prefiguring debate in the art world centuries
later) wrote, ``Sensation ... possesses the  &UR; initiative &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   The overuse of  &UR; bold &LR;  to modify Godwin's word vitiates its
potency. An alternative to  &UR; initiative &LR;  is  &UR; undertaking &LR; , but that
may have fallen by the wayside as the managers of funerals became
known as  &UR; undertakers &LR; . (They now prefer  &UR; morticians &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bold &LR;  suffered a decline in use for some years ( &UR; brave,
undaunted &LR;  and  &UR; intrepid &LR;  were preferred) but made a comeback in
the great example of the split infinitive of our time: the ``Star
Trek'' plan ``to  &UR; boldly  &LR; go where no man has gone before.'' In
``Star Trek: The Next Generation,'' the  &UR; man &LR;  was changed to  &UR; one &LR; ;
that was a  &UR; bold initiative &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
