<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSE'S LONGEST TAIL  
 CLEANING UP THE PASTURES  
 FRESH START FOR STOMACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comet Hyakutake, which was many people's choice for Best
Astronomical Phenomenon of 1996 (Naked Eye Division), has now taken
a new honor: Longest Tail of All Time.
</P>
<P>
   In two studies in the journal Nature, researchers from Britain,
the United States, Switzerland and Germany report that Hyakutake,
which graced the skies for about three months that year, had a tail
that was 350 million miles long, or almost four times the distance
of the Earth from the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   This far outstrips the previous record-holder, the Great March
Comet of 1843, which had a tail that was twice the Earth-Sun
distance.
</P>
<P>
   The Hyakutake measurement was obtained through a happy accident:
the Ulysses spacecraft, launched in 1990 to study the solar wind
from above and below the plane of Earth's orbit, happened to wander
through the tail on May 1, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   On that date, the spacecraft's instruments recorded some odd
measurements, including variations in the structure of the solar
wind's magnetic field. The data eventually led the researchers to
suspect that the spacecraft was within the tail of a comet (a comet
tail consists of gases that have been ionized by solar radiation).
They determined that the comet was Hyakutake by analyzing its
position relative to the spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers estimated that at the 350-million-mile distance,
Hyakutake's tail had a cross-section of about four million miles.
Not bad for a dirty piece of ice and rock that is less than two
miles in diameter. The finding also has implications for the
ability of future spacecraft to detect unseen comets. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Cow pie'' is a quaint term, to be sure, but there is precious
little else that is quaint about cow manure. For one thing, it can
contain strains of E. coli bacteria that, if they get on fruits or
vegetables or in the water supply, can harm people. Composted
manure is generally safe (having been heat-treated by the high
temperatures generated in the composting process), but raw manure
that is spread on fields or gardens as fertilizer can be a source
of E. coli contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Now, scientists at Cornell and the Agricultural Research Service
(part of the federal Department of Agriculture) have found a
promising alternative way to kill microbes in manure. The solution,
they say, is to add sodium carbonate, also known as washing soda.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who reported on their work in the journal
Environmental Science and Technology, made the finding when they
mixed urine and manure. Dairy cows usually produce twice as much
manure as urine, but when the researchers mixed them in equal
amounts they noticed that most of the bacteria in the manure was
eventually killed. They identified carbonate, produced through the
action of an enzyme in the manure on urea in the urine, as the
bacteria-killer.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggest that much additional study of the idea
on farms _ not in a lab _ is needed. But they said that adding
sodium carbonate to manure ponds or tanks could ultimately prove to
be an inexpensive way of reducing the bacteria problem. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The behavior of the thornback ray, a marine creature found in
European waters, adds new meaning to the term ``gut wrenching.''
According to researchers in Britain, the ray responds to a tainted
meal by rinsing the stomach, extruding it through the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   While people may only (italics)feel(end italics) like their
stomach has been turned inside out after a case of food poisoning,
say, the ray can actually perform such a feat. It then shakes the
stomach from side to side in the water, like a dirty dishrag. This,
the researchers report in Nature, apparently removes indigestible
bits of food or other offending particles. The whole process is
very quick, taking only about four seconds. If you're lucky, you'll
miss it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
