<HEADLINE>
`TALK TO ME' MAKES ABC LOOK REALLY, REALLY DUMB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: D  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As satire, ``Talk to Me'' is brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   But word on the street is that it's not satire. It's supposed to
be funny in the straight-on, ha-ha sense, not in the wink-wink,
nudge-nudge sense.
</P>
<P>
   Pity. If it were poking fun at situation comedy, critics would
be singing hosannas. Instead, that sound you hear is wailing, and
possibly even some gnashing of teeth, brought on by ABC's
unbelievable, monumental, criminally negligent stupidity at taking
``Sports Night'' off the air in favor of this piece of uninspired
offal.
</P>
<P>
   Surely someone at ABC knows this show is dreadful. Or is
everyone over there so caught up in the success of ``Who Wants To
Be a Millionaire'' that no one is screening the rest of the stuff
being extruded from the back room where they keep Regis Philbin's
dark shirts?
</P>
<P>
   There's no good reason for ``Talk to Me'' to be on the air.
Period. It is not funny. It is not imaginative. And, as comedy sets
go, it is not even all that pleasant to look at.
</P>
<P>
   Kyra Sedgwick, apparently a graduate of the Trying Too Hard
School of Comedy, is the star of this dud. She also is one of five
executive producers, which may help explain why it's such a mess.
Sedgwick plays Janey Munro, the irreverent, wise-cracking host of a
radio talk show in New York City. She has a couple of studio
sidekicks, a wacky sibling, and if this is starting to sound like a
female facsimile of ``Frasier,'' you're more astute than the folks
at ABC, who evidently don't watch much TV. (The show's creator,
Suzanne Martin, is a former ``Frasier'' hand.)
</P>
<P>
   The premise is that Janey's life away from the station provides
the material for her show, so in tonight's premiere we see her
trying to deal with a recent breakup by ``taking it like a man.''
Next week, she dabbles in homosexuality, just to make sure she's
not missing something by taking it from a woman. On someone else's
show, both episodes might be amusing, but on ``Talk to Me'' they're
more offensive than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Guest stars who used to be famous _ Gene Simmons tonight,
Paulina Porizkova next week _ add that special sense of
desperation. Beverly D'Angelo, as a socially conservative
psychologist-of-the-air and Janey's nemesis, adds the crowning
touch of someone who looks about as comfortable in this project as
a Republican on ``The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance of ``MAD TV'' alumna Nicole Sullivan, who plays
Janey's unemployed sister, Kat, is the funniest thing about ``Talk
to Me,'' which might be a lesson for ABC: Instead of casting
big-name actresses in a comedy, try hiring funny ones.
</P>
<P>
   `Fail Safe' not a failure
</P>
<P>
   It helps to have been a child of the Cold War, but CBS's
``live'' broadcast of ``Fail Safe'' Sunday night was the sort of
theater TV used to be famous for and that viewers of any age should
applaud.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it wasn't perfect. Lines were flubbed, camera shots seemed
oddly selected and some of the acting _ e.g., Harvey Keitel's _ was
overwrought. But other performances, most notably Brian Dennehy's
as Gen. Bogan, Hank Azzaria's as a scary academician and Sam
Elliott's as a bombastic congressman, were on the mark, proving
that while live dramatic television is indeed a crap shoot it is
something worth encouraging as networks look for new and different
ways to attract viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer/star George Clooney chose ``Fail Safe''
because the original 1964 film about the erroneous deployment of a
U.S. Air Force nuclear-bomber squadron over the Soviet Union is his
favorite movie, and he wanted something that fit the look and feel
of 1950s live television.
</P>
<P>
   I'd call it a qualified success. Ideas for next time: Forget
black and white; pick a more timely topic.
</P>
<P>
   Odds 'n' ends
</P>
<P>
   OK, ABC isn't completely stupid. It has renewed ``Once and
Again,'' a drama about relationships after divorce, for next
season. ``The Practice'' and ``NYPD Blue'' also will be back for a
fifth and eighth season, respectively. ... ``NYPD Blue'' will have
to get along without Andrea Thompson, who is leaving the series
after this season to try her hand as a news anchor at KRQE-TV in
Albuquerque. Thompson, who plays Detective Jill Kirkendall, has no
journalism experience. ... NBC has renewed ``The West Wing'' for a
second season. ... This year's fall season will begin later than
normal because of the Summer Olympics. Nielsen Media Research, the
company that measures TV viewership, says it will start the fall
season no sooner than Oct. 2 _ a victory for every network except
NBC, which is televising the Olympics and hoped to use the expected
ratings surge as a fall springboard. But Nielsen decided it was
fairer to have the Olympics coverage, scheduled Sept. 15 to Oct. 1,
to fall outside fall.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Me. Half-hour comedy series about an irreverent radio
talk-show host. Starring Kyra Sedgwick, Nicole Sullivan, Max Baker,
David Newsom, Mike Estime, Peter Jacobson and Beverly D'Angelo.
Series premiere Tuesday night on ABC. Parental guideline rating:
TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
