<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2457 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-     04-10 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: BREAKING THE CYCLE OF SEASONAL SNEEZES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are you filled with dread instead of delight about the arrival
of spring, anticipating the sneezes, runny nose and itchy eyes that
are the hallmarks of seasonal allergic rhinitis? Well, suffer no
more. There is now a wide array of treatments, over the counter and
prescription, that can suppress the annoying symptoms of spring
(and fall) allergies, which can interfere with sleep, work and
enjoyment of life and increase your vulnerability to colds,
sinusitis and other respiratory infections.
</P>
<P>
   You are hardly alone. Ten to 30 percent of Americans are
allergic to wind-swept pollen from trees, grasses, weeds and/or
molds. In spring, you can blame such trees as alder, ash, birch,
cedar, elm, hazel, maple, oak, olive, pecan, sycamore and walnut.
In summer, common allergens include grasses like timothy, ryegrass,
Bermuda grass, English plantain and sheep sorrel. And, of course,
there's fall, with pollen from ragweed, sage and Russian thistle
the common culprits.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the allergy season is year-round, the result of
continuous contact with mold spores, dust mites, feathers, pet
dander or cigarette smoke. But whether your symptoms are seasonal
or perennial, there is now likely to be an effective treatment that
can curb your misery with a minimum of side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Allergies are signs of an immune system run amok. Instead of
attacking only the body's enemies, it mounts an all-out assault
against innocent substances called allergens, which are almost
always proteins. In tissues that have contact with the outside
world (like the lining of the nose and breathing tubes and eyes),
mast cells that are storehouses of histamine and other protective
chemicals spew forth their ammunition when ``danger'' strikes in
the form of an allergen to which you are sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   The mast cells are ``told'' to begin their attacks by antibodies
called IgE, which the body mistakenly produces when exposed to
particular allergens. Unlike most other short-lived antibodies, IgE
antibodies can hang around for years, ready to set off an allergic
response the next time you are exposed to that same allergen.
</P>
<P>
   The cascade of histamine and other substances cause itching,
sneezing and runny nose, usually within minutes of exposure to the
offending allergen. As if that were not bothersome enough, some 6
to 12 hours later come the delayed symptoms: nasal congestion and a
heightened sensitivity to the particular allergen and to irritants
like scents and tobacco smoke.
</P>
<P>
   You can minimize your exposure to troublesome airborne allergens
by keeping windows closed, using air-conditioning at home and in
the car, showering and washing your hair nightly, staying indoors
when pollen counts are high, wearing glasses outdoors, finding
someone else to cut the lawn and hedges and using a high-efficiency
air cleaner in the rooms where you spend the most time (especially
the bedroom). If such measures are not possible or are inadequate
at keeping your allergic symptoms at bay, there is a veritable army
of treatments you might try.
</P>
<P>
   NASAL SPRAY _ Cromolyn sodium, sold over the counter as
Nasalcrom, is a highly effective nonsteroidal drug that can stop
nasal allergic reactions before they start by stabilizing mast
cells and preventing the release of histamine. Start using it
before allergy season and continue until exposure to the offending
allergens has ended. It is extremely safe, even for children,
pregnant women and the elderly, but it is underused, probably
because it must be administered four to six times a day for maximum
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Intranasal corticosteroids are also seriously underused,
according to doctors who specialize in allergy treatment. These
safe and effective sprays are considered the most potent weapons
against allergic rhinitis, and because they are used topically,
they do not cause symptoms associated with oral or injected
steroids. Popular products, which are available only by
prescription, include Flonase, Nasonex and Rhinocort-AQ, which need
to be used only once a day.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment with nasal steroids is best started now, before
allergy season is in full bloom. These drugs combat the delayed
response of nasal congestion as well as itching, sneezing and runny
nose. They do not, however, always relieve itchy eyes. Their main
side effect is nasal irritation, which can be prevented by spraying
straight up toward the sinuses, avoiding exposure to the nasal
lining as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But the American College of Allergy, Asthma and Immunology warns
against the use of steroid injections for seasonal allergies.
Although these injections provide relief for weeks, they are far
more hazardous than the nasal sprays.
</P>
<P>
   Other nasal products include Atrovent, which can dry up a runny
nose but has no effect on other allergy symptoms, and saline nasal
sprays (Ocean, NaSal and Salinex), useful in relieving nasal
congestion and sneezing. But avoid using nasal sprays containing
oxymetazoline (Afrin, for example) for more than three days because
longer use can cause rebound congestion.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIHISTAMINES _ As you would guess from the name, these drugs
block the action of histamine and thus are most effective if taken
preventively, before you develop allergic symptoms. Older products
like Dimetane, Chlor-Trimeton and Tavist are available over the
counter. These nonprescription drugs tend to induce drowsiness,
though less so than diphenhydramine, which is the main ingredient
in Benadryl. To counter the sedating effects and to combat nasal
congestion, some of these products are sold in combination with a
decongestant like pseudoephedrine or phenylpropanolamine, which act
as stimulants.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, the newer prescription antihistamines like
Claritin, Allegra and Zyrtec, all now available as once-a-day
pills, rarely cause sedation or any other side effect. In addition,
there is a low-dose Allegra and Claritin syrup for children ages 6
and older. But these nonsedating antihistamines have not been
tested for safety during pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Also available are antihistamine drops for the eyes (Livostin, a
prescription product, and Vasocon-A and Naphacon-A, both sold over
the counter), Cromolon (a prescription product that prevents
histamine release) and anti-inflammatory eye drops like Acular,
sold over the counter. However, avoid eye drops that ``get the red
out''; these contain blood-vessel constrictors (naphazoline,
ephedrine, phenylephrine and tetrahydrozoline), which dry the eyes
and can cause rebound redness.
</P>
<P>
   DECONGESTANTS _ These drugs (pseudoephedrine and
phenylpropalomine) are sold without a prescription. They can
relieve nasal congestion but do not stop runny noses, sneezing or
itching. Possible side effects include jitteriness, rapid heart
rate, insomnia and elevated blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   IMMUNOTHERAPY _ If the allergens to which you are sensitive can
be well defined, weekly allergy shots for three to five years can
bring prolonged relief and reduce or even eliminate the need for
additional medication. But even with such protection, it is wise to
avoid exposure to the allergens as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
