<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE SHORT AND SKINNY ON THE NFL DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPAKCER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With next weekend's NFL draft, you will be
hearing an awful lot about such former student-athletes as LaVar
Arrington, Courtney Brown, Peter Warrick and Chris Samuels.
</P>
<P>
   In most mock drafts, these will be the first four players
chosen, though not necessarily in that order.
</P>
<P>
   As always, the draft is top-heavy in big names and deadly
numbers but light in more compelling areas of interest such as how
many 25-year-old married men will be taken this year? Which draft
pick will incur the wrath of that fat guy in the Jets jersey and
hardhat with a plastic jet glued to the top?
</P>
<P>
   These answers may help:
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   The numbers game
</P>
<P>
   HEAVIEST: Stockar McDougle, T, Oklahoma, 361 pounds. ``He's a
load-and-a-half,'' said Terry Donahue, the San Francisco 49ers'
director of personnel. ``He might be two loads.''
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTEST: Cornell Craig, WR, Southern Illinois, 165 pounds.
Stretched out on a 6-foot frame, he's downright spindly.
</P>
<P>
   TALLEST: Todd Wade, T, Mississippi, 6-8. His father and
grandfather both played for Ole Miss, so in 2025 we should expect
to see Todd's son lining up for the Rebels.
</P>
<P>
   SHORTEST: Troy Walters, WR, Stanford, 5-6 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   FASTEST: Melvin Harris, C, Virginia, 4.32 seconds for 40 yards.
Of course, all football 40 times are bogus, but since the same
inexact standards are applied to all, it doesn't really matter.
</P>
<P>
   SLOWEST: Jonathan Gray, T, Texas Tech, 5.85 for the 40. At that
rate, it would take him three years to run the Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   STRONGEST: Leif Larsen, DT, UTEP, 45 repetitions of 225 pounds
in the bench press.
</P>
<P>
   SMARTEST: QB Todd Husak, Stanford, and CB Ahmed Plummer, Ohio
State, each scored 39 out of 50 on the Wonderlic test of
intelligence given to all players at the scouting combine.
</P>
<P>
   DUMB AND DUMBER: The lowest Wonderlic score at the combine was 4
turned in by a Midwest running back who shall remain nameless.
</P>
<P>
   LONGEST NON-HYPHENATED SURNAME: Ryan Johanningmeier, OL,
Colorado. Good thing he's a 310-pounder. That name would never fit
on the back of a little guy's jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Career men
</P>
<P>
   GIVE THIS MAN A JOB: Offensive lineman Manuia Savea of Arizona
is 25, married and has three children.
</P>
<P>
   PROBABLY DID WELL ON THE INTELLIGENCE TESTS: LB Isiah Kacyvenski
is the only Harvard player listed in the draft guides. One such
said he is ``smart'' and ``has many off-the-field options.'' No
kidding.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   What's in a name?
</P>
<P>
   CRIME WAVE QUARTET: Cedrick Killings (DT, Carson-Newman), T.J.
Slaughter (LB, Southern Miss), Tramont Lawless (LB, Memphis),
Ainsley Battles (CB, Vanderbilt)
</P>
<P>
   GOOD MANNERS DEPT.: Dextra Polite (CB, Clemson), Sherrod Peace
(DE, North Carolina)
</P>
<P>
   YOU MEAN VERTICALLY CHALLENGED: Anthony Midget (CB, Virginia
Tech)
</P>
<P>
   WHERE'S THE FIRE?: Earthwind Moreland (CB, Georgia Southern)
</P>
<P>
   FUN SURNAME TO SAY OVER AND OVER: Shannon Poppinga (CB,
Augustana)
</P>
<P>
   GEOGRAPHICALLY CORRECT: Brad St. Louis (TE, Southwest Missouri
St.)
</P>
<P>
   OPPOSITE OF APPLAUSE: Boo Williams (RB, South Carolina), Carlton
Booe (RB, Northeastern Oklahoma)
</P>
<P>
   TO THE SWIFT: Antonio Speed (LB, Valdosta State), Joey Goodspeed
(FB, Notre Dame)
</P>
<P>
   DROP THE CHALUPA: Chris Chaloupka (QB, Sam Houston St.)
</P>
<P>
   ISN'T HE ON ``THE SOPRANOS''?: Giovanni Carmazzi (QB, Hofstra)
</P>
<P>
   MUST BE A FAMILY NAME: Plaxico Burress (WR, Michigan State),
Laveranues Coles (WR, Florida State)
</P>
<P>
   SHOULD HAVE BEEN A QB: Patrick Pass (RB, Georgia)
</P>
<P>
   BEST OF THE REST: Spergon Wynn (QB, Southwest Texas), Kofi Shuck
(WR, Wyoming), Imani Percoats (WR, Oregon State), Shockmain Davis
(WR, Angelo State), Jacques Rumph (WR, Carson-Newman), Trung
Canidate (RB, Arizona), Thaddeus Variance (RB, New Mexico
Highlands), Omar Bacon (RB, Utah), Cheston Blackshear (G, Florida),
Mao Tosi (DT, Idaho), Scooter Sprotte (LB, Arizona), Derek Fudge
(LB, East Tennessee St.), Hap Hines (K, Georgia)
</P>
