<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2479 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER11-COX     04-10 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Star quality
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain predicted Monday that if Hillary Rodham Clinton is
elected, she will be a ``star'' unlike any politician seen in the
Senate since Robert F. Kennedy. But he says she's still too liberal
for his taste. McCain made the comments in a day campaigning for
Clinton's opponent in New York, Rudy Giuliani. ``This is the first
time in history a first lady has run,'' McCain told students at
Columbia University. ``She would be a star of the quality that has
not been seen in the Senate since Bobby Kennedy. ... Many of us
believe in a scenario if Gore lost and she is elected to the
Senate, she'd be running for president.'' Asked by reporters to
clarify his remarks about Clinton, McCain said, ``I believe she'd
be very liberal, and I don't believe she'd be good for the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   PROUD OF THE COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani, joined for the second time in a week by John
McCain, ridiculed a suggestion that he and the senator are linked
to the far right wing. ``I want to show everybody that I want to
associate with the senator,'' Giuliani said at a midtown Manhattan
deli with McCain. Giuliani's comments were a reaction to a remark
last week by Hillary Rodham Clinton's media consultant, Ellis
Verdi: ``I am surprised that Mayor Giuliani would associate himself
with someone who is that far to the right,'' Verdi was quoted in
the New York Post as saying. Giuliani: ``I noticed that, since my
last visit here, I am now part of the `vast right-wing conspiracy.'
``I am very proud to be part of that organization.''
</P>
<P>
   BUT JOHN, YOU'RE THE ONE WHO LOST
</P>
<P>
   John McCain may soon relent to do some campaigning for that
other Republican who wants a win in New York. CNN.com reports that
McCain is warming, slightly, to the idea of supporting George W.
Bush. ``My strategy is to make sure that Governor Bush is the
president of the United States.'' McCain said in a CNN television
interview in New York. ``I just need to reach some understandings
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW WOULD MARCIA CLARK HAVE DONE?
</P>
<P>
   The police corruption scandal has damaged Los Angeles County
District Attorney Gil Garcetti's campaign for a third term, placing
him far behind challenger Steve Cooley in a poll published Monday.
Garcetti trailed Cooley, one of his own top deputies, 55 percent to
18 percent in the Los Angeles Times poll. Twenty-six percent of
those polled said they had not made up their minds, but Garcetti
would still trail by 11 percentage points even if he won all those
votes, according to the poll, which had a 3 percentage point margin
of error. The scandal involves officers who allegedly framed, beat
and sometimes shot innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   AND FLORIDA'S A KEY BATTLEGROUND STATE
</P>
<P>
   The vice presidency has been famously likened to ``bucket of
warm spit,'' but it seems Sen. Bob Graham (D-Fla.) wouldn't mind
carrying that bucket. In a meeting with Roll Call reporters and
editors, Graham indicated he'd take the job _ if Al Gore asks him
to be his running mate, that is. Said Graham: ``If the presidential
nominee of your party asks you to serve in that position, it is
almost impossible to say no.''
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE TOO MUCH OF AN OUTSIDER
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Congress has fallen out of love with George W.
Bush, according to the New York Times. After pre-primary pledges of
support, congressional Republican leaders are starting to plan
around either a Bush loss or a coattail-free win. In addition to
Bush's dwindling poll numbers, the Times says, many Republicans say
the Bush-Congress relationship is doomed by lack of communication,
making a unified agenda nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   HEAVY DOSE OF ISOLATIONISM
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan and his Minnesota supporters turned out in force in
Bloomington to re-establish the state's branch of the Reform Party.
And this time it's stacked with Buchanan supporters. After
commenting on Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura's comments about the
party being ``dysfunctional,'' Buchanan went on to criticize
Ventura, Al Gore and George W. Bush for supporting an end to trade
restrictions with China. But Buchanan's loudest applause came when
he attacked the International Monetary Fund, world trade groups and
other international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   HE'S WAITING FOR THE MOVIE TO COME OUT
</P>
<P>
   As the 2000 presidential campaign took a welcome literary turn,
George W. Bush attacked Al Gore's book on the environment, ``Earth
in the Balance.'' ``I think the vice president is probably going to
have to explain what he meant by some of the things in the book,''
Bush warned, ``to share with us the philosophy behind some of the
standards in the book.'' But in response to a question, according
to The Associated Press, Bush said that uh, no, he hadn't read the
book. Some explaining from Bush may be in order, too.
</P>
<P>
   SOFT ON MICROSOFT?
</P>
<P>
   The state and federal governments have won the first round of
their antitrust case against Microsoft, but with years of legal
appeals anticipated, the new president could change how the case is
resolved. George W. Bush has signaled he would be more friendly to
the company; Al Gore generally has stayed silent. There is
precedent for a new administration changing course in a major
antitrust case: In 1982, Ronald Reagan's Justice Department threw
out a case against IBM that had lingered since 1969. But, since
there are 19 states also listed as plaintiffs in the Microsoft
case, legal scholars say the next president wouldn't affect the
case as much.
</P>
<P>
   VOTING WITH THEIR FEET
</P>
<P>
   Runners in Sunday's Cherry Blossom 10-mile race had to choose
among three chutes to pass through near the race's end: Democrat,
Republican, Other. The highly anticipated results: Democrats ran
away with the victory. With a quarter-mile to go, runners could
veer left through the Democratic gate, steer right through the
Republican gate or head straight through ``other.'' Electronic
chips in the runners' shoes recorded the results, with participants
promised anonymity as to how they voted. Some 2,269 runners picked
Democrat (44 percent); 1,432 picked Republican (28 percent), edging
out ``other'' by only six runners. But what was the margin of
error?
</P>
<P>
   LIKE MUSIC FOR POLITICAL JUNKIES
</P>
<P>
   Three of Steve Forbes' former campaign staffers are launching
``what they say is the first national all-politics radio station on
the Internet,'' Reuters reported. Based in Davenport, Iowa,
Policast.com is to serve as an around-the-clock, seven-day-a-week
operation, with political news, commentary and humor. Said former
Forbes senior adviser Steve Grubbs: ``We aren't going to do
hurricanes or earthquakes; just politics _ national, state and
municipal. The demand for political news has exploded, and we
intend to deliver.'' Joining him are K.B. Forbes and Amanda Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
