<HEADER>
A2480 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-CHILDREN-ALONE-NY     04-10 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CHILDREN-ALONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT CHILDREN DO WHEN HOME AND ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By LESLIE BERGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twelve to 14 percent of American children ages 5 to 12 spend
some time home alone after school, a new study has found, but the
period without adult supervision averages only an hour, most of the
children are older, and many seem to welcome a measure of privacy
and independence.
</P>
<P>
   Only 1 percent of the youngest children in a national sampling,
ages 5 to 7, were left in so-called self-care, while 8 percent of
the children 8 to 10 years old were in self-care, according to the
study by the University of Michigan's Institute for Social
Research. The biggest share of the children spending time alone was
older, about 23 percent of the 11- and 12-year-olds in the study.
</P>
<P>
   Eating, going to the bathroom and watching television are the
first three things children do when they get home, the study found.
And a little time alone may not be such a bad thing given working
families' hectic schedules and children's super-structured lives,
suggested Dr. Sandra Hofferth, the study's lead researcher. Often,
she said, older children used their time alone to read, study and
simply decompress.
</P>
<P>
   ``As children grow older, they want increased autonomy,''
Hofferth, a sociologist, said in an interview. ``What may be right
for younger elementary school children may not be right for older
ones. Around 9 or 10, kids want to care for themselves and don't
want to be in programs for babies anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, presented last week at a meeting of the Society for
Research on Adolescence in Chicago, was based on diaries of the
activities of about 1,500 children ages 5 to 12. The diaries were
kept in 1997; parents were interviewed for a clearer picture.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have been tracking latchkey children since the
1980s. The most significant shift in patterns came between 1984 and
1990, when the estimated number of children 5 to 12 in self-care
nearly doubled from 1.8 million to 3.4 million, Hofferth said.
Today, she said, 75 percent of women with school-age children work
outside the home at least part-time.
</P>
<P>
   The latest study, Hofferth said, shows that the number of
children in self-care has remained fairly steady over the last
decade, perhaps because many parents have begun sharing home duties
in split shifts, either by working part time or staggering their
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The findings also document in new detail how children's
activities vary from home, recreation centers and after-school
programs. Children in structured after-school programs were more
likely to participate in sports while children at home were more
likely to study or read.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Deborah Lowe Vandell, a professor of educational psychology
at the University of Wisconsin, who has written extensively on day
care and after-school programs, said the findings were consistent
with her own recent research in which children said they wanted
autonomy and privacy and the ability to set their own schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be foolish to say all self-care is bad, that
children shouldn't have any time alone, especially as they get
older,'' Vandell said. But she warned that sometimes too much
unsupervised time could be worse than over-programming.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, most children's after-school time, or 100 minutes
a day, was spent watching television. The diaries also showed that
an average of 74 minutes was spent playing, 60 minutes studying, 60
minutes in sports, 30 minutes on household chores, 30 minutes
reading, and 20 minutes in conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Most children, about 73 percent, go straight home after school,
whether or not they are alone, the study found. The first things
they reported doing upon their arrival were eating (27 percent);
engaging in personal care (19 percent), which could mean ``washing,
bathing and none of your business''; and watching television (15
percent). Only 13 percent of the children sampled made studying
their top priority.
</P>
<P>
   The child's personality, as well as the family income level and
neighborhood safety, were other factors in shaping after-school
routines. Quieter children were more likely to be left alone than
aggressive ones, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, researchers also found that children of older and
better-educated mothers were more likely to be unsupervised at home
than children of mothers with a high school education or less.
</P>
<P>
   But Hofferth said the ability to stay in touch by phone made a
huge difference in parents' willingness to leave children
temporarily alone, and that many parents with blue-collar jobs had
limited access to phones. In addition, more educated mothers seemed
more comfortable allowing their children some autonomy at younger
ages, Hofferth said.
</P>
<P>
   Children living in socially cohesive neighborhoods, where
parents rely on one another for emergencies, also were more likely
to take care of themselves after school. At the same time, however,
children in higher income families were more likely to be enrolled
in sports and other afternoon activities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
