<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULITZER-PRIZES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULITZERS TO WASHINGTON POST, WALL STREET JOURNAL AND AP 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Washington Post received three of the 14 Pulitzer Prizes
awarded for journalism Monday, including the public service award
for its coverage of the neglect and abuse of the mentally retarded
in city group homes in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal won two other prizes, while the Village
Voice, a free weekly newspaper in New York, was awarded the prize
for international reporting for its coverage of the AIDS crisis in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Post staff won the award for breaking news for ``its
clear and balanced coverage of the student massacre at Columbine
High School.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press won the award for investigative reporting
``for revealing, with extensive documentation, the decades-old
secret of how American soldiers early in the Korean War killed
hundreds of Korean civilians in a massacre at the No Gun Ri
Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   The fiction award went to ``The Interpreter of Maladies,'' a
collection of short stories by Jhumpa Lahiri.
</P>
<P>
   The drama award was won by Donald Margulies for his play
``Dinner with Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   David M. Kennedy, a professor of history at Stanford University,
won the award for history for his book ``Freedom from Fear: The
American People in Depression and War, 1929-1945.''
</P>
<P>
   The award for general non-fiction was given to John W. Dower, a
history professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, for
his book ``Embracing Defeat: Japan in the Wake of World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post's other two awards were received for
criticism, given to Henry Allen for his writing on photography, and
for feature photography for coverage of Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In awarding the public service award, the Pulitzer committee
singled out notable reporting by Katherine Boo, an investigative
reporter at The Post since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Village Voice was honored for its eight-part series by Mark
Schoofs, who spent more than six months in nine countries examining
the AIDS crisis and its consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal staff was awarded the Pulitzer Prize in
the national affairs category ``for its revealing stories that
questioned U.S. defense spending and military deployment in the
post-Cold War era.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul A. Gigot of the Journal also won for columns on politics
and government, many of them related to the impact of the crisis
surrounding the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Bersia of the Orlando Sentinel won the award for
distinguished editorial writing for ``attacking predatory lending
practices in the state'' and prompting changes in local
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The award for explanatory reporting went to Eric Newhouse of the
Great Falls Tribune in Montana for coverage of alcohol abuse in the
community. George Dohrmann of the St. Paul Pioneer Press, whose
exposure of academic fraud in the men's basketball program at the
University of Minnesota brought his newspaper scathing criticism
from Gov. Jesse Ventura, was awarded the prize for beat reporting.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Moehringer of the Los Angeles Times won the feature writing
award for his portrait of Gee's Bend, an isolated river community
populated by descendants of slaves in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Pett of the Lexington (Kentucky) Herald Leader won in the
editorial cartoons category.
</P>
<P>
   The award for breaking news photography went to the Denver Rocky
Mountain News photography staff for the ``emotional images taken
after the student shootings at Columbine High School.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking a 14-year streak, The New York Times did not win an
award this year.
</P>
<P>
   The other award winners in the arts category included Stacy
Schiff for her biography ``Vera (Mrs. Vladimir Nabokov).''
</P>
<P>
   The award for poetry was given to C.K. Williams for his work
``Repair.''
</P>
<P>
   The prize for music was awarded to Lewis Spratlan for his
composition ``Life is a Dream, Opera in Three Acts: Act II, Concert
Version.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
