<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TINA-TURNER-REVIEW-AR     04-10 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINA-TURNER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUISED BUT NOT BROKEN, TINA TURNER ROCKS ALONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indomitable and indefatigable, Tina Turner reigned at Madison
Square Garden on Friday night, defying time, pop fashion and any
man who would try to hold her down.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, 61, has long since staked out her archetype: the strong,
lusty woman who has grown tougher with every setback and every
betrayal. It's an archetype that is reinforced by her songs, her
autobiography, her leathery voice and her leonine presence.
Strutting across the stage in spike heels, shaking her blonde
tousled moptop, she sang, ``I may be bruised but I ain't broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Her set ranged through 40 years of music, including the first
song she recorded, ``A Fool in Love'' from 1960, a prescient wail
of pain about an irresistible, mistreating man. The rest of the set
was bipolar, swinging between vows and kiss-offs: ``Let's Stay
Together'' answered by ``What's Love Got to Do With It?''; ``Better
Be Good to Me'' followed by ``Heard It Through the Grapevine.''
Songs from her current album, ``Twenty Four Seven'' (Virgin),
either promised devotion or, more convincingly, sent a man packing
in ``When the Heartache Is Over'' and ``Absolutely Nothing's
Changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner became a superstar during the video era, and she has
mastered the rock spectacle. Her show included video screens,
fireworks, costume changes, moving sets and dancers who shook
everything sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
   Turner danced, too, posing with hand on hip and shoulders thrown
back or prancing with quick coltish steps. She still wears
skin-tight clothes. Yet at the center of the extravaganza was her
voice: the bluesy rasp and yowl that sliced through blues-rock
guitar chords and snapped ballads to attention. She also sang the
Beatles' ``Help'' as a slow gospel supplication, confessing to
insecurity and longing without disguising her tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's voice has two modes, the ones she famously sums up as
``nice and easy'' _ a smoky purr _ and ``nice and rough'': the
rising, tearing tone that could clear city traffic for blocks
ahead. She turns quiet verses into sadder-but-wiser reflections or
clipped preacher's syncopations. Then, when a chorus leaps upward,
she combines torment and defiance, channeling a primal power.
</P>
<P>
   Turner is not about to become a grande dame anytime soon,
reflecting from a distance on past triumphs and heartbreak. The way
she sings, she's still a fierce contender in the battle of the
sexes.
</P>
<P>
   Lionel Richie, who shared the bill, was oil to Turner's vinegar,
unctuously flattering the audience for remembering his songs after
he disappeared for most of the 1990s. He sang his hits from the
'70s and '80s, skillful genre exercises that never shied away from
a romantic bromide; the one new song was about Cinderella.
</P>
<P>
   The set was a reminder of Richie's variety, from the nasal funk
of the Commodores' ``Brick House'' to the heartland rock of
``Dancing on the Ceiling'' to countryish ballads like ``Easy'' to
his anticipation of current Latin pop, ``All Night Long.''
</P>
<P>
   His voice was warm and the band helped him milk the songs,
changing them from promises of romance to an unabashed courting of
the crowd and his dormant career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1712EDT &QL; 
