<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2491 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AIRLINE-QUALITY11-COX     04-10 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-QUALITY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIRLINE QUALITY FELL IN 1999, REPORT FINDS
 &HT;    450&AMP;add. With AIRLINE-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The overall quality of U.S. air travel declined
last year, with consumer complaints doubling despite the industry's
promises to improve service, the annual Airline Quality Report said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The continuing decline of the overall industry's quality
documents that the airline-sponsored plan to increase customer
service is failing,'' said Brent Bowen, co-author of the study and
director of the Aviation Institute at the University of Nebraska at
Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines was the best carrier in the nation, rising
from fifth place last year, according to the report for the major
domestic airlines.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways fell to sixth from the top spot the previous year,
and American Airlines fell to seventh, down from third place. Delta
Airlines was ranked fourth, rising one spot from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The report weighed U.S. Department of Transportation performance
data on on-time arrivals, involuntary denied boarding, mishandled
baggage and a combination of 11 customer complaint categories.
</P>
<P>
   Only the industry's baggage handling showed a slight improvement
over the previous year, falling to 5.08 errors per 1,000 passengers
from 5.16 per 1,000 a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But on-time performance _ flights arriving within 15 minutes of
schedule _ slipped from 77.2 percent to 76.1 percent, and denied
boardings rose marginally from 0.87 per 10,000 passengers to 0.88.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the volume of consumer complaints increased by 130
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer complaints are on the rise because of the airlines'
inability to take complaints seriously, Bowen said. Many customers
are turning to the Department of Transportation, which recently
made it easier for consumers to file complaints on its
</P>
<P>
   Web site, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airlines still don't seem to get it'' that consumers want
basic services such as on-time service, said Dean Headly, co-author
of the study and associate professor of marketing at Wichita State
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do recognize that there there are problems and we are doing
something about them,'' said Diana Cronan, a spokeswoman for the
Air Transport Association, the trade association representing the
major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Cronan said criticism that the airlines' plan to improve service
is failing was ``unfair because the plan was implemented in
December and was only in effect for two weeks in 1999. We ask that
the flying public give us a chance and wait until the plan has been
in effect for a year before judging us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Southwest recorded the third largest margin of improvement in
this year's report and had the lowest rate of customer complaints
of the 10 airlines surveyed. However, its on-time arrivals
percentage and customer complaint rates grew worse last year,
according the report.
</P>
<P>
   Delta suffered a decline in the areas of on-time arrivals,
mishandled baggage and customer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways' rating fell more than any other major airline's. The
carrier's customer complaints were twice as frequent as its
counterparts'. Even though American Airlines improved its on-time
performance, the airline's 69.5 percent rate was the worst of all
the major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The airline industry's low performance, Bowen said, can be
attributed to poor management and dissatisfied workers at companies
such as United. He said airlines with fewer labor problems tend to
perform better, and those who don't spend enough money to satisfy
customers' needs tend to do poorly.
</P>
<P>
   The airline quality study is conducted annually by the Nebraska
aviation institute and the W. Frank Barton School of Business at
Wichita State University.
</P>
<P>
   Major airlines, according to the report, are those whose
operating revenue for a 12-month period is $1 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   For additional information:
cid.unomaha.edu/(tilde)unoai/research/aqrindex.html,
www.dot.gov/ost/dapc/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
