<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2500 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-FRUIT-FLY-2TAKES-     04-10 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FRUIT-FLY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FLY PEOPLE MAKE HISTORY ON THE FRONTIERS OF GENETICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass., N.Y.)   (Science Times)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dung beetle was worshiped by the ancient Egyptians, and the
honeybee has always had its admirers, but only one insect has a
computer database, its own CD-ROM and an international cult of
5,000 followers, each with a PhD.
</P>
<P>
   So minutely has that insect, the Drosophila fruit fly, been
scrutinized that every bristle on its tiny head has a scientific
name.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the fly became the second animal to have its full
genome decoded. (The first was its leading rival for biologists'
affections, the laboratory roundworm.) Fly people, as Drosophila
researchers call themselves, were presented at their annual meeting
in Pittsburgh last month with a CD-ROM from the Celera Corp.
containing the 120 million units so far identified in the fly's
DNA.
</P>
<P>
   The fly has attained this prominence in human affairs because it
is one of the principal model organisms studied by biologists as a
means of understanding the general design of life.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the unity of evolution, the fly's genes and those of
people overlap considerably. Fly people, who are passionate about
the merits of their favorite organism, are easily provoked into
confessing that they think of people as large flies that lack
wings.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one class of researcher to whom fly people cannot
help feeling slightly superior, it is worm people, the students of
the C. elegans roundworm.
</P>
<P>
   The fly and the worm are quite similar as model organisms, which
is perhaps one reason for the rivalry. Their genes are easily
manipulated, in contrast with those of the mouse, another leading
model organism, which seems uncomfortably similar to people at the
DNA level but is very cumbersome to manipulate genetically.
</P>
<P>
   When the fly's genome was decoded, fly biologists rushed to
calculate how many known human disease genes had direct
counterparts in Drosophila and the C. elegans worm. Their summary
table published in Science magazine last month, showing a decided
advantage for the fly, caused no little offense in the worm
community. ``Very fly-centric,'' complained Dr. Gary Ruvkun, a worm
biologist at the Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A considerable puzzle in the fly-centric universe has been the
surprisingly small size of the Drosophila genome. The fly is a
complex miniature machine, with wings, blood and kidney, and a
brain that is powerful enough to compute flight activity and
elaborate behavior patterns. Surely it needs far more genes than
the worm, a microscopic little tube made of exactly 959 cells.
</P>
<P>
   According to those who decoded the worm's genome, evolution has
found it necessary to write 18,424 programming instructions, aka
genes, to develop, operate and maintain a worm. But only 13,601
genes, nearly 5,000 fewer, have been detected in the fly's genome.
</P>
<P>
   This embarrassment has yet to be explained, and is only partly
relieved by reports that the worm's gene number has recently been
revised downward to about 16,000 genes.
</P>
<P>
   The little fly has performed several outstanding services to
biology during the 93 years of its laboratory employment. Its
adoptive father, Dr. Thomas H. Morgan, a Columbia University
professor, saw that its quick life cycle and prolific offspring
made the fly an ideal test bed for exploring Mendel's laws of
genetics, which had been rediscovered a few years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The fly was also inexpensive compared with other laboratory
animals, a fact not lost on Morgan, who was something of a
cheapskate. The flies could be raised in containers no more
complicated than a milk bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to legend, he and his students stole empty
half-pints from milk boxes on Manhattan stoops on their
early-morning walks to the lab, and they lifted more from the
Columbia student cafeteria,'' Jonathan Weiner wrote in ``Time,
Love, Memory'' (Knopf, 1999), an engaging joint biography of the
fly and one of its leading students, Dr. Seymour Benzer.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgan laboratory laid the foundation of modern genetics in
discovering that genes are arranged in linear array on the
chromosomes and that their order can be mapped by tracking the
pattern in which genetic traits are co-inherited in the progeny. If
two genes lie very close to each other on a chromosome, they will
rarely be separated when the chromosomes exchange DNA segments, as
happens when egg or sperm cells are generated.
</P>
<P>
   But if the two genes lie at opposite ends of a chromosome, they
are much more likely to be inherited separately (some offspring
will have one, some the other). Working with the first few mutant
flies that Morgan had discovered, his student Alfred Sturtevant
showed how a map of the genes' position on a chromosome could be
constructed directly from the co-inheritance patterns.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fly fell into temporary eclipse after the discovery of DNA
in 1953. Geneticists needed much simpler organisms, like bacteria
and the viruses that prey on them, in which to work out the
molecule-level events of DNA metabolism. But when the bacterial
type of cell was well enough understood, biologists came flocking
back to the fly to gain an understanding of animal cells.
</P>
<P>
   The fly's second great gift to biology was essentially to crack
the great mystery of how a many-celled complex animal develops from
a single egg cell. Though the frog and the mouse deserve credit
too, it was the fly that revealed the basic system of genes and
signaling molecules that set up the founding patterns in the
developing embryo and direct the development of different organs in
their proper sites.
</P>
<P>
   These master patterning genes have immediately recognizable
cousins in vertebrates like humans, although there are somewhat
more of them. It looks as though those big flies without wings are
assembled by just the same genetic mechanisms, though with more
fripperies and curlicues, as Drosophila.
</P>
<P>
   The fly seems in the act of parting with a third amazing gift,
though the package is still being unwrapped: the rules that govern
the inheritance of behavior. Evolution has taken great care in
designing every physical feature of the fly's body, so no less
might be expected of the fly's behavior, which is just as important
to its survival.
</P>
<P>
   Benzer and his students at the California Institute of
Technology discovered the first genes that affect the biological
clock, which is a kind of behavior, and more recently other fly
people have discovered two elaborate cascades of genes that between
them seem to control many aspects of the fly's sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The little creature's courtship ritual is not so entirely
different from the human variety. The male taps on his inamorata
with his forelegs, sings her a song by extending and vibrating one
of his wings, and then tries to mate with her. She may accept the
proposition or respond with a buzz, a gesture needing no
translation.
</P>
<P>
   Many if not all of these behaviors are controlled by specific
genes, chiefly two known as fruitless and dissatisfaction.
Biologists name genes inversely, some would say perversely, by
describing what the organism cannot do after one of its genes has
been rendered defective with a mutation.
</P>
<P>
   Male flies with a mutation in their fruitless gene cannot
perform the courtship song correctly. Their sexual orientation is
deranged and they will court each other rather than females (hence
``fruitless''). Females with a defective dissatisfaction gene
resist copulation. Further details about the fly's sexual hang-ups
and much else besides can be found in flybase, the electronic
encyclopedia of fly lore, at flybase.bio.indiana.edu.
</P>
<P>
   If each step in the fly's courtship is choreographed in its
genes, are the flies just miniature automata with no freedom of
action? And if so much of the fly's behavior is under tight genetic
control, how much of human behavior is also framed by the genes?
</P>
<P>
   The decoding of the fly's genome opens out vast new avenues for
fly people to explore. Only some 2,783 genes are recorded in
flybase, the fruit of 93 years of fly person labor. The genome
sequencers found all but five (and some or all of these five may be
erroneous), and another 10,823 genes besides. The role of about
half of the fly's 13,601 genes can be guessed, because their DNA
sequences resemble those of genes whose purpose is known, but 22
percent of the genes match nothing in the data bases.
</P>
<P>
   Even when roles have been assigned to all of the fly's presently
predicted genes, Drosophilists will still be one major step away
from the total definition of the fly. Imagine having a full list of
parts for a Boeing 747 but not a single instruction for how to
assemble them. Drosophila melanogaster has, perhaps, a fourth great
gift of knowledge still concealed within its frail, miraculous
body.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
