<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2507 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HEALTH-INTERNET11-COX     04-10 0228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INTERNET11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mammoth medical database contains millions of articles
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your doctor hands you _ or your spouse, or your parent, or your
child _ a difficult, unexpected diagnosis. Suddenly you need to
know as much as possible, as quickly as possible, about a disease
or condition you had barely heard of yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   What do you do? In the data wilderness of the World Wide Web,
where do you go?
</P>
<P>
   A good place to start, to see what has been written about
diseases and to investigate the latest in treatments and research,
is the mother and father of all medical databases: the National
Library of Medicine, a division of the federal National Institutes
of Health. The library itself is in Bethesda, Md., but its content
_ literally millions of articles on aspects of medicine, science
and health care _ is available online at www.nlm.nih.gov.
</P>
<P>
   A cautionary note: NLM searches can be rewarding, but they
aren't easy. Several search programs have been written to help
navigate it. For a basic introduction, with links to explanations
and tutorials in English and several other languages, begin at
www.nnlm.nlm.nih.gov
</P>
<P>
   /nnlm/online/.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
