<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Africa an emotional challenge for Basinger
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vanity Fair's ($3.95) Leslie Bennetts profiles Georgia native
Kim Basinger this month on the eve of the actress' starring role in
``I Dreamed of Africa.'' Despite her Oscar for ``L.A.
Confidential,'' Basinger still hasn't gotten the respect she
deserves, Bennetts writes. That may change with the new film based
on Kuki Gallmann's best-selling book about her experiences in
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Gallmann and her husband moved to Kenya in 1972 to establish a
farm. However, her husband died in a car crash. Then her son died
from the bite of a puff adder. Basinger, who portrays Gallmann in
the film, says, ``There's not an emotion I didn't get to play....''
</P>
<P>
   The woman who hails from Athens, Ga., also talks about her
volatile relationship with husband Alec Baldwin and his attempts to
turn what he describes as ``a Tennessee Williams character'' into a
soccer mom.
</P>
<P>
   Other must-read pieces include Christopher Hitchens' reflections
on ``The Great Gatsby'' on the novel's 75th anniversary, and an
excerpt from a new book, ``In the Heart of the Sea,'' a gripping
true-life account of a whale attack that inspired Herman Melville's
``Moby-Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mixed bag: Talk ($3.50) has yet to reach the level of Vanity
Fair, but you can't say that Tina Brown doesn't try to offer
something for everybody. The May issue features a very good cover
story on Russell Crowe and his role in the soon-to-be-released film
``Gladiator,'' and solid articles on Tony Blair and his legacy and
Rupert Murdoch's renegade daughter Liz.
</P>
<P>
   The fluff in between is entertaining and uneven. Susie Orbach's
pop-psychology analysis of why women hate men is better suited for
Cosmo or Redbook. Sam Sifton's observations on why women are
attracted to men who are ``just gay enough'' is edgy and amusing.
How do you know if you're just gay enough? You own an Eames chair,
you act like a young Marlon Brando and you never miss ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  All about Elian: As the furor over Elian Gonzalez intensifies,
Time ($3.50) and Newsweek ($3.50) weigh in with cover stories on
the tug of war between the boy's father and his relatives in Miami.
Time's Lance Morrow makes an interesting point in his essay on
``The Second-Class Parent.'' If it had been Juan Miguel Gonzalez
who died, and the mother waiting back in Cuba, Morrow writes,
``Elian would have been sent back to her immediately, on the
premise that the mother-child bond trumps politics.'' Newsweek,
meanwhile, offers a glimpse of what kind of life Elian would have
back in Cuba. On one hand, he would have a nurturing life free of
the kind of crime that exists in Miami. On the other hand, although
his father is relatively well-off by Cuban standards, there would
be chronic shortages and limited prospects. And no Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Domestic affairs: Barbara Ehrenreich kicked up a dust storm
with her Harper's ($4.25) article ``Maid to Order,'' in which she
referred to the affluents' ``degradation'' of domestic workers.
Ehrenreich, who says she does most of her own cleaning, notes that
although the feminist revolution has resulted in more domestic
task-sharing between husbands and wives, women still do most of the
work. Cleaning services help ease the tension, she says, but adds
that ``the micro-defeat of feminism has created the ``sudden
emergence of a servant class'' beholden to a tiny overclass.
Ehrenreich was accused by writers at Salon and other media of being
anti-labor and of not understanding that cleaning houses was no
more demeaning than other work.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In sync: Jezebel ($3.95) tunes in to the city's music scene in
a package on Atlanta's best DJs, local bands on the rise and a
timeline of Georgia talent. Among the diamonds in the rough are
Massinfluence, Monochrome, Mandarico, Lift, 6 Piece and Steep. If
you haven't heard them (or heard of them), Jezebel notes, chances
are you will.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Organized anarchy: The New Yorker ($3) examines the coalition
of activists that disrupted the World Trade Organization's meetings
in Seattle last fall and finds it to be an ``amalgam of political
theater and ground-level organizing.'' Largely co-ordinated via the
Internet, the coalition plans to protest the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank on Sunday in Washington. One of the
organizers, 27-year-old Juliette Beck, explains the group's mission
as an attempt to ``drag these institutions out into the sunlight of
public scrutiny, where they belong. They'll shrivel up like
Dracula!''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
