<HEADER>
A2518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-EXPLORATION11-COX     04-10 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPLORATION11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATIONAL GEOGRAPHIC SETS NEW GOALS FOR EXPLORATION
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Summoned by the National Geographic Society from
mountaintops, ocean depths, rain forests and desert digs, assembled
adventurers sounded a common refrain Monday: Discovery on Earth has
barely begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exploration is alive and well. It is not something of another
century,'' declared Robert Ballard, who discovered the sunken
Titanic in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the 21st century is going to be THE great age of
discovery,'' echoed Steven Ambrose, historian and author of a
best-selling book on pathfinders Lewis and Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years of study have only scratched the surface of
discovery about behavior of chimpanzees in Tanzania, said Jane
Goodall, the author and anthropologist.
</P>
<P>
   Founded more than a century ago, the National Geographic Society
gathered what it called a ``Who's Who of exploration'' to initiate
a new mission of not only finding the wonders of the world. but
saving them as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Society will sponsor seven ``explorers in residence'' who
are dedicated to discovery and preservation of Earth's natural and
cultural resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, as we explore, the places and treasures we find
are too often threatened with destruction,'' said Society President
John Fahey. ``Today's explorer must also be a conservationist.''
</P>
<P>
   The explorers' introduction at the National Geographic Society
headquarters was not only the first time they had gathered under
one roof, but perhaps the only time that all had simultaneously
been under a roof, period. Their lives have been spent mostly out
of doors _ in the wilds or on ship decks or under water.
</P>
<P>
   The initial ``explorers in residence'' and their missions are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul Sereno: A paleontologist, Sereno has discovered new
dinosaur species on several continents. He is beginning a
three-month trek to the Sahara, tracking not only ``one of the most
unusual dinosaurs ever known'' but also the remains of unknown
animals who lived during the dinosaur era.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sylvia Earle: A marine biologist nicknamed ``Her Deepness,''
Earle has led more than 50 expeditions totaling more than 6,000
hour underwater. Her next project is exploring marine sanctuaries
of the Channel Islands, Monterey Bay and the Florida Keys and
studying ``how to live better with the aquatic systems than sustain
us.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Wade Davis: An anthropologist and botanical explorer, Davis
has lived with 15 indigenous groups of people in the Amazon and
Andes. Among his seven books is one on folk preparations implicated
in the creation of zombies. His next explorations will be of remote
outposts of civilization in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Johan Reinhard: A high-altitude archaeologist, Reinhard is
best known for his 1995 discovery of the ``Inca Ice Maiden,'' a
frozen human sacrifice found on Peru's Mount Ampato. Racing against
looters, he is continuing a search for Inca burial sites in
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ballard: His next mission is a expedition to the Black Sea in
search of ancient shipwrecks and evidence of Noah's great biblical
flood.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ambrose: After helping preserve parts of the Lewis and Clark
Trail, he is leading a campaign to restore parts of the Mississippi
River.
</P>
<P>
   _ Goodall: She will launch a study of wild chimpanzees in the
Congo and Tanzania beyond her Gombe Stream Preserve.
</P>
<P>
   The National Geographic Society began supporting exploration in
1890 by backing the expedition of Israel C. Russell, who found
Mount Logan, Canada's highest mountain. The society will support
projects for each of the ``explorers in residence'' for several
years and the explorers will serve as advisors on other Society
projects.
</P>
<P>
   At a luncheon, the explorers joked about their new status.
</P>
<P>
   '`I'm not in residence anywhere,'' said Goodall.
</P>
<P>
   But they were somber in their warnings about environmental
dangers to wild plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there hope for the future?'' asked Goodall. ``Yes, but I
don't believe there is a long window.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.nationalgeographic.com/eir
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
