<HEADER>
A2519 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PRACTICAL-MAN11-COX     04-10 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-MAN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Practical man's clunker reaps a heap of grief
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The practical man got run over last
week.
</P>
<P>
   By his buddies.
</P>
<P>
   Striding sturdily toward the production department, his mind on
urgent newspaper business, he decided to take a shortcut through
the cafeteria. There, his industrious colleagues were again
matching their massive wits _ this time over automobiles _ at that
dillydallying debauch they call lunch. They mowed him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen the Practical Man's car?'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bloated boat,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dented dinosaur.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uglier than a dead fish at a fashion show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tackier than bib overalls at The Breakers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clampetts had a better ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Stung by the ambush, bleeding from the barrage, the practical
man stuck out his bottom lip, shouted ``You guys are so mean!'' and
fled sobbing to the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   JUST KIDDING!
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the practical man said, ``It moves. It's mine. I like
it.'' And went back to work.
</P>
<P>
   But it got him thinking. Is there something wrong with his car?
</P>
<P>
   The practical man drives a 1985 Chevy Caprice. It cost him
$2,300 six years ago. It's never failed to start, never left him
stranded and it's required less than $1,000 to maintain since he
bought it. He has no car payment, carries no costly collision
insurance and gets no grief from stupid drivers, who steer clear
for two reasons: He's bigger than they are, and he obviously isn't
afraid to rub fenders to retain his right of way. He likes the car
because it's cheap and it gets him there.
</P>
<P>
   But his pals want more than transportation. They want fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them drive sport utility vehicles. It doesn't matter to
them that SUVs are neither sporty (they're half-truck, half-station
wagon, for God's sake!), nor particularly useful (the Chevy can
carry more people and twice the groceries).
</P>
<P>
   What matters is that SUVs pretend to be what their owners are
not _ fun yet rugged, whimsical yet wise, young yet responsible _
thus concealing what their owners actually are: flabby yet
middle-aged. For the price of 15 Chevys, SUV drivers get a sad
dream and a spare tire bolted to the hatchback that few of them
know how to remove, much less actually use.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the lunch gang apparently figured that at age 40, it
was time they grew up and got practical, because most dropped 30
grand on minivans. These toy boats seem handy _ until your first
visit to Home Depot, when you realize that a kid on a bike can
carry home more lumber. And they seem family friendly _ until your
dog barfs and your toddler slathers sticky goo on seats that cost
you 30K, or until you try to go on vacation and discover you'll
have to put the luggage on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Note to potential minivan buyers: Don't waste thousands playing
at practicality when a few hundred gets you the real thing: A 1973
Dodge Maxivan. The practical man's 15-passenger church bus cost him
$500, can cart your family and his to Disney with room to spare and
swallows 4-by-8 sheets of plywood whole. It also makes a great fort
for the kids between outings.
</P>
<P>
   But the practical man is missing the point. His pals would never
drive an '85 Chevy or a '73 Dodge because cars like those are just
too old and ugly. But who has more style? The drone who drives what
everyone else does, or the practical man, whose wheels are his
alone?
</P>
<P>
   Q&AMP;A FROM READERS
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man,
</P>
<P>
   Due to the hostile nature of your response to my recent
suggestion to include a Practical Woman column, I can only deduce
that you feel threatened by the possibility that there are actually
women who are as practical (if not more so) than men.
</P>
<P>
   I envisioned a utopia of practicality, with both the male and
female pragmatic viewpoints disseminated. Alas, you actually
exhibited the kind of reaction you seem to dislike yourself _
emotional and insecure.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I will still read your column, but I will never have the
same respect for you, Practical Man.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sincerely, Wendi Ladika (a.k.a. I would've made a great
Practical Woman)
</P>
<P>
   A: All right, Wendi. The practical man sugarcoated it last time,
but now he must speak the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Give it up. What could you possibly write about? The practical
way to buy your 25th pair of shoes? How to spot a bargain on the
shopping channel? Ten makeup tips for the practical woman?
</P>
<P>
   The practical man isn't practical because he's a man. He scorns
stupidity of any gender and laughs as loudly at sports fans as he
does at fashion models. Any practical woman, if she were truly
practical, would do the same, write the same column _ and put him
out of a job. So once again: Scram, Wendi!
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man,
</P>
<P>
   While reading your column recently, I almost had to throw up at
your description of how to extract peas from a child's nose.
</P>
<P>
   What struck me was that, the day before, I had just been reading
``Angela's Ashes'' and had come upon the image of the father
sucking stuff from a child's nose. This was something I had never
heard of in all my 71 long years on this earth, and I found the
image totally, totally disgusting. And I was trying to put that
picture away from my mind when I came across your write-up.
</P>
<P>
   Is this thing going to keep haunting me now?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ramona Rougerie, West Palm Beach
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, Ramona, a pea up the nose is nothing. Someday the
practical man will tell the tale of Little Peter's Potty and the
Mystery Marble. That's the image that's still haunting him.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man,
</P>
<P>
   I enjoyed your April 2 column. When one of my daughters stuffed
a cherry pit up her nose, I panicked and called my doctor who told
me to bring her right down. Instead, I poured some black pepper
into my palm and asked her to sniff it. Out popped the pit along
with the sneeze that ensued _ thus saving the doctor's time and my
daughter's discomfort. Pass it along!
</P>
<P>
   _ Audrey Hirsch, Royal Palm Beach
</P>
<P>
   Send questions and comments to The Practical Man, Accent, The
Palm Beach Post, P.O. Box 24696, West Palm Beach, Fla. 33416. Or
e-mail PracticalMan (at)pbpost.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
