<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEIGER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Steiger reflects on long career of triumphs, failures
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 74, Rod Steiger looks back at a long career of more than 100
films and TV movies and sees plenty enough that's good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 60 percent virgin and 40 percent whore,'' he says bluntly.
``I've not sold out that much. I've made my own triumphs, and I've
made my own mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   In movies he's portrayed Rasputin, Pontius Pilate, Rudolph Hess,
Mussolini, Napoleon and Al Capone. He landed his first Oscar
nomination for his second film: 1954's best picture winner, ``On
the Waterfront,'' opposite Marlon Brando. Later came ``The
Pawnbroker,'' the tale of a tormented Auschwitz survivor, and
another Oscar nomination. Then he won best actor as the Mississippi
bigot in the racially ignited ``In the Heat of the Night.'' A few
years later came one of his biggest mistakes. He turned down
``Patton,'' which ultimately went to George C. Scott, and instead
filmed ``Waterloo.''
</P>
<P>
   At 8 tonight, Steiger recaps much of his career in Turner
Classic Movies' ``Private Screenings: Rod Steiger,'' a thoroughly
interesting and often revealing hourlong interview hosted by Robert
Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Screenings,'' Steiger talks openly about his love-hate
relationship with his alcoholic mother, his absent father and key
events that led to some of his greatest movie scenes. For example,
his renowned ``silent scream'' in ``The Pawnbroker'' was inspired
by his recollection of seeing Picasso's ``Guernica'' with its
powerful images of Spanish figures, heads titled back and arms
raised upward, in complete despair.
</P>
<P>
   Steiger came to Atlanta late last year to film ``Screenings''
and visited a few art galleries in Buckhead. Age has made it much
more difficult for him to walk. He covers his enormous frame
head-to-toe in black knit. When he takes off his hat, his bald head
and sagging jowls make him resemble Darth Vader _ minus the mask.
But his voice still booms, his passion for work remains unbridled
(last year, he played supporting roles in ``Crazy in Alabama,''
``End of Days'' and Oscar nominee Denzel Washington's ``The
Hurricane'').
</P>
<P>
   Steiger also sat down at TCM to a hefty lunch of fried chicken,
mashed potatoes and pecan pie and talked about his years as an
actor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw a quote recently where you were lamenting that TV
acting was creeping into the movies. What did you mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: It wasn't the acting. It was the diminishing of the time for
rehearsing. We don't get hardly any time anymore. You know, movies
would be 80 percent better if actors would do more homework. They
don't, especially the ones who think they are gifted. Because many
of them don't come from the theater. So they don't understand that
rehearsing gives you the courage to do more things. When you don't
feel secure, you unconsciously resort to a cliche whether you are a
reporter or a mechanic or anything.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There was a story going around a while back that you and the
writer for ``Crazy in Alabama'' got into a big row. Seems you
weren't speaking the dialogue as written.
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know. I improvise a lot. I think an actor should
change whatever makes him feel comfortable except the thought of a
line. Or the cue. It's like porridge. If it's too hot, maybe you
want to put some more milk in it. Go ahead, I don't care. As long
as the point is ultimately the same. The porridge and the cue are
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read over and over again that you turned down ``Patton''
but have never read why. So why?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your strength depends on how you feel, physically and
mentally. I had had all these successes _ the Academy Award or
whatever it was. So my philosophies were stronger. I said I'm not
going to glamorize a guy who had to do with killing and war. I was
a schmuck. It was a very big business, professional mistake. 'Cause
if I had done ``Patton'' half as good as Mr. Scott, I would have
walked into ``The Godfather.'' But I said, ah no, I'm not going to
do this. So we all make mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But in turning it down, you played Napoleon in ``Waterloo.''
Wasn't that about war?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's different. That's historical. ``Patton'' showed the
ruthless killing. When you see something that's 100 years ago, it's
more of a story.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which of your films do you think speaks most to the public?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The Pawnbroker'' spoke to a lot of people who were not
Jewish. Of course, one of the essences of the film is loneliness.
And that touches anybody. I think ``The Harder They Fall'' taught a
lot of people who weren't interested in boxing what the boxing
world was like. But that's a peripheral perk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Private Screenings: Rod Steiger''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on Turner Classic Movies, followed by 1967's ``In the
Heat of the Night'' (9 p.m.), a repeat of ``Screenings'' (11 p.m.),
1959's ``Al Capone'' (midnight) and 1965's ``Doctor Zhivago'' (2
a.m.). Three more films air Friday on Steiger's 75th birthday:
1968's ``No Way to Treat a Lady'' (8 p.m.), 1956's ``The Harder
They Fall'' (10 p.m.) and the 1956 Western ``Jubal'' (midnight).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
