r l BC-USHER-HERO?11-COX     04-10 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USHER-HERO?11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An accident, a celebrity, a mystery
 &HT;    By Lyle Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Andrew LaRocco and James Ward saw a fellow
motorist emerge from a burning wreck last winter, they rushed to
her aid.
</P>
<P>
   LaRocco says he got her to roll on the ground to extinguish the
flames that had charred her clothes and skin. Joining him moments
later, Ward says he helped move her and stayed by her side as she
softly uttered prayers.
</P>
<P>
   But when the story became national news, neither man got any
credit. It all went instead to pop idol Usher Raymond, the
20-year-old recording artist and movie star who lives in
Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Even though LaRocco and Ward said they never saw Raymond, the
woman's son heard that Raymond had intervened and went on a local
radio station to thank him. Usher accepted his gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the tale of Raymond as a celebrity-hero was born. But
Raymond won't talk about what role he played.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never wanted it publicized in the first place,'' says
Jonetta Patton, the star's mother and manager. ``He did it out of
the goodness of his heart. Usher doesn't want to talk about it
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident took place about 10 p.m. Jan 17. Danielle Marcia
Wright, 47, of Marietta, Ga., was driving east on I-285 in a Ford
Mustang convertible. The Mustang crashed into a retaining wall,
then was hit by another car, and exploded. Wright died Feb. 24 at
Grady Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   LaRocco, Ward and three other eyewitnesses who were contacted by
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution said they did not see Raymond. The
officer who took statements at the scene didn't see him either. ``I
remember his face because I met him at a Hawks game last year,''
says DeKalb Officer R.L. Knock. ``My son has one of his albums.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Wright's son, Army Sgt. Norris Sanders, went to Grady
to see his mother, he says nurses told him that Raymond had been
there to visit. He says Raymond also tried to call his family. ``My
grandmother spoke to him, but she didn't know who he was and she
lost the number,'' Sanders says. So Sanders called Ryan Cameron,
morning disc jockey for Hot-97.5 radio, to contact Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron persuaded Raymond to speak with Sanders by telephone on
his March 3 show. It was a brief but heartwarming exchange in which
Sanders expressed his gratitude and Raymond confirmed that he had
helped Wright at the accident scene.
</P>
<P>
   The tape of the conversation cannot be found, Cameron's producer
says now. But Cameron remembers the conversation this way: ``Usher
happened onto the scene after the collision occurred, and he at
least helped put out the fire on Mrs. Wright. He was holding her on
the ground on the scene. Mrs. Wright was praying, saying, 'God is
good.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ward remembers her uttering the same phrase.
</P>
<P>
   After the radio show aired, the story of Raymond's heroism
whipsawed through the music media. MTV.com ran a story on its Web
site, which included an audio clip of his voice from the radio
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just prayed to God and asked that (he) allow me to do the
right thing, because I didn't want to make it worse than it
actually was. I did the best that I could,'' Raymond says on the
clip.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders remains convinced that Raymond helped his mother.
LaRocco and several other witnesses at the scene said they never
saw Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard Usher on the radio, I thought he must have been
talking about another accident,'' says Dani Bethea, 28, of Atlanta,
who also stopped to help and later gave her statement to police.
</P>
<P>
   LaRocco, a 31-year-old Avondale Estates, Ga., resident who owns
an employee benefits company, says he was driving behind Wright's
car and saw the crash. As he stopped to help, LaRocco says, he saw
Wright punch a hole in the burning roof. Enveloped in flames, she
clambered across the trunk and fell to her knees.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, 50, is a paramedic for a private ambulance service who was
returning home after teaching a course in emergency treatment. He
remembers the aftermath of the accident vividly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked her up to move her, but there was nothing to hold
her by because so much of her body was burning,'' says Ward, who
also placed his jacket over her. ``She was saying `God is good. God
is great.'''
</P>
<P>
   LaRocco is adamant that Raymond didn't assist. Ward is nearly as
sure. ``I don't think anyone else put a jacket over her. I guess it
could have happened, but I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
