<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2527 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WOMEN-WORKPLACE11-COX     04-10 1726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-WORKPLACE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dressing for success has new meaning for women in business world
today
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Rebekah Lowe remembers one of the
earliest career-building tips she received as a young woman
starting out in business: If you're pregnant, you should never
mention anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like the elephant in the living room,'' said
Lowe, East Florida regional executive for Wachovia Bank. ``Heaven
forbid anyone realize I'm female.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, who manages bank operations from Titusville to Miami, says
those views have changed profoundly over the past 10 years as women
have established themselves as competent and confident
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am much more comfortable,'' said Lowe, 41, from her office
in downtown West Palm Beach. ``I have felt the need and desire to
be far more integrated with my personal and work life ... People I
work with know plenty about my husband and my children and my golf
game.''
</P>
<P>
   While pioneering business women often felt compelled to avoid
acknowledging their home lives and to cover up their sexuality,
women in today's work force are freer to express _ and even
celebrate _ their beauty and femininity.
</P>
<P>
   And they are finding it can be good for their careers. After
all, men traditionally have relied on the power of charm and a good
golf game to boost their business image.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can get in the door with your looks and prove it with
your brains, more power to you,'' said Michelle Brown, manager of
communications and public relations for Triarc Restaurant Group,
the Fort Lauderdale-based franchiser of Arby's.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 31, is typical of a new generation of women in business
who are unapologetic about using more than confidence and smarts to
get ahead. The shift in attitude is evident in the way women dress
and interact at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Boxy business suits and masculine bow ties have given way to
soft twin sets and colorful pantsuits. And women are comfortable
offering a nurturing ear to a male colleague as well as engaging in
friendly banter, teasing and even flirtation.
</P>
<P>
   `PART OF THE PACKAGE'
</P>
<P>
   ``Society in general is moving off this model of how the
corporate person should look and respond,'' said Rosalind Murray,
executive director of Board Connection, which recruits and trains
people for the boards of nonprofit groups in Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, she said, ``people are no longer trying to keep
those things that make them a woman in a little box that you open
at 5 o'clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's morning ritual includes makeup, fragrance, jewelry and a
classic, yet always womanly, outfit. ``For me, beauty equates
professionalism,'' said Brown, who lives in Lake Worth. And as the
mother of two young boys, she says talking about her kids at the
office helps her connect with others and build work relationships
with women and men.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, 41, who also serves as president of the Palm Beach
County chapter of the National Coalition of 100 Black Women, a
leadership and advocacy group, said her style of dress has softened
and become more comfortable over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might throw on a silk suit,'' she said. ``I also like to
dress down some days, wear Capri pants and a sweater set. Before, I
would never show any cleavage at all. Now, I might show some _ it's
part of the package.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more of an expression of who I am as opposed to
what people want me to look like as a woman in business.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that doesn't mean dressing inappropriately. But,
Murray reasons, men are never told, ``make sure you are less
handsome at work.''
</P>
<P>
   That sort of self-assuredness comes from knowing and believing
in yourself, a confidence made possible by the women who marched
off to work 30 years ago, said Gayle Landen, a local consultant and
past president of the Executive Women of the Palm Beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this has happened because we have paid our dues,'' said
Landen, president of Landen, Wells &AMP; Associates, a business
consulting firm in Palm Beach Gardens. ``There were many women who
started in the '60s and '70s that wore the corporate uniforms and
got places on the board and mentored to others.''
</P>
<P>
   As a consultant for General Motors Corp. in the early 1980s,
Landen remembers seeing a room of women executives all dressed in
navy blue and black suits. Today, she said, you'll also see pants,
designer suits and bright colors.
</P>
<P>
   Carly Fiorina, who became chief executive of Hewlett-Packard Co.
last year, was pictured on a recent magazine cover wearing a
stylish red pantsuit. The attractive, 45-year-old CEO narrates one
of the company's new TV spots, appearing in tight close-up.
</P>
<P>
   LETTING THEIR HAIR DOWN
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauty is an asset in our society, no matter what sex you
are,'' said Murray, of Board Connection. ``To mask it could be
taking away some opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as recently as a few years ago, women, especially
younger ones in positions of power or authority, felt pressure to
conform to the once popular view that when it comes to women,
attractiveness and intelligence don't mix.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Rep. Sharon Merchant (R-North Palm Beach) said she felt
she had to look ``conservative and smart'' when she first ran for
office at age 28. As a result, she wore dark suits and always
pulled back her hair.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at 36, Merchant wears ``whatever color I want, and I
don't wear my hair up that much anymore.'' Why? ``I've just gotten
more comfortable with the role I play,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Karen Marcus, who at 32 was the youngest woman ever
elected to the Palm Beach County Commission, said she wore long
skirts and high-neck blouses and put her hair in a matronly bun for
years after she was elected in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus, 47, said she consciously downplayed her beauty in the
early years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had people tell me I couldn't run because I'm too
attractive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Marcus, who admits she ``couldn't wait to get out of those
suits,'' feels more comfortable wearing stylish clothes that are
flattering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around long enough _ I've at least proven there is
some substance behind the outside,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Young women moving up in business today, however, feel less
compelled to suppress the very things that make them attractive as
women. Much of that has to do with the success of women like
Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart women now are pretty _ pretty women are smart,'' said
Brown, of Triarc Restaurant Group. ``You have more and more
examples nowadays of attractive, intelligent women.''
</P>
<P>
   Look no further than the pages of Fortune or The Wall Street
Journal for proof of that.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Fiorina of Hewlett-Packard, there is Jill Barad,
who last month stepped down as CEO of Mattel Inc., and Andrea Jung,
who became Avon Products Inc.'s first woman CEO last year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, nearly 12 percent of the 11,681 corporate officers in
America's top 500 companies were women, up from 8.7 percent five
years earlier, according to a study released last year by the
women's research group Catalyst.
</P>
<P>
   `ONE BIG FAMILY'
</P>
<P>
   While women still struggle to balance their family and work
lives, the idea that a woman can be young, attractive, maternal and
at the same time excel at the office is no longer questioned by
many women in their 20s and 30s. Kate Betts, the former fashion
news director at Vogue, last year took the top job at Harper's
Bazaar, the country's oldest fashion magazine. Three days after
accepting the high-profile job, Betts gave birth to her first
child, at 35.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Dunn, the 35-year-old vice president of investor
relations and public relations for Office Depot Inc., had her first
child six months ago. Dunn said she never worries about how
investors or colleagues perceive the way she looks or dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really counts is do you know the numbers,'' she said. ``I
don't think I have to prove myself. I have to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, who handled investor relations for Talbots Inc. before
joining Office Depot nearly two years ago, is the only woman on a
wing of offices that houses the Delray Beach-based company's top
executives, including CEO David Fuente and Chief Financial Officer
Barry Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   At a fairly senior level herself, Dunn feels free to joke with
her male colleagues, as well as to talk with them about family
life. ``They all have kids or grandkids,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This freedom, which some have referred to as the feminization of
the workplace, is evident at the West Palm Beach law firm of
Ackerman, Link &AMP; Sartory, where the managing partner, 35-year-old
Wendy Sartory Link, balances practicing law and caring for
17-month-old twins.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that only four of the 20 people on the firm's staff
are men. But, Link said, ``our work culture is that we are one big
family. We work together to get things done. The men share stories
about their families every bit as much as the women do.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm, which specializes in business and securities law, has
received awards for its gender- and family-friendly policies from
the Florida Bar Association, the Economic Council and the Business
Development Board of Palm Beach County. For example, all workers
get paid time off to spend at their children's schools.
</P>
<P>
   Those types of policies are becoming more prevalent as career
women have made child rearing a concern for working parents of both
sexes.
</P>
<P>
   The establishment of women firmly and comfortably in the
workplace has not only meant that women feel free to be themselves,
but also that the skills women bring to the business world are
increasingly valued, said Landen, the business consultant.
</P>
<P>
   `THIS IS JUST THE BEGINNING'
</P>
<P>
   ``They build better families and teams,'' Landen said. ``They
listen better and they are not afraid to take risks. They have
fierce advocacy for what they believe in. They take great joy in
watching those behind them grow or their children grow and
flourish. Women have a great sense of celebration and joy _ that
makes it exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning. Women have the right kinds of
skills and they are comfortable with themselves. They are going to
dress and decorate their homes and drive the cars that express
themselves as a whole woman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
