<HEADLINE>
LISTEN UP, GANG _ GOOD OLD BILL GATES NEEDS OUR HELP 
 
</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as soon as I finish my coffee this morning, I'm going to
get on the phone and start organizing an effort to form a human
chain around Bill Gates' house.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, I've never much cared for the fellow. But as I
try to make sense of what the devil's been happening to my paltry
401(k) fund lately, I can't help but think we need to keep the
Justice Department's mitts off him right now. He may be a greedy,
scheming monopolist, but by gum, he's our greedy, scheming
monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of people, I grumble at the mere mention of his name
anymore. I can trace my contempt to the maddening evening a few
years ago when I tried to use Microsoft Word to update my resume.
</P>
<P>
   I was so crazed and bug-eyed by the time I finished erasing the
unwelcome indentations and herding paragraphs back where they
belonged, the only person I could have beaten out for a job was
Theodore Kaczynski, and that's only if he grew his beard back.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates, to me, symbolizes all that went wrong with
technology after, roughly, the creation of that primitive
electronic game, ``Pong.'' Back then, the ball moved ever-so-slowly
between the paddles, and we could all grasp the point of the
information age.
</P>
<P>
   It's grown dizzyingly fast and complex since then. Most of us
have no choice but to imitate John McEnroe. We scream obscenities
and throw operator's manuals at the line judge _ the unblinking,
poker-faced Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   My dislike for him grew even more intense a couple of years ago
when I read that he makes about $150 a second.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Templeton, the founder of an Internet newspaper called
ClariNet, did the math. In 1998, Billy Boy was worth an estimated
$40 billion, a sum accumulated over the course of 22 years. That
works out to about $500,000 a hour, assuming he put in a yeomanly
14 hours every business day.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Gates rakes in about $150 a second. As Templeton noted, if
Gates walked down the sidewalk and spotted a $500 bill on the
ground, it might not be worth his while to take the four seconds
necessary to bend down and pick it up. Call me jealous, but I just
can't like a guy like that _ unless, of course, I happen to be
walking behind him on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Love him or hate him, though, I think we all need him right now.
</P>
<P>
   About a week ago, a fellow in Amsterdam posted information on
his financial Web site about a stock offering by a California-based
company called F/Rite Air, pronounced ``Fried Air.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, Webmaster Raymond Spanjar told visitors to his
site, had just developed an ``air ionizer'' that produces good
feelings rivaling Prozac. The product is so promising, he said, the
U.S. Air Force is testing it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure. Uh-huh. We ask our fighter pilots to test all of our
pharmaceuticals and mood-altering gizmos. As you've probably
discerned, good old Raymond was staging an April Fool's Day prank.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a few folks took him seriously, though. He announced on
his site that he had reserved 1 million shares and would sell them
to investors. According to the Reuters news agency, the offers
poured it. Before Raymond confessed it was a joke, he'd tallied up
15 million guilders, or $6.49 million worth of orders.
</P>
<P>
   The scary thing, Raymond says, is that not a single person asked
for a prospectus for F/Rite Air. In the birthplace of tulipmania,
people were ready to fork over money because, well, any silly idea
could make a person a millionaire nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Amsterdam, of course. Look at the chief executive
officers of our country's biggest companies. In its annual survey
of CEO pay, Bloomberg News reports that compensation packages
jumped 20.9 percent in 1999, thanks largely to dizzying profitable
stock options.
</P>
<P>
   The median CEO received $4.4 million in total pay, and the
average pay _ skewed by the biggest packages _ was a whopping $10.4
million a year. The list of big earners increasingly includes heads
of high-tech companies, some of which are still earning little or
no real profit.
</P>
<P>
   It's all castles in the air, in other words. Fried air, in some
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Right about now, good old cyberbaron Bill Gates looks about as
reliable as a friendly game of Pong. Join hands, won't you, please?
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
