<SLUG> BC-KOREA-TALKS-1STLD-WRITEHTHRU-1000&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS FOR A NORTH-SOUTH SUMMIT MEETING SURPRISE MANY SOUTH
KOREANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for complete writethru to restructure and add details.)  
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ An unusual catalog of emotions _ shock,
relief, wariness _ were on display Monday as South Koreans learned
that their country's president would go to North Korea in June for
the first-ever summit meeting with his communist counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   One reaction, nearly universal, was shock that a meeting few had
imagined possible had been successfully negotiated in secret. In
almost every case, the surprise was followed with a happy sense of
relief that the Cold War might finally be ending in one of its last
redoubts.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the practical question, asked by almost all: What will
it cost us?
</P>
<P>
   Such a mood-dampening question, on an occasion seemingly fit for
celebration, was an expression of the extraordinary circumstances
of a diplomatic breakthrough whose basis has still not been
publicly explained.
</P>
<P>
   Why, indeed, after years of snubbing South Korea as an
insignificant puppet of the United States, had the North Korean
government chosen the eve of crucial national elections in the
South to offer that country its most precious diplomatic plum?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all waiting for the details of what we must give them
and what we can expect from North Korea,'' said Yeon Ha-cheong, the
dean of the school of marketing, and an expert in relations with
that country at Myongai University, in Seoul. ``North Korea will
certainly demand lots of things.''
</P>
<P>
   After announcing the breakthrough Monday, the South Korean
government compounded the mystery by providing almost no
information about the secret negotiations that had led to the
agreement with the North. The government did say that the task of
fixing an agenda for the talks would be left to diplomats in the
weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That left many South Korean experts on North Korean diplomatic
behavior wondering aloud Monday who was playing whom. To hear them
speak, either the South Korean government was cynically
manipulating the issue of national unification for vote-getting
purposes, or the leadership was being had by a Pyongyang government
that sensed it was desperate for a pre-election breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, the legislative vote here on Thursday will
determine how much power the South Korean president, Kim Dae-jung,
wields for his remaining three years in office.
</P>
<P>
   And in addition to finally rewarding Kim for the steep political
risks he has taken in reaching out to the North, several analysts
here said that Pyongyang likely calculated that the eve of the vote
was the moment to strike a diplomatic deal at the highest price.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of meeting cannot come all of the sudden, out of
nowhere,'' said Cho Dong-ho, head of North Korean economic studies
at the Korea Development Institute, a private nonprofit group. ``No
one knows in detail, but the basic agenda must be a longer-term
framework of political contacts between us, and of course economic
cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although North Korea is widely believed to be past the worst of
its catastrophic economic difficulties of the last decade, when
200,000 or more people died of starvation, the country is still
afflicted with debilitating power shortages.
</P>
<P>
   One potential reward that was widely mentioned Monday as a
possible recompense for giving the South Korean president such a
diplomatic vindication on the eve of South Korea's elections was a
reconnection of the power grids between the two countries, enabling
the booming South to furnish desperately needed electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about quid pro quos has only been magnified by North
Korea's recent diplomatic behavior. For years, following the end of
the Cold War and the loss of most of its communist allies, the
country bore the title of the world's most isolated regime.
</P>
<P>
   But North Korea has recently emerged as one of the most
diplomatically active countries, as it has rushed to establish ties
with a wide range of countries. And in most instances, formal ties,
or even serious diplomatic contacts, have come at a steep price
tag.
</P>
<P>
   Persistent reports have circulated in recent weeks that
Pyongyang, since agreeing to resume official talks with Japan, has
sought $5 billion in ``reparations'' from that country for Tokyo's
brutal colonial past in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, too, has often been put in a position where
it has had to commit to helping ease North Korea's economic
catastrophe _ through major food or fuel deliveries _ in exchange
for Pyongyang's cooperation in suspending nuclear weapons
development or in halting the testing of long range missiles.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kim's political rivals, feeling threatened by a dramatic
diplomatic turnabout after weeks of campaigning against his
so-called Sunshine Policy _ the program of steady diplomatic and
financial engagement with North Korea that produced the
breakthrough _ by deeming it a fruitless sellout of South Korea,
Monday clung to the line that the coming summit meeting, with its
hidden and presumably high costs, was no victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government must have paid a huge price, or agreed to some
secret conditions to reach this deal, but that side has not been
revealed,'' said Jan Kwang-keun, a spokesman for the Grand National
Party, the main opposition group. ``We want to remind people that
such compensations involve taxpayers' money.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The public's reaction, although largely positive, was often
laden with complex sentiments and anxieties that are the legacy of
the two countries' shared history of wartime violence,
yield-no-quarter ideological jousting and harshly contrasting
economic fates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really think these countries will unify anytime soon?''
asked Han Kyoung-ok, a 51-year-old woman who was preparing to board
a train to Pusan at midday. ``For people of my generation, this is
good news. But younger people have grown soft in this country, and
now I fear that the northerners, who have lived through so much,
will out-compete us.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, this statement reflected the fact that in the span of
her life _ roughly the period since June 1950 when the war that
left the countries divided broke out _ Han has witnessed an
extraordinary turnabout in the fortunes of the both countries.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of their separate histories, the communist
North, although more sparsely peopled, was by far the more
prosperous of the two.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970s, though, and accelerating more each year, South
Korea has outstripped its neighbor, becoming one of the world's
most energetic and entrepreneurial societies. The Stalinist North,
though still heavily armed, has meanwhile flirted with economic
collapse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like Han, several people here expressed trepidation about the
diplomatic opening with the North and the unpredictability of
renewing high-level contact between countries that share the same
language, history and culture but that have been so divided by
politics and economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't support unification, because things are nice the way
they are now,'' said Hwang Ji-hwa, a 21-year-old woman, who spoke
in downtown Seoul. ``There are just too many differences between
our countries. If we try to unify, things might get out of hand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
