<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-LATER-TODAY11-COX     04-10 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATER-TODAY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Viewers tuning in to `Later Today'
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sitting in their cozy ``Later Today'' kitchen set,
Jodi Applegate, Florence Henderson and Asha Blake are doing what
they do best: goofing off.
</P>
<P>
   It's 10:05 a.m. The gabby trio just finished taping their
daytime series. Now it's time to tape what is TV's most annoying
tag line _ ``It's like `Today,' only later.''
</P>
<P>
   Applegate is the first to flub her line. She tries again. The
forever bouncy anchor stumbles once more, still unable to say the
name of her show without stammering. The third time, however,
Applegate's delivery is flawless. But now Henderson, looking mighty
elegant with $500,000 worth of Harry Winston diamonds draped around
her neck (it was for an Oscar fashion show segment), hams it up by
pronouncing later ``Laaaaa-tahhhhhhhh.'' Blake, the Halle Berry
clone, is in stitches.
</P>
<P>
   A few moments pass. Now Ma Brady belts out the word later as if
she's performing an aria at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure our slogan is a bit hokey,'' Blake admits later in her
dressing room. ``But it's grown on us. It's fun and the audience
has come to expect us to have fun with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And more viewers are having fun watching ``Later Today.''
Developed and produced by NBC News, ``Later Today'' was created to
capitalize on ``Today's'' colossal success. Like its mighty cousin,
``Later Today'' is a mixture of hard news, consumer information and
celebrity chit-chat. One moment Applegate is wondering if Leelee
Sobieski's co-star was a good kisser in the film ``Here on Earth,''
the next she's rolling on the floor giving a dog CPR. The show's
primary emphasis, however, is giving viewers news they can use.
There have been segments, for instance, on overcoming shyness, how
to find the right diet and enjoying sex after 45.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reviews, however, weren't kind. TV Guide said ``Later
Today'' was ``especially disappointing.'' The New York Daily News
called it ``as shallow as a birdbath.'' The New York Times
proclaimed the show was ``unoriginal (and) unexciting.'' The
Orlando Sentinel cracked it should be called ``Later Insipidity.''
</P>
<P>
   Applegate, who co-anchored ``Weekend Today'' on NBC as well as
serving as an MSNBC daytime anchor, shrugs off those early reviews.
``The original `Today' show was panned in 1952,'' says the
35-year-old New York University graduate, ``so it doesn't matter at
all. In the long run, what matters is, do the viewers like it?''
</P>
<P>
   And more apparently do. The numbers tell the story: Last
September, ``Later Today'' averaged a 2.1 rating and 2.4 million
viewers. As of the week of March 27, those numbers were up to a 2.3
rating and 2.6 million viewers, representing a 21 percent increase
over ``Leeza,'' the show that aired in the same time slot on NBC
last year. By comparison, ``The View,'' the popular ABC gabfest
``Later Today'' is usually compared to, averages a 2.7 rating and
2.9 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But the road to increased ratings and more viewers has been a
rocky one. Like any new show, ``Later Today'' continues to be a
work in progress. Gone are those insipid true and false questions
the hosts asked the audience about ``Today.'' Also, Applegate,
Henderson and Blake no longer cram 5,000 topics to discuss at the
top of the hour. Celebrity interviews are longer, and so are many
of the show's segments. For example, a recent segment on Mary
Vincent, a woman who was raped and brutalized 20 years ago, ran for
16 minutes _ the length of two segments. ``Early on, we never would
have done that,'' says Michael Bass, ``Later Today's'' executive
producer. ``Before, we were jamming too many things into one show
and we weren't getting enough information across. Now the pacing is
a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass, who is also ``Today's'' senior broadcast producer, points
out that ``Later Today'' is taking more risks. The true and false
bit with the audience may be history, but that hasn't stopped the
show from turning the studio audience into another guest. ``We want
to use the studio audience to our advantage,'' Bass says. ``Instead
of doing a regular fashion show, we did a game show. We had people
from the audience as contestants and they had to decide if
something was purchased at a bargain store like Target or at a
designer place on Fifth Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of the problems with a hybrid show like ``Later Today''
is it must marry the delicate mix of hard news and fluff. For
instance, on a recent show, ``Later Today'' rebroadcast Katie
Couric's interview with John and Patsy Ramsey. The mood in the
studio was somber and deadly quiet. A few minutes later, though,
there was the bubbly Henderson, presiding over a wild Oscar fashion
show. ``It's a difficult balance,'' says Blake, 37. ``One moment,
it's hard news, then you're cooking truffles. It's not always
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The on-air chemistry between Applegate, Henderson and Blake
wasn't easy to develop, either. Unlike the women on ``The View,''
the ``Later Today'' conversations and friendly you-go-girl chat
sessions often felt forced and stilted. Even Bass admits the
chemistry ``wasn't so great'' in the beginning. But Blake notes
that was to be expected early on. ``It's like when you meet
somebody for the first time when you're dating,'' says the
Minnesota native and former co-anchor of ABC News' ``World News
Now.'' ``You tell them who you are, and you're listening to who
they are and after a year or two, you hit them on the shoulder and
say, 'What the heck are you wearing?' You feel comfortable around
them. Now I can say, 'Florence, that's a hideous color of
lipstick.'''
</P>
<P>
   Applegate, who amazingly can turn her nose into a blaring
trumpet (she does dead-on Chuck Mangione tunes), readily admits
meeting the former ``Brady Bunch'' star was intimidating. ``Who
among us did not grow up watching `The Brady Bunch'?'' she says.
``That was a little surreal. It was like meeting Mr. Spock or
Captain Kirk.''
</P>
<P>
   And Applegate still can't get over Henderson's girlish figure.
``She has four children, she's been on this earth 30 years longer
than I have and she has the cutest little figure that I never
had,'' she marvels. ``Well, maybe I had it for five minutes when I
was 11.''
</P>
<P>
   Three women. One TV show. Can they all really get along?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever is the opposite of the catty, back fighting
stereotype, that's what we are,'' Applegate says. ``We're pals and
friends and often go out together.''
</P>
