<HEADER>
A2549 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SENIORS-SCHOOL11-COX     04-10 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORS-SCHOOL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer school for the 55-and-over set: It's the latest thing
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When you're over 55, you don't want to
spend your summer sitting on the beach drinking Margaritas.
</P>
<P>
   You want to spend it in summer school.
</P>
<P>
   Because this isn't your kid's summer school, with tired teachers
drumming pre-algebra into less-than-receptive brains. Senior summer
school means classrooms on the side of a mountain in Nepal or
studying music in the Opera House in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Elderhostel, Interhostel, Senior Summer School, Explore. These
are some of the organizations that offer ``schools'' for seniors,
where they can study art, political science, health and religion.
Many times, the classroom goes on the road. And at these schools
there's no homework and no tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stop learning at this point in your life, you're dull
and have nothing to look forward to,'' says Florence
Million-Kleeman of West Palm Beach, who as gone on two Senior
Summer School trips and is planning another one this summer.
``Sitting on a beach would be boring, not to mention getting
melanoma. I want to learn and be a part of things.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior schools say many, if not most, of their students come
from Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest market is South Florida,'' says Brian Bussian,
program director for Senior Summer School. ``We have a lot of
retired professionals who have worked and traveled a lot.'' These
students spend two to 10 weeks studying college level courses _
political science and international relations are popular _
especially designed for them at schools including the University of
Wisconsin, the University of California, San Diego State
University, the University of Judaism in Los Angeles and Marymount
Manhattan College. While the regular students are gone for the
summer, the seniors can take advantage of inexpensive university
dormitory lodging.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year-old organization, based in Deerfield Beach, has seen
the number of participants double in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, Bussian says, is this age group has the money and
they're not interested in traditional tours. ``They want in-depth
study-tours, small classes, field trips and a home-away-from-home
feeling that a university setting offers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sociology experts who study buying trends are not surprised by
the interest in adult travel schools. ``When you're in your 20s and
30s, you buy things. In your 40s and 50s, you buy services,'' says
Minneapolis trends consultant Hazel Reinhardt. ``But after 60, you
seek experiences, travel and study.''
</P>
<P>
   True, says Million-Kleemann. ``I don't want more possessions,''
she says. ``At this point in life you have enough. But I want to
enjoy life as much as God will give me.''
</P>
<P>
   She studied literature at San Diego University for a month last
summer and then went to the University of Judaism in Los Angeles
with Senior Summer School. ``It was the most glorious summer I've
ever had. The classes were wonderful. There was lots of discussion,
and not the strain or stress like when you went to school. You're
just there to learn. You go at your own pace.''
</P>
<P>
   She has signed up for two months in San Diego this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Jaffe, a professor at Florida Atlantic University, and
his wife, Mata, a semi-retired college professor of speech
pathology, have taken seven study-trips with Interhostel, a
nonprofit, international educational organization run by the
University of New Hampshire. Among the places they've visited:
Nepal, France, Morocco, Spain, Guatemala, Mexico, Belize and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their trips are extremely educational,'' says Arthur Jaffe.
``They have alliances with local universities that provide
leadership and professors who are specialists in health, economy
and history.''
</P>
<P>
   Classes often go beyond the classroom, he says. ``They give you
a little carrying stool, and you might stop and sit under a tree,
while a local expert explains what we're on our way to see.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to hear about things, and quite another to go to
a place and see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Nepal, they have so little but they share and take care of
one another. It's wonderful, it's not every man for himself. We can
learn from them. And many Americans would think they were
backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee and Janet Arcand of North Palm Beach have spent two
Christmases in Interhostel programs _ one in Prague and the other
in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Prague, we went to concerts, castles, churches and museums,
and had educational lectures at our hotel about the history of the
area,'' says Janet Arcand. ``We experienced a traditional Czech
Christmas dinner, and they brought in a pastry chef and we made
cookies. The women from the church taught us Christmas carols, and
we went to a lace factory and a Christmas ornament factory. We saw
a ballet, `Romeo and Juliet,' and went to Carlsbad Spa.''
</P>
<P>
   In Vienna, they attended lectures about the history of Christmas
music and went to three operas.
</P>
<P>
   But probably nothing could compare to attending a New Year's Eve
ball at the Vienna City Hall. Lee wore a tuxedo and Janet wore a
black jeweled gown and they waltzed for the first time in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
