<HEADLINE>
RAIN, SNOW AND A PAUSE FOR APRIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, April 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Periods of rain will develop in the Middle Atlantic and
Northeastern states Tuesday as warm, moist air passes over chilly
air at the surface. Farther north, the air will be cold enough to
cause scattered patches of snow in New England, with accumulations
likely from the northern Hudson Valley to the Green and White
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, showers will develop ahead of a cold front in the
Ohio and Tennessee Valleys. Some of these showers will be
accompanied by brief bursts of heavy rain. Showers and strong
thunderstorms will develop over Texas as the same front moves into
increasingly warmer and more humid air.
</P>
<P>
   A large area of high pressure over the Western states will
provide abundant sunshine and unseasonably mild readings. Warm
conditions will spread to the Pacific Coast as light offshore
breezes keep skies sunny.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: APRIL PAUSE
</P>
<P>
   Many have heard of the January Thaw, a few days of above
seasonal readings in late January that occurs most years in the
Northeast. There is another less known blip in the temperature
record which happens in early April in the East. Long-term
temperature records show a marked leveling of the average
temperature during the first week of this month, a pause in the
progressive rise to springtime readings at many eastern locations.
The current chilly weather only helps reinforce this April pause. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
