<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2552 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CHARTER11-COX     04-10 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As deal fails, Charter Behavioral Health Systems seeks new buyer
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The expected buyer of the core business of Charter
Behavioral Health Systems' 37 hospitals has pulled out of the
proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Alpharetta, Ga.-based Charter said Monday that 30 other
organizations are interested in buying the business of some or all
of the company's psychiatric facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Charter, currently under Chapter 11 protection, said bids for
the hospital business are due into the bankruptcy court next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Crescent Operating said a new subsidiary, COPI
Healthcare, does not expect to close on the purchase of the Charter
business assets. In February, Charter said that it had a firm offer
of $24.5 million from the COPI unit to acquire the hospitals'
business, which has undergone a major downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   Crescent Operating did not elaborate on its statement. A related
firm, Texas-based Crescent Real Estate Equities, still owns most of
the Charter buildings and properties.
</P>
<P>
   Six Charter hospitals are in metro Atlanta. ``There's quite a
bit of interest in the Atlanta hospitals,'' said Charter
spokeswoman Karen Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   But she added, ``To sell (the Charter system) as a whole would
allow us to continue business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said after the bids arrive, an auction for the hospitals
will take place, and that Charter will recommend the winner to the
bankruptcy judge. Any sale must be approved by the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The court will also eventually decide the issue of severance
packages for more than 4,000 employees of 33 hospitals that Charter
recently closed. Those layoffs have prompted former Charter
employees to sue the company, demanding severance pay and
accumulated vacation pay.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Charter's hospitals in Georgia _ in Athens, Macon, and
Augusta _ have closed, leading to 452 layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Charter has about 5,000 employees nationwide, providing services
for 2,000 hospital patients and for thousands receiving outpatient
services.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently has grappled with lower payments from
health insurers and a U.S. Justice Department investigation into
patient care issues. A ``60 Minutes II'' broadcast last year
alleged patient injuries, deaths and other problems at Charter
facilities. Charter denied systemwide problems exist.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
