<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2553 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ASTEROID-ART-2TAK     04-10 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTEROID-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING A CLOSE LOOK AT ONE OF EARTH'S NEIGHBORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Colo., Calif., N.Y., Ariz.)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 21 and graphic are being sent to NYT
photo/graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking cautious baby steps, a robotic spacecraft is to settle
Tuesday into a closer orbit of an asteroid it has been circling for
almost two months. Guided by gentle shoves from small thruster
rockets, the craft, NEAR Shoemaker, is taking up a circular orbit
62 miles from the center of the asteroid Eros for more detailed
studies.
</P>
<P>
   After spending about 11 days at this altitude, the craft is to
take another downstep on its way to settling in at a height of 31
miles for months of close-up observations of the pitted, tumbling,
rocky mass below.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to give us our first real chance to understand
the structure of an asteroid,'' said Dr. Andrew F. Cheng, the
project scientist with the Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics
Laboratory in Laurel, Md., which built the craft for NASA and
controls the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there are many different types of asteroids out
there, perhaps dozens of varieties,'' Cheng said. ``If we ever want
to mine one for minerals or deflect one, we have to know the
structure of these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Spacecraft have gone by about a half-dozen asteroids, and each
appears very different from the others, scientists say. Some are
coal-black and reflect little light, while others appear bright.
And some seem to be solid rock, while others appear to be
conglomerations of smaller structures and dust loosely held
together by gravity.
</P>
<P>
   The Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous (NEAR) spacecraft, after a
four-year journey from Earth, on Feb. 14 became the first to orbit
an asteroid and settle in for long-term studies. Last month, the
1,700-pound craft was renamed NEAR Shoemaker in honor of the late
Dr. Eugene M. Shoemaker, a pioneer in the study of asteroid and
comet impacts on the planets.
</P>
<P>
   Eros is one of the larger asteroids, measuring about 21 miles
long and 8 miles thick. It is a potato-shaped rock covered with
craters, unexplained long grooves, and a large gouge in the center.
Because of the asteroid's relatively small size, odd shape and the
fact that it rolls end-over-end instead of turning on its long
axis, orbiting the body is tricky.
</P>
<P>
   Eros' gravitational field is so slight that the spacecraft must
keep its speed down to about 3 mph to stay in orbit. Controllers
are taking so long to lower NEAR Shoemaker to its optimum study
altitude because they must first map variations in the asteroid's
density, and resulting gravitational deviations that could affect
the tenuous orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary results from NEAR Shoemaker and its six main
instruments indicate that the cratered asteroid, now 130 million
miles from Earth, is strewn with boulders, rocks and a loose layer
of gravity-bound debris called regolith. Energy from three
unexpected solar flares last month bounced off the asteroid and
allowed the spacecraft's X-ray/gamma ray spectrometer to pick up
signs of surface minerals sooner than planned. The readings suggest
a surface that contains magnesium, aluminum, silicon, calcium and
iron, researchers report.
</P>
<P>
   The so-far successful $224 million mission, scheduled to orbit
and study Eros for a year, was the first launched under NASA's new
Discovery Program of streamlined ``faster, better, cheaper''
planetary missions. The concept has come under scrutiny because of
last year's failures of two Mars spacecraft, and recent reports
that criticized the management of those projects.
</P>
<P>
   NEAR Shoemaker marks the beginning of intensified asteroid
studies in coming years as scientists using Earth-based instruments
and spacecraft try to uncover the nature of the tens of thousands
of rocky bodies circling the sun in a belt between Mars and
Jupiter, and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   This heightened interest is both scientific and practical.
Asteroids are believed to be leftover material from the formation
of the solar system more than 4 billion years ago. And scientists
believe that early asteroids colliding with the primal Earth may
have brought with them minerals, water and even the building blocks
of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life on this planet definitely has been shaped by asteroid
impacts,'' said Dr. Clark R. Chapman, an asteroid expert at the
Southwest Research Institute in Boulder, Colo., ``and it
conceivably could happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe the bodies in the asteroid belt are the
remnants of material that failed to form into a planet in the early
years of the solar system, perhaps because of the gravitational
influences of giant Jupiter. Colliding asteroids in this region are
believed to be a primary source of meteoroids that constantly
bombard Earth, some of which survive the heat of passing through
the atmosphere to reach the ground as meteorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there are as many types of asteroids as there are
types of meteoroids, and there are dozens of types of meteoroids,''
Cheng said. ``And there are obviously many asteroids we don't get
meteoroids from.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are particularly interested in an estimated 800 or
900 asteroids that are larger than 1 kilometer, or six-tenths of a
mile, in diameter whose orbits cross that of the Earth. These
so-called near-Earth asteroids, which include Eros, pose the most
obvious threat of one day colliding with Earth and causing massive
damage, although scientists say no such collision is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   While asteroid collisions with Earth are no longer as common as
in prehistoric times, scientists estimate that large ones still
occur every few hundred or thousand years. And in that lies a
practical reason for learning more about them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If, without warning, someone suddenly throws something at you,
it is hard to defend yourself if you do not know what it is. Your
reaction _ to duck, catch it or swat it away _ would be very
different depending on whether the object is a small pillow or a
brick.
</P>
<P>
   Since its formation, Earth has had a lot of things thrown its
way and has the bumps and bruises to prove it. And with more hits
inevitably coming, people are starting to think about doing
something about it. But scientists know so little about asteroids
and their makeup that they can only guess at ways to deflect or
destroy one imminently endangering Earth. Despite suggestions in
recent motion pictures that people can shatter or deflect an
approaching asteroid with large nuclear explosions, some scientists
say this proposed solution may not work with many types of
asteroids.
</P>
<P>
   The dark asteroid Mathilde, a 37-mile-long body that the NEAR
spacecraft passed in 1997 on its way to Eros, appears to be a loose
pile of rubble instead of a solid piece of rock. Readings from the
spacecraft, passing 753 miles from Mathilde, suggest the asteroid
has a density only slightly higher than water and surface evidence
of huge collisions that should have shattered a solid object.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidence suggests that Mathilde swallows up impacts, like
shooting a BB into a wad of fluff,'' said Dr. Donald K. Yeomans of
NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif. ``It would
stay together by just absorbing the energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its light density, an asteroid the size of Mathilde
would still cause great damage if it struck another body,
scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Asteroids like Mathilde may be dust bins of debris swept up in
the early days of the solar system and held together by the gravity
of their own mass, some researchers say, but there may be other
types of rubble asteroids created by past collisions.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence suggesting that some solid-looking asteroids
may be fractured inside because of collisions with other objects or
undergoing stresses caused by the gravitational tugging of larger
bodies they pass, some scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Erik Asphaug, an astronomer at the University of California
at Santa Cruz, says the internal structure of asteroids may be
determined by their impact histories. In a paper published two
years ago, Asphaug and colleagues reported that computer
simulations suggested that many asteroids were aggregates of debris
from previous collisions. Some may be a few large fragments held
together by self-gravity and covered with debris, while others are
rubble piles of many smaller pieces, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The simulations indicated that a mile-wide solid asteroid could
shatter into several pieces if hit by a house-sized object, but
still hold together. Subsequent hits pulverized parts of the
asteroid, but old rubble absorbed shock waves and minimized damage
to other parts. The researchers said that this type of internal
structure would make it more difficult to divert an asteroid with a
nuclear explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William F. Bottke of Cornell University said that such
fractured asteroids could be further pulled apart by encounters
with planets and other bodies. This could account for evidence on
Earth, Mars and Venus that about 10 percent of large impact craters
show evidence of a small crater nearby that formed at the same
time, he said. These binary craters suggest that some asteroids
have fragments that stay close to the main body when they crash
into a planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that there could be a lot of rubble asteroids
formed in different ways,'' Bottke said, ``and this changes the
whole picture of what it takes to blow up an asteroid.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. H. Jay Melosh, an impact crater expert at the University of
Arizona, said that this showed a need to come up with alternatives
to nuclear bombs for defending Earth from asteroids. ``There isn't
a big enough bomb in any nation's arsenal to deflect a
one-kilometer asteroid,'' he said. ``It would take a
million-megaton bomb, and I don't think anyone wants a gigaton bomb
orbiting the Earth for asteroid defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Melosh suggests exploring other options, and favors positioning
a giant parabolic mirror made of reflective fabric material near
the threatening asteroid. This mirror could concentrate the Sun's
rays to vaporize the surface of the asteroid, generating an
opposite reaction that slowly pushes the space rock off course.
</P>
<P>
   Other suggestions for moving asteroids include attaching large
rocket engines to them; landing cannonlike devices called mass
drivers to scoop up and hurl asteroid material away, creating an
opposite recoil reaction; or attaching a giant solar sail that
would use the pressure of sunlight to move the body slowly. But
Melosh said that these suggestions required attaching things to
tumbling asteroids covered with loose rubble, a daunting task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of these technologies will be developed
until we see a definite threat,'' Melosh said, ``and we will need
several years of warning to do it. But everything depends on first
finding out more about asteroids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
