<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2557 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-MAUI-LADN &LR;      04-10 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MAUI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO BEAT THE HIGH COST OF MAUI
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER ROSE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAANAPALI, Hawaii _ Any way you cut it, Maui is not cheap. Even
after resigning themselves to overpaying for air fare and
accommodations, the budget-minded find that the cost of visiting
(and living in) Maui is high. Food, gas, lodging ... everything
seems to be at least 20 percent more expensive than it should be.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways, however, to save money on incidentals such as
food and souvenirs, as well as popular activities such as luaus,
boat trips and snorkeling without cutting corners.
</P>
<P>
   This is where I like to save: I'm a believer in flying on major
airlines and staying at nice hotels when on vacation. My days of
buying student train passes and staying at hostels are part of a
romantic but unmissed past. But just as I try to avoid paying
retail here at home, I seek every opportunity to get value when I
buy goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   My first great discovery was that there are a Big Kmart and
Costco on the island. They're next door to each other in Kahului,
near the airport, which is pretty centrally located for most
visitors. Some may find the presence of chain stores on Maui
horrifying, a symbol of the encroachment of big, soulless
corporations on paradise. I say, bring on the bargains. These
stores are big for a reason: People shop there by the millions.
</P>
<P>
   We soon found that many of the locals share my view. Our guide
on one of the very popular bike-down-the-volcano tours, when asked
what CDs of Hawaiian music he would recommend, suggested several
CDs ... and added that he'd seen them at a very good price at the
local Costco, which has a respectable Hawaiiana section.
</P>
<P>
   You can't find everything at these ``big box'' stores. You're
probably going to have to pay full price for a really nice aloha
shirt from a department store or a specialty shop like Reyn
Spooner. Costco does carry some luxury goods (Coach handbags,
Orrefors crystal) but it has virtually nothing in the way of unique
Hawaiian collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   I actually held off shopping at Kmart and Costco until several
days into our trip, figuring I'd shop at smaller stores, buy what
seemed unique and price-compare more commonplace items. Though
Kmart's souvenir section was not very large, its prices on items
I'd looked at elsewhere were almost all significantly better.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaiian-made body lotions in various floral scents, which I'd
seen elsewhere at $5 apiece, were $3.50 here. A three-pack of
assorted macadamia nuts was about $1.50 better than what I'd paid
at Hilo Hattie, a gigantic souvenir shop (still worth visiting)
with outlets in Maui, several of the other Hawaiian islands ... and
in Orange County, in case you get the urge to pick up floral leis
after you return to Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't been looking for calendars, but when I saw some lovely
ones at Kmart _ featuring gorgeous scenes of Maui and Hawaii _ for
only 89 cents, I snapped up a few for family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a ``sunshine on sale'' package that many hotels
participate in, offering a free, lavish buffet every morning with a
stay of at least five or six nights, our breakfast was covered
every day. Since we ate a large morning meal, we also saved money
on lunch: Several days, we picked up packaged sandwiches for about
$3 at one of the many ABC Stores _ sort of Hawaiian 7-Elevens _
around the island and ate them outdoors, picnic- style.
</P>
<P>
   ABC also has very good prices on souvenirs, from macadamia nuts
to costume jewelry. We bought two small gift-packaged bottles of
Hawaiian floral cologne for my husband's nieces for $2.50 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Another discovery was the plethora of activity discounters. My
naturally skeptical husband was ... well, naturally skeptical of
outfits that offer savings of 20 percent or more on some of Maui's
most popular things to do. We read the fine print in all the ads:
We were handed one promotional magazine full of activity discount
ads as we left the airport, and picked up another along the way.
</P>
<P>
   A representative at the Aloha Desk at our hotel (virtually every
major hotel has one, with staffers who will recommend and book
activities) cautioned that with the discounters we should know
exactly what we're getting. For example, some rock-bottom
advertised prices for luaus don't include food, just the show.
Also, she said, some discounters lure you with low prices but
require you to listen to timeshare pitches. We avoided these.
</P>
<P>
   We settled on a discounter called Coconuts, located next to a
gas station between Kaanapali and Lahaina; we liked their
``two-fer'' deals, which packaged two activities for one price. We
bought a submarine ride which departs from Lahaina and the popular
Marriott luau for $114 (plus tax) per person. This was a savings of
about 20 percent per person. Similar savings were available on
packages that included a mountain bike or snorkeling trip.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more confounding choices was between companies that
specialize in bike-down-the-volcano trips. Since being launched by
a now-defunct company called Cruiser Bob's some years ago, this has
become one of the most talked-about tourist activities on the
island. More than half a dozen firms are now in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Departures are almost all in the morning, with many trips
requiring you to leave your hotel in the middle of the night (2:30
or 3 a.m.). Finding a company that was reasonably priced and would
pick us up at our hotel at a civilized hour (after 7 a.m.) became
our priority in shopping around.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't even consider the lowest-priced companies, which don't
pick you up and don't provide a guided tour (they just rent you the
bike and drive you to the top of the mountain). All the guided-tour
operators tout their superiority in offering safety and comfort to
riders; in reality, we found they all offer about the same
equipment in terms of bikes, helmets and wind gear (it gets mighty
cool on the mountaintop).
</P>
<P>
   We settled on Cruiser Phil's, a smallish company that probably
gets some mileage out of its similarity in name to Cruiser Bob's.
Phil's isn't in business with the discounters, but offers a
competitive everyday price ($89 when we visited), which includes a
morning snack (coffee and muffins) and a sandwich lunch at a cute
restaurant on the way down the hill. We liked the small size of our
group, and our guides; one was a dreadlocked young Hawaiian who
plays in a reggae band, the other, like so many of the people we
encountered, a middle-age California transplant.
</P>
<P>
   We even tried to be value-conscious when splurging a bit. I
wanted an hour massage at the hotel, which normally runs $85. The
second afternoon of our stay, I went out to have a look at the
outdoor tents where they give oceanside massages. Since they were
totally booked that day, they'd left coupons for $8 off an indoor
massage on their clipboards. I took one, and booked a wonderful
massage for the following day.
</P>
<P>
   We also earned hotel bonus points for the money spent on the
massage and a fairly pricey meal at the hotel on our last night,
since I had signed us up for the hotel's rewards program via the
Internet shortly before our trip. There's nothing to lose in
joining such programs _ membership is free _ and if you travel even
two or three times a year, they can earn you free hotel stays or
airline mileage in short order. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
