<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-BIAS11-COX     04-10 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BIAS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coaltion urges Coca-Cola chairman to settle suit
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A coalition of advocacy groups met Monday with
Coca-Cola Chairman Doug Daft to urge him to settle the racial
discrimination lawsuit quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Daft told representatives of the Coalition for the People's
Agenda that the company is preparing a response to a detailed
settlement proposal recently submitted by plaintiffs' attorneys,
said the Rev. Joseph Lowery, chairman of the coalition. The
organization is made up of about 15 groups, including the NAACP of
Georgia, Concerned Black Clergy, the Georgia Association of Black
Elected Officials and the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply urged them to get this crisis behind them,'' Lowery
said. ``We urged them to be fair and just with the employees.'' In
addition to Daft, Lowery's group met with Executive Vice President
Carl Ware, who co-chairs the company's Diversity Advisory Council,
and Vice President Ingrid Saunders Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Lowery said he could not predict whether a settlement could be
reached by Saturday, when a bus ``ride for justice'' is scheduled
to leave Atlanta for the annual shareholders meeting in Delaware on
April 19. The planned three-bus convoy, which is scheduled to hold
rallies in three cities before reaching the Wilmington shareholders
meeting, is being organized to pressure the company into settling
the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, who also met with Daft recently to urge
a settlement, is planning to attend the shareholders meeting, said
Janice Mathis, chief of staff and general counsel for Jackson's
Rainbow/PUSH Coalition. ``The only thing that could stop his
attending could be if they reached a settlement,'' Mathis said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal suit, filed by eight current and former employees,
alleges that Coca-Cola has discriminated against African-Americans
in pay, promotions and performance evaluations. The plaintiffs are
seeking class-action status so they can represent about 2,000
current and former black employees in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company has denied the allegations and opposed the
plaintiffs' efforts to make it a class-action case.
</P>
<P>
   Lowery also said his group urged Daft to do a better job of
diversifying the company's board of directors, which includes only
one African-American _ Donald McHenry, former U.S. ambassador to
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He agreed that they ought to address diversity at every level
in Coke, including the board level,'' Lowery said of Daft's
response.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
