<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2566 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      04-10 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, April 11 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ELECT (Lima, Peru) _ As the government vote count suggested
that President Alberto Fujimori is close to winning an outright
re-election victory in Sunday's balloting, international election
observers expressed grave concerns Monday over the way the
government handled ballot boxes and vote tally sheets as well as in
the slowness of the official vote tally. Crying that fraud was
already being committed, Fujimori's main opponent, Alejandro
Toledo, led tens of thousands of people late Sunday night in a
march on the presidential palace demanding that the will of the
people be respected. The crowd was dispersed in the predawn hours
today by policemen firing tear gas, but opposition leaders said a
denial of a second round would bring a mass civil disobedience
campaign that would make the country ungovernable. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   RAMPAGE-KILLERS-III (Salt Lake City) _ With the voices inside
her head ordering her to kill, Lisa Duy walked into Doug's Shoot'n
Sports here to buy a semiautomatic pistol. The manager, Dave
Larsen, ran a background check on her and the agency quickly
approved the sale, having found no record of felony convictions or
mental illness. The only thing unusual, Larsen thought, was that as
she left the store, Duy was wearing the shooting-range ear
protectors he had lent her. Less than two hours later, on Jan. 14,
1999, Duy, ear protectors still in place, walked into the studios
of television station KSL and began firing her new weapon. She shot
more than four dozen times in all, killing a young mother and
wounding the building manager. What the background check had been
unable to detect was that Duy had a long history of psychiatric
problems. Of the 100 episodes of rampage killings examined for this
series by The New York Times, none better illustrates than the case
of Lisa Duy just how difficult it can be to enforce a key provision
of the nation's fundamental gun control law. That provision
prohibits people who have been involuntarily committed to mental
institutions from buying a handgun. But laws in most states guard
the privacy of the mentally ill, so gun background checks typically
fail to turn up mental health histories. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   Third in a series of four. 4,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BUSH-HEALTH (Undated) _ Public health in Texas is a
measure of George W. Bush's governance. A state with the per capita
income of Oregon (near the middle) has about the same per capita
spending on public health as Mississippi (near the bottom).
Millions are uninsured, including hundreds of thousands of
children, and large percentages of the poor, but Bush and his
officials worked against adding them to the insurance rolls, even
though the federal government offered to pay most of the cost. Bush
paid very little attention to public health issues as governor, and
his top appointed health official is not seen as a strong advocate.
By Adam Clymer. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-PLANE-CRASH (Washington) _ The V-22 Osprey, a hybrid
helicopter/turboprop, was scuttled by the Pentagon but Congress
kept it alive. Now three of the 15 finished military aircraft have
crashed, killing 26 soldiers, and the Pentagon has grounded the
remaining planes. The aircraft remains expensive, experimental and
exemplary of the way weapons are built for today's U.S. military.
By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOBBY (Albany, N.Y.) _ In flush times, the Legislature has
become a leaner place and partisan politics is only partly to
blame. Stung by embarrassing revelations that Philip Morris treated
scores of lawmakers last year, and then underreported the expense,
the Republican-controlled Senate adopted a voluntary ban on free
meals with lobbyists and gifts over $25. The Democratic-led
Assembly refused to go along, although 10 of its members have
individually pledged to abide by the ban. Now the shrinking
waistlines are just one indication that a deeply entrenched
lobbying culture has begun to change. By Winnie Hu. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTIOXIDANTS (Undated) _ The National Academy releases a
report on antioxidants, which many people take in hopes they will
prevent heart disease, cancer and many other health problems. By
Denise Grady.
</P>
</TEXT>
