<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2567 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-LADN &LR;      04-10 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNORKELING _ A SENSORY EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By ERIC NOLAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAANAPALI, Hawaii _ ``Hey, there's a sea turtle out here!''
</P>
<P>
   The boyish squeal drifted up from the waters near Black Rock,
off the west coast of Maui. It found its way over the balconies of
the Sheraton Hotel rooms that cling to the rock face, and probably
awakened a few guests trying to sleep in.
</P>
<P>
   Here it was barely past dawn, the sun just now peeking over the
summit of nearby Puu Kukui, and already the cove was astir with
youngsters, paddling along in their swim fins, puffing through
snorkels, peering down into the water through their plastic masks.
</P>
<P>
   You could hardly begrudge them their enthusiasm, though. There
are rich coral beds off this coast, which form habitat for tropical
fish in many strange shapes and brilliant colors. And surveying
them is as simple as plunging into the clear, warm, often-shallow
waters and swimming along the surface of their exotic world.
</P>
<P>
   There is much to behold. The Moorish idol is striped in black,
gold and white, and has a long sash that trails behind its dorsal
fin. The yellow trumpetfish looks like a survivor from a
prehistoric age _ a tubelike fish with eyes positioned well back
from the tip of its flat snout. The saddleback wrasse features many
of the hues from Hawaii's trademark rainbows, including a
translucent blue and a shocking pink.
</P>
<P>
   A snorkel excursion can produce exhilarating surprises, too. On
a February visit to secluded Honolua Bay on Maui's northwest
corner, I was perhaps 150 yards offshore with some other snorkelers
when a pod of spinner dolphins entered the bay and made right for
us. For several minutes, it was all fins and snouts as they
splashed along, some of them leaping out of the water to execute
their corkscrew maneuvers. Then suddenly we couldn't see them.
</P>
<P>
   Another swimmer cried out, and we looked down into the water.
The dolphins _ perhaps 40 or 50 in number _ had submerged and were
passing beneath us, next to us. They swam languidly by, in many
cases passing within 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   One of the noteworthy aspects of snorkeling is its broad appeal.
It's not unusual to see very young children in the water swimming
alongside seniors. Overweight people don't seem to have any trouble
with this endeavor. Furthermore, the gear is not cumbersome or
complicated and is available for rental at numerous outlets around
the islands.
</P>
<P>
   There are also aids for those who aren't strong swimmers or
aren't comfortable with the idea of sticking their faces in the
water and drawing precious air through a narrow plastic tube.
Boogie-board-like floats are available, some of which are equipped
with a plastic porthole in the nose.
</P>
<P>
   Maui's west coast has several excellent snorkeling spots _ which
is fortuitous, because that's where most of the island's tourist
accommodations are concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   Some words of caution, though: Always swim with a partner. Be
advised that the southwest shore can get rough in summer, the
northwest shore can be treacherous when the wind is up in winter. A
good rule of thumb is to limit your activity to calm days and stay
in sheltered water. And children _ no matter how well they swim in
your pool at home _ should be watched constantly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-SNORKLING-LADN     04-10 1674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SNORKLING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAGNIFICENT SEVEN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Sidebar to snorkling story.) 
 
 
 
 
By ERIC NOLAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grab the snorkel gear, head for the water.
</P>
<P>
   Maui visitors who are inclined to explore nature's aquarium
should consider these sites on the island's west side. They
constitute the region's magnificent seven.
</P>
<P>
   l. Honolua Bay
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of this derives from its massive size and its
designation as a marine sanctuary. There is a stunning variety of
underwater life (I encountered a sea turtle here a few years back),
with coral beds along each edge of the bay. And if you're lucky,
you just might get a chance to swim with dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Positives: In the summer months, Honolua is as tranquil as a
bathtub, and inviting for all levels of swimmers. Snorkel excursion
boats commonly sail up from Lahaina to moor here, so if you drive
up, you'll save a lot of money _ and be able to stay as long as you
wish.
</P>
<P>
   Negatives: The beach is a jumble of smooth boulders, with only
small patches of sand, so it's not particularly friendly for
picnicking or sunbathing. The rocks also make it tricky getting
into the water (although a wrecked boat dock eases entry for some).
There are no facilities. Nor is there a parking lot. Or a highway
sign identifying this bay. Foot access is via rocky dirt road.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Drive north on the Honoapiilani Highway (Route
30) past Kapalua. After passing J.T. Fleming Beach Park, the road
winds along cliffs. The bay is located at a sharp curve to the left
immediately after you begin to descend from the bluffs. Park along
the road, then walk to the beach along a dirt road through lush
jungle. Don't fret over the ``Private Property, Keep Out'' sign _
it pertains to the adjoining land, not the access road itself.
</P>
<P>
   2. Molokini
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the most popular tourist excursions for Maui
visitors, for good reason. From shore you can see this
crescent-shaped sliver of an island that lies between Maui and
Kahoolawe, and it seems to beckon you.
</P>
<P>
   That island is the very tip of a volcanic cone, and the waters
within the crater are 30 feet deep and rich with coral and tropical
fish. (Just around the edge of the island, by contrast, it's 350
feet deep with a freight-train current.)
</P>
<P>
   Here I encountered a snowflake moray eel _ out of its rocky
burrow and swimming across the bottom like a water-borne sidewinder
rattler _ as well as the threadfin butterfly fish with its exotic
striping and colors.
</P>
<P>
   If you pick the right tour company, half the fun of Molokini is
getting there and back. Our choice was Paragon, which employs a
47-foot, 38-passenger catamaran and spends a lot of time under
sail. On the return trip, as we picked up the winds that rip across
Maui's isthmus, captain Greg Thomas got us up to an exhilarating 17
knots. Spray was periodically splashing over the bow as we left two
other Molokini tour boats in our wake.
</P>
<P>
   Positives: The water is much clearer in the crater than it is
back on shore, making the underwater viewing spectacular. The boats
provide gear, and it might be comforting knowing that a guide on
the boat is keeping watch over you. After your exertions, you'll
find sandwiches and iced beer and soft drinks on most boats. If you
undertake only one snorkel outing during your visit, it's hard to
beat this.
</P>
<P>
   Negatives: This excursion is so popular that the tour boats line
up in the crater like station wagons at a drive-in theater. It's
not a particularly intimate interaction with nature.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Plan to set an alarm. To avoid the afternoon
winds, all boats head for Molokini around 7 a.m. from Maalaea
Harbor (south of Lahaina, at the isthmus). Cost can run from $50 to
$70. Paragon information and reservations: (800) 441-2087 or (808)
244-2087.
</P>
<P>
   3. Black Rock
</P>
<P>
   The cliff extends out into the water at the midpoint of popular
Kaanapali Beach, and the mature coral that clings to its base teems
with a wide variety of tropical creatures. The sea turtles that
frequent this neighborhood have become so accustomed to seeing
humans that the Sheraton's dive shop staffers refer to them as
pets. We saw an entire school of yellowstriped goatfish, which have
two thin, tentacle-like fins that protrude from their jaw. The fish
swim along the bottom and use these appendages to root morsels out
of the sandy bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Positives: This spot is extremely convenient to people staying
in one of the Kaanapali resorts. Soft, sandy beach makes it easy to
get in, and gentle water ensures pleasant swimming.
</P>
<P>
   Negatives: Because of its proximity to the major resorts, there
is often a bit of a crowd in the water. Also, be wary of the
daredevils who jump off the cliff overhead. Unless you're staying
here, parking can be a bear.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: From the main highway, turn left at the sign for
the Kaanapali resort area. Black Rock is at the north end of this
region, at the back of the Sheraton hotel. There are a few
beach-access parking spaces located between the Kaanapali Beach
Hotel and the Sheraton; if they're full, you can park in the
Sheraton's multilevel garage at posted rates. Sheraton Maui
information and reservations: (808) 661-0031.
</P>
<P>
   4. Ulua Beach
</P>
<P>
   This is easily the best snorkel spot in the Wailea area, along
Maui's southwest coast. A jumble of rocks forms a point between the
Renaissance hotel and the Wailea Elua condo complex, and the marine
life seems to favor the high-rent locale.
</P>
<P>
   Here I encountered a 2-foot-long, white-spotted pufferfish with
a bulbous, misshapen head that recalled John Hurt in ``The Elephant
Man.'' There were other bizarre creatures, including a unicornfish,
which swims around with a blunt rod protruding from its forehead,
and a school of goatfish perhaps 200 strong.
</P>
<P>
   This spot is popular for scuba instruction, and it's clear these
people want to get maximum use out of that expensive gear they just
bought. It's not unusual to see them don head-to-toe wetsuits,
including booties and even cowls _ then wade out into 10 feet of
80-degree water and dive next to an 8-year-old kid with trunks,
snorkel, mask and no fins.
</P>
<P>
   Positives: Ah, a rarity for some of Hawaii's finer beaches _
facilities. In developing this area, the resorts put in a 38-space
parking lot, rest rooms, shower and foot-washer. There is an
excellent beach here. Don't feel you need to crowd into the sand
that fronts the public-access area. All of Hawaii's beaches are
public; go ahead and get comfortable in front of the condo complex.
There is also a shady knoll to offer relief from the blazing
west-Maui sun.
</P>
<P>
   Negatives: The coral is within a few inches of the water surface
in some places, so if you're not paying attention, an ocean surge
can threaten to beach you on an altogether unfriendly surface.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Drive south on the Piilani Highway from Kihei
until it terminates at the Wailea resort area and turn right to the
coast. Turn right again onto Wailea Alanui, then turn left when you
see the sign for Mokapu Beach/Ulua Beach between the Renaissance
and the Wailea Elua Village.
</P>
<P>
   5. Ahihi Bay/La Perouse Bay
</P>
<P>
   This is the most remote snorkeling spot of the lot. It can be
found where the road turns to dirt and gravel at Maui's extreme
southwest corner. The black-lava coves here were formed by
Haleakala's last-gasp eruption around 1790.
</P>
<P>
   Positives: Most tourists are scared off when the road starts to
give out, so you'll find blessed relief from the crowds of Ulua and
Black Rock. The views of Molokini and Kahoolawe are sensational.
</P>
<P>
   Negatives: That solitude has its down side. When you're the only
two snorkelers in a vast cove, it can be a little spooky.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Follow the only road south of Wailea and Makena
until the asphalt gives out. Ahihi Bay is just past a sign
identifying the Natural Area Reserve. To reach La Perouse Bay,
continue south past a lottery-dream estate to a rough parking area
on the right. A trail from the parking area curls left to the
black-lava crescent.
</P>
<P>
   6. Olowalu Beach
</P>
<P>
   Rough water can be intimidating to novice snorkelers. Here's the
solution: a swimming-pool-like stretch of coast between Lahaina and
the isthmus. It's also known as Mile Marker 14 Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Positives:The water is shallow, and thus warm. You'll likely see
golden coral, unicornfish and urchins hiding in crevices.
</P>
<P>
   Negatives: The beach is smack along the highway, so you're
subjected to the constant roar and rattle of big trucks. There are
portable toilets. The parking area is trashy. Snorkeling is best
done in an idyll; this isn't it.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: From Lahaina, drive south on the main highway
(with the trucks) and watch for the mile-marker signs. Marker 14
and the beach are just past a ``Pass With Care'' sign on the right.
Northbound from Kihei, turn left into the parking area when you see
the emergency call box just past mile-marker 14.
</P>
<P>
   7. Napili Bay
</P>
<P>
   This is a delightful little cove in Maui's low-rent tourist
district just north of Kaanapali. The beach slopes steeply into the
water, and there's a chunk of reef perhaps 100 feet offshore,
square in the middle of the bay. Numerous tropical fish call it
home.
</P>
<P>
   Positives: The beach is lovely, even though the motels are built
a bit too close to the shore for comfort. The water is particularly
calm in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Negatives: Parking is sorely limited. The beach, though
picturesque, is a narrow strip, so there isn't much room to spread
out for a picnic or a post-swim snooze.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Head north of Kaanapali on the main highway and
turn left when you see the signs for Napili (the road is called
Napilihau, but that's irrelevant because it's unmarked). Turn right
at Lower Honoapiilani Road (stop sign) and proceed to Napili Place.
Turn left there, make a U-turn when it's convenient, and park in
the dirt off the right shoulder. Follow the blue and white
``Shoreline Access'' sign to a beach path that cuts between two
motels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
