<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-10 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STRIPED BASS MAY SOON HAVE NEW LIFELINE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Imagine catching two striped bass at once,
including one that wasn't even hooked?
</P>
<P>
   A miracle? Well, maybe there is still time for miracles for the
striped bass in the San Francisco Bay and Delta.
</P>
<P>
   You see, on a recent trip to the Delta, we really did catch a
striped bass without using even a hook (and we'll get to that).
</P>
<P>
   At the same time came news of another revelation: According to a
well-connected insider, government approval is imminent for a
program to salvage 1.27 million yearling stripers at the Delta
pumps. The baby bass will be transferred to submerged net-pens,
then fed and grown out to yearling size, and released when they are
strong enough to swim away from the suction flow of the pumps.
</P>
<P>
   This is the bombshell that could once again make the Bay-Delta's
striped bass one of the most wide-ranging and productive fisheries
in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Since the California Aqueduct pumps started cranking in 1968,
the striped bass and many other fisheries have gone literally right
down the drain. The pumps take 80,000 gallons of water per second,
and with it go the baby bass, along with salmon, catfish and other
fish, all sent to points south.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe miracles can still happen. In the past few springs,
the Delta pumps have been shut down for several weeks to keep them
from eating endangered salmon and smelt. A side benefit has been
for the striped bass, often kept out of the pumps as well. They
have had improved spawns also boosted by high freshwater flows from
Delta to Bay from seven straight wet years in Northern California.
That is another reason why the striper fishery is on a big rebound.
</P>
<P>
   It is also what inspired this recent trip. I booked a day with
the best striper boat in the land, Fishin' Fool IV, and its
captain, Barry Canevaro, joined by Sacramento radio star Bob Simms,
best-selling novelist John Lescroart, and Borders' book honcho Tom
Hedtke. We left just after dawn from Pittsburg Marina, then toured
all the old favorite spots, Middlegrounds, the Mothball Fleet,
Grizzly Bay, then cruised up the Sacramento River, finding clear,
green water at the spot called the ``Power Lines,'' located
downstream of Rio Vista.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Delta is just loaded with stripers,'' Canevaro said.
``When they head down to the Bay for summer, people aren't going to
believe how many fish there are. In May, I'm going to follow them
right down and move my boat to Richmond.''
</P>
<P>
   We anchored, used ghost shrimp for bait, and after casting out,
immediately began getting nibbles. At times, three rods were
twitching at once, driving us crazy as we tried to hook the bass.
Plenty of times we did just that.
</P>
<P>
   Lescroart caught the first one, a 7-pounder, providing a great
tussle for its size, then in turn, Hedtke hooked up with a near
identical fish, which took off on power dives to the Delta bottom.
This is called ``getting your chain pulled.''
</P>
<P>
   But what pulled my chain was all the ``Delta trout,'' as I call
them, the obvious zillions of healthy baby bass. You could take a
spinning rod with a Kastmaster and catch and release dozens of them
(the best spot is warm-water outfall at the Antioch Power Plant).
These are the future of a fishery that is coming back after being
nearly lost by the rapacious water pumping to benefit Southern
California during the drought in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that all these baby bass are just the start of what
could turn into the biggest fish success story in America.
</P>
<P>
   For years, fishermen have been trying to figure out how to keep
the millions of baby stripers out of the Delta pumps and California
Aqueduct. That is how the salvage program was invented, being run
as a pilot with about 100,000 fish a year. But to expand it, the
Department of Fish and Game is required to obtain what is called a
Section 10 Permit from the National Marine Fisheries Service. It's
been four years now, and still no permit.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes word that approval for this permit is finally at
hand, though no confirmation of that was provided by any agency,
state or federal. The DFG said only that if the permit is approved,
then a press release will be issued. But it is known that the
funding is in place, with money for the program available from
funds raised from the $3.70 Striped Bass Stamp reauthorized in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have given up on the striped bass, this may sound
like a miracle. But this restoration plan is based on simple common
sense.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to a miracle, well, you have to go fishing to
experience one of those. We caught a half-dozen stripers and a
sturgeon on a beautiful blue-sky day where anything seemed
possible. And so it was:
</P>
<P>
   At the end of one battle, Lescroart leaned back with the rod,
persuading a striper to the boat. Just as Canevaro netted the fish,
another striped bass, about a 4-pounder, suddenly appeared and swam
right into the net. Just like that, the net was lifted out of the
water with two fish in it. There it was, a fish caught without
being hooked.
</P>
<P>
   We let the fish go, watching it dance off. Perhaps it was
celebrating, just like we were.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
