<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2575 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-DISCO11-COX     04-10 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCO11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disco will survive
 &HT;    By Chris Hutchins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The moment is frozen in time _ a roar
from the past ringing powerfully in the present.
</P>
<P>
   Loleatta Holloway is wailing, her high note vibrating through
the ballroom of the Marina Marriott in Fort Lauderdale. Feeling the
note surge through their souls, the crowd of 300 claps, stomps and
dances at the climax of ``Good Vibrations,'' a hip-hop song
released a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at the World Disco Classic 2000 last Saturday have
come to see Holloway. And to dance. To dance like it was yesterday
_ and like there's no tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The late-night performance is just part of this year's Classic,
which was held last weekend (from Thursday to Sunday). The event,
hosted by a group of Florida producers who are disco fans, pays
homage to the '70s dance scene. There have been countless
conversations about dancing tonight. There have been dance
competitions. And times where anyone can come out to the dance
floor.
</P>
<P>
   The dance? It's that quintessential 1970s groove, the Hustle.
And aside from a few swing dancers, it's what everyone is dancing
tonight: A saucy fusion of mambo and salsa, born in the Latino
communities of New York City. It started as a street dance created
by club-hoppers back then. It's a sexy dance, a hunt of sorts. He
leads, she follows. She falls away, he tugs her back. A slippery
dance, a give and take.
</P>
<P>
   There are no formalities and no rules, save one: Keep the
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   That rule is safe tonight. The dancers _ some who have come from
as far away as Canada _ are veterans. Most came of age in the '70s.
They remember the flamboyant clothes, the great times, the
emotional electricity when they Hustled. They were 18 then.
</P>
<P>
   They're in their 40s now. Real-life responsibility kicked in
long ago. Spouse. Kids. Home. The sideburns are gone, the
bell-bottoms traded in for khakis. But that primal power is still
in the dance. And that camaraderie is still here, on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all trying to stay together with this,'' explains
Lighthouse Point resident Robert J. Jacobs. ``Let's face it:
Disco's been out for a long time. I remember when disco was
officially proclaimed `dead' on `Saturday Night Live.' I was bummed
after that. But the dance is still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   It is. According to Drew Axelrod, one of the event's organizers,
more than 600 people attended the Disco Classic during the weekend.
And disco music lives on in the techno remixes of old hits, the
lyric and music samples mixed into what DJs are calling ``Disco
House.''
</P>
<P>
   The behavior of Hustlers has evolved, too. There are few
``divas'' here tonight. Most are dressed in fun, but sensible,
clothes. The dance floor is wooden, not underlit by flashing red,
yellow, blue lights. The first Bee Gees song doesn't come until
9:55, and it's a remix. In fact, the only thing that screams
``discotheque'' is the small, shimmering mirrorball hanging above
the DJ booth.
</P>
<P>
   But the look doesn't matter. It's the music that counts. There's
something about it _ something about the rhythm, the groove, the
dance steps _ that keeps the faithful coming back. People here tell
you: If you don't dance, you won't get it. They talk about Hustle
running ``through your soul,'' about disco being ``a part of
something inside you.'' They use words like ``kinetic'' and
``dreamy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our passion,'' explains Trish Hansberry, who flew in from
Lancaster, Pa., just to dance here. ``It's the thing that gets us
excited, gets the adrenaline pumping. We love to learn. We love to
watch. We just want to get better and better, and that's why we do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Disco isn't dead. The Hustle made a comeback in the early 1990s,
turning on a whole new generation of young people, and bringing
back many of their parents. There are folks here like Brian and
Silvana Gallagher, who won this year's prestigious ``King and Queen
of Hustle'' title. They saw the resurgence as a second chance, and
re-learned the moves. Others, like 56-year-old Bud Rowe, grabbed it
for the first time, and didn't let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``On my 50th birthday, I learned that I had a spot on my lung,''
the Harrisburg, Pa., resident says. ``I had to wait a week for a
CAT scan. During that week, I promised myself I'd do whatever my
dream in life was. That was to really learn to dance. That was 6
1/2 years ago. Haven't stopped since.''
</P>
<P>
   And the spot?
</P>
<P>
   ``Turned out to be calcium, nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are the people who've been with disco and the Hustle
from the beginning. Vince Montana Jr., regarded in this community
as the father of disco's orchestral sound, is here tonight. Those
sweeping violins, the sassy brass, the Latin percussion _ it was
all a part of SalSoul, the orchestra he launched in the mid-'70s.
</P>
<P>
   Disco Classic organizers gave him a lifetime achievement award
tonight. He cried as he gave his acceptance speech. He played a few
familiar tunes, like ``Tangerine,'' on a xylophone. Dancers crept
to the floor, timidly at first, and Hustled to his performance. He
was shaking hands and signing autographs the rest of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is inspiring music. It's happy music. It's good for the
soul,'' Montana says. ``You take this other stuff on the radio,
it's distortion. This is happy. People will always go to happiness
before they go to pain. Basically, it's a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. As Holloway hits her high note late in the evening, no
other words can describe the feeling. Hundreds of people dancing,
clapping, whooping praise to Holloway, to Montana, to the music.
They shout for the emotion, for the past, for the present. And,
undoubtedly, for the future.
</P>
<P>
   When Holloway finishes, the audience explodes into applause.
Standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   The moment is frozen. The gray hairs, gone. Everyone looks 18
again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
