<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-AIRLINE-RATINGS-HNS &LR;      04-10 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-RATINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SOUTHWEST OFFERS BEST SERVICE; UNITED COMES IN LAST, REPORT
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Southwest Airlines provided the best service to
passengers among the nation's 10 major airlines last year,
according to a study released Monday by university researchers.
</P>
<P>
   But for the industry generally, customer complaints jumped 130
percent in 1999 over 1998, fueling speculation that Congress may be
asked again to approve a passengers' bill of rights regulating the
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-based Southwest, which flies to 55 cities and carries
more than 52 million passengers a year, ranked first in two of the
four categories considered by the study _ baggage-handling and a
low number of customer complaints about it to the Department of
Transportation. It was second in on-time arrivals, landing as
scheduled on 80 percent of its flights. In the fourth category,
bumping passengers because of overbooking, it ranked third worst
among the 10 airlines.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines finished last in the study, partly because of a
287 percent hike in complaints against it last year over 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumers are fed up with poor service,'' Brent Bowen,
director of the Aviation Institute at the University of Nebraska at
Omaha, said at a news conference here. Bowen and Dean Headley, an
associate professor of marketing at Wichita (Kansas) State
University's business school, co-authored the study, their 10th
annual report on airline performance.
</P>
<P>
   In the overall rankings for 1999, Continental Airlines finished
second, followed by Delta, Northwest, Alaska Airlines, US Airways,
American Airlines, America West, Trans World Airlines and United.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways suffered the steepest drop from 1998, plummeting from
first to sixth place. The 1998 rankings, after US Airways, were
Continental, American, Delta, Southwest, America West, TWA, Alaska,
Northwest and United.
</P>
<P>
   The report said complaints about US Airways' service nearly
quadrupled, its bumping of passengers more than doubled, it
mishandled baggage 20 percent more often and its percentage of
on-time arrivals dropped 7.5 points from 78.9 percent to 71.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Southwest, only Northwest and Alaska improved their
rankings. ``I think we all know from our flying experiences that
things have gotten worse,'' said Headley, He also said the airlines
``seem to have a problem making sure things happen the way they
promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, flights were less likely to arrive on time, and people
were slightly more likely to be bumped because of overbooking. The
only figure that improved was baggage handling. Luggage arrived
late or was lost by airlines 5.08 times for every 1,000 passengers
last year compared with 5.16 times in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The study's release comes about four months after the 10 major
airlines and four other carriers implemented voluntary plans to
make flying more passenger-friendly in order to avoid a
government-imposed passengers' bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure had built for such legislation after passengers
testified before Congress about sitting in a plane on a Detroit
tarmac more than seven hours during a snowstorm and about waiting
nine hours at another airport on a plane that never took off.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of passing any measure, Congress agreed last fall to
temporarily allow the airlines to regulate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Under the voluntary program that went into effect last Dec. 15,
the airlines said they would inform customers if there was a better
rate on another airline and would respond to any consumer
complaints in writing within 60 days. They also promised to update
passengers on the status of delayed planes every 15 to 20 minutes
and to do their best to return mishandled baggage within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Transport Association, which represents the major
airlines, urged consumers to defer judgment on their performance
until next year's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan was only in place for the last two weeks of 1999,''
said Diana Cronan, an ATA spokeswoman. ``A year from now when this
report comes out I think we'll see a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who led the movement last year for a
passengers' bill of rights, disagreed. Lisa Finkel, a Wyden
spokeswoman, said the new report provides the senator with new
ammunition to seek legislation mandating such rights, which she
said
</P>
<P>
   ``are not given the attention they deserve. There really is a
need for across-the-board changes.''
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY11-COX     04-10 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OIL PIPELINE CRITICS LAUNCH NATIONAL SAFETY CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Citizen groups and state officials called Monday
for sharply increased regulation of the national network of
underground pipelines that carry millions of gallons of crude oil,
gasoline and other hazardous substances.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been shameful neglect of safety by both industry and
regulators,'' Robert Rackleff, a county commissioner of Leon
County, Fla., and a longtime pipeline critic, told participants in
a two-day ``National Pipeline Safety Reform Conference.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents of two boys who died last year in the explosion of a
gasoline pipeline in Bellingham, Wash., also spoke and called for
reform in memory of their sons.
</P>
<P>
   Frank King, whose son died in the explosion, brought tears to
the eyes of the audience when he described a bedside vigil at which
doctors told him 10-year-old Wade, a Little League catcher, was
dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember leaning down by Wade's ear an whispering to him,
'It's okay to go. There's a baseball game going on in heaven, and
they need a left-handed catcher.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Participants at the meeting said thousands of leaks in the 1990s
had damaged property, fouled natural areas and caused more than 200
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting attracted representatives of community groups from
Florida to Alaska, as well as lawyers and land owners who are
fighting pipeline projects and local officials who say they are
hamstrung by federal officials who are biased in favor of the
industry they are supposed to regulate.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the meeting asked participants to press their
senators and congressmen to support bills that would shift much
responsibility for policing more than 200,000 miles of crude oil
pipelines from the federal Office of Pipeline Safety to state
officials.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Association of Oil Pipelines, an industry
group, said that ``devolving authority to the states is not going
to enhance pipeline safety.''
</P>
<P>
   She said unhappiness with pipelines is spreading, partly because
of construction of new lines and partly because of publicity about
accidents, but insisted that the industry has reduced the number of
spills and leaks in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, Texas, lawyer Renea Hicks, who represents ranchers who
are fighting plans to use new and existing pipelines to pump
gasoline across Texas from Houston to El Paso, said pipeline
projects tend to spawn unusual coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the city of Austin and Texas's Lower Colorado River
Authority have joined environmentalists, ranchers and other
conservative landowners in questioning the Longhorn Partners
Pipeline Co. proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers tend to be ``much more conservative in other areas of
politics,'' Hicks said. When they are aligned with city and water
authority officials, ``people cannot complain about there being
environmental crazies out there,'' opposing the project, Hicks
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rackleff said intense media interest driven by recent pipeline
leaks, including the one leading to the Bellingham explosion, meant
federal pipeline reform legislation might be passed by Congress
this year.
</P>
<P>
   He said Office of Pipeline Safety statistics indicate more than
300 million gallons have spilled from oil pipelines in the last
decade, ``and that does not include nine out of 10 incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Lois Epstein, an engineer with the national environmental group
Environmental Defense(cq) and an organizer of the meeting, cited a
spill last weekend from a fuel line near the nation's capital as
evidence of lax federal oversight. The leak, from a Potomac
Electric Power Co. pipeline, spilled more than 100,000 gallons of
fuel into Maryland's Patuxent River and surrounding wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pipeline ruptures like the one in Maryland are not isolated
incidents,'' said Epstein. ``The Maryland spill follows several
major oil pipeline ruptures this year that have had enormous
environmental consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.pipelineleaks.com, www.aopl.org.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
