u i BC-JAPAN-FOREIGNERS-560&AMP;     04-10 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-FOREIGNERS-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOKYO GOVERNOR CRITICIZED FOR ANTI-IMMIGRANT COMMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The governor of Tokyo has set off a swell of criticism
in diplomatic circles and foreign communities here by saying that
immigrants in Japan, mainly people of Korean and Chinese descent,
were likely to riot after a major earthquake. The governor,
Shintaro Ishihara, called on Japan's military to be prepared to
maintain order during such an uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Much to the shock and dismay of many Japanese and foreigners
alike, Ishihara referred to immigrants as sangokujin, a derogatory
term used in Japan after the country was defeated in World War II
to tell Korean and Chinese residents to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atrocious crimes have been committed again and again by
sangokujin and other foreigners,'' Ishihara said during the weekend
at a ceremony of the Ground Self-Defense Force, Japan's equivalent
of an army. ``We can expect them to riot in the event of a
disastrous earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sangokujin'' literally means people from third countries and
was used, not as an insult, by the Allied Forces who occupied Japan
after World War II to refer to people who were not Japanese or from
the occupying forces. But the Japanese gave the word a xenophobic
twist, and it is rarely used today except as a sharp insult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police have their limits,'' Ishihara said. ``I hope you will
not only fight against disasters but also maintain public security
on such occasions. I hope you will show the Japanese people and the
Tokyo people what the military is for in a state.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's comments were particularly painful to many
Koreans living in Japan because they revived memories of the racial
violence that flared after an earthquake struck Tokyo and Yokohama
in 1923, killing 97,000 people. Korean residents were blamed for
setting fires and looting, and several thousand ethnic Koreans in
these cities were massacred by Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``These remarks bring the nightmare home to us of the
groundless, hostile rumor of the 1923 earthquake by which many
innocent comrades were victimized just because they were
foreigners,'' the Korean Resident Union in Japan, which represents
about 600,000 South Koreans, said in a statement. ``The comment is
also something that has the potential to ruin friendships between
many Japanese and many foreign residents in Japan who had hoped to
create a society in which they can coexist.''
</P>
<P>
   Chu Kyu-ho, the political minister for the South Korean Embassy
in Tokyo, said that while Ishihara's remarks were not likely to
sour the current good relations between the countries, the governor
had damaged Japan's reputation internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that the Japanese people will disavow his remarks
because they are so inappropriate and so ridiculous,'' Chu said.
``But what really worries me is that many Japanese don't know their
own history and may not even understand what's behind this sort of
remark.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Korean residents of Japan are descendants of Koreans who
were forcibly brought here to work as laborers during Japan's
colonization of the Korean peninsula in the early 1900s. Choe
Kwan-ik, deputy director of international affairs for the General
Association of Korean Residents in Japan, which represents
displaced North Koreans in Japan, said that until Japan apologizes
for the atrocities it committed in Asia and makes reparations, its
officials would continue to make comments like Ishihara's.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   South Korean and Chinese have long expressed concern that
Ishihara, who was elected last April, would use his position as
governor of Japan's most populous region as a stage from which to
promote his nationalist views. A spokesman for Ishihara said he was
traveling Monday and would have no comment. The outspoken governor,
who is best known for his 1989 anti-American book, ``The Japan That
Can Say No,'' has in the past called for Japan to develop nuclear
weapons and dismissed the 1937 Rape of Nanking, in which Japanese
troops killed tens of thousands of Chinese, as a lie.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists and political analysts noted that Ishihara's
comments came at a time when an undercurrent of intolerance for
foreigners was growing in Japanese society although the country is
suffering from a sharp decline in its economy and population and
must increasingly rely on immigrants to get by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our birthrate is shrinking and the number of elderly is
growing so quickly that we will need foreign laborers to nurse
them,'' said Hiroshi Tanaka, a civics professor at Ryukoku
University in Kyoto. ``People realize that we can't survive without
foreigners, but that's no reason to be afraid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2612 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-FAILSAFE-REVIEW-AR     04-10 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FAILSAFE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THRILL OF LIVE FACES, THE WHIFF OF BLIND NOSTALGIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Production notes at end of review) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The impact was in the close-ups. When the naked television
camera came in tight on Richard Dreyfuss or Brian Dennehy, when
their anguished faces filled the screen and their characters' souls
filled your heart, then it was clear that the drama transcended the
stunt. In those moments the CBS adaptation of ``Fail Safe,''
broadcast live to much of the country on Sunday night, lived up to
its billing as an event. It proved that this medium's intimate
immediacy is an underused asset waiting to be exploited in the
service of compelling storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   The show's ultimate impact was blunted by far too much talky
(and often preachy) exposition, by some of the project's
self-imposed technical limitations and by the stop-and-start rhythm
dictated by the commercials. But ``Fail Safe'' demonstrated the
vast potential of a carefully mounted television production _ not a
bargain-basement movie, not a stage play glimpsed from the
footlights _ to thrill an audience.
</P>
<P>
   This grim morality tale of the Cold War, with its
slap-you-in-the-face 1960s warning about the imminent danger of
world destruction, seems an odd choice as the vehicle for
television's redemption. In 1962, when the novel by Harvey Wheeler
and Eugene Burdick was published, and in 1964, when the Sidney
Lumet film version was released, the story of an accidental attack
on Moscow by American bombers tapped fears as real as the morning
headlines. The spare, serious film, following on the heels of the
wildly satirical ``Dr. Strangelove,'' was enthusiastically
welcomed. In The New York Times, Bosley Crowther wrote, ``It packs
a melodramatic wallop that will rattle a lot of chattering teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   The relentless publicity for Sunday's show announced by every
available means that the film had had a profound effect on young
George Clooney, who grew up to become a big-deal actor and the
godfather of the television version. He had the standing to dictate
the terms of engagement for this black-and-white production.
</P>
<P>
   His vision may have been flawed, but it convinced CBS to mount
its first live drama in 39 years and attracted a cadre of fine
actors, the writer Walter Bernstein (author of the 1964 movie
script) and the film director Stephen Frears (``High Fidelity,''
``The Grifters''). Their efforts probably did not set many teeth to
chattering, but the show packed its own kind of wallop.
</P>
<P>
   As the misguided bomber speeds to its target, the story darts
among four locations. In the Omaha war room, a weary general
(Dennehy) tries to guide his men through the crisis under the gaze
of two visitors, an acerbic congressman (Sam Elliott) and a
computer executive (James Cromwell) whose company made the
equipment that has been programmed to choreograph the attack. In
the cockpit of the last bomber to make it to Moscow, the pilots
(Clooney and Don Cheadle) carry out their assignment as they, too,
have been programmed.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting of high-level strategists, the secretary of defense
(Norman Lloyd) tries to keep order as a cold-blooded consultant
(Hank Azaria) takes boundless joy in the events that a moral
warrior (Harvey Keitel) sees only as a tragedy. And in Washington
the noble president (Dreyfuss) confronts his powerlessness as he
tries to bargain by telephone with his Soviet counterpart with the
aid of a translator (Noah Wyle).
</P>
<P>
   Each of these characters is a one-dimensional, one-adjective
pawn in a chess game headed for tragic checkmate. (This sterling
president may be one of the show's most anachronistic elements.)
They all spend most of the drama's two hours explaining to one
another what has happened and what is about to happen. So Dreyfuss'
president must say to Wyle: ``OK Buck. Tell you what we're gonna
do. I'm going to talk to the Soviet premier.'' Then he does.
</P>
<P>
   But when you've forgotten the speeches, you'll remember the
looks on those faces. Some combination of the actors' talent,
Frears' skill, Clooney's commitment and the adrenaline that must
have been surging produced those moments. There was ice in Azaria's
eyes. There was the deepest kind of loss in Keitel's. Life was in
those details.
</P>
<P>
   Let there be no more talk of going back to the Golden Age of
Television. Memories of such golden ages _ of baseball, of
newspapers, of doughnuts _ tend to be hopelessly clouded by
nostalgia. Yes, television used to have live drama nearly every
night because that was one of the things that early television knew
how to do. But for every ``Marty'' and ``Requiem for a
Heavyweight'' there were hours of fodder, cranked out to feed the
hungry medium.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney and his team chose to accept only some of the old
limitations. The play was shown in letter-box format (with black
bands across the top and bottom of the screen), to provide stark
vertical images, some looking into deep, lavishly assembled sets.
But commercial television doesn't need slavish homages to the past.
It does need to deepen its vocabulary, and now it knows it can.
There are books and plays calling out more compellingly for
adaptation than ``Fail Safe.'' There are writers who can be
encouraged to produce memorable new scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Is a broadcast renaissance at hand? Get serious. But if the
networks do get serious, even once in a while, there could be
golden moments ahead.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FAIL SAFE'
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Sunday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Stephen Frears; screenplay by Walter Bernstein,
based on the novel by Harvey Wheeler and Eugene Burdick; live
director, Marty Pasetta Jr.; George Clooney, Pamela Oas Williams
and Laura Ziskin, executive producers; Walter Bernstein and Harvey
Wheeler, co-executive producers; Tom Park, producer. Produced by
Maysville Pictures in association with Warner Brothers Television.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: George Clooney (Col. Grady), Noah Wyle (Buck), Richard
Dreyfuss (president), Hank Azaria (Professor Groteschele), Brian
Dennehy (General Bogan), Harvey Keitel (Gen. Warren Black), Don
Cheadle (Pierce), James Cromwell (Gordon Knapp), Sam Elliott (Rep.
Tom Raskob), John Diehl (Colonel Cascio), Norman Lloyd (Secretary
of Defense Swenson) and William Smitrovich (General Stark). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
