<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2614 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-NINERS-HNS &LR;      04-10 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DRAFT MAY OFFER NINERS WITH A MUCH-NEEDED QB 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Three years ago, the 49ers thought they had
their idealized Quarterback of the Future when they made Jim
Druckenmiller their No. 1 pick in the 1997 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Druckenmiller is more likely Miami's
quarterback of the future. He was ridden out of San Francisco on a
trail of disparaging comments by general manager Bill Walsh just
before the start of the '99 season.
</P>
<P>
   With Steve Young's status still unsettled and Jeff Garcia the
only other quarterback on the roster, the 49ers are compelled to
look for a QB in the upcoming draft. Whether Young returns or walks
away from the game, the time is now for San Francisco to find and
develop a quarterback for the club to rebuild around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get the best quarterback we can,'' coach Steve
Mariucci said. ``Whoever it is, we'll develop him and improve his
skills.``
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the QB cornucopia of 1999, there's only one quarterback
of first-round quality in this draft, Marshall's Chad Pennington.
If they stay where they are at No. 12, the 49ers should have a
chance to get Pennington _ if they really like him that high.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci sounded less than fired up about Pennington, saying,
``I think he's a good player. I believe he'll be the first
quarterback who's going to be taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Through hard work, Pennington built himself into a
6-foot-3-inch, 229-pound prospect. After leading the Thundering
Herd (college football's best nickname) to a 13-0 record and
passing for 3,797 yards and 37 touchdowns last season, he spent six
weeks at the International Performance Institute in Bradenton,
Fla., honing his body to professional standards.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington is smart (3.8 grade-point average) and fast enough
for a quarterback (4.9 for 40 yards). He's a polished player at the
position, lacking only the same kind of cannon arm that did so much
good for Druckenmiller while he was a 49er. In other words,
Pennington can make most all of the throws a quarterback has to
make, particularly in San Francisco's style of offense.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Pennington, the 49ers like three other quarterbacks
in this draft _ Tim Rattay of Louisiana Tech, Tee Martin of
Tennessee and Giovanni Carmazzi of Hofstra. Of the three, Carmazzi
might be the best prospect, although he played on a lower level of
competition in college. Martin was Peyton Manning's backup in
1996-97. Rattay is just a shade over 6 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three would be guys we like, in addition to Pennington,''
said Terry Donahue, the 49ers director of player personnel.
``They're guys we'd like to have, those mobile-type quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Since defense is such a screaming maniac of a need for the
49ers, they might take a pass on Pennington at No. 12 and go for a
cornerback, linebacker or defensive end instead. All told, the
49ers have 10 picks in the draft's seven rounds, including three in
the first 35 selections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to find some defensive starters and certainly add to
our defensive depth,'' Mariucci said. ``We want to add to our
quarterback depth chart and probably one offensive lineman. We're
certainly going to major on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   However, with the way most draft projections play out,
Pennington at No. 12 seems to make the most sense, especially since
the 49ers figure to have a shot at the best cornerback in the
draft, Ohio State's Ahmed Plummer, when their turn comes up again
in the first round at No. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking generally about cornerbacks, Mariucci said, ``That
would be our hope, to get at least one starter and another guy who
would eventually start.''
</P>
<P>
   They may already have such a player on the roster. Cornerback
Anthony Parker, last year's fourth-round pick, did not play at all
in '99 because of a knee injury. Neither did defensive tackle
Reggie McGrew, last year's No. 1 pick. Guard Tyrone Hopson and wide
receiver Tai Streets played sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   Parker and McGrew could see significant playing time this
season, and Streets could be the third receiver if Jerry Rice does
not return. In a sense, the 49ers are looking at Parker, McGrew and
Streets as delayed draft picks to augment the players they will
select next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at them as redshirt freshmen,'' Mariucci said. ``Last
year's class will add to this year's class. We'll have a lot of
youth on the field. We're going to make that a positive thing.
We're going to start with a fairly young team and develop them into
professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers will go into this draft with a mandate to get faster,
especially on the edges on both sides of the ball. Streets should
bring improved speed to the wide receiver group. On defense last
year, the 49ers were routinely torched by receivers simply running
past their collection of no-talent cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a very fast team,'' Donahue said. ``We need to
become a faster team. We're trying to put an emphasis on speed and
trying to say, if nothing else, let's be sure we come out of here
with increased speed.''
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to leave out quarterback Chris Redman as a
prospect. The Louisville slugger did himself no good by running a
plodding 5.3 time for 40 yards at the combine; there are 300-pound
offensive linemen who run faster than that.
</P>
<P>
   Other than quarterback and cornerback, the 49ers will try to
find an outside linebacker to take Lee Woodall's spot in the lineup
(Michigan State's Julian Peterson?); a strong safety to compete
with Zack Bronson for the starting job (Tennessee's Deon Grant?);
an offensive tackle with offensive tackle size (Mississippi's Todd
Wade? Wisconsin's Chris McIntosh?); and a defensive end with
pass-rush skills (Virginia Tech's John Engelberger?)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun,'' Donahue said. ``Last year, Jevon
Kearse was a sure-fire top 10 pick, guaranteed. And he went 16th.
There are a lot of different things that happen on draft day. And
it's exciting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
