<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-LOUISVILLE11-COX     04-10 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISVILLE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What is the future of American theater?
 &HT;    Expect shorter works and maybe a gimmick or two
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Rape, misunderstood artists and new
</P>
<P>
   technologies.
</P>
<P>
   These are the preoccupations of the American theater in this new
millennium, or at least the issues consuming the Tony Award-winning
Actors Theatre of Louisville. As it has for the past 24 years, it
took the temperature of the American stage and its playwrights last
weekend with a fevered showcase of premieres known collectively as
the Humana Festival of New American Plays.
</P>
<P>
   For 72 hours, this genteel Southern town became the center of
the theater world, unveiling seven full-length plays, three
10-minute scripts and five brief scenes delivered over, yes, the
telephone. In total, 31 writers' work was represented, giving the
perhaps illusory impression that the American theater is busy and
healthy, though mired in dark, brooding subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The festival built its reputation on sending to New York such
acclaimed plays as D.L. Coburn's ``The Gin Game'' and Beth Henley's
``Crimes of the Heart.'' In recent years, as Broadway has grown
indifferent to new plays, the festival has sent its wares into the
nonprofit regional network. The city of Manalapan's Florida Stage
has been a prime consumer, for instance, producing six festival
scripts in the past seven seasons, including such intriguing works
as ``Keely &AMP; Du,'' ``Below the Belt'' and its current show, ``God's
Man in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the festival produces so much new work, theater writers
search it closely for clues to the mind-set of today's American
playwrights. Actors Theatre producing director Jon Jory who leaves
the company this fall after 31 years to teach theater at Seattle's
University of Washington _ notes that his selections have never
been based on thematic similarities. However, he recalls reading
with amusement a decade ago that the most significant recurring
motif of that year's festival was ``offstage barking dogs.'' Anyone
remember that trend filtering elsewhere?
</P>
<P>
   'Years of turmoil'
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was hard to miss this festival's preoccupation with
the consequences of sexual violence, mainly but not exclusively
against women. The aftermath of date rape is the subject of two
emerging 20-something writers, Stephen Belber (''Tape'') and
Alexandra Cunningham (''No. 11,'' ``Blue and White''). Veteran
playwright Charles L. Mee gives sexual politics a classical and
often comic spin with ``Big Love,'' a modern version of Aeschylus,
in which 50 sisters who are forced into marriage resolve to kill
the grooms on their wedding night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just in personal terms, the past 30 years of turmoil in the
relations between men and women has churned up a lot of passion,''
comments Mee. ``I think a lot of men who were reluctant to speak up
for their own points of view have started speaking out a little
more. I think a lot of people have looked back at the Greeks
specifically to see what we've forgotten about what it is to be
human.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida Stage producing director Louis Tyrrell is high on Mee's
``Big Love'' but is more interested in obtaining the rights to
Belber's ``Tape,'' perhaps for next season. ``The threads of the
piece created solid fabric,'' he enthuses. ``It deals with
contemporary values in a very important way, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at the festival were City Theatre co-producers Susie
Westfall and Stephanie Norman, who have already arranged to produce
10-minute plays by Tina Howe and David Ives in this year's Summer
Shorts in Miami. And it will likely be just a matter of time before
some company in South Florida grabs the festival's hit, Jane
Martin's ``Anton in Show Business,'' particularly popular with the
industry audience of critics, artistic directors and film
executives.
</P>
<P>
   It is both a satirical valentine to the theater and _ to stretch
the thematic tie-in a bit _ an illustration of how artistic efforts
get raped in the name of corporate sponsorship, star package
productions and unbridled ego. Also looking to show business for
metaphor was director Anne Bogart, who conceived and directed ``War
of the Worlds,'' a production full of stage magic about the
tumultuous, rejected career of Orson Welles, from ``Wunderkind'' to
jug-wine pitchman.
</P>
<P>
   If these were the most compelling plays the festival uncovered
this year _ from more than 700 scripts submitted _ that is also a
reflection of the dearth of plays dealing with larger political
subjects, of dissent and unrest. Perhaps it is a reflection of good
economic times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone in the country has been benefitting from the
economy, but for those who are, for the moment that's one worry
removed that allows your mind to move elsewhere,'' Jory suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Just because financial indicators are positive, some theater
artists still feel beleaguered. The latest perceived threat seems
to be the Internet, which not only keeps theatergoers in their
homes but is seen as a competing delivery system for theatrical
material.
</P>
<P>
   Bogart disagrees, believing there will be a backlash in the
years ahead. ``I think there's more and more of a longing to
breathe common air with other people,'' she says. ``The more
computerized and virtual we live our lives, the bigger theater can
become.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fear the Internet, Mee sees it as a potential boon.
``I think it's the global culture that's going to change the
theater, because the Internet has shrunk the globe. It has to
affect the way we make plays. It's a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Impact of technology
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, because of interchange with other cultures and
traditions, the American theater has become more stylized. More and
more, the neo-Expressionistic influences of Eastern Europe, the
abstractions of the Asian stage and the formalism of the classics
have been showing up in new productions over here. ``There was this
crashing realization that realism was just another style. That was
the lagoon we swam in, and it didn't occur to us that it was part
of a larger ocean,'' Jory says. ``A lot of it came from exposure to
other nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology continues to have a major impact on theatrical form,
and the festival has been dabbling with its own experiments in play
delivery. Last year's festival featured plays printed on T-shirts.
A more enduring novelty _ some would say ``gimmick'' _ is ``The
Phone Play.'' For the second consecutive year, Actors Theatre
patrons lined up to listen to two- to three-minute conversation
snippets over phones installed in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is persuaded. ``It doesn't excite me at all,'' says
Bogart. ``I'm not drawn to pick up a phone. But whatever gets
people in the building, I celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the American theater, looking back from the
perspective of one more century, is going to point to ``The Phone
Play'' as its central esthetic,'' concedes Jory, its initiator.
Still, it is a novelty that creates attention and attendance for
his festival, which is its own justification. He further predicts
that a year or two from now, as the search for new forms continues,
that bank of phones might well be replaced by a pod of
Internet-linked computers.
</P>
<P>
   Phone plays may be brief by necessity, but they point out
another trend in theater _ the intermission-less play. Five of the
seven ``full-length'' plays presented at the Humana Festival ran
about 90 minutes, without a halftime strolling opportunity for the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something wonderful about an audience coming in and
being in that world until they're released from it,'' says Mee,
whose ``Big Love'' has no intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think actors love the idea that the audience doesn't have a
chance to get out,'' Jory adds.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Sir Peter Hall flew in to Louisville last
week for a media blitz to publicize a production of a new 15-hour
play called ``Tantalus,'' based on ancient Greek political history,
which he will premiere in Denver in October. It purports to be the
longest single production in the 2,500-year history of theater.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is a sign of the theater's health in the new millennium
that every trend has an equal and opposite counter-trend.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tape': Dominic Fumusa (left) and Stephen Kunken star in this
Stephen Belber play about former classmates sorting out old
transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   _ 'Big Love': Charles Mee has updated an ancient Greek play with
both hilarious and serious results. Starring in this tale of forced
marriages are (from left) Aimee Guillot, Aimee Hayes, Pascaline
Bellegarde and Karenjune Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   _ 'Anton in Show Business': Annette Heide and Caitlin Miller
star in this affectionately jokey and occasionally vicious satire
of the theater by Jane Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
