<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot will begin selling Maytag brands at
warehouse stores next month as the retailer rolls out a major
appliance expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The Maytag partnership fills a void left by Whirlpool Corp.,
which was dropped from Home Depot's appliance launch this year
after the manufacturer had problems making deliveries during the
first few months of the rollout.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have expected Home Depot to partner with Maytag as it
continued the launch with only General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maytag is a necessary addition to our business,'' said Davis
Poole, manager of logistics and implementation for Atlanta-based
Home Depot's national appliance rollout. ``We had been looking at
them from the beginning.'' Home Depot already sells Maytag brands
at 15 Expo Design Centers.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag brands, including its Jenn-Air cooking appliances, will
debut at Home Depot stores in Jacksonville, Fla., next month. Home
Depot will expand distribution to selected markets several weeks
later and expects all of its U.S. stores to carry Maytag appliances
by year end.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric appliances are available at nearly 400 stores
now and should be in most of Home Depot's U.S. stores by the end of
August.
</P>
<P>
   Appliances could add as much as $2 billion in annual sales to
Home Depot, according to analysts' estimates. Sears, which sells
about $5 billion in appliances a year, has long dominated the
category although it faces increasing competition from Circuit
City, Best Buy and Lowe's Cos.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit City, for example, announced last month it was testing
freestanding appliance stores in Virginia and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
