<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-SERVICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR-SERVICE WOES CONTINUE TO PLAGUE PASSENGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite airlines' efforts to stall congressional attempts to
mandate better passenger treatment by announcing improvements in
customer service, the nation's major air carriers saw consumer
complaints increase 130 percent last year, according to an annual
survey by university researchers.
</P>
<P>
   And, given the demand for air travel and the limited capacity in
airport terminals, on runways, and in airplanes, things are likely
to get worse, according to an author of the study.
</P>
<P>
   The dismal performance by airlines in 1999 comes after increased
anger by passengers over shoddy treatment _ exemplified by
passengers being stuck for hours on snowbound Northwest Airlines
aircraft in Detroit. That anger resulted in calls by politicians
for passenger protections and a concerted effort by the airlines to
improve service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continued declining industry performance quality in 1999 gives
cause for Congress to again seriously consider the passage of an
Airline Passengers' Bill of Rights,'' wrote Dean Headley and Brent
Bowen, coauthors of the study conducted annually since 1991 by the
Wichita State University business school and and the Aviation
Institute at the University of Nebraska at Omaha. ``Many consumers
believe that the airlines have not delivered on promises to
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the poor service, airlines are enjoying profitable
times, even with dramatic increases in fuel prices. Airlines are
reporting near record loads, with planes being more than 70 percent
full on average.
</P>
<P>
   Those heavy loads are expected to continue _ demand is
forecasted by the federal government to increase by more than 3
percent a year. System capacity remains constrained, which means
things will get much worse before they get better, Headley said in
a telephone interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is scary when you look at the increase in demand versus the
lack of capacity. The bottom-line picture is that it will be five
years at least before there are new runways that can change
capacity,'' Headley said. ``By the time we get to that point, it is
entirely possible that every day at the airport will look like the
Wednesday before Thanksgiving. And what will that do to customer
complaints and attitudes? It will get a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual study ranks carriers based on customer complaints to
the Department of Transportation and uses federal statistics for
on-time arrivals, lost baggage complaints, and the number of
passengers bumped from flights because of overbookings. It ranked
Southwest Airlines as the best of the 10 major airlines.
Continental finished second, followed by Delta, Northwest, and
Alaska Airlines. US Airways, which held the top spot in 1998,
dropped to sixth, followed by American, America West, TWA and
United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The only area in which the industry improved from 1998 to 1999
was mishandled baggage. The number of complaints was down to 5.08
per 1,000 passengers from 5.16 per 1,000 passengers in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On-time arrivals declined to 76.1 percent in 1999 from 77.2
percent the previous year and involuntary denied boardings
increased slightly to 0.88 per 10,000 passengers. Consumer
complaints increased from 1.08 per 100,000 passengers to 2.48 per
100,000.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Air Transport Association, which worked with
the airlines to develop improved customer service pledges that went
into effect in December, was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The study also chided the airlines for ``many anti-consumer
oriented rules developed recently to enhance perceived productivity
at the expense of consumer comfort'' that have led to increased
complaints. Among the new rules cited are strict limits to carry-on
bags, limiting pre-boarding to children, and not allowing consumers
to take earlier connecting flights when seats are available.
</P>
<P>
   The study says the airlines are not solely to blame and that the
Federal Aviation Administration needs to do more to improve the
national airspace system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not expediting the implementation of GPS navigation and
approaches, free-flight, ground incursion management, data-link and
other enhancements to handling increased capacity in a constrained
system will soon have a direct and noticeable deteriorating effect
on consumers' attitudes and confidence in the use of airline
services,'' the study says.
</P>
<P>
   An FAA spokesman said the language in this year's report is
``virtually identical to what they said in 1999 and they overlooked
some of the tremendous strides we made in the last year.'' New
computers have been installed in the nation's 21 en route centers
and new display systems are being installed as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
