<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-POINTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI TO OFFER `POINTS' TO WEB SITE VISITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those frequent-user points you're used to racking up with
airlines and credit cards are coming at you on the Internet, too.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI Inc., the Andover, Mass. venture investment firm, is
launching a ``CMGI points'' program, so that online visitors to its
many sites can earn travel and gifts, through an alliance with
Netcentives Inc. CMGI said it would acquire 4.9 percent of San
Francisco-based Netcentives's shares as part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Netcentives shares jumped 16 percent to $27.25, while CMGI
shares slumped 10.5 percent in a down day for Nasdaq stocks, to
$83.9375.
</P>
<P>
   The move reflects CMGI's effort to develop loyalty among Web
users _ a challenge for all business-to-consumer Internet players.
Companies are looking for ``sticky traffic,'' or customers who will
come back regularly to their sites.
</P>
<P>
   This also marks CMGI's first effort to push its own brand. While
any of its 70 companies that choose to participate can tout their
own name on the reward program, links to sister companies will show
CMGI's name and let users build up points in the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   Rewards will include airline miles, as well as thousands of
gifts, from golf clubs to jewelry. Netcentives's technology tracks
the time users spend on each site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our purpose is really to help our companies get big fast,''
said Bill White, executive vice president of marketing at CMGI. He
calls rewards programs a ``natural evolution'' on the Web.
``They're very popular with influential consumers in the
traditional world.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Frankel, chief of Internet research at Adams, Harkness &AMP;
Hill, a Boston investment banking firm, said such plans are likely
to help build brand loyalty. He notes that iwon.com (not a CMGI
company) is drawing traffic by offering lotteries worth thousands
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In CMGI's case, he said, ``Here's a way to earn points without
spending money. You can get something for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   CMGI's AltaVista search engine will be the first unit to employ
the points program, next month. Netcentives said clients for its
``click rewards'' program include America Online, American Express,
barnesandnoble.com, and Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   The recent shakeup in Internet stocks has awakened investors'
concerns about how companies that depend on Web traffic will fare.
Roughly half of CMGI's investments are in b-to-c companies, which
sell to consumers instead of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   White said CMGI is still a big believer in b-to-c.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aim to let our companies demonstrate their success relative
to their competitors,'' he said. No gimmick can replace top
technology and services, White said. But ``they do help provide
retention, and they are an incentive to get somebody to try
something new.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2643 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     04-10 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE RED SOX, A HUNDREDTH ANNIVERSARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ New century. New season. New paint on the old park. New
center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Same old hope.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday is the 100th home opener for the Boston Red Sox.
(itals)One hundred.(unitals) That's one for every bottle of beer on
the wall, one for every point scored by Wilt Chamberlain in
Hershey, Pa., in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's first American League home opener was played at the
Huntington Avenue Grounds (corner of Huntington and Rogers
Avenues), and Cy Young beat Connie Mack's Athletics, 12-4, in front
of 11,500 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-eight years ago, five days after the Titanic sank in the
North Atlantic, the Red Sox opened their new park with a 7-6
victory over the New York Highlanders in front of 27,000 fans.
Bleacher seats cost 25 cents and John F. Kennedy's grandfather
threw out the ceremonial first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Weather permitting, Ramon Martinez will throw the first pitch of
the 2000 Fenway season Tuesday to Minnesota Twin Todd Walker, and
35,000 fans will fill the ballyard that's been home to the Red Sox
since Woodrow Wilson was president.
</P>
<P>
   Olde Fenway, state-of-the-art in 1912, has become
state-of-the-heart, a crumbling edifice slated for demolition
sometime this decade. The Red Sox play their home games in the
oldest park in the major leagues, and the rickety joint has been
home to more sorrow than success since the last World Series winner
played here in 1918.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Red Sox of great expectations started their season with
a limp 2-4 road trip through Seattle and Anaheim, but that won't
dampen the spirits of thousands of Boston baseball fans who once
again are absolutely convinced that . . . this is the year.
</P>
<P>
   The cover of Sports Illustrated's baseball preview said the Red
Sox will win the World Series. Sage Larry King is similarly on
record, as is half the population of Red Sox Nation. Some of these
expectations are based on fact and reality. Some are trendy, others
downright delusional.
</P>
<P>
   What is abundantly clear is that many New England sports fans
are counting on the Red Sox to ease the dull pain inflicted by
various Patriots, Bruins, and Celtics since the Sox closed out
their magnificent 1999 season with a playoff loss to the world
champion Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   More than ever, New England needs the Red Sox to be good. The
region's ever-fragile psyche has been shaken by the buffooneries,
ineptitude, and abject underachievement of men who throw footballs,
hit slapshots, and dribble basketballs.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, Bruins, and Celtics all finished out of the
playoffs. Pete Carroll was fired, Pat Burns is likely to get the
gate, and Rick Pitino sometimes sounds as if he's losing his mind.
The Sox, often a source of ridicule and disappointment, are the
last line of defense in Boston's desperate attempt to avoid the tag
of Loserville, USA. It is an unusual position for the franchise
that virtually invented ``wait till next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox players know the situation. From the first day of spring
training, veterans Pedro Martinez, Nomar Garciaparra, John
Valentin, and Mike Stanley were reminded of the excitement the Sox
were generating back home in the frozen North. Newcomer Carl
Everett can't possibly grasp the magnitude of the mission _ he
hasn't been in Boston yet _ but it'll be painfully obvious in a
couple of hours when he takes his position in center field and gets
his first showers of praise or poison (depending on what he did in
his previous at-bat).
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is not an easy game. Tom Hanks brings home the point in
``A League of Their Own'' when he tells Geena Davis, ``If it was
easy, everybody'd do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true. Who among us wouldn't trade places today with
Everett, just for the chance to patrol the great green patch of
Fenway's center lawn in front of 35,000 passionate fans eager to
make comparisons to Ken Griffey or Willie Mays?
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Red Sox claim they are up to the task. There was no
overreaction when they dropped four straight to the Mariners and
Angels. Manager Jimy Williams is not given to panic. The Sox know
who they are. Assembled in the image of bloodless creator Dan
Duquette, they will not succumb to the hype, hope, or occasional
horror created by outsiders. Cheer, boo, rip, praise. It matters
not to the 25 men in the Boston clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   First pitch is at 1:05. Celebrating 100 years of major league
baseball on the landfill from Huntington to Brookline Avenue, the
cowhide-covered sphere is passed from Cy Young to Ramon Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
