<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2648 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-EMBASSY-U.S.-1S     04-10 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-EMBASSY-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA REJECTS U.S. ACCOUNT OF EMBASSY BOMBING IN BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add details and restructure: subs lede and adds new grafs
2,3 to restructure; adds new 4th graf with comment from U.S.
official; 9th graf to clarify; adds new grafs 10,11 with State
Department comments; deletes original last graf and adds 7 new
grafs of background and comments from Chinese.)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ China on Monday rejected the official U.S.
explanation for the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade
during NATO's air war against Yugoslavia last year, and again
demanded a ``thorough and comprehensive'' investigation. But U.S.
officials declared the matter closed.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for China's foreign ministry in Beijing, Zhu
Bangzao, criticized the Central Intelligence Agency's dismissal of
a mid-level officer blamed for the attack as inadequate and
reiterated China's demands that the Clinton administration ``punish
those responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   China's response indicated that its government remained deeply
suspicious of U.S. assurances that the bombing on May 7, which
killed three Chinese and wounded at least 20 others, was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect we're going to have to agree to disagree on this,''
a senior administration official said Monday, adding that there
were no plans to further investigate the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, 11 months after the bombing, the CIA dismissed
one officer and punished six others for their roles in identifying
and approving the target, which officials have said was intended to
be a military supply headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's spokesman insisted in a statement that the bombing
was ``a tragic accident,'' which officials have blamed on mistakes
made by the dismissed officer in locating the supply headquarters
on a map.
</P>
<P>
   Under Secretary of State Thomas R. Pickering notified the
Chinese ambassador to the United States of the punishment on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chinese foreign ministry spokesman disdained the
official U.S. explanation Monday. ``To pretend that the United
States did not know the position of the Chinese Embassy in
Yugoslavia is not credible,'' Zhu said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   What officials have said was the intended target, the Federal
Directorate of Supply and Procurement, was nearly 1,000 feet from
the embassy in the New Belgrade section of the capital, and Zhu
said the two buildings did not resemble each other. ``It was
impossible for the U.S. side to mix up these two buildings,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's spokesman, James P. Rubin, responded
Monday that the investigations had been ``thorough and complete.''
He said the administration had gone to great lengths to explain to
the Chinese the circumstances leading up to the bombing, and
described the dismissal of the agency officer and the punishment of
six others as ``appropriate steps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have followed through and implemented fully our commitment
to the Chinese to brief them fully on the results,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of the embassy caused grave strains in relations
between the United States and China, leading to attacks by mobs on
the U.S. Embassy in Beijing and a suspension of military ties and
other contacts with U.S. diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the attack, many Chinese officials and news
reports described the strike as deliberate, but Zhu did not repeat
that assertion Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For months afterwards, Chinese officials repeatedly raised the
bombing in meetings with U.S. officials, even as the two countries
made progress on other matters, like China's planned membership in
the World Trade Organization. More recently, Chinese officials had
moderated their complaints and in some meetings did not raise the
issue at all, according to administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the United States agreed to pay $28 million to
compensate China for the damage caused to the building. It had
previously agreed to pay $4.5 million to the families of those who
were killed. In return, China agreed to pay $2.8 million for damage
to the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Zhu said that the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade had ``unmistakable
markings'' that should have prevented its bombing. He expressed
disbelief at U.S. assertions that reviews after the target was
picked failed to detect the mapping error U.S. officials have
described.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have said the targeting error was not detected
during numerous reviews because military databases used during the
war did not note the current location of the Chinese Embassy, which
moved from its old location in central Belgrade more than four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's sharply worded criticism from China reflected the anger
still lingering over the attack. Defense and administration
officials in Washington say the Chinese position appears intended
in part for domestic consumption in China, but they also say the
bombing has deeply wounded Chinese pride.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, the Chinese spokesman, alluded to that Monday when he said
the attack ``greatly hurt the dignity of the Chinese people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an extremely serious international unlawful act,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
