<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  RIO GRANDE: SEVENTH MOST ENDANGERED RIVER
</P>
<P>
   By Alison Vekshin
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, April 10 -- Excessive water consumption and
over-engineering of riverbed habitat threaten the Rio Grande, which
ranked seventh among the nation's 13 most endangered rivers,
according to a survey released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   American Rivers, a national, non-profit conservation group,
ranked the rivers based on their serious and immediate
environmental degradation. It cited research published in
Conservation Biology, a scientific journal, that shows animals
living in the nation's rivers and streams are dying at a rate five
times faster than animals living on land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dams, dikes, ditching and draining have altered our rivers to
such an extent that today in America our native fish are homeless
in most parts of the country,'' said Rebecca Wodder, the group's
president. ``These days, if you're a fish, a river is a dangerous
place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1,960-mile Rio Grande, the nation's fifth longest river, has
been experiencing uncontrolled growth. Diversions for irrigation
have drained so much water that some sections have been left
completely dry, the report said. Combined with diversions for
municipal use, they claim almost 95 percent of the Rio Grande's
average annual flow.
</P>
<P>
   Other threats to the Rio Grande include flood control, land
development and pollution, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio Grande last made the group's endangered list in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds ironic but the river needs more water,'' said Steve
Harris, executive director at Rio Grande Restoration.
</P>
<P>
   He said El Paso's and Albuquerque's plans to divert more water
from the river will make the river go dry more often for longer
periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   Best Metcalf, U.S. director of the Rio Grande/Rio Bravo Basin
Coalition, said the Rio Grande Valley's population is burgeoning
and is relying on the river's water.
</P>
<P>
   Fluctuation in water flow is the river's main problem, said
Daniel Malanchuk, chief of the El Paso regulatory office of the
Albuquerque Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It's a problem that it's a border river between two
nations with different sets of laws.'' The report found that in
general, dams, levees and stabilized riverbanks have destroyed
river habitat and are contributing to the extinction of native fish
and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   At least 123 North American freshwater species have become
extinct since the beginning of the 20th century, said Anthony
Ricciardi of Dalhousie University in Nova Scotia, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The group has been issuing an annual list of endangered rivers
for 15 years. The Lower Snake River, which flows through
Washington, Oregon, Idaho and Wyoming, ranked first on the list.
The Missouri River, which spans from Montana to Missouri, ranked
second.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
