</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXILES SEEK `MIRACLE' TO KEEP BOY FROM GOING BACK TO CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Even as relatives caring for Elian Gonzalez met Monday
with a team of government psychiatrists to determine the best way
to hand the boy over to his father, the struggle to keep him with
them continued in court and on the streets of Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   With a mid-evening prayer vigil planned near the house Elian now
calls home, many in the Cuban exile community held out hope that
another ``miracle'' would occur -- a reference to Elian's survival
and Thanksgiving Day rescue off the south Florida coast. Still, a
reunion between father and son appeared imminent, the demonstrators
conceded for the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this moment, it looks like it's all over,'' said Yohanny
Martin, 25, a salesman who has made almost daily pilgrimmages to
the house. ``But it's not all over. That wouldn't be justice for
Elian, who has to be free.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, reversed himself Monday
and said he would travel to Miami to pick up his son under certain
conditions, among them a neutral location for the transfer. Miami
Police Department spokesman Angel Calzadilla reiterated that
officers would keep the peace outside the house but would not enter
it to help federal officials remove Elian.
</P>
<P>
   US Attorney General Janet Reno has been adamant in her efforts
to reunite Elian with his father, who arrived in Washington last
week with his second wife and their infant son. The only unresolved
issues, according to federal officials, are when, where and how the
reunion will occur.
</P>
<P>
   The mayors of Miami and Miami-Dade County, both Cuban-Americans,
planned to meet with Reno Tuesday in Washington to ask for a 30-day
transfer of custody, a delay they said would give Elian time to
adjust to leaving the American family he has come to know for the
Cuban one that has claimed him from the start. Miami Mayor Jose
Carollo noted that Elian was already ``snatched'' from one mother,
when she drowned enroute to Miami, and that it would be unhealthy
to take him suddenly from the young cousin to whom he has become
attached.
</P>
<P>
   That cousin, 21-year-old Marisleysis Gonzalez, remained
hospitalized Monday for exhaustion. At the family's request, their
meeting with two government psychiatrists, a psychologist and
officials with the Immigration and Naturalization Service was moved
from another location to the hospital where she is being treated.
Neither side had any comment after the session.
</P>
<P>
   James McGovern, a Massachusetts Democrat, had his own meeting
planned with Juan Miguel Gonzalez, along with the congressman's
wife, Lisa, and their toddler son. They carried a gift with them
for Gonzalez's 6-month-old boy: a little brush and comb set with
the US Capitol pictured on the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to tell you, I'm watching this guy on TV and my heart
aches for him,'' McGovern said. ``I couldn't imagine having my son
pulled away from me. I don't think I could bear it. It's probably
something I appreciate more now that I'm a father. I don't know
what I would do.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying his long-term interest was in normalizing relations with
Cuba, McGovern added that he hopes President Clinton will do
something before leaving office that no other president has done:
``Look at the right wing Cuban exile community and say `No.' This
craziness has to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, however, the family was not yet taking no for an
answer Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives, led by Elian's great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez, met
by minutes the deadline to formally appeal the federal court ruling
that gave Reno the right to return Elian to his father in Cuba. A
court hearing is scheduled for May 8.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the family's last-ditch efforts appeared unlikely to
pan out. Although she issued no ruling and set a hearing date for
next week, Circuit Court Judge Jennifer D. Bailey said the
relatives' appeal for custody seems to have little legal merit and
that they have shown little evidence that returning Elian to his
father would harm the child.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the house in Little Havana, however, protesters remained
firm in their conviction that returning Elian to a communist
country would not only be harmful but immoral. Few are predicting
violence anymore, and the smaller-than-usual crowd Monday afternoon
was calm if a bit downcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a certain element of bluff, the threats and the
warnings to do things that would be more self-destructive than
anything else. . .,'' said Max Castro, a University of Miami
political science professor who favors returning Elian to his
father, even if it means the child will grow up in Cuba. ``They
realized to a certain degree that they were shooting themselves in
the foot, so they figured, 'Let's stand down on this one.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With a rush-hour traffic slowdown at Miami International Airport
scrubbed last Friday, Cuban demonstrators were still vowing to form
a human chain to stop federal officials from removing Elian from
his great-uncle's home. But they continued to insist they would
welcome the father, whose stated desire to return to Cuba, they
said, is simply the communist line he has been fed by Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The father says what Fidel wants him to say,'' said Alfredo
Latour, 64, who worked for a Spanish-language magazine publisher
before he retired. ``Nobody wants to live in Cuba. Everyone wants
to leave, but they can't. And if he wants to stay there, well it
doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Anne Kornblut of the Globe Staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
