<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHO WILL BE THE NEW VEEP? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush insists he has made no
list yet, and Vice President Al Gore only last week initiated a
formal process to study the backgrounds of dozens of possible
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   They may be taking their time, but the rest of the political
world isn't. Since the only mystery left about the Republican and
Democratic presidential tickets is the identity of the running
mates, the national game of ``who'' is already in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bush nor Gore has the luxury of an easy pick _ an
obvious party star who would automatically be everyone's first
choice. The two most prominent potential candidates have
emphatically ruled themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain would bring political punch,
personality and foreign policy credibility to a Bush ticket. But
the governor prefers a veep ``who likes me.'' Any such latent
sentiment between the two surely died in the nasty South Carolina
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Colin Powell's bipartisan popularity rests in part
on his resistance to political activism. Although McCain, if
properly wooed, might change his mind, Powell never would. His wife
Alma is known to fear that as the first black candidate on a
national ticket, he might be killed.
</P>
<P>
   There are no Democrats who have similar broad party-expanding
appeal. House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt comes closest, but
his current role is pivotal in the Democratic campaign to regain
control of the House. He is more important to the party right where
he is.
</P>
<P>
   So the usual suspects are governors and members of Congress who
might balance the ticket by being helpful in key states or among
certain ethnic, generational or religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the first rule of veepdom is to be seen and not
heard, like a juvenile, and to never hurt the ticket. This rule,
however, has not always worked out well in practice.
</P>
<P>
   The most frivolous modern pick was Barry Goldwater's choice of a
snappy wordsmith, Rep. William Miller of New York in 1964 because
``he will drive (President) Lyndon (Johnson) nuts.'' Miller did
nothing of the sort, instead spending the campaign playing cards
with his traveling entourage.
</P>
<P>
   The most comfortable pick was George Bush the elder's 1988
selection of Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana because he liked the
younger man and saw him as non-threatening. But Quayle was a
political disaster, from his limp military record to his dismal
debate performance with his Democratic counterpart, the much
smarter Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The boldest was former Vice President Walter Mondale's 1984
choice of Rep. Geraldine Ferraro of New York, a pioneering act of
gender bravery driven by Mondale's grim assessment of how badly he
trailed President Reagan. But while Mondale cleared the candidate's
background for scandal he failed to look into that of her spouse.
The financial messes involving Ferraro's husband were discovered
too late.
</P>
<P>
   In the past a typical approach was simply to embrace a defeated
rival in hopes of uniting the party. Thus Ronald Reagan took George
Bush, Michael Dukakis took Bentsen and Bob Dole took Jack Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   Geographical balance led Illinois Gov. Adlai Stevenson to pick
Sen. John Sparkman of Alabama, John F. Kennedy to pick Sen. Johnson
of Texas and Richard Nixon to take Maryland Gov. Spiro Agnew.
</P>
<P>
   But that theory evaporated with Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton's
1992 selection of Sen. Al Gore from neighboring Tennessee. The
pairing clicked so well that geography is now merely one of many
factors to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the veep is supposed to bring an alternate ideology to
the ticket to reassure voters that the nominee is not unacceptably
hard-line about the issues he campaigns on. This tactic does not
work well since vice presidents are not independent entities.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge is currently a prospect for
Bush's short list because he is a Catholic from a big northeastern
state who is pro-choice and might soften Bush's anti-abortion
image. New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, also pro-choice, is
similarly attractive if Bush decides not to give up on the
Northeast, his weakest region.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Ferraro did nothing to save Mondale (no male could
have either), the notion of a female vice president is still alive.
But women do not necessarily vote for other women. They did not go
for Elizabeth Dole, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore recently appointed former Secretary of State Warren
Christopher to examine the personal stories and financial records
of hordes of prospects. People who don't feel like cooperating get
dropped _ as well they should.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates should not be confronted with unpleasant
surprises, as George McGovern was in 1972. His running mate, Sen.
Thomas Eagleton of Missouri, turned out to have had electric-shock
treatments for depression that he had failed to mention.
</P>
<P>
   It is more exciting to speculate that Bush and Gore will try to
do something adventuresome than to resign ourselves to the idea of
boring partners who offer more of the same. Why shouldn't Bush pick
his brother Jeb, governor of Florida, a state he needs to carry?
Bush-Bush would create certain dynasty problems. But what the heck,
the Kennedys have managed it.
</P>
<P>
   Why shouldn't Gore select Secretary of Defense William Cohen, a
former Republican senator so moderate that Democrats love him? He
even writes poetry.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is imagination and a little courage, fellows.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
