<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2664 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-EXPLORERS-CENTURY-BOS     04-10 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPLORERS-CENTURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMED EXPLORERS SAY MUCH LEFT TO BE DISCOVERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the Hubbard dining room at the National
Geographic Society Monday, seven of the world's most famous
explorers discussed the weighty topic of whether the age of global
exploration was over.
</P>
<P>
   Far from it, they said.
</P>
<P>
   To prove their point, the seven, who were named as the National
Geographic's first members of an Explorers-in-Residence program,
described what they wanted to go after.
</P>
<P>
   Their answers revealed a world of the unknown, even in this age
of discovery that has physically reached some of the ends of the
earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be studying and reconstructing the earliest and most
primitive dinosaur this year in Argentina,'' said paleontologist
Paul Sereno, who noted that half of all dinosaurs discovered were
found in the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   After Argentina, Sereno will take a three-month trek into the
Sahara Desert, digging up other dinosaur fossils.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Goodall, the leading authority on chimpanzees after 40
years of study, will push for saving the rapidly dwindling species,
especially in the Democratic Republic of Congo, formerly known as
Zaire. Archeologist Johan Reinhard will explore higher-altitude
Andean Mountain burial sites for preserved mummies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will go back to the Black Sea and look for evidence of
human habitation from the legend of the biblical flood,'' said
ocean explorer Robert D. Ballard, president of the Institute for
Exploration in Mystic, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Anthropologist Wade Davis, who received his doctorate in
ethnobotany from Harvard University, plans to walk from the Chumbi
Valley to Rongbuk monastery in the Himalayas to explore the makeup
of distant cultures. Stephen Ambrose, author and historian, hopes
to help restore parts of the Lewis and Clark trail.
</P>
<P>
   And marine biologist Sylvia Earle will study marine sanctuaries
off Florida's Keys and California's Channel Islands and Monterey
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't know what's out there,'' Earle said. ``Less
than 5 percent of the deep sea has been seen at all.''
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic hopes its explorer program will promote
conservation and scientific learning. The explorers were chosen to
take part for several years, spending much of the time in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in history that we have the ability to
do widespread irreparable harm to the environment,'' said Terry
Garcia, vice president for mission programs at National Geographic,
standing under a portrait of the society's founder, long-bearded
Gardiner Greene Hubbard.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we also have the chance in using the advanced
communications to draw attention to the sustainability of the
planet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The explorers stressed how much remained unknown, saying the
perceptions that there was little left in the physical world to
uncover was wrong. In short comments, several made references to
the oceans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The universe below is the greatest frontier ever,'' said
author Ambrose. ``Except maybe botany, and all the plants yet to be
discovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodall said new uses of DNA would lead to many discoveries
among chimpanzees and other animals.
</P>
<P>
   And she made another point: Discoveries can be made any time, as
any child knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 4 1/2 years old, no one would tell me where eggs
came from. So I sat in a henhouse for several hours,'' she said.
``Finally when I saw a hen lay an egg, it was exciting to me as,
Eureka!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
