<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2671 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-GAY-CEREMONY &LR;      04-10 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-GAY-CEREMONY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFECT UNION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With CNS-GAY-COMMITMENT) 
 (EDS: Note language in 14th graf.) SAME-SEX COUPLES SEEK MORE (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Stephen Parker is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By STEPHEN PARKER   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Supporters of same-sex marriage have battled in
states across the nation to enjoy the same rights as married
heterosexual couples. Now they're taking the fight to Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   On April 29, as many as 5,000 gay and lesbian couples will
participate in a mass wedding outside the Internal Revenue Service
headquarters in the nation's capital. The location was chosen to
protest the denial of tax benefits for gay and lesbian couples,
says the Rev. Elder Troy Perry, founder and moderator of the
Universal Fellowship of Metropolitan Community Churches, who
organized the event and will conduct the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Those planning the nonsectarian wedding expect it will be the
world's largest demonstration celebrating same-gender unions. It is
planned in connection with the April 30 Millennium March on
Washington for Equality, which is expected to draw hundreds of
thousands of participants to the National Mall in support of civil
rights protections for gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgendered
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding and demonstration are the most recent and most
visible events in the struggle for same-gender marriage, a fight
that's been waged for nearly a decade. No state legally recognizes
marriage between same-sex couples, but the wedding planners say now
is the time to rally against discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the last minority group you can hate in public and still
get away with it,'' says Perry, who founded his church as a place
in which Christians could worship and be openly gay. ``It's
important to share in these elections what we want from government
and what we're striving for.'' The movement now has 314 churches
and about 52,000 active members, Perry says.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government and 34 states now have laws known as
``defense of marriage acts,'' which restrict marriage to
heterosexual couples. Similar legislation is pending in 10 more
states, according to the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund, a
gay and lesbian advocacy group based in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the right to marry, gay and lesbian couples seek
other spousal benefits, including the right to qualify for shared
health-insurance benefits, to file joint tax returns, to visit
partners in the hospital and make medical decisions for them in
emergencies, and to inherit each other's property.
</P>
<P>
   ``The religious right says we don't settle down, we're
promiscuous,'' says the Rev. Elder Nori Rost of the Pikes Peak
Metropolitan Community Church. ``But when we want to encourage
long-term relationships, they say, `Absolutely no way.'''
</P>
<P>
   The movement to legalize same-sex marriages won a short-lived
victory in 1993 when the Hawaii Supreme Court ruled that denial of
the freedom to marry is discrimination. But the court recently said
its decision was rendered moot in 1998, when voters passed a
constitutional amendment allowing the Hawaii Legislature to
restrict marriage to opposite-sex couples. In a conciliatory move,
the state has passed a ``reciprocal beneficiaries'' law, giving the
broadest rights and benefits ever accorded to gay and lesbian
couples in the United States, according to Lambda.
</P>
<P>
   Gay-marriage supporters lost another major battle in California
last month as voters approved Proposition 22, which excludes legal
recognition of same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   The latest fight is over a ``civil unions'' bill approved by the
Vermont House of Representatives and pending in the state Senate
that would give same-sex couples the same rights and benefits as
married heterosexual couples, with one notable exception _ the
right to legally marry.
</P>
<P>
   The commitment ceremony falls on the same day as a Texas
couple's 45th anniversary. The Rev. Ralph Lasher, 72, and his
partner, Harry Gibson, 79, will renew their vows in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've served as a role model for people,'' Lasher says of his
longtime relationship with Gibson. ``They constantly strive and use
us as an example that it can happen. It's important to let people
see we can be serious about relationships _ it's not all about
one-night stands.''
</P>
<P>
   But another couple, Richard, 53, and Tony, 58, will speak about
the discrimination they have faced as a gay couple. (Because of
Tony's uncertain immigration status, they asked that their last
names be withheld.) The couple obtained a marriage license in 1975
from a Boulder, Colo., city clerk who claimed it was legal for gay
men to marry. Tony, an Australian immigrant, applied for residency
as Richard's spouse, but an Immigration and Naturalization Service
official denied the request in a typed response, stating, ``You
have failed to establish that a bona fide marital relationship can
exist between two faggots.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd also will hear from Rev. Jimmy Creech, 55, a former
United Methodist minister from Raleigh, N.C., whose credentials
were removed because he performed a holy-union ceremony for two gay
men in April 1999. Creech has a wife and three children but has
taken up the fight for legal same-sex unions because, he says, to
deny them is purely bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are relationships that deserves honor, acceptance and
support by society,'' Creech says. ``Marriage is not based on
gender; it's based on love and commitment. To define it purely on
biological terms is to distort the whole understanding of
marriage.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1928EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2672 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-GAY-COMMITMENT &LR;      04-10 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-GAY-COMMITMENT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(WITH CNS-GAY-CEREMONY ) 
 GAY COUPLES FIND A PLACE AT THE ALTAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Stephen Parker is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By STEPHEN PARKER   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nori Rost still remembers the day she admired her
best friend's white wedding gown and watched family and friends
gather around the bride and groom. She couldn't stop crying and
repeatedly left the reception line to pull herself together. As a
lesbian, Ross realized she could not have a picture-perfect wedding
of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Rost never did get married. But she has performed up to 100
commitment ceremonies for gay and lesbian couples during 10 years
as pastor of the Pikes Peak Metropolitan Community Church in
Colorado Springs, Colo. These ceremonies are church weddings that
aren't recognized as legal marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Gay and lesbians has been fighting for years to gain the freedom
to legally marry. They have encountered many setbacks, including a
conservative Christian effort to protect traditional marriage.
Thirty-four states have passed laws excluding legal recognition for
gay and lesbian spouses, but Rost argues same-sex marriage would in
no way threaten traditional marriage between a man and woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if there is only a limited number of marriage
certificates to give out, and gay and lesbian couples would take
them,'' Rost says.
</P>
<P>
   Gay and lesbian couples know they may have a long fight ahead
before they gain the entitlements of legally sanctioned marriages.
But thousands have taken the plunge anyway, exchanging vows and
rings in churches throughout the nation. According to the National
Gay and Lesbian Task Force Policy Institute, a number of sects
perform commitment ceremonies. Among them: the Universal Fellowship
of Metropolitan Community Churches _ which was founded specifically
as a place for gay and lesbian Christians to worship _ Unitarians
and Universalists, United Church of Christ, Quakers and independent
Jewish synagogues. The Central Conference of American Rabbis,
representing the Reform movement, said in March that Reform rabbis
who decided to officiate at same-sex ceremonies would have its
support.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Community Church of New York has performed
hundreds of commitment ceremonies. ``This is not about rights,''
says the Rev. Pat Bumgardner. ``The ceremony is a recognition of
the holy nature of their love and its value. There is something
legitimating about doing that in a church before God.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Krueger, 38, and Linda Randolph, 48, of Larkspur, Colo.,
walked down separate aisles in their holy-union ceremony. Both wore
chiffon, knee-length white dresses, and exchanged vows and rings.
The women will celebrate their 10-year anniversary in November, and
they say the ceremony helped their love grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more and more in love with each other every day,''
Krueger says. ``We have found a deepening of our relationship. Even
though there have been tough times, we've come through them being
stronger on the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Many committed gay and lesbian couples raise children _ from
former heterosexual spouses, artificial insemination or adoption.
Roughly half of the hundreds of New York couples united in
Metropolitan Community Church ceremonies raise children, Bumgardner
says.
</P>
<P>
   Don Campbell, a 60-year-old graphics designer from Colorado
Springs, Colo., divorced his wife 14 years ago, but he says he has
a great relationship with his son and daughters. His partner, Tom
Simpleman, is a 51-year-old pharmacist who is also divorced with
children. In their June 1998 commitment ceremony, their sons were
the best men, and the daughters, ``I guess you call them
groomsmaids,'' Campbell says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're honest about who we are, and people see we're normal
people who happen to love somebody who's the same sex we are, the
more accepted we're going to be,'' Campbell says.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 1928EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2673 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-JEWS-IN-JERUSALEM     04-10 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-JEWS-IN-JERUSALEM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWS IN JERUSALEM: THE GREAT DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Maya Dollarhide is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By MAYA DOLLARHIDE   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II's recent visit to Jerusalem
refocused the world's attention on the centuries-old conflict among
Christians, Jews and Muslims over the city each considers to be its
Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   But Jerusalem is also the site of another conflict _ lesser
known to some in the outside world _ that is equally emotional and
divisive. It pits the city's ultra-Orthodox community, which rules
Jerusalem, against Conservative, Reform and secular Jews.
</P>
<P>
   At the very core of this conflict is the sensitive debate of
what it means to be a Jew.
</P>
<P>
   There are roughly 200,000 Jews living in Jerusalem today.
Eighty-five percent of them would consider themselves ``religious''
and 60 percent would be considered secular or non-Orthodox Jews,
according to Rabbi Michael Paley, an Orthodox American rabbi, who
has lived and worked in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Non-Orthodox Jews are not recognized in Israel by the
ultra-Orthodox community. Yet they must live by laws created by the
Orthodoxy in Government. For example, the city keeps the Sabbath,
even if all its inhabitants do not. Public transportation and most
businesses and restaurants, are closed Friday evening until the sun
sets on Saturday. In addition, the work and school week start on
Sundays for the Jewish community. Only the Muslim and Christian
schools are open on Saturdays. The simple difference in the school
week makes it difficult for children of the various religions to
mix.
</P>
<P>
   But the most controversial aspect of the Orthodox versus the
other Jewish groups is the inability of Conservative and Reform
rabbis to perform weddings or help with divorce proceedings.
Throughout Israel, only Orthodox rabbis have the power to do these
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem for the Reform and Conservative movements
in Israel is that they represent only a handful of neighborhoods
and seats in the government,'' Paley said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem is getting crowded. New businesses open up daily next
to sacred sites, and tourists can go from McDonald's to the Western
Wall in 10 minutes. The secular and the religious worlds that are
jockeying for position live in side-by-side tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secular world and the religious world live side by side,
but they do not mix,'' said Paley.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I lived in Jerusalem,'' said Abby Beshkin, 27, a former
Hebrew University student, ``it was hard for me to convince people
that my political views leaned towards the left, but that I was
still Orthodox and religious.'' While Beshkin kept the Sabbath, she
also believed that public transportation should be available for
those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   Some Jews in Jerusalem say they observe the Sabbath only because
it is strictly enforced in the city. In the ultra-Orthodox
neighborhoods, men will sometimes throw stones at cars they see on
the road. ``Sabbath!'' they shout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is open on Friday nights,'' said Deborah Doft, 27,
also a former Hebrew University student. ``I had friends who would
drive into Tel Aviv because there is more going on there. There are
bars and cafes open on Fridays. But not in Jerusalem, except maybe
a few in the Arab quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   David Erlick is a self-proclaimed secular Jew living in
Jerusalem. Although Erlick does not always celebrate the Sabbath,
he closes down his successful cafe on Friday nights. ``No one would
come anyway,'' he said. When they were younger, Erlick and secular
friends used to break all of the Sabbath rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have barbecue with pork and watch television,'' he
said. ``It would really upset my more conservative-minded
neighbors.'' Erlick said more happens on Fridays in Tel Aviv and
Beshkin agreed, ``Public transportation doesn't run in Tel Aviv,
but you see more cars on the road and more clubs are open,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tel Aviv is considered to be the most secular city in Israel.
``The religious live in Jerusalem,'' Paley said. `` The secular _
they like Tel Aviv.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, these issues have to do with a civil society,
reconciling a Jewish State to a state containing many citizens,''
said Stuart Shoffman, a senior editor for the Jerusalem Report.
``It's tricky and technological.'' Shoffman believes that everyone,
including the Muslim and Christian people living in Israel, must
have equal living situations in order for the city to run at its
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority of the city doesn't fall into the ultra-Orthodox
community. There is a large spectrum,'' he said. ``The secular and
the religious Jewish education, everything is divided.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Reuven Hammer, a Conservative rabbi, said bitterly at a
panel discussion in Jerusalem last month, ``This is the only
country in the free world where Jews are denied basic religious
freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   But as dialogue between the groups starts to happen, many are
optimistic that the religious and secular communities can be woven
together into the fabric of Israeli life, especially in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in Israel,'' said Schoffman. `` I have to believe
things will get better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
