<SLUG> BC-CNS-LOWRENT-BROKER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS REAL-ESTATE BROKER SPECIALIZES IN LOW-RENT APARTMENTS FOR THE
POOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Natalie Leston is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By NATALIE LESTON   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not a day goes by that Linda Stephens doesn't
remember how, three years ago, she and her three children were
evicted from their Bronx apartment. Stephens was in the middle of a
second divorce, her salon business was going under, and the family
had to go on welfare for several months. After living with friends
and relatives for six months, she finally found a new apartment she
could afford.
</P>
<P>
   A few months after moving into her own apartment, Stephens got
her real-estate license and found an apartment for a woman who had
also been evicted. That led to more calls and referrals and, soon,
she had her own business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed to be my calling,'' Stephens said.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when rents in New York City are skyrocketing, it is
especially difficult for low-income working residents to find an
affordable place to live. The Census Bureau says the average
monthly rent for an apartment in the city's five boroughs increased
37 percent from 1991 to 1999, from $475 to $648. But those figures
also include rent-regulated apartments, and do not as accurately
reflect current market conditions. Some studio apartments go for as
much as $1,850 a month, and rents for larger apartments are
significantly higher. For a person with a job paying minimum wage
or not much more, it can be difficult to find an affordable
apartment, and a real-estate agent who is willing to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous lack of affordable housing in New York
City right now that is safe and suitable,'' said Joshua Goldfein, a
lawyer at the Legal Aid Society's Homeless Rights Project, which
represents the homeless and helps them find work.
</P>
<P>
   Goldfein said that the amount of government-subsidized housing
had fallen sharply in recent years as a result of cuts in financing
for low-income housing. And many city-owned residential buildings
have been sold to private owners.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens works with about 20 to 30 individuals or families each
month, most of which she says are ``quite desperate.'' They have
been displaced from their homes for a variety of reasons, including
losing their jobs, getting divorced, suffering domestic abuse, or
being HIV positive. Many are living in shelters or with relatives
in overcrowded conditions. Since starting her business, Stephens
says, she has worked with about 200 low-income individuals and
families.
</P>
<P>
   To find her apartments for her clients, Stephens calls landlords
she has contacts with, mostly in the Bronx and Manhattan. She has
learned, she said, which landlords have the cleanest and most
affordable apartments. Rents for the apartments she takes clients
to see start at $550 for a one-bedroom, $650 for a two-bedroom and
$750 for a three-bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens works out of her Morris Park apartment in the Bronx,
which she says allows her to save on office rent as well as spend
more time with her children, who are 15, 17 and 20. While most
real-estate brokers charge a fee of as much as 15 percent of annual
rent as commission, Stephens charges one month's rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most real-estate brokers it's about the money, not about
the people,'' she said. ``For me it's a personal issue to help as
many people as I can and also be able to help my family.'' Stephens
said she earns enough to provide for her family _ she wouldn't say
how much _ but that they have few luxuries.
</P>
<P>
   About half her referrals, Stephens said, come from city agencies
that deal with the homeless or from private nonprofit groups like
the Coalition for the Homeless. If she cannot help potential
clients, she will direct them to appropriate agencies or groups for
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes broker's fees are so ridiculous that we stop using
them,'' said Donna James, the program director for the Coalition
for the Homeless' Rental Assistance Program. ``But with Linda
Stephens, it works both ways. She refers people to us, and we
sometimes call her when we need an apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   When agencies are involved, however, the process can be lengthy.
If a landlord has a vacancy, and there is an agency to help pay the
rent, it's a ``win-win situation,'' Stephens said. But it can take
weeks or even months for a landlord to get a check, and many are
unwilling to hold an apartment until they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a tennis match, back and forth, until you finally
get the keys and a lease,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens said she constantly lives with cash flow problems as
she waits for her own checks from clients. But she said she looks
into a potential client's background and resources before taking
them on so she has always been paid her fee except in one or two
instances.
</P>
<P>
   Her job, however, does not necessarily end after she has found
an apartment for a client, or even after the person has moved in.
Often with low-rent apartments, there are heat or electrical
problems and, sometimes, a family simply cannot afford the rent
after they have moved in. In cases like these, Stephens often acts
as an arbitrator to help find a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it is so exhausting and emotionally draining,'' she
said. ``I'm a person, so I take the client's problems too
personally.''
</P>
<P>
   But she still hopes to expand her real-estate services to all
five boroughs of New York and, in the next couple of years, to
start her own nonprofit group to help low-income residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been blessed,'' Stephens said, referring to her own
family. ``By helping others, I've helped myself. You don't change a
good thing, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
