<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-TATTOO-ARTISIS &LR;      04-10 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-TATTOO-ARTISIS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TATTOO CLASSES OFFER STUDENTS A NEW WAY TO BECOME ARTISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Jocelyn Anderson is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By JOCELYN ANDERSON   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bryan Bogle pulled up his gray trouser leg to reveal
an abstract geometric symbol, jet black ink against his light skin.
Instructor Bruce Kaplan, his long, dark hair secured by a leather
headband, nodded approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not bad,'' Kaplan said. ``Next time, you should to put the
needle in deeper and not leave it as long. It will look smoother.''
At long last, Bogle had successfully tattooed something other than
a practice grapefruit at home.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle is a student at Sacred Tattoo shop in lower Manhattan,
where Kaplan had given him five lessons in the art of creating
permanent designs by piercing the skin with ink-injecting needles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practicing on fruit is completely different from skin,'' says
Bogle, a 21-year-old art student who wears his dark hair short with
sideburns. His skin is peppered with seven tattoos, including a
particularly intricate spider web woven across his left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straight lines are the hardest,'' Bogle says, especially since
tattooing is done with an oversize needle that is attached to a
power box and a cord. ``I'm used to paintbrushes. Here you've got
such a heavy machine, it's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogle, like others who find their way to Kaplan's Canal Street
shop, is looking to perfect a skill that has become increasingly
popular. Once the province of sailors, today's body art is sported
by everyone from co-eds to cowboys. But even as tattoos have
proliferated, instruction studios are somewhat rare. The
traditional way to enter the profession is through apprenticeship
with a tattoo artist for a year or more, a method many
traditionalists still say is the best way to true artistry. Despite
such naysayers, Kaplan says he is improving the profession by
ensuring that would-be tattoo artists get the proper training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are clueless,'' Kaplan said, noting that many young
people are purchasing the elaborate electric tattoo needles but
lack the knowledge to use them. ``We sell them the equipment, so
why not sell them the knowledge?''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's lessons, at $100 each, cover use of the electric
needle, which Sacred Tattoo also sells, techniques of sterilization
and safety, and viewing sessions in which the student watches him
give different types of tattoos to customers. Then, students go off
to practice on their own on grapefruits.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 or so students Kaplan has trained in his first year of
teaching have come from varied backgrounds and have included women
learning to apply permanent eyeliner and physicians who use
tattooing techniques in plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The volume of students at Kaplan's studio does not meet with the
approval of other practitioners. In an industry where many artists
say the techniques have been kept a secret for decades, some
consider the mass teaching approach a weakening of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bakaty, the owner of Fineline Tattoo on Manhattan's Lower
East Side, doubts that quick introductions to tattooing without
practice under the watchful eye of an expert can produce skilled
artists. Bakaty says each shop should develop a sense of cohesion:
the practitioners in his shop, for example, are mostly people who
have trained under him for long periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   Tattoo artistry was recognized as an official profession in New
York City two years ago when the Department of Health decided to
require practitioners to be licensed. Department of Health records
list 509 licensed artists, said Eric Giebelhaus, spokesman for the
agency. Each plunks down $25 to take an exam on sterilization and
$100 for a license.
</P>
<P>
   But this system makes it too easy to enter such a technically
demanding field in the opinion of Carlo Fodera, owner of Technical
Tattoo supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible because you learn from a little textbook,'' said
Fodera. ``You're learning sterilization, but you're not learning
the technical aspects of applying ink to skin. Tattooing is just as
technical as it is artistic. You have to know how many layers of
skin to penetrate or you can give a really bad tattoo.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, bad tattoos from less experienced artists
have some benefits for established artists, said Chester Oswalt, a
tattoo artist for Sunset Strip Tattoo in Los Angeles. The novice
competition actually brings him more customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get more tattoo artists, these cowboys with equipment out
there,'' said Oswalt who has been tattooing for 11 years. ``But
then they mess up, and the people have to come to me to get it
fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Bogle is not worried. As music by Bob Dylan played on the
stereo system in Sacred Tattoo, Bogle leaned back and braced for
the pain of the needle. His arm was already covered with a
``sleeve'' of tattoos. He had come to Kaplan to extend the pattern
to his chest. Someday, he said, he will be on other side of the
needle_giving tattoos to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I got my first tattoo I was fascinated with it,'' said
Bogle. ``If I could tattoo in my house for a while or get a job
right away I'd be happy. I'd like to work in a tattoo shop even if
I'm not tattooing.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
(mp) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
