<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2681 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-PRISONS-HISTORY &LR;      04-10 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-PRISONS-HISTORY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRECTION DEPT. SEEKS TO CAPTURE ITS HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Trenton Daniel is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By TRENTON DANIEL   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Capt. Beverly Pinckney of the Department of
Correction unlocked a door to the new steel storage cage &UR; , &LR; 
rummaged through a metal file cabinet and pulled out an aged copy
of the Rikers Review.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's one of the magazines put out by some of our inmates,''
she said, thumbing through the publication produced at the Rikers
Island prison compound.
</P>
<P>
   She  &UR;  &LR; turned to a couple of filing cabinets and pulled open the
brown drawers. Inside was a historical trove mothers' written pleas
to visit their babies' graves, inmates' redemption-themed short
stories and poetry, century-old handcuffs, photos of the burials of
indigents in unmarked graves.
</P>
<P>
   The collection of memorabilia and documents is part of a novel
plan for an archive to preserve a historical record about prisons
and prisoners in both the city and state of New York. The archive,
being developed by the Department of Correction, will be a
permanent repository of letters pertaining to prison business,
annual reports and inmate photos. It will include memorabilia such
as a female guard's uniform and prisoners' metal dining trays from
decades past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of the historical society is to tell the story of
those accused of breaking laws,'' said Thomas McCarthy, who, in
addition to working as the DOC spokesman, directs the archive from
a cubicle furnished with only a desk, phone and computer. McCarthy,
61, said he will focus exclusively on the project after he retires
next year. ``There's a story about the tension in society between
the part of society that wants to lose the wall, and the other part
that wants to build high walls. This struggle is a story. It is a
story that needs to be told.''
</P>
<P>
   The archive today is an unorganized collection in a closet-sized
cage at the department's academy in Queens. But McCarthy hopes one
day to turn it into a museum more accessible to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy founded the New York Correction Historical Society in
1997, winning approval and a tiny budget from the city's prison
commissioner to preserve and promote the history of New York City
and state correctional services.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the archive was opened to researchers and the
public. The ``real treasure of the collection,'' said McCarthy, is
a ledger book meticulously recording the names, birthdates and
causes of death _ ranging from smallpox to alcoholism _ of the
indigents buried in the City Cemetery, or Potter's Field, between
1872 and 1875. More than 750,000 indigents, including the stillborn
babies of the poor, are buried in the cemetery on Harts Island;
aging photographs feature expressionless Rikers Island inmates
burying the dead in pinewood coffins.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the letters in the archive are the requests of poor
mothers seeking to visit the Potter's Field graves of their
stillborns. Another letter accompanied the donation of 2,600
baseball bleacher seats from Ebbets Field in Brooklyn to the
Correction Department. Handcuffs in the collection recall the days
when large thick keys were used to lock heavy metal cuffs.
</P>
<P>
   The prison guard's uniform skirt is a recent addition to the
archive. Only last year, the prisons banned the skirt uniform,
which was difficult to wear when using gas masks that strap on the
leg during riots.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said the archival project appears to be unique among
prison systems, but is an important chronicle of the department's
history. ``We know who we are from our memory of who we were,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
