<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2682 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-BARAK-0411-CO     04-10 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BARAK-0411-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, BARAK TO DISCUSS MIDEAST PEACE, MILITARY SALES TO CHINA
 &HT;    (650&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton meets Tuesday with Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, hoping to press forward the slow-moving Middle
East peace process and head off Israel's planned sale of advanced
radar to China.
</P>
<P>
   With Barak and Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat
aiming to ink a final peace accord later this year, White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton felt ``the time is right,'' to
talk face-to-face with both leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that there is a breakthrough expected,'' Lockhart
told reporters Monday. ``But there is a lot going on on this track
in the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Much is on the table, as well, regarding Israeli-China
relations. Clinton's not happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   The specific irritant is Israel's plan to sell China an advanced
Israeli-built airborne radar system mounted on a Russian aircraft.
The so-called PHALCON system, U.S. military officials fear, could
give a critical boost to China's ability to control an air attack
on neighboring Taiwan, a close U.S. partner in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen traveled to Israel last week to
try to convince Barak's government to cancel the proposed sale.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said Barak would
hear more on the matter Tuesday, when he meets with Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, and then with White House National
Security Adviser Samuel Berger, before an evening appointment at
the White House with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been profoundly concerned about a particular issue
related to the sale of certain aircraft systems to China,'' Rubin
told reporters. ``I don't intend to predict where and to what
extent it's discussed at any particular meeting, but I would expect
it to be discussed. ``
</P>
<P>
   Barak is scheduled to fly back to Israel on Wednesday _ a day
before he hosts Chinese President Jiang Zemin in the first-ever
visit by a Chinese head of state to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is slated to host Arafat for a White House meeting April
20.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Israeli and Palestinian officials have been meeting at
Bolling Air Force Base near Washington in recent weeks, hashing
over the details of a complex set of peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   After 50 years of enmity and war, the two sides have set a
mid-May deadline for agreeing to a blueprint for a final peace
accord. They hope to strike that final agreement by Sept. 13, if
they can settle their most difficult outstanding disputes _
including the future of Jerusalem, the question of Palestinian
statehood and the right of Palestinian refugees to return to
Israeli-controlled lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The President believes that it's appropriate from time-to-time
to sit down and talk to the leaders face-to-face to try to move the
process forward,'' Lockhart said. ``And the President believes the
time is right to sit down and meet with both leaders, in the
context of this week and next week.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be Clinton's third meeting with a Mideast head of state
in a little more than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Clinton met at the White House with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak, who has played a long-standing role in
helping to advance talks between Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   He met with Syrian President Hafez Assad in Geneva on March 26,
but was unable to persuade the Syrian leader to resume stalled
peace talks with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Assad responded formally to Israeli ideas Clinton
presented in Geneva. Rubin said there were ``differences,'' between
Assad's position in Geneva and views expressed in Friday's
diplomatic communique, but no breakthroughs that augured an
immediate resumption of Israeli-Syrian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our standpoint, we have not heard anything that, in our
view, could address seriously the remaining gaps,'' Rubin told
reporters. ``But we will continue to see if there are ways to
overcome the gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hosted Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk
al-Sharaa for a week of peace talks last January in Sheperdstown,
W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations broke down, however, over the nut issue of
Israel's return of the strategic Golan Heights in exchange for
security guarantees from Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Syria is insisting that Israel agree to return the Golan Heights
_ land Israeli troops seized in the 1967 Israeli-Arab war _ in its
entirety before substantive security talks may advance.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has sought to retain some access to the Sea of Galilee _
Israel's main source of fresh water _ which is located within the
disputed territory.
</P>
<P>
   In a related issue, Israel plans to withdraw its troops from
southern Lebanon sometime in July. U.S. officials had hoped the
withdrawal would be part of a larger peace accord between Israel
and Syria _ which has close military ties with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   With talks between the two countries stalled, though, Barak has
said he intends to withdraw the troops with or without the
cooperation of Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
