<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-FEAR-OF-CLOWNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, CLOWNS ARE NO LAUGHING MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Michael Goldman is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By MICHAEL GOLDMAN   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regina McCann works in a funeral home. But her nightmares aren't
caused by dead people. They're caused by clowns, or, as the
28-year-old mother of two explains, ``a whole bunch of clowns on
stilts of all different heights chasing my car.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, the fear of clowns, performers who strive to make
audiences laugh, might seem trivial, even funny. But to a largely
silent and unknown number of children and adults, the fear of
clowns, or coulrophobia (derived from the Greek word for limb), is
no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   McCann, a secretary who lives in Elkin, N.C., says that while
she tries to avoid clowns, if she does see one, the confrontation
causes an intense physical reaction. ``I just can't stand it,'' she
said in serious, even tones. ``I stiffen up, sweat and get
goose-bumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Clowning is one of the oldest and most universal forms of
entertainment, according to Bruce Johnson, author of numerous books
on clowning, including ``Jest in Time,'' a history of the subject.
Court jesters were the first clowns, Johnson said, performing in
China and in Egypt as early as 1818 B.C. Throughout history, he
said, clowns have served a special role. ``The court jesters could
criticize the kings through their humor when the kings wouldn't
accept that criticism from anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's precisely the tendency of clowns to operate outside of
societal norms that causes some to fear them. ``They're social
outlaws,'' said Benjamin Procter, a 25-year-old art director for a
Manhattan software company who freely admits ``clowns scare the
bejesus out of me.'' ``Because they're playing this character, it's
as if they're authorized to do things ordinary people can't do.
They can pull off your toupee or jump into the audience and
generally make fun of you while suffering no consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   That clowns mask their identity also troubles Procter. ``They'll
have a smile painted across their face that has nothing to do with
their actual mouth position,'' he said. ``Clowns are people who are
hiding their identity. They can't be trusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people who fear clowns may have had had a traumatic
childhood experience, according to Ronald Doctor, a professor of
psychology at California State University, Northridge, who has
written a book on phobias. ``Kids around 2 or so,'' he said, ``are
very reactive to a familiar body with an unfamiliar face.''
</P>
<P>
   But for as many people who develop the fear that way, Doctor
said, there are as many who develop it through movies in which
clowns behave badly. Stephen King's movie ``It,'' which featured a
demented, murderous clown named Pennywise, did for clowns, Doctor
said, what ``Psycho'' did for the shower and what ``Jaws'' did for
swimming in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   As if that wasn't damaging enough, it's a matter of record that
the serial killer John Wayne Gacy liked to dress up as ``Pogo the
Clown'' and entertain at children's parties when he wasn't sexually
torturing and murdering teen-age boys.
</P>
<P>
   But to Kathryn O'Dell, executive director of International Clown
Hall of Fame, a Milwaukee organization dedicated to ``honoring and
sustaining the art of clowning,'' it's the images and fears of
clowns that are disturbing, not the clowns themselves. Children who
fear clowns, she added, ``are the same children who are afraid of
Barney, Santa Claus and the Easter Bunny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Butterscotch the Clown,'' who goes by the name Candy Will in
real life, believes children's fears are often exacerbated by
insensitive parents. The 46-year-old clown from San Juan
Capistrano, Calif., ``would like to beg parents not to force their
child into the arms of a clown if the child is afraid and crying.
This is where most of the phobias start.''
</P>
<P>
   Allyson Lezon, a 22-year-old clown from Salem, Conn., agreed
that children with fears should not be forced to interact with
clowns. Lezon, also known as ``Bubbles Lezagna,'' said she's able
to draw many children out, though, by acting ``as if Bubbles is
afraid of little girls and boys. After a few minutes of that,
they'll come out and try to comfort me.''
</P>
<P>
   Her strategy for scared adults: ``just back away.''
</P>
<P>
   If prevention fails, however, there's hope for a cure. Since
most coulrophobes don't see clowns on a regular basis, the need is
rare, said Jerilyn Ross, president of the Anxiety Disorders
Association of America, a Rockville, Md., organization. But Ross
warned that if, say, a clown moves in next door, a coulrophobe
might seek professional help. Treatment consists of ``challenging
negative perceptions and teaching relaxation techniques such as
different ways to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, she said, it may be necessary to put the client in a
situation with a clown. O'Dell, of the International Clown Hall of
Fame, runs a program designed expressly for that purpose. The
program, ``Put on a Happy Face,'' allows clowns and the children
and adults who fear them to meet in ``a safe space.''
</P>
<P>
   But is all the fuss over clowning around really necessary? To
Janice Kupiec, a 24-year-old legislative researcher in Arlington,
Va., who fears clowns, the answer is yes. ``Of course people think,
`Why be afraid of clowns when they are so many other things to be
afraid of that are real?' It's not something I sit around and think
about every day. But when I see a clown, I get scared.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL; 
