<HEADER>
A2688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MARTA-DEATH11-COX     04-10 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTA-DEATH11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By David Pendered
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MARTA has halted all routine maintenance on and around
its tracks for a week while investigators determine the cause of a
crash Monday that resulted in the second death this year of someone
working near a MARTA rail line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to refocus on safety and go over processes and
procedures and make certain we understand that safety begins with
us,'' said MARTA spokeswoman Dee Baker.
</P>
<P>
   A father and son were involved in Monday's deadly event at the
Lenox station in Buckhead. The father was killed and the son, who
sustained a life-threatening head injury, is being treated at Grady
Memorial Hospital, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous deadly event still under review, one MARTA
worker was killed Feb. 25 and another critically injured when a
train struck them alongside tracks near the Avondale station. The
worker who survived remains hospitalized at DeKalb Medical Center,
a hospital official said.
</P>
<P>
   George Ivey, a 17-year member of the MARTA board, said MARTA
must create ways for employees to better protect themselves when
they maintain the rail system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be something for people in the danger spot so
they will be safe,'' Ivey said. ``Whether the accident happens
because of human deficiency or some other deficiency, it has to be
corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's accident is being investigated by MARTA police and the
National Transportation Safety Board. Investigators said it is too
early to guess at the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Two MARTA workers were placed on paid administrative leave, a
typical move in serious collisions. The train operator and a worker
who controls which tracks trains use are on leave pending the
outcome of the investigation, MARTA officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The tracks that trains use are determined by transit workers in
an Avondale rail center. In a system somewhat like airplane traffic
control, MARTA employees use computer-generated images and electric
switches to route trains around work areas and cut off the rails'
high-voltage electricity, which powers train motors.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are determining whether human error or mechanical
breakdown resulted in train No. 166 not being diverted around a job
site in the Lenox station.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's event, the two workers were aloft in a cherry picker
parked on the northwest corner of the rider platform. They were
repairing ceiling tiles when their vehicle was hit by a train at
about 2:25 a.m., according to MARTA's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus Spencer, 57, of Decatur, was pronounced dead at the
scene by an investigator with the Fulton County medical examiner.
Spencer's son, Columbus Spencer Jr., 30, also of Decatur, was
listed in critical condition at Grady Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The deceased's wife and daughter declined comment, speaking
through a Grady spokeswoman. A few neighbors contacted in the
Decatur apartment complex shared by the father and son said they
did not know the men.
</P>
<P>
   Trains usually do not run in the wee hours of a Sunday morning.
MARTA ran the train to serve a capacity crowd of fans attending the
Cash Money/Ruff Ryders rap concert at Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Train No. 166 went from the Lindbergh station to the Doraville
station before 2 a.m.. Just north of the Lenox station, it shifted
to the southbound tracks to avoid a section of closed track.
</P>
<P>
   The northbound segment of the Doraville line has been closed
periodically over the past month while MARTA tests a new propulsion
system for its aging fleet of trains. Replacement parts are so
difficult to get that some train cars have no propulsion system.
They are placed between cars with functioning motors.
</P>
<P>
   Train No. 166 proceeded north from Lenox along the southbound
line and dropped riders at Doraville. The operator headed back
south, on the southbound line, on an express run to pick up about
35 riders at Lindbergh and take them to the Dunwoody station.
</P>
<P>
   As the train entered the Lenox station, the operator realized
the train had not been diverted to the northbound lane to avoid
workers hovering over the southbound lane. The operator looked
ahead and saw the cherry picker, where the Spencer's were working,
MARTA officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The train was traveling at about 30 mph when it crashed into the
cherry picker, the operator reported to MARTA investigators. It
would have been going faster if electricity had not been shut off
just north of the rider platform.
</P>
<P>
   When the train hit the cherry picker, the impact was so terrific
that both workers were ejected from the bucket. The vehicle's boom
was thrown onto a billboard buried in concrete on the rider
platform, bending it at a 45-degree angle. A safety helmet worn by
one of the men landed on the top of the train after the collision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally feel really bad for the family,'' said Dwight
Ferrell, who joined MARTA in October as senior vice president of
operations. ``We are going to do everything we can to make certain
nothing like this ever happens again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
