u e BC-FLOYD-OPERA-HNS &LR;      04-10 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-OPERA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COMIC OPERA BY LEADING COMPOSER WILL OPEN IN HOUSTON 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CHARLES WARD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A runaway hit novel capturing a turn-of-the-century
Southern town, flaws and all.
</P>
<P>
   An admired film director, raised on a sheep station in the
Australian Outback, who touched universal emotions with his
``Driving Miss Daisy.''
</P>
<P>
   A Methodist minister's son, shaped by the rites of the rural
South, who at age 73 has composed his first comic opera.
</P>
<P>
   A storekeeper of crusty independence in Cold Sassy Tree, Ga.,
who enters a marriage of convenience with a much younger woman _ a
Yankee, no less _ who is deemed a gold-digger by his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Fact and fiction are swirling into focus in Carlisle Floyd's
``Cold Sassy Tree,'' whose Friday opening will be the Houston Grand
Opera's world 25th premiere.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Olive Ann Burns' 1984 novel, ``Cold Sassy Tree'' will
be a marked departure from some of HGO's introductions _ including,
say, the brusque modernism of Sir Michael Tippett's ``New Year''
(world premiere, 1989) or Phillip Glass' elliptical and confusing
``Akhnaten'' (American premiere, 1984).
</P>
<P>
   ``What attracted me to the novel as a possible opera libretto
was several things,'' Floyd said. ``Rich, colorful, vividly drawn
characters, a basic dramatic situation which would impel subsequent
action and events, and a very broad emotional scale, ranging from
broad comedy to intense drama and even tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the comedy that is the major departure for the prolific
Floyd, the leading American opera composer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing comic opera is one devil of a job,'' he said, a matter
of intellect, timing, pacing, calculated effect. The project has
prompted the opera world to note a parallel with ``Falstaff,''
Verdi's last opera and his one great comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Among his other works, Houston Grand Opera has staged Floyd's
two most successful operas: his treatment of John Steinbeck's ``Of
Mice and Men'' and his best-known work, ``Susannah,'' a retelling
of the Biblical story of Susannah and the Elders that Floyd, always
his own librettist, set in Appalachia.
</P>
<P>
   About 1981, Floyd's sister gave him ``Cold Sassy Tree'' to read
just for entertainment. Hints of operatic possibilities began to
click, and Floyd passed the novel onto HGO general director David
Gockley, who also liked it. The book had been so popular it led to
a 1989 TV movie starring Faye Dunaway and Richard Widmark.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd's literary skills _ he began studying creative writing at
17 at Converse College in Spartanburg, S.C. _ were challenged by
``Cold Sassy Tree.''
</P>
<P>
   While plentifully populated, the opera centers on a few
characters: storekeeper Rucker Lattimore, his daughters Mary Willis
and Loma, his 14-year-old grandson, Will Tweedy, and the emigre
milliner Love Simpson, who is half Lattimore's age.
</P>
<P>
   Lattimore scandalizes the mythical town of Cold Sassy Tree by
announcing, three weeks after his wife is buried, that he plans to
marry Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   The move is purely pragmatic. He needs help keeping his house
and, thus, maintaining his independence as he ages. Simpson, he
says, is an experienced housekeeper; marrying her will be cheaper
than hiring someone else to do the same chores. In return, Simpson
will receive title to the house and its contents when Lattimore
dies.
</P>
<P>
   The daughters and the community are horrified. They isolate
Simpson, but their mistreatment only leads to an evolution in the
relationship between Simpson and Lattimore. The pair fall in love
and consummate the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Will Tweedy's teen-age life forms a secondary plot. Like his
grandfather, he has nonconformist tendencies. He befriends the
daughter of poor mill-workers in a nearby town and dreams of
becoming a writer _ instead of a businessman who will take over his
grandfather's general store.
</P>
<P>
   A tragedy forces the townspeople to soften their intolerance:
Lattimore is wounded in a robbery at the store. He tells Will to
follow his own heart, but doesn't give Simpson enough time to
reveal the most important news of their short marriage life: She is
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   As the lead singers describe Lattimore and Simpson, they seem
almost destined for each other.
</P>
<P>
   The shopkeeper is a straightforward, no-nonsense kind of man
with ``the best of progressive male thinking at the time,''
according to bass-baritone Dean Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Soprano Patricia Racette finds Simpson ``a very stylish lady in
a small town that's not very stylish.'' She's self-sufficient, an
outsider who has suffered hardships that she has kept to herself.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes talking with film director Bruce Beresford,
one suspects that had Floyd, as the saying goes, set the Yellow
Pages to music, the Australian would have eagerly accepted the job.
</P>
<P>
   After Beresford's 1980 Academy Award nomination for best adapted
screenplay for ``Breaker Morant,'' his directorial projects began
to attract some of the top stars of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't Beresford's star-laden resume that attracted
Gockley and Floyd. Rather, it was his ability, proved emphatically
in ``Driving Miss Daisy'' (which won an Oscar for best picture of
1989), to depict realistic American small-town life without
``Disneyfication.''
</P>
<P>
   Beresford was raised on a sheep station about 300 miles west of
Sydney, Australia _ and 15,000 miles from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in that country environment, he absorbed a cultural legacy
not dissimilar to that of parts of America: a comparatively
well-off populace living in a democratic country founded by
immigrants. He also experienced the gossip and scandals of
small-town life.
</P>
<P>
   Beresford first explored the milieu in 1983 with the film
``Tender Mercies,'' with a screenplay by Oscar-winning Texas writer
Horton Foote.
</P>
<P>
   Beresford became hooked on opera after he moved to London in
1962 to pursue a career in film. He has staged five operas since
the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing Floyd's aria ``Ain't It a Pretty Night'' from
``Susannah'' about 10 years ago won Beresford over long before
Floyd approached him in New Orleans, while he was filming the
recent ``Double Jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I nearly fell over,'' the director said. ``My God, next to
Benjamin Britten, he's my favorite 20th-century opera composer.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after ``Cold Sassy Tree'' opens, Beresford will head for
Vienna to film, in period style, an original script about Alma
Mahler. The siren-like Austrian was wife or lover to many seminal
figures in early 20th-century Viennese culture, including composer
Gustav Mahler.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Floyd may heave a deserved sigh of relief. ``I now
understand why there are so few successful comedies in opera.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
