u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-SIMON11-COX     04-10 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-SIMON11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plague of injuries over, FSU's Simon says
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corey Simon knows something about indecision.
</P>
<P>
   Simon was a Parade All-America defensive lineman from Pompano
Beach, Fla., when he signed with Georgia in 1995. But he never
arrived in Athens. Simon asked to be released from his letter of
intent, and after the NCAA started investigating his recruitment,
Georgia decided to let him go.
</P>
<P>
   Simon transferred to Florida State and sat out his freshman
season because of NCAA rules. After a frustrating series of
injuries reduced his production his first two seasons, Simon
finally came into his own as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   Still, NFL teams are wondering whether Simon's health is too
much of a risk to choose him among the top 10 picks of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had surgeries early in my career,'' Simon said. ``Everything
is fine, but they definitely are asking about it. When you invest
that much time and money into a person, you want to make sure what
you are getting is not damaged goods. I understand the process and
have no qualms with it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon didn't help himself a few weeks ago when he refused to
lift weights for scouts. Simon said he had a chest contusion at the
time, but the incident caused some teams to further scrutinize his
past injuries.
</P>
<P>
   When Simon finally lifted, he bench-pressed 225 only 20 times,
not a great number for a defensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to buy a brand new Mercedes without test-driving
it first?'' Simon said. ``I've shown everybody my shoulders are
fine. There's nothing else I can do to prove I'm fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon, 6 feet 2 and 297 pounds, proved he's fine during the past
two seasons. He was an All-American after a junior season in which
he had 65 tackles, including 16 for losses, second-best in FSU
history.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Simon helped the Seminoles to their second national
title. In a 46-29 victory over Virginia Tech in the Sugar Bowl, he
had five tackles, including a sack, broke up a pass and recovered a
fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Simon says he is versatile enough to play nose guard in a 3-4
defensive alignment or tackle in a 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more of a quick kind of guy,'' he said. ``When I have to
get down and dirty and mix it up a little bit, play hard-nosed
football, I can do that as well. I think I have a well-rounded
game.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, FSU coach Bobby Bowden was wondering whether Simon
would play at all. Simon had rotator-cuff surgery after high
school, then more shoulder surgery only four games into his
redshirt-freshman season. As a sophomore, he sat out two games with
a pinched nerve in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed he was unlucky,'' Bowden said. ``I didn't know
if he could get through a season without getting injured.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Eagles, who might take Simon with the sixth
pick, and other NFL teams are wondering the same thing. But Simon
said they can be assured they're getting one thing _ a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have that winning attitude,'' he said. ``We don't know what
it feels like to lose and that's how we took it out on the field. I
love the feeling of victory. That's how I play the game. I don't
play to lose. I don't play for second place.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
