u f BC-STATES-BIGDIG-NAT     04-10 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BIGDIG-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  FEDERAL BIG DIG REPORT CITES MISMANAGEMENT
</P>
<P>
   By Alex Canizares
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - A federal audit of the Big Dig that shows how
mismanagement has led costs to spiral beyond the project's $12.2
billion cost estimate will be released Tuesday, congressional
offices said.
</P>
<P>
   US Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater will brief
Massachusetts legislators and Gov. Paul Cellucci in the office of
Rep. Joe Moakley, D-South Boston, Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Slater has recently reviewed the much-anticipated report, the
result of a 14-member task force's complete evaluation of the
Central Artery/Ted Williams Tunnel project's finances, accounting
practices, and management and oversight processes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the report's contents have been kept under tight wraps,
</P>
<P>
   congressional aides said they expected the document t show that
the project's true costs could drastically exceed the $12.2 billion
price tag maintained by the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   A Department of Transportation source who asked to remain
anonymous said the report is likely to put the Big Dig's total
price tag as high as $14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Boston newspapers reported last week that the auditors may
arrive at a $13.6 billion cost estimate, a whopping $2.8 billion
over the $10.8 billion the Big Dig maintained as accurate just six
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to be shocked,'' the source said of the
state's congressional delegation. ``This is beyond anyone's wildest
dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the discrepancy is expected to lie in the project's
controversial insurance trust fund, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating a good safety record, the Big Dig hopes to retrieve
$826 million from the fund in 2017, and also remove $150 million
for construction costs. The department of transportation's
inspector general has long attacked the use of funds from the
insurance program - meant to be used in case of injuries at the
site -- to help fund construction.
</P>
<P>
   The report could also call for changes in management in the
Massachusetts Turnpike Authority. Cellucci is already under
pressure by state lawmakers to fire the project's embattled chief,
James Kerasiotes.
</P>
<P>
   The report ``basically points to a mismanagement of the project
in terms of letting it get out of control or not realizing how the
costs have gotten out of control,'' a congressional aide close to
the task force said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The close relationship between the government-employed Big Dig
managers and private contractors hired to keep the managers
accountable is a longstanding problem, the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   A federal highway spokeswoman declined to comment on the
report's findings last night.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is unclear how binding the report's recommendations
will be, aides said Cellucci will face strong pressure to follow
its suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's gut feeling is that this won't be the last
overrun,'' the congressional aide said. ``The key is that as it
gets more expensive, it is up to Massachusetts to come up with a
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington has kept close watch over the Big Dig - 70 percent of
which is paid with federal dollars - since the project announced a
surprise $1.4 billion shortfall in February.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from lawmakers angered by the Big Dig's surprise
cost increases in February, Slater announced an ``action plan'' to
sort out the Big Dig's finances.
</P>
<P>
   He commissioned the task force to open the Big Dig's finance
books, and threatened to freeze all future federal funding until a
finance plan that protects the rest of the state's road and bridge
projects was approved.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
