<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, April 11. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ELECT (Lima, Peru) _ President Alberto Fujimori appears to
be on his way to squeaking out an improbable first-round reelection
victory based on the first official vote tallies, stirring cries of
fraud from independent election monitors and a sharp statement from
the U.S. State Department calling for a second round runoff to
avert a crisis. By Clifford Krauss. (We plan to move the story by 9
p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   With 3-column photo.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   RAMPAGE-KILLERS-III (Salt Lake City) _ Of the 100 episodes of
rampage killings examined for this series by The New York Times,
none better illustrates than the case of Lisa Duy just how
difficult it can be to enforce a key provision of the nation's
fundamental gun control law. That provision prohibits people who
have been involuntarily committed to mental institutions from
buying a handgun. But laws in most states guard the privacy of the
mentally ill, so gun background checks typically fail to turn up
mental health histories. By Fox Butterfield. (The report has moved
in ``a'' news file; an ABRIDGED version will also move.)
</P>
<P>
   Third in a series of four. 4,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BUSH-HEALTH (Undated) _ Texas has had one of the nation's
worst public health records for decades. More than a quarter of its
citizens have no health insurance. The state ranks near the top in
the nation in rates of AIDS, diabetes, tuberculosis and teen-age
pregnancy, and near the bottom in immunizations, mammograms and
access to physicians. But since George W. Bush became governor in
1995, he has not made health a priority, his aides acknowledge. He
has never made a speech on the subject, his press office says. But
with health care near the top of the election agenda, Bush _
starting on Tuesday with a speech in Cleveland _ will begin
discussing insurance and other health issues. By Adam Clymer. (The
story has moved in ``p'' news file.) 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-LOBBY (Washington) _ How Microsoft is lobbying to
improve its image in the wake of a judge's ruling that it has
violated antitrust laws. By Joel Brinkley. (Scheduled to move by 10
p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-PLANE-CRASH (Washington) _ The V-22 Osprey is a classic
case of a military program that wouldn't be stopped. The crash of
an Osprey on Saturday night in Arizona, which killed 19 Marines,
came after years of arguments inside the Pentagon against building
it, and years of dogged efforts by Congress to protect the $37
billion program. By Tim Weiner. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``w'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   2-column graphic reefer box to PULITZER-PRIZES; story inside.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOBBY (Albany, N.Y.) _ In flush times, the Legislature has
become a leaner place, and partisan politics is only partly to
blame. Stung by embarrassing revelations that Philip Morris treated
scores of lawmakers last year, and then underreported the expense,
the Republican-controlled Senate adopted a voluntary ban on free
meals with lobbyists and gifts over $25. The Democratic-led
assembly refused to go along, although 10 of its members have
individually pledged to abide by the ban. Now the shrinking
waistlines are just one indication that a deeply entrenched
lobbying culture has begun to change. By Winnie Hu. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT22.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Cuban Americans in Miami seem resigned
to the fact that they have lost the battle to keep Elian Gonzalez
in the United States, as Justice Department officials readied to
present the child's Miami relatives with a letter instructing them
on when and how he would be handed over to federal officials. By
Rick Bragg. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With sidebar, CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Investors continue to sell shares of
technology companies, sending the Nasdaq composite index plunging
258.25 points, or 5.8 percent, to 4,188.20. It was the second-worst
point decline for the index, behind last Monday's 349.15 point
drop. By Kenneth N. Gilpin. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in
``f'' news file.) 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-TALKS (Seoul, South Korea) _ An unusual catalog of
emotions _ shock, relief, wariness _ are on display as South
Koreans learn that their country's president would go to North
Korea in June for the first-ever summit meeting with his communist
counterpart By Howard W. French. (The 1stLd-Writethru has moved in
``i'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTEROIDS (Undated) _ Taking cautious baby steps, a robotic
spacecraft is to settle Tuesday into a closer orbit of an asteroid
it has been circling for almost two months. Guided by gentle shoves
from small thruster rockets, the craft, NEAR Shoemaker, is taking
up a circular orbit 62 miles from the center of the asteroid Eros
for more detailed studies. By Warren E. Leary. (The story has moved
in ``a'' news file.) 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FRUIT-FLY (Undated) _ The Drosophila fruit fly, whose genome
was just decoded, has attained vast prominence in human affairs
because it is one of the principal model organisms studied by
biologists as a means of understanding the general design of life.
Because of the unity of evolution, the fly's genes and those of
people overlap considerably. Their advocates, who call themselves
fly people, are easily provoked into confessing that they think of
people as large flies that lack wings. By Nichols Wade. (The story
has moved in ``a'' news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
