<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2705 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOREA-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      04-10 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC WOES MAY HAVE SPURRED KOREAN SUMMIT PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A collapsing North Korean economy, the growing strength of its
political leader, and fear in South Korea of the consequences of
German-style reunification led the historic announcement Monday of
a summit conference between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   That is the consensus view of present and former US and South
Korean officials and scholars, including Seoul's ambassador to the
United States, Lee Hong Koo, and former assistant Secretary of
Defense Joseph S. Nye Jr., both of whom have been deeply involved
in the politics of the divided peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea accepted the South's longstanding offer of
engagement ``out of sheer necessity,'' Lee said in a telephone
interview from Atlanta, where he was participating in a joint
US-South Korean effort to promote trade and investment between the
countries.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of hostility, the North ``sees there is no real
alternative,'' Lee said. ``Isolation doesn't pay, and the economy
has reached bottom. The only way to survive is to take a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Nye, dean of the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard, said
the North's move came from economic weakness, while the South's
increasingly aggressive attempts at engagement in recent years came
from careful study of the social and economic impact of German
reunification.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, with the North Korean economy in a tailspin,
``South Korean opinion was split,'' Nye said. ``There was
resistance to aid or accommodation because, some felt, the apple
would just fall off the tree. The North would collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, ``South Koreans have thought through what it
would mean to take over a collapsing North Korea,'' he said. ``They
recognize the considerable disorder that could create, that it
could bring the South Korean economy down again just when it is
recovering from the Asian financial crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, both men said, a strong majority of South Koreans, and the
major world powers, agree that the abrupt absorption of the North's
economy and collapse of its social structure would be undesireable.
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Kleiner, a former German ambassador to South Korea who
now is professor of international relations at Boston University,
said that while disastrous economic conditions are clearly a factor
pushing the North, so too is the strength North Korean dictator Kim
Jong Il has gained by weathering the crises of the six years since
the death of his father and predecessor, Kim Il Sung.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kim Jong Il feels he is secure,'' Kleiner said. ``He
survived a critical situation after his father's death, then a
horrible economic situation. Now he has gotten some help from
outside, the economy is a little better, and he feels he can afford
a big step.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all agree, however, that Kim is more secure.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Natsios, a former top official of the Agency for
International Development who now is Massachusetts secretary of
administration and finance, also believes the economic stress is a
key reason for the North Korean moves, but because it has made Kim
insecure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The population is traumatized, distressed, suffering. There is
evidence of rage,'' said Natsios, who recently completed work on a
book about the North Korean famine of the mid-1990s. Natsios
interviewed numerous refugees from North Korea in China in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was huge opposition to Kim Jong Il,'' he said. ``People
said things you never would have heard earlir. I think if a second
famine occurs there will be a political and military reaction. Kim
Jong Il is nervous. He is trying to hedge his bets.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued in Washington, President Clinton praised
the two Koreas for agreeing to hold the summit, which is scheduled
for June 12-14 in Pyongyang, the North Korean capital. China, Japan
and Russia promised support for the talks, which raise hopes of
easing of tensions along the world's most militarized border.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers said the timing of the announcement _ an apparent
gift to South Korean President Kim Dae Jung's party before
Thursday's parliamentary elections _ was reason for optimism that
relations between the Koreas will stay sweet in the immediate
future. ``But if people interpret this meeting as weakness,'' Nye
warned, ``the North Koreans will compensate with nasty rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
