<P>
   LEDE STORY:
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Investors continued to sell shares of
technology companies Monday, sending the Nasdaq composite index
plunging 258.25 points, or 5.8 percent, to 4,188.20. It was the
second-worst point decline for the index, behind last Monday's
349.15 point drop. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8:15 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISPLAY:
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINES-ADS (Undated) _ The magazines that are doing well have
never had it so good. Magazines like In Style, Vogue, Vanity Fair
and W are so packed with advertisements that they blowing past
their records for size, heft and length. They are part of a growing
breed: the obese magazine, publications so fat that if they were
people, they ought to be in a high school auditorium sweating to
the oldies with Richard Simmons. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos and two graphics.)
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT SIDE:
</P>
<P>
   STANLEY-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The Stanley Works may tell
investors about the need to be patient, but the company's chief
executive appears to have failed to heed the same advice. Three
years after John M. Trani, a rising star at General Electric, took
over as chief executive of Stanley Works, investors are still
looking for some of the GE management magic. For his efforts,
though, Trani pulled a sizable pay increase out of his company last
year. Trani, who had an impressive performance at GE's medical
systems division, was greeted with much enthusiasm when he took
over Stanley at the end of 1996. But the much-anticipated revival
has yet to take place. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM CENTER:
</P>
<P>
   IRIDIUM (Chicago) _ In the coming months, Iridium LLC, the
bankrupt global satellite telephone company, will begin sending 88
giant satellites spiraling toward Earth, where they will burn up in
a fitting and fiery end to one of the colossal corporate failures
in recent memory. After spending more than $5 billion on a system
that promised to communicate ``with anyone, anytime, virtually
anywhere in the world,'' Iridium could muster only about 55,000
subscribers, not enough even to pay interest on its start-up costs.
By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are tonight's columns:
</P>
<P>
   HIGHTECH-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ As 3Com makes plans to become a
much smaller networking solutions company, shedding several
slower-growing operations, executives have decided to change
agencies. The San Francisco office of FCB Worldwide, which has
handled the 3Com account since the company consolidated agencies in
October 1997, is losing the assignment, effective on July 1, to the
New York office of Lowe Lintas &AMP; Partners. FCB San Francisco will
continue as the agency for the Palm computing unit, which is being
spun out of 3Com. The 3Com shift is indicative of the ferment among
high-technology marketers as competition intensifies in that
fast-moving, free-spending category. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's financial stories.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
