<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN'S MIAMI RELATIVES UNABLE TO DERAIL TRANSFER, LIKELY TO GET
NOTICE FROM GOVERNMENT TUESDAY
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A flurry of court action and a much-delayed meeting
Monday seemed to do little to derail the upcoming hand-over of
6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials are expected to send the boy's Miami relatives
a letter Tuesday outlining when and where the boy is to be turned
over for a reunion with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have indicated they want the transfer to happen this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the day, NBC News reported that Elian's father is
willing to go to South Florida to pick up his son at a neutral
location. The reunion would take place on Wednesday or Thursday,
possibly at Homestead Air Force Base south of Miami, the report
stated.
</P>
<P>
   NBC said the information came from an unnamed American source
directly involved in the negotiations, who met with Juan Miguel
Gonzalez for several hours over the weekend. But federal
immigration officials said Monday that they knew nothing of the
possible trip.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gonzalez spent the day at the home of a top Cuban
diplomat in Bethesda, Md., where he and his wife and baby son have
been living since they arrived in the United States last week.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, the Florida relatives who have cared for Elian since
his shipwreck in late November failed to show up for a scheduled
meeting with three mental health experts sent by federal officials
to discuss the transfer of the boy. Late in the day, after a rush
of telephone calls, the experts went to a Miami hospital where
Elian's cousin, Marisleysis Gonzalez, has been staying for several
days since she collapsed from nervous exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   The experts met for about one hour with Lazaro Gonzales, Elian's
great-uncle, and his attorneys. Elian reportedly was not in the
room, but was nearby with Marisleysis, who the Miami family says
has become a surrogate mother for the boy since his real mother
drowned on the boat with 10 others crossing from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would comment after the meeting ended. The family
has repeatedly demanded that child psychologists meet with the boy
to determine whether the transfer should take place, but U.S.
Attorney General Janet Reno has insisted the only role of the
experts is to make the boy's transition as smooth as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami family also went to two courts Monday in an effort to
forestall handing over Elian. One set of arguments was filed at the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta, which is scheduled
to hear an appeal of the family's lawsuit in the case on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   The family is appealing a March decision by a Miami federal
judge that upheld the order by the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service that Elian should be returned to his father.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the family also turned to a Florida family court,
where they had attempted to win custody of Elian in January.
</P>
<P>
   But that effort seemed likely to end in failure, as Miami-Dade
County Family Court Judge Jennifer Bailey expressed serious doubts
about the merits of their case. Bailey told the family she doubted
seriously whether her court had any jurisdiction in the case, but
instructed them to file a brief on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A previous family court judge _ who was removed from the case
for possible conflicts of interest _ ruled in January that the
family could pursue a custody claim. But federal officials brushed
aside the ruling, saying the matter is an immigration issue, not a
custody dispute, and that immigration matters are solely a federal
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   While the family appeared to be quickly running out of options,
two top local officials said they would travel to Washington
Tuesday to meet with Reno in a bid to slow down the transfer of the
boy.
</P>
<P>
   Reno reportedly will meet with Miami Mayor Joe Carollo and
Miami-Dade County Mayor Alex Penelas, who drew heavy criticism two
weeks ago when he said federal officials were provoking Miami's
Cuban exiles with their handling of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo said he would ask Reno for a 30-day transition period
for the boy at a neutral location near the Miami home of Elian's
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno has said firmly that she expects Elian to be
transferred to his father this week, and she seemed unlikely to
change her mind.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the home of Elian's relatives in Miami Little Havana
neighborhood, a small band of protestors continued to mill about in
the street, occasionally chanting and singing in support of the
boy. A prayer vigil a few blocks away from the home was expected to
draw large crowds Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Protestors have vowed to form a human chain around the house to
stop the boy's transfer, and some have predicted that violence will
break out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll sit in or do whatever it takes,'' said Michel Reyes, 24,
who said he has been at the house for days with only short breaks.
``We won't attack anybody, but the government doesn't have the same
track record,'' he said, referring to the Branch-Davidian fire near
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
