<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-DECIMAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING NASDAQ STRESS, SEC REVERSES DECIMAL QUOTE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A statue of George Washington guards Federal Hall in
lower Manhattan, a bustling location for his 1789 inauguration.
Today, Washington's gaze is aimed down the narrow, crooked passage
called Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   That's how The Street likes its politicians: They are welcome to
watch, but no tinkering, please, in the workings of the investment
world. That sentiment is strongest in times of market uncertainty,
such as now.
</P>
<P>
   As the Nasdaq Composite index was tumbling 6 percent Monday _
its third wild day in a week _ Wall Street scored a victory against
politicians. The Securities and Exchange Commission reversed its
order to begin a conversion, on July 3, to pricing all stocks in
decimals, rather than the traditional fractions _ $50.1875 a share,
not 50 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Trading in dollars and cents was being pushed by a Congress
seeking to simplify trading for average investors moving into the
stock market in droves. It would also save up to $1 billion a year
by improving the prices investors pay for stocks they buy, Congress
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the SEC, in a letter to Congress, said now is not the time
and cited Nasdaq's ``lack of readiness.'' The agency did not
propose an alternative date for the conversion by the brokerage
industry and by US stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC was apparently capitulating to Nasdaq officials who have
maintained that it would be impossible to meet the summer deadline.
More quietly, officials of the computerized exchange have made
clear they are already struggling to handle an explosion in trading
volume, wildly swinging stock prices and strains that are pushing
its systems to their limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a time of unprecedented volume and volatility,'' the SEC's
chairman, Arthur Levitt, told Congress, ``I believe it would be
ill-advised to force a major structural change in our markets
without the confidence that order will be maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   On ten days this year, Nasdaq's share volume has exceeded the 2
billion mark, a record first achieved on Feb. 17. Volume continues
to rise: Nasdaq volume hit nearly 2.9 billion last Tuesday as the
market plummeted 500-plus points before its remarkable bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   Trading bottlenecks have caused several system glitches at the
Nasdaq in recent months, ranging from trivial to interruptions in
trading for several costly minutes. And trading would accelerate
more, experts said, in a conversion to decimals. As trading
increments become smaller in a conversion from 1/16ths _ the
equivalent of 6.25 cents _ to 5 cents or 1 cent, it would increase
the number of price points at which investors could bid on stocks,
adding to buying and selling activity.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Goldstein, a professor at the University of Colorado,
said the SEC, in seeking a delay, is protecting Nasdaq from
anything that might threaten its stability. Last Tuesday, for
example, Nasdaq's so-called message volume _ requests to change
standing orders to buy or sell stocks _ was severely backed up as
the market was tanking, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their computer systems are very close to the edge. The NYSE
can handle five to 10 times its (current) volume, but if Nasdaq
doubled its volume it would be in a lot of trouble. It might even
shut down,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while NYSE officials said publicly that their systems
are ``ready'' for conversion at any time, Nasdaq officials have
been seeking to delay decimals until next year. Nasdaq's chairman,
Frank Zarb, said recently that he supports trading in decimals.
But, ``We will not put investors and the market at risk by forging
ahead too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq declined to comment on the SEC's letter.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt discussed a compromise, in the absence of a full
conversion to decimals. He said his agency would consider a limited
test this fall on select stocks traded on the NYSE, the American
Stock Exchange and some regional exchanges _ but not on
Nasdaq-listed stocks. He also expressed concern that this move,
too, may ``pose risks to systemic stability'' and ``harm the
investors we seek to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Mere suggestions that some stocks would be traded in decimals,
some in fractions, caused angst for brokerage industry firms on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   A ``bifurcated'' system,'' said Margaret Draper, spokeswoman for
the Securities Industry Association, a lobbying group for Wall
Street and regional brokerage firms, would ``create confusion and
be at cross purposes to the whole goal of decimalization, which is
to make it more investor friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   SIA, whose members make markets in Nasdaq-listed stocks, have
said publicly they would convert to decimals. But critics have
accused the industry of digging in its heels because the move to
decimals would shrink spreads between bid and ask prices, eating
into market makers' profits. Spreads are used by market makers at
brokerages to make profits while they are buying and selling
Nasdaq-listed stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Houtkin, a career market maker who now runs a day-trading
firm in Montvale, N.J., All-Tech Direct Inc., said the industry had
used Nasdaq's acute capacity problems to push its agenda of delay.
SIA estimated it would cost the industry an estimated $900 million
to convert their computer systems and prepare for decimals.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street firms ``are scared to death about what's going to
happen with decimals,'' Houtkin said in an interview last month.
``Market makers don't want decimals _ we're talking about spreads
going down to a penny.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Abbey, a PaineWebber executive who chairs the decimal
committee for the SIA, said members just want a smooth conversion.
SIA recommended first converting to nickel increments _ $1.05,
$1.10 etc. _ because it would be ``least disruptive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there will be many more trades, smaller trades. We
know there will be many more quotes sent out because prices will
need to move a little less before you need to quote again _ a penny
or two rather than 6 cents,'' Abbey said. ``Computers and networks
all need to be both changed and significantly enhanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the delay, staff for representatives pushing
conversion to decimals _ Ed Markey, a Massachusetts Democrat, and
Michael Oxley, a Ohio Repulican _ said they were disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are losing money every day on this,'' said Oxley's
spokeswoman, Peggy Peterson. ``Technology and competition are
making (stock) trading cheaper and investors ought to get the
benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   But PaineWebber's Abbey wonders about the proposed benefits for
investors. If the number of potential prices at which stocks can be
bought and sold is increased, he argued investors would be
overwhelmed with the lightning-fast updates of trading data on
their computer screen. Even now, he said, ``The screen is
constantly flashing at you _ imagine it flashing at two or three
times the rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the world's stock exchanges already trade in decimals,
and proponents argue that it would standardize trading at a time
securities markets are globalizing.
</P>
<P>
   But, Nasdaq is the dominant concern of the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   A shortage of liquidity _ the ability to find a buyer for a
stock when investors are selling _ was thrown into the spotlight a
week ago, when the stock markets plunged because there were not
enough buyers to snap up stocks being sold. Stocks remarkably
rebounded by day's end, but the depth of the decline sent tremors
of anxiety through The Street.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, who analyzed NYSE's 1997 move from trading stocks in
eighths to sixteenths, said mutual fund managers would have more
difficulty buying large blocks of stock if decimals are used.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said decimals, per se, aren't the issue. Smaller
trading increments are the issue, because this would provide more
places for more investors to cut in _ with a slightly higher bid _
to buy stocks. This, in turn, would reduce the number of investors
willing to place ``limit orders,'' orders in which an investor
stands ready to buy at specific prices. ``Limit orders provide
liquidity,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Individual investors buying a few shares may get a better price
in a decimal system, Goldstein said. But, mutual funds _ indeed,
all investors _ would suffer if liquidity is reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this should be done,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
