u f BC-REZULIN-SUIT-BOS &LR;      04-10 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REZULIN-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS FILE REZULIN CLASS-ACTION SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Smithe is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A law firm Monday said it filed a class-action lawsuit
against Warner-Lambert Co. over a diabetes prescription drug,
Rezulin, that has been linked to 63 deaths from liver failure.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court in Newark, N.J., by the
law firm Gilman and Pastor LLP, follows a March 21 decision by the
company to withdraw the orally-taken drug from the market at the
request of the US Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Although a spate of individual cases have been launched over
Rezulin, Gilman and Pastor claim they are the first to file a
class-action suit.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert, responding to the suit, acknowledged that some
patients experienced adverse reactions while taking Rezulin. But
the company said it had adequately warned patients about potential
side effects.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Morris Plains, N.J., estimated that
500,000 people took Rezulin last year. The diabetes drug generated
revenues of $625 million for Warner-Lambert in 1999, down 16
percent from $748 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also named the company's pharmaceutical division,
Parke-Davis Pharmaceuticals, Ltd., which aggressively promoted,
marketed and distributed Rezulin, the brand name for the compound
known as troglitazone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeking a class of users for court-supervised medical
monitoring for those who took Rezulin and should either have a
blood test or an echocardiogram to determine if they have suffered
any injuries to their liver or heart,'' said Daniel D'Angelo , an
attorney at Gilman and Pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Rezulin was approved for sale by the FDA in January 1997. It has
since undergone several product warning label modifications, after
some patients died of liver failure and others complained of side
effects to their liver. Last June, the FDA reclassified Rezulin
from a sole diabetic treatment to a drug of last resort for
patients who failed to respond to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also cites a decision by Glaxo Wellcome Inc., which had
rights to Rezulin in Europe, to suspend sales in Great Britain
because of reported deaths and liver injuries in the United States
and Japan. The drug was banned in England in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Warner-Lambert knew of liver damage and related
injuries, it ``persisted in selling the product without taking
action to protect consumers,'' according to the 19-page complaint.
The class-action suit is seeking unspecified monetary damages,
patient testing and treatment of those who are at risk of
development heart and liver disease.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement after the suit was filed, Warner-Lambert, said
some patients had adverse reactions while taking Rezulin.
``However, the company adequately warned about risks associated
with the product, and we intend to vigorously defend any
lawsuits,'' Warner-Lambert said in its statement.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action suit, filed on behalf of plaintiff Otis R.
Smithe of Northwood, N.H., claims that Warner-Lambert and
Parke-Davis misled Rezulin users over the risks of liver or heart
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband took Rezulin for a year and a half to treat his
diabetes and he developed problems with his kidneys so the doctor
switched him to Glucophage (the nation's leading oral diabetic pill
from Bristol-Myers Squibb Co.), '' said Marianna Smithe, whose
husband is 74 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert, which has been successful with Lipitor, its
cholesterol-lowering drug, will merge with Pfizer Inc. this year.
Warner-Lambert said it set aside $100 million to cover the cost of
taking Rezulin off the market. A company spokesman said those funds
were unrelated to any litigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
