<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ INDEX DECLINES 258 POINTS; DOW RISES 75 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KENNTH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors continued to sell shares of technology
companies on Monday, sending the Nasdaq composite index plunging
258.25 points, or 5.8 percent, to 4,188.20. It was the second-worst
point decline for the index, behind last Monday's 349.15 point
drop.
</P>
<P>
   The resumption of the slide was something of a surprise, if only
because by the end of last week the Nasdaq had regained much of the
loss it sustained last Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in the technology-heavy Nasdaq was led by big drops
in stocks like Oracle, Sun Microsystems, Qualcomm and JDS Uniphase.
The Nasdaq composite index has fallen 17 percent since it peaked at
5,048.62 on March 10. Even with those declines, the index is still
up 2.9 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after last week, valuations in technology stocks have to
continue to be a concern,'' said John McStay, managing partner of
John McStay Investment Counsel, a Dallas-based firm that manages
more than $5.5 billion. ``The market's statement was made with a
comma, not a period.''
</P>
<P>
   While the slide in technology stock prices is worrisome, McStay
and others said the resilience of stocks in other sectors is a
positive for the overall market.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 75.08 points, or 0.7
percent, to 11,186.56, on strength in bank, drug and consumer
stocks. Meanwhile, technology stocks helped to drag down the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which fell 11.89 points, or 0.8
percent, to 1,504.46. And a slide in technology and biotechnology
company stock prices pulled the Russell 2000 index of small
capitalization companies down 24.33 points, or 4.5 percent, to
518.66.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's recovery in technology stocks may have buoyed some
spirits, but articles in various magazines and newspapers over the
weekend about the need to raise margin requirements on stocks
probably did not sit well with speculators and day traders.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did comments from Richard McCabe, chief market analyst at
Merrill Lynch. McCabe issued a report to clients on Monday morning
saying that technology stocks have begun what he described as an
``important corrective trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors should use rebounds in technology stock prices to
reduce their exposure in stocks that have fallen 40 percent to 50
percent from their recent highs, McCabe said. At the same time, he
urged investors ``to increase commitments to the energy, basic
industry, consumer-cyclical and financial sectors of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Traders were reluctant to predict if the Nasdaq would retest the
levels reached during trading last Tuesday, when the Nasdaq
composite index fell as low as 3,649.11. But they said the index
could fall further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could the Nasdaq go back to 3,900 or so?'' asked Kenneth M.
Sheinberg, head of listed trading at SG Cowan. ``That could be done
fairly easily. The rally off the intra-day lows last week was kind
of a bear trap.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheinberg said market reaction to Motorola's earnings will go a
long way to determining how technology shares fare on Tuesday.
After the market close on Monday, the cellular phone manufacturer
reported first-quarter profits of 59 cents a share, more than
double what it earned during the period a year ago. Most Wall
Street analysts had projected an increase of 58 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everyone loves the number, it will be a relief,'' Sheinberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no relief for technology shares on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm fell 11 1/16, to 141 3/16. JDS Uniphase dropped 11 3/4,
to 110 1/8. Oracle was down 4 5/8, to 82 1/2. And Sun Microsystems
lost 7 13/16, to 91.
</P>
<P>
   But financial stocks did well.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's financials index gained 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow was led higher by J.P. Morgan, which rose 4 11/16, to
134 9/16; American Express, which gained 4 1/8, to 143 3/16; and
Citigroup, which closed at 62 1/4, up 3 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   And drug stocks did well.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer rose 1, to 39 13/16. Warner-Lambert jumped 3 3/8, to 107
5/16. And Bristol-Myers Squibb gained 1 7/8, to 61 3/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
