   ----------------------------- ------ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (moved in the ``k'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   WHY DO THEY HATE HILLARY SO MUCH?
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-HATERS-SLATE _ Judging from the outpouring of
high-pitched, even hate-filled books on the subject of Hillary
Clinton, the hideous possibility of her election to be the junior
senator from the Empire State is looming large in many prolific
minds. What, exactly are the Hillary Haters so worried about? What
sort of senator would she be that she evokes such visceral
response? By Jodie T. Allen.
</P>
<P>
   THE ORTHODOX JEW AND THE VICE PRESIDENCY
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-VICE-PRESIDENT-SLATE _ Could an Orthodox Jew serve as
president of the United States? The question isn't strictly
Talmudic anymore, since the name of an Orthodox Jew has cropped up
on Democratic vice-presidential candidate short-lists. Sen. Joseph
Lieberman _ who is clearly a long shot _ is a Democrat from
Connecticut whose presumed appeal for Al Gore lies in his
right-of-center politics, his religious commitment, and his early
condemnation of Bill Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky. By
Judith Shulevitz.
</P>
<P>
   THE COSMO GIRL'S DIRTY LITTLE SECRET ISN'T SEX
</P>
<P>
   COSMO-SECRET-SLATE _ Four years after Helen Gurley Brown was
pushed out as Cosmopolitan's editor, the superannuated ``girl'' is
in the news again. She is making the media rounds to flog her new
memoir, ``I'm Wild Again.'' But on close inspection, ``I'm Wild
Again'' is a strangely inapt title and a poor description of
Brown's life. She's not wild again (and she may never have been
very wild in the first place). This is the autobiography of a
puritan. The Cosmo girl's dirty little secret isn't sex. It's work.
By David Plotz.
</P>
<P>
   `WEB' OF INTRIGUE: CIA CYBER-SPOOKS JOIN INTERNET FRENZY
</P>
<P>
   CIA-DOT.COM-INDEPENDENT _ (Los Angeles) _ It's been a long time
since espionage was cool or sexy. The end of the Cold War stole the
spooks' main reason for existing, and the Internet robbed them of
their technological chic. But now the CIA thinks it has hit upon
the ideal way to get its groove back: it is throwing caution (and
several tens of millions of dollars) to the wind, joining the
dot.com frenzy and investing in Silicon Valley. By Andrew Gumbel.
</P>
<P>
   THE HI-TECH SHAKEOUT, RATTLE AND TOLL
</P>
<P>
   HITECH-SHAKEOUT-INDEPENDENT (London) _ Wednesday morning, while
walking the dog, I bumped into an old friend. ``I must ask you,''
she said, ``what you think about Bill Gates and the market. What is
going to happen?'' What, indeed. In all probability, what we are
seeing is the first stages of the high-tech shakeout. It's
equivalent to the end of the 19th century's railway boom. But the
railways still got built, and that changed the lives of humankind.
By Hamish McRae.
</P>
<P>
   YOSHIRO MORI: A MAN WITH A LOOSE MOUTH
</P>
<P>
   MORI-BIG-MOUTH-JAPAN-ASAHI (Tokyo) _ With a hefty body built up
playing rugby and his often serious demeanor, Yoshiro Mori, Japan's
acting prime minister, is often described as a man of few words. In
truth, Mori is one of the more eloquent speakers among Japanese
politicians. However, his past comments have frequently gotten him
into trouble. By Asahi News Service.
</P>
<P>
   SAD END TO THE KEIZO OBUCHI ERA
</P>
<P>
   SAD-OBUCHI-LEGACY-ASAHI (Tokyo) _ In recent weeks, Japanese
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was fond of saying, ``I have a lot of
things I want to do.'' Alas, as he remains comatose in a Tokyo
hospital following a massive stroke early Sunday, his dreams are
forever dashed. Now that the Obuchi cabinet has abruptly come to an
end, it remains to be seen how his party, the LDP, will respect his
political legacy. By Hiroshi Hoshi.
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY, SECRECY SURROUND OBUCHI'S STROKE
</P>
<P>
   OBUCHI-`DISAPPEARED'-INDEPENDENT (Tokyo) _ Keizo Obuchi, the
comatose Japanese prime minister, disappeared for four hours after
suffering a stroke Sunday and was out of contact with his
government as aides tried desperately to cover up his critical
condition, the Independent has learned. An extraordinary sequence
of events raises more questions about the Japanese government's
capacity to handle emergencies. By Richard Lloyd Parry.
</P>
<P>
   PROPERTY RIGHTS _ AND WRONGS _ IN A WIRED WORLD
</P>
<P>
   WHO-OWNS-IDEAS?-ECONOMIST _ In Thomas Jefferson's inspiring
vision, there are no barriers to the acquisition of knowledge.
Nobody owns it, everybody partakes of it _ and the world becomes
richer. Two centuries later, when knowledge has taken over much of
the economy, Jefferson's words seem to take on a new power. These
days, ideas are capital.
</P>
<P>
   BREAK IT UP, BOYS: `WINDOWS' OF OPPORTUNITY FOR MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   FIXING-MICROSOFT-ECONOMIST _ It may have come as a shock to the
markets, but few others can have been surprised that Microsoft was
found guilty. A bolder and more imaginative Bill Gates would now
consider restructuring his company himself, as a better and more
creative alternative to the terrifying legal lottery that he
appears to have chosen.
</P>
<P>
   WEST'S MACHIAVELLI IS NO BETTER THAN IRAQ'S SADDAM
</P>
<P>
   RETHINK-SADDAM-ECONOMIST _ If, year in, year out, the United
Nations were systematically killing Iraqi children by airstrikes,
western governments would declare it intolerable, no matter how
noble its intention. They should find their existing policy toward
Iraq just as unacceptable. In democracies, the end does not justify
the means.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE ON A KNIFE-EDGE
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-FOLLY-ECONOMIST _ Zimbabwe is in crisis. The blame lies
almost entirely with President Robert Mugabe and his ZANU-PF, the
party that has ruled the country since it gained independence from
Britain in 1980. Mugabe has always swung between emotion and
reason. Conceivably, reason may regain the upper hand and he will
allow next month's election to be free and fair. But some nudging
will almost certainly be needed. If not, disaster will surely
ensue.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: GOLDEN ECONOMIC PRIZE, OR RISING MENACE?
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DEMYSTIFIED-ECONOMIST _ The West cannot quite make up its
mind about how it wants to deal with China. In America, big
business lobbies Congress to treat China as a normal trading
nation, while Congress urges the Clinton administration to sell
more weapons to Taiwan, as defense against Communist Chinese
threats. Golden economic prize (2.6 billion armpits to deodorize)
or rising international menace (those ugly threats)? Is China one
or the other? Both or neither?
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN NEEDS A NEW PRIME MINISTER WITH A MANDATE, SOON
</P>
<P>
   POST-OBUCHI-JAPAN-ECONOMIST _ After Keizo Obuchi's stroke, Japan
has had to find a new prime minister. No one, however, seems to be
looking for any other change; that, most Japanese seem to think,
can wait until after the general election, due sometime before
autumn. Alas, Japan cannot afford to be so relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX: THE NEXT SILICON VALLEY?
</P>
<P>
   DOT.COM-PHOENIX-ECONOMIST _ America's arid Southwest is
attracting people faster than any other part of the country.
Maintaining quality of life, while continuing to attract the firms
that will provide the jobs to sustain population growth at almost
three times the national rate, is a balancing act. For Phoenix, the
answer may be the Internet. After all, an industry that doesn't
need too much space, and brings in a lot of money and not too many
people, seems like a good prospect for a city that wants to slow
down a bit. Could Phoenix be the next Silicon Valley?
</P>
<P>
   JACK E., OH...: IT'S A SINNERS' RACE FOR TEDDY'S SEAT
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-BADBOYS-SENATE-ECONOMIST _ Even in the age of negative
politics, there is something a little extraordinary, even
admirable, about Jack E. Robinson III's run for the Senate seat
that comes up for election in Massachusetts this year. In his
nine-page ``Robinson's Report,'' he reveals every skeleton in his
political closet, and is now challenging his notoriously inhibited
opponent, Sen. Ted Kennedy, to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   THE KU KLUX KLAN: STILL RIDING, WITH A BIGGER AGENDA
</P>
<P>
   KKK-ARKANSAS-ECONOMIST _ Half a century or so ago, the Ku Klux
Klan was remembered for its nocturnal cross burnings, its bombing
of black churches, its occasional murders. Now, in a new century,
it has picked up the trappings of modernity. It has an Internet
address for the ``Invisible Empire.'' And now Klansmen leave their
rallies in minivans and SUVs, not on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   THE UNCOMPROMISING POSITIONS OF RUDY GIULIANI
</P>
<P>
   RABID-RUDY-NY-ECONOMIST _ In an age when politicians seem able
to ``emote'' anything, New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani is a
gloriously feeble actor. Assuming, that is, that Hizzoner even
bothers to try _ which he usually does not. Make a few sympathetic
comments about unarmed men killed by policemen? Not on your life,
Mister. Keep financing a museum that has annoyed you?
Fugeddabahdit. A few routine courtesies to your opponent? Whodya
think you are, lady?
</P>
<P>
   DOES DOLLARIZATION MAKE CENTS FOR EL SALVADOR?
</P>
<P>
   DOLLARIZE-ELSALVADOR?-ECONOMIST _ Will El Salvador be the next
Latin American country to adopt the dollar as its currency? On
paper, at least, El Salvador is a far more promising candidate for
dollarization that, say, Ecuador, which recently adopted the
greenback out of desperation with its own, sliding, currency.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL, SANS REGRETS: BEFORE YOU HIT THE `SEND' BUTTON ...
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-`WHOOPS!'-ECONOMIST _ Who has not banged out an angry
reply to an apparently brusque e-mail message, hit the send button
_ and then regretted it? Surely no technology has led to so many
rifts and fractured friendships (not to mention subpoenas) as
electronic mail. But nowhere is e-mail more perilous than in
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN'S SOCCER-BALL INDUSTRY MENDS ITS TATTERED IMAGE
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-LABOR-PAKISTAN-ECONOMIST _ Ending child labor in Pakistan
can have unexpected consequences. In the mid-1990s, Pakistani
soccer-ball manufacturers were under attack when the western press
discovered that they were employing children for 80-hour-a-week
shifts, working for pennies in near darkness. The industry hastily
made profound changes and, three years later, child labor in
Sialkot's soccer industry is mostly history. The effects, though,
have been double-edged. Like soccer itself, getting rid of child
labor is not always a win-win game.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE THE FORBIDDEN `SECRET ROOMS' OF PORNOGRAPHIC POMPEII
</P>
<P>
   EROTIC-POMPEII-ECONOMIST _ Two and a half centuries after the
excavation which brought the ancient, destroyed cities of Pompeii
and Herculaneum to light, a collection of ``obscene objects,'' long
kept behind closed doors, is about to be opened again to the
general public. A preview of the erotic material in Naples reveals
more than anything that they are far above the standards _ as art
as well as entertainment _ of what passes for pornography today.
</P>
</TEXT>
