<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PUTIN TO VISIT
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Vladimir Putin will come to Britain on Sunday on
his first trip to the West since assuming power in December.
Officials at 10 Downing Street said he would spend Monday in talks
with industrialists and Prime Minister Tony Blair, who visited
Putin in St. Petersburg last month. A spokesman could not confirm
reports that the Russian would see the queen. He said the exchange
of visits underlined Britain's belief that it is better to build a
new relationship with Russia rather than isolate it over its
military campaign in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: CHEERS!
</P>
<P>
   The government proposed new rules that would allow pubs to serve
drinks after 11 p.m. for the first time since World War I. Under
the current system, pubs have to stop selling alcohol at 11,
although customers are usually given a short grace period to finish
their drinks. The present system encourages many people to drink up
quickly before 11 and results in customers leaving en masse. This
can lead to increased drunkenness, with people ``hitting the
streets _ and sometimes each other _ at the same time,'' Home
Secretary Jack Straw said.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: PLUNDER ON THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Germany has started an Internet Web site listing thousands of
works of art plundered by the Nazis from museums and individuals in
World War II. The site, www.lostart.de, lists unclaimed treasures
confiscated for the ``Fuehrer Museum'' that Hitler dreamed of
building in Linz, Austria. The site, with listings in German,
English and eventually Russian, allows anyone to peruse items that
may have belonged to their families. The artworks are now in
storage in government depots in Berlin or on temporary loan to
museums.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: MINISTER BACKED
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo gave new backing to Tourism Minister
Oscar Espinosa, whom Mexico City prosecutors have accused of
embezzling $50 million during his time as Mexico City mayor.
Zedillo stood side by side with Espinosa at a convention as
governing party officials showered the embattled minister with
praise. ``I have the president's backing and my conscience is
clear,'' Espinosa told reporters later.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: ISRAELI TO BE TRIED
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli judge ruled that a 19-year-old Israeli soldier can be
extradited to Canada to face murder charges. Daniel Weiz has
indicated he would go to Toronto to be tried, along with two
Canadian teen-agers, for the murder of a 15-year-old boy who in a
Toronto park on Nov. 14. Weiz, who was visiting his father, has
admitted being in the park, but has denied committing the murder.
If Weiz is convicted, Canada has agreed to send him back to Israel
to serve his sentence. Under a new Israeli law, a citizen can be
extradited only if there is a promise the sentence can be served in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: HOLY WAR
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of militant Muslims, dressed in white and waving
scimitars, rallied at the Parliament building in Jakarta, calling
for a holy war against Christians in the former Spice Islands,
where sectarian violence has taken thousands of lives in the past
15 months.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: INSULATING SUHARTO
</P>
<P>
   Doctors prevented the attorney general's investigators from
holding a second round of questioning of former President Suharto
at his home, saying the stress could bring on a a new stroke.
Suharto has been charged with corruption during his 32-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: ANWAR BACKER TESTIFIES
</P>
<P>
   Brandishing his passport, Mohamad Azmin Ali, once the secretary
of former Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim, told a court that
the two men were in Europe on many of the dates Anwar is accused of
having sodomized his former family driver.
</P>
</TEXT>
