<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL (moved in the ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   MIXED-UP MEASUREMENTS
</P>
<P>
   DISCOVER-METRICS-NYTSF _ Last September, NASA's $165 million
Mars Climate Orbiter stumbled disastrously off course because of a
small mistake: One team of flight controllers had programmed the
spacecraft with English units (pounds and feet), while the other
had entered numbers using a metric scheme (newtons and meters). How
could this happen? By Bob Berman. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKTHROUGH BRIEFS
</P>
<P>
   DISCOVER-BRIEFS-NYTSF _ Brief reports from the fields of science
and technology as compiled by the editors of Discover magazine.
Among this week's headlines: ``Bedroom MRI's,'' ``Genetic Code
Breaker'' and ``The Bird on the Plain Flies Mainly with the
Brain.'' WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BIGGEST HOLE YET IN OZONE LAYER SPREADS CANCER FEARS
</P>
<P>
   OZONE-CANCER-INDEPENDENT _ A large hole has opened up in the
ozone layer over the Arctic, which scientists believe will severely
damage the natural shield protecting the northern hemisphere from
cancer-causing sunlight. More than 60 percent of the ozone layer
has been lost at certain altitudes over the North Pole _ a
deterioration on 1997, the previous worst year. By Steve Connor.
</P>
<P>
   FENCE-SITTING SUBURBAN MOMS MAY HOLD KEY TO THE WHITE HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   SOCCERMOMS-SUBURBS-CENTERPIECE _ For Peter Hart, a Democratic
pollster, Ruth Cullison, a homemaker and former art teacher in the
suburbs of Baltimore represents the quintessential swing voter.
Like a lot of Americans, Cullison is following the presidential
campaign at a distance, with a keen sense of anticipatory
disappointment. ``This is going to be like a retro election,'' she
says. ``Do I want an old Bush, or do I want an old Clinton?'' By
James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBS HO! A MIGRATION OF THE MELTING POT
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-SUBURBS-CENTERPIECE _ For more than a century America's
urban schools have been witnessing immigrant children enter into
and master English as their common language. But Rolling Terrace
Elementary is in the suburbs. Located in Takoma Park, Md., the
school is one of the most ethnically diverse schools in the
country, with more than 50 different nationalities are represented
here. By Lawrence Osborne.
</P>
<P>
   THE SERPENT IN THE GARDEN: A GATED-COMMUNITY TALE
</P>
<P>
   GATED-SUBURBS-CENTERPIECE _ Following the custom of
subdivisions, Canyon Gate is named after the quality least in
supply. There are no canyons. There is one gate. When Chris and
Christina Foley drove by, after the birth of their second child,
they saw little more than scraped earth and the gate, which was
enough to make them stop. ``For the first time in Houston,'' the
brochure read, ``the luxury of guard-gated neighborhoods is within
your reach.'' They bought a lot and built a home. Then the snakes
began to arrive. By Randall Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLES (moved in the ``l'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-POWERED REPORTERS REVEAL HOW THEY MADE THEIR MARRIAGE WORK
</P>
<P>
   COKIE-ROBERTS-LIFEBEAT _ ``There is no formula for balancing
work and family,'' says Cokie Roberts. Cokie, 56, the co-anchor of
ABC's ``This Week,'' has been married to former New York Times
reporter Steve Roberts, 57, for 33 years. Both have demanding jobs
with unpredictable hours. They answer questions about their family
life and about their new book, ``From This Day Forward,'' which
describes not only their own marriage but also the history of
marriage in America. By Joan Smith. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMPETITORS OF ALL AGES RACE AGAINST TIME AT NEMEAN GAMES
</P>
<P>
   GREEK-GAMES-LIFEBEAT _ Last year, the revival of Greece's
panhellenic games at the restored stadium of Nemea on the
Peloponnesian peninsula, drew 500 runners from 29 countries. This
June, the games will be repeated in the ancient stadium, with
barefoot participants dressed in tunics racing on hard-packed,
yellow clay, just as Greek athletes did 2,000 years ago. By
Lawrence Wells. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTY SITES LET NICHE BRANDS PUT THEIR BEST FACE FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-BEAUTY-LIFEBEAT _ Since last summer, online beauty
retailers have proliferated even though major players like Estee
Lauder, Lancome and Clinique _ which account for 70 percent of the
$4 billion high-end beauty market _ have not signed on. However,
Jupiter Communications, an Internet research company based in New
York, projects that by 2004, 5 percent of all beauty products will
be sold online. Insights into the online beauty business are
combined with practical information on which Web site to tap if you
want to buy products like ``Hope in a Jar'' or ``The Miracle
Worker.'' By Donna Wilkinson.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN EXERCISE BECOMES A ``FIX''
</P>
<P>
   EXERCISE-ADDICTION-LIFEBEAT _ Exercise addicts crave exercise
the same way that alcoholics crave a drink. The daily workout
becomes obligatory, even if the addict is sick or injured.
Improvement, recordkeeping, calorie and scale-counting become
compulsive behaviors. However, through cognitive and drug
therapies, people can overcome exercise addiction and can re-learn
how to live a balanced life. By Shawn O'Leary. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (moved in the ``e'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   BANK SHOT: PAUL NEWMAN IS BACK `WHERE THE MONEY IS'
</P>
<P>
   PAUL-NEWMAN-IN-WHERE-THE-MONEY-IS-STARBEAT-NYTSF _ At an age
when most men are basking in retirement, Paul Newman _ who turned
75 on Jan. 26 _ is busier than ever. He races cars, he runs a
food-products company and, most notably, several years after his
last starring role, he's returning to the big screen in ``Where the
Money Is.'' In the film, opening nationwide on April 14, he plays a
cagey convicted bank robber who uses a fake stroke as a means of
getting out of prison and back into business. By Jeanne Wolf. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   A MATTER OF TIME: JAMES CAVIEZEL STARS IN `FREQUENCY'
</P>
<P>
   JIM-CAVIEZEL-IN-FREQUENCY-STARBEAT-NYTSF _ What if you could
talk across time _ say, talk to your late father and, perhaps, even
keep him from having died? That's the concept behind ``Frequency,''
the new science-fiction drama opening nationwide on April 28 and
starring Dennis Quaid and James Caviezel, who shot to stardom two
years ago in ``The Thin Red Line.'' By Ian Spelling.
</P>
<P>
   MATTHEW PERRY BRINGS A BUDDY HOME TO `FRIENDS'
</P>
<P>
   MATTHEW-PERRY-ON-BRUCE-WILLIS-ON-FRIENDS-STARBEAT-NYTSF _
Matthew Perry recently invited a pal to drop by and guest-star on a
few ``Friends'' episodes. His co-stars didn't complain too much _
after all, Perry's friend was big-screen superstar Bruce Willis.
But the way his career is going, Perry may soon be as big a name as
Willis, who co-stars with Perry in the current film smash ``The
Whole Nine Yards'' and will appear in three ``Friends'' episodes
beginning on April 27. By Andrew Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   BORN TO DIRECT? SOPHIA COPPOLA STEERS `THE VIRGIN SUICIDES'
</P>
<P>
   SOPHIA-COPPOLA-DIRECTS-THE-VIRGIN-SUICIDES-STARBEAT-NYTSF _ In
making her directorial debut, Sophia Coppola had to fight her way
out of two daunting shadows: those of her father, legendary
director Francis Ford Coppola, and of her husband, Oscar-nominated
director Spike Jonze. But, according to many critics and audiences
at the Cannes Film Festival, she's done exactly that with ``The
Virgin Suicides,'' opening on April 21 nationwide. By Cindy
Pearlman.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH NOONAN
</P>
<P>
   FAIRCHILD-PEGGY-NOONAN-INTERVIEW-NYTSF _ Peggy Noonan's new
book, ``The Case Against Hillary Clinton,'' aims to stop Hillary's
Senate campaign dead in its track. An interview. By Susan Watters.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   OH BABY! HOW CHIC
</P>
<P>
   FAIRCHILD-MATERNITY-CHIC-NYTSF _ It's long overdue, but
retailers and designers are beginning to capitalize on a trend
that's gaining momentum: maternity chic. By Anne D'Innocenzio. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (moved in the ``t'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   DEDUCING HOLMES' CITY
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-FARE-NYTSF _ If you seek the city of Sherlock Holmes, the
fog-bound London illuminated by gaslight and dreams, you can still
find it to a surprising degree. On a visit last August, Stephen
Kendrick discovered that Holmes was an apt guide to London, where
the game's still afoot, and so is the touring.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING AROUND: A ROOM WITH A VIEW ... FOR A GOOD PRICE
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SHOPPING-ART-NYTSF _ Hotels have become as adept as the
airlines at shifting their prices to suit the marketplace. So when
it comes time to shop around, a single call or a simple visit to a
Web site is rarely enough. Here, tips on how to get the best rates
on rooms. By Everett Potter. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS (moved in the ``a'' and ``f'' news files)
</P>
<P>
   HONEY, THERE'S A DOT-COM GROWING IN THE LIVING ROOM
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-ETAIL-PRIMER-NYTSF _ For more than 15 years, Tony Dunne had
informally designed interiors of homes for family and friends. Last
May, he was designing two apartments when he returned home from a
long day spent in furniture showrooms and told his wife about an
idea he had for a business. HauteDecor.com would bring together
about 20 top designers and have each create virtual rooms, in which
everything would be for sale. On July 1, 1999, they received
$500,000 for financing. This is their story. By Rosemary Breslin.
</P>
<P>
   TRACKING THE WEB TO REMOTE WESTERN CHINA
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-CHINA-NYTSF _ Thanks to modem connections and the efforts
of local entrepreneurs, the Internet is trickling into back alleys
and basements of the most remote regions of western China. A
nationwide system of local Internet service providers was completed
last year; now the seven westernmost provinces account for 5
percent of the country's Internet use. By Jennifer 8. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   PEDICARTS LINK SHANGHAI'S STREETS TO THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-SHANGHAI-NYTSF _ In the United States, ``fulfillment'' of
Internet orders can be left to domestic mail carriers. But in
China, where the dreams of dot-com wealth soar as high as the
obstacles to e-commerce _ like snail mail that deserves the name, a
balkanized banking system and a near-absence of consumer credit
cards _ success calls for a kind of ingenuity not taught at
business school. By Grace Fan.
</P>
<P>
   SPINNING OFF CAN MEAN BIG MONEY, BUT BIG DANGER TOO
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-SPINOFF-RISKS-NYTSF _ As establishing an Internet presence
becomes imperative for brick-and-mortar companies, they face the
urgent question of how much distance, physical and logistical, to
put between themselves and their online operations. By Hillary
Appelman.
</P>
<P>
   HIS PITCH: COME ON IN, THE WATER'S LUCRATIVE
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-CEO-RECRUITING-NYTSF _ Today, the nation's most experienced
managers are trying to decide whether to jump to Internet startups
with little more than a business plan and a pile of
not-yet-valuable stock options. Nobody understands this dilemma
better than David Beirne, a top technology headhunter who is now a
partner in Benchmark Capital, a leading Silicon Valley venture
capital fund. A Q&AMP;A interview. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW ECONOMY'S CURRENCY IS STOCK, STOCK AND STOCK
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-EQUITY-STAKE-NYTSF _ Today, hordes of business-to-business
contractors who make deals with high-tech companies are trading
their services for equity. While law firms have long taken slices
of their clients' companies on top of regular fees, consultants are
now doing the same, along with public-relations agencies, executive
search firms and commercial landlords. Now, signing contracts with
new clients resembles aggressive stock picking. By Martha Baer.
</P>
<P>
   IS ANYONE NOT OUT FOR E-BILLIONS? JOSIE TRUE, FOR ONE
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-NONCOMMERCIAL-SITES-NYTSF _ Without millions of dollars of
investors' money to buy mass-market advertising, noncommercial
sites, especially ones catering to untapped or underserved sectors,
face an uphill battle as they try to gather like-minded audiences
from the far corners of cyberspace. But such efforts are far from a
lost cause. By Andrea Adelson.
</P>
<P>
   HELP! MY BRAIN'S BEING EATEN BY A ZILLION DOT-COM ADS!
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-ADVERTISING-NYTSF _ A gerbil shot from a cannon. An actor
singing off-key. A college student who burps the alphabet. These
were just a few of the colorful images used in the past year by
dot-com companies flooding the airwaves with ``edgy'' advertising.
To analyze why dot-com advertisements are so wild, whether they
work and where they are going, a group of advertisers and dot-com
clients watched one another's commercials and exchanged views.
</P>
<P>
   BEHIND `NAME YOUR OWN PRICE' LIES A MESH OF PARTNERS
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-PRICELINE.COM-NYTSF _ Priceline.com allows a buyer to
propose a price that the seller, whether of airline tickets or
orange juice, can choose to accept or reject. This approach comes
out as the slogan ``Name Your Own Price.'' What Jay S. Walker, its
46-year-old founder, has in mind is more radical than eBay, pushing
a strategy that is becoming more important throughout e-commerce:
partnerships. Included: a sidebar about the author's experience
using Priceline. By Allen R. Myerson.
</P>
<P>
   TO PUT GE ONLINE MEANT PUTTING A DOZEN INDUSTRIES ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-GE-ONLINE-NYTSF _ Early last year, John F. Welch, the chief
executive and chairman of General Electric, asked the managers of
the huge company's businesses to establish a strategy for using the
Internet and to put it into effect before the end of 1999. All 12
of the GE's departments, from airplane engines to appliances to
industrial systems, met the goal. Here is what the
multibillion-dollar company learned by adapting to the Web. By
Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   CHARITIES SEE WEB'S POTENTIAL, BUT FIND IT HARD TO AFFORD
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-NONPROFITS-NYTSF _ Businesses have discovered the power of
the Internet for communicating with employees and customers quickly
through e-mail or a Web site. Nonprofit organizations should find
the Internet just as appealing. But the majority of charitable
organizations have been hindered by a lack of money, time, workers
and technological savvy. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   AUCTIONS CREEP INTO ALL KINDS OF SITES (BECAUSE THEY'RE FUN)
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-AUCTIONS-NYTSF _ Ebay isn't the only site running auctions
anymore. Retailers like Sharper Image Co. and Lands' End have
instituted auction components as part of their sites. Why? Once
consumers have gotten the bidding bug, they will go to auctions as
much for the thrill of the chase as to obtain an item. And they
will keep coming back. By Sally McGrane.
</P>
<P>
   BETTER WAYS TO SEARCH THAN TYPING `NEEDLE AND HAYSTACK'
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-WEBSEARCH-TEST-NYTSF _ The modern equivalent of searching
for a needle in a haystack is searching for just about anything on
the Web. To illustrate this, three people were asked to track down
three very different items in a random, completely unscientific
test. Here are the results. By Lisa Napoli.
</P>
