<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2732 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SOC-PRO-TEAM11-COX     04-10 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-PRO-TEAM11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta named as one of 8 markets in new U.S. women's soccer
league
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta was announced Monday as one of eight markets
slated to receive a franchise in a new professional women's soccer
league. Now, the team has to find a place to play when the league
starts in April 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's United Soccer Association, which has signed every
member of the 1999 U.S. Women's World Cup championship team, also
announced that Atlanta-based Turner Sports Inc. purchased rights
for a national television package.
</P>
<P>
   The package consists of 22 games on Turner Network Television
and CNN/Sports Illustrated, an all-sports news cable outlet, in
each of the first four years.
</P>
<P>
   The local investment group, Cox Enterprises Inc. _ the parent
company of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution _ has had numerous
discussions with Atlanta soccer leaders and team officials in
recent weeks but is just starting to explore serious prospects for
a venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we know the markets, the legwork has to be done,''
Cox Enterprises spokeswoman Colleen Brannan said. ``There are such
a variety of options (for venues) here. I don't think we're there
yet (in choosing one).''
</P>
<P>
   Alternate cities are Chicago, Columbus, Ohio, Detroit, Los
Angeles, Miami, Portland, Ore., Raleigh-Durham, N.C., and St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The first season requires minimum seating of 5,000. In Atlanta,
that number probably means play in a high school stadium, at least
in the beginning. One possibility is DeKalb Memorial Stadium, where
the A-League Atlanta Silverbacks begin their second season
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some good conversations (with Cox Enterprises),''
Silverbacks President Paul Sabiston said. ``We'd love to see a
women's professional league. We're trying to reach the same market.
You've got to work hard on your core base of fans. You just can't
put a soccer ball on a billboard and say: Hey, we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   One component of the planned Atlanta Soccer Village complex,
which was unveiled almost a year ago and which would be located in
or near Stone Mountain Park, would include a 5,000-seat stadium.
Project manager Amanda Brown-Olmstead would not elaborate on her
discussions with Cox Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a lot of possibilities,'' she said. ``I hope
the WUSA team does become part of the Atlanta Soccer Village.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown-Olmstead said funding has not been raised for such a
facility because there is no tenant, but she was optimistic
something could be constructed quickly, if necessary. Two years
ago, the Charleston Battery, an A-League rival of the Silverbacks,
built a 5,200-seat facility in four months.
</P>
<P>
   TNT will air 15 women's pro soccer games each season, and seven
will be on CNN/SI, according to Turner Sports President Mark
Lazarus. The two networks have a mostly male viewership, while the
interest in women's soccer, judging from the World Cup, is upscale,
suburban and family-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't consider family viewing (to be) niche,'' Lazarus
said. ``We consider it pretty widespread. At its very core, this
product is about families.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer has expressed an interest in putting
together a rival bid for a women's league. The deadline is May 1
for the bid to be submitted to the U.S. Soccer Federation, which is
the sanctioning power.
</P>
<P>
   But WUSA officials and top U.S. players don't want any part of
it, unless it is for cross-promotional purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the most important thing is that we want the focus to
be on women's soccer,'' midfielder Julie Foudy said. ``We will play
only for the WUSA.''
</P>
<P>
   OTHER FRANCHISES
</P>
<P>
   Other markets awarded initial franchises are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Boston
</P>
<P>
   _ New York
</P>
<P>
   _ Philadelphia
</P>
<P>
   _ Orlando-Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   _ San Diego
</P>
<P>
   _ San Francisco Bay
</P>
<P>
   _ Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
