<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2734 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-ALBEE-BABY-HNS &LR;      04-10 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBEE-BABY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBEE PLAY WILL HAVE U.S. PREMIERE IN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVERETT EVANS 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ An artist's creations often are called his children,
so it's more than a pun to announce that playwright Edward Albee
has a new baby _ ``The Play About the Baby,'' whose U.S. premiere
the Alley Theatre of Houston will present Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright is directing the four-person cast, which includes
Marian Seldes and Earle Hyman, two of American theater's most
distinguished actors.
</P>
<P>
   Albee wants the almost-new arrival to be judged on its merits,
despite the inevitable urge to compare it to ``The Zoo Story,''
``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' and his three Pulitzer Prize
winners, ``A Delicate Balance,'' ``Seascape'' and ``Three Tall
Women.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wishes to reveal little about the play's content,
preferring to surprise playgoers with its twists and mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   The basic ingredients are: a young couple, identified as Boy and
Girl, who have just had a baby, and a mature pair, called Man and
Woman, who intrude and draw the young duo into games of control,
raising questions about who will keep the baby _ and whether, in
fact, it exists.
</P>
<P>
   Even from that bare-bones summary one recognizes Albee musing on
themes that have long concerned him. ``Virginia Woolf'' features
older and younger couples in a clash of gamesmanship, as well as a
child whose existence is called into question. Several other plays
explore parenthood and identity, including the satirical ``The
American Dream.'' Mysterious visitors are a recurring element,
notably in ``Seascape'' and ``The Lady From Dubuque.''
</P>
<P>
   Backstage at the Alley, Albee exudes an air of relaxed
confidence. Despite the echoes of his earlier plays, he maintains
that this ``Baby'' has an identity all its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``In its genesis, its harks back to `The Lady From Dubuque,'''
Albee says. ``What it shares with that play is the theme of how
much of our reality is determined by what we need.'' In
``Dubuque,'' the title character arrives unbidden at the home of a
dying woman. Initially a cause of bewilderment, she ultimately
proves a source of consolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Play About the Baby'' had its world premiere at London's
Almeida Theatre in September 1998, directed by Howard Davies, who
also directed last season's acclaimed Broadway revival of ``The
Iceman Cometh.'' ``Baby'' drew mixed reviews, with some critics
complaining that the playwright had recycled ideas. Yet it found
enthusiastic supporters, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very fond of the London production,'' Albee says. ``It
was beautifully directed and beautifully acted. I'm grateful to
Howard Davies, because I learned a lot about the play from working
with him.'' The stars were Frances de la Tour and Alan Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Albee's one quibble was with the setting, which he found ``too
specific.'' ``Baby'' calls for a spare, abstract set. E. David
Cosier's model for the Houston production is virtually a bare
stage, slightly modified. The Houston design team _ Cosier, costume
designer Teresa Snider-Stein and lighting designer Jeffrey Koger _
also did the 1994 all-Albee season at New York's Signature Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   There were plans to move the London ``Baby'' to New York last
season, but Albee felt an American play needed American actors.
When the desired actors were unavailable, New York plans fell
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted with the cast we have here,'' he says. ``If this
is as effective a production as I think it is, we may go to New
York next fall.''
</P>
<P>
   David Burtka and Rebecca Harris, both with recent off-Broadway
credits, play the young couple.
</P>
<P>
   Albee is still ``tinkering'' with the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ending I'd originally written, which I (deleted from) the
London production, I am restoring here. It's just a moment, a final
visual metaphor. I'm clarifying some things and confusing others.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs. ``I never try to be obscure, really never write to
obfuscate. That would be perverse, in the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   The publication last year of the first Albee biography, Mel
Gussow's ``Edward Albee: A Singular Journey,'' offered readers a
deeper understanding of the wellsprings of Albee's writing. He was
an adopted child, raised by wealthy but distant parents, which
perhaps explains his lifelong fascination with parenting and
identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I approached 70, I knew someone would be doing a book. I
thought better it should be Mel Gussow (who has covered Albee since
the 1962 premiere of `Virginia Woolf') rather than someone
unfamiliar with my work. I had no problem with the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mel first approached me, I told him the one thing I
didn't want him to do too much of was to relate every single thing
that happened in my life to the content of my plays. But naturally,
whenever he found the opportunities, he played detective and made
those connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want anyone getting the idea I've just been
putting my life onstage. I invent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I read that book like an adventure story,'' Albee
says. ``I was wondering what would happen next. Frankly, I'd
forgotten a lot. And then, as I read, I remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   Albee is working on his next play, ``Who Is Sylvia?'' He says it
is ``about the limits of our tolerance'' and will be ``funny, cruel
and brutal.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Hartford (Conn.) Stage Company's acclaimed
production of his ``Tiny Alice'' is scheduled to go to New York
next season. And this fall, Albee will teach a course in theater
criticism at Baruch College in New York. He has taught playwriting
at the University of Houston each spring since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In his writing and his personal manner, Albee in recent years
seems to have evolved, as one critic noted in his review of
``Baby,'' ``from angry young man to rueful older one.'' With his
prizes, several works regarded as modern classics and the renewed
appreciation of recent seasons, perhaps it was inevitable that the
bad boy of American drama would mellow into one of its senior
statesmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've mellowed,'' he responds, as if mildly
affronted. ``I still have many of the same angers. I've just gotten
more experienced talking to journalists. With this next play, I
feel I might even be thrown out of the country.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
