<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S MOTHER IS HONORED WITH A BACHELOR'S DEGREE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Ohio)   By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ In an event seamlessly meshing the personal
and the political, Pauline LaFon Gore, the mother of Vice President
Al Gore, received her bachelor's degree Monday from Union
University, the tiny Baptist college in western Tennessee that she
left two years shy of finishing her course work in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   And as she listened on, her son, the presumptive Democratic
nominee for president, headlined the ceremony with a speech that
was part tribute to his mother's powerful influence, and part paean
to ambitious women everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``She grew up in a time when poor girls were not supposed to
dream,'' Gore told the audience at the exclusive Nashville City
Club. ``What motivated my mother to strive was not the dream of
money at all, but the dream of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore described his mother, who is 87, as being quietly motivated
by the stories of women from her mother's generation who were not
allowed to inherit land. She not only put herself through college
by waiting tables, she also took notes and read assignments for her
blind sister, Thelma.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, students were allowed to attend law school
without receiving a bachelor's degree, so she quit Union to enroll
at Vanderbilt University Law School in Nashville, where she became
one of the first women graduates, in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, she married another law school graduate, Al
Gore Sr., who later became a Democratic congressman and senator
from Tennessee. He died in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, the vice president credited his mother with
coining the memorable slogan that he says helped his father defeat
a powerful incumbent, Sen. Kenneth McKeller, in 1952. Below every
sign that carried McKeller's slogan, ``The thinking feller votes
McKeller,'' the Gore campaign posted a sign that read, ``Think some
more and vote for Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his mother's role as a campaign adviser for him and
his father, Gore told the story of a long-time supporter of his
father who told his mother, ``If your son is as good as his old
man, I'll be for him.'' To which his mother replied, ``Well, I
trained them both, and I did a better job on my son.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she has been severely weakened by a heart attack and
stroke, Mrs. Gore was alert enough Monday to gasp when her son
inadvertently revealed her age by discussing her 80th birthday
party seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president credited his mother with helping to end
gender discrimination at the Nashville City Club, asserting that
the club first began admitting women shortly after his mother was
thrown out of the dining room after trying to dine there with a
male friend in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also used his speech to praise his father as an example of
a Southern progressive who supported civil rights, opposed the
Vietnam War and was an early advocate of campaign finance reform _
an issue Gore is trying to champion in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``She shared his conscience,'' he said of his parents. ``In all
things large and small, she was his strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said Mrs. Gore, whose only remarks were a brief
thanks to the university, was the second person in the college's
history to be awarded a bachelor's degree without having completed
the required course work.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Later in the day, Gore traveled to Dayton, Ohio, where he held a
town meeting with about 200 undecided voters, his first such event
in nearly a month.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio is considered a battleground state. President Clinton and
Gore won the state in 1996. But recent polls show Gore trailing
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first questions Gore was asked at the town meeting
was whether he would shut down a hazardous waste incinerator in
East Liverpool, Ohio. In 1992, Gore vowed to block the incinerator,
but it has remained open, infuriating environmentalists around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Gore blamed the Bush administration for issuing,
during its final days, a permit to test the incinerator, leaving
the Clinton administration, he claimed, few options to shut it
down.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Elian Gonzalez, Gore offered yet another shading of
his position. Reaffirming his support for having a family court
decide the custody battle, Gore added that he thought the boy's
Cuban father and American relatives should meet to resolve the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, with tensions as high as they are, and both
sides trying to reach a solution, we need to encourage the talks
between the family members themselves,'' he said. ``Because that's
the ideal solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
