u f BC-STANLEY-MARKETPLACE-A     04-10 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANLEY-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: STILL WAITING AT STANLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stanley Works may tell investors about the need to be
patient, but the company's chief executive appears to have failed
to heed the same advice.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after John M. Trani, a rising star at General
Electric, took over as chief executive of Stanley Works, investors
are still looking for some of the GE management magic. For his
efforts, though, Trani pulled a sizable pay increase out of his
company last year.
</P>
<P>
   Trani, who had an impressive performance at GE's medical systems
division, was greeted with much enthusiasm when he took over
Stanley at the end of 1996. The stock rose by nearly a third during
the month after his arrival to top $39 a share.
</P>
<P>
   He promised to take Stanley's popular brand of tools and
hardware to new heights _ and profitability. Based in New Britain,
Conn., Stanley had not been as aggressive as it could have been in
slashing costs and searching out new markets. The new chief
executive boasted to Wall Street that Stanley would eventually be
able to grow at twice the industry's average rate.
</P>
<P>
   But the much-anticipated revival has yet to take place, despite
the boom in the home improvement market. Since 1996, the company's
annual revenues have remained essentially flat at about $2.7
billion. The company's ``core'' earnings, which it considers a more
telling indicator of its true profitability, dipped slightly last
year to $2.06 a share and are below what they were in 1997. The
stock, which peaked at $57.25 in early 1998, is now trading about
where it was when Trani initially became chief executive. While the
company's peer group has trailed the overall market since 1997,
Stanley's stock has lagged behind that of such competitors as Black
&AMP; Decker. It closed Monday at $26.125.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are disappointed. ``I think, generally, people are
very impatient,'' said Kevin Grant, one of the portfolio managers
for the Oakmark Fund and a Stanley shareholder. Despite Trani's
rhetoric, the task of bringing operating discipline and greater
ambition to Stanley has proved much harder than predicted, he said.
Trani ``has had to spend almost two years getting to know what he
has,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that the process of remaking Stanley has been a
difficult one. ``The last three years have been trying times, to
say the least,'' acknowledged James C. Lucas, an analyst with
Janney Montgomery Scott. ``Stanley Works is not going through a
restructuring, it is going through a re-creation process. It really
is a five-year process.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts and investors say that Trani has taken too
long to strengthen the company's management team. Only last year,
for example, did he hire James M. Loree, a former finance executive
at a unit of GE Capital, as the company's new chief financial
officer. ``These are people who should have been brought into
Stanley in 1997,'' said David R. Giroux, an analyst for T. Rowe
Price, a mutual fund company that is a large investor in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   And while they applaud Trani's efforts to reorganize the
company, they say that some of his initial attempts were not
entirely successful. Over the last few years, the company has had
various manufacturing inefficiencies and difficulty serving some of
its key customers.
</P>
<P>
   The company, while acknowledging its own frustration with the
pace of its progress, argues that significant steps have been taken
that will eventually help the company achieve its goals of
improving revenues and earnings. ``You have to take a long-term
view,'' said Vance N. Meyer, a spokesman for Stanley Works. ``There
are a lot of seeds being planted.''
</P>
<P>
   Trani has streamlined the company into a much more efficient
producer of tools and hardware. He has significantly concentrated
the company's product line on best sellers and brought some badly
need innovation to Stanley. The company has introduced hundreds of
new products, ranging from a new 25-foot tape rule to a
high-tension hacksaw that has been praised for its design.
</P>
<P>
   There are some early positive signs. During the second half of
1999, the company was better able to fill the orders of some key
customers. Revenues gained 2 percent, and operating cash flow
increased to $222 million. ``The worst is probably behind Stanley
works,'' Giroux said.
</P>
<P>
   But while he and other shareholders are still waiting for
concrete improvement in revenues and earnings, Trani is already
reaping substantial rewards. While some of his compensation is tied
directly to the company's stock, he was awarded about $4 million in
cash last year, according to Stanley's proxy statement, the result
of a higher bonus and substantial payout from the company's
longer-term performance plan.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of Trani's compensation was his yearly salary and
bonus, some $2.3 million, $500,000 more than he was paid in 1998
and in 1997. The performance plan kicked in the other $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although the board considered some of the factors cited in the
proxy statement, like core earnings, in considering Trani's
compensation last year, it also considered other aspects of
Stanley's operating performance, like the introduction of new
products and improved cash flow, according to Meyer, the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Only investors will have to wait to see if these early
indications are really a sign of a new and improved Stanley Works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
