<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Flight to quality' in markets examined
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don't panic. What's happening in the stock market is
that investors are simply looking for quality. That's the way
Business Week (April 17) explains what happened on Wall Street last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Among the week's highlights was April 4, ``the most volatile day
in the history of the stock market,'' when the Dow Jones industrial
average and the Nasdaq composite each plummeted more than 500
points before staging a remarkable recovery.
</P>
<P>
   What happened was not so much a change of investor interest from
``new economy'' stocks to ``old economy'' stocks, but ``a flight to
quality across the entire equity spectrum,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   The two most famous indexes, which had been separatedly widely
since late last year, started moving closer together recently when
investors shunned technology stocks _ which they had been buying
pell-mell _ and turned to brick-and-mortar blue chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can only be healthy for the market,'' Business Week says.
``For the last year and a half, the stock market has become a
market of extremes: extremely high valuations for the `new economy'
denizens that dominate the Nasdaq _and extremely low valuations for
anything that smacked of the `old economy.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, and especially the last few days, the
market tried to correct those extremes. And true to Wall Street's
form, the shift took place in a violent way.
</P>
<P>
   EXTREMELY DIFFERENT BOARDS
</P>
<P>
   The difference between a good board of directors and a bad board
is that the latter will show its flaws soon enough, but the former
may do its job so well no one really knows how they do it.
</P>
<P>
   So says Fortune (April 17), which identifies today's four best
boards and the six worst. Among the best is Atlanta-based Home
Depot, whose requirements include each director visiting at least
20 stores each year.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric, Intel and Texas Instruments also have ``best''
boards.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune says its annual survey of institutional investors,
investor advisory firms and shareholder rights advocates came up
with the six worst boards: Advanced Micro Devices, Archer Daniels
Midland, Maxxam, Ogden, Rite Aid and Warnaco.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, this is the magazine's Fortune 500 edition, the
results of which have already been published.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH MENTIONING ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Money (April) and Mutual Funds (May) offer articles on
retirement planning and investment strategies aimed at early
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   _ Technology Investor (May) credits Atlanta-based
Healtheon/WebMD for trying ``to streamline the economy's
least-efficient sector'' _ health care.
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual Investor (April) looks at ``indexmania,'' or the
growing reliance on mutual funds indexed to one of the many stock
market averages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
