<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ARMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN LAWMAKERS EDGING TOWARD ARMS-CONTROL PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In the first major test of a new and more centrist
parliamentary majority in Russia, President-elect Vladimir Putin
reached agreement Monday with his legislative allies to bring a
long-delayed nuclear arms reduction treaty to a ratification vote
in parliament as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of ratifying the treaty, known as START II, predicted
that they had the votes to win. The decision to move forward
immediately with the vote in the wake of Putin's victory in last
month's presidential election was hailed as a significant advance
of the arms control agenda here, one that had been blocked for five
years by a Communist-led coalition that dominated the parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But with the victory in December of liberal and centrist
parties, who won a majority of the 450 seats in the Russian Duma,
or parliament, a strong ratification vote would also demonstrate
the political realignment that is taking shape in Russian politics
as Putin is preparing to undertake a new phase of economic reforms
for which he will need strong parliamentary backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidential elections have given us a good chance to be
guided by Russia's interests and not to look back at internal
problems and engage in politicking,'' said Sergei Ivanov, the
director of Russia's national security council under Putin, after a
meeting of the advisory body in the Kremlin Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A number of legislative leaders here, as well as senior members
of the Clinton administration, have been urging Moscow to vote on
the treaty before Putin is sworn in on May 7. Last Friday in
Washington, Strobe Talbott, a deputy secretary of state, was quoted
by Reuters as saying, ``The Russians continue to assure us,
including in the last 24 hours, that the process for ratifying
START II in the Duma is under way.''
</P>
<P>
   But with all the prodding, it appeared that Putin decided to
test his strength in the Duma only after it was clear from
legislative leaders that a majority would support ratification.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty is still likely to be opposed by Communist deputies.
The Communist Party's leader, Gennadi Zyuganov, in a televised
interview Monday night, reiterated his view that the treaty ``in
its current state is absolutely defective'' and would destroy
``Russia's most important nuclear missile umbrella'' at a time when
Russian lacked the budget resources to maintain a strategic missile
force as large as that of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``They propose to destroy our missiles, while mass production of
new ones has not started and there is no money for it,'' Zyuganov
said.
</P>
<P>
   But another legislative leader, Vladimir Lukin, a member of the
reformist Yabloko faction and a former ambassador to the United
States, said he did not believe the Communists would be able to
muster more than 150 votes if they opposed ratification. ``So it
seems that a majority is being hammered together,'' he said, adding
that the chances for ratification are ``rather high.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the ratification of the seven-year-old treaty is
the least contentious item on the arms control agenda. A more
heated debate lies ahead in START III negotiations, in which Moscow
is seeking deeper cuts in strategic arsenals, in part because it
can no longer afford a large array of strategic weapons, and where
Washington is seeking Russian acceptance for American plans to
build an anti-ballistic missile shield over the United States to
protect it from ``rogue states'' and accidental launches.
</P>
<P>
   These plans have aroused deep concerns here and in China that
the United States will ultimately destabilize the strategic balance
by having both a shield against nuclear missiles and the most
robust offensive nuclear forces.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Moscow warned that it remained opposed to American
plans to build a national missile defense system that would
undermine the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty of 1972. Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov, meeting with American businessmen and
journalists Monday, said, ``The collapse of the 1972 ABM Treaty
would cast the world into a new confrontation.'' He added that an
American decision to abrogate the treaty would undermine relations
between Moscow and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The climate in which our economic cooperation develops depends
to a large extent on the long-term resolution of issues related to
strategic stability,'' Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
   Dimitri Rogozin, chairman of the Duma's international affairs
committee, said ratification of the START II treaty and its
extensions agreed to in 1997 provided ``an opportunity to keep the
Americans from quitting the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   The START II treaty, negotiated in the last year of the Bush
administration, commits the United States and Russia to reduce
their nuclear arsenals to between 3,000 and 3,500 warheads each
from about 6,000. One milestone of the accord is a ban on
land-based missiles with multiple warheads. American arms control
negotiators have long sought the elimination of these systems, most
notably the heavy Russian SS-18 rockets with 10 warheads each. The
destruction of missiles and warheads was to be carried out by 2003,
but in the absence of ratification, the two sides agreed to
deactivate the affected missiles by that date and carry out
destruction by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Boris Yeltsin failed repeatedly to bring the
treaty to a vote in 1996 and 1997. In late 1998, as the
Communist-led Duma prepared to debate the accord, American and
British air strikes on Iraq caused a delay. The Clinton
administration's announcement last year that it intended to seek
amendments to the ABM treaty resulted in another delay. In March
1999, Duma leaders said they would debate and vote on the measure
the following month, but consideration was postponed again with the
onset of NATO's air campaign in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The committees on defense and international affairs both
recommended ratification Monday in closed-door meetings and the
speaker of the parliament, Gennadi Selezynov, said the Duma
Council, consisting of leaders of all factions, would meet on
Tuesday to set the final schedule for the debate and vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
