<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASY-ACCESS BEACHES  
 VISITING SHEIKDOMS  
 BERMUDA DOLPHINS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Questions may be italicized) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have had two knee replacements and use a cane, and I have
difficulty getting into and out of the water at the beach unless
there is something for me to hold on to. Do you know of any
Caribbean beaches with a pier going into the water or some other
kind of railing or steps that would put me into deep water? _ Alvin
V. Hart, New York, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Mar Sin Barreras (Sea Without Barriers) is in Puerto Rico at
Luquillo Beach on the northeast end of the island. There, you will
find a ramp going into the ocean. The beach also has special life
preservers for guests with disabilities and staff to assist you, if
you need it. For beachgoers who need a wheelchair, Mar Sin Barreras
also has specially designed beach wheelchairs. Toilet and shower
facilities are also designed to be accessible. Information: (787)
889-4329. A similar project is under construction at Boqueron, on
the southwest part of the island.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility you might consider is to go snorkeling or
swimming on a dive boat. Red Sail Sports, www.redsail.com, with
centers in Aruba, (011-297) 861603 and the Cayman Islands, (345)
945-5965, has experience with clients who have limited mobility.
Rod McDowell, with the company's Cayman Islands office, said that
you could take a half-day boat trip, with access into the water by
ladder, for $65, with lunch.
</P>
<P>
   At Divibonaire, www.divibonaire.com, (800) 661-3483, there's a
dock with steps leading into the water. It is at the Divi Flamingo
Beach Resort on Bonaire, and it is free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Last spring, I read about a prince from the United Arab
Emirates who had entered a horse in the Kentucky Derby. His country
was described as a tourism destination, with luxury hotels and
beautiful bazaars. How accessible is it for an American? _ Marie
Anderson, Pensacola, Fla. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The United Arab Emirates, on the Arabian Gulf between Saudi
Arabia and Oman, is a union of seven sheikdoms formed in 1971 when
the British left the Gulf. The largest _ Abu Dhabi _ is about
26,000 square miles; the smallest, Ajman, is about 100 square
miles. Of all the Persian Gulf states, the United Arab Emirates has
some of the best tourism infrastructure and the most relaxed entry
rules, and English is widely understood.
</P>
<P>
   The best time to visit is November through March. At other
times, it can be extremely hot and humid. Ramadan, the month when
Muslims fast from sunrise to sundown, is another period you might
wish to avoid; the dates vary.
</P>
<P>
   Americans need a visa (issued for two weeks to three months),
obtained through a United Arab Emirates Embassy. Applicants will
also be asked to submit documentation of travel plans, which can
include a hotel reservation; often, the hotel you are staying at
can help.
</P>
<P>
   Contact the Embassy of the United Arab Emirates, Suite 700, 1255
22nd Street NW, Washington, D.C. 20037; (202) 955-7999, fax (202)
333-3246. Call between 9 a.m. and 1 p.m. Monday to Friday. Visas
cost $51.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors should dress modestly. Although women do not have to
cover their heads with scarves, tight jeans and skirts above the
knee are not advisable.
</P>
<P>
   According to the State Department, there is relatively little
crime. The biggest danger is driving, and since a rental car is the
most convenient way to get around, the risks should not be taken
lightly. Traffic accidents are a leading cause of death, with
reckless driving, wandering camels, unmarked speed bumps, dust
storms and flash floods (particularly November through January) the
major hazards.
</P>
<P>
   The country's telecommunications, roads, hospitals and other
infrastructure are modern and well-maintained. The landscape is
varied, from the Hajar Mountains in the east to vast deserts to
beaches. Abu Dhabi, the capital city, and Dubai, farther north
along the coast, have 21st-century skylines concealing ancient
souks. Dubai has more night life and better air access, and is the
best base for exploring the emirates.
</P>
<P>
   About two hours' drive from either Abu Dhabi or Dubai are Al Ain
and Buraimi, an oasis on the Oman border with an interesting
museum, livestock and camel souks and forts (and the country's
largest skating rink). The Liwa Oasis, on the southern edge of the
emirates, is a popular getaway for its desert scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Dubai is an easygoing city, with colorful souks and boat rides
on Dubai Creek. The Dubai Museum occupies the 19th-century Al
Fahaidi Fort, with exhibits on desert life, culture and weaponry.
The gold souk is also fun to explore. The best beaches are in
Jumeirah on Dubai's outskirts. Farther north, Sharjah has an
intriguing natural-history museum.
</P>
<P>
   Flights from the United States are not cheap; a typical
round-trip bargain fare to Dubai in the more-temperate months is
about $1,500, and there are no nonstops. But you may do better if
you shop around.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels like the Intercontinental, Novotel, Hyatt Regency and
Four Points Sheraton cost from $150 to $200 a night, but prices are
negotiable. Call up www.uae-pages.com or www.emirates.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. This August we will be going to Bermuda with our daughters,
their husbands and four grandchildren. They want to swim with
dolphins while there, but I understand that reservations must be
made far in advance. Is this correct? _ Freda R. Eiberson, Long
Beach, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Dolphin Quest, which opened in 1996 on the grounds of the
Southampton Princess Resort, is on a cove on the island's south
shore. Guests can interact with bottlenose dolphins in the
three-acre Dolphin Lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   Through October, a half-hour Kids Encounter (ages 5 to 12) costs
$85. Children can touch the dolphins while sitting on a submerged
dock.
</P>
<P>
   An Adult Encounter (ages 13 and older) is a half hour and costs
$95. Participants can touch and swim with dolphins. For each
program, swimsuits and towels are required.
</P>
<P>
   Space is limited in these programs, which are offered daily.
Guests at the Southampton or Hamilton Princess hotels can make
reservations at any time by calling (800) 441-1414. Otherwise, you
can reserve no more than four days in advance; contact Dolphin
Quest at the Southampton Princess, Post Office Box HM 1379,
Hamilton, HM FX, Bermuda; (441) 239-6957, fax (441) 238-4176.
</P>
<P>
   If you would like to reserve a private session with the
dolphins, however, you can make the reservation as far ahead as you
wish. It will cost $1,500, and you can have up to 10 persons in the
session, which is half an hour, like the the ones described above.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
