<HEADER>
A2752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-GENOME-NYT &LR;      04-10 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GROUPS IN DNA RACE DIFFER ON FIXING PROJECT'S FINISH LINE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Mo., British Columbia)  By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leaders of the public consortium racing to decode the human
genome are expressing doubts that their rival, the Celera Corp.,
can produce a high quality version as soon as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining the human DNA sequence, or genome, is expected to be a
major landmark in scientific history and initiate a new,
genetically based era in medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Celera's president, J. Craig Venter, said that he had
finished gathering raw sequence data on the human genome and
expected to piece together the millions of fragments into an
assembled sequence in three to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium expects to finish its version of the human genome
by 2003, but plans to have a ``rough draft'' by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Francis Collins, head of the National Institutes of Health's
part of the consortium, attended a meeting in Vancouver, British
Columbia, over the weekend, and was quoted by The Associated Press
as saying, ``What we all need to recognize is that for the
sequencing for the human genome, there is not going to be a finish
line for any group, for at least the next couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   A consortium spokeswoman said Monday that Dr. Collins had not
criticized Celera but was referring to the definition of completing
the human genome. Nonetheless, Celera's stock dropped 20 percent,
to $103 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Completion is a matter on which the two sides differ, not least
because defining it is tantamount to deciding where the finish line
for the human genome race really lies. If some form of near
completeness passes muster, it now seems that Celera may win; if
the scientific community demands absolute completeness, then
probably only the consortium can afford to persevere to the end.
</P>
<P>
   Celera says that it can produce an essentially complete version
of the genome, and that it will fill in the inevitable gaps later.
Consortium biologists warn that Celera's version may be seriously
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Celera published its decoding of the Drosophila
fruit fly genome, a project undertaken to test its strategy for the
human genome. The fly genome had many small gaps, but was highly
praised by biologists who study the fly.
</P>
<P>
   The company said last week that its human genome would be of the
same quality as the fly's.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Waterston, director of the consortium's genome sequencing
center at Washington University in St. Louis, noted that Celera had
proportionately less raw data available for the human genome than
it had for the fly. ``I doubt that it will be as good as the fly
project,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the consortium's results, which are publicly
available, Celera seems to have comparatively little human data
available, especially in the 25 percent of the genome that the
consortium has not yet tackled.
</P>
<P>
   But Celera's scientists believe the human genome will be easier
to assemble than Drosophila's, even though it is 30 times as large,
because its regions of highly repetitive DNA _ the main obstacle to
assemblers _ are less problematic than the fly's. J. Paul Gilman,
Celera's director of policy planning, said the fly work had shown
that genomes could be successfully assembled by Celera's method
using less DNA data than first calculated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
