<HEADER>
A2756 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS-RECAP11     04-10 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-RECAP11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We start with the Atlanta Thrashers' 14-61-7 record.
It is what people will remember the most until training camp starts
in September.
</P>
<P>
   The record that was the fourth-worst among 13 expansion teams
since 1970. The record with the fourth-highest loss total in NHL
history. The record that featured 29 home defeats, second all-time.
The record that included losing streaks of 12, 10 and seven.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran center Ray Ferraro, looking at that dismal record, said:
``I know we made a lot of changes this year. But, let's face it, we
only won 14 games, so we'll probably make a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers' inaugural season has been put to bed. Or laid to
rest. Only those counting turnstile rotations can claim success.
But, standings aside, general manager Don Waddell saw progress from
the season-opening 4-1 loss to New Jersey to the season-ending 2-1
loss to Carolina _ and not because of the goal differential in
those two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we approached the season was we wanted to be better in
game 20 than at the start, better in game 40, game 60 and game
80,'' Waddell said. ``But you can't always measure things in wins
or losses. Right now, there's no question our lineup is better than
before. Would we like to have had more wins? Of course? Have we
made strides? Yes. Are we going to stand pat? No.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers won only half as many games as Nashville did in
its first season, although it is worth noting that the Predators
finished with an identical 28-47-7 record this season. Nashville
might think now that its first-year mark skewed reality; the
Thrashers hope the same for their own record.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey teams are built from the back out, and goaltending was a
problem most of the season for the Thrashers. Starter Damian Rhodes
started slowly, missed four months with an ankle sprain, played
well for a stretch after his return, then appeared fatigued from a
string of 11 starts in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse was what happened during his absence. Norm Maracle,
though strong in his last few appearances, was inconsistent and
lost the confidence of the coaching staff. Maracle, Scott
Fankhouser and Scott Langkow, all rookies, rotated during Rhodes'
absence. The defense included two busts from the expansion draft,
Darryl Shannon and Kevin Dean, so it's no wonder the Thrashers had
the league's worst team goals-against average of 3.78 and allowed
313 goals.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell made several moves to improve the team's skill level.
The best sent Kelly Buchberger and Nelson Emerson to Los Angeles
for Donald Audette and defenseman Frantisek Kaberle. In 14 games,
Audette had seven goals, 11 points and 50 shots on goal. The team's
average shot total improved after the trade to 28.6 from 25.2.
Goaltending and defense now are the priority.
</P>
<P>
   A preview of this summer:
</P>
<P>
   _ In goal: The Thrashers will not pick up the $1 million option
on Maracle's contract, although he might be back at a lower figure.
Regardless, Waddell will pursue a veteran goalie in a trade,
probably before the June 23 expansion draft. Several teams that
have two strong goalies plan to protect only one from Minnesota and
Columbus, and they might choose to get something in return for the
other. Maracle has been criticized for his poor conditioning and
work habits. Waddell said he still believes in the goalie, but he
also said, ``This is the most important summer he's going to have
as a professional. He can't spend three months on his boat.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The draft: The Thrashers will be weighted first in a lottery
for the No. 1 pick in the June 24-25 entry draft. But whether they
have the first or second pick, Waddell might trade down or even out
of the first round, because it has no clear-cut top choice. ``Last
year, I said I won't trade the first pick,'' he said. ``I'm not
saying that this year.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Signings: The free-agent market is thin, but Waddell will be
busy with his own team. At the NHL and minor-league level, 19
players, not including Maracle, do not have a contract for next
season. Johan Garpenlov, who is not expected back, and Mike
Stapleton, who might be, are the only unrestricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers went through 43 players this season, and Waddell
conceded that there had been mistakes: Shannon and Dean on defense,
Maracle to date, the decision not to pick up Steve Sullivan off
waivers from Toronto. Chicago did, and Sullivan scored 22 goals for
the Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell worried more about tomorrow than today, which led to the
departures of veterans like Terry Yake and Jody Hull in the
pre-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would've been a better team this year if we kept those
guys,'' Waddell said. ``But where would we be at the start of next
year? What if guys like (Andreas) Karlsson never got a chance to
play? Would they be as good next year?''
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, the expectations go up. Waddell said he would be
disappointed ``if we didn't win at least 10 more games.'' That
total, 24, might be more reachable than originally thought.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
