<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURFING FOR BARGAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 16) 
 By L.R. SHANNON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is common enough, and easy enough, to reserve a seat on an
airliner from your computer's keyboard, but we don't always want to
travel by air. At times we want to get from here to there by rental
car, or to have one waiting for us at the airport; there are even
souls who prefer to or must travel by train or bus. How easy is
that to arrange from the screen? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has its ups and downs, no pun intended. I tried to rent cars
from five well-known companies _ Hertz, Avis, Budget, Enterprise,
and National _ with mixed results, and also dipped into Amtrak and
Greyhound, which were solid if uninspired. All of them require a
lot of information, such as where you are leaving from and when,
what class of car you want to drive or _ in Amtrak's case _ what
class of seat you want. The selections are mostly made from menus,
so there is little typing to do, and the menus are similar enough
from one site to another that when you've learned to use one you
have largely learned to use them all _ and dissimilar enough that
you must not leap to conclusions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Renting cars on line is a growing business. Frank Camacho, staff
vice president for marketing at Hertz, said that 3 percent of the
company's rentals were booked online last year, and that the rate
has been increasing by 100 percent a year for three years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the rental cars, I decided to get a compact car seating four
from a station near my house in northern New Jersey, picking it up
at 9 a.m. on April 22, and returning it on April 29. I breezed
through both Hertz, at www.hertz.com, and Avis, at www.avis.com,
and found similar cars at each for the same price, $387.95 with
unlimited mileage. But at Enterprise's site, www.enterprise.com, I
had to change both pickup and return times to match the hours when
the office was open. The price: $218.99 for 750 miles, 20 cents a
mile thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   I went through the process at Budget, www.drivebudget.com, and
was finally told: ``We are unable to confirm your request for one
of the following reasons: There are no cars available. The car/rate
you requested is not available for one-way rental.'' I could have
selected a new day, time or location, but chose not to. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   National Car Rental, www.nationalcar.com, was more of a problem.
There was no office in my neighborhood, so I selected one from a
list of offices in New Jersey, and finished the rental process. An
arcane error message appeared. I tried a second and third time, to
make sure I hadn't done something wrong or omitted a step, and got
the same message both times. Finally, a call to the toll-free
telephone number given on the Web page brought the disconcerting
information that National had no office at the location I had
picked from National's own screen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The prices do not include insurance, or reflect discounts or
incentives that vary from site to site. When you wrap up the rental
by providing credit-card information, you are given a confirmation
number, just as if you had made arrangements by telephone, to take
to the company's office.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are other rental-car agencies besides the big names, of
course. Among those I peeked at were www.americar.com, with offices
in Orlando, Fla.; Syracuse; Huntsville, Ala.; Minneapolis and
Albany, and www.autorentnet.com, which rents cars in both the
United States and Europe. The second has a section where you can
rent luxury cars _ Jaguars, BMW's, Mercedes-Benzes and others _ for
about $570 to $2,900 a week. The section for more reasonably priced
cars, however, is restricted to Europeans visiting the United
States. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At www.amtrak.com, you can browse among the schedules and fares
and buy tickets. I checked out one-way fares from Newark to
Washington; an irritation is that you must use Amtrak's
three-letter abbreviations, so the fares I checked out were from
NWK to WAS. An unreserved coach seat on the morning of April 22, a
Saturday, was $67. If you reserve a seat online, you must print out
a copy of the screen with the confirmation number and exchange it
for a ticket at the train station. According to Steven Taubenkibel,
an Amtrak spokesman, 5 percent of all tickets are now sold online.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
