<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2766 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PERU-ELECT-NYT &LR;      04-10 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUJIMORI APPEARS CLOSE TO WINNING PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION IN FIRST
ROUND
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ Official returns on Monday showed President Alberto
Fujimori approaching a first-round victory in Peru's presidential
election, prompting cries of fraud and fears of mass disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Sunday's voting, polls of voters and independent
vote counts had suggested that neither Fujimori nor his challenger,
Alejandro Toledo, would garner a majority, raising hopes among
foreign diplomats and election monitors of a second-round ballot
that might avoid the irregularities and dirty tricks that have
accompanied the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But with 39 percent of the vote counted, the National Election
Office said Fujimori had received 49.88 percent to Toledo's 39.98.
That, coupled with unexplained delays of up to several hours in
getting ballot boxes and tally sheets to computer centers, led to
suspicions of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The ballots have already been destroyed, as allowed by Peruvian
law.
</P>
<P>
   When the first allegations of counting irregularities surfaced
just before midnight, Toledo led tens of thousands of protesters on
a march to the presidential palace, where they were driven back by
police using tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters carried Toledo on their shoulders, then threw tear
gas canisters back at the police and at the palace itself, chanting
``The fear is gone!''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said on Monday that the election results should be
annulled. ``The quantity and seriousness of the irregularities _
from the ballots to the counting centers _ has led us to the
conclusion not to recognize the results,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, a business-school professor trained in the United
States, has never held high public office. But during his long-shot
campaign he demonstrated a knack for timing and an ability to
motivate energetic support, especially from working-class people.
</P>
<P>
   He and his supporters threatened a prolonged civil disobedience
campaign, one which could make a third five-year term untenable for
Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign election monitors expressed particular concern over the
widespread delays in getting tally sheets and ballots to counting
centers. Some arrived as many as seven hours after polls were
closed, even in cities like Lima and Arequipa, where there was no
reason for such delays.
</P>
<P>
   The head of Organization of American States observer team,
Eduardo Stein, also said he could not understand why dozens of
government computer centers were shut down through Sunday night and
most of Monday, when they were supposed to be open and tallying
ballots. He said he could not ascertain how the government was
coming to its official count, or where the count was taking place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am worried,'' said Stein, a former foreign minister of
Guatemala. ``All the signals we got yesterday evening were
disquieting because there was a big and inexplicable delay in the
transportation of the vote tabulation sheets and the ballot boxes
to the computer counting centers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Something sinister is happening here,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If everything that caused those delays has a
reasonable explanation, why don't they offer a reasonable
explanation to the public?''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has remained silent since the vote, but top government
officials have publicly rejected charges of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   A questionable Fujimori victory would put the United States and
the Organization of American States in the difficult position of
deciding whether to accept the results or retract their recognition
of the Fujimori government and levy sanctions until new elections
are called.
</P>
<P>
   When the election had appeared headed for a run-off, the State
Department had urged the Peruvian government ``to take every
possible measure to ensure that the next round of voting fully
meets democratic standards of openness, transparency and
fairness.'' There was no subsequent statement.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has long been a key U.S. ally in fighting international
narcotics trafficking, and is seen as a strong leader who can
prevent the kind of guerrilla turbulence wracking neighboring
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   But since election day there have been reports that convicts
voted, that ballots were tampered with to remove Toledo's name,
that people were paid to vote for Fujimori and that police and army
officials harassed election monitors of opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   According to election observers, the vote tally sheets, which
were scheduled to be delivered by 9 p.m. on Sunday night to the
computer centers, did not reach the centers until between 4 a.m.
and 5 a.m. Monday morning, and the delays were nationwide and
appeared to be systematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This process has been contaminated,'' said Rafael Roncagliolo,
a director of Transparencia, a private Peruvian election monitoring
group that is largely funded by the U.S. government. ``If they
avert a second round, we can only conclude that they have had a
long-term plan for fraud all along.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick count of vote tally sheets by Transparencia on Sunday
night found that Fujimori had won 48.7 percent of the vote. On
Monday, Transparencia officials said that if anything, its tally
overestimated the Fujimori vote. An Organization of American States
quick count of separate vote tally sheets came to a similar
conclusion that a second round would be held.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, with 39.15 percent of the official vote count
complete, the government election authority reported that Fujimori
had won 49.88 percent of the ballots, just short of the majority
needed to avert a runoff vote with Toledo. Election officials noted
that their tallies did not include votes from the most remote
jungle and Andean Indian villages, where Fujimori has been
traditionally strongest and where election monitors say the chances
for fraud are greatest.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Portillo, the top Peruvian election authority, told
reporters on Monday that there were no computing problems and that
``a very rigorous effort'' was being made to assure an accurate
vote count. ``A Dutch observer asked me why there were so many
safeguards,'' he added, ``and I responded that we are very careful
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
