<HEADER>
A2768 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS11-COX     04-10 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CUBS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves turn cold in loss against Cubs
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Newly falling snow provided a fitting backdrop to what
the Cubs did to the Braves in the ninth inning Monday afternoon,
turning back-to-back walks into a four-run rally to stun the Braves
4-3 and warm the 38,655 fans who showed up for the opener of the
85th season at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Down 3-0 with three outs left, the Cubs mustered their first
miracle of the 2000 season after losing three extra-inning games.
They rode Shane Andrews' three-run homer off Kerry Ligtenberg for
their third win of the season, handing the Braves their third loss.
</P>
<P>
   It spoiled a dominating start from Kevin Millwood, wasted
another home run from Andres Galarraga, and exposed Ligtenberg's
decision to pick the frigid confines of Wrigley Field to start
throwing his slider.
</P>
<P>
   After using exclusively fastballs to collect two saves in his
first two opportunities, Ligtenberg threw a slider to Andrews 1-2,
which he fouled off. Ligtenberg came right back with another
slider, this one worse, and Andrews turned on it for a homer to
left field that tied the game 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   Another single to Damon Buford, and Ligtenberg had to put the
game in the hands of 21-year-old Luis Rivera, who gave up the
winning single to Jeff Reed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main problem was walking the leadoff batter,'' said
Ligtenberg, who walked Glenallen Hill after Mike Remlinger had
walked Mark Grace to start the ninth. ``That started the whole
thing. ... I didn't make the pitches I needed to make. I wanted
(the slider) to be out more.''
</P>
<P>
   For Rivera, the trip to the mound was his first with a game in
the balance. Joe Girardi sacrificed the winning run into scoring
position for Reed, who timed Rivera's fastball for a single down
the left field line, this after missing it badly twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to stick with my best pitch,'' Rivera said. ``He beat
me, so that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga's road back from cancer took a turn on Waveland
Avenue, where he deposited a Jon Lieber fastball for his fourth
home run of the season and a 3-0 lead for Kevin Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   But by the ninth, it was all for naught.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who won each of their first two series against the
Rockies and Giants, will have to take two in a row from the Cubs on
Wednesday and Thursday to see that streak continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kerry hung a slider and boom, out,'' said Bobby Cox, summing
up the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones blamed it on a shrinking strike zone from home
plate umpire Larry Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was you had a tea cup-sized strike zone,'' Jones
said. ``There weren't any walks all game and all of a sudden it's a
different game. It's a fluke. It's a shame because we played hard
and Millwood pitched his butt off.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
