<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2777 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-VICENTE-AZR &LR;      04-10 1849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICENTE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE VICENTE FOX IS SHAKING UP MEXICO'S PRESIDENTIAL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM QUINONES  
   
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MIGHT HAVE MISSED IT. First
``n'' in SAM QUINONES takes a TILDE; Moving in the ``A'' and ``K''
categories)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JIQUILPAN, Mexico _ Nearly 500 students exploded in cheers as
the tall presidential candidate in the light blue shirt arrived at
the Instituto Tecnologico de Jiquilpan in this town in the central
state of Michoacan.
</P>
<P>
   The students had been waiting for 90 minutes in the sun, but
their enthusiasm was undimmed. Vi-cen-te! Vi-cen-te! they chanted.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox broke into a wide grin, put on a school T-shirt,
then took the microphone in his hand and held it to his face like a
rock star.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of improving education, of `bringing this country up to
date` and moving it into the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Then, midway through his 20-minute speech, the candidate turned
confrontational. He asked the students to ``help build a tomb for
Little Cuauhtemoc.'' The crowd laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was referring to Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the presidential
contender of a center-left coalition who had once governed
Michoacan. Cardenas' father, Lazaro who ruled Mexico in the 1920s
and is widely considered the country's best-loved president, was
born in Jiquilpan.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's swipe at the Cardenas legacy was so incendiary that it
made national news. The remark was pure Fox, a bit of the blunt
style that has made the candidate the most controversial politician
in Mexico these days.
</P>
<P>
   On July 2, Mexico will hold its most competitive presidential
election in itshistory. The overriding issue facing voters is
whether to oust the Institutiona Revolutionary Party (PRI), which
has ruled Mexico for 71 years, making the nation the world's
longest-running one-party regime. The election is Mexico's version
of Berlin in 1989, or Chile's plebiscite on Augusto Pinochet in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, the candidate from the center-right National Action Party
(PAN), has thebest chance of doing that, analysts and opinion polls
suggest. After trailing b as many as 10 percentage points in polls
earlier this year, some polls show Fox now virtually tied with PRI
candidate Francisco Labastida. Others show him trailing by about 7
points.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, who many Mexicans believe lost a 1988 presidential bid
to the PRI candidate through widespread fraud, consistently places
a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   As Mexico breaks from decades of undisputed PRI rule, other
parts of Mexican society are becoming active. Grass-roots,
neighborhood and environmental groups the news media, the church
and the business elite are taking on social and political roles
that they once left to the massive PRI regime.
</P>
<P>
   For many Mexicans, Fox, who turns 58 on Election Day,
personifies this unpolished, non-governmental Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A rancher and former president of Coca-Cola de Mexico, he comes
from both therural and cosmopolitan sides of the country. His stump
speech focuses on helpin small businesses. As Guanajuato's
governor, he set up a micro-banking system primarily to serve poor
women that now has 40,000 clients and has been copied in other
states. He wears a suit and tie on occasion but usually sports an
open-collar blue shirt, cowboy boots and a large ``FOX'' belt
buckle. At 6 feet 6 inches, he usually stands a full head above his
crowd. He can speak Spanish like a farmer and English like a New
York banker. He is the grandson of an Irish immigrant; his father
was a Mexican rancher, and his mother was born in Spain. He is a
divorced Catholic and father of four adopted children. He advocates
secular education yet used a picture of the Virgin of Guadalupe in
his campaign until the country's election board told him to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he shows that the great myths of Mexican politics are
being discarded,'' says Jesus Silva-Herzog Marquez, a political
scientist at the ITAM, a private university in Mexico City. These
include ``the anti-entrepreneurial myth, in which being a
successful entrepreneur within Mexican politics was shameful, and
there was no bridge between politics and the business world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox has taken on these subjects and this hasn't created any
problems,'' Silva-Herzog says.
</P>
<P>
   On a stop with touring motorcyclists, the candidate rode a
Harley in a helmet and leather jacket _ a jarring sight for
Mexicans used to decades of staid politicians in business suits.
The stunt earned him the cover of the ``Proroceso'' newsweekly.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign speeches are often full of details of his
proposals, and at times he risks losing his audience. At a rally in
Pinos, Zacatecas, a small ranching town, Fox declared, ``I know
your dreams, of how many hopes you sow when you plant the ground,''
then launched a discourse on municipal reform, inflation reduction
and loan programs for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   About every week or two this year, Fox has uttered something to
shock the Mexican body politic. Last month, he bent back the index
finger of his ictory ``V,'' to leave the erect middle finger,
telling a crowd that it was Labastida's sign. To Protestant
ministers in January, he drew parallels between the Catholic Church
and the PRI, making the point that both had held a monopoly on
power in Mexico. In February, he called Labastida a mariqueta (a
sissy) and an ``electoral pirate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is used to a very velveted way of political speaking,''
says Silva-Herzog. ``Socially, we use this very roundabout way of
speaking. This tone is what the politician uses who speaks very
sweetly, who uses many ambiguous references. It's a tone that I
think now expresses the distance between politicians and Mexican
society. (Fox's style) confirms him as the representative of a
different way of doing politics.''
</P>
<P>
   That style appears to alienate some of those whose support Fox
will need to win. The same polls that show him inching closer to
Labastida also show that half of the voters consider Fox
``impulsive,'' hardly a good thing for a politician in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Edna Jaime, a political scientist at the Mexico City think tank
CIDAC, says that often his style clashes with Mexicans' highly
conservative approach to politics. Polls and recent elections have
shown that Mexicans ``want ch ange, but they don't want to run any
risk,'' Jaime says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally contradictory. They want change, but they're not
willing to run the most minimal risk,'' she adds. ``So Vicente Fox
needs to sell a message of certainty. But he's not doing that
because he's very volatile in his words and actions. He's not
generating certainties.
</P>
<P>
   `In spite of that, he's got at least 32 percent of the vote,
according to his lowest poll numbers, and others show him with
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Fox style has proven attractive in a country used to
silver-tongued politicians who never say what they mean, says
Carlos Castillo Peraza, a former National Action Party president
and now a newspaper columnist.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think it's reached its limit,'' Castillo Peraza says.
``Now he's got to make a strong effort to present himself as a
statesman.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's plain speaking, more characteristic of entrepreneurs than
politi cians, is a sign that he came to politics from business. Fox
worked his way up from the bottom at Coca-Cola de Mexico. In 1974,
at age 32, Fox was made president of the company for Mexico and
Central America. Five years later, he was to be promoted to
director of Coca-Cola for Latin America. But because he didn't want
an international career, he resigned to return home to Guanajuato
to help manage his family's ranch and boot business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Manuel Clouthier was the PAN's candidate for president.
Clouthier was a businessman and attracted many other formerly
apolitical businessmen to the party. These neopanistas, as they're
known, energized the party. They have since become governors and
mayors and pushed the party from a sleepy bastion of bluebloods and
far-right ideologues into a more centrist and pragmatic
institution. Fox was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, at Clouthier's urging, he ran for Congress and won. In
1991, he ran for governor of Guanajuato and lost. However, the
election was rife with fraud. Civic protest forced the victorious
PRI candidate to vacate his seat in favor of a negotiated third
candidate from the PAN. In 1995, Fox ran again for g overnor and
won.
</P>
<P>
   For the next few years, he was mentioned often as a likely
presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no one was expecting it when, in 1998, he changed Mexican
politics by announcing he was running for president. This was two
years before the election.
</P>
<P>
   For Mexico, it was a radical precedent. It upset the
usually-staid PAN, which was used to a certain decorum; no one had
ever announced so early. He eventually scared away all other
potential candidates and won the party's nomination unopposed.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI also was forced to change. Soon its members were
announcing that they too were running. This was unheard of in a
party where rivals humbly held their tongues awaiting the
president's decision, only weeks before the filing deadline, as to
who would be the candidate. The PRI made a virtue of ne cessity,
held a presidential primary in November and heralded it as a sign
that the party was now democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He established a new electoral calendar,'' Castillo Peraza
said. ``For the first time in its history, the PAN had only one
candidate. But this took an argument away from the PAN, the
argument that the PRI isn't democratic. It made it easy for the PRI
to say they were the democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, his reputation as an outsider and a doer
while governor of Guanajuato has given the PAN an opening to voters
it never had before: the small farmers, the urban poor and the
young who once supported Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cardenas doesn't convince us anymore,'' said Ricardo Anaya, a
23-year-old industrial-engineering student in Jiquilpan. ``He's
lost twice before. Fox is the candidate who pays attention to young
people.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after the school stop in Jiquilpan, Fox was speaking
in the impoverished Indian village of Tarecuato, where people speak
their native Purepecha as much as Spanish. No National Action Party
candidate had ever held a rally in Tarecuato, villagers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Mexico that isn't heard,'' he boomed across a
plaza half-filled with shoeless boys with rotting teeth, grizzled
men in white cowboy hats and wrinkled old women in blue shawls.
``I'm not a politician. I was born on a ranch and worked all my
life, just like you.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that the PRI's 40 percent hard-core vote is largely
rooted in such poor rural communities. And political observers say
that grabbing a piece of that vote will be necessary, though
extremely difficult, for Fox to win the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're at a disadvantage,'' Fox said. ``We know among
the poorest people is where the PRI has its controlled reserve of
votes. The job is to keep working in those places. That's what
we're doing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
