<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-LAND-ART-580     04-10 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-LAND-ART-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE PEASANTS PROTEST SLOW PACE OF LAND REFORM
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEGUTU, Zimbabwe _ The black peasants stormed onto the white
farmer's land in March, demanding a chunk of the rustling fields of
tobacco and sweet corn, emboldened by President Robert Mugabe, who
blames the farmers for the slow pace of land redistribution.
</P>
<P>
   The squatters settled in, not realizing that Mugabe had already
tried and failed to seize the 4,000-acre farm, along with 1,400
other properties. He backed down when the owners protested and the
government found itself short of cash and unable to meet legal
deadlines. The government's actions, in 1997, were not reported in
the state-controlled newspaper, which applauds the squatters who
have invaded more than 900 farms.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in Mugabe's private and public postures is
telling. He talks tough, but takes a pragmatic approach, even a
conservative tack, in acquiring white-owned land, a close look at
his record shows. The issue of land reform is a central one in
Zimbabwe, where whites own more than half the fertile farms,
including 2 million acres of fallow land that Western donors say
could be better used by peasant farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated threats over 20 years, and a bitter campaign
for a constitutional amendment on the issue, the government has
never seized any property without paying for it, land experts and
commercial farmers say. In fact it has rarely used a tough law that
lets it delay payments up to five years; instead it has paid up
front. And when Mugabe's government has run short of cash,
officials have decided to slow the pace of redistribution.
</P>
<P>
   In March, while the government was boasting that it was about to
redistribute half of the country's white-owned commercial farmland,
officials were privately refusing to accept an available property
for sale. The government could not afford it, its lawyers admitted.
</P>
<P>
   The government's stance is surreal, said Rogier van den Brink,
an economist who represents the World Bank in Harare, the capital,
and who supports land distribution and praises the government's
respect of property rights. ``Despite all the talk and all the
threatening, on the ground the government has always followed the
law,'' he said, ``it hasn't taken any title deed for which it
hasn't paid cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Parliament approved a constitutional amendment early in April to
let the government seize land without compensation, but experts
like van den Brink doubt that even that will result in a spate of
land confiscation. For one thing, the government lacks the
administrative capacity to process many land transfers quickly. And
experts say the amendment is meant mainly to goad Western donors to
provide the money they pledged in 1998 for redistribution of almost
500,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   The government also wants to appease rural constituents ahead of
national elections in May.
</P>
<P>
   In the heady days after independence two decades ago, Mugabe
promised a sweeping land reform. The initial plan was to resettle
162,000 black families on good land by the mid-1990s. But less than
half that number have actually been resettled. Land redistribution,
primarily financed by Britain, slowed considerably in the 1990s
when the government began offering long-term leases to the black
political elite, a development that made donors back away from the
program.
</P>
<P>
   White farmers stopped identifying underused land for purchase.
And as the economy unraveled, land reform sank in the government's
list of priorities, at least in private.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One elderly farmer, Alf Jackson, sued the ministry to try to
force the government to take his 4,700-acre farm, which it had
agreed to buy for $486,000. When officials tried to back out of the
deal, he sued, and in 1999, the Supreme Court ordered the
government to buy the land.
</P>
<P>
   But in March, even as Mugabe was blaming whites for blocking
land reform, his lawyers were sheepishly acknowledging they could
not afford Jackson's farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the calculation has been that they have to promise
high and deliver what is practical'' to the rural people eager for
good land, said Sam Moyo, who runs the Southern African Regional
Institute for Policy Studies in Harare. But he added: ``They're not
prepared to go to war to take land. They don't really believe in
destroying property rights.''
</P>
<P>
   And there have been hopeful signs about the program in the
future. Britain has agreed to discuss financing the government's
program. Mugabe, in turn, agreed to turn over to the poor some land
that had been given to officials.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe has praised the squatters, disregarding the international
outcry and a local court order requiring their eviction. For their
part, officials at the Commercial Farmer Union, which represents
the white farmers, emphasize that the squatters have been
overwhelmingly peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers are going to court to see that squatters are told to
go home soon. The government is opposed to such a court order, on
the ground that it could cause violence.
</P>
<P>
   And meanwhile, at the farm in Chegutu, the invaders and the
invaded maintain a peaceful detente. The farmer, Jackie de Wet,
provides drinking water. In return, the landless men and women
promise to sleep in the grass, away from the house, where his
mother lives.
</P>
<P>
   The squatters are jobless young men, mothers who struggle to
feed their children, fathers who can no longer afford a bus ride to
town for a bag of corn meal. They build grass huts outside the
metal fence and are living on roasted ears of corn.
</P>
<P>
   De Wet says he sympathizes with their plight. ``These guys are
being used by the government as pawns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And despite Mugabe's claim that blacks are ready to battle
whites for the soil, the squatters here say they have no intention
of fighting or harming de Wet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to work with him,'' explained Japfumaneyi Masuko, 43,
who is hoping for a sliver of his fallow farmland. ``We want to
share.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
