u a BC-PULITZER-PRIZES-1STLD     04-10 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULITZER-PRIZES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULITZERS TO IMMIGRANT NOVELIST, HISTORIAN, WASHINGTON POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite and expand by 180 words.)  
(See also PULITZER-PRIZE-HIGHLIGHTS) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jhumpa Lahiri, a 33-year-old immigrant born in London and raised
in New England, won the Pulitzer Prize for fiction Monday for her
first book, a collection of stories evoking the isolation and
disconnection of South Asian immigrants in America.
</P>
<P>
   Lahiri, who won for ``Interpreter of Maladies'' (Mariner
Books/Houghton Mifflin), was the second immigrant author to win a
national fiction award in five months; in November, Ha Jin, a
Pulitzer finalist from China, won a National Book Award for his
novel ``Waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   A work of Asian history, John W. Dower's ``Embracing Defeat:
Japan in the Wake of World War II'' (W.W. Norton), won the Pulitzer
Prize for nonfiction. This comprehensive portrait of modern Japan
by Dower, a professor of history at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, also won a National Book Award.
</P>
<P>
   The journalism awards were dominated by The Washington Post,
which won three prizes, including the public service award, and The
Wall Street Journal, which won prizes for the ``Potomac Watch''
columns of Paul A. Gigot and for its staff's coverage of U.S.
defense spending in the post-Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
   The Village Voice, a free New York City weekly, won the prize
for international reporting for Mark Schoofs' series on AIDS in
Africa, which Schoofs called a ``catastrophe that is transforming
the continent forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press, its writers Sang-Hun Choe, Charles J.
Hanley and Martha Mendoza, and its researcher, Randy Herschaft, won
the investigative reporting award for piecing together, more than
45 years later, details of an American massacre of civilians during
the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   The Post won the public service award for its coverage of the
abuse and neglect of the mentally retarded in group homes in the
District of Columbia, in a series spearheaded by Katherine Boo.
Henry Allen of The Post won the award for criticism for his ``fresh
and authoritative'' writing on photography. And Carol Guzy, Michael
Williamson and Lucian Perkins won the feature photography award for
coverage of Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The Post's photography award was the only prize given for
coverage of the Kosovo conflict, which was one of the biggest
events of 1999. But the coverage of the wrenching mass shooting at
Colorado's Columbine High School brought Denver's daily newspapers
two awards.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Post won the award for breaking news for its ``clear
and balanced'' coverage of the student massacre. The Rocky Mountain
News photography staff won for breaking news photography for its
``emotional images.''
</P>
<P>
   George Dohrmann of the St. Paul (Minn.) Pioneer Press, whose
reporting on widespread academic fraud in the men's basketball
program at the University of Minnesota provoked local outrage, won
for beat reporting.
</P>
<P>
   The prize for explanatory reporting was awarded to Eric Newhouse
of The Great Falls Tribune in Montana for his examination of
alcoholism and its consequences. J.R. Moehringer of The Los Angeles
Times won for feature writing, and Joel Pett of The Lexington
Herald-Leader in Kentucky won for editorial cartooning.
</P>
<P>
   The whiff of controversy that sometimes accompanies the awards
process was absent this year, but there were echoes of controversy
in other quarters _ particularly within The Associated Press, which
labored for months over the Korean massacre account. The delay in
getting the story out, coming in the months after CNN retracted its
controversial ``Tailwind'' report, angered the reporters involved,
but the editors defended it as simple and appropriate thoroughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance of the story and the strength of our
reporting left no doubt in our minds that our story would
eventually get out,'' Hanley said. He added, ``The delay that did
occur was largely unwarranted, in the view of the journalists
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Wolman, the AP's managing editor, said, ``We are extremely
proud of the editorial process that produced such a meticulous and
valuable piece of work.''
</P>
<P>
   The editorial writing award was given to John C. Bersia of The
Orlando (Fla.) Sentinel, for his campaign against predatory lending
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The Pulitzer Prize for drama was awarded to the playwright
Donald Margulies, who teaches play writing and screenwriting at
Yale University, for ``Dinner with Friends,'' a tragicomedy about
the vicissitudes of marriage in middle age. The award for biography
was given to Stacy Schiff for ``Vera (Mrs. Vladimir Nabokov)''
(Random House).
</P>
<P>
   The prize for a work of American history was awarded to David M.
Kennedy, a Stanford University history professor, for his book
``Freedom From Fear: The American People in Depression and War,
1929-1945'' (Oxford University Press).
</P>
<P>
   ``Repair'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux), a collection of verse by
C.K. Williams, was awarded the prize for poetry. The prize in music
was awarded to ``Life is a Dream, Opera in Three Acts: Act II,
Concert Version'' by Lewis Spratlan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
