<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2792 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DISABLED-STUDENTS-NYT     04-10 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-STUDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISABLED STUDENT IS SUING OVER TEST-SCORE LABELING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., spelling vonMayrhauser is CQ) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Breimhorst cannot take tests the way other students do: He
has no hands.
</P>
<P>
   So when he was applying to business schools in 1998, Breimhorst
received permission from the Educational Testing Service to take
the Graduate Management Admissions Test on a computer with a
trackball, and was given 25 percent more time to accommodate his
disability.
</P>
<P>
   Under the longstanding policy of the testing service, his
results were mailed out with the notation, ``Scores Obtained Under
Special Conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Breimhorst, a 29-year-old graduate of Stanford University, was
not admitted to business school. Now, in a federal lawsuit that
could affect hundreds of thousands of students with disabilities,
he is challenging the way the testing service flags the scores of
students who use accommodations to take the exams. The lawsuit
asserts that such flagging is a kind of scarlet letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a suspicion that their scores are less valid than
others, stigmatizing students with disabilities in exactly the way
the Americans with Disabilities Act is supposed to prevent,'' said
Josh Konecky, the lawyer for Disability Rights Advocates, the
nonprofit law group in Oakland, Calif., that represents Breimhorst.
``It's a national problem that people in the disability community
have talked about for years.''
</P>
<P>
   In its materials, the testing service explains that the
special-conditions notation is there because ``when standardized
tests such as the GMAT are taken under nonstandard conditions, the
scores may not accurately reflect the test-taker's educational
ability.''
</P>
<P>
   And the testing service says it has an obligation to flag the
scores so that school admissions offices will not be misled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's educationally valid to tell those who rely on
our reports that the scores were not achieved under standard
conditions,'' said Stan vonMayrhauser, the general counsel at the
testing service. ``We've thought about what feels right, we're
comfortable with what we're doing, and we feel confident that
reporting the true facts of how a test was taken is not illegal or
discriminatory.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has issued little guidance on when it is
acceptable to flag test scores, leaving the legal issue murky.
</P>
<P>
   ``People argue persuasively on both sides,'' said Robert
Schaeffer, the public education director of FairTest, a Cambridge,
Mass., organization that is critical of standardized testing
practices. ``On one hand, it appears to be true that scores on
time-extended tests are not equivalent to those taken without
accommodations. On the other side, it is an absolute red flag, and
college admissions people admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue has become more pressing as the number of requests for
accommodations increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are going up for two reasons,'' said Diana Pullin,
an education law professor at Boston College. ``More people with
physical disabilities are surviving and gaining access to higher
education, and more people with learning disabilities are
exercising their rights. And with the trend toward more high-stakes
testing, I think we'll see a lot more litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The testing service grants, and flags, thousands of
accommodations each year on the SAT, the Graduate Management
Admissions Test, the Graduate Records Exam and dozens of other
tests. On the SAT's alone, more than 24,000 students had some kind
of accommodation last year, ranging from blind students taking the
test in Braille to easily distracted students allowed to take the
test in a separate room.
</P>
<P>
   The largest, fastest-growing and most controversial group of
disabled students _ almost 9 out of 10 of those receiving
accommodations _ are those with attention deficit disorder or
learning disabilities like dyslexia.
</P>
<P>
   Many testing experts say it is difficult to know precisely what
accommodations they should give people with disabilities: What will
level the playing field and not give them an advantage?
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters further is the increasing awareness that
accommodations for learning disabilities are sought less frequently
by poor black or Hispanic students than by white children from
affluent schools.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the accommodations granted _ for physical or learning
disabilities _ involve extended time.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to defuse the issue, many experts suggest, would
be to make all tests untimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can make a decision that a test doesn't have to be
timed, you can eliminate most of the requests for accommodations,
and the problem goes away,'' Pullin said.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer of FairTest said that untimed tests tended to raise
everyone's scores _ and give an edge to female test-takers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the College Board, which sponsors the SAT, only
about 2 percent of those who receive accommodations on the SAT do
not get extended time, perhaps just using a large-type version of
the test, or having a separate room in which to take it. The
testing service does not flag those scores, the board said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we stopped flagging those results based on research
in the 1980s suggesting that accommodations that did not involve
extended time did not affect the validity of the scores,'' said
vonMayrhauser.
</P>
<P>
   Breimhorst's lawsuit charges that the testing service has no
evidence for concluding that the scores of disabled people who
receive accommodations are less reliable or valid than the scores
of those who take the test without accommodations. The service's
flagging policy, the complaint says, makes the scores of disabled
people less valuable than those of others, and violates the
Americans With Disabilities Act and the Rehabilitation Act.
</P>
<P>
   Two advocacy groups, the International Dyslexia Association and
Californians for Disability Rights, are also plaintiffs in
Breimhorst's suit, filed last summer in federal district court in
the Northern District of California.
</P>
<P>
   The testing service sought to have the case dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   But on March 27, Judge William Orrick refused the request,
writing that the federal laws ``require the test provider to take
steps to best ensure that the tests equally measure the skills of
disabled and nondisabled test takers.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the judge said, ``If test providers meet this
burden, then there would be no reason to flag the test results of
disabled test takers who receive accommodations.''
</P>
<P>
   VonMayrhauser said he read the opinion to mean that flagging
would be legally unacceptable only if disabled and nondisabled
test-takers got the same results on exams.
</P>
<P>
   But Konecky and other lawyers for the disabled read the opinion
to mean that the test service has a responsibility to see that its
tests are as valid for those with disabilities as for others, and
if both groups can be assessed equally well, flagging should not be
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The case is not expected to go to trial until next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
