<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     04-10 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NEIGHBORS PRAISE YANK FROM YAKIMA 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Out in the Lower Yakima Valley of Washington state, they grow
asparagus and sweet corn and luscious yellow cherries and apples,
particularly apples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody wants us to call ourselves the Big Apple,'' the Rev.
Dave Edler, pastor of the Yakima Foursquare Church and a former
major leaguer, dryly informed a New Yorker Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Yakima is not especially tiny at 55,000, but it is
small enough for people to keep tabs on their own, to see if
success or money has changed them. The word on Mel Stottlemyre is
unanimous. ``Very modest guy, modest life style,'' Judge Michael
Schwab of Superior Court in Yakima County said. ``He went off as
one of us, and he has done us proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre grew up in Mabton _ ``A one-stoplight town, and
probably a blinking light, at that,'' Edler noted _ but he played
for Yakima Community College, and he once owned a sporting goods
store and a baseball camp in town. There is also a baseball field
named after his youngest son, Jason, who died of leukemia in 1981
at the age of 11.
</P>
<P>
   Now Yakima is worrying about its local hero, the Yankees'
pitching coach, who announced on Sunday that he is suffering from
multiple myeloma, cancer of the bone marrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the topic of the morning,'' said Mel Moore,
Stottlemyre's friend and former business partner, who attended
Monday's weekly meeting of the Monday Morning Quarterbacks, who
give money and awards to young athletes in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The Monday Morning Quarterbacks know the heart and soul of the
Yankee from Yakima. ``He's respected not only for what he's
accomplished but for what he stands for,'' Moore said. ``He doesn't
talk a lot, but when he does, people listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore recalled the time, more than 20 years ago, when the Little
League team with Mel Jr. and Todd Stottlemyre, two future major
leaguers, clubbed an opposing team by a score that may have been as
lopsided as 30-0. Some parents felt it was unfair to run up a score
like that, and the father did more than just agree. ``Mel
recommended an all-bat rule,'' Moore recalled. ``The entire roster
had to bat around, even if there were 14 of them.''
</P>
<P>
   That local rule kept the two Stottlemyre boys from batting every
inning, but it was the right thing to do, and that is what Mel
Stottlemyre is known for in his hometown _ and in the major
leagues, too.
</P>
<P>
   At the Yankees' delayed home opener Wednesday, Stottlemyre will
be back monitoring the pitchers from the dugout following a day of
treatment for this very serious intruder.
</P>
<P>
   His illness is the latest touch of sadness in a stadium that has
seen too many heroes die young _ from Gehrig to Ruth to Munson to
Howard to Martin to Mantle to Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Stadium has been home for much of Stottlemyre's career.
He pitched there, he coached there, and once he legged out an
inside-the-park grand slam there, one of the most thrilling sights
in baseball, particularly for a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Usually this son of the Northwest let his sinkerball confound
the Yastrzemskis and the Kalines, and let the excitement come from
the flamboyant types like Mantle and Ford and Pepitone.
Pronouncements were not his style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tall and strong and quiet,'' Schwab said Monday. ``Not a
braggart.'' People in Yakima recall how Stottlemyre worked as a
roving instructor for the Seattle Mariners so he could stay close
to Jason. ``That little boy was in spring training with the
Mariners, and everybody would rush to play catch with him,'' said
Edler, the minister, who played parts of four seasons with the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us hurt when Jason died,'' Edler said Monday. ``Now,
for us to know the news, to hear that he's walking into this
adversity, it's hard to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home, the friends are creating a circle of love around the
family. ``We'll definitely get people praying for him,'' Edler
said. ``People will be amazed to see him handle this.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre has talked up the word ``cure'' rather than
``treatment,'' and has helped to advance the cause. He and his
wife, Jean, received the National Recognition Award from the
Leukemia Society of America in 1992, and Todd, now with the Arizona
Diamondbacks, has donated $1 million to leukemia research. Todd
once said that he thinks about Jason every single day. On Sunday,
Todd wanted to leave his club to be with his father, but the father
reminded him that he had an obligation to his team. You do your
job, and you don't make a fuss. That is the man they know at the
Monday Morning Quarterbacks _ Mel Stottlemyre from Mabton in the
Lower Yakima Valley. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
