<HEADLINE>
MIAMI'S HOLD ON ELIAN APPEARS TO BE LOOSENING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI) 
 By RICK BRAFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Cuban Americans in Miami seemed to concede on Monday
that they have lost the battle to keep Elian Gonzalez in the United
States, as Justice Department officials prepared to present the
child's Miami relatives with a letter instructing them on when and
how he should be handed over to federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Joe Carollo of Miami said on Monday that he planned to go
to Washington to ask Attorney General Janet Reno Reno for a 30-day
transition period to minimize the trauma to Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a flurry of last-minute appeals by South Florida
politicians, Justice Department officials said the instructions on
the surrender of the boy would probably be presented to the Miami
family sometime on Tuesday, and that Elian would be handed over to
federal officials on Wednesday or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The letter is the first step in the removal of the boy from his
great-uncle's house in Little Havana and a reunification with his
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who awaits Elian at a Cuban
diplomat's house outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials are expected to ask family members to take the
boy to a neutral site so that he can be handed over without
incident.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Cuban exile leaders, once defiant, seemed resigned,
although they were not guaranteeing that such a transfer could be
made without a confrontation of some kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fought the battle,'' said Ramon Saul Sanchez, who has
led the protest outside the home where the boy has lived with his
great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, and other relatives since being
rescued at sea in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Elian is going to remember is that these people here did
not betray him,'' and worked hard to try and keep him here, Sanchez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo and his counterpart, Mayor Alex Penelas of Miami-Dade,
were expected to fly to Washington on Monday to meet with Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Both mayors have said they want the boy to stay, and drew
criticism from around the nation when they said their officers
would not assist federal officials in removing the boy from the
home. On Monday, as Carollo outlined the goal of his meeting with
Reno, it was clear the emphasis had changed
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to ask her to be fair and make sure this process is
done gradually, away from the arms and the strong hands of the
Castro security apparatus,'' Carollo was quoted as telling The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Although Elian's removal from the house is expected to be
completed this week, lawyers for the family filed papers in an
appeal of a federal judge's ruling in March that upheld Reno's
authority in the custody case. The appeal is to be heard at the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Atlanta, on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   In another last-minute legal proceeding, a Miami-Dade County
circuit judge ordered lawyers for the family to file a brief by
Tuesday that would explain why a state court should hear the case
at all.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge, Jennifer Bailey, did not offer much hope for a
state court intervention in the case, saying that the lawyers had
presented no evidence that the boy would be in danger if he was
returned to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also said she did not see how any ruling by her would
overrule the federal court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, after refusing for four months to hand the boy over
to federal officials so he could be returned to his father, Lazaro
Gonzalez met with government-appointed psychiatrists and
psychologists to discuss the least traumatic way of handing over
the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service officials, who declined
to comment on what was said in that meeting, agreed to change the
site from Jackson Memorial Hospital near downtown Miami to Mercy
Hospital in Coconut Grove, where Gonzalez's 21-year-old daughter,
Marisleysis Gonzalez, is recovering from stress and exhaustion
related to the custody battle over Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez had apparently wanted his daughter, who is close to
Elian, to be at that meeting, but she did not attend. Gonzalez kept
government officials waiting two hours as he insisted on changing
the site of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Cardona, an immigration spokeswoman, said it was ``another
instance of the government bending backwards'' to try and make the
removal of Elian as painless as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was not at the meeting, instead visiting Ms. Gonzalez in
her hospital room. She and Lazaro Gonzalez had wanted the
psychiatrists and psychologists to interview the boy, but
government officials refused.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Gonzalez house, when asked by reporters about the
seeming inevitability of the boy's return to his father,
demonstrators talked only about holding yet one more candlelight
vigil, instead of vowing a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will cope,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
</TEXT>
