<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-YOUTH-HOME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTABILITY OF RELIGION-BASED PROGRAMS IN DISPUTE IN TEXAS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Allegations of abuse and neglect involving a
Corpus Christi ministry for troubled youth may have delivered a
black eye to Texas faith-based programs that Gov. George W. Bush is
trying to use as a springboard in his Republican bid for president.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm on Monday said
the incidents raised questions about whether there is enough
accountability in Bush's faith-based programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even faith-based organizations must have accountability and
sufficient state oversight to ensure the health, safety and
well-being of the people who are receiving the services,'' Malcolm
said. ``If Bush insists on having a faith-based network with little
oversight and no accountability, we'll see more of these kinds of
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   A cornerstone of the faith-based programs Bush pushed through
the Legislature in 1997 was a system of alternative accreditation
for religious-based child-care facilities that believed submitting
to state licensing would endanger their religious distinctiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The first 24-hour child-care facilities to open under such
alternative accreditation last year were the Rebekah Home for Girls
and the Anchor Home for Boys, run by the People's Baptist Church
and Ministries in Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry was founded by the late Rev. Lester Roloff. Amid
allegations of child abuse, Roloff's two homes for troubled youth
were moved from Texas to Missouri in the mid-1980s and then later
closed rather than submit to state licensing.
</P>
<P>
   The Rebekah and Anchor homes reopened in Corpus Christi last
year after receiving alternative certification from the Texas
Association of Christian Child Care Agencies Inc., a private
organization created under the law signed by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Nueces County sheriff's deputies arrested Allen
Smith, the ministries superintendent, and accused him of unlawfully
restraining an 18-year-old man and a 17-year old boy.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Texas Department of Protective and Regulatory Services
last year issued a finding of possible abuse or neglect at the
ministries' Rebekah Home for Girls, a ruling that is now being
challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jones, a spokesman for Bush, said the governor wants the
cases fully investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any allegations of abuse should be taken seriously, and there
should be an aggressive and exhaustive investigation,'' Jones said.
``If any allegations are confirmed, PRS should take whatever steps
are necessary to protect the young people in those facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The allegations being investigated by the Nueces County
Sheriff's Department involve incidents at the Lighthouse Home for
Men, a facility for 18-to 25-year-olds that is not subject to state
licensing. The People's Baptist Church has five homes for troubled
individuals on its 500-acre grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Protective services spokeswoman Marla Sheely said the state
agency is investigating the Lighthouse incident because it involves
an individual who is age 17.
</P>
<P>
   Sheely said the agency also has investigated an allegation of
``abuse or neglect'' at the Rebekah home, but she declined to give
details because the matter is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest incident, the Corpus Christi Caller-Times reported
that the investigation began after Justin Simons, 18, told deputies
a church employee had punched him in the chest and that he had
sprained both ankles when forced to jump over a pit. Simons said he
also had his wrists tied with another resident and then the two
were forced to run through the woods while bound together.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Jones, a lawyer for Smith and the church, told the Houston
Chronicle his client will be exonerated because state law gives
custodial care facility employees the right to use force in certain
circumstances. Jones said the People's Baptist Church facilities
have been treated unfairly in the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press is making this look like a bunch of child abusers
out there, and they're not,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. David Blaser, a Dallas minister and head of the
alternative certification agency, also declined to discuss the
specifics, other than to say the state agency found no actual abuse
at the Rebekah home but issued a negative ``finding.'' Blaser said
the Christian child care association is challenging that ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't agree with that finding,'' Blaser said. ``We don't
like having that against one of our homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaser said the Corpus Christi facilities founded by Roloff are
the targets of unfair media criticism. He said the homes take the
most troubled youth who often have drug, drinking and emotional
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you deal with children who have problems, you're going to
have problems,'' Blaser said. ``The Roloff homes take the bottom of
the barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
