<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2799 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-MARINE-CRASH-TEX     04-10 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINE-CRASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS ARRIVE TO SEARCH FOR CAUSE OF FATAL TILT-ROTOR CRASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By CHRIS VAUGHN 
And BOB COX 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A team of Marine Corps and Navy investigators arrived in Arizona
on Monday at the site of the blackened debris of an MV-22 Osprey
aircraft to try to determine why 19 Marines died during a night
training exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines do not yet know what caused the accident Saturday
night near a civilian airport in Marana, Ariz., as they simulated
an evacuation of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   But Lt. Gen. Fred McCorkle, head of Marine Corps aviation, told
The Associated Press that he believes ``we'll have a pretty good
idea'' within a week.
</P>
<P>
   The accident was recorded on infrared tape by an F/A-18 fighter
that was overhead, Marine Capt. Aisha Bakkar-Poe said. The crew
chief of a second Osprey saw it nose into the ground, she said,
with no apparent sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Four V-22 tiltrotors, which are built jointly by Bell Helicopter
Textron in Fort Worth and the Boeing Co. in Ridley Township, Pa.,
remain in use by the Marines. But none are being flown as
investigators look for a cause. Bakkar-Poe also said the planes are
on the ground out of respect for other pilots and the families of
those killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a close-knit community of pilots,''
Bakkar-Poe said. ``And the emotional impact that this has had on
the service was significant enough, the commandant does not feel
it's appropriate for them to be flying.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash has again focused unflattering attention on the
safety, merits and costs of the Osprey, which can take off, land
and hover like a helicopter, then shift its propellers forward to
fly longer distances like a plane _ faster than helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the 15 finished Ospreys have crashed since 1991,
killing 26 people. Supporters and opponents said on Monday that the
program is in no real danger. But they said the outlook could
change, depending on whether the crash was the result of a
mechanical or structural failure, or human error in operating it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blow, not just because of the loss of life but because
they were pretty close to concluding their tests,'' said R.M.
Rausa, a retired Navy captain with the Association of Naval
Aviation.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the program has gone too far to be curtailed.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Marine Col. Terry Dugan, who wrote his thesis at the
Naval War College on the V-22 program, also said he doesn't believe
one mishap would slow the program significantly.
</P>
<P>
   But Dugan, now a commercial pilot who lives near Fort Worth, is
no fan of the program. He said he thinks the Marine Corps has
``mortgaged its future'' on the Osprey and would be better off
investing in less expensive conventional helicopters. He said he
also was troubled before Saturday's accident by the V-22's main
selling point: it's part helicopter, part plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition from forward flight to hover, no matter what
the gee-whiz technology is, is always a difficult transition,''
Dugan said. ``We proved that with the Harrier,'' the ``jump jet''
that also takes off and lands vertically. ``Going to hover from
forward flight is a dangerous time.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Kinneard, a spokesman for Boeing Helicopters in
Pennsylvania, declined to comment on reports that some of the
Marines had concerns about the V-22's readiness and reliability.
But he said the aircraft has undergone redesign and years of
testing to fix problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we've licked all of the major problems and most of the
minor ones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bakkar-Poe said the Marine Corps is confident in the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a proven aircraft,'' she said. ``The capabilities of this
aircraft increase our warfighting capabilities exponentially.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and Bell are 50-50 partners on development of the V-22,
which has spun off a similar civilian version. Boeing Helicopters
makes the fuselage and cockpit, and installs avionics and flight
control systems. Bell produces the wings, tail sections,
transmission, rotor systems and installs the engines.
</P>
<P>
   The Osprey that crashed was delivered to the Marines in December
and had logged more than 130 hours of flight time. Boeing and Bell
have offered their help in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their airplane,'' Kinneard said. ``They may call on some
of our Boeing and Bell expertise, but that's up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marines had hoped to complete their operational evaluations
by this summer so that full production could begin this fall. The
Marines are scheduled to buy 360 of the aircraft to replace their
30-plus-year-old CH-46 helicopters. The Air Force and the Navy have
said they plan to buy about 50 each.
</P>
<P>
   The Osprey program has many supporters in Congress, including
U.S. Rep. Kay Granger, R-Fort Worth, who said on Monday that the
V-22 remains a ``vital element'' for the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be watching the investigation closely, but believe the
V-22 still warrants congressional support as a leading-edge troop
transport and deployment aircraft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Retired Navy Rear Adm. Eugene Carroll Jr., vice president of
the Center for Defense Information, called the Osprey program ``a
mess that is at least eight years behind schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   The center is a think tank that advocates cost savings in the
military. He believes Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney was right in
recommending the Pentagon cancel the program in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll considers the cost _ which the Congressional Budget
Office put at $60 million apiece _ as far too much for a craft that
he considers susceptible to enemy fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are up against the wall, wondering what went wrong
this time,'' Carroll said. ``Even if it works like they say, and it
never has, the cost keeps going up and the taxpayers' are not
getting our money's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bill de Decker, from the helicopter sales company, Conklin &AMP;
de Decker Associates in Arlington, outside Fort Worth, was more
forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like anything mechanical, it's very complicated and
sometimes these things break,'' he said. ``I hope they get the
problems solved very quickly because, in my opinion, it's a very
fine aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Maria Recio contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2800 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-MARINE-PLANE-CRASH-1S     04-10 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINE-PLANE-CRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS FOUGHT HARD FOR HYBRID MARINE PLANE; MANY NOW WONDER WHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `Two test ...,' to CORRECT number of crewmen
killed in '92 crash to seven, sted nine.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The V-22 Osprey is a classic case of a military
program that would not be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The crash of an Osprey on Saturday night in Arizona, which
killed 19 Marines, came after years of arguments inside the
Pentagon against building the aircraft, and years of dogged efforts
by Congress to protect the $37 billion program.
</P>
<P>
   The military began flying the first five Ospreys six months ago
despite questions about the safety and cost of the hybrid aircraft,
designed to take off and land like a helicopter but cruise like an
airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Defense Department officials tried to cancel the program
11 years ago: too expensive, too experimental, they said. Congress
refused. For four years running, Pentagon officials fought
Congress, trying to stop the Osprey.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Navy Secretary Sean O'Keefe told the House Armed
Services Committee that the Pentagon would not spend $790 million
authorized by Congress to build three test aircraft. He said that
``the V-22 cannot be built to meet the requirements specified. It's
an engineering impossibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But Congress again defied the Defense Department, proclaiming
the aircraft to be a potential technological wonder before tests
had validated that claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology was a revolutionary concept that lit the
imagination of lawmakers, and the contractors fueled that fire,''
O'Keefe said in an interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Marine commanders wanted it badly. They had developed no other
alternative to replace the Vietnam-era Chinook helicopter, and they
argued that Marine missions could not be adequately served by even
the newest Army helicopter. Members of Congress said the V-22 had
great commercial potential. And the contracts represented hundreds
of high-tech jobs across the country. Key congressmen, some of them
ex-Marines, dug in their heels.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., the staunchest advocate of the V-22,
Monday dismissed criticism of the aircraft with a barnyard epithet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who would come out now and question the program, they
don't know what they're talking about,'' he said in an interview.
``If there is a technological problem, which I highly doubt, let's
look at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Two test aircraft crashed in the early '90s; one of those
accidents, in 1992, killed seven men. The design of the Osprey has
evolved throughout the decade to reflect lessons learned from those
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Cooper, a long-time military aviation expert at the
Congressional Research Service who retired last month, said two
crashes while testing an aircraft ``do not tell us anything'' about
the aircraft. They are to be expected in testing a new military
system like the Osprey, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It will take weeks or months to determine whether the crash on
Saturday was caused by a design defect, a manufacturing flaw or
human error.
</P>
<P>
   The Osprey's mission is to transport 20 to 24 fully armed
Marines, a larger number than can be carried by most military
helicopters, in and out of combat and on rescue missions. Marines
often ferry from ship to shore, and the corps argued for the Osprey
because it could fly farther and faster than a helicopter, but
still land in hot spots without the luxury of a runway.
</P>
<P>
   It has been in development for 18 years; its cost has grown
dramatically over time, partially due to the long fight over moving
the aircraft from the drawing board to the assembly line.
Government agencies outside the Pentagon place the cost today as
high as $60 million apiece. That raises doubts about its commercial
potential.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said Monday that it has not formally grounded the
Osprey, but the Marines will not fly the remaining four until they
understand what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident in the program because of the amount of
testing we've done and the number of hours we've flown it,'' said
Maj. Dave LaPan, a Marine Corps spokesman. ``We've really put this
aircraft through its paces.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Pentagon bowed to Congress and agreed to build
the aircraft, some of its officials, along with auditors from the
General Accounting Office, have warned that the Osprey's testing
was unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the accounting office reported that the aircraft's
major elements ``remain inadequate or untested.''
</P>
<P>
   That year, the Pentagon's inspector general said the aircraft
had gone into development ``without proper authorization'' and
without ``formal review'' _ the result, in part, of ``highly
unusual political factors.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Pentagon said the aircraft's prototypes could not
yet carry passengers or hover over unprepared landing zones. The
Defense Department also criticized the tests the aircraft was put
through as ``extremely artificial.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the GAO concluded that ``after 15 years of development
effort, the V-22 design has not been stabilized.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one ever developed an alternative aircraft. And its
potential, Marine commanders said, was too good to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft's prime contractors, the Boeing Co.'s helicopter
division, in Ridley Park, Pa., and Bell Helicopter Textron of Fort
Worth, Texas, carpeted Congress with data showing that the V-22
would work wonders _ and that parts of it would be built in 40
states.
</P>
<P>
   They persuaded a majority of members of Congress. And the
pressure from Congress to forge ahead never stopped. The supporters
included the most conservative Republicans and the most liberal
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   No one fought harder than Weldon, who represents the
Pennsylvania district that includes Boeing's helicopter division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a coalition that was broad and deep,'' Weldon said
Monday. ``We had the ex-Marines in Congress. We brought in the
retired Marine reserve officers' association. I brought in the
United Auto Workers and the civil aviation people.'' The latter
group promoted the idea that the aircraft had potential commercial
uses.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, the aviation expert, said, ``It does have range and
speed advantages. But is it worth it?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not, said O'Keefe, the former Navy Secretary, now a
professor of business and government at Syracuse University. The
futuristic technology may not mesh with its more mundane mission,
he said, ``It's a bus to bring 20 people from ship to shore.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``revolutionary concept'' of the Osprey entranced Congress,
but has proven hard to realize, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was within the realm of the believable,'' O'Keefe said.
``But all the work that was needed to be done, to this day, it
hasn't been accomplished. This was something that required a little
more than pressing the envelope of technology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
