<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NORTH-KOREA-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA OPENS ITS DOOR, JUST A CRACK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For anyone who has ever dreamed of going behind the Iron
Curtain, or at least what is left of it, Communist North Korea now
allows foreigners to visit its magnificent Kumgang Mountains, which
were closed to the outside world at the end of the Korean War 50
years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In February, the first non-Koreans began traveling to Mount
Kumgang National Park, just north of the demilitarized zone that
divides the Korean peninsula into North and South, on sightseeing
boat tours operated by the Hyundai Group, South Korean's biggest
conglomerate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai began offering the tours, at first only to South
Koreans, in late 1998. So far about 150,000 South Koreans and
several hundred foreigners, mainly Americans and Europeans, have
taken the four-day tour, the company said. This correspondent took
it in February. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Y.D. Hong, director of marketing and sales for Hyundai's cruise
division, said the tours provide a rare opportunity to peek inside
North Korea, which remains isolated under the hard-line rule of a
Stalinist government.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And a peek is all they get. Tourists have no freedom to wander
on their own, and little chance of meeting everyday North Koreans.
The trip's highlight is the excursions to the Kumgang Mountains _
Diamond Mountains _ which offer some of the most spectacular
natural scenery in Asia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After decades of isolation, the mountain range, which rises to a
height of 5,377 feet, is unspoiled, with stunning peaks, pristine
ponds and lakes, unusual rock formations and hundreds of cascading
waterfalls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the tour there are two all-day hiking trips, including
the Kuryong waterfalls, the Manmulsang region's craggy mountains
and valleys, and the Haegumgang region, where the Kumgang Mountains
meet the sea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the first hiking trip, tourists are taken to an
indoor-outdoor spa, which costs $12 to visit; after the second day,
they are taken to a riveting performance of the Pyongyang Moranbong
Circus for $25. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every day about 1,000 South Koreans visit the area, which
historically has been a place of reverence and reflection. For many
elderly South Koreans, who fled the Communist North before the
Korean War and still have relatives there, the Mount Kumgang trip
is an emotional homecoming. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best time to visit is between April and November, when there
is no snow on the trails and flowers are in bloom. Reservations
should be made at least a month in advance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because there are no accommodations for foreigners in the area,
the Hyundai cruise ships double as hotels, with restaurants,
discos, game rooms, swimming pools and shopping facilities on
board. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ships have international staffs, consisting mainly of
Filipino, Malaysian and Russian workers, most of whom spoke
English. But some of the South Korean mountain guides had
difficulty explaining things in English. Hong said that by the
start of the spring season, Hyundai plans to have guides who are
fluent in English, Japanese and Chinese. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hong recommends that foreign visitors arrive in Seoul at least
one day ahead of their scheduled trip, which is for four days and
three nights. Hyundai plans to offer shorter trips, for two or
three days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trip begins with a five-hour bus ride from Seoul to the
South Korean port of Tonghae, where tourists board a Hyundai cruise
ship for a 12-hour overnight voyage to the North Korean port of
Changjon, at the foot of the mountains. North Korea is very
protective of its coastline, so the cruise ship must first travel
to international waters and then double back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before going ashore, visitors, under the constant watch of the
North Korean military, are given a list of regulations. It is
forbidden to take photographs of any military installation or
personnel in North Korea. Doing so can result in the confiscation
of film, fines or detention.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While tourists have no contact with local residents, they are
permitted to speak with North Korean officials, especially
environmental guards and inspectors who monitor the mountain paths
_ and were friendly and eager to talk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tour package, which includes lodging, meals and transit,
costs from $700 for a standard room to $1,500 for a luxury suite
during the high season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a limited time, Hong said, Hyundai is offering a 20 percent
discount to non-Koreans who sign up for the tour this year. The
company hopes the tours will interest American veterans of the
Korean War, many of whom will be returning to South Korea this year
to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the conflict. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More information about the tour is available at
www.kumgangsantour.com, or by contacting Hong at hmm(at)hmm.co.kr,
or (82-2) 3706-5023 from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. Korean time (Korea is 13
hours ahead of Eastern time). Foreign tourists are required to
submit a reservation form, a copy of a valid passport and two color
photos. Payment may be made by credit card. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Hyundai is advertising that the Mount Kumgang tours are
open to all foreigners, Hong said that North Korea has not yet
granted permission for people of Japanese descent or Koreans who
are not residents of South Korea to enter the country. That means
that Japanese-Americans and Korean-Americans are ineligible for the
trip. But Hong said that the company expects to reach an agreement
with North Korea soon that will permit members of the two groups to
visit. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
