<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MAGAZINE-ADS-ART-2TAK     04-10 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-ADS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE THUD FACTOR -- THE FAVORITE SOUND OF HEAVYWEIGHT MAGAZINE
PUBLISHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos, NY24 and 25, have been sent to NYT photo clients.
A graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Clements, a magazine consultant, has a new idea
for a product: a special piece of luggage designed to carry big,
fat magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering how much these things weigh these days, it will be
indispensable,'' he said. ``Who can carry this stuff home?''
</P>
<P>
   Clements was joking, but just barely. After all, the magazines
he was referring to _ In Style, Vogue, Vanity Fair and W _ have all
in the last year blown past their records for size, heft and
length. They are part of a growing breed: the obese magazine,
publications so fat that if they were people, they might spend
their time in a high school auditorium sweating to the oldies with
Richard Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   Toss them on a desk, and you'll hear what publishers like to
refer to as ``the thud factor.'' (The louder the thud! thunk! or
boom! the better.) As the economy continues to thrive, some
magazines have become so fat with advertising that the editorial
content is sometimes relegated to the increasingly hard-to-find
nether reaches of the publication.
</P>
<P>
   These magazines are so packed with perfume-scented pages and
dot-com ads _ ranging upward to 1,200 pages a magazine, in extreme
cases _ that some are bigger than the Minneapolis/St. Paul
telephone book (988 pages). Because they are printed on heavy,
glossy paper, they weigh almost as much as a newborn baby. In
Modern Bride's February-March issue, the main editorial feature
section does not begin until page 871; by that point in a
19th-century Russian novel, the heroine most likely would have died
a tragic death chapters ago.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all magazines are so lucky. Just in the last
month, Time Inc.announced that it would stop publishing Life
magazine in May. Conde Nast, a subsidiary of Advance Publications,
shut down Details in the guise of a four-month publishing hiatus.
Both magazines had slimmed down to a foreboding, anemic flimsiness
_ relative to their fat cousins _ in their final months.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most successful magazines know that the good times will
not last forever. No one expects the advertising dollars to keep
flowing so generously from Internet businesses intent on
establishing their brand.
</P>
<P>
   But for now the magazines that are doing well have never had it
so good. This year, In Style broke its own record with 588 pages in
its April issue, Vanity Fair had a record 472 pages, Vogue's March
issue was 566 pages (not an all-time record, but a record for the
month), and W's March issue was 520 pages (W broke its all-time
record last March with 562 pages). While Bride's might send
affianced women across the country to the chiropractor _ this
spring, the February-March issue made it into the Guinness Book of
World Records as the largest magazine ever produced, at 1,271 pages
_ so might Modern Bride, with 1,062 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Internet business and technology magazines like Red Herring,
Business 2.0 and The Industry Standard are also breaking records.
Fortune broke its record with a 630-page issue that arrived on
newsstands last week. At The Industry Standard, a weekly,
advertising pages have grown by over 450 percent in the last year,
running 1,548 pages in 2000 through the middle of March. That
outpaces every other weekly magazine in the country, including
People, by a significant margin, according to Media Industry
Newsletter, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers bought $1.2 billion in consumer magazine advertising
for February, the last month for which complete figures are
available, according to the Magazine Publishers of America, a trade
association. That represents an increase of 15.4 percent over
February of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Circulation increases help magazines justify higher ad rates,
but the number of readers is often less important than who the
readers are and how badly the advertisers want to reach them.
According to the Publishers Information Bureau, Vogue's advertising
revenue is up by 32 percent for the first two months of 2000,
compared with the same period in 1999, to $21.9 million. But the
magazine's circulation was flat for the year ended Dec. 31, the
last period for which figures are available, according to the Audit
Bureau of Circulations.
</P>
<P>
   Samir Husni, a professor of media at the University of
Mississippi and a close observer of the magazine industry, said
that magazines have never been so physically huge. ``We used to
have fat issues in the early 1980s, but it was always just the
September issue of Vogue or Elle,'' he said. ``But now any issue of
Fast Co. or Business 2.0 or In Style is as big as those were.''
</P>
<P>
   But with every embarrassment of riches, there is worry.
Publishers lie awake at night worrying that consumers might get
annoyed at the advertising tonnage. Advertisers fret that their ad
might be lost in the vast commercial soup. With a five-pound beast
of a magazine rolling off the printing presses, there can be
problems at the printers, at the bindery, with the trucks, at the
newsstand, and even with the consumer, who some publishers fear
might not want to carry around a magazine that weighs as much as a
cinder block.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Walker, a consultant to the magazine industry, said that
magazines have become fatter for two reasons: First, the economy is
good and advertisers are eager to spread the wealth and, in the
case of new Internet companies, develop brand recognition with
consumers. Second, the most successful magazines are mostly niche
publications, not general-interest magazines, and there has been an
emphasis on targeting audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion and beauty magazines really are vertical,
special-interest publications, as are the dot.com magazines and the
bridal magazines,'' Walker said. ``So there is a significant amount
of endemic advertising. All the venture capital groups and all the
dot.com groups feel it is a requirement that they be in The
Industry Standard. Calvin Klein is required to be in Vogue and In
Style. But who's required to be in Time? No one. And that's why you
won't see a Time magazine this fat.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the general-interest weekly magazines are getting
chubby these days. The Dec. 5, 1999, issue of The New York Times
Magazine was 214 pages long, a record for recent years. Time
magazine's last issue of 1999 was 252 pages. But does anyone really
look at 1,180 pages of ads anyway? If magazine publishers are to be
believed, the answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is, does it turn off the reader?'' Walker
asked. ``Absolutely not. To a woman reading a bridal magazine, an
ad for a wedding gown is just as interesting as an editorial page
featuring a wedding gown. What's the difference between a Calvin
Klein ad in Vogue and a Calvin Klein editorial page? Absolutely
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard D. Beckman, the publisher of Vogue, said that the
advertising in the March and September issues, when readers are
thinking about new clothing purchases, ``is the strength of the
book _ readers shop the magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ad, the edit, it's all the same,'' said John Balen, the
associate marketing director of Modern Bride.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that readers might be turned off by a magazine's
weight and too many ads prompted Louis Cona, the publisher of In
Style, to survey 5,000 readers of the magazine recently. ``We were
concerned because we thought too much weight might affect the
pass-along readership,'' he said. (A high rate of pass-along
readership _ how many people see each copy _ helps boost
advertising rates.)
</P>
<P>
   Cona said that 66 percent of the respondents said that ``a thick
book makes the issue more valuable.'' And 87 percent said that the
weight of the magazine did not deter them from carrying it to
another place to read.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Yogi Berra's observation _ it's too crowded; nobody goes
there anymore _ holds true for advertisers: some shy away from the
fat magazines. Gene DeWitt, the chief executive of Optimedia
International (U.S.), an advertising services agency in New York,
said that if advertisers could not get highly trafficked pages in a
packed magazine, they might skip that issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the business category, we'll discuss Forbes, Fortune and
Business Week and advertisers will say, `Forget about Business
Week, it's too cluttered,''' he said. (Business Week's ad pages
have risen by 28 percent over last year.) ``And in some issues of
Vogue, if you can't get a good spot, you may say to yourself, `Why
would I want to be in there?' They won't drop the magazine
altogether, but a guaranteed position is required.''
</P>
<P>
   Does more advertising mean more articles? Not necessarily. Most
of the obese magazines stray from the norm for the average ratio of
advertising to editorial content, as measured by the Magazine
Publishers of America. The trade group reported last year that the
average ratio for American consumer magazines was 49.4 percent
advertising to 50.6 editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   Vanity Fair's March issue was 66 percent advertising; the
February/March Bride's _ with a whopping 1,180 pages of ads, said
Nina Lawrence, the publisher of Bride's _ was 93 percent
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Cona of In Style said that he is careful to monitor the ratio of
advertising to editorial pages, keeping it to an average of about
47 percent editorial to about 53 percent advertising. But the April
issue of In Style had 337 pages of advertising and 235 pages of
editorial content, or about 41 percent editorial to 59 percent
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The March issue of Vogue had 177 pages of editorial and 389
pages of advertising, or about 31 percent to 69 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All that advertising can complicate production. In Style has
grown so big in recent months, there have been delays in getting
the magazine to newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only bind 7,500 copies of In Style per hour, as
opposed to most magazines, where you can bind 11,000 copies per
hour,'' Cona said. ``As you slow down that process, you can have
delivery problems to wholesalers, which gets them out late on the
newsstand, which costs you sales.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of trucking the magazines has also risen. When In Style
was first published in 1995, 20 magazines fit into one bundle. Now,
only five do. Cona has had to hire extra drivers and trucks and has
also had to buy bigger, deeper newsstand racks _ but of course all
the cost is offset by the surging advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, there are worse problems to have in this world,'' Cona
said. ``As long as it thuds, it's good.'' He said that he is always
gratified when Don Logan, the chief executive of Time Inc., which
publishes In Style, calls to see the early copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He drops it on his desk and he listens,'' Cona said. ``And the
louder the thud, the happier he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
