<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2805 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-BOEING-BAE-SPI &LR;      04-10 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-BAE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS SAY MERGER OF BOEING AND BAE UNLIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. and BAE Systems, formerly known as
British Aerospace, will continue to court each other as they look
for joint business opportunities. But they are not headed to the
altar.
</P>
<P>
   That was the assessment Monday of aerospace analysts on both
sides of the Atlantic to a published report in a London paper over
the weekend that the two companies are in talks that could lead to
a $46 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   Such a marriage would dwarf Boeing's $14 billion merger with
McDonnell Douglas in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of reasons for these two companies to be
talking,'' said Jon Kutler president of Quarterdeck Investment
Partner, a Los Angeles-based firm that advises aerospace companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two leading companies in both aerospace and defense
so it is natural to have on-going discussions,'' Kutler said.
</P>
<P>
   But he discounted a possible merger, noting that such discussion
between companies are often misinterpreted ``in today's merger
crazy environment.''
</P>
<P>
   BAE Systems has a 20 percent stake in Boeing archrival Airbus
Industrie, which would greatly complicate any merger, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Europeans would not allow Boeing to own 20 percent of
Airbus,'' said Paul Nisbet of JSA Research.
</P>
<P>
   Without citing its sources, the Sunday Telegraph reported that
talks between Boeing and BAE Systems about a merger were
``intense'' earlier this year, though they have cooled slightly.
The paper quoted unnamed executives as saying the discussions are
not dead and will be resumed as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Another UK paper, the Sunday Times, reported in December that
the companies were discussing an ``alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   British Aerospace renamed itself last November after completing
an $11 billion merger with Marconi Electronic Systems to become the
world's second largest defense contractor behind Lockheed Martin.
Boeing, the world's largest aerospace company, is third among
defense giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based company already enjoys a long-standing
relationship with BAE Systems, which is a partner in Boeing's
Harrier and T-45 Goshawk military aircraft programs in St. Louis.
BAE Systems does subcontracting work for Boeing on some of its
commercial airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   And the two companies have been working closely in recent months
to strengthen ties in other areas.
</P>
<P>
   In a move to gain entry to Korea's $3 billion aerospace market,
Boeing and BAE Systems are expected to make a joint bid next month
for a 30 percent stake in Korean Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   BAE Systems has also worked closely with Boeing to help it win
an important competition that could be announced soon to supply the
UK with transport planes. Boeing is offering its giant C-17.
</P>
<P>
   While they would appear to be a good fit, especially on defense
programs, an outright merger is unlikely, industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised to see any formal combination of these
two companies in the near term,'' said Peter Jacobs, who follows
Boeing for Ragen MacKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' he added, ``I certainly would not discount
the possibility of stepped up efforts between the two companies in
targeting new markets or on their existing partnerships.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that Boeing already has ``a lot on the table''
with its recently announced $3.75 billion acquisition of the Hughes
satellite-making business.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Aboulafia, senior aviation analyst with the Teal Group,
an aerospace marketing research firm near Washington, D.C.,
described as ``extremely far fetched'' the idea of a merger between
Boeing and BAE Systems.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Airbus problem, he said, there is also the
issue of BAE Systems' involvement in the Eurofighter program.
</P>
<P>
   BAE Systems has a 37.5 percent share of the work to produce
Europe's top new fighter, the Typhoon.
</P>
<P>
   The jet will be a direct competitor to Boeing's F-18E/F Super
Hornet once Boeing gets the okay from the U.S. government to sell
its new fighter overseas, Aboulafia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eurofighter is core to BAE's business,'' he said. ``You don't
get any more core than that ... If Boeing were willing to drop (the
Super Hornet), then they could talk about a merger.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Navy wants more than 500 of the Boeing fighters, which
will soon enter full production with an initial $9 billion order
from the Pentagon for 222 Super Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   Aboulafia said Eurofighter is a much bigger obstacle to any
possible merger between Boeing and BAE Systems than is the British
company's stake in Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for BAE Systems said the report of possible merger
talks with Boeing is ``pure speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   A Boeing spokesman said the company does not discuss such
matters.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing did confirm another report that it is talking with
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries of Japan about greater cooperation
between the two companies. Alan Mulally, president of Boeing's
commercial airplanes unit, recently met with Mitsubishi's presdient
in Tokyo about cooperation in commercial aircraft and space-related
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi has been a Boeing subcontractor since 1969, and
Boeing is reportedly worried about a move by Airbus to establish
ties with the Japanese manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus has approached Mitsubishi about a possible role in
helping it develop the proposed Airbus A3XX super jumbo. Airbus
already buys some airplane parts from Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   BAE Systems makes wings for Airbus commercial jets. But its role
in Airbus has been diminished by the planned merger of the other
three Airbus partners _ France's Aerospatiale Matra, Germany's
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace and Spain's Construcciones Aeronauticas.
They will have 80 percent of Airbus after the formation of the new
joint company to be called European Aeronautic Defense and Space
(EADS).
</P>
<P>
   One analyst suggested executives with BAE System may have
floated the Boeing merger story to secure a better deal with the
Airbus consortium as it transforms itself into a single corporate
entity. The other partners are currently talking with BAE Systems
about the value of its holdings in the new Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``By posturing a possible alliance with Boeing, BAE is throwing
down the gauntlet before its European counterparts and saying, `We
want fair commercial terms and a good hearing,''' analyst Andrew
Burton of the Royal Bank of Scotland told Bloomberg News.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
