<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNALIST-SLAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAYING OF MEXICAN JOURNALIST BELIEVED TO BE A REPRISAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARLINGEN, Texas _ In the rough-and-tumble world of Mexican
journalism, police reporter Pablo Pineda Gausin had one of the
toughest jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Armed only with a notebook and a camera, the 37-year-old Pineda
followed Mexican police in this large border city documenting the
world of killers, drug traffickers, and immigrant smugglers.
Between crime scenes, he slept on a couch in the lobby of state
police headquarters in Matamoros.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, some of his colleagues said his regular exposes of
local crime bosses may have cost the reporter his life. Pineda was
the victim of an execution-style slaying Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter's body was ferried across the Rio Grande in a small
raft at 2:45 a.m. Sunday and dumped on Texas soil near Los Indios.
Pineda's hands were tied behind his back and his head wrapped in
plastic bag. But the cause of death was a single, large-caliber
bullet wound to the back of the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a tough reporter,'' said Angeles Negrete, a reporter
for El Bravo, Matamoros' largest daily newspaper. ``He was always
doing stories about drugs, about smuggling, about corruption. He
made some people mad at him, including the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Pineda, who narrowly escaped an attempt on his life at his home
last October, worked full-time as police reporter for La Opinion,
the second largest Matamoros daily. He worked for the section of
the paper called ``La Nota Roja,'' or the Red Report, a reference
to its graphic crime coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron County Sheriff Omar Lucio said the killers probably
dumped Pineda's body on the U.S. side of the border to stymie the
investigation. Mexican police have no authority to cross the river,
he said. A similar tactic was used last year when his deputies
found the bodies of two kidnapped Mexican police officials dumped
on a brushy riverbank, Lucio said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities came close to solving the case quickly Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Border Patrol agents saw two men cross the river and dump
what they thought was narcotics or other contraband on the
riverbank, Lucio said. After waiting for several hours to see if
anyone came to pick up the package, the Border Patrol officers
moved in and discovered Pineda's body wrapped in a sleeping bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over there, they have very powerful people and sometimes
(reporters) write something that is too harsh, too direct and to
the point, and probably some people take action on what is
written,'' Lucio said.
</P>
<P>
   His department is cooperating with Tamaulipas state police in
Matamoros, Lucio said. Deputies made arrangements Monday to turn
over crime scene photographs and other information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to hit it, see what facts we can get from people
and work it on the Mexican side where he supposedly was killed,''
said state police supervisor Eduardo Esparza.
</P>
<P>
   Robbery was not a motive, Esparza said. Pineda's bracelet, gold
chains, rings and wallet were untouched. The slaying was more
likely a reprisal, police believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a lot of problems with coyotes (immigrant smugglers),
that's what you hear in Matamoros,'' Esparza said.
</P>
<P>
   Other journalists said there were rumors that Pineda was
involved in smuggling or protecting a group of smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was discussed if he really was a good journalist or if he
was using journalism for other reasons,'' said Hector Miguel
Chavez, who runs a private news agency in Matamoros. ``That's why
we want the authorities to clear this up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
