<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Motorola Posts Strong Earnings
</P>
<P>
   Motorola reported another quarter of strong sales and profit
growth, which could provide a lift to flagging technology stocks.
Profit more than doubled, to $449 million, compared with $184
million in the quarter a year earlier. The results beat Wall Street
forecasts by a penny a share. Before the results were announced,
shares of Motorola fell $3, to $150, but climbed as high as $157
after hours.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo to Buy First Security
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo agreed to buy First Security for $2.9 billion in
stock, less than two weeks after the collapse of First Security's
planned merger with Zions Bancorporation. The deal will enable
Wells Fargo to build its presence in Utah, where First Security is
based.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers Increase 23 Percent in Brazil
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by a flurry of Internet takeovers, mergers and
acquisitions in Brazil surged in the first quarter. The nation,
Latin America's largest economy, had 65 transactions involving the
acquisition of controlling stakes in medium to large companies, 23
percent more than in the first three months of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Fed Testing Alternatives to Checks
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, said that
the central bank was moving to modernize its check-processing
system and was testing new technologies but acknowledged that many
Americans are still clinging to paper checks.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo Urged to Redraw Bank Laws
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, Hideyuki Aizawa, who heads the ruling party's
Financial Issues Research Committee, is urging financial regulators
to reconsider plans to issue banking licenses to nonbank companies
like Sony, saying the banking laws first need to be redrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Privatization of Power Company Set
</P>
<P>
   Legislators in the Philippines are set to vote this week on a
bill that would privatize the heavily indebted national power
company, a reform that the International Monetary Fund and other
lenders have demanded before disbursing critical new loans. The
House of Representatives is scheduled to begin voting today on the
Power Reform Bill. President Joseph Estrada and Manuel B. Villar,
the House leader, both support the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Web Site Removes Microsoft Report
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal's Web site posted and then removed a
report that Microsoft might be forced to make the programming code
for its Internet Explorer Web browser available to customers and
computer makers.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC May Cut Back on Production
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks after OPEC agreed to increase production to
bring down the cost of oil, prices have fallen abruptly and are
near the level at which the cartel had agreed it would then cut
back its output.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Increases 19 Percent at Gannett
</P>
<P>
   Gannett, the publisher of USA Today an 73 other daily papers,
said that first-quarter profit rose 19 percent because of increased
advertising sales and lower newsprint prices.
</P>
<P>
   Approval Urged for Rival of Viagra
</P>
<P>
   Uprima, made by TAP Pharmaceuticals, may soon be cutting into
Viagra's impotence-drug market after government advisers
recommended that the tablet be approved for sale to the public
despite some side effects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
