<SLUG> BC-BBC-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TGIF WHEN USC'S CURRIER'S ON THE MOUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There are Friday guys, Saturday guys and Sunday
guys. That's how a college baseball coach refers to his starting
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Friday guy is the ace, he starts a weekend series against
the other team's top pitcher. Saturday, the solid No. 2, a starter
who can decide a series. Sunday is potluck.
</P>
<P>
   That's what USC got from Rik Currier last year. Sometimes he was
brilliant, others just plain bad and mostly he was mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   Not this year. Currier is delivering for the Trojans. He pitched
a complete game and struck out 12 in USC's 5-1 win over UCLA on
Friday, improving to 8-2. Currier's performance is more impressive
considering the heavy-hitting Bruins scored 23 runs in the series'
next two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Currier) is on a mission to win every Pac-10 start,'' USC
pitching coach John Savage said. ``(This season) he's been a
different guy. When he's going good, he's legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Currier has a 3.99 ERA and opponents are batting only .242
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Currier usually starts Saturdays this year. But he moved up one
day for the UCLA series because Mark Prior, a transfer from
Vanderbilt, has been sick.
</P>
<P>
   After holding the Bruins to five hits, and retiring 15 of 16 at
one point, Savage gave Currier the ultimate compliment:
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched like a Friday guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Currier's career at USC hasn't been consistent. He was a
freshman All-American in the Trojans' national championship season
in 1998 going 6-1 with 100 strikeouts in 71 innings.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped off the map in '99 behind transfers Barry Zito and
Justin Lehr. Currier was 5-7 with a 6.38 ERA, and he gave up 101
hits in 79 innings. This year Currier is giving up less than a hit
per inning - 64 in 67 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I was pressing too hard,'' Currier said. ``I was
letting (things) get to me. It was a downward spiral.... The
pressure that I had was what I put on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Currier, a 5-foot-10 right-hander from Mission Viejo, went to
the Cape Cod League last summer and was selected the league's
pitcher of the year.
</P>
<P>
   His confidence restored, Currier has been one of the reasons the
Trojans (23-13, 6-3) are in the race for the Pac-10 title.
</P>
<P>
   Even as USC advanced to the second round of the NCAA playoffs
last season, Currier considered it a bittersweet experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to be pitching in the big games. It was tough to see
those other guys do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's one of those guys. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising: UCLA leads the Pac-10 after taking two of three
against USC. The Bruins were picked to finish second in the
coaches' preseason poll.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches pegged the Trojans third, a vote of respect for the
talent recruited by the Trojans coaches. USC lost almost every
position player and its top two starters from last season. Top
recruit Pat Manning, a third-round draft choice, signed with the
Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   USC's lineup Friday against UCLA included center fielder Josh
Self (.206 average in 34 at-bats last year), a freshman (Anthony
Lunetta) at second base, Josh Persell (14 starts in '99) at DH,
first baseman Bill Peavey (three ABs in two prior seasons) and left
fielder Brian Barre (25 ABs in '99).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just youth, it's inexperience,'' Gillespie said.
``We've got some older guys that didn't play much.... We probably
have played above, at least record-wise, what we could have
predicted.''
</P>
<P>
   Intensity: The weekend was perfect in Malibu, as usual. A bright
sun, a blue ocean and a white beach.
</P>
<P>
   But the conditions inside Pepperdine's Eddy D. Field Stadium
were not idyllic. The Loyola Marymount players don't really like
Pepperdine and the feeling is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   Even the fans don't get along. When Waves coach Frank Sanchez
delayed Sunday's game for 10 minutes, arguing a call in the fifth,
the LMU fans jeered. The Pepperdine fans hollered at the Lions
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams are so closely matched right now,'' LMU coach Frank
Cruz said after the Lions won 4-3 to take the series, two games to
one. ``I think (the rivalry) is overlooked, but it's not overlooked
by the 60 people that are going at each other in the dugouts and
their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Reborn: LMU right-hander Mike Schultz, considered the 20th-best
major-league prospect in college by one national publication, hopes
his performance Sunday - complete game, nine strikeouts - portends
the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz's ERA dropped from 7.22 to 6.51.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been a matter of confidence,'' said Schultz, who
went to Reseda's Cleveland High. ``(This season) I started throwing
harder and I tried to overpower people instead of hitting my
spots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
