<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-DIANA-ROSS-ART-NYT     04-10 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DIANA-ROSS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISS ROSS LOVES YOU, SO SHUT UP AND FAWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Divas do what they want to do, when they want to do
it. Divas can't resist an adoring audience. Divas have big hair and
flashy dresses. Divas live in a realm where show-business cliches
become a secular creed. Divas profess love while wreaking havoc.
Divas are beloved troupers and glamorous monsters.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Ross lived up to her billing as the ultimate diva at the
taping on Sunday night for VH1's ``Divas 2000,'' which is to be
shown Tuesday night at 9. It was VH1's third annual Divas concert,
but the first to be taped rather than carried live. If costume
changes, band setups and diva whims had extended much longer, it
would have been ``Divas 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   The concert at the Theater at Madison Square Garden was a
tribute to Ross, recognizing her world-beating success with the
Supremes in the 1960s and her career since 1970 as a solo singer
and a movie actress. The plan was straightforward: Mariah Carey,
Faith Hill and Donna Summer each sang their own songs and one of
Ross' hits, with cameos from RuPaul (who claimed Ross' ``I'm Coming
Out'' as a gay anthem) and Destiny's Child.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who's now trying to be a blond Shania Twain, paid
inadvertent homage to Ross' old vocal timing by belting every
phrase of ``Love Child'' right on the beat, flattening it. Summer
was more soulful, bringing a gospel richness to ``Reflections.''
Carey, in her own songs, overdid her swoops and slides, circling
around melody notes like a small plane lost in the fog.
</P>
<P>
   Once Ross stepped onstage, the show was dictated, diva style, by
her needs and impulses. She made her entrance in a brightly
patterned, fringe-trimmed dress, gushing, ``Where I'm at in my life
is about giving you my love.'' VH1 couldn't have planned for a
better way of inciting diva temperament than to start Ross'
performance with sound problems; a VH1 spokeswoman said Ross
insisted on using her own equipment, which was incompatible with
VH1's setup.
</P>
<P>
   Ross sang ``Touch Me in the Morning'' and ``Endless Love''
punctuated by loud bursts of static. She tried to maintain
equanimity, Hollywood style. ``It's just about playing and enjoying
your process,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   From the prompter she delivered a list of thank yous, including
``Mary and Cindy, I love you.'' (Mary Wilson and Cindy Birdsong,
surviving members of the 1960s Supremes, would not accept offers to
join her in this summer's Supremes reunion tour.) ``I don't hear
the sound well enough with this microphone,'' she finally
announced, her voice sharpening. ``This doesn't please me.''
</P>
<P>
   With a new microphone she suddenly decided to sing ``The Best
Years of My Life,'' which she called ``a testimonial song for my
career,'' while strolling through the aisles accepting hugs from
audience members. Second takes were necessary; as she cooed ``Touch
Me in the Morning'' to her band's lounge-flavored backup, she
swayed her hips and instructed the director, Steve Binder to ``get
the fringe.'' Still, she brought a nearly weightless delicacy and
tenderness to the songs.
</P>
<P>
   Next came the reconstituted Supremes, with Scherrie Payne and
Lynda Laurence, who sang with the group in the 1970s after Ross
left. Their choreography needs a lot of work; Payne gestured up a
storm, even after Ross whispered something to her in mid-song.
After two Supremes songs Ross lingered onstage to sing an impromptu
solo reprise of ``Love Is Like an Itching in My Heart.'' Mariah
Carey had better Supremes moves when she and Ross, both in short,
shiny minidresses, shared ``Baby Love'' and ``Stop! in the Name of
Love.''
</P>
<P>
   After all the women and RuPaul gathered for the finale, ``Ain't
No Mountain High Enough,'' Ross stayed to bask in the applause,
then chose to do an encore. ``Where's my band?'' she asked. ``My
band never leaves the stage before I leave the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Errant musicians returned. Binder asked Ross if Destiny's Child
could redo its segment, but Ross ruled, ``No, let me do this
first.'' After calling for requests, she ignored her entire catalog
to sing a diva classic: Gloria Gaynor's ``I Will Survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The neo-Supremes returned to shrill the chorus while the band
vamped and Ross cued solos; a boy came onstage to revive Michael
Jackson's old moonwalk moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time passes quickly,'' Ross philosophized after the final
notes. ``Open your eyes, look and see where you are and enjoy
life.'' Destiny's Child could wait.
</P>
<P>
   How much of the taping will appear in the television version of
``Divas 2000'' is up to VH1. It can joke about divas, or it can
show one unbridled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PULITZER-PRIZE-HIGHLI     04-10 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULITZER-PRIZE-HIGHLIGHTS-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLIGHTS AND EXCERPTS FROM PULITZER WINNERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., N.Y., Mass., Wash., N.J., Conn., Fla., N.H., D.C.,
Minn., Colo., Mont., W.Va., Calif.)   (With PULITZER-PRIZES-NYT) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FICTION
</P>
<P>
   JHUMPA LAHIRI
</P>
<P>
   ``Interpreter of Maladies''
</P>
<P>
   This collection of stories about the lives of people in North
America and India is the first book by Jhumpa Lahiri. Born in
London, she grew up in Rhode Island and lives in New York City. She
is a graduate of Barnard College and Boston University. Many of the
characters in her stories are Indian immigrants in the United
States confronting a cultural displacement.
</P>
<P>
   The book was published last June in a trade paperback edition.
In her review in The New York Times, Michiko Kakutani wrote:
``Lahiri chronicles her characters' lives with both objectivity and
compassion while charting the emotional temperature of their lives
with tactile precision. She is a writer of uncommon elegance and
poise, and with `Interpreter of Maladies,' she has made a
precocious debut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The family looked Indian but dressed as foreigners did, the
children in stiff, brightly colored clothing and caps with
translucent visors. Mr. Kaspasi was accustomed to foreign tourists:
he was assigned to them regularly because he could speak English.
Yesterday he had driven an elderly couple from Scotland, both with
spotted faces and fluffy white hair so trim it exposed their
sunburnt scalps.''
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   JOHN W. DOWER
</P>
<P>
   ``Embracing Defeat: Japan in the Wake of World War II''
</P>
<P>
   John W. Dower subjects the nearly seven-year American occupation
of Japan after World War II to a searching, myth-breaking
examination. Popularly known as a huge success, the occupation, in
Dower's portrait, was a complex and wrenching adjustment by the
Japanese to overwhelming American power. Dower, a historian at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, draws out the occupation's
deep effects on Japanese society, treating topics like the
pervasiveness of prostitution, the postwar role of Emperor Hirohito
and the emergence of a brand of state capitalism with a close
relationship between government and business.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   DAVID M. KENNEDY
</P>
<P>
   ``Freedom From Fear: The American People in Depression and War,
1929-45''
</P>
<P>
   In his one-volume work on the era of President Franklin D.
Roosevelt, part of the Oxford History of the United States series,
David M. Kennedy portrays President Herbert Hoover as a reflective
humanitarian ``overwhelmed by events,'' finds order in the chaos of
New Deal policies, and suggests that Roosevelt bent the law so far
to get aid to France and England that he almost courted
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But the high drama of the book is watching a nation,
straitjacketed by an isolationist Congress, enter the war. A native
of Seattle, Kennedy, the Donald J. McLachlan professor of history
at Stanford University, is also the author of ``Birth Control in
America: The Career of Margaret Sanger'' (1970), which won the
Bancroft Prize, and ``Over Here: The First World War and American
Society'' (1980), which was a finalist for the Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   POETRY
</P>
<P>
   C.K. WILLIAMS
</P>
<P>
   ``Repair''
</P>
<P>
   C.K. Williams, a New Jersey native, lives part of the year in
Paris and teaches at Princeton University. Known for his long,
Whitmanesque sentences and his documentarylike style, he can be
ruthless, even cruel, in his pitiless contemplation of the world
around him. The subjects of his early work were politics, the
Vietnam War, the horrors of the nuclear age. But in recent years,
his poems have become more personal and introspective. In the poem
``Archetypes,'' Williams writes about a sleeping woman who stirs in
her dreams and rises up, like an animal, to her hands and knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your fingers began to move then, in brief, irregular tensions
and releasings;
</P>
<P>
   it felt like your hand was trying to hold some feathery,
fleeting creature,
</P>
<P>
   then you suddenly, fiercely, jerked it away, rose to your hands
and knees,
</P>
<P>
   and stayed there, palms flat on the bed, hair tangled down over
your face,
</P>
<P>
   until with a coarse sigh almost like a snarl you abruptly let
yourself fall
</P>
<P>
   and lay still, your hands drawn tightly to your chest, your head
turned away,
</P>
<P>
   forbidden to me, I thought, by whatever had raised you to that
defiant crouch.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BIOGRAPHY
</P>
<P>
   STACY SCHIFF
</P>
<P>
   ``Vera (Mrs. Vladimir Nabokov)''
</P>
<P>
   The triumph of this portrait of a 52-year marriage is not just
in providing entree to the wife's famous husband. She fascinates in
her own right: first, as a girl reciting Nabokov by heart when, in
1923, she makes her first approach to the aristocratic,
Cambridge-educated writer, already well known among Russian
expatriates in Berlin; ever thereafter until Nabokov's death in
1977 as the provider of the comforts he needed, as he told her,
``for the sake of not thinking about them.'' Stacy Schiff is the
author of ``Saint-Exupery,'' a finalist for the 1995 Pulitzer Prize
in biography.
</P>
<P>
   DRAMA
</P>
<P>
   DONALD MARGULIES
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinner With Friends''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Margulies, 45, a veteran playwright known for comic
excisions of troubled families, won for a gentle, straightforward
play that shuns the arch and sometimes farcical vision of previous
works like ``The Loman Family Picnic'' and ``What's Wrong With This
Picture?'' He lives in New Haven, Conn., where he teaches
playwriting at the Yale School of Drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinner With Friends'' is about four friends, two baby-boom
marriages, one of which is coming apart. In various settings _ a
well-appointed kitchen, a couple's bedroom, a suburban back porch,
an upscale bar _ the play recreates a world meant to give pangs of
recognition to affluent midlife theatergoers. The play opened
Off-Broadway in November and has become a surprise hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``What initially seems a rather conventional glimpse at the
perils of breaking up,'' Peter Marks wrote in his review in The New
York Times, ``becomes an original examination of the terrors of
staying together.''
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS SPRATLAN
</P>
<P>
   ``Life Is a Dream, Opera in Three Acts: Act II, Concert
Version''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Spratlan, 59, is a composer who was born in Miami and has
been a professor of composition at Amherst College since 1970. He
based this opera on a 17th-century Spanish play by Pedro Calderon,
``La Vida Es Sueno.'' Using an English libretto by James Maraniss,
Spratlan created a theatrical world in which the characters were
given distinct musical thumb prints that were meant to embody their
personalities, and in which the dissonances and angularities of
contemporary styles were linked with traditional dance, march and
madrigal forms. Spratlan completed the work in 1978, but revised
its second act for concert use. The concert version was given its
world premiere by the Dinosaur Annex, conducted by J. David Jackson
in Boston on Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   THE WASHINGTON POST
</P>
<P>
   The Post won the gold medal for public service, its second in a
row, with a two-part series describing both the abuse of those
living in the District of Columbia's group homes for the mentally
retarded and how their ill treatment often resulted in death. The
city government has pledged to reform the system.
</P>
<P>
   The writer, Katherine Boo, 35, a native of Washington, spent 13
months reporting after a source on another article about welfare
revisions took her into a group home where retarded residents were
sitting in total darkness with roaches scuttling underfoot. Boo
found that the people who died in those circumstances were often
buried in unmarked graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that the prize is a small marker that the Pulitzer
board has put down on these unmarked graves,'' she said Monday,
``and it says that the people who died here and who suffered here
mattered.''
</P>
<P>
   INVESTIGATIVE REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   THE ASSOCIATED PRESS
</P>
<P>
   The AP won for painstakingly documenting a decades-old cover-up
of atrocities by the U.S. military in the first weeks of the Korean
War. Three reporters _ Charles J. Hanley, Martha Mendoza and
Sang-Hun Choe _ aided by Randy Herschaft, a researcher, disclosed
for the first time how American soldiers machine-gunned hundreds of
civilians under a bridge at No Gun Ri. The work has led to an
investigation by the Army. ``We're proud of the No Gun Ri
reporting,'' the four said in a statement. ``But our celebration is
tempered by the nature of what we confirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   MARK SCHOOFS
</P>
<P>
   The Village Voice
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schoofs said his editors did not blink when he proposed
what was a costly assignment for an alternative weekly: spending
six months documenting the AIDS catastrophe in sub-Saharan Africa.
During his travels, Schoofs, 37, visited rural villages where no
journalist had ever been and contracted a drug-resistant form of
malaria that put him in the hospital. In a 28,000-word series, he
described the struggles of elderly people forced to care for
orphaned grandchildren and the often-heroic efforts of impoverished
villagers to provide for the sick. He said he hoped the series
would bring about more aid to the region. ``This country can make a
huge difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   STAFF OF THE WALL STREET JOURNAL
</P>
<P>
   The Journal series examined the ways the U.S. military spent
billions of dollars after the Cold War ended. In what the newspaper
called an unusual collaboration, the articles were produced by
Thomas E. Ricks, its Pentagon correspondent, and five business
reporters in bureaus around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal found and explained problems varying from the
Defense Department's reluctance to embrace promising technology to
the Navy's use of skilled technicians to count the number of
sailors choosing pork chops for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BEAT REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE DOHRMANN
</P>
<P>
   St. Paul Pioneer Press
</P>
<P>
   George Dohrmann, 27, doggedly pursued academic cheating by the
University of Minnesota basketball team and showed that school
officials were doing players' course work. His reporting exposed
one of the broadest cases of academic fraud in collegiate history _
enraging many fans _ and led to the buyout of the head coach and
dismissal of four other officials.
</P>
<P>
   He quoted Russ Archambault, a former player, who recounted how
one athletic department employee tutored him: ``I sat down and she
just started typing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dohrmann said the key to breaking the story was winning the
confidence of a retired athletic department employee who gave him
records. ``I had to convince her that what she did was wrong,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKING NEWS REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   STAFF OF THE DENVER POST
</P>
<P>
   From the first hour of the killings at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., last April, a staff of 54 reporters and eight
photographers reported relentlessly on the massacre, publishing
more than two dozen stories within 12 hours of the first shot.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the prize was bittersweet for the staff, many of whom
lived in Littleton, said Frank Scandale, The Post's assistant
managing editor for news, who supervised the Columbine coverage.
``You had covered their sporting events, their City Council, their
baton-twirling championships,'' Scandale said. ``And then, to see
these kids on the ground, bloodied and tortured, broke down a lot
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   EXPLANATORY REPORTING
</P>
<P>
   ERIC NEWHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   The Great Falls Tribune
</P>
<P>
   Eric Newhouse, 55, the newspaper's projects editor, won for a
yearlong series of monthly articles on the social and economic
costs of alcoholism in Montana. The project, which included regular
visits with a chronic alcoholic, represented, he said, a
``tremendous commitment'' for a paper with a circulation of 34,000
and a full-time staff of 38.
</P>
<P>
   An 18-year veteran of The Associated Press, Newhouse was a
bureau chief in Charleston, W.Va., when he found himself ``an
administrator, a paper pusher too far divorced from the news I
loved.'' He left for The Great Falls Tribune in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about me,'' he said by telephone in the midst of a
newsroom celebration. ``It's about a small newspaper willing to
devote its resources to such a huge problem. We're very much a
community paper, and people trust us. So many folks were willing to
talk to us with candor and honesty about their problem. I'm in awe
of the folks I've dealt with who entrusted so much to us.''
</P>
<P>
   CRITICISM
</P>
<P>
   HENRY ALLEN
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Previous criticism prizes have included photography reviews, but
this was the first year that the Pulitzer board bestowed a prize
solely for writing about that art.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Allen on photographs by Brassai, who documented Paris
between the wars, on exhibit at the National Gallery of Art in
Washington:
</P>
<P>
   ``When Brassai took his camera out into the Paris night, he was
reveling in the humanity _ not the alienation _ of the whores,
thieves and gay demimonde he photographed: the naked brothel staff
with dimpled bodies whose shapes remind you of Babe Ruth, the
lurking darkness beneath bridges, the cafe girl with spit curls and
a bad tooth lolling heavy-lidded between two sailors, the
quarreling lovers in their adamance and sulk, the two thugs of the
sort who robbed and beat Brassai during his nighttime
investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE WRITING
</P>
<P>
   J.R. MOEHRINGER
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Moehringer, 35, The Times' Atlanta bureau chief since 1997,
painted a 9,000-word portrait of Gee's Bend, Ala., ``the last place
on earth still safe enough for children and dead folks to go
walking after dark.'' The isolated river community is one of the
few places in the nation where the descendants of slaves still live
on the land of their ancestors. Moehringer spent 18 months
chronicling a controversial plan to resurrect the local ferry.
Despite the town's harsh racial history, he said, ``This is a town
that has nothing but love in its heart despite all the cruelty
visited upon it.''
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY
</P>
<P>
   PAUL A. GIGOT
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
   Paul A. Gigot, a member of the editorial board of The Journal,
was honored for the insight and detailed knowledge of politics and
government he imparts every week in his conservative ``Potomac
Watch'' column.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his columns examined the impeachment battle and the
harsh light it focused on Washington and on the reporters who
covered it. In one column, Gigot concluded: ``Only here could could
a man who lies under oath be equated with someone who tries to
defend the value of that oath. The point is never, `What's right?'
but rather, `Who won?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gigot, 44, also appears regularly as a political analyst on
``The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer'' on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL WRITING
</P>
<P>
   JOHN C. BERSIA
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando Sentinel
</P>
<P>
   John C. Bersia, 43, won for editorials about the lending
practices of payday advance and car-title loan companies. ``There
was evolving a double standard,'' he said Monday, ``one for people
who were poor or in desperate financial circumstances and were
forced to borrow at triple-digit rates, and the other for people in
the mainstream, borrowing at lower rates.'' When the state Senate
rejected a bill to regulate car-title companies, which typically
lend a customer about 15 percent of the value of an auto, Bersia
wrote editorials urging Florida's 67 counties to approve similar
legislation. So far, 36 counties have limited the interest charged
by car-title lenders to 30 percent a year or less; 11 other
counties are considering similar laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
