<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2822 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-CAR-HERTA-LADN     04-10 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-HERTA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERTA WILL RACE AT LONG BEACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ CART FedEx Series driver Bryan Herta will compete
for Walker Racing in this weekend's Grand Prix of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Valencia driver is still under contract with Forsythe
Championship Racing, but tangles with CART officials over franchise
restrictions have kept Herta out of the first two events of the
CART FedEx Series.
</P>
<P>
   Herta, who was signed by Gerald Forsythe to drive a Honda/Swift
Champ car sponsored by Panasonic, missed the Miami Grand Prix and
the Bosch Spark Plug Grand Prix in Nazareth, Pa. The Nazareth race
was snowed out.
</P>
<P>
   When Derrick Walker, owner of the Walker Racing team, lost his
driver, Shinji Nakano, to injury during a recent practice session,
Walker asked Herta to replace the Japanese-born driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derrick called me, and he knew I was under contract, but he
asked me to fill in for the next couple of races,'' Herta said.
``Gerry thought it would give me the opportunity to go out and do
some racing. Walker is an excellent team and they use a Honda
engine. So for me, it meets my criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Herta is scheduled to race at Long Beach and
Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. Nakano is supposed to be be back for the
Firestone Firehawk 500 at Twin Ring Motegi in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Herta said he hopes his Forsythe Championship Racing
team will be allowed to compete in Motegi as well. In addition to
not being allowed to compete because the CART Board of Directors
decided in March that Forsythe could not own three franchises,
Herta lost his chassis as Swift decided to end its contract with
Herta's team. Forsythe also owns the Player's team with Patrick
Carpentier and Alex Tagliani as drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little bit behind the eight-ball right now,'' Herta
said. ``It's a day-to-day thing. I'm just waiting to hear from
Gerry and find out what he wants to do. All the pieces are in
place, but all I can do now is focus on the next two races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, I'd like to get a couple of Reynards and catch up
with everyone at Motegi.''
</P>
<P>
   Nakano was the top-finishing rookie and eighth overall finisher
in the season opener at Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BBA-TIGER-STADIUM-1ST     04-10 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TIGER-STADIUM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETROIT HOPES NEW BALLPARK IS STAR PLAYER IN CITY'S REDEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 16th graf, ``This city ..., to delete reference to Jesus
Christ from quote. Also being filed in `s' category.) 
 By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Few major cities have talked more about or waited
longer for a visible symbol of resurrection than this one, the
nation's poorest.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the patience will be rewarded on Tuesday, with the
inaugural game at Comerica Park, the new $300 million home of the
Detroit Tigers baseball team and the showpiece of a burgeoning
entertainment district in downtown Detroit. The stadium was built
with city, county, state and private money, and was named for its
corporate sponsor, Comerica Bank in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders are convinced that the ornate open-air stadium,
with its synchronized water fountains and 50-foot-high Ferris
wheel, will drive investment _ not to mention thousands of visitors
_ back downtown, just as Jacobs Field and Camden Yards transformed
Cleveland and Baltimore into banner cities for urban renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of banners, Tigers officials are quietly picking out
spots to display a World Series banner, should the
down-on-their-luck Tigers bring home the championship, a feat this
99-year-old franchise has not accomplish since 1984. And the way
the team is limping along _ at 1-5, the Tigers have the worst
record in baseball _ fans will probably wait a while longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've endured a lot of rhetoric over the years,'' said Denise
Illitch, the daughter of Tigers owner Mike Illitch. ``But this
ballpark is real. It's proof things are changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Illitch is president of Olympia Development, which is
handling projects surrounding Comerica Park. The Illitch family
also owns the Detroit Red Wings hockey team, which plays at Joe
Louis Arena on the city's waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Change is whirling all around the ballpark. Later this week,
construction will begin on an $800 million office complex several
blocks south that will become the headquarters of the Compuware
Corp., which makes software for managing corporate networks. The
company is moving from Farmington Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Just east of the stadium, construction crews are excavating the
site of Ford Field, a brick-and-glass stadium with a dome, also
costing about $300 million, that will sit alongside Comerica Park
and bring the Detroit Lions football team back to the city for the
first time in 26 years. The Lions, who now play in the Silverdome
in suburban Pontiac, plan to open Ford Field in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 3 million people expected to visit Comerica Park
this season will not have to worry about parking or traffic.
They'll walk to the 40,000-seat ballpark. Forty-seven townhouses,
with price tags of $140,000 to $250,000 are being built across the
street, on land that for years had been used by prostitutes and
drug users
</P>
<P>
   Signs advertising loft space pop up daily in the windows of
deserted office buildings nearby.
</P>
<P>
   But most surprising is the nightlife that has crept back, now
that two of the three voter-approved casinos have opened temporary
sites on the fringe of downtown. On most evenings the parking lots
at the MGM Grand and the Motorcity Casino resemble those of
suburban shopping malls. Eventually the casinos will build near the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one here, not even the ever-jubilant Mayor Dennis
Archer, is ready to proclaim Detroit completely reborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still not where we want to be,'' Archer said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Huge swaths of the city are dominated by weed-choked lots and
abandoned houses. Some basic services like street lighting and bus
service are still unreliable. That is why many Detroit residents
say they are reluctant to believe that the city's renaissance will
ever extend beyond downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absurd that we're spending hundreds of millions of
dollars on a new ballpark when we can't keep our libraries open
regular hours and our kids don't even have safe playgrounds,'' said
Frank Rashid, a lifelong resident and founder of the Tiger Stadium
Fan Club, which pleaded with city officials to revitalize Tiger
Stadium. The famed ballpark sits empty about a mile from Comerica
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city is fixated on shortcuts to revitalization,'' Rashid
said, relaying on huge projects ``that do nothing but deliver false
promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Urban planning and economic experts agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is no evidence that building a new sports stadium
resurrects a downtown or a city,'' said Andrew Zimbalist, an
economics professor at Smith College. ``In cities that are
investing in several downtown projects all at once, there is
additional activity, but it's mostly from the transfer of income
and employment from surrounding communities into the downtown area.
You rarely see a great spread effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mayor contended that Comerica Park was crucial to
Detroit's comeback, if for no other reason than as an morale boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comerica Park will help restore the excitement of urban living
that has been missing far too long from downtown Detroit,'' Archer
said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Comerica Park was designed to dazzle. Life-size
stone tigers and baseball bats guard the entrances. Inside the
ballpark, children can ride a Ferris wheel with seats shaped like
baseballs or a carousel featuring 30 handpainted tigers. The
low-rise outfield stands are expected to be another attraction,
with their postcard view of the city's skyline. Along the wall in
left-center field, huge stainless steel statues of Hall of Fame
players like Hank Greenberg, Ty Cobb and Charlie Gehringer will
keep watch. And the 10-story-tall scoreboard is the largest in
baseball, the Tiger organization says.
</P>
<P>
   As it is with most things, Comerica Park's grandeur comes at a
price. Now that the team offers luxury seats, the price of an
average home game ticket has doubled to $24.83, the fourth highest
in baseball, according to Team Marketing Report.
</P>
<P>
   But even that has done little to spoil this city's excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit has lost so much and had to wait so long for something
to be proud of,'' said 63-year-old Bernard Battistelli, a longtime
Tiger fan, who typically attends 10 to 15 home games a year. ``I'd
rather pay a little extra than sit around another 10 years waiting
for a rebirth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
