<HEADER>
A2827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-OHIO11-COX     04-10 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-OHIO11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush takes campaign to Hispanic community
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush today will use a
campaign visit to Cleveland's West Side to outline his plans for
raising Americans on the ``outskirts of poverty'' into the middle
class.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he will venture where few, if any, Republican
presidential candidates have gone before in Ohio, to a Hispanic
community center, El Barrio, said state Rep. Jim Trakas
(R-Independence), Cuyahoga County Republican chairman.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of Bush's plan for using ``compassionate
conservatism'' to expand the party's base and reverse the two
straight losses in presidential elections, Trakas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how we're going to do better,'' Trakas said. ``It's in
areas where largely in the past we have not been very active.''
</P>
<P>
   Trakas said that he has worked in every presidential campaign
since 1972 and never had seen a Republican candidate stop at a
Hispanic center.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will tour El Barrio, which offers employment and education
programs for children and adults, and then will deliver his speech
at the West Side Ecumenical Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Bush) understands the needs of the Latino community,''
said Angel Dones, a Bush supporter and editor-in-chief of Nuevos
Horizontes, a Cleveland weekly newspaper. ``People are looking for
leadership that will address the issues _ immigration issues,
educational issues, educational training issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who speaks Spanish, has done well with Hispanic voters in
his two winning campaigns for Texas governor. One exit poll in 1998
showed him winning nearly 50 percent of the Hispanic vote, a strong
showing among a traditionally Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   According to exit polls, about 1 percent of the Ohio voters in
the 1996 and 1998 elections said they were of Hispanic origin, said
Eric Rademacher, codirector of the University of Cincinnati's Ohio
Poll.
</P>
<P>
   However, because Ohio is a bellwether state in presidential
elections, Bush's Cleveland stop with potential Hispanic voters
will attract national, as well as statewide attention, Rademacher
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland stops follow earlier Bush forays in Ohio to areas
usually regarded as rich in Democratic votes _ a storefront church
in a black neighborhood in Cincinnati and a predominantly black
housing project in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speech today at the West Side Ecumenical Ministry is
expected to touch on health care, child care, education and
employment opportunities, said one Bush supporter. James Ruvolo,
former Ohio Democratic chairman and an Ohio backer of Vice
President Al Gore, said Bush's efforts to draw support in
traditionally Democratic areas won't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush can go wherever he wants. What matters is his
message. George Bush has no message of accomplishment to talk about
in Ohio,'' Ruvolo said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
