<HEADER>
A2840 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MOTOROLA-EARNINGS-NYT     04-10 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTERLY SALES AND PROFIT RISE SHARPLY AT MOTOROLA 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Motorola Inc., the telecommunications and
semiconductor giant, reported another quarter of strong sales and
profit growth on Monday, which could provide a lift to flagging
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Propelled by strong demand for its cellular phones and
semiconductors, Motorola has been staging a turnaround in its
traditional businesses and remaking itself into a company that is
already profiting from the growth of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the company said that revenue rose sharply, to $8.8
billion, up about 20 percent from $7.3 billion in the first quarter
of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Profit more than doubled, to $449 million, or 59 cents a diluted
share, compared with $184 million, or 26 cents a share, in the
quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts, who had been forecasting a profit of 58
cents, according to First Call/Thomson Financial, cheered the
report. ``This is a very good number,'' said Mona Eraiba of Gruntal
&AMP; Co. in New York. ``They've turned around in an amazing way.''
</P>
<P>
   The company announced its results after the close of regular
trading. Its shares fell $3, to $150, during the regular session
but climbed as high as $157 after hours.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola reported double-digit growth in sales and profit in
most of its divisions, but the strongest sales growth came in its
cellular phone and semiconductor units, which both reported sales
gains of 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But while semiconductor profit rose more than tenfold, operating
profit in the cellular phone unit fell to $49 million from $84
million in the quarter a year earlier because of higher costs
related to a shortage in telephone components and a shift toward
sales of less expensive handsets. It was one of the few troubling
items in the report. ``They had a very good number, but it was
marred by the lower margins in cellular telephones,'' Eraiba said.
``Motorola will have to address that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the analysts are largely pleased with Motorola's progress. A
little more than a year ago, Motorola was faltering, losing market
share in cellular phones and suffering from a downturn in
semiconductor equipment. It was also writing off millions of
dollars because of its failed investment in Iridium LLC, the
satellite telephone venture.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a technology and Internet boom is bolstering demand for
cellular phones and semiconductors. And Motorola has been
refashioning itself into a software and Internet company, forming
alliances with Internet and networking companies and developing
phones equipped with Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it will be at the center of the ``wired world,'' Motorola
also made its biggest acquisition last year, buying General
Instrument Corp., the largest maker of cable set-top boxes, in the
hope of establishing itself in the interactive-television market.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Motorola, which were trading as low as $87 in October,
rose as high as $184 early in March before dropping over the last
month.
</P>
<P>
   With profit expected to reach $2 billion this year, on revenue
of $38 billion, however, Motorola now needs to convince Wall Street
that its sales and profit can continue to grow in an increasingly
competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   The company is already one of the world's largest technology
providers _ its $30 billion in revenue last year compares with $19
billion for Microsoft _ which is part of the reason Motorola is
expanding into everything from wired homes, automobiles and even
biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola has also been spending heavily in advertising and
marketing, and remaking itself in the image of a hip company with
jazzy walkie-talkies and several lines of cellular phones equipped
with Internet browsers that come in vibrant colors and light, slick
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons we have a strong buy on the stock,''
said Brian Modoff, an analyst with Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown.
``They understand the market a lot more than they used to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
