<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2841 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-DOYLE11-COX     04-10 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DOYLE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cash flow isn't slow for Doyle these days
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ One of the rooms at the Doyle household
in LaGrange, Ga., is filled with enough silver and crystal to serve
a large party. This also serves as the perfect demarcation between
Allen Doyle's two worlds as a very successful golfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an amateur, you've got to polish your winnings,'' Doyle's
wife, Kate said. ``As a pro, you get to spend them.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, not much has changed for the ex-hockey player who has
used his wrist-shot-like swing to score big time in his second
career on the links. He spent most of his 30s and 40s as one of the
nation's top amateurs, winning everything but money. His sole
income for five years was operating Doyle's Golf Center, a
no-frills driving range near his home.
</P>
<P>
   But since turning professional at 46, he's more than cashed in
on his talents, earning almost $2.5 million on the Nike, PGA and
Senior PGA tours. This week he will celebrate the most significant
victory of his career when he defends his title in the 61st PGA
Seniors' Championship at PGA National, one of four titles he earned
last year as a rookie on the 50-and-older circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that changed my life because I think I'm the
same guy now that I was then,'' Doyle said. ``But if you would have
asked me what I thought it would have been like, I would have sold
it short. You can't fathom what it's like to win a major on
national TV; at least I couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Doyle hasn't changed since he shot an eight-under
64 in the final round to overtake Vicente Fernandez and win by two
shots. When Doyle's home, he still gets up early and is at his
driving range at 8 every morning to mow the grass and pick up balls
and shoot the bull with his customers.
</P>
<P>
   But, like his swing, Doyle's golf career has not traveled the
usual path. It's been that way from the start as he honed his flat
swing in the 8-foot ceiling cellar of the house he grew up in the
Boston suburb of Norwood.
</P>
<P>
   In his early days in golf, everyone tried to get him to change
his unorthodox swing, saying he would never get far with it. ``Once
I beat them, they stopped saying how funny the swing looked,''
Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   While many of today's stars were raised in country clubs, Doyle
learned the sport playing on municipal courses. When he accepted a
scholarship to college, it was to be a hockey player at Norwich
University, where he was a defensemen who didn't mind throwing
checks, as well as a few fists.
</P>
<P>
   After serving in the Army in South Korea, Doyle and his wife
relocated to Georgia to continue his military service. They thought
briefly about him turning professional, but then she became
pregnant with the first of their two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think that was the time for me to be leaving home,''
Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   So he took a job at a textile factory, spending most of his days
making carpets instead of birdies. His amateur career started to
flourish, however, and eventually he quit the textile business so
he could run an American Legion golf course that would give him
more time to work on his game.
</P>
<P>
   And he did have game: He won six Georgia Amateur titles, played
on two Walker Cup teams, three World Amateur teams, one with Tiger
Woods,
</P>
<P>
   and was the top-ranked amateur in the United States in 1994. He
was the
</P>
<P>
   medalist in the 1991 U.S. Amateur and lost in the 1992
semifinals to Justin Leonard. It's not a stretch to say he's the
greatest amateur player in Georgia since Bobby Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around Georgia and the Southeast, I won't say I was a legend,
but I won most everything I played in,'' Doyle said. ``I had some
stature in the game that few people achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he hit his mid-40s, he knew the driving range wasn't
going to be enough if he wanted to send his two daughters to the
colleges of their choice. So he turned pro, which may not have been
the gamble everyone else thought it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allen would have never turned pro if he didn't think he was
going to be successful,'' his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on a sponsor's exemption, he finished in the top 25 in
his first Nike event, which got him into the next week's
tournament, which he won. By the time that year was over, Doyle had
won three times, including the Tour Championship, to earn a spot on
the 1996 PGA Tour, becoming the oldest rookie ever at 47.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled his next two years on the PGA Tour (finishing 140th
and 189th on the money list) because of his lack of distance off
the tee. But this experience kept his game sharp until he became
eligible for the Senior Tour, easily earning a spot in late 1998 as
medalist of Qualifying School.
</P>
<P>
   He won in Naples, then again two months later with his rally at
the PGA Seniors'. He overcame an early double-bogey with a 31 on
the back nine that included no 4s on his scorecard (he had seven 3s
and two 5s). That was the highlight in a year in which he finished
third on the money list with more than $1.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone else found out what we've known for a long time,''
said oldest daughter Erin, a senior at Southern Mississippi. ``Dad
can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle's only regret during last year's PGA Seniors' was he
didn't include an old hockey helmet in his bag that he could have
worn walking up the 18th fairway. Sort of like Red Auerbach's
victory cigar.
</P>
<P>
   But Doyle has no regrets about the rest of his life. He doesn't
consider it a mistake he spent all those years as an amateur before
finally turning pro at such a late age.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did I shortchange myself along the way?'' he said. ``I
never, ever second-guessed anything. Now if I went through three
wives and my kids hated me, like anyone, I would say I should have
done this different. I'm on top of the world, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
