<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2842 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-ASIA-MALAYSIA-     04-10 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ASIA-MALAYSIA-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VESTIGES OF A GRAND LIFE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It must have been great to be a British governor general.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine it. When the job was still worth having, it came
with complete authority to rule over your colony. Better yet, all
your bosses were half a world away, in an era when that meant they
really had no idea how well you were living. Which was probably
just as well: Most governors general lived quite nicely. When not
putting down the odd local insurrection, they could retreat to
spectacular hilltop homes, their every care (and afternoon tea)
anticipated by an overly large staff.
</P>
<P>
   That way of life died out quickly with the end of colonialism.
No doubt that is largely a good thing _ the quality of rule rarely
matched the governor's quality of life. But fortunately some of the
houses survive, complete with their carefully rolled lawns, their
sumptuous breakfasts and _ in the case of Carcosa, the spectacular
102-year-old mansion in the hills above Kuala Lumpur _ a small army
of butlers and drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The mansion, with seven guest suites, is now part of a small
luxury hotel called Carcosa Seri Negara; a second mansion, with six
more suites, is under renovation after a fire in February.
</P>
<P>
   Carcosa Seri Negara is one of the few places in Asia to recall
an era long gone. It is all about atmosphere, from the gentle
breezes in the morning, to the iguanas that scamper across the
paths when you are out on a morning walk, to the wide veranda,
where you half expect to see Evelyn Waugh sunk into a weathered
wicker chair, scratching out his next novel and barking at the
waiters.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident that Queen Elizabeth II settled in at Carcosa
Seri Negara when she visited this former British colony in the fall
of 1998. After all, there's not much sense of Asian adventure when
you check in at the Ritz-Carlton downtown, one of the many hotels
that feel more like Manhattan than what was once British Malaya.
</P>
<P>
   There have been concessions to modern times at Carcosa Seri
Negara. Every suite has been air-conditioned and updated; in mine,
the veranda had been glassed in to create a cool seating area. When
the wind parted the branches, I could just make out the Petronas
Twin Towers, the world's tallest buildings, a symbol of Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad's single-minded determination to
transform this tropical capital into a wired financial powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But best of all, every suite comes with a personal butler. Mine
was a witty, personable veteran of Carcosa life: Vicky Manian, who
made sure the right fruits and magazines were on the teak desk in
my room, drove me around town on my appointments in a wonderfully
battered old Mercedes, and punctuated every trip with tales of the
hotel's odder guests. (He had only good things to say about the
Queen.) But more about him in a moment.
</P>
<P>
   I had long wanted to stay at Carcosa. In 15 years of bouncing
around in Asia, I've been fascinated with the grand old homes that
served as the seat of colonial power.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's their graceful shutters, or the constant clacking of
the ceiling fans, but every one of them seems haunted by the
history of failed attempts at colonial rule in Asia _ the subtext
of the region's politics to this day. The houses are at once
fabulously luxurious and a little sad, reminders of an age that has
virtually disappeared in the 25 years since the end of the Vietnam
War. And the few that still stand are often in the shadows of
Singapore's skyscrapers or Saigon's cell-phone towers.
</P>
<P>
   They are hard to find and harder to get into. The former home of
the American governor general of the Philippines today sits behind
a huge fence and serves as the office of the American ambassador _
complete with its huge seaside veranda, commanding a view of
Corregidor, where Gen. Douglas MacArthur famously promised to
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably a good thing for American foreign policy that
these walls can't talk,'' one past ambassador said to me over lunch
one day, after guiding me through the house's former bedrooms and
recounting the off-color legends of how Washington's men in Manila
kept themselves entertained during long tropical nights.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the spectacular mansion in Hong Kong. I
interviewed Christopher Patten, Britain's last governor there, just
weeks before the city was returned to China in 1997. As we talked,
the remnants of empire were literally being packed up and shipped
back to London: old oil paintings, maps of the island, books so
dusty it seemed unlikely anyone had taken them off the shelves for
a half century or so.
</P>
<P>
   The place so reeked of colonial power that Patten's
Chinese-appointed successor, Tung Chee-hwa, decided not to move
into the house. He operates from an office tower instead. It's more
professional, but it's got half the view and none of the romance.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Carcosa was built above Kuala Lumpur in 1897 and 1898 as the
home of Sir Frank Swettenham, the first resident general of the
Federated Malay States. (At the time, the governor general still
lived in Singapore, long before its separation from what is now
called Malaysia.)
</P>
<P>
   Later, Swettenham wrote endless tomes about life in the Malay
Peninsula, in which he makes only passing reference to the mansion
he commissioned. But he had a flair for the dramatic _ the land
around Carcosa plunges straight into the jungle, then opens into
the formal Lake Gardens below, an effort by the British to create a
touch of Cotswold-like landscaping at the Equator.
</P>
<P>
   The house, on 40 acres, looks like a British summer mansion,
with some vaguely Moorish accents to the windows. Naturally
Swettenham reserved for himself the most spectacular of the house's
huge rooms, just over the front entrance, presumably so he could
keep an eye on the restless populace below.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he should have been watching the Japanese, who used the
house to make their top officers comfortable during World War II.
But by the time the British regained control of Malaya, life at
Carcosa wasn't quite as much fun. An insurgency to oust the British
dragged on for more than a decade, and the house was soon encircled
with barbed wire. (The property is still fenced in, as I discovered
on a hike.) But barbed wire alone could not protect the residents.
</P>
<P>
   One top British official living in Seri Negara, the adjacent
house on the property, went out for a weekend drive during ``the
emergency'' of the 1950s and never returned. His bullet-riddled
body was found by the road. (Undeterred, Richard Nixon stayed in
Seri Negara a few years later, as vice president.)
</P>
<P>
   Later the hotel became the backdrop for ``The Seventh Dawn,''
starring William Holden. Even after the creation of modern
Malaysia, the house became the residence of the British high
commissioner, and was outfitted with Oriental furniture. It became
a hotel in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place certainly has history,'' Vicky Manian told me, as he
escorted me up the sweeping grand staircase _ all teak, of course _
to my suite. It also has luxury. The suites are large _ big wooden
beds, comfortable sitting areas, marble baths with gold-plated
water works.
</P>
<P>
   There are now saunas and a gym in a pavilion behind Carcosa and
tennis courts and an outdoor pool. The biggest suite, called the
Grand Suite, comes with a private dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs in the main dining room, which looks more or less
like a generic country club, the walls are the same, but the
traditions have changed. The waiters no longer wear headdresses, a
staple of the official dinners in the '20s and '30s. The Filipino
band no longer plays on the veranda.
</P>
<P>
   But the dining room, which serves Malaysian and Continental
fare, remains a gathering place for Malaysia's political elite.
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad used to dine here with his deputy,
Anwar Ibrahim, before Mahathir felt threatened by the suave Anwar's
growing political popularity.
</P>
<P>
   These days the prime minister still drops in for an official
dinner now and again; Anwar eats nightly in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The political risks for visitors are far less _ you are free to
critique the curry and the breakneck drivers in Malaysia, just not
the prime minister _ and no one should miss Carcosa's famous curry
tiffin, a specialty on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   The economic risks are also slight, at least for now. My suite,
one of the midsized, cost about $200 a night, about half the rack
rate _ a reflection of the downturn in tourism after the Asian
economic crisis. Dinner was another $60 for two, without wine, and
the car service is extra as well, depending on time and distance.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not much more than you would pay for a luxury hotel
down in the shadow of the world's tallest skyscrapers. And down
there, no governor general ever ruled, no iguanas scamper about, no
Communist infiltrators ever tried to break through the barbed wire,
and no lazy ceiling fan clacks away as you read the paper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT &LR;      04-10 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNASSUMING SINGH FORCES FANS TO NOTICE HIM AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   People entered the Masters talking about Tiger Woods, but they
left the Masters talking about Vijay Singh.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is low key by nature, because his interviews are not
filled with one-liners, because he lacks the charisma of Woods,
Singh doesn't always receive the attention given to many of the
world's best players. But by winning his second major, Singh has
forced people to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   Only five players under the age of 40 have won two major
championships _ Singh, who is 37, Woods, John Daly, Ernie Els and
Lee Janzen. After winning the Masters in unflappable style by three
strokes on Sunday, Singh talked about the satisfaction of wearing
an Augusta National Golf Club green jacket, when many believed that
he never would.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you win one major, people may say you just had a good
week,'' said Singh, who won the PGA Championship in 1998. ``But
winning two majors kind of puts you on a different level.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh was on a level all his own during the final two rounds.
This Masters lacked some of the back-nine drama of recent years,
but Singh's steady play did not leave room for much drama. He took
a big step toward winning on Saturday, playing 14 superb holes at
two under par, dealing with gusts of 25 to 40 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   It took a ball-striker of the highest order to shoot under par
in those conditions, but ball-striking is Singh's forte. All of
those years of hitting balls on the range, earning his reputation
as one of the game's hardest workers, paid dividends for Singh, who
never wavered in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Sunday, Singh's pursuers gradually fell away, one by
one. Neither Phil Mickelson nor Davis Love III mounted a Sunday
charge. Duval made a costly bogey at No. 13, after a terrible
second shot into the water. Els kept missing putts on the back nine
that he needed to make. Woods failed to break 70 in the first two
rounds, and his shaky putting on Thursday and Friday may have cost
him the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Singh followed one of the classic mottoes in sports _
don't beat yourself. Jack Nicklaus followed that motto many times
in majors. And even when Singh did make a final-round blunder at
No. 11, hitting his second shot into the water, he minimized the
damage by scrambling for bogey to maintain the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Singh's victory will end speculation about Woods winning the
Grand Slam this year. Woods wanted this Masters badly, and he may
have won if he had putted better. But for any player, including
Woods, winning majors is always difficult. In fact, winning any
tournament is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Love, Duval, Els and Justin Leonard have all gone more than a
year without winning on tour. Both Duval and Mickelson, with 26
career victories between them, are still seeking their first major
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the entire week, with big names galore on the leader board,
was further evidence that the world's best players are stepping up
their games, which should be great for golf.
</P>
<P>
   Who says Woods doesn't have a rival? It may not be the same guy
week in and week out who challenges him. But plenty of players are
confident that despite Woods' presence there is plenty of winning
left for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how those who didn't win react to
the disappointment. Woods, Duval, Love, Mickelson and Els had all
been pointing toward the Masters since the year began, and Sunday
night had to be difficult for all of them. Golf can be a cruel
sport.
</P>
<P>
   The world's best tennis players win most of the time. The
world's best boxers win almost all the time. But the world's best
golfers taste defeat far more often than they experience victory.
No wonder so many golfers talk regularly to sports psychologists.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how good you are, it is impossible to have a long
career in golf without experiencing huge disappointments, and the
elite golfers must learn how to overcome them.
</P>
<P>
   During the next few tournaments, there will be somewhat of a
post-Masters lull until the weeks leading up the next major, the
U.S. Open in June at Pebble Beach, Calif. Singh has played well at
Pebble Beach, and he finished third in last year's U.S. Open at
Pinehurst, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Singh can savor a victory that was well deserved,
for a quiet family man from Fiji. It was further evidence that golf
is truly a global game. And as he wore his green jacket on Sunday
night, Singh felt like a man sitting on top of the world. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
