<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AMSTERDAM-MUSIC-REVIE     04-10 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMSTERDAM-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. MARK PASSION: PART BACH, PART PASTICHE, PART SHERLOCK HOLMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ruins inspire either engineers or mystics. The latter
stand among the broken columns hoping for moonlight and musing on
the folly of human aspiration. Engineers see a job left undone, or
in the case of Bach's ``St. Mark Passion,'' a job vanished with few
traces left behind. Restoration is their motto: build on existing
foundations, learn from history as you can; take a flyer on the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   The mystic sees deterioration as patina taken to extremes: a
thing made more beautiful by age and wear. For Ton Koopman, who
brought his reconstruction of the ``St. Mark Passion'' to the
Church of St. Ignatius Loyola on Sunday afternoon, nothing else but
a house in working order would do. Koopman had not even ruins to
work with, only a blueprint. The text for a ``St. Mark Passion''
appears in the complete poetic works of Picander, published at
Leipzig in 1731. Picander was librettist for the ``St. Matthew
Passion'' (which survives gloriously intact); Bach was responsible
for the city's Passion music.
</P>
<P>
   Bach, with his weekly load of music to provide for services,
borrowed extensively from himself. Therefore the music for the St.
Mark would necessarily be on loan, and would fit Picander's texts.
Some of Koopman's matchups are inspired. As the chorus jeers for
Jesus to descend from the cross (``Pfui dich, wie fein zerbrichts
du den Tempel''), the music obligingly plunges in a series of
chromatic scales.
</P>
<P>
   Passions by definition describe Christ's progress to the cross.
Embellishing the story is poetic commentary (choruses, vocal solos
and ensembles) and the four-part chorales, hymnlike pauses for
contemplation by both performers and congregation.
</P>
<P>
   From Picander we infer that the St. Mark was lighter on the
poetry than either the St. Matthew or the St. John but heavier on
chorales. Having literally hundreds to choose from, Koopman had
here perhaps his easiest time, and he has taken some of Bach's more
weirdly beautiful harmonizations. There are even more cantatas, and
from them Koopman has appropriated the appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The recitatives, the narration binding all these replacement
parts together, Koopman has composed himself, relying on his long
experience as a conductor and keyboard player in the early-music
wars. If Bach's own recitatives are filled with steep and sudden
modulation, the new ones go even farther. There were cliff-hanging
moments suspended between tonalities, difficult for both the
afternoon's splendid Evangelist Max Ciolek and the listener's ear
to manage.
</P>
<P>
   Before we can say what the ``St. Mark Passion'' really is we
have to know what to call it. In a way it is all-Bach with the
right text and a reasonable representation of the ``real thing.''
The narrative is followed clearly, and the individual pieces are
worth our while. On the other hand, Koopman's borrowed goods are
not the original composer's choice, and who knows what Bach would
have stolen from himself. Indeed, this St. Mark is a little like
staging ``Hamlet'' on the set of ``Twelfth Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe ``A Passion After Bach'' would say it best: a medley of
church pieces configured for Protestant worship at Easter. It can
be both practical (great sacred music fitted to the season) and a
scholar's parlor game (musicology that is part Sherlock Holmes,
part divination, part personal ego).
</P>
<P>
   Mystics, I think, would have invited Koopman to go away and
leave the ``St. Mark Passion'' alone. They might say that lost
Bach, along with the Mahler Tenth and Schubert ``Unfinished''
Symphonies, are best left in ruins, not treated as handyman's
specials. Andras Schiff often plays as an encore a ravishing
fragment of a Schubert piano piece, leaving it to break off in
midsentence. Left behind as he leaves the stage are the beauty of
the music, a wistfulness over the unknown and an added value: the
heightened sense of human aspiration in all its folly.
</P>
<P>
   Koopman's excellent Amsterdam Baroque Orchestra and Choir were
passionate believers in the ``St. Mark Passion,'' but Bach's more
complex counterpoint was generally blurred by its surroundings. If
St. Ignatius looks the part, its echoes are unfriendly to narrow
complication. The soloists, all good, were Deborah York, soprano;
Annette Markert, mezzo-soprano; Paul Agnew, tenor; and Peter Kooy
and Klaus Mertens, basses. The event was a presentation of Lincoln
Center's Great Performers series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
