<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16)  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Germany Plays Host To a World's Fair &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Expo 2000, Germany's first World's Fair, takes place June 1 to
Oct. 31 in historic Hanover. Forty million people are expected to
visit the city's 400-acre exhibition site for the five-month fair,
whose theme is ``Humankind, Nature and Technology.'' With a record
172 countries participating, Expo 2000 organizers promise a
diverse, ecologically oriented fair. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attractions include the Japanese Pavilion, built mostly from
recycled paper, and the Rueda de la Fortuna, a half-subterranean
Ferris wheel that plunges passengers from darkness into daylight
with every turn, created by Gabriel Orozco, a Mexican artist. The
French architect Jean Nouvel has contributed futuristic
installations called ``The Future of Work'' and ``Mobility,'' the
latter incorporating a representation of a space station.
</P>
<P>
   The Pan-African Pavilion features environmental topics, with
hundreds of butterflies from Kenya to add color. National Day
celebrations vary from ethnic dance and cultural performances by
more than 40 African states to a special appearance by the Vienna
Philharmonic (June 17). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nightly laser shows, open-air cinema, art exhibitions and 100
daily cultural events are part of a busy schedule at Expo 2000. A
marathon 21-hour production of Goethe's ``Faust,'' starring Bruno
Ganz, will have its premiere on July 22 and 23, and will be
performed 16 times.
</P>
<P>
   New ballets for the dance festival have been created by Ea Sola
from Vietnam, William Forsythe and Pina Bausch, and the eclectic
musical roster includes the Berlin Philharmonic, Carlos Santana and
700 concerts by international youth chorales. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two streetcar lines link Expo 2000 to central Hanover and a
bullet train links the Expo site to major German and European
cities, including Amsterdam. Individual day passes bought in
advance cost $34. Budget family or group plans are available.
Ticket information and event schedules are available through
www.expo2000.de or DER Travel at (847) 430-0000 and General Tours
Inc. at (603) 357-5033 or (800) 469-5186. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corinne LaBalme &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   National Parks Limit Use of Jet Skis &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The use of personal watercraft (Jet Skis, Sea-Doos and the like)
in the National Park system is no longer expanding without limits.
A new rule, effective April 20, bans them from 13 areas where they
have been in use, as well as from virtually all the other 379 units
of the service. Their use continues to be permitted, for the
moment, in 21 places. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this rule, in theory, you could back your car up to the
Reflecting Pool in Washington and put your personal watercraft
in,'' said David Barna, a parks spokesman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In nine sites, all National Recreation Areas with artificial
lakes that have extensive motorboating, as well as in the open
waters of Gateway National Recreation Area in New York,
personal-watercraft use may continue under ``prudent'' park
management. In 11 others, evaluation of the impact will continue
over two years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the rule, the service said that a dramatic
increase in personal-watercraft use had been noted in the 34 park
units where there is motorboating. All 34 fall under some part of
the new rule. ``This rule takes a conservative approach,'' the park
service rule said, ``based on consideration of potential resource
impacts, conflicts with other visitors' uses and enjoyment and
safety concerns.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the areas where jet skis are no longer permitted, Voyageurs,
near International Falls, Minn., is likely to provoke the most
controversy. When their use was first allowed there, the limits
were defined as the areas where snowmobiles were permitted in
winter. The possibility that snowmobiles may now also be restricted
is not ruled out by the park service. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A list of places where personal watercraft will be banned and
where they are still allowed is available on the Web at www
.nps.gov/refdesk/hotdocs.htm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Wade &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New Theater In the Heart of London &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Soho Theater and Writers' Center, a theater for new works,
has opened in London's Soho district. Built in a former synagogue,
it includes a 200-seat air-conditioned theater; spaces for
rehearsals, workshops and separate writers' rooms; and a
restaurant, a bar and a brasserie. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The theater is the new home of the Soho Theater Company, which
was founded in 1969 and has launched various playwrights, including
Hanif Kureishi, Timberlake Wertenbaker, Pam Gems and Sue Townsend.
It has co-produced plays with other companies, the Royal Court
among them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plays to be presented at the Soho Theater in the coming months
are ``Jump Malinoff, Jump,'' by Toby Whithouse, a comedy about
Russian immigrants in England, through May 13; ``Be My Baby,'' by
Amanda Whittington, about unwed mothers, from May 18 to June 17;
and ``Angels and Saints'' by Jessica Townsend, about the spiritual
and sexual awakening of a middle-aged spinster, from May 18 to June
17. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices range from $8 for previews to $17.50 on Friday and
Saturday. The Soho Theater and Writers' Center is at 21 Dean
Street. Information: (44-207) 478-0100; www .sohotheatre.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Birthday Parties at the Library of Congress &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In celebration of the bicentennial of its founding on April 24,
1800, the Library of Congress in Washington will present two
exhibitions.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas Jefferson,'' from April 24 to Oct. 31, pays tribute to
the third president, a prime force in the founding of the Library
of Congress. After the British burned the library in the Capitol in
1814, Jefferson sold 6,487 books to the government. More than 2,000
of them that survived an 1851 fire, as well as replacements, will
be on display for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, letters, documents and drawings will illuminate
Jefferson's complexities and contradictions. Featured items include
the original ``Rough draught'' of the Declaration of Independence
in Jefferson's hand, account books from his Monticello plantation
showing items purchased from slave families, and his instructions
to Lewis and Clark as they undertook their search for a land route
to the Pacific. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wizard of Oz: An American Fairy Tale,'' opening on Friday
and continuing through Sept. 23, will mark the 100th anniversary of
one of the best-known copyrights ever issued by the Library of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will see L. Frank Baum's handwritten application to
copyright ``The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'' in 1900. Film clips, movie
props, photographs and other artifacts will be on display. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A free birthday party on April 24 from noon to 2 p.m. on the
Thomas Jefferson Building's Neptune Plaza will feature a few
``living legends.'' Guests will include Gen. Colin Powell, Maurice
Sendak, and Big Bird from ``Sesame Street.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both exhibitions are in the Library's Jefferson Building, 10
First Street SE on Capitol Hill, and both are free. Information:
(202) 707-2000 or www.loc.gov. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Katherine House &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
