are eight ushers left, all in their 60s through 80s, and they will
likely become extinct after this season because during
negotiations, the Yankees claimed they could no longer afford to
pay the ushers their $72 a game salary because they needed it for
players salaries. Irwin Schifren, one of the last ushers, during an
interview, Monday. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PITTSBURGH -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-FRUIT-FLY -- The
Drosophila fruit fly, whose genome was just decoded, has attained
vast prominence in human affairs because it is one of the principal
model organisms studied by biologists as a means of understanding
the general design of life. Because of the unity of evolution, the
fly's genes and those of people overlap considerably. From left:
Human Genome Project members Susan Celniker, Gerald Rubin, Mark
Adams, Gene Meyers, Susanna lewis and Craig Venter gathered at a
meeting last month on the fly. (Gary Tramontina/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) VINALES, Cuba -- April 10, 2000 -- CUBA-JOURNAL-3-COX --
Tourists look over souvenirs in the Valley of Vinales after getting
out of their air-conditioned tour bus in the Pinar del Rio
province. Che Guevara shirts, literature, and calendars are very
popular. Cuba is changing rapidly, and the postcard views of1950
DeSotos and Buicks chugging down picturesque streets are rapidly
giving way to tour buses and resorts. (David Tulis/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HAVANA -- April 10, 2000 -- CUBA-JOURNAL-2-COX -- Many
Cubans love their music and the oceanside boulevard of the Malecon
is a favorite spot to practice their tunes. Erin Garcia Atencio,
right, on the saxophone and Felix Martinez Borero, on the trombone,
say the ocean provides them with a pleasant place to practice.
(David Tulis/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HAVANA -- April 10, 2000 -- CUBA-JOURNAL-1-COX -- A full
moon over Havana harbor and its Malecon boulevard. The Hotel
Nacional, left, which opened in 1930, is seen in this view from
atop the Capri Hotel. Forty years of communist rule, along with
four decades of a U.S. economic embargo, have left this gorgeous
island in something of a time warp. While Americans cannot legally
visit the island unless they are journalists, visiting family or on
educational or cultural exchanges, thousands of U.S. visitors are
slipping into Cuba each year by flying to the Bahamas or Mexico and
taking connecting flights. (David Tulis/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- MARINE-PLANE-CRASH -- The
Pentagon killed the V-22 Osprey 11 years ago. Too expensive, too
experimental, it said. But the plane, a hybrid
helicopter/turboprop, wouldn't die. Congress kept it alive. Now
three of the 15 finished craft have crashed, killing 26 soldiers.
The aircraft remains expensive, experimental and exemplary of the
way weapons are built for today's military. Two Bell-Boeing V-22
Ospreys fly in formation during flight testing in this undated
photo. (Beoing/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-GORILLA-TECH-2 --
American and Rwandan researchers are using satellites and aircraft
to map the habitat of gorillas in the Virunga conservation area.
Rwandan officials hope the technology will benefit the country in
other ways as it recovers from years of war. A satellite image
showing the conservation area. (Georgia Tech/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-VAROS-2 -- Remedios
Varo, considered one of the greatest surrealist painters of the 2th
century, is at last beginning to receive international acclaim,
including the admiration of a cadre not always known for its
arthouse savvy: the scientific community. In a recent symposium, an
expert described how the artist metaphorically conveyed some of the
most revolutionary and complex scientific theories of the age, from
Einstein's special theory of relativity and Darwin's theory of
evolution by natural selection to the premise that humans are the
stuff of stars. Varo's Creacion de las aves (Creation of the
Birds),1957. (The National Museum of Women in the Arts/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-VAROS-1 -- Remedios
Varo, considered one of the greatest surrealist painters of the
20th century, is at last beginning to receive international
acclaim, including the admiration of a cadre not always known for
its arthouse savvy: the scientific community. In a recent
symposium, an expert described how the artist metaphorically
conveyed some of the most revolutionary and complex scientific
theories of the age, from Einstein's special theory of relativity
and Darwin's theory of evolution by natural selection to the
premise that humans are the stuff of stars. Varo's Papilla estelar
(Celestial Pablum), 1958. (The National Museum of Women in the
Arts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) VIRUNGA CONSERVATION AREA, Rwanda -- April 10, 2000 --
SCI-GORILLA-TECH -- American and Rwandan researchers are using
satellites and aircraft to map the habitat of gorillas like Ruhuka,
a 6-month-old female, in the Virunga conservation area. Rwandan
officials hope the technology will benefit the country in other
ways as it recovers from years of war. (Liz Williamson/Dian Fossey
Gorilla Fund International/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-HEPATITIS-C -- The
discovery of 50-year-old Army blood samples is helping scientists
determine what the best course of treatment may be for hepatitis C.
Edward Woodland, who whose blood was tested for something unrelated
while in the Army and was tracked down after all these years, is
living proof that the virus need not be a death knell or even a
threat to health. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
