<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2851 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-ASIA-ECON-$ADV     04-10 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ASIA-ECON-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARGAINS ARE FADING IN ASIA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bad news these days about travel to eastern Asia is that the
region has reverted from being the certifiable steal that it was at
the height of the economic crisis two years ago to once again being
comparably priced with many other parts of the world _ or even
pricier.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, if that's the right term when bargains are
evaporating, is that the region's many currencies seem finally to
have stabilized, and budgeting for travel once again seems possible
throughout much of the area, even when making reservations a few
months in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Most Asian currencies have strengthened handsomely from their
lows of two years ago, accounting for the largest rise in costs for
travel by Americans and others with United States dollars. A
dramatic case in point is Japan, where the yen has appreciated by
22 percent since early April 1998, to about 105 yen to the dollar
from about 135 yen.
</P>
<P>
   Prices in yen have scarcely changed in two years' time; indeed
many have decreased marginally in the recession that hangs over the
country. But that will be little comfort to holders of dollars, who
will have to buy yen at a much higher rate.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Tokyo today will pay about 44,000 yen, about $420,
to stay in a double-occupancy room at the Okura Hotel, one of the
city's top business hotels, and 38,000, $360, for one in the Westin
Tokyo, another favorite among visiting business people. Those rates
in yen have barely budged in the last two years. Unfortunately, the
difference in dollars _ an increase of close to $100 in each case _
will be keenly felt.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long time since Japan has been considered a
bargain by travelers from anywhere. For many visitors _ and
residents _ it often seems to be the most expensive place on the
planet, what with tiny $5 cups of coffee and taxis whose meters
start at $6.50.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best bargains, though, remains the Japan Rail Pass,
available from the Japan National Tourist Organization offices in
the United States. A one-week pass, which covers wide-ranging tours
of the country aboard Japan's famous bullet trains, is 28,300 yen,
or about $270 at current exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   In China, the currency is held steady by a government-fixed
exchange rate. Room rates in Beijing have remained fairly stable as
well. Double rooms are available at the China World Hotel in
Beijing for $210, plus 15 percent service and tax charge. Another
central city establishment, the New World Hotel, offers doubles for
$120, including breakfast, service charge and tax.
</P>
<P>
   In Thailand, a favorite tourist destination for visitors from
both the West and elsewhere in Asia, prices have been on a slow,
steady rebound since the Asian currency crisis. Compared with
precrisis days, many of the country's top hotels are still a
bargain, but if the current trend continues, that won't be true for
very long.
</P>
<P>
   At the high-end Shangri-La in Bangkok, a double now goes for
$210, including breakfast, laundry and dry cleaning, rising to $290
for a deluxe room. Scarcely three years ago, those rooms were $220
and $310, respectively. In the interim, though, a standard double
had fallen to as little as $180.
</P>
<P>
   And at the legendary Oriental Hotel, the rate is $250 a room,
single or double occupancy, plus 10 percent service charge and 7.7
percent tax, up from $220 two years ago. The Westin Banyan Tree's
doubles are $190, up from about $150 two years ago. And the Delta
Grand Pacific, a popular destination for more-budget-oriented
travelers offers doubles for $85, plus service and tax charges, up
from $75 two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For beach vacationers, a week for two at the Club Med Phuket is
$3,200, including three meals a day, drinks and sports activities.
That high-season rate falls to $1,400 for the same package during
the off season. These are the same as two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Singapore, the venerable Raffles Hotel says its rates haven't
changed in two years, with a double costing $700, plus 10 percent
service, 1 percent government tax and 1 percent goods and services
tax. A double at the Westin Plaza is also unchanged from 1998:
$360, plus tax.
</P>
<P>
   No country was harder hit by the region's currency collapse than
Indonesia. At the height of the country's woes, deluxe taxis could
be chartered for less than $10 a day, and rooms at the Shangri-La
in Jakarta, with its marble-clad health club, could be had for
under $100.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia remains the region's best bargain. It has gone through
rocky political times with the secession of East Timor and the
recent presidential elections. Indonesia's currency has been rising
slowly, but visitors will find that prices are far below precrisis
levels and still eminently reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   The Shangri-La, for example, offers double rooms for $155, plus
21 percent for tax and service, and doubles can be had at the
Crowne Plaza Jakarta, another top hotel, for a mere $88, with
breakfast included. At the Westin Surabaya, doubles are $63, and
deluxe rooms are $79, including breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The dream air fare to Asia _ $999 round trip for two people from
the United States to Hong Kong on Cathay Pacific, with five nights'
lodging included _ offered briefly in 1997, may have been the
ultimate deal. But air fare to Asia is still a relative bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay has expanded its $999 round-trip all-Asia pass, which
allows a traveler to visit 16 cities in 30 days; departures from
the United States are from New York, San Francisco or Los Angeles,
with the first and last stop in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet search this month for the lowest air fare from Los
Angeles to Bangkok found $555 on China Airlines and $559 on Korean
Airlines. Continental, Northwest, American and United Airlines all
offered a $638 ticket, just over half of what it was in spring
1997. The best price for a mid-May departure was $680 on Northwest
and Thai.
</P>
<P>
   Not all cities are quite that cheap, though: the lowest Los
Angeles-Tokyo fare for mid-May departure was $811 on Korean Air and
Northwest. The best New York-Tokyo fare for mid-May was $1,161 on
four airlines, which was $200 less than a month earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
