<P>
   (NYT26) SHENYANG, China -- April 10, 2000 -- CHINA-NEIGHBOHRHOOD
-- For urban Chinese who are middle-aged and beyond, the old
``neighborhood committees'' that watched over every household are
among the more obnoxious memories of the early decades of Communist
rule. Now, with experiments in Shenyang and 19 other cities, the
government is trying to reinvent this venerable institution. Guo
Lingbo, 51, heads the Yonghuan Community Administrative Committee,
overseeing 1,800 households. (Erik Eckholm/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- MAGAZINE-ADS-2 -- Toss them
on a desk, and you'll hear what publishers like to refer to as
``the thud factor.'' (The louder the thud! thunk! or boom! the
better.) As the economy continues to thrive, some magazines have
become so fat with advertising that the editorial content is
sometimes relegated to the increasingly hard-to-find nether reaches
of the publication. (Naum Kazhdan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- MAGAZINE-ADS-1 -- In Style,
Vogue, Vanity Fair and W have all in the last year blown past their
records for size, heft and length. They are part of a growing
breed: the obese magazine, publications so fat that if they were
people, they might spend their time in a high school auditorium
sweating to the oldies with Richard Simmons. (Naum Kazhdan/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- IRIDIUM -- The jokes about
the government using the satellites for ``Star Wars'' target
practice don't seem so funny anymore. In the coming months, Iridium
L.L.C., the bankrupt global satellite telephone company, will begin
sending 88 giant satellites, like this one depicted in an artist's
rendering, spiraling toward Earth. The satellites will burn up in
the atmosphere a fitting and fiery end to one of the colossal
corporate failures in recent memory. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ALBANY, N.Y, -- April 10, 2000 -- NY-LOBBY -- After
years of late-night dinners, indulging in steaks and sweets as
eager lobbyists picked up the tab, State Senator Thomas Libous,
right, won many a friend but lost his svelte figure. Then he
embraced a sure-fire diet: a new code of ethics. Libous serves
salad while having dinner with fellow legislators Sen. Nicholas
Spano, center, and George Maziarz at Spano's apartment recently.
(David Jennings/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-ASTEROID-B&AMP;W -- Taking
cautious baby steps, a robotic spacecraft is to settle Tuesday into
a closer orbit of an asteroid it has been circling for almost two
months. The craft, NEAR Shoemaker, is taking up a circular orbit 62
miles from the center of the asteroid Eros for more detailed
studies. The asteroid montage, below, was provided by the
spacecraft earlier this year. The asteroid Mathilde, above, was
photographed on the craft's way to the Eros. (NASA/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- TV-FAILSAFE-REVIEW-B&AMP;W --
Brian Dennehy as the general, flanked by John Diehl, left, and
James Cromwell, in the television production of ``Fail Safe.'' In
many ways, ``Fail Safe,'' broadcast live to much of the country on
Sunday night, lived up to its billing as an event. It proved that
TV's intimate immediacy is an underused asset waiting to be
exploited in the service of compelling storytelling. (CBS/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-BIG-ICEBERGS-B&AMP;W -- Two
mammoth icebergs have broken off the Antarctic ice cap in the last
several weeks, including one that is the largest in more than four
decades. The B-15 iceberg, shown in an infrared image from March
27, is about 185 miles long by 23 miles wide, and is apparently
exceeded only by an iceberg that formed in 1956. (NOAA/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- April 10, 2000 -- TINA-TURNER-REVIEW -- Tina
Turner, 61 and seemingly inexhaustible, ranged across 40 years of
music during a concert at Madison Square Garden on Friday night.
Turner has long since staked out her archetype: the strong, lusty
woman who has grown tougher with every setback and every betrayal.
It's an image that is reinforced by her songs, her autobiography,
her leathery voice and her leonine presence. (Ruth Fremson/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- April 10, 2000 -- TV-DIANNA-ROSS -- ``Get
the fringe,'' demanded Diana Ross, at her VH1 tribute show. Ross
lived up to her billing as the ultimate diva at the taping on
Sunday night for VH1's ``Divas 2000,'' which is to be shown Tuesday
night at 9. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- EUROPE-SHOCK-TV --
Contestants in the ``Chains of Love'' television show with host
Ariane Spieron, right. European television producer John de Mol's
latest brainstorm is a post-millenial evolution of ``The Dating
Game'' in which contestants compete for a date while chained
together for up to five days in handcuffs and ankle irons. (The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- April 10, 2000 -- COWARD-THEATER-REVIEW --
Paxton Whitehead and Hayley Mills in ``Shadows of the Evening,''
one of two one-act Noel Coward plays which opened Monday night at
the Lucille Lortel Theater.. The show isn't really a departure from
familiar Coward formulas; it feels instead like a variation on the
stiff-upper-lip sentimentality of his patriotic plays and
screenplays. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- April 10, 2000 -- TIMES-APPOINT -- The
appointment of Tom Bodkin as an assistant managing editor of The
New York Times was announced Monday by Joseph Lelyveld, the
executive editor. Bodkin, 47, was formerly an associate managing
editor. He retains the additional title of design director, heading
the paper's art department, including the information graphics and
news design staffs. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- ROME-EXHIBIT-2 -- Giuseppe
Cades' self-portrait is on view in ``The Splendor of 18th-Ccentury
Rome'' at the Philadelphia Museum. The exhibit sets out to show
that Rome in the 18th century - not Paris - was the cultural
capital of Europe. (Galleria dell'Accademia Nazionale de San
Luca/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- ROME-EXHIBIT-1 -- Benedetto
Luti's ``Education of Cupid,'' is on view in ``The Splendor of
18th-Ccentury Rome'' at the Philadelphia Museum. The exhibit sets
out to show that Rome in the 18th century - not Paris - was the
cultural capital of Europe. (The Philadelphia Museum/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 10, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-USHERS -- The
hundreds of ushers that once worked Yankee Stadium have steadily
been replaced by beefy security guards over the years. Now there
are eight ushers left, all in their 60s through 80s, and they will
likely become extinct after this season because during
negotiations, the Yankees claimed they could no longer afford to
pay the ushers their $72 a game salary because they needed it for
players salaries. Irwin Schifren, one of the last ushers, during an
interview, Monday. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PITTSBURGH -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-FRUIT-FLY -- The
Drosophila fruit fly, whose genome was just decoded, has attained
vast prominence in human affairs because it is one of the principal
model organisms studied by biologists as a means of understanding
the general design of life. Because of the unity of evolution, the
fly's genes and those of people overlap considerably. From left:
Human Genome Project members Susan Celniker, Gerald Rubin, Mark
Adams, Gene Meyers, Susanna lewis and Craig Venter gathered at a
meeting last month on the fly. (Gary Tramontina/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) VINALES, Cuba -- April 10, 2000 -- CUBA-JOURNAL-3-COX --
Tourists look over souvenirs in the Valley of Vinales after getting
out of their air-conditioned tour bus in the Pinar del Rio
province. Che Guevara shirts, literature, and calendars are very
popular. Cuba is changing rapidly, and the postcard views of1950
DeSotos and Buicks chugging down picturesque streets are rapidly
giving way to tour buses and resorts. (David Tulis/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HAVANA -- April 10, 2000 -- CUBA-JOURNAL-2-COX -- Many
Cubans love their music and the oceanside boulevard of the Malecon
is a favorite spot to practice their tunes. Erin Garcia Atencio,
right, on the saxophone and Felix Martinez Borero, on the trombone,
say the ocean provides them with a pleasant place to practice.
(David Tulis/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HAVANA -- April 10, 2000 -- CUBA-JOURNAL-1-COX -- A full
moon over Havana harbor and its Malecon boulevard. The Hotel
Nacional, left, which opened in 1930, is seen in this view from
atop the Capri Hotel. Forty years of communist rule, along with
four decades of a U.S. economic embargo, have left this gorgeous
island in something of a time warp. While Americans cannot legally
visit the island unless they are journalists, visiting family or on
educational or cultural exchanges, thousands of U.S. visitors are
slipping into Cuba each year by flying to the Bahamas or Mexico and
taking connecting flights. (David Tulis/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- MARINE-PLANE-CRASH -- The
Pentagon killed the V-22 Osprey 11 years ago. Too expensive, too
experimental, it said. But the plane, a hybrid
helicopter/turboprop, wouldn't die. Congress kept it alive. Now
three of the 15 finished craft have crashed, killing 26 soldiers.
The aircraft remains expensive, experimental and exemplary of the
way weapons are built for today's military. Two Bell-Boeing V-22
Ospreys fly in formation during flight testing in this undated
photo. (Beoing/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-GORILLA-TECH-2 --
American and Rwandan researchers are using satellites and aircraft
to map the habitat of gorillas in the Virunga conservation area.
Rwandan officials hope the technology will benefit the country in
other ways as it recovers from years of war. A satellite image
showing the conservation area. (Georgia Tech/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-VAROS-2 -- Remedios
Varo, considered one of the greatest surrealist painters of the
20th century, is at last beginning to receive international
acclaim, including the admiration of a cadre not always known for
its arthouse savvy: the scientific community. In a recent
symposium, an expert described how the artist metaphorically
conveyed some of the most revolutionary and complex scientific
theories of the age, from Einstein's special theory of relativity
and Darwin's theory of evolution by natural selection to the
premise that humans are the stuff of stars. Varo's Creacion de las
aves (Creation of the Birds),1957. (The National Museum of Women in
the Arts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-VAROS-1 -- Remedios
Varo, considered one of the greatest surrealist painters of the
20th century, is at last beginning to receive international
acclaim, including the admiration of a cadre not always known for
its arthouse savvy: the scientific community. In a recent
symposium, an expert described how the artist metaphorically
conveyed some of the most revolutionary and complex scientific
theories of the age, from Einstein's special theory of relativity
and Darwin's theory of evolution by natural selection to the
premise that humans are the stuff of stars. Varo's Papilla estelar
(Celestial Pablum), 1958. (The National Museum of Women in the
Arts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) VIRUNGA CONSERVATION AREA, Rwanda -- April 10, 2000 --
SCI-GORILLA-TECH -- American and Rwandan researchers are using
satellites and aircraft to map the habitat of gorillas like Ruhuka,
a 6-month-old female, in the Virunga conservation area. Rwandan
officials hope the technology will benefit the country in other
ways as it recovers from years of war. (Liz Williamson/Dian Fossey
Gorilla Fund International/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- April 10, 2000 -- SCI-HEPATITIS-C -- The
discovery of 50-year-old Army blood samples is helping scientists
determine what the best course of treatment may be for hepatitis C.
Edward Woodland, who whose blood was tested for something unrelated
while in the Army and was tracked down after all these years, is
living proof that the virus need not be a death knell or even a
threat to health. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
