<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 04/10/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) WASHINGTON -- April 10, 2000 -- MICROSOFT-LOBBY -- Ralph
Reed's lobbying company has a new client: Microsoft. Reed is
quietly lobbying prominent supporters of George W. Bush to write
the Texas governor and probable Republican presidential candidate,
saying that he should take a stand against the government's
prosecution of Microsoft. But Reed's firm has another major client:
Bush himself. Reed, the former executive director of the Christian
Coalition, on Capitol Hill in a 1997 photo. (Stephen Crowley/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) NEW YORK -- April 10, 2000 -- H&AMP;M-FASHION-3 -- Judging
by the throngs descending on H&AMP;M, the new Fifth Avenue clothing
store, many shoppers regard it as a retail Nirvana. To keep the
clothes racks filled, workers unload at least a truckload of
merchandise each hour. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- April 10, 2000 -- H&AMP;M-FASHION-2 -- Judging
by the throngs descending on H&AMP;M, the new Fifth Avenue clothing
store, many shoppers regard it as a retail Nirvana. From left: a
shopper in the store, Becky Bahling, an actress, models the caramel
leather coat she bought for $170; a model in a fitted white poplin
shirt, which is $19, and a pair of hot-pink leather pants, at $129;
model in H&AMP;M merchandise: a $19 cotton sweater and a $109 pair of
suede boot-leg trousers. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- April 10, 2000 -- H&AMP;M-FASHION-1 -- Even in
the morning, well before the lunch (aka shopping) hour, crowds,
left, are large at the new H&AMP;M store on Fifth Avenue. Mattie
Ullrich, a costume designer and an enthusiastic shopper, right,
called this $17 tiger-print camisole ``the coolest thing in the
store.'' (Ruby Washington/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- April 10, 2000 -- LIBBY-PATAKI -- Libby
Pataki, wife of Gov. George E. Pataki, left the business world to
focus on family life. ``My children understand that they have to
share their father,'' Mrs. Pataki, 49, said. (The children are
Emily, 21; Ted, 18; Allison, 15; and George Owen, 12.) ``But there
is nothing in the rule book that says they have to share their
mother. One of us gone is bad enough.'' (Librado Romero/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- OBIT-STOKOE-B&AMP;W -- William
C. Stokoe Jr., an iconoclastic linguistics professor whose
championing of sign language helped change the way deaf people are
educated around the world, died April 4 at his home in Chevy Chase,
Md. He was 80. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) EL PASO, Texas -- April 10, 2000 -- TEXAS-BUSH-HEALTH --
Health care for children is a particular issue in Texas, with 39.1
percent of low-income children uninsured. Last week, at a clinic in
El Paso, Ismael Acosta, 10, had his blood pressure checked by a
nurse, Maria Moreno. (Bruce Berman/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNION CITY, N.J. -- April 10, 2000 -- NJ-CUBANS-2 --
Hudson County, a densely populated blue-collar area just across the
Hudson from Manhattan, is home to the biggest bloc of Cuban
immigrants outside Dade County, Fla. Union City's mayor, Raul
Garcia, 36, who was born in Cuba but grew up here, said that many
of the childhood friends who left town after college have been
returning. ``I think we'll become chic, sort of a Cuban Hoboken,''
said Garcia, who spoke with a city employee in Garcia's waiting
room, framed by busts of Abraham Lincoln, left, and Jose Marti.
(Norman Y. Lono/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- April 10, 2000 -- NY-GIULIANI-SENATE --
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has begun a series of statewide ``Women for
Rudy'' lunches to reinforce his support among Republican female
voters. Giuliani was at the Women's National Republican Club on
Monday, seated between Ninfa Segarra and Irene H. Impellizzeri, his
school board appointees. The woman standing with them was not
identified. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNION CITY, N.J. -- April 10, 2000 -- NJ-CUBANS-1 --
Cuban-Americans mustered 200 or so demonstrators last week for a
march along Bergenline Avenue in Union City, demanding that Elian
Gonzalez remain in the United States and not be returned to Cuba.
Along with the other towns of Hudson County, this densely populated
blue-collar city just across the Hudson from Manhattan is home to
the biggest bloc of Cuban immigrants outside Dade County, Fla.
(Norman Y. Lono/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- OBIT-LAUBIN-B&AMP;W -- Reginald
Laubin, who performed dances of American Plains Indians in the
1940s and '50s, died Wednesday at a hospital in Urbana, Ill. He was
96 and lived in Urbana and in Moose, Wyo. Though not an American
Indian, Laubin, shown performing in 1936, gained respect for his
accurate and dignified portrayals of Indian dances. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) SHENYANG, China -- April 10, 2000 -- CHINA-NEIGHBOHRHOOD
-- For urban Chinese who are middle-aged and beyond, the old
``neighborhood committees'' that watched over every household are
among the more obnoxious memories of the early decades of Communist
rule. Now, with experiments in Shenyang and 19 other cities, the
government is trying to reinvent this venerable institution. Guo
Lingbo, 51, heads the Yonghuan Community Administrative Committee,
overseeing 1,800 households. (Erik Eckholm/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- MAGAZINE-ADS-2 -- Toss them
on a desk, and you'll hear what publishers like to refer to as
``the thud factor.'' (The louder the thud! thunk! or boom! the
better.) As the economy continues to thrive, some magazines have
become so fat with advertising that the editorial content is
sometimes relegated to the increasingly hard-to-find nether reaches
of the publication. (Naum Kazhdan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- MAGAZINE-ADS-1 -- In Style,
Vogue, Vanity Fair and W have all in the last year blown past their
records for size, heft and length. They are part of a growing
breed: the obese magazine, publications so fat that if they were
people, they might spend their time in a high school auditorium
sweating to the oldies with Richard Simmons. (Naum Kazhdan/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- April 10, 2000 -- IRIDIUM -- The jokes about
the government using the satellites for ``Star Wars'' target
practice don't seem so funny anymore. In the coming months, Iridium
L.L.C., the bankrupt global satellite telephone company, will begin
sending 88 giant satellites, like this one depicted in an artist's
rendering, spiraling toward Earth. The satellites will burn up in
the atmosphere a fitting and fiery end to one of the colossal
corporate failures in recent memory. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ALBANY, N.Y, -- April 10, 2000 -- NY-LOBBY -- After
years of late-night dinners, indulging in steaks and sweets as
eager lobbyists picked up the tab, State Senator Thomas Libous,
right, won many a friend but lost his svelte figure. Then he
embraced a sure-fire diet: a new code of ethics. Libous serves
