<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.D., Calif., R.I.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH FILLS COMMITTEE POSTS: As part of the inevitably tightening
coordination between the Bush campaign and Republicans nationally,
three Republican officials who have advised Gov. George W. Bush or
raised money for him are moving to the Republican National
Committee. Fred Meyer, a former chairman of the Republican party in
Texas, will be chairman of the committee's Victory 2000 effort; he
will work alongside Jim Nicholson, the chairman of the committee,
to represent the Bush campaign's interests. Maria Cino, who served
as the political director for the Bush campaign, will become the
deputy chairman for political and congressional relations. And
Jeanne Johnson Phillips, a longtime fund-raiser for Bush, will
become deputy chairman for finance.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Frank Bruni
</P>
<P>
   THE SENATE
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN HELPS CHAFEE: Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., stumped in Rhode
Island on Saturday for Sen. Lincoln Chafee, who is unopposed in the
Republican primary for the seat he gained by appointment after his
father, Sen. John H. Chafee, died in October. The effort was
clearly advantageous to Chafee, as McCain appealed to independent
voters, who make up more than half of Rhode Island's electorate and
who helped him score a Super Tuesday victory in the state. Chafee
will face either Lt. Gov. Richard Licht, who was endorsed by the
state Democratic party last week, or Rep. Bob Weygand, who leads in
opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RACES
</P>
<P>
   NORTH DAKOTA CANDIDATE CHOSEN: At their state convention on
Sunday, North Dakota Democrats nominated Heidi Heitkamp, the
state's popular attorney general, for governor. The Republicans
have nominated John Hoeven, the president of the North Dakota State
Bank. The current governor, Ed Schafer, a Republican, is leaving
office after serving two terms. Democrats say they will make the
male-dominated hierarchy of the state Republican Party an issue in
the fall election.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Dirk Johnson
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES INCUMBENT TRAILS: L.A. District Attorney Gil
Garcetti, who has faced harsh criticism for his handling of a
police corruption scandal, is placing a surprisingly distant second
in the race to retain his job, according to a poll published
Monday. A survey by The Los Angeles Times of 2,202 Los Angeles
County residents found that if the election had been held a week
ago, Garcetti would have won only 18 percent of the vote, compared
with 55 percent for his challenger, Steve Cooley, who is a deputy
in the district attorney's office. Twenty-six percent of those
surveyed were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   _ By James Sterngold
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES:
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Cleveland, Columbia, Mo., and St. Louis
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Columbus, Ohio, and Washington
</P>
