u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-PROSPECTS-N     04-10 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-PROSPECTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL CASTS SUSPICIOUS GAZE OVER PROSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few in the National Football League can remember a time when so
many league and team executives were so concerned about the actions
of players away from the field.
</P>
<P>
   There is no better example of this than an interview one team
recently had with a player who was expected to be a fifth- or
sixth-round selection at the college draft this weekend. The
21-year-old admitted to smoking marijuana once when he was 15 and
again when he was 18.
</P>
<P>
   The team removed him from its draft board.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question about it: The NFL and its teams are
intensifying their examination of players entering the draft.
</P>
<P>
   This practice is manifesting itself in a number of ways. One is
in the league's background checks of draft-eligible players. Each
year the NFL examines the backgrounds of college prospects, but
according to one owner, the league showed extra caution this time
around.
</P>
<P>
   The league investigated 323 draft-eligible players, checking
criminal records, interviewing law enforcement officials at the
players' colleges, as well as speaking to coaches, friends and even
the players themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Of the players who were checked, 68 of them _ or about one in
five _ had what the league called ``reportable information,''
meaning there was some aspect of the player's background that
raised eyebrows on the league's security staff. The transgressions
ranged from speeding tickets to drug possession, fights, and
violations of National Collegiate Athletic Association rules.
</P>
<P>
   What do the numbers mean? They present a good news-bad news
scenario for the NFL. The good news is that the vast majority of
players coming into the sport from the college ranks have no marks
on their records. So when the draft begins on Saturday at Madison
Square Garden, teams will mostly be stocking up on players without
troubled pasts.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that of those 68 players, some have encountered
serious problems. That means dozens of potential headaches are
entering a sport already reeling from negative headlines about
off-field incidents involving its players, including the former
Carolina Panther Rae Carruth and Baltimore's Ray Lewis, both of
whom have been charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   Background checks are not unusual. Each season NFL security
officials do extensive checks on the players' pasts. And it is hard
to compare how 68 players with so-called reportable information
compare to other years, because such information is not normally
made public and thus is not available.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is little doubt that prospects are receiving extra
scrutiny in this draft as part of the league's aggressive attempt
to clean up its image.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL office isn't alone in taking serious precautions when it
comes to drafting college players. An increasing number of
individual teams are combining their security personnel with the
league's resources to insure that nothing is missed. Some teams,
like the Jets, have done this for years, but others are catching
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a list'' said Jacksonville Coach Tom Coughlin,
referring to its scrutiny of college players with problems. ``We
have always graded heavily for circumstances, and we have a code
that represents a particular player.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if off-field conduct will be a major factor in this week's
draft, Coughlin said: ``No question it will be an issue. That's all
we talked about at the league meetings, over and over and over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials expect fewer teams to take large leaps of faith
with troubled players, as has happened regularly in the past.
Lawrence Phillips, the former St. Louis and Miami running back, had
a history of violence against women while at the University of
Nebraska but he was still a first-round draft pick of the Rams in
1996. If Phillips were coming out of college now with the same
troubles, scouts said, he would not be drafted nearly as high.
</P>
<P>
   One NFC general manager said he knows firsthand of a dozen teams
that have pulled at least five players from their draft boards in
recent days because those players had worrisome backgrounds. ``I
think more players are being crossed off than ever before,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   the Baltimore Ravens' owner, Art Modell, said: ``There is more
emphasis by all teams, I think, to draft players with top
character. And teams are now making sure they get all the
information they can on a player.''
</P>
<P>
   But what will happen when a college player arrives _ and one
will _ who has the talent of Lawrence Taylor but the moral code of
Genghis Khan? Will teams be so sure of themselves then?
</P>
<P>
   They may be forced to, as the NFL continues to study possible
new initiatives and penalties for players who are arrested,
including stronger punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Teams may finally be getting the message: what is the use of
investing millions of dollars in a player who might be suspended
for most of his career because of multiple arrests?
</P>
<P>
   Teams also have another concern: is everyone overreacting?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to remember these are kids,'' Modell said. ``A
misdemeanor from a long time ago is not the total picture. We have
to look at the total picture.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
