<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HIGHTECH-AD-COLUMN-NY     04-10 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHTECH-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITION INTENSIFIES IN FAST-MOVING HIGH-TECH REALM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y., Pa.)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As 3Com makes plans to become a much smaller networking
solutions company, shedding several slower-growing operations,
executives have decided to change agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco office of FCB Worldwide, which has handled the
3Com account since the company consolidated agencies in October
1997, is losing the assignment, effective on July 1, to the New
York office of Lowe Lintas &AMP; Partners. FCB San Francisco will
continue as the agency for the Palm computing unit, which is being
spun out of 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   The 3Com account is the first major gain for Lowe Lintas, part
of the Lowe Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies, since
the agency was formed last fall by the merger of Lowe &AMP; Partners
Worldwide and Ammirati Puris Lintas.
</P>
<P>
   The 3Com shift is indicative of the ferment among
high-technology marketers as competition intensifies in that
fast-moving, free-spending category. Among others undertaking
reviews are the Compaq Computer Corp.; DirecTV; Lucent
Technologies, for a spinoff that will market voice-technology
products; the Toysrus.com unit of Toys ``R'' Us; and XM Satellite
Radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``3Com is at an interesting transition point,'' Jan Soderstrom,
senior vice president for worldwide marketing and brand management
at the 3Com Corp., said in a telephone interview Monday from Santa
Clara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of work to make a change,'' she added, ``but it was
really important we had the best partner to communicate a new value
proposition for the brand'' and help ``make the brand a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Ad spending is to be increased by 30 to 40 percent, to $100
million, said Soderstrom, a one-time top marketing executive at
Visa International who joined 3Com in October. The goal is to
introduce in mid- to late June a worldwide campaign, she added, to
promote the 3Com brand as well as product offerings, which will be
pared primarily to broadband and wireless connectivity devices for
consumers and small businesses along with infrastructure equipment
for companies that provide telecommunications and Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to change agencies came after a five-week review
that had been narrowed to FCB San Francisco, Lowe Lintas and two
other agencies, Soderstrom said: Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide, part of
the WPP Group; and Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising. BBDO Worldwide, a
unit of the Omnicom Group with which Soderstrom worked when she was
at Visa, withdrew from the review late last month.
</P>
<P>
   Soderstrom said she was attracted to Lowe Lintas because of the
agency's ``proven track record for turning brands around'' like
Heineken, Mercedes-Benz and Sprite, and its reputation for
``integrating work worldwide.'' 3Com plans for the advertising,
direct marketing and other elements of the campaign, which will be
coordinated by the Lowe Lintas office in New York as the lead
agency, to run in its Asian-Pacific, European, Latin American and
United States regional markets.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she chose the New York office of Lowe Lintas rather
than its San Francisco office, which is near 3Com's headquarters in
Santa Clara, Soderstrom replied: ``We wanted to make sure we use
the office with the most depth of resources. We live in a virtual
community here, so it doesn't matter where the agency is.''
</P>
<P>
   Whichever office 3Com chose, Lowe Lintas, which has had what is
widely perceived as a rocky start to its post-merger life, is
pleased to have the assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very, very happy to team up with 3Com,'' said Lee
Garfinkel, chairman and chief creative officer for the U.S.
division of Lowe Lintas. He added that he believed ``if there were
questions about the merger, they were more outside the agency than
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   At FCB San Francisco, part of True North Communications, Geoff
Thompson, chairman and chief executive, said he wished executives
of 3Com well as ``they restructure and downsize their business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're focusing our attention now on Palm Inc., the new company
recently spun off from 3Com,'' he added, ``and we're as excited
about the potential of the Palm brand as the market seems to be.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some other consolation Monday for FCB as American
Eagle Outfitters, the retailer of apparel aimed at consumers in
their late teens and early 20s, named an office of the agency to
create its first national television campaign for the
back-to-school shopping season. Billings were estimated by the
daily fax edition of the trade publication Advertising Age at $10
million to $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   McElroy FCB in Newport Beach, Calif., part of the FCB Southern
California unit of FCB, was selected for the assignment after a
six-month review, said Michael Leedy, executive vice president for
marketing and e-commerce at American Eagle in Warrendale, Pa. He
declined to identify the three other agencies that had taken part
in the review.
</P>
<P>
   American Eagle, which competes against retailers like
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, has enjoyed sales success with its casual
apparel for young men and women that includes T-shirts, caps and
khaki pants. Other advertising duties for American Eagle, like
print, strategic development and media planning and buying, will
remain in-house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WELLS-FIRST-SECURITY-     04-10 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-FIRST-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS FARGO TO BUY FIRST SECURITY OF UTAH 
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Utah, Calif.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. said Monday that it had agreed to buy the
First Security Corp. for $2.9 billion in stock, less than two weeks
after the collapse of First Security's planned merger with Zions
Bancorporation.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will enable Wells Fargo, the nation's seventh-largest
banking company, to build its presence in Utah, one of the
fastest-growing states in the West. First Security is based in Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Wells Fargo, based in San
Francisco, will pay 0.355 share for each share of First Security.
Based on Friday's closing stock prices, the deal values First
Security at $14.11 a share, a 15.8 percent premium.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of First Security gained $1.1875 Monday, to $13.375,
while Wells Fargo slipped 25 cents, to $39.50.
</P>
<P>
   On April 1, First Security announced that its 10-month attempt
to merge with Zions, also based in Salt Lake City, had fallen
through. Zions shareholders rejected the deal, largely because
First Security's stock price had fallen sharply since June, with
much of the decline coming after the company issued an earnings
warning in March.
</P>
<P>
   That all-stock deal was valued at $5.9 billion when it was
announced in June 1999 but had declined to about $3.8 billion as
First Security's shares dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the wake of the terminated Zions deal, First Security had
few viable options,'' said Sean Ryan of the research firm
Byrne-Ryan. ``The bank's final conference call with Zions, arguably
the most wanton act of self-immolation since the Buddhist monks
that protested the Vietnam war, decimated management's credibility
and likely scared off most plausible suitors.''
</P>
<P>
   On that March 3 conference call, the banks sought to update
shareholders on the status of the merger in light of First
Security's first-quarter earnings warning announced that day. But
the presence of a lawyer representing Zions on the call bewildered
many analysts and shareholders alike, Ryan said, by periodically
not allowing Zions management to answer questions. That day, First
Security stock dropped 38 percent, while Zions fell 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Wells Fargo has acquired several small banks
with $1 billion to $2 billion in assets. ``This is a bit of a break
for Wells Fargo, but it's just a function of them being
opportunistic,'' Ryan said. ``They are able to get this cratered
franchise on the cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   First Security had $23 billion in assets at the end of last year
and has 333 branches _ 138 in Utah _ and 9,600 employees. It
operates similar to a savings institution, with a business that is
generally weighted toward low-return products like mortgage and car
loans. ``The mortgage business has gotten really crushed in this
rate environment,'' Ryan said. ``But Wells Fargo is one of the top
operators in the mortgage business and is well positioned to
resuscitate First Security.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would have assets of about $241 billion and
would have operations in 23 states.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is expected to be completed in the second half
of the year, and Wells Fargo said the deal should add to earnings
in the second year of operations. The company will take a charge of
about $375 million for the merger and integration. First Security
expects to take charges for the Zions merger cancellation when its
first-quarter earnings are announced on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   To satisfy federal regulators, the two banks will sell about
$1.2 billion worth of deposits and associated loans.
</P>
<P>
   First Security has also granted Wells Fargo an option to
purchase authorized but unissued shares of First Security common
stock equal to 19.9 percent of First Security's 206 million shares
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer Eccles, chairman and chief executive of First Security,
will likely be elected to the Wells Fargo board, the banks said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
