<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN SAYS MRS. CLINTON CAN BE A STAR
</HEADLINE>
  By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He is still solidly behind Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
race for the U.S. Senate, but Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., had some
unusually kind words Monday for the mayor's opponent, suggesting
that Hillary Rodham Clinton would be a ``star'' if elected to the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in history a first lady has run,''
McCain told students during a visit to Columbia University. ``She
would be a star of the quality that has not been seen since Bobby
Kennedy was elected senator from the state of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the former presidential candidate who campaigned twice
this month in New York on behalf of Giuliani, moved quickly to
clarify his remark. ``I believe she'd be very liberal and I don't
believe she would be good for the country,'' he said, according to
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton still welcomed the initial compliment, her campaign
spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said. ``Hillary appreciates the kind
comparison to Bobby Kennedy and looks forward to working with John
McCain in the Senate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, speaking at a City Hall Monday afternoon, said he was
not surprised by McCain's remarks. In fact, he said, he agrees with
them. ``I think Senator McCain is correct, but you can be a star
for the wrong reasons,'' the mayor said. ``She would essentially
become a very, very strong advocate for many, many left-wing
causes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
