<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-OHIO11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Uncommitted voters quiz Gore
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANDALIA, Ohio _ Vice President Al Gore took on all comers
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Before about 250 uncommitted voters, Gore answered questions for
two hours and tried to grab the political middle in this year's
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He said his Republican opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, is
out of sync even with the majority of his own party. Gore touted
his proposed economic and social plans as more moderate and more in
tune with the needs of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe his agenda does not represent the mainstream
of the Republican Party,'' Gore said at Vandalia Butler High
School.
</P>
<P>
   This trip, along with his February visit to Moraine, is the
second to the Miami Valley this year. Today, Gore is to visit an
elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was in Cleveland on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, dressed in a golf shirt and slacks, called the night a
public meeting. His stage was the school library. With the tables
having been cleared to accommodate the crowd, he spoke of his
political and personal background for about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The event was called together in less than two days. Local
Democratic planners said Gore campaign officials repeatedly asked
for true independents and not hard-core Gore supporters.
</P>
<P>
   He got a little of both.
</P>
<P>
   Jakob Freels, 18, a Republican and a student at the Miami Valley
Career Tech Center, told Gore that his invitation for weekly
debates with Bush in lieu of paid advertising is self-serving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he just feels more positively speaking to a person
one-on-one,'' Freels said, after speaking privately with Gore after
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about restoring decency to the White House, Gore
reiterated his stance that while President Clinton is his friend,
he disagrees with some of his choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm running for president on my own, my own values, my own
beliefs and my own vision for what the presidency is all about,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore drew some hisses from the audience when asked if he would
return for the region's 2003 celebration of the centennial of
powered flight. He was noncommittal, then said he knew North
Carolina was having a shindig, too.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Gore tried to push his administration's track record
and its economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also refined his position on 6-year-old Cuban refugee Elian
Gonzalez. Gore last week seemed to support having the boy stay in
the United States as court proceedings by Miami relatives played
out, even as the boy's father sought to return him to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Gore said the boy's best interests should be paramount
and that the decision should be made in a family court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to encourage the talks between the family
members themselves,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
