<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOBACCO-BILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIGARETTE BILL IS APPROVED BY ASSEMBLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Legislation that would require tobacco companies
to reduce the flammability of cigarettes sold in New York sailed
through the Assembly Monday and is gaining support in the Senate,
where its prospects remain unclear.
</P>
<P>
   If passed, the proposal would make New York the first state to
regulate cigarette sales to help prevent the hundreds of fires
ignited every year by discarded cigarettes. It has passed the
Democratic-led Assembly for four years in a row, but has never come
to a vote in the Republican-controlled Senate. This year, 14 of the
36 Republican senators have signed on as co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fire safety issue, this is not a smoking issue,''
said Assemblyman Alexander B. Grannis, a Democrat of Manhattan, who
is the main sponsor of the bill. ``It is a cause of human suffering
that we can very simply do something about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has not scheduled a vote on the legislation, although
its main sponsor there, Sen. Frank Padavan of Queens, said he was
confident that one would take place before the end of the session.
``I think we have enough support to get it passed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, about 25 percent of fatal residential fires start
when a smoker falls asleep in bed or a lighted cigarette is dropped
on a couch or chair. In New York, such smoking habits have been the
leading cause of fire-related deaths, including 48 deaths in 1997,
according to the state's Office of Fire Prevention and Control.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, commercially sold cigarettes would have to
meet a fire safety standard determined by the Office of Fire
Prevention and Control in consultation with the Health Department.
The standard would include specific criteria, such as a time period
in which an ignited cigarette that is not being smoked would have
to stop burning. Companies could be fined $10,000 for a violation.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry has generally resisted such measures,
although in recent years, a handful of less flammable cigarettes
have been introduced, including Virginia Slims, More, and Capri
Light. In January, Philip Morris started testing a new paper in
Merit cigarettes that reduce the amount of oxygen entering the
cigarette, slowing down the rate at which it burns and generates
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan McCormick, a spokesman for Philip Morris, said the
company has been working with federal agencies on the issue and
would oppose state legislation, which he said could lead to
conflicting requirements in different states. ``We think this is an
issue that is best dealt with at the federal level,'' he said.
``Cigarettes are products that are manufactured and distributed
nationally.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Darren Dopp, a spokesman for the state attorney general,
Eliot L. Spitzer, said New York has already adopted fire safety
standards for other consumer products like home building materials
and infant clothing. ``Our review is that there is nothing in state
or federal law that would prohibit this.''
</P>
<P>
   Grannis said tobacco companies have been dragging their feet
because a slower-burning cigarette would allow smokers to re-use
their stubs and take longer to finish their cigarettes. ``The
bottom line is if the cigarette stops burning, then you will have
to relight it, and they won't sell as many cigarettes,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
