u f BC-BRAZIL-INTERNET-NYT &LR;      04-10 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET TAKEOVERS SPUR A BIG SURGE IN ACQUISITIONS IN BRAZIL
</HEADLINE>
  By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Fueled by a flurry of Internet takeovers,
mergers and acquisitions in Brazil surged in the first quarter of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America's largest economy had 65 transactions involving
the acquisition of controlling stakes in medium- to large-sized
companies, or 23 percent more than in the first three months of
last year, according to figures compiled by the Brazilian unit of
KPMG, the consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   A healthier economy provided the backdrop to the increase in
takeover activity, since Brazil was struggling to recover from a
debilitating currency devaluation in the same period last year. But
there is no doubt that a frenzy of dealmaking in the country's
vibrant Internet industry contributed to the growth of mergers and
takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen of the transactions involved Internet companies, up
from three in the first quarter of 1999. Among the foreign firms
involved in this buying spree were PSINet Corp., which acquired two
Internet service providers, and Portugal Telecom, which bought
Zip.net, a portal company, for $365 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a nationalist tendency in Brazil to view
transnational takeovers skeptically,'' said Marcos Moraes, the
founder of Zip.net, who still sits on its board. ``I hope this
nearsightedness will not keep us from trying to bridge the gap
between Brazil and developed countries through the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's Internet industry continues to undergo a rapid
consolidation process, imitating, in a way, the Internet industries
of the United States and other rich nations. Other Brazilian
industries contributed to the increase in takeovers as well, driven
in part by a perception that bigger companies are more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have pointed to Brazil's largest-ever corporate
takeover, Companhia Cervejaria Brahma's $7 billion acquisition of
Companhia Antarctica Paulista, recently approved by antitrust
officials, as a signal of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scale matters, period,'' said Carlos Novis Guimaraes, the head
of Latin American investment banking at Lehman Brothers. ``The
Brahma-Antarctica deal could be played out in sectors that are
still quite fragmented, like banking and insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   One closely watched deal will be the privatization this year of
Banco do Estado de Sao Paulo SA, or Banespa, which has extensive
consumer banking operations in southeastern Brazil. Among the
candidates to buy Banespa is Citigroup, as well as Brazil's largest
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Another big transaction will be the federal government's
privatization of its reinsurance monopoly, IRB-Brasil Resseguros
SA.
</P>
<P>
   Still, concern has emerged over the effect that wide swings in
the Nasdaq and other U.S. markets may have on mergers and
acquisitions in Brazil. On Monday, the Bovespa index for the Sao
Paulo stock exchange fell 4.2 percent, led lower by technology
issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
