<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENTAL HEALTH EXPERTS INTERVIEW ELIAN'S GREAT-UNCLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After being stalled for hours Monday by Miami relatives
of Elian Gonzalez, three government-appointed mental health experts
interviewed the boy's great-uncle, bringing U.S. immigration
officials closer to reuniting the 6-year-old with his father and
ending a bitter 4 1/2-month custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials will meet with the mental health experts
Tuesday after they return from Miami to review their evaluations of
Lazaro Gonzalez and Juan Miguel Gonzalez, the boy's father who was
interviewed Sunday, said Maria Cardona, spokeswoman for the
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   After being advised by the panel, the agency will issue the
Miami relatives instructions on how they must surrender Elian to
U.S. authorities, Cardona said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the agency is discussing options to ensure the boy is
returned to his father, who wants to take his son back to Cuba. She
said the relatives will receive the instructions either Tuesday or
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Elian has been living with his great-uncle in Miami since his
rescue off the Florida coast near Fort Lauderdale. He was found
floating on an inner tube Thanksgiving Day after an ill-fated boat
journey from Cuba that took the lives of his mother and 10 others.
He was among three survivors on a boat that capsized.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the Miami family, who have argued that Elian
deserves his day in court, filed motions with the 11th Judicial
Circuit Court in Miami and U.S. 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta on Monday in a desperate attempt to keep the boy in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys have threatened to seek an injunction to keep U.S.
authorities from forcibly removing the boy from the Little Havana
home where he lives with his great-uncle.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities have sought a peaceful, orderly transfer of
custody and said they have ``bent over backward'' to avert a
showdown at the home, where hundreds of Cuban exiles have held a
round-the-clock vigil and pledged to not give up Elian without a
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials are seeking a neutral site for the
transfer of custody, either in Florida or Washington, but not at
the Little Havana home.
</P>
<P>
   Since Elian's rescue, he has been at the center of a political
tug-of-war between supporters who want him to remain in Miami,
primarily from anti-Castro Cuban exiles, and his father, whose
cause has drawn the interest of Cuban President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's great-uncle was interviewed for about an hour by a panel
of two psychiatrists and a psychologist from Washington and New
York late Monday afternoon, 2 1/2 hours after their scheduled
appointment at the University of Miami Jackson Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez had refused to leave the side of his daughter,
Marisleysis, who was hospitalized Saturday in Mercy Hospital for
undisclosed reasons. He had asked the Justice Department on Sunday
to reschedule the meeting to allow his daughter to attend after she
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   But government officials decided to continue with the scheduled
meeting. After Gonzalez refused to come to them, Robert Wallis,
U.S. Immigration and Naturalization district director in Miami,
called Mercy Hospital and asked to move the meeting there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was quite rude to keep the doctors waiting,''
Cardona said. ``This is another instance of the government bending
over backwards ... for Elian's well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward A. Rosasco, Mercy Hospital president, said the meeting
was moved to a room near Marisleysis with the ``full permission of
the family.'' He said the mental health experts interviewed
Gonzalez for about an hour with a family attorney, Manny Diaz,
present. After the meeting, Gonzalez and INS officials left the
hospital without issuing a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot speculate on what the conclusion was, there was no
debriefing of the hospital staff,'' Rosasco said. ``It was cordial.
As the meeting broke up ... there was conversation between both
parties as they were leaving the conference room.``
</P>
<P>
   Rosasco said Elian was at the hospital earlier in the day
visiting Marisleysis, who has become a surrogate mother to the boy,
but was not at the hospital when the meeting took place. Attorneys
for Miami relatives have repeatedly asked that Elian undergo a
psychological examination to determine how he would be affected if
he was returned to Cuba with his father. They had their own
psychiatrists examine the boy.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. authorities have contended that the purpose of the
meeting was never to examine the boy or determine how the custody
transfer would affect him. The focus of the meeting was to discuss
how Miami relatives would assist U.S. authorities with the transfer
of custody, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Marisleysis was nearby, Rosasco said, the mental health
experts did not talk to her.
</P>
<P>
   Marisleysis was first hospitalized last Thursday when she
collapsed after a series of interviews with morning news programs.
At the time, a family spokesman said she had suffered from
exhaustion and stress.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the Miami family will now seek relief from state
and federal courts. Over the weekend, attorneys contacted the
emergency duty judge, who relayed the call to 11th Judicial Circuit
Court Judge Jennifer Bailey. Attorneys faxed their motions to the
judge Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   But Bailey stated Sunday that a federal court has already ruled
in the case and that attorneys had yet to show compelling evidence
that the boy will be harmed if he is returned to Cuba, indicating
the attempt by Miami relatives to seek relief in a state court may
be futile.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an estimated 10,000 demonstrators clogged Flagler
Street near the home of Elian's great-uncle in a peaceful prayer
vigil. The demonstration was similar to a prayer vigil held last
week in which thousands gathered in support of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
