<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-MICROSOFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET JOURNAL'S WEB SITE WITHDRAWS MICROSOFT SOURCE CODE
STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For a few hours early Monday, The Wall Street
Journal's Web site heralded a scoop: The Microsoft Corp., embroiled
in an antitrust battle, might be forced by the Justice Department
to make the programming code for its Internet Explorer Web browser
available to customers and computer makers. The Reuters news agency
picked up the article, and sent it to its news customers around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   But, just as radio stations and others were broadcasting the
news, the Journal removed the report from the Web site. Dick Tofel,
a spokesman for the newspaper, would neither confirm the article's
accuracy, nor give details about why it was removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story was not ready for publication and should not have
been posted,'' was all he would say.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft would not confirm the story either. ``We don't have
any idea what radical remedies the government is kicking around,''
said Mark Murray, a Microsoft spokesman. ``This idea seems
particularly illogical in that Microsoft already gives away
internet Explorer for free.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's incident again raises the specter of whether the
pressure to be first with news _ a pressure that has been increased
by the Internet _ is causing journalists to compromise accuracy for
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Many print publications are using their Web sites to get out
news that they feel might be stale by the time their printed pages
are published many hours later.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, during the height of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, both
The Journal and The Dallas Morning News posted articles on their
Web sites offering details about private meetings between Lewinsky
and President Clinton. Both pulled the stories a few hours later,
and published modified versions later on.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft story did not appear in The Wall Street Journal
newspaper which, along with Wall Street Journal Interactive, is
published by Dow Jones &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Although The Journal does have some reporters who write
specifically for the Web site, most of the articles there are
written by the newspaper's staff. The Microsoft piece was written
by John Wilke, a regular Wall Street Journal reporter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-SENATE-AR     04-10 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-SENATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI DOES LUNCH TO BOLSTER WOMEN'S SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT29 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani began a series of statewide
``Women for Rudy'' lunches Monday to reinforce his support among
Republican female voters, a group that has largely remained loyal
as polls show that the mayor's reaction to the shooting of Patrick
Dorismond has caused a drop in his support among men.
</P>
<P>
   At the first lunch, at the Women's National Republican Club in
Midtown Manhattan on Monday, Giuliani received a hero's welcome
from 250 guests, many of whom said that his fight against crime had
made them feel safer and that his economic policies had made them
prosper.
</P>
<P>
   But as he has in the past before similar groups, the mayor made
no specific mention of women's issues. Instead, he delivered his
standard speech about what he considers the Giuliani renaissance of
New York City, and only occasionally alluded to his Senate
opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody that used to run the city,'' Giuliani said to
murmurs of approval, ``and used to run the city with the high crime
rates and the big welfare rates, and used to run the city when it
was called ungovernable, all of those people support my opponent,
right? Every single one of them! They used to run the city, they
support my opponent. What does that tell you about ideas,
ideologies, issues?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we've done something different. We've changed it. Lots of
people don't like that. Lots of people are embarrassed by it. I'm
proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news briefing afterward at City Hall, Giuliani said that he
had deliberately avoided speaking specifically about women. ``I
don't consider women voters different than men voters,'' he said.
``They're the same to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``white voters and black voters are the same.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Catholic, Jewish, Protestant, Russian Orthodox, outside of
Russia, Muslim voters,'' he said, ``they're all the same to me.''
</P>
<P>
   His approach, he said, had helped move the city away from its
emphasis on ``vast and intricate subcultures.''
</P>
<P>
   In a clear reference to Clinton, he added that women support him
because ``they don't feel that I have some kind of pandering group
of views that say, `Oh, gee, you know in front of a white audience
I'm going to say one thing, in front of a black audience I'm going
to say another thing, in front of a women's audience I'm going to
say a third thing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who leads the mayor 49 percent to 41 percent in a New
York Times/CBS News poll of 1,573 respondents conducted this month,
also leads among women overall, with 52 percent to the mayor's 38
percent. Her support among women is statistically unchanged from a
similar Times/CBS News poll conducted in February, before the
police shooting of Dorismond, when Clinton led Giuliani among women
voters, 50 percent to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the poll showed that Giuliani's support among men had
dropped in the same time period. In February, Giuliani led Clinton
among men over all, 54 percent to 37 percent. By April, it was
Clinton who was leading among men, 46 percent to 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed that one of the mayor's biggest declines in
support was among independent men, who supported him, 62 percent to
26 percent, over Clinton in February. By April, they were
supporting him by 47 percent to 32 percent, a net drop of 15
points.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At Monday's lunch, a number of guests characterized Giuliani's
attacks on Dorismond as merely impolitic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps his choice of words wasn't clear,'' said Jennifer
Duncan, 31, a Republican from Rocky Point, on Long Island, who
works as a hotel catering manager in Manhattan. ``Just listen to
him. He's an intelligent man. He certainly wouldn't want an
innocent gentleman killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said that the mayor's record on crime was his most
attractive attribute. ``I was mugged when I first came to
Manhattan, and it's a much safer city because of him,'' said Carol
Nobbs, 53, a real estate broker and a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's criticism of Dorismond, she said, did not bother her.
``He was defending himself,'' she said of the mayor. ``Which he has
a right to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Giuliani is to attend a ``Women for Rudy'' lunch in
Rochester and then what his advisers are calling a ``women's town
hall meeting'' in Buffalo. On Thursday, Giuliani is to attend a
``Women for Rudy'' lunch in Mineola, on Long Island.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
