<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BUS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cuban-Americans show busloads of support in losing battle
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Resignation showed in the faces of thousands of
Cuban-Americans as they made a last-ditch show of support Monday in
their losing battle to keep 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Among those rallying near the home where Elian is staying with
his Miami relatives were about 100 Cuban exiles from Palm Beach
County who came in two chartered buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely not a celebration,'' said Jorge Avellana,
one of the organizers of the caravan that left Monday afternoon
from the Cuban-American Club in suburban West Palm Beach. ``The
real loser of this battle is the American system of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Elian may have only a few more days before he's removed
from the Miami home where he has lived for the past four months,
those on the bus caravan said they felt it was important to show
support for his cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be going to Cuba no matter what, but we need to show
the world that we don't agree with that,'' said Duny Falero of
Greenacres, who rode the bus with her 11-year-old son. Falero said
it was her first protest as a Cuban-American.
</P>
<P>
   The bus trip was organized by a coalition of 15 political,
veteran and social groups in Palm Beach County, but many of those
who boarded said they don't belong to any of the groups. Some said
they heard coalition spokesman Ernesto Priede of West Palm Beach
speaking on a Miami radio station asking people to make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Most said they were drawn to the battle not because of their
hatred of Fidel Castro, but because the federal government was not
allowing Elian's Miami family to petition in family court to settle
the custody question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going to happen with Elian, but I'm here
because I believe it's an injustice,'' said Ana Lopez, a West Palm
Beach resident who said she left Cuba 39 years ago. ``As an
American, I stand for what I believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Her shoulders draped in a Cuban flag, Delia Garcia-Menocal of
Wellington stood a few blocks from Elian's home, listening as
religious leaders led the crowd in prayers for the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a child of the world,'' said Garcia-Menocal, a great
niece of Mario Garcia-Menocal, who served as Cuba's president from
1912-20. ``He doesn't belong to a dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   Priede said the newly formed coalition, called the Cuban
Patriotic Coalition of Palm Beach County, was formed in January
after the federal government took the position that Elian must be
reunited with this father and returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be a permanent group to deal with whatever
issues arise about Cuba,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
