<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-LOBBYIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIP MORRIS FINED FOR ETHICS VIOLATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Five months after New York state fined Philip
Morris and imposed a three-year ban against its chief Albany
lobbyist for violating the state's lobbying laws, Connecticut's
Ethics Commission announced Monday that it had taken similar action
against the same tobacco company and lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement signed last Wednesday by Philip Morris and
its lobbyist, Sharon T. Portnoy, the company agreed to pay a
$20,000 penalty, and Portnoy was to pay $4,000 and abide by a
one-year ban from lobbying Connecticut lawmakers. Portnoy is the
first lobbyist in Connecticut to be banned for violating the
state's comparatively strict ethical guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   In November, after an investigation by New York's state ethics
commission, Philip Morris paid the state a $75,000 fine, and
Portnoy paid a $15,000 fine and was barred from lobbying in Albany
for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's penalty against Philip Morris was imposed
primarily because the company failed to itemize properly and fully
report money it paid to Portnoy and its top Connecticut lobbyists,
Clem Roy and Craig LeRoy, a high-level aide to Gov. John G. Rowland
from 1997 to 1999. The company has said its violations were not
intentional.
</P>
<P>
   Portnoy's punishment was primarily for falsifying the amount she
spent on five meals for three Connecticut lawmakers during
out-of-state conferences in Philadelphia, Honolulu and San Antonio
in 1997 and 1998, said Brenda M. Bergeron, an Ethics Commission
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   None of the three lawmakers violated any state lobbying laws,
though Portnoy misled them about how much their meals cost, state
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, for example, Portnoy reported paying $122 for two
dinners she bought for state Rep. Hector A. Diaz, D-Bridgeport, at
Deux Cheminees, a restaurant in Philadelphia, and Bali by the Sea,
in Hawaii. But the two meals actually cost $186.06, in excess of
the $150 annual limit the state allowed lobbyists to spend on
lawmakers in 1997, Bergeron said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in 1998, Portnoy reported paying $72.37 for a meal
for Rep. Minnie Gonzalez, D-Hartford, at Mansion del Rio, a
restaurant in San Antonio, even though the bill was actually
$84.43. That same year, Portnoy reported paying $145.57 for two
meals for Rep. John S. Martinez, D-New Haven, even though both cost
$185.09.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the state lowered the annual amount a lawmaker could
accept in meals from lobbyists to $50 from $150, and Gonzalez and
Martinez paid back the amount Portnoy told them they owed, Bergeron
said, to stay under those limits.
</P>
<P>
   Alan S. Plofsky, the Ethics Commission's executive director,
said Portnoy was not aware that she was violating the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0427 </DOCNO>
