<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-LINEUP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNDAY BEST? ON TV, IT'S THE
 NIGHT OF NIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 BY BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Remember NBC's glory days of Must-See TV, the
Thursday nights when ``Seinfeld'' and ``ER'' held television
viewers in the net work's iron grip?
</P>
<P>
   Of course you do if you so much as channel-surfed past the
Peacock Network, you caught an ad for it. We're still feeling the
fallout from one of the best marketing gimmicks television has ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   But five years later, how does that lineup hold up?
</P>
<P>
   Not all that well actually. Certainly not as well as TV's
traditional Holy Grail, CBS' 1973 Saturday-night lineup, with its
roster of such non-stop legends as Archie Bunker, Mary Tyler Moore
and Bob Newhart.
</P>
<P>
   That's no surprise we always remember TV as being better way
back when. (If only Steve Allen still hosted ``The Tonight Show'' _
wait, bad example.)
</P>
<P>
   What may shock you is this: Sunday night current Sundays, right
here, right now may be the best lineup of the lot, maybe the best
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it takes a little fudging (more on that later), but
nostalgic types need to yank their heads out of the sand and quit
moaning about how good TV used to be. Because, for one night
anyway, it's better than it ever was.
</P>
<P>
   But first, those Thursdays. In 1995, NBC's comedy heyday, here's
what we saw: ``Friends,'' ``The Single Guy,'' ``Seinfeld,''
``Caroline in the City'' and ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   Swap ``Suddenly Susan'' for ``Caro line in the City'' and you've
got 1996's lineup, a change that hardly matters. And that's the
problem if this were truly a powerhouse, it would.
</P>
<P>
   But Must-See TV was, more than anything else, a network gimmick,
not a valid description. For proof, look how NBC has expanded it's
Must-See umbrella, says Robert Thompson, director of the Center for
the Study of Popular Television at Syracuse University, to include
dogs like ``Battery Park.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quickly you realize that this is Must-See TV simply because
NBC says it is Must-See TV,'' Thompson says. ``It's like McDonald's
calling the Big Mac a must-eat hamburger. `Says who?' is the
ultimate response one has to give to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't exactly electronic snake oil NBC was selling.
``Friends'' and ``ER,'' along with ``Frasier'' (which slipped into
``Sein fel''d's slot), still draw enough view ers to make hits out
of would-be road kill like ``Stark Raving Mad,'' the same way the
old lineup bailed out disasters like ``Suddenly Susan,'' which
promptly tanked when moved from its cushy spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thursday is one of the few nights that the old-fashioned
network way of watching television remains,'' Thompson says. ``You
put it on at (7 o'clock) and you leave it on one channel till you
go to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was, of course, the way we watched television in 1973,
when there were only three networks and CBS' Saturday-night lineup
went like this: ``All in the Family,'' ``MASH,'' ``The Mary Tyler
Moore Show,'' ``The Bob Newhart Show'' and ``The Carol Burnett
Show.'' Hey, I was only 10, and I knew even then that this was some
thing special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carol Burnett'' was simply very good; each of the other shows
broke some kind of ground, either bringing a newfound realism to
the sitcom (``All in the Family,'' ``MAS''H), exploring new
territory (Moore's reluctant feminist) or reveling in mainstream
hip swagger (``Newhart'' _ for the time).
</P>
<P>
   And yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``As groundbreaking as that Satur day night was in a real,
actual assessment, I don't know,'' Thomp son says. ``You put ``The
Simpsons'' against ``All in the Family,'' ``Mary Tyler Moore'' and
``Bob Newhart,'' and I'd have to put ``The Simpsons'' on top. ``The
Simpsons'' is arguably the greatest comedy that's ever been on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Not arguable here _ it's the best, hands down. And it just kicks
off current Sunday nights. From there, it's ``Malcolm in the
Middle,'' ``The X-Files,'' ``The Practice'' and ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I know that's three different networks and one of them
cable. But let's face it, we live in a different TV universe now,
with remotes as com mon as the thumbs that punch them and hundreds
of channels to choose from. Times have changed _ a lot, even since
1995 _ and so have the requirements for great nights of television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology has allowed everyone now to program their own
evenings of television,'' Thompson says. Bet ter, more-varied
nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm'' is hilarious, and even if ``The X-Files'' isn't the
show it once was, it's still better than most of what's out there,
no pun intended (well, maybe a little). Thompson says he thinks
that if ``The Practice'' had appeared before 1981, when ``Hill
Street Blues'' changed the blueprint for TV drama, it would be
``the best drama on the medium ever.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't quite buy that, but I'll agree it's a good show. And
what better way to end a night of quality viewing than the sublime
``Sopranos'' (the show I'd give Thompson's superla tive to)?
</P>
<P>
   All the night lacks is a catchy slogan. Come to think of it,
it's just fine without one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-10-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000410.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-10 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3012 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      04-10 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THE DEAL WITH DI
 CAPRIO AND CLINTON? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 BY BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - ABC's news stars are apparently all in a tizzy over
Leonardo DiCaprio's ``interview'' with Bill Clinton last week.
Interview _ that's what the White House says ABC requested. ABC,
meanwhile, says it asked for a ``walk-through.'' Whatever the case,
DiCaprio ended up sitting down with the president and asking him
questions as part of a planned ABC special about Earth Day (the
segment may or may not air).
</P>
<P>
   So now news hounds like Sam Donaldson reportedly are furious. My
question: Why?
</P>
<P>
   Does DiCaprio's whatever-you-want-to-call-it blur the line
between jour nalism and entertainment? Sure. So does Donaldson's
pit-bull act on his Sunday morning talk show. So does the screaming
match that is ``Cross fire,'' on CNN. So does Diane Sawyer standing
on her head while interviewing Elian Gonzalez. So does sending the
local weatherman to milk goats at the county fair while he's
telling us there is a 10 percent chance of rain.
</P>
<P>
   The line between TV news and entertainment is increasingly
fuzzy, which is a legitimate problem. For anyone who contributes to
it to complain about DiCaprio's whatcha macalit is hypocrisy of,
say, ``Ti tanic'' proportions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of exits, ``NYPD Blue's Andrea Thompson, who plays
Detec tive Jill Kirkendall, is leavingthe show at the end of the
season for a rather novel reason: She wants to become a TV
newscaster.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of ironic, since all the newscast ers I've ever seen act
like they want to be TV stars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bad news for fans of ``Secret Agent Man,'' all two or three of
you: UPN is putting the show on ``hiatus,'' the equivalent of being
sent to TV Siberia. Might return in the summer, if you're desperate
(and if you care, you are). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fans of ``Roswell,'' which returns to Channel 61 Monday at 8
p.m., are flooding WB offices with bottles of Tabasco sauce (the
favorite treat of the show's teen aliens) to show their loyalty to
the show. This is a show worth saving, folks, so tune in. But save
your bottles the folks at WB called to say they have plenty
already. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tell me this happened to you, too, so I don't feel like the only
idiot in Arizona:
</P>
<P>
   You settle down in front of the tube Sunday night, watch ``The
Practice'' and once it's over switch to HBO for ``The Sopranos''
the perfect TV nightcap. Only when you change channels the show is
ending. What?!
</P>
<P>
   And then it hits you Daylight Saving Time kicked in all over the
rest of the country, and HBO's schedule changed accordingly. You
moron!
</P>
<P>
   At least that's how I felt last Sunday. So make sure you check
``The Republic's'' TV book when you're looking for a cable show. Of
course, that won't solve the biggest problem
</P>
<P>
   choosing between ``The Practice'' and ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. Might be time to learn that trick with the VCR where you
tape one show and watch another. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
