<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; EXCITE:  &LR; ExciteAtHome, the nation's largest provider of cable modem
service, has decided to team up with a Colorado company to provide
zippy access to the Internet over phone lines in areas it can't
serve through cable television lines. Redwood City, Calif.'s
ExciteAtHome is expected to announce today that it will work with
Rhythms NetConnections of Englewood, Colo., near Denver, to roll
out digital subscriber lines _ fast Internet connections over phone
lines _ in several major cities starting in late summer.  &UR; BY TODD
WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MARKET: &LR;  The mighty bull market has been good to a lot of people
for a long time, but it is fraught with psychological perils. After
years of strong and virtually uninterrupted growth in their
financial assets, many investors are not mentally prepared for a
bear market. When it happens _ if it happens _ the emotional
repercussions could be ugly, experts say. If Mmonday's 5-plus
percent plunge on Nasdaq is any clue to the future, a lot of
investors out there had better prepare themselves for severe mental
anguish, loss of self-esteem, even physical discomfort.  &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; ARTHUR M. LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SECRET: &LR;  It sounds like something from ``Mission Impossible.''
Equinix, a Silicon Valley company, plans to give reporters and
customers today a peek at a top-secret bunker somewhere ``in the
greater San Jose area,'' where it plans to let Internet service
providers and large companies swap e-mail and other Internet
traffic. The Redwood City, Calif., company says the new facility
will feature armed guards, bulletproof walls, hand scanners, bomb
protection and some sort of ``man trap'' to catch intruders.  &UR; BY &LR; 
 &UR; TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WELLS: &LR;  Wells Fargo Bank said Monday it had agreed to buy Utah
banking power First Security Corp., a jilted bride abandoned at the
altar by another suitor just two weeks ago. Based on its closing
share price of $39.50 Monday, Wells is paying about $2.9 billion in
stock for the Salt Lake City bank, less than half what Zions
Bancorporation said it would pay for its crosstown rival when their
merger was unveiled last June.  &UR; BY SAM ZUCKERMAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MONEYBAG (COLUMN): &LR;   &LR; Q: I have been providing material and &LR; 
 &LR; physical help to my ailing father for a few years. His sole &LR; 
 &LR; income is a Social Security check for about $600 per month. He &LR; 
 &LR; pays $200 per month for rent, but rarely spends any other &LR;   &LR; money.
I pay for his food, personal &LR; - &LR; hygiene products, &LR;   &LR; housekeeping,
laundry, etc., and am rarely reimbursed. Can I &LR;   &LR; claim these
expenses as a deduction on my income tax? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A: Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller says you may
be able to claim your father as a dependent, which would entitle
you to an extra $2,750 exemption on your 1999 tax return (rising to
$2,800 on the next return).  &UR; COLUMN BY ARTHUR M. LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NET WORTH (COLUMN): &LR;  First there was B2B, short for
business-to-business Internet companies like Ariba and Commerce
One. Then came B2C, applied retroactively to business-to-consumer
companies like Amazon.com, Yahoo or America Online. The next
logical step was C2C, a nickname for consumer-to-consumer companies
like eBay. Now get ready for (drum roll, please) B2B2C.
 &UR; COLUMN BY KATHLEEN PENDER &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
