<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-DSL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EXCITEATHOME PLANS DSL SERVICE  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ExciteAtHome, the nation's largest provider of
cable modem service, has decided to team up with a Colorado company
to provide zippy access to the Internet over phone lines in areas
it can't serve through cable television lines.
</P>
<P>
   Redwood City, Calif.'s ExciteAtHome is expected to announce
today that it will work with Rhythms NetConnections of Englewood,
Colo., near Denver, to roll out digital subscriber lines _ fast
Internet connections over phone lines _ in several major cities
starting in late summer. ExciteAtHome says it will initially target
Los Angeles, New York and other cities where it doesn't have
partnerships with cable TV firms.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Rhythms agreed to pour $15 million into At
Solutions, the ExciteAtHome affiliate that will offer the
residential DSL service.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement could be seen as a snub, however, for two Bay
Area DSL providers: Northpoint Communications in San Francisco,
which already works with ExciteAtHome on DSL for the business
market, and Covad Communications in Santa Clara, Calif., which
entered the residential market before Rhythms or Northpoint and has
more consumer customers.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome's Adam Grosser, president of subscriber networks,
said the company picked Rhythms because it liked its plan for
encouraging customers to install DSL themselves, which could cut
costs and speed up the installation process.
</P>
<P>
   The companies will also face stiff competition from local
telephone companies, like Bell Atlantic and Pacific Bell, which
have dominated sales of DSL service to the consumer market. But
Grosser said ExciteAtHome could have an edge over other Internet
service providers, like Mindspring, because it already has 1.15
million high-speed Internet customers and plans a heavy marketing
effort. ``We are the leader in broadband,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, ExciteAtHome could also work with Rhythms and its
cable partners to offer DSL in areas where it has pacts with cable
partners, but the lines haven't been upgraded for speedy Net
service. For instance, ExciteAtHome's local partner, AT&AMP;T, said it
could take several years to upgrade all neighborhoods in San
Francisco, Oakland, San Jose and other area cities for high-speed
Net service.
</P>
<P>
   But Grosser said the company hasn't approached its cable
partners yet, because it first wants to expand into new areas.
Moving into New York, for instance, will allow it to compete
against Time Warner, which serves New York and is in the process of
merging with ExciteAtHome rival America Online.
</P>
<P>
   By partnering with Rhythms, ExciteAtHome said it will expand its
territory to cover 15 million more homes, in addition to the 72
million already in its territory. But ExciteAtHome cannot actually
deliver service to all those customers, because many cable lines
haven't been upgraded and DSL only works over short distances.
Customers too far from a telephone switching office won't be able
to get the service.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome also plans to begin testing high-speed Internet
service over wireless by year end, Grosser said. But he said he
didn't think the company would use satellite technology any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
