<HEADLINE>
POWER FAILURE SHUTS DOWN NATIONAL AIRPORT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: D.C., Va.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A power failure prevented takeoffs and landings at
Reagan National Airport Monday night, forcing planes to divert to
Dulles International Airport west of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Davis, a spokesman at the operations center at Reagan, said
power was lost in the Federal Aviation Administration tower and in
the radar room. The terminal and the runway lights were not
affected, he said, and at 10:15 p.m., the cause of the problem had
still not been found.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines said it was unclear how schedules would be affected on
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Some power was lost at 7:50 p.m., said Eliot Brenner, a
spokesman for the FAA. The airport was able to continue operating
on a generator until 8:40 p.m., he said, when a wider power failure
occurred, forcing the airport to stop commercial takeoffs and
divert landings.
</P>
<P>
   Control over the air space was transferred to Dulles and to a
control center in Leesburg, Va., Mr. Brenner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
