r f BC-MARKET-ANXIETY-SFCHRO     04-10 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ANXIETY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HIGH ANXIETY COULD PREVAIL IN BEAR MARKET CONDITIONS  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The mighty bull market has been good to a lot of
people for a long time, but it is fraught with psychological
perils. After years of strong and virtually uninterrupted growth in
their financial assets, many investors are not mentally prepared
for a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   When it happens _ if it happens _ the emotional repercussions
could be ugly, experts say. If Mmonday's 5-plus percent plunge on
Nasdaq is any clue to the future, a lot of investors out there had
better prepare themselves for severe mental anguish, loss of
self-esteem, even physical discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Some people will develop all the physical symptoms of
anxiety,'' says Dr. John Schott, a psychiatrist on the Harvard
Medical School faculty who doubles as a money manager. ``Insomnia,
increased heart rate, palpitations, sweating, upset stomach,
increased blood pressure. Some will have depression, self-doubts,
look glum, start to lose interest in things, worry excessively.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors have suffered that kind of emotional damage during
previous bear markets, Schott notes, but ``we probably will see
more of it,'' because there are more individuals than ever in the
market, and many of them ``don't even realize that stocks can go
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while last Tuesday, it looked as though the next major
cardiological and gastrointestinal crisis had begun. Both the Dow
Jones industrial average and the Nasdaq composite index plummeted
more than 500 points midway through that day's trading session.
</P>
<P>
   But they recovered the bulk of their losses before the closing
bell. So, investors mopped their &LR;   &LR; brows, stopped checking their
pulses, wolfed down some Pepto-Bismol and once again faced the
future with hope.
</P>
<P>
   From a psychologist's perspective, what happened that day
started out as a case of jitters among rank-and-file investors,
says Richard Geist, head of the Institute of Psychology and
Investing in Cambridge, Mass. They got nervous just contemplating
the possibility of a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a feeling that a lot of high-tech stocks were
overvalued, and the Nasdaq had run up considerably over the past
year,'' Geist observes. ``People were looking for an excuse to sell
things off.''
</P>
<P>
   Geist, who already has interviewed many investors about last
week's crisis, reports that the sell-off was exacerbated by the
collapse in antitrust negotiations between Microsoft Corp. and the
federal government, as well as by concerns over the Federal
Reserve's string of five interest-rates boosts since the middle of
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Individual selling began to occur, and then portfolio
managers started to get anxious, too,'' Geist remarks. ``Then, what
really precipitated the sell-off was margin calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors are permitted to buy stocks on margin with money
borrowed from their brokers, paying only 50 percent of the price
with their own funds. This gives them powerful leverage, with each
5 percent gain in stock values increasing their investment by 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But when stocks drop, leverage works the other way, causing
margined investments to fall twice as fast as the market. That can
prompt brokers to issue margin calls, demanding that the investors
add more collateral to their accounts. If the investors can't or
won't, the brokers are entitled to liquidate the stocks.
</P>
<P>
   As margin calls kicked in last Tuesday, many investors were
forced to unload vast amounts of stock to cover their losses, and
prices went into a free-fall. When prices reached what many
considered the bargain basement, institutional investors ``began to
come in,'' according to Geist, and prices shot back up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The next time the ending might not be so upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Or, then again, it might.
</P>
<P>
   And when will the next time be, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   That in itself is cause for anxiety, because nobody can
correctly anticipate the stock market consistently. To do so, you
would have to be tapped into the psyches of millions of investors
simultaneously, and even modern technology hasn't found a way to do
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what is going on'' in the market, says Joan
DiFuria, a Kentfield psychologist who worked at a couple of
commodities exchanges before going into her present line of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that very quickly,'' she says. ``People who had been
buying and selling copper all day for 25 years tried to outguess
the market, but they never could.''
</P>
<P>
   So, proceeding from the proposition that no investor knows for
sure what will happen, it follows that all investors are at the
market's mercy, DiFuria observes.
</P>
<P>
   The wise ones, she says, will prepare themselves for periods
when the market turns bearish. They won't invest in stocks that are
too risky for their emotional makeup, and they will hedge their
bets with stop losses _ orders to sell if a stock sinks to a
certain level _ or put options. Put options allow you to sell a
stock or index at a fixed price, and then go up in value if the
underlying security's price goes down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know yourself, your values, your goals, your
emotional fortitude,'' DiFuria warns. ``People's emotions go up and
down with the Dow. When people have lost money, they usually are
questioning themselves, saying `I wasn't very smart. Why did I do
that?' They get paralyzed, spending all their time watching the
market on TV or on their computer, rather than spending time with
their friends and family, or on their work.''
</P>
<P>
   DiFuria, a long-term investor with holdings in such big-name
tech stocks as America Online, Cisco and Intel, says her way of
dealing with volatility is to follow the market on TV when it is
rising, but when it goes down, ``I shut it off.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  E-mail Arthur M. Louis at alouis(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
