r f BC-SECRET-EQUINIX-SFCHRO     04-10 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-EQUINIX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEB MAKES IT HARD TO HIDE `SECRET' FACILITY  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It sounds like something from ``Mission
Impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Equinix, a Silicon Valley company, plans to give reporters and
customers today a peek at a top-secret bunker somewhere ``in the
greater San Jose area,'' where it plans to let Internet service
providers and large companies swap e-mail and other Internet
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The Redwood City, Calif., company says the new facility will
feature armed guards, bulletproof walls, hand scanners, bomb
protection and some sort of ``man trap'' to catch intruders.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the company said security is so tight that it forced a
dozen reporters to promise not to reveal the location _ where
people will be shuttled in 20-minute intervals this morning _
before giving them directions. And Equinix asked the federal
Securities and Exchange Commission to keep the location
confidential in documents available to investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protecting the anonymity of the facility is a key concern,''
said Equinix spokesman Dave Fonkalsrud. He compared the security at
the site to Fort Knox.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the security measures might be over-hyped.
</P>
<P>
   A San Francisco Chronicle reporter was able to find the site's
address on the Internet within an hour.
</P>
<P>
   He simply went to a Web site run by the City of San Jose,
Calif.'s finance department, plugged the name ``Equinix'' into the
city's database of business licenses and the address popped up: 11
Great Oaks Blvd., in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The address is also on file with the city's planning department.
(Just ask to see file H-99-54.) In addition, the reporter was also
able to find the address within a few minutes by calling the
company's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Fonkalsrud declined to comment on what steps the company took to
conceal the location or why it was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But MAE-West, the West Coast data hub that handles nearly a
quarter of the Internet's traffic, has operated since 1992 with a
public address on Market Street in downtown Palo Alto, Calif.,
without any problems.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom, which operates MAE-West, or the ``Metropolitan
Area Exchange,'' said it has security guards and other measures to
protect the network and only lets its own employees touch the
equipment. But spokeswoman Linda Laughlin said hiding the address
is unnecessary. It would also be difficult, she said, because
countless customers have access to the information.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Internet is really just a conglomeration of
different networks all linked together, companies and ISPs need to
trade messages back and forth at key hubs around the country. As
the Internet has grown, private hubs, like the ones Equinix is
building, have popped up on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Fonkalsrud also declined to give more details about the
company's security measures. But the company bragged about its
efforts in documents filed with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``For security purposes, an Equinix (Internet Business Exchange)
center is anonymous,'' the company said in a document filed in
February.
</P>
<P>
   The company said there were no signs or markers on the outside
of the building that would indicate who was using the building or
why. And Equinix said the building doesn't have any windows or
raised floors, which could conceal intruders.
</P>
<P>
   Each site typically has about nine Equinix workers, plus two
armed security guards on duty all the time, the document said. And
the company has digital cameras stationed throughout the center, as
well as on the roof and around the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Equinix plans to build 30 such facilities worldwide over the
next four years for roughly $1 billion. It opened its first one
last year in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Equinix is also expected to make several announcements Tuesday,
including the formal unveiling of the center and key customers.
Before opening a center, the company told the SEC it would have
agreements from several customers and filled at least 20 percent of
the capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The company originally told reporters the San Jose location
would open in November of last year, but it acknowledged in its
government filings that it has fallen behind schedule in some parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Equinix also said the White House adviser on Internet security,
former National Security Agency Director Mike McConnell, would show
up for the tour along with several Silicon Valley executives: Marc
Andreessen, who helped start Netscape Communications, and Yahoo
co-founder David Filo. Equinix said top executives from several
other companies, including Cisco Systems in San Jose, would also
show up. But a Cisco spokeswoman denied any senior executives would
attend, and said the public relations staff didn't even know about
the event.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
