r f BC-WELLS-FIRSTSECURITY-S     04-10 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-FIRSTSECURITY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WELLS PICKS UP SNUBBED BANK FOR A SONG  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Wells Fargo Bank said Monday it had agreed to
buy Utah banking power First Security Corp., a jilted bride
abandoned at the altar by another suitor just two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Based on its closing share price of $39.50 Monday, Wells is
paying about $2.9 billion in stock for the Salt Lake City bank,
less than half what Zions Bancorporation said it would pay for its
crosstown rival when their merger was unveiled last June.
</P>
<P>
   That combination was cursed almost from the start, plagued by a
Zions earnings restatement, a government antitrust investigation
and a First Security warning on disappointing March-quarter
profits. The announcement prompted Zions' merger adviser, Goldman
Sachs, to withdraw its endorsement. Late last month the bank's
shareholders rejected the takeover by a 2-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Into that breach stepped Wells. First Security chief executive
Spencer Eccles told reporters he called Richard Kovacevich, his
Wells counterpart, the day after the Zions takeover collapsed. The
two CEOs met on April 3 and came to terms that night.
</P>
<P>
   For San Francisco's Wells, the nation's seventh-largest bank,
the purchase will make it the dominant financial institution in the
Mountain States region. ``Wells has once again shown itself to be
an opportunistic, yet disciplined `buyer,' '' said Joseph Morford,
an analyst at the brokerage firm Dain Rauscher Wessels.
</P>
<P>
   First Security originally paired with Zions as part of an
industry trend in which major regional powers joined forces, a
process that had already swept through New England, the Southeast
and Midwest. Zions, though smaller than First Security, was
considered more nimble and better managed, and was the senior
partner in the proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
   First Security is the third-largest bank headquartered in the
West, with $23 billion in assets and a total of 333 branches in
Utah, Idaho and five other Western states. Founded in 1928, it was
the first bank company permitted by federal regulators to have
subsidiaries in more than one state and its president, Marriner
Eccles, served as Federal Reserve Board chairman during the
Roosevelt administration.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, which already has a presence throughout First Security's
territory, will operate banking offices in 23 Western and
Midwestern states when its separate purchase of National Bancorp of
Alaska is completed later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase price equals 11.5 times First Security's projected
earnings for the year and 1.6 times its book value, ``well below
comparables for recent transactions,'' Morford calculated.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some bank watchers believe that the Utah bank has been
harmed by operational problems and the distraction of its failed
sale to Zions. ``They are totally damaged goods and the question is
how extensive the damage to the franchise has been,'' warned Sean
Ryan, president of the New York investment firm Byrne, Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, First Security said its March-quarter revenue would
drop 8 percent from the fourth quarter of 1999 due mainly to a
decline in its mortgage business as interest rates rose.
</P>
<P>
   Wells said it expects to take $375 million in charges against
earnings as it combines the two banks and will complete the
takeover in the second half of 2000. The bank is likely to cut an
unspecified number of jobs in states outside California where
operations overlap.
</P>
<P>
   The bank won't combine the institutions until 2001, after it has
finished merging the computer systems of the old Norwest and Wells
Fargo. Minneapolis' Norwest bought Wells Fargo and took its name in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   To meet government antitrust requirements, which prohibit one
bank from monopolizing local banking markets, Wells expects to sell
about $1.2 billion in deposits.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its First Security purchase, Wells will acquire the
San Francisco investment bank FS Van Kasper, giving it entree to
stock underwriting and the merger advisory businesses. Wells
expects to add to Van Kasper's staff of more than 300, said Dennis
Mooradian, the bank's president of private client services.
</P>
<P>
   Wells recently took over a small Seattle brokerage, and Van
Kasper is in the process of acquiring an Oregon investment bank,
units that could be combined into a single investment banking and
brokerage operation.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
