<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-DEDUCT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MONEYBAG: Parents Can Become Good Tax Deductions  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Q: I have been providing material and physical help to my &LR; 
 &LR; ailing father for a few years. His sole income is a Social &LR; 
 &LR; Security check for about $600 per month. He pays $200 per month &LR; 
 &LR; for rent, but rarely spends any other money. I pay for his &LR;   &LR; food,
personal &LR; - &LR; hygiene products, housekeeping, laundry, etc., &LR;   &LR; and am
rarely reimbursed. Can I claim these expenses as a &LR;   &LR; deduction on
my income tax? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A: Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller says you may
be able to claim your father as a dependent, which would entitle
you to an extra $2,750 exemption on your 1999 tax return (rising to
$2,800 on the next return).
</P>
<P>
   To qualify, you must provide more than half your father's total
support for the tax year in question. If your father spent his
entire $7,200 income each year, your contribution to his support
would have to be greater than $7,200. But you indicate that he only
spends about $200 per month on himself, or about $2,400. In that
case, you could claim your father as a dependent by contributing
more than $2,400 to his support.
</P>
<P>
   There are other tests that must be met as well before you can
claim your father as an exemption. Your father's taxable income
must not exceed $2,750 _ which appears to be the case, because
Social Security is not considered taxable income in this
calculation. In addition, your father must be a U.S. citizen, and
must not be filing a joint tax return of his own. The final test,
which no doubt your father can pass with flying colors: He must be
your relative.
</P>
<P>
   That last test is not considered a slur against your mother.
Congress prescribed it to prevent taxpayers from claiming
non-relatives as dependents, unless they live under the same roof.
</P>
<P>
   You don't specifically mention your father's medical expenses,
but assuming that you pay them, you might be able to add them to
any medical deduction you claim for yourself and your immediate
family. Three of the tests mentioned above apply in this case: You
must provide more than half his support, he must be a U.S. citizen,
and (chuckle) he must be your relative.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Q: In your column a while back you compared mutual funds and &LR; 
 &LR; trusts that track the stock-market indexes, and suggested that &LR; 
 &LR; trusts offer certain advantages over funds. I'm having trouble &LR; 
 &LR; finding more information about these trusts. My discount broker &LR; 
 &LR; can't or won't help me, and a book I bought by a Princeton &LR; 
 &LR; University professor mentions only index funds, not trusts. Can &LR; 
 &LR; you offer any further information? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A: Most of the index-tracking trusts are traded on the American
Stock Exchange. Take a look at their Web site, at  &LR; www.amex.com &LR; . &LR; 
 &LR; Click on the prompt for ``Index Shares,'' then follow other
prompts that will help you learn more about a broad assortment of
trusts, including those that follow the Dow Jones industrial
average, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, the Nasdaq 100 index and
various sub-indexes, such as the S&AMP;P Utilities and S&AMP;P Energy.
</P>
<P>
   I like trusts better than funds because they offer greater
flexibility. They trade as stocks, so you can move in and out
during the day and sell them short _ something you can't do with
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Also, they charge small management fees _ generally less than
0.2 percent of the trust assets annually. Some _ though not all _
index funds charge upward of 1 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   When I wrote the earlier column touting index trusts, one reader
disputed my analysis, pointing out that you must pay brokerage
commissions to buy and sell trust shares. While I should have
pointed that out myself, I don't think it is much of a drawback in
an era when several online discount brokers charge only $5 to $10
per trade. A large management fee probably will hurt you a lot
more.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Q: Early in the morning, before the New York Stock Exchange &LR; 
 &LR; opens for trading, I'll listen to the Bloomberg ``Market &LR; 
 &LR; Minute'' on the radio, and they sometimes say what the S&AMP;P &LR; 
 &LR; futures are currently trading at. I've even heard them mention &LR; 
 &LR; Nasdaq futures. Why are they being traded before the NYSE &LR; 
 &LR; opens? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A: Not content to gamble money only during regular hours,
traders in stock-index futures also risk financial ruin on
electronic exchanges throughout the evening and night, and in the
wee hours of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   If index futures rise during off-hours, it means that the
preponderance of off-hours traders think the stock market will
start off strong in the next regular session, perhaps because one
or two key companies reported unexpectedly strong earnings after
the stock markets closed for the day. If index futures are down,
the traders are betting that the market will be weak at the opening
_ perhaps because some big company reported disappointing earnings,
or because Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan made another of
his wet-blanket speeches at a rubber-chicken dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the overnight traders are correct. Sometimes they
aren't. Don't bet the farm on their powers of prognostication.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Send E-mail to moneybag(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
