<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NET WORTH: WHATEVER B2B2C IS, IT'S CLEARLY THE PLACE 2B  &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ First there was B2B, short for
business-to-business Internet companies like Ariba and Commerce
One.
</P>
<P>
   Then came B2C, applied retroactively to business-to-consumer
companies like Amazon.com, Yahoo or America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The next logical step was C2C, a nickname for
consumer-to-consumer companies like eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Now get ready for (drum roll, please) B2B2C.
</P>
<P>
   Given that no industry loves acronyms more than technology, it
was only a matter of time before this tongue-twister emerged.
</P>
<P>
   What it stands for, if you haven't guessed, is
business-to-business-to-consumer, but what it means is still a work
in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Generically, it describes companies that sell products or
services to companies that in turn sell to consumers, all via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In the offline world, they might be called ``vendors'' or
``consultants.'' But in the online world, a little jargon _
especially if it includes B2B _ might add millions to a company's
market value.
</P>
<P>
   The first time B2B2C appears in the Dow Jones Interactive
database is in a September 27, 1999 story in Computergram
International about OrderTrust:
</P>
<P>
   ``OrderTrust Inc. makes its money from transactions made over
the Web by sitting in the middle of a transaction and connecting
call centers to Web front ends to suppliers to payment processors.
OrderTrust likes to think of itself in a separate space to the
business-to-business players. ... it says it is in the `b2b2c
space.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; From that inauspicious _ and incomprehensible _ &UR;  &LR; start, the
term has been gaining steam at investment and venture-capital
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: Many B2C companies, especially e-tailers, are in
trouble. Big trouble. A lot of them spent enormous sums late last
year to lure customers to their sites, but most of those customers
didn't buy much or never returned.
</P>
<P>
   Online businesses spent 57 percent of their marketing dollars on
customer acquisition, 37 percent on brand awareness and only 6
percent on customer retention last year, according to a study last
summer by Boston Consulting Group.
</P>
<P>
   To stay in business, e-tailers obviously need to squeeze more
money out of every customer. And that's where B2B2C companies come
in, says Joanna Rees Gallanter of Venture Strategy, a San Francisco
VC firm.
</P>
<P>
   One example is Net Perceptions Inc. (NETP), a Minneapolis
company that sells ``recommendation'' software. A B2C merchant
installs the software on its Web site and it tracks a customer's
purchases and navigation habits and compares them to the records of
others who have similar preferences and navigation habits, then
comes up with something the customer might like to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It plays the role of a virtual salesman,'' says Gallanter,
whose firm seeks out B2B2C plays.
</P>
<P>
   Net Perceptions' customers include barnesandnoble.com, CDnow,
Preview Travel and Ticketmaster Online.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples include Netcentives Inc. (NCNT) and MyPoints.com
(MYPT). Both are based in San Francisco and sell loyalty marketing
programs to Web sites and some offline customers. Although they
differ in some ways, both programs reward customers who buy online
with airline miles or points they can use to buy other merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Netcentives' customers include Lycos, the AOL AAdvantage
program, Disney's Go.com and the American Express blue card.
</P>
<P>
   MyPoints' customers include About.com and ExciteAtHome. MyPoints
also runs offline loyalty programs for Albertson's and Kroger. The
company's upcoming annual report features B2B2C on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; B2C Converts
</P>
<P>
   Another group of B2B2C companies got started in the B2C market,
but figured they could do better selling their Internet expertise
to other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jeeves Inc. (ASKJ) began as a natural-language search engine
for consumers. Now the Emeryville, Calif., company is selling its
search technology under a private label to other companies _ such
as DaimlerChrysler, Compaq and Radio Shack _ that use it to answer
customer questions on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their B2C business isn't bad,'' says Ryan Jacob, manager of
the Jacob Internet fund. ``But clearly the business-to-business
side is where there's opportunity for tremendous growth.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest quarter, the consumer service accounted for
two-thirds of Ask Jeeves' $10.9 million in revenues and the
corporate service accounted for one-third. Losses were $23.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   Another company that started out in B2C is Cyberian Outpost
Inc., best known its ad showing a gerbil being shot out of a
cannon. It originally sold computer hardware to consumers online, a
cutthroat business that has already claimed several victims.
</P>
<P>
   The Kent, Conn., company, which is changing its name to
Outpost.com, hasn't abandoned the consumer business, but it has
started selling turnkey e-commerce services to others companies,
mainly brick-and-mortar retailers that want to go online but don't
know how.
</P>
<P>
   Outpost.com will design, build and run a company's Web site and
handle everything from inventory management to fulfillment to
product returns.
</P>
<P>
   John Seabern, co-portfolio manager of RS Diversified Growth fund
in San Francisco, is a big fan of Outpost (COOL), in part because a
new management team seems to have gotten the consumer side of the
business under control. But the main attraction is its B2B side.
</P>
<P>
   The company ``has developed an excellent infrastructure,'' he
says. It guarantees free, next-day delivery for all products sold
through its own and its corporate customers' sites.
</P>
<P>
   It has contracts with six retailers including Brookstone and
Wolf Camera. ``We expect another 20 by the end of the year,''
Seabern says.
</P>
<P>
   Seabern says that selling Internet services to other companies
is a ``much higher-margin business'' than selling directly to
consumers. ``There's no capital going into it, and there's no
inventory risk.'' Although Outpost might manage and even warehouse
a customer's inventory, in most cases it doesn't take ownership so
it doesn't have the financial risk.
</P>
<P>
   Outpost spokesman Jim Gallagher estimates that B2B2C sales will
grow from 5 percent of revenues currently to 20 percent by year
end.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, any B2B2C business is only as good as its customers.
And unless e-commerce becomes profitable, none of these companies
are going to be around long.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an investor, you have to look at the risks associated with
having a lot of customers that are dot-com players and marginal
businesses,'' says Jacob. Fortunately, ``you're going to see a lot
of these companies diversifying their customer bases to include
offline businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Only time will tell whether B2B2C is 2GR82B4GOT10, or just
another fad. But since we're on Internet time here, it shouldn't
take long.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  E-mail Kathleen Pender at kpender(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
