<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' BROWN TO MISS JUST TWO WEEKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In they limped, or at least what's left of them.
One week into the new season, and the Los Angeles Dodgers are
already making like the walking wounded.
</P>
<P>
   On their day off Monday, the Dodgers worked out at Pacific Bell
Park, counted heads and tried counting their blessings.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is they now hope right-hander Kevin Brown may only
be lost for a couple of weeks with his fractured right pinkie,
instead of the more extreme five-to-six-week scenario some first
feared.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was examined in Los Angeles on Monday by doctors Norman
Zemel and Frank Jobe, who told him he could take the splint off for
some light throwing but should avoid actually pitching for a couple
of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   If kicking and screaming, the competitive Brown is expected to
be placed on the disabled list Thursday. They have yet to decide
who will take his spot on the roster and in the rotation, but
disappointing Carlos Perez - who was supposed to be sent to
Triple-A to get a couple of starts in while the fifth spot in the
rotation was skipped - remains with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to put (Brown) on the disabled list and we're
looking at going with (Eric) Gagne, (Mike) Judd or possibly Carlos
Perez,'' said general manager Kevin Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson said it was a ``good probability'' that
Perez would start.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is left-hander Jeff Williams, who was with
the Dodgers on Monday and will be added to the roster today when
right-hander Gregg Olson is placed on the disabled list. For now,
Williams goes into the bullpen, but they need to name a starter for
Thursday's series finale against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Olson has an irritated nerve in his right forearm that Johnson
said needs rest and may require an anti-inflammatory injection.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is hoping Brown may be able to rejoin the rotation when
he comes off the 15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, he'll be able to throw enough in there to where at
the end of that period he can come back and start when he comes off
the DL,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, outfielder Gary Sheffield (sprained right ankle)
practiced and first baseman Eric Karros (strained back) did not.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield took batting practice but complained of his lateral
movement in the outfield, and noticing Karros was missing, threw a
new suggestion at Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked if Eric was going to play, and I told him it was
doubtful,'' Johnson said. ``So he said, `How 'bout if I play
first?' I said that was an interesting thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield took a few grounders at first after practice and said
it was easier on the ankle at this strange position. Sheffield, who
broke in with Milwaukee as a shortstop, has never played first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine over there,'' Sheffield said. ``You don't have to
run as much. I don't think it would be a big problem.''
</P>
<P>
   More likely, either Karros will play or veteran Geronimo Berroa
will start against Giants left-hander Kirk Rueter. If Sheffield
can't play, then Johnson can turn to F.P. Santangelo in left.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Karros can't go, my bench is versatile enough that I can
put a right-hander over there or one in the outfield,'' Johnson
said. ``That's something I couldn't do last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Berroa, who is playing for his ninth major-league club, was
called up when Perez was sent down after his disastrous opening
start in Montreal. Perez can be called back immediately if it is
due to injury.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield said he would have to wait until today to determine if
he could play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game-day decision, really,'' he said. ``But it's better
than it was yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   All this shuffling could have been avoided, of course, if the
Dodgers had their Saturday game in New York snowed out instead of
Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Tidbits: Fox owns which team? A billboard in San Francisco
reads: ``Go Dodgers,'' with the Fox logo underneath. Only ``Go'' is
crossed out graffiti-style, and the word ``stinks'' added after
Dodgers.... As if the Dodgers weren't having enough problems, their
phone system went down for most of the day Monday at Dodger
Stadium.... Before the workout, there was a team meeting so club
officials could explain how renovated Dodger Stadium would impact
the players. They'll have a new parking lot and family lounge....
Trainer Stan Johnson said although Brown doesn't need his small
finger to throw, he could aggravate it by pitching in a game while
hitting, fielding or if he fell on it. ``Any of that and it could
become a bigger problem,'' Johnston said.
</P>
</TEXT>
