<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A BROADER AUDIENCE FOR THE COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, April 11:
</P>
<P>
   Before April is out, the Supreme Court is to hear arguments in
three cases of great interest and importance. It is too bad the
court still refuses to allow televised coverage of its proceedings,
thereby depriving the public of access that could prove enormously
instructive.
</P>
<P>
   On April 19, the justices will consider whether the Miranda
warnings long required before police can interrogate a suspect in
custody were effectively overruled by Congress. On April 25 the
court will hear arguments on the effort by various states and
Congress to water down abortion rights by criminalizing a vaguely
defined surgical procedure dubbed partial birth abortion. A day
later, legal advocates will spar over whether the Boy Scouts has a
constitutional right to exclude gay youths and adults from
membership.
</P>
<P>
   These are complex legal and social issues about which many
Americans are still trying to make up their minds. The legal
debates in the nation's highest court would be an ideal chance for
the public to consider the weighty constitutional issues in play.
But that is not to be, thanks to the court's aversion to allowing
television coverage of oral arguments similar to C-Span's
enlightening coverage of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Several justices are said to be reluctant to surrender their
personal privacy. But the Supreme Court belongs to the public, not
the justices. Some justices are also said to worry that televising
the arguments would provide a distorted view of the court's work,
which mostly takes place when cases are discussed, and decided,
behind closed doors. That underestimates Americans' intelligence
and the value of openness in promoting the public's understanding
of issues and respect for the court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
