<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SCHOLARSHIP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA CONSIDERS SCHOLARSHIP LIMITS
</HEADLINE>
 LIMITS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NCAA's Management Council began a campaign to solve some of
college basketball's major problems yesterday by adopting proposals
regarding scholarship limitations and summer recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   The Management Council approved a recommendation that would
limit a Division I men's program to awarding eight scholarships
during any two-year period with a limit of five scholarships in any
given year (total scholarships would remain at 13). Also, the
council voted to cut the summer recruiting period in half in 2001
with the plan to develop legislation that would significantly alter
the summer recruiting model for 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea with the scholarship limitations is to emphasize to
the schools and the recruits that the fit between school and
athlete should be a good one,'' said Stanford athletic director Ted
Leland, chair of the Management Council.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, the NCAA's board of directors (presidents) will
vote on the Management Council's recommendations. Thus far, the
presidents have used their rubber stamp 95 percent of the time in
approving proposals advanced by the council.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting the number of scholarships, the council believes, would
help graduation rates. However, the newly formed Student Basketball
Council is against those limitations because it believes it reduces
the opportunity for players to transfer because schools will be
more miserly with their scholarships on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposal that the council believes will help graduation
rates will allow men's and women's basketball players to attend
summer school at their college before their freshmen seasons. This
``early immersion'' allows for a scholarship money to allow players
to attend up to six hours of summer school before their first fall
semester.
</P>
<P>
   The complex issue of summer recruiting figures to provide an
ongoing challenge. The 24-day evaluation period has been in effect
for more than a decade. It allows coaches to analyze and assess
hundreds of players at various tournaments and ``showcases'' around
the country. For smaller schools, it is a ``one-stop'' recruiting
opportunity that provides the most bang for the buck.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is that the summer recruiting period is populated
by people the NCAA deems ``undesirables.'' While doing away with
summer recruiting is impractical, the NCAA wants to somehow regain
control from the influential shoe companies and street agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we've had the wrong people become involved with
summer recruiting,'' said NCAA president Cedric Dempsey, who at the
Final Four recommended that summer recruiting be eliminated.
``Those people are involved with influencing young people, and they
shouldn't be in that position. We think it's time to put an end to
the `hand out' system.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Management Council said today in a strong voice is
that there is no longer support for the current system.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
