<HEADLINE>
SIZZLING SECOND BASEMEN
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rangers second basemen are hitting a combined .583 after the
first week of the season. Luis Alicea is 8-for-12 when playing
second base, and Frank Catalanotto is 6-for-12.
</P>
<P>
   That's the highest batting average at one position for any team
in the American League. Only two other teams have positions where
players are batting over .500.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim Angels left fielder Darin Erstad is batting .556 with 15
hits in 27 at-bats, and the Baltimore Orioles' first basemen are
hitting .579 (11-for-19) because Will Clark (9-for-18 overall) has
eight hits in 14 at-bats at first base. AL second basemen this
season Team H AB Avg. Rangers 14 26 .583 Angels 9 25 .360 Orioles 8
25 .320 Devil Rays 8 27 .296 White Sox 9 31 .290 Royals 8 28 .286
Indians 7 27 .259 Blue Jays 6 28 .214 Twins 7 32 .219 Athletics 4
19 .211 Red Sox 2 20 .200 Yankees 4 26 .154 Tigers 3 21 .143
Mariners 3 22 .136 THOMPSON THROWS
</P>
<P>
   Rangers left-hander Justin Thompson threw 71 pitches in an
extended spring training game yesterday against the Minnesota
Twins' extended spring training team.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, rehabilitating from off-season shoulder surgery, threw
six innings, allowing two runs on one hit and one walk. He struck
out five.
</P>
<P>
   If he shows no ill effects after his workout, he is scheduled to
pitch on another rehabilitation assignment Saturday for Class-A
Port Charlotte against Sarasota. RANGERS AT YANKEES
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers open a two-game series tomorrow at 1:05 p.m. at
Yankee Stadium, where they are 8-28 since the start of the 1994
season. The Yankees called off their home opener scheduled for
today because of a forecast calling for rain and cold. Rain is also
in the forecast Friday and Saturday in Cleveland, where the Rangers
are scheduled to open a three-game series against the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were 4-2 at Yankee Stadium in 1993, the only time in
club history they have had a winning record in a season in New
York. Since 1972, they are 53-106 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were 4-8 against the Yankees last year and were
outscored 76-47. That was the largest difference for the Rangers
against any team. They hit .246 against the Yankees, their lowest
average against any American League team. Catcher Ivan Rodriguez
hit .156 against the Yankees last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees went 3-3 on their opening road trip against the
Anaheim Angels and the Seattle Mariners. On Sunday, the Yankees
were stunned by the news that pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre has
multiple myeloma, a form of blood cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Scott Brosius is on the disabled list with a
strained ribcage muscle. Rookie Alfonso Soriano, called up to
replace him, has two home runs and two errors in two games. Shane
Spencer had three home runs in the first five games but sat out
Sunday with a cut on his left middle finger. TOUGH OPPONENTS
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have three of the 11 active hitters who own .300
lifetime batting averages (minimum 250 at-bats) against the
Rangers. The list: Player, team H-AB Avg. Tim Salmon, Angels
116-285 .407 Paul O'Neill, Yankees 87-255 .341 Roberto Alomar,
