<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEK 1 MIGHT BE A PRECURSOR TO WILD SEASON FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seven games into the Rangers' season and this is what we have to
show for it: a 4-3 record, 22 home runs at The Ballpark, 50 runs
scored by the home team, a handful of flyballs and line drives lost
in the glare off the new Gold Club behind home plate, a serious
case of windburn, a Gold Glove first baseman in a huff and one
clubhouse scuffle.
</P>
<P>
   Whew! Does that about sum it up?
</P>
<P>
   It was a fascinating first homestand for the Rangers, and the
storylines only get better from here. The Rangers are in New York
but what was supposed to be a three-game series has already been
whittled down to two games because of forecasted rain, snow and
cold.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your early-season pop quiz, boys. Here it comes.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a mistake to read too much into such an early-season
meeting, especially now that it's two games, but it would be just
as wrong to think that whenever and wherever these two teams meet
isn't important to the psyche of the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   It's not October, but it matters just the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you play the Yankees, you always want to show that
you can compete with them,'' general manager Doug Melvin said
yesterday before boarding the team's charter flight for New York.
``We haven't done that too well, especially in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to turn that around. There's been a gray cloud over
our head. We've been built for the long haul, but we know we have
to go through the Yankees at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin is hopeful that, with the many off-season changes the
Rangers made, this year's team won't be haunted by the playoff
failures of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees have been like a bad tee shot for us,'' Melvin
pointed out. ``You can go to your ball, thinking about what your
next shot is going to be, or you can get down and let it effect
you. I think we just have to put \Rwhat's happened with\R the
Yankees behind us, like a bad tee shot, and concentrate on our next
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, manager Johnny Oates, who stepped on the toes of his
star cleanup hitter, Rafael Palmeiro, by starting David Segui at
first on Opening Day, must now arbitrate a disagreement between
shortstop Royce Clayton and backup outfielder Chad Curtis, who
squared off in the Rangers' clubhouse Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   A witness to the confrontation between Clayton and Curtis said
it was over rap music with explicit lyrics that Clayton was playing
on the clubhouse stereo.
</P>
<P>
   According to a witness in the clubhouse at the time, Curtis,
never one to use diplomacy when a face-to-face confrontation is an
option (see Jeter, Derek, New York, and Belle, Albert, Cleveland),
objected to the music, and the two players exchanged shoves before
Palmeiro got between them.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said Oates is handling the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a club that some people think has been a bit
passive in the past,'' Melvin said. ``Maybe we've got a little bit
of fight now, if we can focus that on the field. Maybe we've been a
little boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's our job to make sure those things don't come
to a head and cause disruption, but maybe it's good that there's a
little spark in the clubhouse. We knew with some of the new guys
coming in, there would be some new energy in there.''
</P>
<P>
   No blood, no foul, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad Curtis has been known for that, being a spark plug,''
Melvin said. ``I don't encourage it, but if we have a problem early
on, it's time to say, `OK, we've got a few things here, let's get
'em ironed out. We're all in this thing together.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a little edge, let it be. If it gets disruptive or
becomes a distraction, it's my job and Johnny's job to do something
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only seven games, but already Melvin could point to
positive signs after the first Rangers' homestand:
</P>
<P>
   ``If people had questions about our offense, I think we've put
those to rest in most cases, unless we face David Wells too many
times. Besides that game, I think we got a good read on our offense
in that we're going to be able to produce runs up and down the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even I'm a little surprised at the home runs we've hit and the
power we've shown. Maybe I shouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our starting pitching will be better. It showed some signs of
coming around. We have to shut down the first-inning scoring
against us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are signs that the bullpen can be a strength,
just as we thought it would be. Johnny started defining the roles
out there, and that's good. I just got off the phone with a
National League team wanting to know if we'd part with anyone in
our bullpen. I said no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fact that our team hasn't given up. Even though
we've given up early runs in almost every game, we've come back.
And we're leading the league in double plays turned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A little edge, a little fight, isn't all bad.''
</P>
<P>
   A pillow fight would be more than what the Rangers have shown
against the Yankees the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   I say point Curtis at his old team and turn him loose. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
