 BC-ADD-BUDGET-AZR 
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following Arizona Republic story has been added for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for TUESDAY, APRIL 11. If you
have any questions, please contact the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AFGHAN (BALTIMORE) _ Activists working to help the women in
Afghanistan say the United States is largely to blame for the
suffering of Afghan women under the Taliban militia. It was U.S.
action that brought the Taliban to power, and the Taliban could be
removed if the United States and the United Nations had the will to
do so. Last week, activists lobbied for sup port of Afghan women at
Feminist Expo 2000, an international gathering of women's rights
advocates in Baltimore that drew about 6,000 women and men from
throughout the world. By LUCI SCOTT. Story will move in the ``A,''
``K''' and ``L'' categories.
</P>
<P>
   ORPHANS (undated) _ Decades before political scandals cast a
shadow over Arizona at the end of the 20th century, a series of
events in Clifton-Morenci wrote an ugly chapter of the state's
history at the beginning of the century. It was a chapter full of
racism, anti-Catholic bigotry and orphans dickered over like dry
goods. University of Wisconsin historian Linda Gordon has
chronicled these events in her book, THE GREAT ARIZONA ORPHAN
ABDUCTION, a work rich in detail about the town and the scandal
that pitted Anglo residents against their Mexican-American
neighbors. By BARBARA YOST. Story will move in the ``E'' and ``L''
categories. &QL;
</P>
