<HEADER>
A3066 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     04-10 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILESTONE TARNISHED BY JOYLESS JUNIOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What number tells us more about Ken Griffey Jr.?
</P>
<P>
   Home run No. 400?
</P>
<P>
   Or jersey No. 24?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, history might tell us it was the No. 400.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Griffey became the youngest player in baseball to hit
400 homers, edging out Jimmie Foxx and sending the Cincinnati kid
on his way toward Hank Aaron on the all-time homer list.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this season, look for Griffey to pass Cal Ripken
(currently 403 career homers), Duke Snider (407), Darrell Evans
(414), Billy Williams (426), Andre Dawson (438), Dave Kingman (442)
and maybe Carl Yastrzemski (452), while Jose Canseco (431) and
Barry Bonds (447) are still chasing the fences, too.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, whatever glory there is in 400 homers and the
promise of many more to come, there is the stink of infamy in
Griffey's latest demand.
</P>
<P>
   After first handling the matter with class, Griffey now wants to
wear No. 24 _ Tony Perez's number in Cincinnati, not Griffey's.
</P>
<P>
   When Michael Jordan came back to basketball and decided to wear
No. 45, you knew it wasn't going to last.
</P>
<P>
   The number was a transient bit of business, one you almost
suspected Nike had put Jordan up to, just to ring up more $80
jersey sales.
</P>
<P>
   One bad playoff game against Orlando, though, and the next thing
you knew, Sir Air was flying high again in No. 23.
</P>
<P>
   As for Griffey, taking the No. 30 and slapping it on his back
was no goofy matter.
</P>
<P>
   No. 30 is Ken Griffey Sr.'s old number. It is a meaningful
number and a meaningful gesture.
</P>
<P>
   After all, after he cut the list of teams to which he would
agree to be traded from four to one, Griffey said his decision on
Cincinnati was ultimately about family, about wanting to be home.
</P>
<P>
   The trade he demanded to the Reds was very much about wanting to
play where his father played baseball, about wanting to play for
the same franchise that spawned the World Series-winning Big Red
Machine.
</P>
<P>
   And most important as to why Griffey settled on No. 30 was the
fact that Griffey's number from his 11 years with the Mariners was
not available.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, No. 24 is going to be retired by Cincinnati. This is
being done to honor Perez, who will be inducted into the Hall of
Fame this August.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Griffey promised to honor Perez's wish to keep that
number from being used. Griffey said it was the Big Dog's decision.
He wouldn't ask for it. He would consider using it if Perez
offered. Otherwise, no. Griffey was taking the high road.
</P>
<P>
   It was this sort of gesture that made it appear as if Griffey
were starting over in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   He was going to shed that sour and irritable skin that seemed to
have tightened on him his last year or so in Seattle, where it was
clear he wanted out, needed a change.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, nothing would faze him. Back home, it was all going
to be good. Back home, he was going to be happy, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   But already, after one pressure-filled opening week of poor
plate appearances and one ill-advised outburst about wanting his
No. 24 back, Griffey is back to projecting his familiar, joyless
self.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mariners understood how important it was to cut
Griffey loose, Griffey has had the luxury of a fresh start in a
town predisposed to loving him.
</P>
<P>
   This has seemed a perfect opportunity for Griffey to
re-establish himself not only as baseball's preeminent player but
also as baseball's pleasing, attractive marquee ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Although he would probably emphatically deny any responsibility
for why he is being perceived as spoiled and bratty and bending
under pressure, Griffey does seem to be squandering this chance.
</P>
<P>
   All the Pepsi commercials in the world aren't going to be able
to undo the uneasy image Griffey is more truthfully projecting in
more meaningful, public settings.
</P>
<P>
   Think back to the 1998 All-Star Game, when he refused to take
part in the home-run hitting contest. Although he felt under unfair
pressure to perform after an all-night flight and early morning
news conferences, Griffey had to be cajoled by baseball elders such
as Frank Robinson to do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe when it came to getting out of Seattle, Griffey should
have demanded a trade to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   There, at least, Griffey had suggested that he and the current
owner of No. 24 had already struck a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey would get No. 24 and Wally Joyner would get a steak
dinner or a round of golf. Everyone would be happy. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the Griffey love affair in Cincinnati was damaged a
decade quicker than it took in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Mariner fans at Safeco Field were seen holding up
signs:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken Who?''
</P>
<P>
   True, fans, like sportswriters, can be ridiculous, but there is
some element of relief that Griffey is gone, the team left behind
more amenable, more eager and open.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Cincinnati, before the Reds' first homestand
featuring Moeller High's own Ken Griffey Jr. was over, ``The Kid''
was up to his old tricks, making rash demands, prompting Reds
officials to come scurrying to the clubhouse to attempt to appease
him.
</P>
<P>
   For a player so young, with so far to go, with so many homers
and so many curtain calls left, it would be a shame if, during his
Hall of Fame induction, people shook their heads and said: ``If
only the guy had learned how to live up to all that natural beauty
and talent.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
