<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' SHABBY PLAY HELPS PHILLIES WIN, 9-7 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ If Bobby J. Jones cannot be an effective starter
and Todd Zeile cannot make the transition to first base, the Mets
will be seriously hampered this season. Those two issues came
together in a troubling second inning of a 9-7 loss to the
Philadelphia Phillies Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored four runs in the first inning, and the Phillies,
playing their home opener, looked awful. Many in the Veterans
Stadium crowd of 47,115 booed as the Phillies misjudged fly balls,
leading to four Mets doubles.
</P>
<P>
   But the Phillies soon benefited from the Mets' shabby play.
Jones allowed three singles and a run to open the second inning,
then issued a walk to load the bases. Another run scored on a
fielder's choice, bringing up pitcher Paul Byrd, who pushed a bunt
toward Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, a converted third baseman who had made a throwing error
and an error attempting to catch a pop-up this season, was in
position to field the bunt. But he let the ball skip through his
legs, and a third run scored.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Doug Glanville, doubled high off the wall in
left-center, tying the score. A sacrifice fly brought in Byrd and
gave the Phillies a 5-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   If the inning was worrisome because of what it might say about
the rest of the season, it was also ominous for the later innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets chased Byrd with four consecutive hits to start the
fifth. The first was a single by Rickey Henderson, who stole second
and scored on a double by Jon Nunnally. The run was Henderson's
second of the game; the 41-year-old leadoff man wants to set the
career record for runs scored but had not scored this season before
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   A double by Edgardo Alfonzo and a single by Mike Piazza gave the
Mets another lead, 7-5, and put Jones in position for a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had worked 1-2-3 innings in the third and fourth, but he
ran into trouble when he encountered Glanville again leading off
the fifth. Glanville stroked a double to left, and Ron Gant
followed with an opposite-field double to right, scoring Glanville.
</P>
<P>
   That was it for Jones, who was relieved by Rich Rodriguez. After
a walk and a strikeout, Rodriguez allowed a sacrifice fly to tie
the score. Then he faced Mike Lieberthal, who made the All-Star
team last season en route to a career-high 31 homers. Lieberthal
was searching for his first home run this season, and he got it,
belting Rodriguez's second pitch deep into the left-field seats to
give the Phillies a 9-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Things could have gotten much worse for the Mets an inning
later. With one out, Kevin Sefcik tripled to right center, chasing
Rodriguez (0-1) from the game. Turk Wendell entered, and got
Glanville to fly out to shallow center.
</P>
<P>
   Sefcik decided to test Nunnally's arm, but the throw was
accurate, if short. It bounced off the turf and into the mitt of
Mike Piazza, who braced for a collision as Sefcik barreled home.
Sefcik plowed into Piazza with his right shoulder, knocking Piazza
onto his back and sending the trainer Fred Hina and manager Bobby
Valentine racing from the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Sefcik was out and Piazza was fine, if winded. He lay on the
dirt for a moment before rising and returning to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The game featured a matchup of starting pitchers who figure to
be crucial to their teams' success this year. The Mets have a good
idea of what to expect from their top three starters, but are less
sure about Jones, who made only nine starts last year in a season
cut short by shoulder problems.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' first start of the season did not go well; he lost to San
Diego last week and allowed four runs on six hits while failing to
get out of the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Phillies' rotation starts off strong, with Curt
Schilling (who threw 63 pitches on a minor league rehab assignment
Monday night and is expected back from shoulder surgery next month)
and Andy Ashby. One of their biggest questions is whether Byrd, a
former Met, will pitch as he did in the first half of last season,
when he went 11-5 and made the All-Star team, or the second half,
when he was 4-6.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd allowed six runs in two-thirds of an inning in his first
start this year, and he allowed seven runs in four and a third
innings Monday night. Reliever Amaury Telemaco pitched an inning
and two-thirds and was credited with the victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
